<HEADLINE>
NOW A STAR, VAN GUNDY STILL TAKES SOME NICKS  
 MALONE SAYS HE'S NOT MIFFED  
 MAGIC MAY GET SERIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ During a visit to San Francisco's Chinatown
over the weekend, a certain coach from New York was noticed among
the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's Nick Van Gundy,'' said a man, shaking Jeff Van
Gundy's hand with delight.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy said: ``They forget the Knicks is not my first name.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if Van Gundy, a native of the Bay Area, found out
anything as he returned here as coach of the Eastern Conference
All-Stars, it is that he is no longer the diminutive, anonymous guy
roaming the sideline at Madison Square Garden. He has come a long
way from the day Rick Pitino extended his hand to welcome him to
the Providence Friars as a graduate assistant coach by saying,
``Congratulations, Jim, you've got the job.''
</P>
<P>
   After regaling sportswriters with his own Horatio Alger story
last week, Van Gundy received one of the largest ovations before
the 49th All-Star Game at The Arena in Oakland. The old-school
purist who continually took shots at Commissioner David Stern's
league is now just as much a part of the product as any marquee
sideline tactician.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he exactly reveled in this gaudy weekend affair. With
the N BA turning the Bay Area into an excessively long party, Van
Gundy's agenda Saturday night involved watching game tapes of the
Knicks' next opponent, Toronto, in his hotel room. ``What else you
going to do?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose Mercury News referred to Van Gundy as Martinez's
``second favorite son,'' next to Joe DiMaggio, who was also born in
the small town north of the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy gained a greater appreciation for some players and was
surprised when Vince Carter apologized for being late to practice
on Saturday. But the coach added with a smile, ``Some of them are
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And Van Gundy was not beyond taking on the flash and flair of
the younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I hate? I watched that rookie game,'' he said.
``They play harder in the All-Star Game than they do in that game.
And that's every year. So I wonder, if the older guys can show more
respect for how the game is supposed to be played, why wouldn't
young guys? I'm not indicting young players. But I just think that
game is too loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans want to see competition. They should practice like six
one-on-one games. What fans wouldn't want to come out and see Eddie
Jones play Grant Hill one on one? Or someone trying to guard Allen
Iverson? Grant Hill versus Vince Carter. Come on. I'd want to see
that. I just think it could be such a great game. I think there's a
misconception by maybe those players about what fans want to see.
Or maybe I have the misconception. Maybe that is what everyone
wants to see.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked what it felt like to be part of All-Star Weekend,
to be a commodity in a changing NBA he never seemed to enjoy or
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're selling me,'' Van Gundy said before he gave the
East a pregame speech, ``it's going broke.''
</P>
<P>
   MALONE SAYS HE'S NOT MIFFED
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular thought last week, Karl Malone is not a
stodgy, old complainer who is emotionally wounded because the NBA
is promoting young players more than, say, stodgy, old complainers.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is what the Mailman said Sunday before his 15th
All-Star Game. Fined $10,000 by the league for not attending
Friday's news media session, said to be upset because he was not
voted to the Eastern Conference team as a starter this year at age
37, Malone finally rolled into town this morning after foregoing
most of the weekend festivities.
</P>
<P>
   He originally hinted that he would miss the game to rest nagging
minor injuries, but after a stiff fine from the NBA was threatened,
he ended up relenting. Malone said he spent time with his family
and was never basing his decision on the fact that he was bothered
by the league's decision to market younger and more athletic
players.
</P>
<P>
   `` I wanted to see my kids play, and I didn't know it was a big
deal,'' Malone. ``I saw everything from `he wasn't voted in' to
everything else. And nothing came from me. I've come to every media
session we've had for 15 years and I had an opportunity to go see
my kids play, and that's what I did. That's the issue I want to
clear up.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Malone, John Stockton and David Robinson were the
only holdovers from the 1992 Dream Team to be selected to the game.
At the 1998 game in New York, Malone was so miffed about Kobe
Bryant's waving him off during a pick-and-roll play, he said he
would never play in another All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's water under the bridge,'' Malone said. ``I was
frustrated at the time. Kobe and I have talked about that several
times since it happened. I always planned to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to play ``five or six minutes,'' adding that,
``I'm not playing 20 or 30.'' Told that Phil Jackson, the West
coach, joked that he would play 40 minutes, Malone said: ``I'm very
coachable. But you can tell Coach I'm not playing 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   MAGIC MAY GET SERIOUS
</P>
<P>
   For most of their careers it was Like Magic, Like Michael. But
after Michael Jordan took over recently as head of basketball
operations for the Washington Wizards, Magic Johnson is thinking
about his own serious foray into team management.
</P>
<P>
   An official in the Western Conference said Johnson has expressed
interest in taking over the Dallas Mavericks' basketball operations
after this season. Isiah Thomas, the NBC analyst and Continental
Basketball Association owner, has also expressed interest in
working for the Mavericks and their new owner, Mark Cuban. Johnson
will seriously pursue a position only if Thomas does not do so.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has also been reportedly interested in resurrecting the
Los Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm saying is, people have put me with certain people,''
Johnson said. ``This may just be a conversation, so don't make it
like Earvin is getting back into it. Because maybe not. I love what
I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Johnson is an executive vice president with the Los
Angeles Lakers and maintains 5 percent ownership in the team, his
primary basketball interests are directed in playing and coaching a
traveling all-star team in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm trying to get a job,'' he said. ``But if I
am going to do it, it's got to be on my terms. Because I know why
these different teams are losing. Everybody has got to be about
winning. Wherever I go to. It can't be like the old ways. You got
to be about winning. Because if you're not, there's no sense doing
it. I can sit on the sideline and live a happy life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
