<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS' VICTORY COMES AT BAD TIME FOR RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time was of the essence Sunday night at Madison
Square Garden when the Rangers played the Islanders. The game
started a half-hour earlier than usual, and maybe that was why Theo
Fleury of the Rangers showed up later than everyone else before
leaving early with the flu. Time stood still twice in the second
period and once it helped the Rangers score a tainted goal.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the horn blew to end regulation time, the Islanders
had a 4-2 victory. They had not defeated the Rangers in Manhattan
since January 1997. The Islanders now have a three-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   The result left the Rangers in seventh place in the Eastern
Conference, which will send eight teams to the Stanley Cup
playoffs. They remain one point ahead of eighth-place Pittsburgh
and three ahead of ninth-place Buffalo. The Islanders remain in
13th place in the 15-team conference.
</P>
<P>
   It was the final game of the season series between these rivals,
ending the series at 2-2-1. Kevin Weekes, the Islanders' goalie,
has defeated the Rangers four times this season _ twice with
Vancouver and twice with the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Krog scored his first NHL goal for the Islanders. The
others were scored by Josh Green, Mathieu Biron and Claude
Lapointe. Jorgen Jonsson had three assists. Jan Hlavac and Radek
Dvorek scored for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders played without Eric Cairns, their large
defenseman, who was suspended for an altercation on Saturday night.
After Cairns and Pittsburgh's Matthew Barnaby were sent off the ice
with penalties, they met in the corridor in Nassau Coliseum and
menaced each other. Cairns, a former Ranger, landed a punch before
security guards broke it up. Both are suspended indefinitely. The
Islanders were also without two injured defensemen; Zdeno Chara has
a shoulder injury and Kenny Jonsson has post-concussion symptoms.
So the Islanders called up defenseman Aris Brimanis from Kansas
City of the International Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Hlavac, the Ranger rookie who scored three times in the previous
game, gave the Rangers a 1-0 lead at 7:37 on their second shot of
the game. He scored off the rush, set up by Petr Nedved and Dvorak.
</P>
<P>
   After Nedved pulled Weekes out of position, he sent a backhand
pass across the crease to Hlavac, who steered it into the vacated
net for his 14th goal of the season. Although the Rangers took the
lead into the second period, they were being out-shot by 10-6 and
outhit by 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, the Islanders tied it the score at 1-1 on
Krog's goal. It came shortly after an Islanders power play and was
set up by some slick passing from Jorgen Jonsson and Mariusz
Czerkawski.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went ahead by 2-1 at 7:16 on a disputed goal. Dvorak
put a rebound past Weekes just seconds after Gino Odjick of the
Islanders left the penalty box. But Odjick was still skating toward
the play when the puck crossed the line and the Islanders protested
_ with justification _ that he should have been released earlier.
The problem was the scoreboard clock, which failed to start for 14
seconds after the previous face-off. Because of this, the Rangers'
power play lasted 2:14. Although the officials adjusted the time
remaining, reducing it by 14 seconds, they did not erase the goal.
Earlier in the period, after the Islanders first goal, the clock
froze for about 50 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders tied the score at 2-2 at 8:20 on a goal by Green,
who knocked in a rebound after a shot by Jamie Heward, and they
took a 3-2 lead at 16:20 on a goal by Biron that was set up by
Jorgen Jonsson.
</P>
</TEXT>
