<HEADLINE>
DEAD ROBBER TO GET HIS DAY IN COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTANDT  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With 29 gunshot wounds from a furious gun battle
with police, North Hollywood bank robber Emil Matasareanu bled to
death while handcuffed and under heavy guard in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That much is not in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, however, a federal civil jury in Los Angeles will
begin to hear evidence about whether police deliberately denied
Matasareanu medical aid after an accomplice was killed and 11
officers and six civilians were wounded during the North Hollywood
shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violence of the crime, Matasareanu's family believes
it is entitled to hold the city liable, claiming officers
deliberately let him bleed to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son _ yes, he did wrong, but what they did was even more
wrong. They let him die,'' said Matasareanu's mother, Valerie
Nicolescu-Matasareanu. ``They became judge and executioner.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-anticipated trial is expected to contain surprises,
including whether Matasareanu and Larry Phillips Jr. were alone in
robbing the Bank of America on Feb. 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The city's attorneys said officers acted properly by waiting to
call in paramedics immediately because they were unsure whether
other robbers were still in the neighborhood and whether
Matasareanu was booby-trapped with bombs.
</P>
<P>
   They also dispute Matasareanu's attorney's claim that the
hulking bank robber asked for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the opposite _ he told them to shoot him in the head,''
said Senior Assistant City Attorney Don Vincent, who is defending
the city, former police Chief Daryl F. Gates and former Officer
James Vojtecky against accusations of federal civil rights
violations. A third defendant, retired Officer John Futrell, is
represented by a private attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an ambulance there 10 minutes after the shooting
subsided. The care was there.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a Daily News story after the robbery, one of the
police officers said he asked Matasareanu, ``How many other guys
are we looking for; how many are there?''
</P>
<P>
   Matasareanu reportedly looked up at the officer and sneered:
``F--- you. Shoot me in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Stephen Yagman, who is bringing the lawsuit on behalf
of Matasareanu's two children, said the police had a duty to do all
possible to save his life, regardless of what he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite irrelevant whether he himself wanted or did not
want help because the legal responsibility of the police would have
been exactly the same, to take appropriate action with respect to
his serious medical needs,'' said Yagman, who has won many lawsuits
against the LAPD for misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Matasareanu's two children, 4-year-old Alexander and 8-year-old
Emil Jr., live in the Los Angeles area with their mother, who
declined to comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the first lawsuit arising out of the shootout will
put the officers' decisions, minute by minute, under intense
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Following a botched robbery at the bank, the two men, wearing
full body armor, fired more than 1,200 rounds of ammunition from
automatic weapons during the televised 44-minute gun battle.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips died after shooting himself _ he had already been shot
by police but the heavily armored Matasareanu continued his
rampage. He was wounded and handcuffed at about 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Futrell, a senior lead officer who was not involved in any of
the shooting, arrived near Matasareanu at about 10:04 a.m., said
his attorney, Bradley C. Gage.
</P>
<P>
   Futrell told Matasareanu to stay still so the wounded gunman
would not further hurt himself, Gage said.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent said police were unsure whether other gunmen were in the
area, and they also feared Matasareanu's heavily armored body might
be booby-trapped with explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Gage believes there were more than two robbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt in my mind that there were a minimum of three
bank robbers,'' Gage said, basing his assessment on a report that
there was further assault weapon fire after Phillips was dead and
Matasareanu was under arrest. In his complaint, Yagman claimed
there were six robbers, three of whom escaped and one of whom,
apart from Matasareanu, was arrested by police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emil Matasareanu was seriously wounded by the police (and)
could have been saved but was left to bleed to death,'' Yagman
declared in the complaint. ``By permitting him to bleed to death,
the police permitted the only source of information that ever would
be available to them to cease to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected to testify will be Vojtecky, who was in
charge of guarding Matasareanu and said he heard the gunman ask to
be shot in the head, Vincent said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have said they eventually learned _ and now insist _ that
Matasareanu and Phillips were the only robbers.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   As Matasareanu bled, Futrell told paramedics he needed only one
ambulance for Matasareanu, not the several he believed were being
dispatched, Gage said.
</P>
<P>
   Gage said he will show that fire officials felt it was too
dangerous to send the ambulance, but the paramedic crew came anyway
at about 10:07 a.m., Gage said. Instead of treating Matasareanu or
a wounded officer, the crew aided a civilian who had been shot in
the head, Gage said.
</P>
<P>
   When another ambulance had not arrived by about 10:45 a.m.,
Futrell made a second call, but it did not go through because of
heavy radio traffic, Gage said. After his third call at about 10:50
a.m., an ambulance arrived within five to eight minutes, Gage said.
</P>
<P>
   It was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics pronounced 30-year-old Matasareanu dead at about
11:10 a.m., but a second autopsy report puts the likely time of
death at 10:50 a.m., Gage said. Matasareanu bled to death from a
thigh wound, according to an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives continue to look for some $900,000 in missing loot
from the pair's bank and armored car robberies.
</P>
<P>
   Yagman said he hopes to convince 12 jurors that officers
Vojtecky and Futrell, now retired, violated Matasareanu's civil
rights by showing ``deliberate indifference'' to his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to provide medical attention, police
``cold-bloodedly murdered'' Matasareanu, Yagman said in the
complaint. ``These defendants created the dangerous situation that
caused decedent's death.''
</P>
<P>
   Yagman refused to discuss the lawsuit in detail.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty other officers who were originally named in the suit,
including then-Police Chief Willie L. Williams, were dropped
because Yagman said he could find no wrongdoing on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   If the jury finds Vojtecky and Futrell liable, the case would
shift focus to the only other individual defendant, former police
Chief Gates, according to Gage.
</P>
<P>
   Yagman said he hopes to prove that Gates, who retired nearly
five years before the shootout, fostered a departmentwide
``custom'' of officers mistreating people, as he claims happened
with Matasareanu.
</P>
<P>
   That is one threshold for seeking damages from the city.
</P>
<P>
   In case damages are awarded, the city has countersued to recoup
some of the estimated $1 million it spent on repairs, legal fees
and pensions for officers forced to retire because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys do not expect the lawsuit to get that far, and
will challenge it in a pretrial motion to dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of this suit will likely have great impact on a
separate lawsuit brought by Valerie Nicolescu-Matasareanu, who is
suing the city and 50 unnamed police officers for identical civil
rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of support for police on the eve of the lawsuit, a
group of San Fernando Valley anti-crime activists will gather today
across from the Bank of America to encourage citizens to bring
flowers to police stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to stand by our officers throughout this trial,''
said Mary Lou Holte.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
