<HEADER>
A5971 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-ALASKA-CRASH-SPI &LR;      02-14 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-CRASH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STABILIZER MECHANISM WEAR NOTED IN 1997 REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stabilizer control mechanism on Alaska Airlines Flight 261
was found to be worn and in need of replacement more than two years
ago, but the airline decided not to replace it, the National
Transportation Safety Board said Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanism in question consists of a jackscrew and a fixed
nut that moves the horizontal stabilizer atop of the plane's tail.
It has become the focus of the investigation into the Jan. 31 crash
off the California coast that killed all 88 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Sunday night, safety board chairman Jim Hall said
the plane MD-83 that crashed underwent a heavy maintenance check on
Sept. 29, 1997 at Alaska's maintenance facility in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most recent time that mechanics inspected the
jackscrew and nut assembly for tolerances, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   During that check, Hall said, the jackscrew and nut underwent
what is known as an ``end play check,'' in order to determine if
the amount of wear on the assembly was within tolerances specified
by Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   According to maintenance records, the check showed the assembly
was ``at maximum allowable end-play limit'' and the ``initial
planned action was to replace the nut,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   But that decision was re-evaluated and the assembly was
re-inspected on Sept. 30, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The maintenance record entry also indicates that the results
of the re-check fell within the specified tolerances,'' Hall said.
``The record further reflects that it was re-checked five times
with the same result.''
</P>
<P>
   An Alaska Airlines maintenance inspector signed off on each
re-check, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board is continuing a ``meticulous examination'' of
Alaska's maintenance records, Hall said, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance of this information is continuing to be
evaluated by the ... Safety Board. No determination has been made
as to whether this information has any bearing on the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilots of Flight 261 had reported a serious stabilizer
problem, and the jackscrew mechanism and nut were found to have
been badly worn and damaged when they were recovered from the ocean
last week.
</P>
<P>
   When two more Alaska MD-80 series planes were found last week
with jackscrew problems, the government ordered all similar planes
in the U.S. fleet inspected,
</P>
<P>
   Airlines had reported finding jackscrew problems in 22 planes by
midday Sunday. More than 1,100 must be inspected.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska said it grounded eight of its MD-80 series planes after
finding potential problems with the jackscrew assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the plane plunged into the ocean, it is clear
that a jammed stabilizer on the MD-83 set in motion a chain of
events that resulted in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   But aviation experts say it is far from certain that Flight
261's stabilizer problems caused the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stabilizer was definitely part of the causal sequence,''
said Bill Waldock, a crash investigator and associate director of
the Center for Aerospace Safety and Education at Embry-Riddle
Aeronautical University in Prescott, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   But he and other experts said there may be other explanations
for the plane's final dive, including a rare tail stall or even
that wing flaps were ripped off because pilots deployed them while
the jet was flying too fast.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots of Flight 261 were able to control the doomed jet for
nine minutes after the stabilizer jammed in its full ``nose-down''
trim position, sending the jet into an initial dive of more than a
mile from its cruising altitude of 31,000.
</P>
<P>
   At 18,000 feet, they were preparing for an emergency landing at
Los Angeles International Airport when the plane made a second and
far more violent dive _ just four seconds after the wing flaps were
extended.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's still the key question: What caused the final dive? It
may or may not have been the stabilizer,'' said John Hansman, head
of the aeronautics and astronautics department at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators may not have an answer for months, and major
investigations like this can take a year or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the wreckage of Flight 261 has yet to be pulled from the
ocean, and the flight data recorder and cockpit voice recorder are
still being analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Radar tracking records indicate something came off the plane
just as it began its horrifying plunge toward the Pacific, raising
speculation the stabilizer itself broke off.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the radar data, the U.S. Navy has been searching for
pieces of the airplane about four miles from the main impact point.
They have found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But the Navy has recovered from the main crash site several
large pieces of both the right and left side of the 40-foot-long
stabilizer, as well as portions of the right and left elevators.
</P>
<P>
   The elevators, attached to the rear of the stabilizer, make the
plane go up or down when the pilot pulls or pushes on the control
column, or yoke.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the wreckage recovered, it now appears the stabilizer
was probably intact when the plane hit the water.
</P>
<P>
   If so, what broke off Flight 261?
</P>
<P>
   Most likely it was the left wing flaps, said Chuck Eastlake, a
pilot and professor of aerospace engineering at Embry-Riddle's
campus in Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   If the left flaps ripped off, the plane would have been sent
into a rapid dive and roll to the left, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what happened to Flight 261. The plane dived and
went into a rapid, 60-degree-per-second roll to the left, becoming
inverted before smashing into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The flight data recorder shows Flight 261 was flying at 270
knots, with the stabilizer jammed in the full nose-down trim
position, when the pilots extended the flaps 11 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Flaps are extended for landing and take off. They provide more
lift at slower speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the flaps down for landing on the MD-80-type plane
pitches the nose down, and the pilots of Flight 261 were already
having problems keeping the nose up because of the jammed
stabilizer.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Capt. Ted Thompson and First Officer William Tansky may
both have been pulling back on the control column to counter the
extreme force of the jammed stabilizer that was pushing the nose
down, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The flight data recorder shows the pilots were using about half
their elevator control to counter the plane's nose-down problem.
They may not have known how much elevator they had left, and put
down the flaps at high speed to help maintain control.
</P>
<P>
   ``They only needed half the elevator deflection to counter the
jammed stabilizer,'' Eastlake said. ``They may have been worried
about losing control of the plane if they slowed down any more, so
they put the flaps out going too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastlake theorizes the left flap then ripped off. So does former
airline pilot Dan Gellert of Sequim, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is `what caused this incredible sequence of
events at 18,000 feet,''' he said. ``Something very drastic had to
happen to cause all of these events in such a short time. And what
really sticks out for me is that the flaps were extended to 11
degrees and then the upset happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Gellert has flown for Eastern and Alaska airlines, among others,
and is an experienced pilot in the DC-9, which was the basic design
for the MD-80 series.
</P>
<P>
   He said the pilots were going too fast for the wing flaps to be
extended 11 degrees, and ``They probably would have ripped off the
plane at that speed.''
</P>
<P>
   John Thom, a Boeing spokesman in Long Beach, Calif., where the
MD-80-series planes were made, said the manual recommends a maximum
speed of 240 knots for a flap extension of 10.1 to 20 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   But flaps can be extended up to 10 degrees at speeds up to 280
knots, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they will find the pieces that may have broken off
the plane,' Eastlake said. ``That would be conclusive whether it
was the flaps or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the flaps are found away from the main wreckage it would
not prove they broke off and caused the final dive, however. They
could have come off after the dive began, as the plane experienced
a negative 3 ``Gs'' of acceleration and exceeded its design
limitations. Anything not tied down would have been hurled into the
ceiling at three times the force of gravity.
</P>
<P>
   With flaps retracted, the MD-80 is designed to withstand a
maximum of 2.1 positive Gs to a maximum of 1 negative G. Flaps
extended, the operating limit is positive 2 Gs to zero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0012EST &QL; 
