<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCONSISTENCIES IN ACCOUNTS BY WITNESS OF DIALLO SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty days after Amadou Diallo died, WNBC-TV
broadcast last Feb. 24 an interview with Schrrie Elliott, a Bronx
woman who appeared to be the only bystander to have witnessed his
shooting by four police officers. The report suggested that Elliott
had been less than half a block away, on the same side of the
street as the officers and Diallo's building.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, WNBC broadcast another interview with Elliott,
whose face was hidden in both interviews. This time, however, the
report suggested she had been across the street, looking into the
vestibule where Diallo was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The reports indicate both the importance and unpredictability of
Elliott, 32, who is to testify Monday for the second time in the
officers' murder trial in Albany. She could corroborate or refute
what the officers say happened that night, but her recounting of
what she saw has rarely been consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Those inconsistencies will take center stage when Elliott, who
was first called to the stand last week as a defense witness _ only
to deliver testimony that was more helpful than hurtful to the
defense _ returns as a witness now labeled ``adverse'' to the
defense. The officers _ Sean Carroll, Kenneth Boss, Edward McMellon
and Richard Murphy _ will also begin taking the stand Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That ``adverse'' label will allow defense lawyers to
cross-examine her on her previous statements _ to WNBC, to the FBI
and to a Bronx grand jury. In doing so, they will try to destroy
her credibility on everything except one key point: that she heard
a police officer shout ``Gun!'' just before the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   They will have as ammunition her own troubled history, including
a criminal record. Her previous troubles with the law underscore
that for all parties concerned _ not least Elliott _ her witnessing
the shooting was an unfortunate twist of fate. ``I really believe
this was her worst nightmare,'' her sister, Shneaqua Elliott, said
last week.
</P>
<P>
   By her sister's account, witnessing the shooting was deeply
traumatic for Schrrie Elliott, who had visited a cousin in the
Bronx and was walking from the Elder Avenue subway stop in
Soundview to her home on Evergreen Avenue when she saw the shooting
on Wheeler Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Shneaqua Elliott said that when she returned home later that
morning, Schrrie was anxious and trembling. ``She just looked like
she had run 10 blocks,'' Shneaqua Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Schrrie Elliott told the grand jury that she did not leave her
home for two weeks after the shooting. But prosecutors said in
court last Thursday that their records show she had appeared in
court regarding a pending criminal case against her on Feb. 4, 1999
_ hours after the shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
