A5975 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-LPGA-LADN-(SLANG)     02-14 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIES SEES HER WAY TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ Laura Davies beckoned them all, which
turned out to be just so much show.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend at the Los Angeles Women's Championship would
ultimately be dominated by Davies, bad weather, and of course, eye
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Davies _ the plain-speaking, now clear-eyed Englishwoman _ saw
her three-stroke lead vanish quickly on a soaking Sunday afternoon
at the Wood Ranch Golf Club, an opening that only teased would-be
pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   Davies twiced regrouped after a pair of bogey runs, eschewing
driver and umbrella on the way to a three-stroke victory in the
$750,000 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Under a constant drizzle that left some holes in standing water,
Davies played it conservatively with a one-over-par 73, finishing
five strokes under at 211 in the 54-hole LPGA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The unpleasant weather played havoc with nearly everyone's game.
Among the top ten finishers, only Carin Koch _ who along with
Michele Redman and Janice Moodie, tied for second _ broke par
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Davies double-bogeyed the water-drenched first hole, but so did
five others who began the day three or four strokes back.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no runaway, but no one could sustain a charge.
Dottie Pepper caught Davies for a moment after three holes, then
faded. Mi Hyun Kim, Lorie Kane, Redman and Koch all closed to
within a stroke at different times but could never climb the
mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, hope abounded. It looked like plenty at least had a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to see my name on the leaderboard,'' Koch said.
``I thought, `Nobody is doing too much.' I saw the board change a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which got Davies' attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was panicking a little bit,'' Davies said. ``That's the way
it is. I'm not trying to trick anyone to think it's easy. It's hard
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But every time Davies wobbled and appeared as if she might
falter, she was able to right herself and come back with a big
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Redman had pulled to within one for the second time after Davies
bogeyed 14, but Davies came back with an eight-foot putt for birdie
on 14 and then all but clinched the tournament with a 40-foot chip
for a final birdie on 17.
</P>
<P>
   For Davies, who had spur-of-the-moment laser eye surgery the day
before the tournament began, it marked only her second LPGA victory
in the past 34 months. It was her 18th tour victory overall, the
first she won without breaking par on the final day, and the first
with that spiffy new vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could focus on the trophy on 18,'' she said. ``It was the
first time I'd seen one.''
</P>
<P>
   With two days of mostly solid rain, the roughs and bunkers were
heavy and wet. Davies went for accuracy and decided against using
her driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was just to hit the fairway,'' she said. ``We played
with a 3-iron all the way around, except the par 3s. We sacrificed
some length, but the tactic paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not have looked very pretty, but when you have the
lead, you do what you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies said she briefly considered switching plans at the
five-par sixth, but her caddie, Terry Mundy, talked her out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry said, `We have a plan. Let's win with it or lose with
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moodie was two strokes back at 2-under after she hit a 20-foot
putt to birdie 17. Moodie realized she had a chance to put some
pressure on Davies going into the clubhouse and take second by
herself. But she just missed an 17-foot birdie putt on 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `This putt could get me some cabbage,'''
Moodie said.
</P>
<P>
   Davies earned $112,500 with the victory. Moodie, Koch, and
Redman each took $53,465.
</P>
<P>
   Redman said she intentionaly did not study the leaderboard and
was unaware she was only trailing Davies by one shot after 14
holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know,'' Redman said. ``I tried really hard to just
play my game and not look at the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I hit the ball pretty well today, because it was
really tough out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies did not win an LPGA tournament last season for the first
time in seven years but said she is a much improved player from 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a better player now,'' she said, ``and I have better
eyes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0016EST &QL; 
