<HEADLINE>
AN AILING CARDINAL INSPIRES WITH A SERMON ON SUFFERING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back from a journey to the Holy See that was most
likely the last of his life, Cardinal John O'Connor spoke to
worshipers at St. Patrick's Cathedral on Sunday about the ``power
of suffering'' in a homily that for many crystallized his own
illness and his impending retirement as archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's farewell visit last week with Pope John Paul II, who
elevated him to archbishop 16 years ago, happened to coincide with
the first day of a special four-day Holy Year event dedicated to
the sick, when thousands of Roman Catholics struck by illness and
infirmities gathered in Vatican City in St. Peter's Square. The
cardinal could have sat among them: Last year, he underwent surgery
to remove a brain tumor, followed by radiation.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal said he was touched by the tenderness of the pope,
who is also frail and aging, in addressing the faithful. ``It was
amazing to watch the Holy Father, because there was so much love
being radiated,'' the cardinal said. ``One could not but be deeply
moved.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal did not mention his own retirement or discussions
with the pope over who would succeed him. A spokesman for the
cardinal, Joseph Zwilling, said the next archbishop would be named
next month.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor tendered his resignation on his 75th birthday five
years ago, in keeping with church tradition. But with his 80th
birthday last month, the cardinal lost his vote for the next pope,
making his retirement in the coming weeks a near certainty. Last
week, he wrote of his impending retirement in a farewell letter to
fellow bishops in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Associates have said that before his own illness, when O'Connor
was still strong enough to visit priests who were sick or dying, he
would tell them that they might have felt stronger when their
health was good but were spiritually most powerful in their pain
and anguish. His message was much the same Sunday. As worshipers
listened, many wept silently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can contribute by offering up our sufferings,'' he said.
``Suffering is a viable use to offer to Almighty God.''
</P>
<P>
   Dermott Smith, who was visiting New York from St. Louis, was
among those who seemed overwhelmed by the sermon. ``It was very
down to earth,'' he said, ``simple and moving.'' Smith said that
the last time he stood in St. Patrick's Cathedral, he was 25. Now
he is 75, and as he listened to the cardinal, he said he hoped his
own good health would last.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor seemed stronger Sunday than in recent months, standing
for much of the Mass and speaking in a steady voice.
</P>
<P>
   He also returned to using his trademark one-liners. His homily
lasted a little longer than usual, and he told the congregation:
``I'm sorry. I've just been told I'm talking too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Nervous giggles rose from the pews. The cardinal paused, then
added archly: ``This is a new phenomenon. Maybe it's a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The congregation burst out in laughter and scattered applause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
