<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE SHOULD FORGET ABOUT OHIO ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What is it with these sons of Ohio and Seattle sports?
</P>
<P>
   First, Cincinnati native Ken Griffey Jr. can't stand it here.
Then, Joey Galloway of Columbus, a couple of hours upstate, is so
torqued with his circumstances that he squanders the first half of
a season, then drifts for the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Is it us? Our coffee breath? Too many puddles? Did they lose a
whole day trying to get on I-5 from Mercer?
</P>
<P>
   I was just in Ohio, and I failed to see the comparison to
Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   The state is jammed between Kentucky and Indiana, which is like
being married to Beavis AND Butthead. Then I think about the
Bengals and Browns, and my head hurts. How about those Cavaliers,
with Indiana native-turned-Macy's-balloon Shawn Kemp?
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland once lit afire its river, and Cincinnati natives
sometimes refer to their burg as Porkopolis. All you need to know
about cultural enlightenment is that Cincinnatians can forgive Pete
Rose anything but will tolerate nothing from photographer Robert
Mappelthorpe. And let's not even bother with Marge Schott.
</P>
<P>
   Please, Ohioans, save the nasty letters and e-mails. You're nice
folks. I've been treated well every visit. But for Seattle to get
hosed twice in five days by big-time Ohio athletes, well, the
crankiness must be worked through.
</P>
<P>
   One remarkable development from last week was how much money was
left on the tables in order to make the escapes from the Northwest
horrors.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's willingness to take about $26 million less from the
Reds than the Mariners offered has left some baseball jaws
slackened. In a similar vein, although not to the same degree,
Galloway was willing to accept $215,000 in fines and $837,000 in
lost salary to get what he wanted from the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   He got it _ a trade to a team willing to pay him his original
contract demand of $42 million over seven years, with a $12.5
million signing bonus. The Seahawks had offered $35 million over
seven years, with a $7 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The different economic rules of baseball and football required
different tactics, but one result was the same _ they whacked their
old teams.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey bludgeoned the Mariners partly because the baseball
system is weighted so heavily in favor of player rights. The
10-and-5 rule is unique to baseball, and in hindsight, it appears
Griffey had been laying for it for years.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, the system is weighed heavily in favor of the teams.
Which makes Galloway's achievement all the more remarkable. The
holdout and subsequent poor play did not prevent him from gaining a
guaranteed $5.5 million upgrade in the bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Since he didn't care about Seattle or his teammates, his
strategy must be said to have worked.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Seahawks would seem to have made out better than
the Mariners, because they received two first-round draft picks
from the Cowboys while the Mariners picked up four players of
exceedingly modest skills.
</P>
<P>
   But as valuable as first-round NFL picks are on paper, they are
still unknown quantities; futures, not realities. Galloway was a
proven gamebreaker, although he never quite lived up to his
potential, even before the past season.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest virtue the Galloway transaction provided the
Seahawks was relief against the salary cap, where they are
squeezed. Although there is no salary cap in baseball, the
Mariners' biggest virtue in the Griffey transaction was also
payroll relief, a chance to use his 2000 salary of $8.5 million
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But just try to wrap your sports heart around a balance sheet,
or a cap strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Mariners and Seahawks will survive, and so will
fans. Player movement has always been a part of pro sports. Only
the naive assume loyalty is a big factor.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean a sense of rejection isn't legitimate. Seattle
fans nowadays not only invest their emotions, ticket and souvenir
money in the players and teams, they have committed $717 million in
tax money, plus interest, to house in opulent fashion these
franchises _ more public money than any market in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody thinks about that during a ninth-inning home run or a
game-winning touchdown catch. In those moments, ``our'' guys have
just made us enormously happy and proud. An affinity is usually
irresistible. That affection is the foundation of the
spectator-sports industry.
</P>
<P>
   But because sports are all about emotion and little about common
sense, when good, popular players leave, the hurt is sincere. When
the departures leave holes virtually impossible to fill, the hurt
gets wrapped in anger.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and Galloway can make narrow business and personal
arguments for doing what they did. Those arguments don't do
anything to fix a sense of abandonment and betrayal, nor do they
repair damage to the franchises.
</P>
<P>
   As the calendar works to dissipate those consequences, it would
be shrewd of the Seahawks and Mariners to pass on any new players
from Dayton or Akron.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
