<SLUG> BC-NY-VETO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY COUNCIL DEMOCRATS PLAN TO DARE A GIULIANI VETO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over the next few weeks, Democrats in the City
Council, led by Speaker Peter Vallone, are planning to approve a
barrage of legislative initiatives that have been strongly opposed
by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, all but daring the mayor to use his veto
powers.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing the bills, some of which have been in committee for
years, the Democratic majority in the council is deliberately
putting itself on a collision course with Giuliani, a Republican,
at a time when he is eager to portray himself as collaborative and
well suited to the U.S. Senate.
 &UR;  &LR;  Democrats, including some council members and Giuliani's Senate
campaign opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, have been just as eager
to portray him otherwise: as an angry autocrat who would be out of
place in the Senate, where political compromise is essential.
</P>
<P>
   The administration maintains that Giuliani's success as a
Republican mayor in a heavily Democratic city is evidence that he
can work cooperatively.
</P>
<P>
   But the council's legislative blitz also reflects a changed
political landscape. As Giuliani runs for Senate and Vallone
prepares to run for mayor next year, the interests of the city's
two most powerful officials have diverged sharply and policy
differences between them have become more stark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of frustration with negotiating in good faith for the
last six or seven months and coming up nowhere,'' said Bruce R.
Bender, Vallone's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Among the council initiatives are bills that would establish
grievance procedures for workfare participants and create a new
transitional jobs program, change some rules that govern the city's
public markets and begin an intense voter registration drive.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the bills would protect workfare recipients from
losing benefits over petty disputes, offer a strong mechanism for
job training and bring more equity to public markets.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani has expressed outspoken opposition to most of the
measures, calling the grievance procedures unnecessary, the
transitional jobs program a reversal of welfare reform, and the
public markets bill an effort to soften his stance against
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   And one senior mayoral aide charged Sunday that the coordinated
action on the bills had been orchestrated by Harold M. Ickes, the
former White House deputy chief of staff who is Clinton's top
political adviser and also a paid political consultant for the
council.
</P>
<P>
   Council officials rejected the charge, saying the bills were
good government policy and pointing out that the measures had been
in the works long before anyone knew who was running for Senate.
And, they said, the measures have been amended to address some of
the mayor's objections.
</P>
<P>
   Senior council officials said Sunday that they were still hoping
to reach a deal with the mayor, but that they were committed to the
legislation and were prepared to override a veto if necessary.
Giuliani administration officials declined to speculate on whether
the mayor would issue any vetoes, saying they doubted the the bills
would even come out of committee.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration officials did not react with the vehement
anger toward the council that they had expressed in the past,
suggesting that Giuliani was not looking for a fight and that they
might be willing to talk. The question is whether the council will
give them time.
</P>
<P>
   Council hearings on the bills are scheduled this week _
transitional jobs Tuesday in the General Welfare Committee,
workfare grievance on Wednesday in the Governmental Operations
Committee and public markets on Thursday in the Economic
Development Committee.
</P>
<P>
   All three hearings are timed to allow the committees to approve
the bills and get them on the agenda for votes by the entire
council at its next full meeting on Feb. 29. Several council
officials said they expected the bills to pass with the support of
Vallone.
</P>
</TEXT>
