<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI VOWS MORE ATTENTION TO UPSTATE VOTE  
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
(ms)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said during a brief trip to
Long Island Sunday that he would eventually spend more time in
upstate New York campaigning for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been criticized in recent weeks by some Republican
leaders who say he has failed to pay enough attention to the
upstate region, which has a large number of undecided voters and is
considered critical to both Giuliani and his Democratic opponent,
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During a campaign stop in Huntington, Giuliani restated his
commitment to being mayor, but as the campaign continues, he said,
he will certainly do more traveling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, as the campaign moves along, we will spend more
time campaigning,'' Giuliani said, before taking an opportunity to
poke fun at Clinton as a campaigner. ``But it will not be a
Hollywood-style campaign or approach to senator. It won't be a
royal tour of the state. It will be directly dealing with people's
problems and giving everything I have to try to solve them.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had a Sunday brunch with local Republican leaders at
the Golden Dolphin Diner in Huntington. (He ordered his standard
chicken Caesar salad.)
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to New York City, he called on President
Clinton to tap into some of the nation's oil reserves to bring down
the cost of home heating oil, which, he said, had more than tripled
in some parts of the state from the beginning of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
