<SLUG> BC-NY-KIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVING SOCIALITE'S MURDER, WITHOUT A BODY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.) (ms) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With 125 witnesses but no body, prosecutors are to
begin their complex circumstantial case Monday against Sante and
Kenneth Kimes, the mother and son accused of killing a wealthy
widow in a plot to steal her Upper East Side mansion.
</P>
<P>
   On July 5, 1998, Irene Zambelli Silverman, a socialite,
disappeared. The Kimeses, tenants in her East 65th Street town
house, were arrested and charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators have never found Silverman's body or any
witnesses to her death. That missing evidence will profoundly shape
and lengthen the trial, being held in state Supreme Court in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecutors will try to throw as much against the wall as they
can and see if it sticks,'' said David Yellen, a visiting law
professor at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   Besides second-degree murder, the Kimeses are charged with
fraud, conspiracy, robbery, larceny, forgery, weapons possession
and eavesdropping, among other crimes. If convicted of all charges,
each could be sentenced to 1311/3 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that after Kimes, 24, rented a room in
Silverman's town house, Kimes, 64, followed her son to New York
from Florida and began forging documents, tapping phones and
hatching schemes to learn Silverman's Social Security number and
secretly gain ownership of the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers plan to argue that Silverman, who was 82 when
she disappeared, is simply missing, not murdered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0025EST &QL; 
