<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTH-DATA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER GROUP OFFERS DATA ON THE VOLUME OF SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For the first time, consumers can learn how often
a particular doctor or hospital in New York performs a certain type
of surgery, in what consumer advocates call an important step
toward arming patients with the information they need to shop for
health care.
</P>
<P>
   A small nonprofit group, the Center for Medical Consumers,
compiled the numbers from data collected on every hospital patient
by the State Health Department. It chose 21 common surgical
procedures, like mastectomy and knee replacement, and determined
how many of each were performed at each hospital, and by each
doctor, across the state in 1998. The center will release the
numbers at a news conference Monday, but they were posted Friday on
its Web site, www.medicalconsumers.org.
</P>
<P>
   Although the numbers can point toward doctors and hospitals with
experience in a field, even advocates acknowledge that the figures
are no better than a crude indicator of expertise, and critics in
state government and the health care industry warn against making
judgments based on volume.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups and state officials both say that what is needed
is a far more detailed evaluation of hospitals and doctors that
takes into account how sick each patient was before treatment, and
the outcome of each patient's case _reports that are years away, if
they are ever produced at all.
</P>
<P>
   For years, consumer groups have called on the state to release
information on the volume of procedures. But the Health Department,
concerned about misinterpretation of the data and caught in a
political tussle between those groups and the health care industry,
has refused.
</P>
<P>
   Many studies have shown that in areas of health care, like heart
surgery and breast cancer treatment, volume correlates with
expertise; in other words, patients tend to fare best when treated
by the doctors and hospitals who treat their ailments most often.
Still, the release of the data on volume remains controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strong correlation between volume and better
outcomes,'' said Arthur A. Levin, director of the center. ``What
startled me about the numbers was that for many procedures, a high
percentage are being done by physicians who do one, two, three of
these a year, not the ones who are doing 50, 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups like Levin's have long pressed the Health
Department to use its vast collection of data to compile detailed
report cards on hospitals and doctors, showing, say, survival rates
for everything from prostate cancer to hepatitis, hospital by
hospital and doctor by doctor. Such an undertaking would be
enormous, requiring that each case be adjusted by myriad risk
factors, like smoking, obesity or blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 state law required the Health Department to produce such
reports for each hospital. (After considerable lobbying by the
Medical Society of the State of New York, the main doctors' group,
the law prohibited the department from producing such reports on
doctors.) The state created a task force, which included Levin, to
advise it on the hospital reports, but it has made little progress
toward producing them.
</P>
<P>
   The department long resisted any form of public disclosure of
the information, in part because doctor and hospital groups wanted
it kept confidential, contending that some of their members would
be unfairly tainted. The state would not even release the raw,
patient-by-patient data for outside analysis until forced to by a
court order obtained several years ago by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Some detailed information on hospital performance is available,
but it is spotty. The state publishes annual hospital report cards
for cardiac surgery. Some private groups have analyzed other areas
of hospital performance, and hospitals sometimes publish statistics
comparing themselves favorably with competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates have said that, short of producing report
cards on hospitals and doctors, the state should at least publish
the data on volume, to show which hospitals and doctors are
experienced at which procedures. But the department has resisted
this call, even though it has collected the information for more
than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``To just put out volume data without taking patient risk
factors into account could possibly be misleading the public,''
said John Signor, a health department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing that the state would not publish the information, Levin
and a colleague painstakingly combed through the information that
was released through The Times' lawsuit to produce the reports it
has published.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Horner, legislative director of the New York Public
Interest Research Group, said that the information gave patients
the power to ask informed and important questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should make a decision based on volume alone,'' said
Horner, whose group is a leading advocate of releasing the data.
``But it allows you to ask intelligent questions. If your doctor
refers you to a surgeon, and you go on this Web site and find that
he's only done that surgery twice, you might want to go back to
your doctor and say, `Why should I go to this surgeon?'''
</P>
<P>
   But some experts are skeptical about how meaningful the data
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volume can be an indicator,'' said Dr. Mark R. Chassin, a
former state health commissioner. ``But it is at very best a weak
proxy for what one really wants, which is really valid data on
risk-adjusted outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital industry also reacted with caution. ``We definitely
recognize that volume is one important variable in judging the
quality of care,'' said Susan Waltman, senior vice president of the
Greater New York Hospital Association. But, she added, ``We
appreciate that the center itself has commented upon some of the
limitations of relying upon volumes of procedures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
