<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5993 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TRADE-SP     02-14 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TRADE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASH OF WILLS LED TO GALLOWAY'S DEPARTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Joey Galloway has the contract he wanted but
the Seahawks could not, and would not, give him. The Seahawks have
multiple picks in the first round of the NFL draft for the next two
years. The Dallas Cowboys have a receiver to replace Michael Irvin
and replenish owner Jerry Jones' ego.
</P>
<P>
   The blockbuster trade between the Seahawks and Cowboys
accomplished all of this Saturday, when Galloway collected a $12.5
million signing bonus as part of his seven-year, $42 million
contract with the Cowboys and the Seahawks acquired Dallas'
first-round draft choices this year and in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But left unanswered was this:
</P>
<P>
   How could Galloway, a player like no other the Seahawks had ever
had, become just another player they no longer have?
</P>
<P>
   The unraveling of this relationship boiled down to a clash of
strong wills _ with coach and general manager Mike Holmgren in one
corner and Galloway in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Each tried to say the right things, during and after Galloway's
101-day holdout. But their body language spoke more clearly.
Galloway did not want to be a part of Holmgren's Seahawks,
especially at what he felt was the club's below-market price. And
as this eight-month ordeal was dragging into it its second
off-season, it was becoming increasingly clear to Holmgren that
Galloway could not stay.
</P>
<P>
   The final realization occurred during the postseason talks
Holmgren held with each of his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started getting a little inkling in our exit interview, when
I really asked him to tell me how he was feeling about the whole
thing,'' Holmgren said after his news conference to announce
completion of the Galloway trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I want you here. You tell me how this is for you,'''
Holmgren said. ``This isn't prison. I don't want anyone feeling
that way. He was good about it, I don't think it was personal. But
that's when I first started thinking this was going to be the only
way to remedy the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   This revelation from that exit meeting, however, was rooted in
Galloway's refusal to enter the new world of the Seahawks _ the way
things are being done and will be done under Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren wants his players, as well as everyone else in the
league, to take him at his word. So when he told Galloway his new
deal would continue to be worked on after Galloway reported to
training camp, Holmgren expected to see the team's leading receiver
on the practice field at Eastern Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   It never happened. Galloway not only sat out all of training
camp and the entire preseason, but the first eight games of the
regular season. The lack of progress in the negotiations, and
things that were said and done during the prolonged impasse, only
served to further fray an already disentangled dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway wanted what he felt was a fair contract, and he felt
some vindication after finally getting it from the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren, however, will not back down from his contention that
the Seahawks offered Galloway what he was worth, as well as his
conviction that the club will not overspend just because owner Paul
Allen has billionaire-deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiscally, we have to change. We have to make good decisions,
particularly on monies that are going to be accumulated down the
road,'' Holmgren said of the spending spree the past three
off-seasons that has left the club all but tapped out on its salary
cap. ``If we find a player we have to have _ (begin italic) have to
have (end italic) _ the numbers still have to make sense to me.
Certainly the resources here allow us to do that. But I also have
to be a good steward of Mr. Allen's money.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway is a proud person who felt disrespected by the
Seahawks' initial offer, and he became disgruntled by the hardline
stance the club took as his holdout went from days to weeks to
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Seattle deteriorated in so many ways,''
Galloway said. ``I'm glad that is behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the easiest way to explain all of this is the simple
fact that Holmgren never shared Galloway's appraisal of his
talents.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying that Galloway's speed and uncanny ability to
explode into an extra gear while seemingly running at full throttle
are unmatched in the NFL. There was no comparison between the
numbers Galloway put up in his first four seasons (261 catches,
4,122 yards and 36 receiving touchdowns) and those of other players
who entered the league at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   But to play in Holmgren's offense, a receiver also must be able
to block, turn a short catch over the middle into a long gain and
sell his routes when he is not the primary receiver.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that Galloway couldn't do these things. It was worse.
He seemed unwilling to do them.
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons, and countless others, Holmgren and Galloway
never reached a common ground. At least they finally realized they
never would.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never did click,'' Holmgren said. ``People will say the
right thing after something like that. But it's one of those
unfortunate things where it never seems to be as good after it's
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides not only agreed to cut their losses, they were able
to turn them into significant gains.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
