<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-CRASH     02-14 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY BOARD SAYS ALASKA AIR PUT OFF FIXING WORN PART 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS 1st and 6th grafs to clarify that inspections were done by
airline ; ADDS 5 grafs at end with background) 
 (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Transportation Safety Board said
Sunday night that a part of the tail assembly on the Alaska
Airlines jet that crashed last month had been found by the airline
to be worn and in need of replacement in September 1997, but that
the airline later decided it was good enough to keep in use.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly in question is a jack screw, a rotating screw that
looks like the ones used to move a garage door up and down, and a
nut that connects to the screw. When the screw turns, the nut rides
up and down, moving the horizontal stabilizer, which makes the nose
of the plane point up or down.
</P>
<P>
   Before the crash, which killed all 88 people aboard, the cockpit
crew radioed to mechanics on the ground that they were having
problems with the stabilizer. And when the Navy recovered the jack
screw and nut from the waters off Los Angeles, the screw was partly
stripped.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not said whether they think this was a cause
or a result of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   During major maintenance checks, mechanics hold the nut still
and push the screw up and down to check for ``end play,'' a measure
of wear.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board chairman, James Hall, said in a statement
Sunday evening that when the airline last performed a major
maintenance of the plane, at a hangar in Oakland, Calif., mechanics
initially noted that the assembly had reached the allowable limit
of its end play.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said, ``the initial planned action was to replace the nut''
during the inspection. But according to the maintenance records, he
said, the next day ``this initial planned action was re-evaluated
and the assembly was re-inspected.''
</P>
<P>
   The second inspection found that the part was within normal
tolerances, he said; according to the records the assembly ``was
re-checked five times with the same result.'' So the plane, an
MD-82, went back out with the same jack screw assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the board would study the maintenance of the rest of
the plane as well as of the stabilizer system from the time the
plane was manufactured, in 1992, until the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration, which last week ordered
emergency inspections of all MD-80s and similar airplanes, said
that 15 planes, including four at Alaska Airlines, may show signs
of problems. Of the others, four were at Delta, two at Airtran (the
airline formerly known as ValuJet), and one each at American,
Continental, TWA, Northwest and Hawaiian Air.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines have until midday Monday to finish inspections, and
until Wednesday to report, although many have already finished. The
FAA is also anticipating hearing later this week from foreign
airlines, which are not bound by its rules but will probably
perform the inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA order will also permanently shorten the time interval
allowed between inspections of the jack screw assembly, to every
650 hours of flying time, or about every three months, said Eliot
Brenner, a spokesman for the agency. He said the previous rules
allowed planes to fly about eight months between inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Garvey, the administrator of the agency, said in an
interview on CNN Sunday morning, ``Obviously, in light of the
accident, we're taking a very, very careful look with the NTSB at
the maintenance records, at the procedures that they have in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   A Federal grand jury has been looking into allegations of
maintenance irregularities at the Oakland, Calif., hangar where the
airline maintains its MD-80s, but is not examining records from the
plane that crashed, according to the airline.
</P>
<P>
   While the cause of the crash is still unknown, the case is
causing the most widespread emergency inspections of jetliners
since the crash of Trans World Airlines Flight 800, a Boeing 747,
in 1996. The crash led to findings of problems and then emergency
inspections on hundreds of another Boeing model, the 737.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the jack screw irregularities found by the
airlines in the last few days remains unknown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
