<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDRY: MAN IN THE WHITE HAT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In Tom Landry's youth, Hollywood created cowboy heroes
in the cinemas. The heroes were good guys who wore white hats and
never did anything wrong. They were fictional.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, who died Saturday at age 75 after a magnificent life,
was real, the last true American cowboy hero. John Wayne, on the
big screen, represented what Tom Landry was really like in life.
Landry became a legendary figure in this country as the coach of
the highly successful Dallas Cowboys. Sports fans across the
country followed him on television as he developed the Cowboys into
America's Team, winning two Super Bowls, competing in three more,
and coaching the squad to 20 consecutive winning seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``People watched him on television and thought he was stoic,''
said former Patriots general manager Bucko Kilroy, who played in
several Pro Bowls with Landry the player, and then worked in Dallas
with him for six years when Landry was starting his brilliant
coaching career. ``But he really wasn't. He was a man of great
principles. He had character, integrity, was very religious, and
treated everyone with respect. He also had a great sense of humor,
but he didn't show it that much to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry grew up in Mission, Texas, near the Mexican border, the
son of a fireman, not a cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   He went to war as a teenager, and was flying US bombers over
enemy territory in Europe during World War II before his 20th
birthday. He flew a bomber on 30 combat missions and was shot down
behind enemy lines.
</P>
<P>
   Landry's older brother, Bob, had been killed in the war before
Landry left the University of Texas, where he was an outstanding
two-way player, to fight for his country. Despite what most of us
now would call the ``Private Ryan Rule,'' under which a member of
the armed forces did not have to go into combat if one of his
siblings already had been killed, Tom Landry decided to fight the
fight. Years later, he was asked how he could balance bombing
people with his strong religious beliefs against violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fighting for my country and what I believed was right,''
said Landry, ``and I think God knew I was on the right side.''
</P>
<P>
   On one mission, Landry was forced to crash-land on the way back
to his base after his plane had taken some hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very lucky to be alive,'' he said. ``We really weren't
sure where we were. There was a thick ground fog where we had to
put the plane down. When we hit the ground, both wings were
stripped off the plane by trees. It just happened that where we
landed was on a farm and our path took us down a row of trees,
knocking off the wings but not doing anything to us.''
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Landry came home to a new adventure,
professional football. He played five years in New York and by the
age of 29 was named defensive coach of the Giants. The offensive
coach was a young college coach named Vince Lombardi.
</P>
<P>
   Together, under head man Jim Lee Howell, they built the
wonderful Giant teams of the 1950s that became the darlings of
football fans across New England in the days before the founding of
the Patriots in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the 1950s that Landry started to show signs of being
an exceptional coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cleveland Browns came into our league and no one could
stop them,'' Steelers owner Dan Rooney recalled Sunday morning,
just hours after Landry died in a Texas hospital after a two-year
battle with leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a great offense with Otto Graham, Mac Speedie, Dante
Lavelli, Marion Motley. We had an off week in our schedule so I
went over with our coach, Walt Kiesling at the time, to scout a
game in Cleveland. They were playing the Giants, and Tom was the
defensive coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The game became a milestone contest in the history of the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landry threw a new defense at Cleveland that day, and shut
them down,'' said Rooney. ``The Giants won in a big upset. Tom had
devised the 4-3 defense, which is still used by most teams in the
league to this day. He did something no one had done before that,
dropped off his defensive ends and used four defensive backs, and
it worked great.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry developed some great defenders for the Giants, such as
Andy Robustelli and Sam Huff, both in the Hall of Fame. Huff gives
credit to Landry for saving his career. Huff was an unheralded
player out of West Virginia and was ready to quit in training camp
as a rookie when Landry talked him into staying and made him the
middle linebacker in his 4-3 alignment. In those days, many of the
players and coaches roomed in the same hotel near Yankee Stadium,
and at night Landry would go to Huff's room and spend hours
teaching him.
</P>
<P>
   Landry finally got his own acclaim when he was named head coach
of the Cowboys in 1960, a job he held for 29 years before being
unceremoniously fired by owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Landry was once asked at a Super Bowl news conference the No. 1
reason he had success in Dallas. When he answered ``a great
owner,'' some of the members of the media started to laugh. But
Landry was serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't win a game the first year I coached,'' he said. ``And
we didn't have a winning year the first six years I coached. One
time there was a lot of talk that I was going to be fired, so Clint
Murchison (the Cowboys' original owner) called a press conference
to announce that he was giving me a new 10-year contract. There
aren't many owners that would have done that with the record we
had.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1966 on, Landry's Cowboys became the force to be reckoned
with in the National Football League. He amassed 270 victories,
third most in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tom was coaching the Giants, Cleveland was the team to
beat,'' said NFL vice president of public relations Greg Aiello,
who spent 10 years with Landry in Dallas before moving to the
league office in New York. ``Tom really admired Paul Brown.coached the game in a suit, tie, hat. Tom dressed the same way, and
had the same sideline demeanor his whole career. Bill Walsh later
said when he started the San Francisco dynasty that he tried to
build his team to beat the Cowboys, and Tom Landry, because he knew
if they wanted to win it all, that's what they had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry dominated Dallas for a quarter-century, but even he did
not know the extent to which he had affected the lives of Cowboys
fans until he was fired, and the city of Dallas had a parade in his
honor. Some 100,000 people turned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the greatest experiences of my life,'' said
Landry. ``To see all of those people, holding signs, yelling out
nice things, got me all choked up. I never experienced anything
like that in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   After he was fired, Landry asked for one last chance to address
his team. He was fired in the offseason and the players were on
vacation. When they returned, he talked to them in the locker room
to thank them for what they had done for him and to wish them well
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got so emotional,'' said Aiello, who was there at the time,
``that Tom couldn't finish. He couldn't get through it. He loved
players. When he coached, he had troubles with some players that
all coaches have, but when they retired, they would always say
great things about him for what he had done for them. He taught
them football. He taught them discipline. And he lived the way he
talked. No one ever called him Tom. We all had great respect for
him, we always called him Coach Landry, even when he wasn't
around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys like me get to paying tribute to those who came
before us, Tom Landry is at the top of that list,'' Bill Parcells
of the Jets said Sunday. ``He was a tremendous person. He was one
of the great innovators in the history of the game, both on offense
(designing the multiple offense) and defense. He was the kind of
coach that every young coach coming along in the league looked up
to. Coaches like him and Don Shula, Vince Lombardi, Paul Brown,
Chuck Noll made it so much easier for guys like me who followed
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve DeOssie, who spent five years with Dallas after being a
fourth-round draft choice out of Boston College, credits Landry
with saving his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had a great training camp my first year because I
had played well in all of the preseason games,'' he said. ``The
final exhibition game against Oakland, I had an interception, a
sack, and made eight tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``On cut day, Landry called me into his office and said, `Son,
what will you do if you don't play pro football?' I went into his
office thinking he was going to tell me I was starting and now he
was talking like he was going to cut me. When I got the lump out of
my throat I told him I'd have to go get a job and support my
family. He told me I was heading in that direction, and if I didn't
practice better, I wouldn't make it in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that day forward, I practiced so hard the other guys
started to get mad at me. Coach Landry was an exacting coach. He
left nothing to chance. Everything was worked on in detail. He was
a fine man. I was in that final meeting when he came to say goodbye
to the players, and everyone in the room choked up with emotion. I
think every player had tears in his eyes. We all were thinking this
is not the way for Coach Landry to end it. He was such a man of
distinction, had so much class, we knew it wasn't right and that's
why it hit all of us so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, this reporter was at a Miami playoff game in
Jacksonville. The great Bob Hayes, known as the world's fastest
human in the 1960s when he won gold medals in the sprints in the
Olympics, was sitting in the back of the press box. Hayes played
for the Cowboys and Landry when he finished college, and even
though he had been down on his luck since retiring, he and Landry
had stayed in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Landry is very sick, you know,'' he said in passing.
``Talked to him on the phone the other day, his voice was so weak I
could barely hear him.'' When I said that was too bad, Hayes
replied, ``Don't worry about Coach Landry. God's got a special
place for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
