u s BC-BKN-ALLSTARGAME-BOS &LR;      02-14 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ALLSTAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL, DUNCAN, GARNETT LEAD WEST ALL-STARS 
</HEADLINE>
 GAME-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ You know the tired cliche to the effect that
``We have seen the future of X and it is blah, blah, blah, etc.?''
</P>
<P>
   This time you can believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The 21st century of NBA basketball is here in the form of the
starting Western Conference front line, a frightening assemblage of
tall, agile, and intelligent players who Sunday demonstrated their
wondrous skills in front of 18,325 Bay Area fans and a worldwide
television audience, leading their team to a 137-126 triumph over
the East in a very entertaining All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   So awe-inspiring were Shaquille O'Neal, Tim Duncan, and Kevin
Garnett, 7-footers all, that ordinary superlatives were completely
inadequate. Never mind that their totals of 70 points, 33 rebounds,
12 assists and 62 percent shooting (33 for 53) represented the
greatest statistical day any starting All-Star frontcourt ever has
had. It was about more than the numbers. It was about power (Shaq),
grace (Garnett), and versatility (Duncan) in physical packages that
never have been seen to this degree in the history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The only good thing for the rest of the league is that when the
game was over the trio had been disbanded. Imagine if they somehow
were placed on the same team for 82 regular-season games and given
the benefit of one style of coaching and a mandate to play defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be scary,'' opined none other than Bill Russell, a
frontcourt observer. ``You know how I always used to say, `Well,
the game is on the schedule, so you might as well play it?' In this
case I'd say, `Take the game off the schedule.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy,'' said Golden State coach Garry St. Jean with a sigh.
``Seventy wins.''
</P>
<P>
   East coach Jeff Van Gundy, who tried to find some way to combat
this majestic trio, thought 70 wins would be underachieving. ``It
would be a record for wins,'' he said. ``They may lose, but I don't
know who it would be. You've got Garnett, with his range, and who
can guard threes (i.e. small forwards) and even some twos (i.e.
shooting guards). You've got Duncan in the low post. You've got
Shaq. I could play point guard on that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny he should mention that. Complicating matters for the
undersized East team was that this dot.com-age frontcourt was being
directed by the game's best young choreographer. That would be
Phoenix guard Jason Kidd, who ooped and alleyed and shot a nice
assortment of passes to this guy and that to rack up a game-high 14
assists.
</P>
<P>
   The East actually hung in gamely through three periods. It was
64-59, West, at the half, and 99-97, West, after three, courtesy of
a falling-down, buzzer-beating putback by Sacramento's Chris
Webber. The East was not exactly impotent, not with potent
mid-sized weapons such as Ray Allen (14), Glenn Robinson (10), and
Slam Dunkmeister Vince Carter (12). And then there was the slithery
Allen Iverson, who led the East with 26 points and nine assists,
spending a great deal of his time at point guard, a position at
which he is, in theory, supposed to be an alien visitor. ``It was
easy,'' he said with a shrug. ``It's very easy when you're playing
with four All-Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   With the East contributing some unforced errors, the West pulled
away in the early stages of the fourth period, doing so with Shaq
on the bench nursing a banged-up shoulder. But when you've got
Duncan and Garnett, you're able to scrape by.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good show from the start. Before the game was five
minutes old, there had been two alley-oop dunks, an indescribable
Iverson spin-o-rama, and a vicious Shaq smash of a play-action
Iverson drive off the glass to start a West fast break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was one of the best All-Star Games in a while,''
said Rick Barry, MVP of the last All-Star Game held in these here
parts (1967). ``They fooled around a little, but you could tell
they all wanted to win, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The East players are no fools; they recognized what they were up
against in that phenomenal West front line. ``It was a pretty good,
exciting game,'' said Carter, ``but they were just too big for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Big is one thing. But big like this is another matter. ``There
have been some big frontcourts in All-Star Games before,'' said the
West's Phil Jackson, who became the first All-Star coach to wear a
campaign button (Bill Bradley, of course). ``What was it, 1984,
when Ralph Sampson was MVP playing alongside Kareem?'' (Close. It
was 1985). ``But there has never been a group this big and this
agile.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq is skipping the Sydney Olympics, so the 2001 All-Star Game
will be the next time we'll see Shaq, Duncan, and Garnett together.
Set the VCR now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
