u s BC-GLF-BUICKINVITATIONAL     02-14 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS LOSES TOUCH IN BUICK 
</HEADLINE>
 INVITATIONAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Having made a pair of double-bogeys in the previous
six holes to let his comfortable lead slip away Sunday in the Buick
Invitational, Phil Mickelson walked slowly to his ball in the 13th
fairway.
</P>
<P>
   It was a par 5 he should have reached in two, but his drive
squirted left into wet rough near a tree, all he could do was punch
out, and now Mickelson was staring at his worst nightmare more than
a hundred yards ahead on the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what everybody was thinking,'' said Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   Which was: Tiger Woods was about to pull another rabbit out of
his hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was only one thing on my mind,'' said Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   Which was: Pull a 9-iron out of his bag and make birdie.
</P>
<P>
   It was a soft shot from 116 yards, not a hard wedge because ``I
didn't want to spin it back off the green,'' and Mickelson landed
it to about 3 feet, an easy birdie that set off a series of shots
that put an end to Woods's pursuit of one of golf's greatest
records.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, settling his nerves down the stretch at Torrey
Pines's South Course, birdied four of the final six holes to shoot
a final-round 70 and halt Woods's streak of six straight victories.
The lefthander who grew up in this city and on this course finished
at 18-under 270, four clear of Woods (68) and Shigeki Maruyama
(72).
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't dog it out there,'' said Woods, whose pursuit of
Byron Nelson's 11 straight victories had captivated the golf world.
``I am disappointed that I didn't win, but I'm proud of how I hung
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Woods, tied for fourth six shots off the lead to
start the day, had pulled square with Mickelson was unthinkable _
even to a guy who had stormed from seven back with seven holes to
play to win last week's AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am. ``I
mean, to even be under par with the way I was hitting the ball
today was a miracle,'' said Woods, who hit just six of 14 fairways
and 10 of 18 greens.
</P>
<P>
   But tied he was, thanks to his 6-foot birdie putt on that 13th
green as Mickelson stood down the fairway. It was Woods's second
straight birdie, his fifth of the day, and put him at 15 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew. Oh, yeah, I knew,'' said Mickelson, whose smile, so
visible earlier in the round, had turned to a stern, blank stare.
The smile had left, not so much because of Woods's birdie-birdie
effort at Nos. 12 and 13, but because of what he had done at the
par-4 seventh and par-3 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way (Woods) has played lately has generated a lot of
interest in golf,'' said Mickelson, ``but I certainly wasn't going
to hand him the tournament _ even though that's what it looked like
I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off three consecutive birdies to get to 19 under,
Mickelson was in the middle of the fairway at the 453-yard seventh,
holding a 5-iron, not to mention leads of six over Maruyama and
seven over Woods. He ballooned his shot left, the ball hitting the
slope next to the green and coming to rest near a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson tried to get cute, left his third shot in the rough,
then chipped 8 feet strong with his fourth. He missed the putt for
bogey and brought Woods back into the picture. Maruyama, too,
though Mickelson's playing partner went out in 37, didn't make a
birdie till the 13th, and was never the threat Woods was.
</P>
<P>
   At the 207-yard 11th, Mickelson pulled his tee shot left and
short, into thick rough. Again, he applied finesse, not reason, and
left his flop shot in the rough to set up another double-bogey. ``I
should have just knocked those shots on the green and taken
bogey,'' said Mickelson. ``I gave back two (each hole) when I
should have given back just one.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with an arsenal of skills that are unmatched, Woods does
not need charity _ but he gratefully accepted the life Mickelson
granted him. Then he decided to take things into his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   At the 468-yard 12th, Woods drove into rough again but chopped a
161-yard 8-iron to 6 feet for his fourth birdie of the day. He was
14 under, one back.
</P>
<P>
   After Mickelson saved par at the 12th and exchanged birdies with
Woods at the 13th, the duel seemingly was on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not won in a while (August, 1998),'' said Mickelson,
``and it was important for me to win again. It was important for me
to go head-to-head against the best.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``the best'' was not at his best on this day. Woods said he
was fighting swing problems all day and there was plenty of
evidence to support his claim. His first drive of the day, in fact,
was pulled left into the gallery. That it hit a chair, bounced in
the fairway, and set up a birdie was a nice break, said Woods, but
indicative of the way things would go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't hitting the ball well enough to catch up. It finally
caught up to me,'' said Woods, who came over the top of a 9-iron
approach from 129 yards on the 14th. From the back of the green
down a slippery slope, Woods rolled it 7 feet strong and missed the
comebacker for his first bogey of the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, his mind set again on attacking pins, split the
fairway at 14, knocked a wedge to 5 feet, and made the birdie to go
to 17 under, three strokes up. Comfortable? Hardly, said Mickelson,
though Woods made it a bit more so with a bogey on the par-3 16th
after burying a 4-iron under the lip of a bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson also bogeyed 16, but said he felt in control. He
showed it, too, with a birdie-birdie finish that took Woods's magic
act out of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mickelson's 14th PGA Tour win, his second here in front
of the home fans, and proved that Woods, despite what recent events
had indicated, is not unbeatable. Was he proud that he was the one
to stop the streak?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Mickelson. ``I would be proud if I could be
the guy who had that six-tournament streak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
