r s BC-BKN-NBA-LADN-(SLANG)     02-14 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ THINKING BIG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Shaquille O'Neal doesn't have the Most Valuable Player
award he so covets. But he's getting closer. He's got half of one.
</P>
<P>
   But the Los Angeles Lakers' mammoth center had barely said
thanks, after earning co-MVP of Sunday's NBA All-Star Game, before
he was already eying a bigger and better trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This award is very nice, but I'm trying to get the big-picture
award,'' said O'Neal, who shared MVP honors with San Antonio's Tim
Duncan after they led the West to a 137-126 victory at The Arena in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim is one up on me, because he has the big-picture award (an
NBA championship),'' O'Neal said. ``This is nice, it's fine. I'll
be a part of history. But the big-picture award is the award I'm
really looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that O'Neal doesn't value these lesser plaques.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he quietly fumed when media voters named the Bulls'
Michael Jordan the All-Star MVP, though O'Neal outscored him (25
points to 20).
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't forgotten the snub.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would not have won today, I still would have moved on,''
he said. ``I moved on in San Antonio when y'all gave it to Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan had the bigger numbers (24 points, 10 rebounds), but
O'Neal got his quicker _ tallying 22 points, nine rebounds and
three blocks in 25 minutes. In deference to a sore right shoulder,
and a six-game road trip that starts Tuesday, West coach Phil
Jackson rested his center the entire fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal, a leading candidate for season MVP, sewed up
Sunday's honor early, as the West led for nearly the entire game
behind his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his time,'' said Lakers teammate and fellow All-Star
Kobe Bryant. ``He's been having a excellent season up to this
point, and whenever we were penetrating, I know personally I was
looking for big fella whenever I got it, try to get him to get this
thing going.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan played 33 minutes and shared the team high in scoring
with Kevin Garnett of the Minnesota Timberwolves. Philadelphia
76ers guard Allen Iverson scored a game-high 26 points and had nine
assists for the East.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of Iverson, Bryant, Garnett and Toronto's
Vince Carter, the game was a bit short on sizzle, rarely arousing
the 18,235 fans in attendance. They saved most of their adulation
for two of the all-time greats _ Jordan and Wilt Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   A Jordan highlights video played during a fourth-quarter
timeout, when Jordan was handed the All-Star host city torch on
behalf of his new employer, the Washington Wizards. Washington has
the game in 2001. The man who handed Jordan the honor was Golden
State Warriors owner Chris Cohan, who as the Bay Area's version of
Donald Sterling, was understandably booed.
</P>
<P>
   A video tribute to Chamberlain, who died in October, played
during a second-quarter timeout, evoking warm applause.
</P>
<P>
   For the live-action highlights, there was Carter, the new
slam-dunk champ, whose first four points came on a reverse jam off
an Iverson lob and a 270-degree spinning slam off the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal also played crowd-pleaser with a series of powerful
dunks, the best a breakaway, 360-degree spinning jam that evolved
so slowly, it looked like a stop-action film. ``Kind of caught me
off guard, I didn't know he had that in him,'' said Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal showed off his ballhandling by leading a coast-to-coast
fast break and laying it up himself.
</P>
<P>
   So make that the Most Versatile Player award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fast break better,'' O'Neal said. ``My teammates
were calling me `The Big Luggage' because of my handles.''
</P>
<P>
   His ballhandling teammate didn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Shaq bringing the ball up, I'm comfortable with it.
I don't know if P.J. (Jackson) is,'' Bryant said with a smile.
``Every time Shaq brings the ball up, I'm out in the lane. . . . He
throws the alley-oops, he can penetrate, so it's cool with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant played 28 minutes and though he had a relatively quiet
game _ 15 points on 7-of-16 shooting _ he displayed a few dunks and
one surprise move: a jump hook early in the third quarter, which he
swished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to throw the sky-hook for Magic (Johnson, who was in
attendance),'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Jackson, coaching his third All-Star Game, played
diplomat on all fronts. He played everyone significant minutes,
save for Utah's Karl Malone (3 minutes) and San Antonio's David
Robinson (7 minutes) _ both aging stars asked out because of
nagging injuries.
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson removed his ``Bill Bradley for President'' pin
before the NBC cameras rolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't told to take it off,'' he said, ``but there was
friendly persuasion. The (Al) Gore people ran in from somewhere, I
don't know where.T.T.T. In fairness to the game, I decided to take
it off.''
</P>
<P>
   This All-Star Game might just as well be remembered for who
!ital!wasn't rebounding, dishing and jamming. No Jordan, for the
first time since 1995. No Charles Barkley and Hakeem Olajuwon,
Patrick Ewing and Mitch Richmond, Scottie Pippen and Shawn Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   In their place was Generation Y2K _ a group of nine first-time
All-Stars. Ushered in was the NBA's era of Iverson, Carter and
Michael Finley. Rasheed Wallace, Glenn Robinson, Jerry Stackhouse
and Allan Houston. Only one new All-Star came from the old school _
Indiana stalwart Dale Davis, in his ninth season.
</P>
<P>
   And even some of the All-Star vets were kids _ Bryant, making
his second appearance, is the youngest at age 21. Duncan and
Garnett are just 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's changing,'' said Seattle's Gary Payton, an
old-timer at 31 years and six All-Star Games. ``The NBA's changing.
The younger guys are playing hoop now and they're doing their
thing. So it's good to see some new things, but in a minute, you
won't see me here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
