<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6007 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RAMPART-ACCOUNT-2ndta     02-14 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-ACCOUNT-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: choked and punched. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   However, the District Attorney's Office had found its own
physician, Dr. Jordan Goodstein, a surgeon at Cedars-Sinai.
Goodstein reviewed Jimenez's medical records, photographs of
Jimenez, a summary of police reports related to the alleged beating
and scientific data from the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Goodstein concluded that ``the material provided to him did not
suggest that Jimenez had any serious injury,'' according to
documents, nor did it indicate the bloody vomit was related to
``blunt force trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodstein argued that it was more likely that Jimenez had a
small injury to his tongue or in his mouth, which was not detected
by the E.R. doctor. That possible, but undetected, cut might have
caused the blood stain on the carpet, he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   According to Goodstein, the presence of mouth cells and saliva
in the blood stain suggested ``the likelihood that this has been
expectorated from the mouth rather than vomited.''
</P>
<P>
   That same issue came up at the LAPD disciplinary hearing. After
testimony from both the emergency room doctor and Goodstein, the
board found the conflicting opinions to be inconclusive and
stressed that any difference of opinion did not nullify other
evidence that Hewitt used unnecessary force.
</P>
<P>
   The board said any speculative cut to the mouth ``could have
occurred after Jimenez struck his head on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the bedsheet on which the E.R. doctor scribbled
Hewitt's name also was entered into evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the disciplinary board relied on the testimony of
the security guard at the hospital and the cop who released Jimenez
from custody, both of whom stated that Jimenez did not look well
and needed medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness testified that he observed a person fitting
Jimenez's description vomiting outside the police station.
</P>
<P>
   And contradictory to the county prosecutors' stance, an LAPD
criminalist testified that the blood on the interview room carpet
was ``consistent with voluminous droppings, not spitting,''
documents reveal.
</P>
<P>
   The District Attorney's Office also raised questions about
Jimenez's credibility as a witness. ``He is a felon on parole for
kidnapping,'' the report noted.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors argued Jimenez lied to investigators about
details of his arrest and claimed he did not know the name of the
officer who released him or the real name of the man he was with
when arrested. He later conceded that he knew his friend Hernandez
and the cop who let him go.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors also surmised Hewitt could argue in court that
the cop who released Jimenez was the real attacker. They said
Jimenez was an informant for that officer and probably did not like
Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, those arguments were rejected by the LAPD Board of
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to tell Officer Hewitt and others who may hear about
this case that we know that the issues of credibility of a gang
member and a hard-core criminal vs. the credibility of a Los
Angeles police officer is of concern to you and may be to many
department employees. And it was an issue to us,'' an LAPD captain
on the board explained.
</P>
<P>
   While the board factored in Jimenez's and Hewitt's credibility,
the captain said, ``We based our decision ... on corroborative
evidence and testimony involving independent witnesses. ... (The)
charges are not hinged on credibility issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply, the board ruled there was enough evidence and
corroborative testimony to conclude that Hewitt beat Jimenez and
deserved to be fired.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the Rampart corruption probe said Hewitt
should be behind bars awaiting a jury trial, not sitting at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put this guy before a jury,'' the source said.
``When is the last time you heard of the Police Department pushing
for the criminal prosecution of one of its own and the DA's Office
refusing to do anything?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disturbing and insulting to the investigators.''
</P>
<P>
   If county prosecutors ultimately opt to put Hewitt on trial,
their own rationale could come back to haunt them.
</P>
<P>
   To make the jury question the charges against him, sources said,
Hewitt could easily submit the prosecutors' March report that
concludes, ``There is insufficient evidence to prove the truth of
the charges.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got all of this evidence,'' the source said. ``I'm telling
you, boxes of it _ and they do this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      02-14 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMOS TO AFFECT REVOLUTION FORTUNES DIRECTLY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Mauricio Ramos might not have won the
duel with Carlos Valderrama Sunday night. But the Revolution's
midfield leader took some strong steps toward establishing a
possession style of play in a 1-0 loss to the Tampa Bay Mutiny in
the MLS preseason tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Valderrama, whose arrival in Tampa last season paved the way for
Ramos to depart, sent a soft, bouncing pass into the penalty area
for Raul Diaz Arce to head into an empty net in the 83d minute.
Defender Gaston Pernia and goalkeeper Ignacio DeLeon collided and
were sprawled near the penalty spot for nearly a minute.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike in the Revolution's opener, a reserve-fueled 2-1 win
over Chicago, the midfield of Leonel Alvarez, John Harkes, Johnny
Torres, and Ramos seemed cohesive. Ramos did not touch the ball for
the first five minutes but his teammates soon began finding him.
And Ramos displayed some accurate left-footed 40-yard bombs toward
the flanks as well as quick touch passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with the main team in the first half; it was
better than in the first game,'' coach Fernando Clavijo said.
``They moved the ball well, forced errors, and played hard and won
50-50 balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo benched Eduardo ``El Tanque'' Hurtado for part of the
game and went with forwards Wolde Harris and Flavio Zuniga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eduardo needs to be motivated,'' Clavijo said. ``He is 10 to
15 pounds overweight. It's not a big issue now because there is
plenty of time before the start of the season, but I want to make
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along he can be a force in this league if he
wants to be. He has suffered because of the loss of Giovanni
(Savarese). But I haven't given up on him. He was unbelievably trim
when he was playing in Ecuador, but then he took a month off.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado blew past a defender in the penalty area and lofted a
perfect cross to Imad Baba, who fired wide on the Revolution's best
chance in the 77th minute. The play concluded an impressive
counterattack started by Marcelo Russomando, and continued as
referee Ali Saheli played the advantage, later cautioning defender
Kalin Bankou.
</P>
<P>
   But Russomando's giveaway led to the goal six minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution added two goalkeepers _ Scott Budnick, formerly
of Tampa Bay and Miami, and DeLeon, 21, of Deportivo Maldonado in
Uruguay. DeLeon, who has Italian citizenship, will likely find a
club in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Russomando, 29, played for Bella Vista, one of Uruguay's most
storied clubs. He and DeLeon are available on free transfers
through the Uruguayan super agent Paco Casal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russomando is used to the libero position and he can solve a
lot of problems,'' said Gonzalo Madrid, a Casal representative and
former rival of Clavijo. ``He has played on the national team, but
Uruguay has a lot of guys like Paolo Montero (Juventus) at that
position.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution dropped two central defenders _ Nicola
Innocentin, 22, and Adolfo Ovalle, 29. Innocentin, a free transfer
who is hoping to qualify for the MLS's junior international
program, will train with Miami, and Ovalle, a veteran of Emelec in
Ecuador, Santiago Morning, and Universidad de Chile, has been
claimed by Dallas . . . The Revolution will play the US Under-20
team in an exhibition Tuesday and another MLS foe either Wednesday
or Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
