<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT FAST OUT OF CHUTE 
</HEADLINE>
 SHOOTOUT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ After he won the pole for the 42d Daytona
500 Saturday, the only driving Dale Jarrett had planned on doing
Sunday was on the golf course. Until, that is, Jarrett's crew
chief, Todd Parrott, threw a wedge into the works and told him to
report for duty at Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was planning on playing golf this morning and I wasn't even
going to run that Bud Shootout qualifier, but Todd said we had to
run it,'' Jarrett said. ``So I showed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett did more than that. The defending NASCAR Winston Cup
champion flexed the muscle of his No. 88 Ford Quality Care Taurus
by outdriving the field in Sundya's 25-lap qualifier to earn a
berth in the Bud Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the 25-lap featured event, Jarrett made it a clean
sweep when he became the first driver to win both the qualifier and
the Bud Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who won the 500 pole with a hot lap of 191.091 miles
per hour, started from the rear of the Shootout's 15-car field. He
never led a lap until he got a late-race push from the No. 18
Pontiac of Bobby Labonte, and motored to an exciting last-lap pass
of the Chevrolet Monte Carlos of runner-up Jeff Gordon and
third-place finisher Sterling Marlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting from 15th, I knew that, as close as the competition
was, our only chance was to do something with the pit stop and for
our crew to make a great stop _ and they did all of those things,''
Jarrett said. ``It's kind of hard to believe, but they got me in
the position and from there it's just being lucky and making the
right moves.''
</P>
<P>
   The race was marred by a last-lap crash in Turn 4 involving
Labonte, Marlin, and Ricky Rudd, Jarrett's teammate whose No. 28
Ford Havoline Taurus spun out after contact with Labonte's car,
slammed into the wall, became airborne before landing on its roof,
and slid to a stop near the start-finish line. Rudd was not hurt,
but his car, a backup, was severely damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby was on the outside and my car just took off pushing,''
Marlin said, taking full responsibility for the accident. ``I was
trying to turn it and it was like the wind got up under the front
end. I thought for a split second I was going to miss him, but it
was my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's car got sideways and slammed into the wall, causing
Rudd to lose control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one really looked bad, but it wasn't really nasty,'' said
Rudd, who survived a particularly nasty wreck 16 years ago in this
event. ``I just hate to see the car get torn up. The car actually
ran better than we thought it was going to run.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Jarrett's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good opportunity for us to see what he had with the
car and run it,'' Jarrett said, ``because we hadn't been in these
type situations, so it gave us a little heads up on that.''
</P>
<P>
   After he won a broken-field runaway in the qualifier, Jarrett
used some perfect pit strategy and a little help from Labonte to
move up in the pack halfway through the 25-lap Shootout. On the
last lap, Marlin went low out of Turn 2 to prevent Gordon from
passing him on the inside, but inadvertently cracked open a window
of opportunity for Jarrett to make a pass outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Jeff and Sterling get side-by-side, I knew they
were giving me a chance then,'' Jarrett said. ``I was hoping
Sterling would stay down there beside him as much as he could
because that was going to give me more of an opportunity. The 18
(Labonte) stayed right with me and it gave me that push I needed
and I really sailed off into Turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exciting race for us, but the pit stop and the pit
strategy is what got me in a position to win the race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
