<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HOPING THEY CAN SHARPEN THEIR SKATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins were given a day off Sunday to regroup
following back-to-back losses in New York to the Rangers and at
home against the Florida Panthers. On the way to the dressing room
after their 5-1 drubbing at the FleetCenter, the Bruins heard a
cascade of loud, heartfelt, deeply frustrated boos from the fans
who stuck around.
</P>
<P>
   From a standings perspective, the Bruins are far from out of it.
However, the way the team is playing right now, it looks completely
out of it. This year has been full of missed opportunities. On
Friday, the Bruins had the chance to tie the Rangers for eighth
place in the Eastern Conference. Instead, their lost weekend has
resulted in the Buffalo Sabres and Pittsburgh Penguins moving ahead
of them.
</P>
<P>
   There was turmoil at the beginning of the year when the club
stumbled out of the gate at 0-5-4. There was turmoil after
Thanksgiving when the Bruins went 3-12-8 during a 23-game span.
There was turmoil when owner Jeremy Jacobs publicly criticized
coach Pat Burns. There was turmoil when right wing Joe Murphy
verbally attacked his coach on several occasions before being fired
for insubordination. And the turmoil continues Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The only tranquil part of the season was a one-month period from
Oct. 23 to Nov. 24 when Boston put together an 11-2-1 run. However,
the team couldn't sustain it.
</P>
<P>
   With 24 games remaining, the Bruins can't seem to get out of
their own way. As captain Ray Bourque said Saturday night after the
Florida game, ``Win one, lose one ain't going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what is wrong with this team, goalie Byron Dafoe
laughed ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the million-dollar question right now,'' he said.
``It's really hard to pinpoint. I can't say it's a lack of effort.
We've been playing hard but mistakes are killing us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were in the Rangers and Panthers games heading into
the third periods _ but then collapsed. One goal led to others and
eventual disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we give up a goal and then we start reeling,'' said
Dafoe. ``With the playoffs looming, we have to find a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the team's thin talent level is an issue. Gone is center
Jason Allison, who won't be back until training camp at the
earliest. Anson Carter is playing out of position and is hurt. Dave
Andreychuk has been severely affected by the loss of Allison. Joe
Thornton is banged up. The defense, which has been suspect all
season, used to be the club's strongest suit. When the perennially
challenged offense fell off, the defense was always there to carry
the day. And the rare time when the defense failed, the goaltending
was there. Too often this season, the team defense is the weak link
and Dafoe has had a hard time.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that when the Bruins gave up three goals in a
game, that was a big deal. Now, it's a routine event. Consider that
last season, in 82 games, the Bruins gave up three or more goals 31
times. Through 58 games this year, the Bruins already have given up
three or more on 30 occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the team goals-against, it's up so much higher
than it was last year,'' said Dafoe, whose club was outscored,
10-3, over the weekend. ``It's tough. I look at my own play and I
ask myself how I can be better. All you can do is keep working.
We're trying to figure it out and it's definitely very frustrating.
Talk about your sleepless nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as the father of an infant son, Dafoe said he has two
reasons keeping him wide awake at night, one a much happier reason
than the other.
</P>
<P>
   So, now what? The team has been assured that Burns won't be
fired this year, a point president/general manager Harry Sinden
hammered home Saturday in an effort to shoot down persistent
speculation about the coach's termination.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the club continues to muddle along, not out of the
race for a postseason berth but looking increasingly like a
nonstarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make excuses for us,'' said Dafoe. ``We're
coming up short.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's one ray of light, Dafoe said it's the fact that a
decent run could change everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope no one is losing sight of that,'' said the netminder,
looking for the silver lining in a season that has been shrouded by
a giant dark cloud. ``It's very much in reach. If we could put a
streak together . . . ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
