<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKY US CHAMPS SLIP OUT OF TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
 FIGURE SKATING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ They were still occupying their thrones when the US
Figure Skating Championships ended here Saturday night, but their
crowns had been knocked askew.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Kwan had won her fourth women's title in five years,
but she won it because she made one mistake and high school rivals
Sasha Cohen and Sarah Hughes each made two. Michael Weiss retained
the men's title he'd inherited from Todd Eldredge, but needed four
artistic tiebreakers to beat 19-year-old Tim Goebel, who made
history by landing three quadruple jumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the old saying in boxing that the champion has to be
knocked out,'' said Carol Heiss Jenkins, Goebel's coach. ``That
usually means a fall or two. It has to be pretty clear-cut. It's
like boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who thinks skating is a sport, not an art, Goebel
knocked the 23-year-old Weiss through the ropes. No man had even
landed one quad at a national championships. Goebel not only nailed
three in a row (one of them a combination), he landed half a dozen
triple jumps.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, who has hit only one quad in competition, couldn't come
close on the only one he tried. He prevailed because Goebel stepped
out of a triple axel in a combination, which prevented him from
getting a string of perfect 6.0 technical marks, and because
Weiss's artistry is more evolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the other side of the stick,'' said Weiss, who
was once labeled an unrefined aerialist. ``I've been in the
position where I was trying quads and Todd Eldredge was beating me.
But the judges have shown they want to see a balanced program.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges also were reluctant to weaken a defending world
medalist by sending him to next month's global championships in
France second in his own country. That sentiment also helped
19-year-old Kwan, who has won two world titles and was runner-up
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought Sasha was going to beat her at all,'' said
John A.W. Nicks, Cohen's coach. ``Michelle is the model of
consistency and she has carried the flag of the United States very
well for years. One flaw in an otherwise excellent program was not
going to hurt her.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if the champs can't bring their stagnant technical side up
to the ever-rising mark, they'll almost certainly be unseated at
next year's championships in Boston _ and they know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my hands full,'' admitted Kwan, who is still stuck on
the same triple toe-triple toe combination she was doing five years
ago and who couldn't even land it here. ``I've just got to put my
mind to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year-old Hughes tried two triple-triples in the long
program and landed one of them. By next year, she'll probably be
able to hit the triple axel (which no woman has done since Tonya
Harding nine years ago) and possibly a quad. The 15-year-old Cohen
doesn't have the triple-triples yet, but she will.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, meanwhile, needs to find time amid her UCLA studies to be
the bold leaper she was at 15. ``At first it was, `She's a jumping
bean,' '' Kwan said. ``Then it was, `She's artistic, she's
beautiful on the ice.' I want to be the jumping bean again _
because I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Weiss can land a quad or three, he'd better start soon,
because the men's bar is ascending rapidly. He won this title with
nothing tougher than a triple axel-triple toe. He won't win another
without an upgrade. And he won't beat the Russians next month.
``I'm definitely going to have to step it up when we go to
Worlds,'' Weiss conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Evocative choreography to ``Carmen'' won't save him in 2001.
Once Goebel, the sport's new midair dervish, can build a polished
program around his quads and boost his artistic marks by a couple
of tenths, he'll be the new king. ``The judges aren't telling me
anything I don't already know,'' said Goebel. ``I just need time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
