<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SHORTTRACK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHNO OUT; WEINSTEIN WINS 
</HEADLINE>
 SPEEDSKATING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALPOLE, Mass. _ After Apolo Anton Ohno was injured in the
quarterfinals, Daniel Weinstein won the 1,000-meter race Sunday,
securing a US spot at the World Cup individual championships. He
also qualified for the World Cup team competition.
</P>
<P>
   When Ohno caught his skate on a marking block in the
quarterfinal heat of the 1,000-meter race, Weinstein had mixed
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, his thought was that the semifinal heat would be
easier, ``but when I saw Apolo hit the boards,'' said Weinstein,
19. ``I realized that the relay team needs him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught the block and my knee popped,'' said Ohno. ``I
freaked when it happened because I couldn't pop my knee back. But
when I sat down, I was able to pop it back.''
</P>
<P>
   That 1,000-meter race in the US Short-Track Championships at
Iorio Arena was key to determining the US men's champion, and with
Ohno off to Children's Hospital in Boston for X-rays, the race was
left to Weinstein, a freshman at Harvard University, and Rusty
Smith, 20, of Sunset Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a marvelous race, as Brookline's Weinstein took the
lead with four laps to go ``and I made an outside move on Rusty,''
he said. ``Then, with two laps to go, he passed me again, and I
passed him right back.''
</P>
<P>
   And the two came to the finish line, skate to skate, with
Weinstein edging Smith, 1:30.761 to 1:30.841. Tom O'Hare, 22, of
St. Louis, was third (1:30.877) and Ian Baranski, 20, of Saratoga
Springs, N.Y., was fourth (1:33.194).
</P>
<P>
   Ohno's X-rays came back negative and he was released from the
hospital. It is unclear whether Ohno will be ready to compete in
the Goodwill Games next weekend in Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apolo has been looking forward to competing in the Goodwill
Games and it's something he really wanted to do,'' said Susan
Ellis, the US National Short-Track team coach. ``But it's too early
to know if he'll be able to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fall and the fact Ohno did not receive any points
for the 1,000-meter race, he will be one of three US skaters
competing in the World Cup individual championships next month in
Sheffield, England. Weinstein, as champion, and Smith, as
runner-up, also will compete. Those three, plus O'Hare and
Baranski, will make up the five-member US team at the World Cup
team championships next month at The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, Amy Peterson, 28, of Ballston Springs,
N.Y., won the US championship, continuing her dominance as she
easily took both the 1,000-meter and 3,000-meter races, just as she
won the 500 meters and 1,500 meters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson and Julie Goskowicz, 19, of Maple Grove, Minn., who
finished second to Peterson in all four races, will represent the
United States in the World Cup individual races at Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   Those two, plus Natick's Caroline Hallisey, 19, who finished
third in the championships despite being disqualified for an
illegal pass during the semifinals of the 1,000 meters, Brigid
Farrell, 17, of Saratoga Springs, and Arlington's Sarah Lang, 22,
will comprise the five-member US team in the World Cup team
competition at The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm six years older than any of the other girls,'' said
Peterson, downplaying the ease of her dominance, ``and I have much
more experience than the other girls. That experience definitely
pays off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peterson, who suffers from chronic fatigue syndrome, belied
her ailment and crushed her competition. Hallisey, who was also
under the weather, was ecstatic at her third-place finish despite
being disqualified and receiving no points in the 1,000 meters. In
fact, Hallisey now seems committed to short-track skating after
saying she was possibly leaning toward long-track skating before
the US Championships began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the best of all passes,'' said Hallisey, explaining
her DQ. ``But I'm really happy to make the team (for the worlds).
To see how strong I was skating, considering how I felt, I might
stick it out now (in short-track).''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein was excited about winning the US title ``before all my
family and my friends from school.'' His US title in the bag,
Weinstein decided to have some fun while breaking from the pack
early in the 3,000 and opening up a huge lead before Smith skated
him down in the final half-lap and eked out a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often, the 3,000 goes slow early with skaters just
standing, but with 25 laps to go, I decided to (break out),'' he
said. ``For some reason, I got the urge.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the US team's chances in international competition, and
Salt Lake City in two years, Weinstein said, ``I'd say we're in the
top four or five (countries) now. But we're definitely moving up.
Apolo's only 17, I'm 19, and Tommy (O'Hare) is the old man at 22.
We're such a young team.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Both Ohno and Weinstein, in fact, are still listed as
juniors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
