<HEADLINE>
WATCH OUT FOR FLAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Kings coach Andy Murray spent Saturday
night channel surfing among eight NHL games on his satellite dish,
but he kept coming back to one team that looked very familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The Calgary Flames are in the midst of a woeful 0-7-1 stretch,
including six consecutive losses heading into tonight's game at the
Staples Center. As Murray watched the Flames lose 4-3 to the
Phoenix Coyotes, he was reminded of his own team's six-game slide
in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go through it, hoping the team continues to play hard and
work its way out,'' Murray said. ``We played some really bad games
at the beginning, then got better but still couldn't win. I
considered us dangerous every time out and the Flames are the same
way right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (25-22-7) have won four of their last five, including
victories over Western Conference elite teams Detroit, Phoenix and
Dallas. In fact, before Saturday's game against Calgary, Coyotes
coach Bob Francis kept his team off the ice and made them watch
tapes of the Kings 5-2 victory over Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary (23-27-6) was the league's surprise club during the
season's first four months, setting an NHL record with 10 overtime
victories. Fred Brathwaite replaced injured veteran Grant Fuhr in
goal and was considered by many an MVP candidate. Now, Brathwaite
has been pulled from a couple of games and replaced by
Jean-Sebastien Giguere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone eight games without a win now and everyone looked
like this, either a one-goal loss or overtime,'' Flames coach Brian
Sutter said after the Phoenix game. ``You know you're right in it
until the end. What you do is dig down a little more in those
situations yourself. It's called growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Audette closer: Second-line winger Donald Audette skated in
practice Sunday for the first time since going on injured reserve a
month ago with a severely sprained left ankle. Audette will not
play tonight but should return early in the Kings seven-game,
11-day trip that begins Wednesday in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference now is pain,'' Audette said. ``I don't have any
now and it makes it much easier to get around on the ice. I'm
excited about getting back. I've been going crazy with boredom.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, however, likes the effort of Audette's replacement,
Jason Blake, and said it would be unfair to make a switch
immediately. Audette skated with the third line in Sunday's
practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
