<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS JUST A BLIP ON WAY TO WOODS' ULTIMATE GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Not all twenty-somethings are like the woman we
recently saw quoted as saying, ``The real drive is to make a lot of
money and retire by the time you're 32.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, the patron saint of Generation Y2K's cabal of
capitalists, could retire right now, at age 24, and live, as you'd
expect the Sultan of Swing would, in obscene opulence.
</P>
<P>
   Since turning professional in the fall of 1996, Woods has
grossed $13,316,379 on the course and several times that much off
it. From a promotional standpoint he is the most prime piece of
property this side of the Sunset Strip, endorsing everything from
clothes and cars to burgers and breakfast cereal to Titleists and
timepieces.
</P>
<P>
   Kids walked around the South Course at Torrey Pines on Sunday
with their faces painted orange with black stripes in deference to
Woods. Because of him, adults were decked out in swooshes. Thanks
to him, the golfers' garish outfits no longer account for all the
color on the course.
</P>
<P>
   And because of him, the Buick Invitational and CBS got a final-
day telecast worthy of the first day of sweeps week.
</P>
<P>
   It was by no means a disappointing ending just because Phil
Mickelson snapped Woods' consecutive win streak at six, hanging on
by his cuticles to beat Woods and Japan's Shigeki Maruyama by four.
</P>
<P>
   Woods did everything but blow on his putter in an effort to roll
a lucky seven. Down six strokes at the beginning of the day, he
pulled to within four of Mickelson with nine holes remaining and
drew even with him with five holes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, his aura evaporated the last five holes. It was four days
coming and as inevitable as Cal Ripken Jr. sitting out a game,
Edwin Moses failing to break the tape, Joe DiMaggio going hitless,
Wayne Gretzky going pointless, the Bucks toppling the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, I feel disappointment,'' said Woods, who
was battling his swing all week. ``I wasn't hitting it good today.
I tried almost everything. At least I made it interesting for
Phil.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it looked like Woods was going to make mincemeat of
Mickelson, the way he had Matt Gogel the previous week in Pebble
Beach. Mickelson carded his second double bogey in five holes at
No. 11 around the time Woods' second consecutive birdie putt was
dropping at No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Woods and Mickelson, a San Diego native, were
even at 15-under par. But for the first time since late August,
Woods blinked first. He played the final five holes in 1-over par
while Mickelson covered the same terrain in 2-under par.
</P>
<P>
   So the streak is dead. Big deal. Byron Nelson, who had 11
consecutive wins in 1948, is the only golfer who ought to be
breathing easier today.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing really ended Sunday. Woods simply completed another leg
of the exhausting Iconman race he seems fully intent on completing.
</P>
<P>
   He is on such a torrid pace, by the time he reaches the finish
line he will have lapped history. Woods is as much an anomaly as
the marathon runner who sprints out of the starting blocks. He
doesn't show any signs of slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Since Woods stood up at a press conference in Milwaukee in the
fall of 1996 and said, ``Hello, World,'' the world has been
smitten, cradling Woods to its bosom.
</P>
<P>
   It's wonderful that Woods hasn't been frozen out, like his idol,
Jack Nicklaus, was in his first few years on the Tour when he was
bearing down on fan favorite Arnold Palmer. Woods deserves the
world's embrace. Not because he swings like Celine Dion sings and
has a smile you can spot a mile away. Not because he takes the job
of being a role model as seriously as he does his day job.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is worthy of applause because he's focused on a finish
line that's not delineated by any streak or monetary target.
</P>
<P>
   Woods doesn't want to win 11 consecutive tournaments because
Nelson did or 18 majors because Nicklaus did. He wants to win every
time he tees it up because he is addicted to competition.
</P>
<P>
   Golf is his drug.
</P>
<P>
   Not fame. Not fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Simply sport.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play for the thrill of it,'' Woods said. ``You play for the
first three-and-a-half days to give yourself a chance on the back
nine on Sunday. You give it everything you have and there's no
regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has played in 73 events as a pro and finished first or
second in 22 of them. He has been a junkie, indiscriminately
feeding his craving for competition.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt any relief to put the pressure of the streak
behind him, Woods replied, ``I wish I could say there was. I don't
know if you can be too excited about finishing second.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he's hopelessly addicted to the highs of his sport.
If he's not careful, it'll end up being history's undoing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
