<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-ALL-STAR-GAME-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST IS BEST IN NBA ALL-STAR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The enormous power and brute strength was
enough to make Western Conference coach Phil Jackson a little
giddy.
</P>
<P>
   As if his group of all-stars weren't towering enough, Jackson
wanted to drive home the point by starting five 7-footers.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so that was the big joke in the locker room before the West
bullied the Eastern Conference in a 137-126 victory Sunday at the
Arena in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   When the West's front line of Shaquille O'Neal, Kevin Garnett
and Tim Duncan finished decimating a considerably smaller East
squad inside, the punch line to the NBA's 49th All-Star Game was
simple:
</P>
<P>
   Size matters, a lot.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, Duncan and Garnett combined for 70 points and 33
rebounds, and that was all the West needed to snap a four-game
All-Star losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in here arguing before the game because Kevin wanted
to play the point,'' starting West point guard Jason Kidd said,
smiling. ``That's a monster front line. And all of those guys can
handle the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, the Triple Towers are more of an authority when
it comes to finishing plays.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and O'Neal were the most dominant players on the floor
and shared the game's Most Valuable Player award. They were
primarily the reasons Kidd collected a game-high 14 assists in
front of his hometown fans.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Oakland native and Sonics guard Gary Payton came off the
bench for the West and dished out eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   The West, which won the midseason classic for just the 18th
time, had a simple gameplan. If the fastbreak or spectacular play
wasn't available, just lob the ball to the middle. Something good
or earth-shattering was bound to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The West outscored the East, 86-54, in the paint and finished
with a 58-46 edge in rebounds. No one on the East had more than
eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a battle of size versus quickness,'' said Duncan, who
missed just two of 14 shots and grabbed 14 rebounds. ``There's so
much talent on both sides. And on this given day, the size won.
Hopefully, (the power) keeps swinging to the West side because we'd
love to keep on winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The West roster had seven players 6-foot-9 or taller, with
Duncan (7-foot), O'Neal (7-1) and David Robinson (7-1) the biggest
giants. Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo (7-2) was the only man who
matched up for the East, which had just three players over 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing in the NBA is not one dominant player,''
Garnett said. `` ... And the big man has transcended the game,
handling the ball and having a 6-11 guy in the small forward
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who felt as though he was overlooked for MVP at the 1996
All-Star Game in San Antonio, played as if he were on a mission. He
converted 11 of 20 field goals and didn't play in the fourth
quarter. O'Neal also got a rise out of the crowd in the second
quarter when he dribbled the length of the court and scooped in a
layup.
</P>
<P>
   About 95 percent of his other scores were dunks. O'Neal said he
wasn't trying to win the MVP as much as he was making a statement
about where he intends to be in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nice and exciting. I'll be a part of history,'' said
O'Neal, who also had fun converting a 360-degree dunk on one
fastbreak. ``But the big-picture award (NBA championship) is the
award I'm really looking for. If we would not have won today, I
still would have moved on. I moved on in San Antonio when you (the
media) gave it to Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan attended Sunday but only as a spectator. And even he
would not have made a difference for the East this time.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Allen Iverson, the league scoring leader, was
Jordanesque in his first all-star appearance, finishing with a
game-high 26 points. And when Iverson wasn't scoring, he tried to
set up Toronto leaper Vince Carter for highlight reel dunks and
finished with nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys did a great job of finishing when I gave them passes,
and they didn't take anything away from my game,'' Iverson said.
``A lot of guys were so unselfish, they wanted to bring the ball
down and have me run off screens.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the East made several runs, its only lead was 97-95
late in the third quarter. And that was brief. Duncan immediately
tied the game with a thunderous dunk, and Chris Webber put back a
Payton miss for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The West took control for good with a 20-9 run to start the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a historical front line, there,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the West's smaller players were nonfactors. Kidd had
the most assists in an All-Star game since Payton recorded 15 in
1995. The game also marked the first time Payton and Kidd played
together professionally in their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Payton actually ignited Kidd's game when he came off the bench
in the first quarter and set up Kidd for two open jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get him in the flow,'' Payton said. ``He
didn't take a shot until I got in there. So I drew the double team
and got the ball to him. He started to look more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton didn't look to score, but he is the most accomplished
Oakland product in the NBA. That was confirmed when Payton received
the loudest ovation of any player during pregame introductions.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much chance Payton and Kidd would share MVP. They
were on the floor together for a total of six minutes in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Karl Malone and John Stockton get (co-MVP) in Salt Lake
City, and getting it here would have been awesome,'' Kidd said.
``But it didn't put a damper on the weekend. We won, we stopped our
losing streak and we had a lot of fun. That was the key.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
