<HEADER>
A6023 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-ANITA-LADN-(SLANG     02-14 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ANITA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARE HAS MYSTIQUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ If Manistique didn't stamp herself as the best
older mare in the West with Sunday's muddy victory in the $200,000
Santa Maria Handicap at Santa Anita, she certainly cast herself as
the best on this track.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year-old daughter of Unbridled won her fifth
consecutive race at Santa Anita in as many tries, giving owner
Marshall Naify's 505 Farms its second consecutive victory with this
sturdy horse.
</P>
<P>
   Manistique, who carried 125 pounds, gave away five to 15 pounds
to her seven rivals, but it meant little in the end as she won for
the 11th time to push her earnings over $11 million in 15 career
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about that?'' Manistique's trainer, John Shirreffs, said.
``I'm extremely proud of her because she didn't have the best of it
today weight-wise, and she was squeezed coming out of the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Manistique's reputation started to come into question outside
California with a disappointing eighth place in November's
Breeders' Cup Distaff at Gulfstream Park, making her 0-3 outside
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Here, she has no rival, but her dominance was starting to slip.
In her previous four starts, she finished second at Del Mar last
August, won by a neck at Santa Anita in October and had an
impressive victory at Hollywood Park in December to show Shirreffs
she means business again.
</P>
<P>
   She strengthened her reputation again Sunday by beating a modest
field in the Grade I feature. She is now unbeaten in 11 starts at
Santa Anita and Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so rewarding because some of the Racing Form people
have been knocking her a little,'' Shirreffs said. ``So this is
really nice because this is one of the best fields she's ever run
against in California.''
</P>
<P>
   The Robert Frankel-trained Keeper Hill and Argentine-bred
Bordelaise figured to challenge Manistique. But under the urging of
jockey Corey Nakatani, she took the lead just past the eighth pole
and held off Snowberg and Gourmet Girl. Bordelaise and Keeper Hill
faded to the back of the pack, finishing seventh and eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeper Hill looked magnificent and so did (Bordelaise),''
Shirreffs said. ``I was a little worried when she (Manistique) was
four-wide, but Nakatani rode a good race because he didn't get
really hung out there badly. He kind of waited a little bit until
he got around the turn before he started going with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in her worst races, she digs it out when she's close to
the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakatani said he moved her outside because the track wasn't that
muddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to move her out of the dirt and get her comfortable
early,'' he said. ``She settled real nicely. The track is not that
bad out wide today. I was still sitting on her around the turn and
she just kept picking them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then she did slip a few times in the lane and hesitated a
little when she got to the track marks, so I got after her a couple
of times late. She's just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Manistique returned $5.20, $3.60 and $2.60 as the betting
favorite. The Santa Maria is the second of two preps for the
$300,000 Santa Margarita Invitational Handicap March 5.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Anees, last year's Breeders' Cup Juvenile champion and
Eclipse Award winner as a two-year-old colt, was expected to make
his return to training over the weekend after being sidelined with
a bruised foot.
</P>
<P>
   However, the rains and muddy conditions forced trainer Alex
Hassle Jr., to wait until the skies clear. . . .
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas' Surfside, a 1-7 winner against a field of four
in Saturday's $200,000 Las Virgenes Stakes for three-year-old
fillies, produced an track-low exacta payoff of $2.10. . . .
</P>
<P>
   A week from today, Santa Anita will celebrate President's Day
with a special Monday (Feb. 21) card featuring the $200,000 San
Luis Obispo Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   A better reason to visit the track: Santa Anita will randomly
distribute parts of $100,000 as fans enter.
</P>
<P>
   Each paid adult receives a free wallet filled with coupons for
restaurants and attractions worth more than $100. One lucky fan
will open a wallet with $50,000. An additional $50,000 in cash will
be distributed to other fans in attendance.
</P>
</TEXT>
