<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-PATIENTS-RIGHTS-     02-14 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PATIENTS-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE PUSH FOR PATIENTS' RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Feb. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Senate and House approved vastly different
patients' rights bills. After months of delay, a conference
committee will meet later this month to reconcile the differences.
It is crucial that any compromise bill apply to all insured
Americans and give them a meaningful right to sue health plans for
damages incurred when care is improperly denied.
</P>
<P>
   The two bills differ greatly in the number of people covered and
their right to sue. The excellent House bill, sponsored by Charlie
Norwood and John Dingell, would cover all 161 million Americans who
have private insurance. It would also change federal law to permit
patients to sue their health plans in state courts under state
laws. This strong measure was approved by an impressive bipartisan
vote of 275-151 and has White House support.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the provisions of the weaker Senate bill, by contrast,
would apply only to the 48 million Americans in ``self-insured''
plans that are exempt from state regulation. The Senate bill
provides no right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Given this gulf, progress toward a viable compromise could take
months. But election-year politics may force some movement. After
all, 68 renegade House Republicans voted for the comprehensive
bill, a humiliating defeat for Speaker Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans, who have been adamantly opposed to
comprehensive legislation, seem to know this is a potent issue for
the Democrats. The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, recently
said a compromise might have to include a limited right to sue in
certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential politics is also putting a squeeze on Congress.
Both Democratic candidates, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen.
Bill Bradley, support the House bill. Even the top Republican
rivals, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain, support
some liability provisions. Bush backs federal legislation that
would mirror the patient protections laws in Texas. McCain says he
would support lawsuits after patients have gone through a full
review process, but with a cap on noneconomic damages.
</P>
<P>
   The conference committee is stacked with House members who voted
against the Norwood-Dingell bill. They may try to produce a final
bill that sounds consumer-friendly without providing true
protections. But the public wants more power over its health care,
and Republicans should grant it or they will suffer politically on
this issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
