<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-3R     02-14 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S PRESIDENT SUSPENDS ACCUSED GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS 2nd graf with Wiranto bowing to President's order; EDITS 3rd
graf to conform; ADDS reaction of armed forces commander in 9th
graf) 
 (ms) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ President Abdurrahman Wahid on Sunday
backed away from his demand for the resignation of his defiant
security minister, General Wiranto, then turned around hours later
and suspended him.
</P>
<P>
   The general Monday morning bowed to the president's order,
saying, ``The fact that the president took a differ- ent decision
today, I don't know why, but it's his right and we must accept
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's apparent flip-flop came on the day he returned
from a two-week foreign trip during which he had repeatedly urged
the general to step down but constantly changed the details and
emphasis of his statements.
</P>
<P>
   The president's unusual long-distance confrontation had created
uncertainty in Jakarta and in foreign financial markets. It had
raised questions over whether he was cleverly pressuring the
general and smoking out enemies or whether he was not in full
control of his own impulsive statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't change my mind,'' the president insisted to reporters
this Monday morning. ``Yesterday I said that he will be examined by
the attorney general's office. Then after that he will resign. That
still applies.''
</P>
<P>
   But his Cabinet secretary, Marsi-H lam Simanjuntak, did call the
sus- pension a ``new decision,'' saying the president had decided
on the suspen- sion on Sunday night ``for the sake of the
government's stability.''
</P>
<P>
   The net result seemed to be that Wahid had succeeded in assert-
ing his dominance over the general but had reinforced doubts about
his own consistency and management style.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation with the country's most prominent military
figure also turned the president's policy of assertion of civilian
control into a dangerous crisis. It raised fears of a military
coup, fueled in part by Wahid's warnings, although the top armed
forces commander, Adm. Widodo Adi Sutjipto, said Monday that the
military supported the suspen- sion of Wiranto. And it left in
question both Wahid's personnel policies and the steadiness of his
stewardship as president.
</P>
<P>
   His demands for resignation had followed a report by a local
investigating commission that said the general _ Indonesia's most
prominent military man _ should face trial for his part in
atrocities committed in East Timor last year in which hundreds of
people died.
</P>
<P>
   The president's unusual behavior went so far as ordering Defense
Minister Juwono Sudarsono _ technically Wiranto's subordinate _ to
tell the general to resign. But the president chose not to issue a
direct order to the general.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to this verbal onslaught, Wiranto refused to resign
until he could speak directly with the president.
</P>
<P>
   That moment came hours after Wahid returned early Sunday to
Jakarta, in a meeting that also included Vice President Megawati
Sukarnoputri and the attorney general, who is charged with
investigating the general.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid then met with reporters and said, ``I asked him to resign
but he said he preferred to be investigated by a legal process and
I said, `OK' We have to give him a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I have the prerogative to replace my ministers. But
we abide by the law. If the results of the report implicate him,
then he must resign.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to an expected report by the attorney general,
Marzuki Darusman, on whether Wiranto should be put on trial for the
violence and destruction that followed East Timor's vote last
August for independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Then, late at night, the president again met with Wiranto,
emerging at midnight to tell a small group of reporters that he had
suspended the general pending the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Many Indonesians remained confused Monday by their garrulous
president, and some analysts said he may have devalued the power of
his word by constantly changing it and by failing to demand
obedience.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some analysts said, it was notable that
during two weeks of sparring, Wiranto failed to garner strong
support from within the military, with several prominent commanders
asserting their allegiance to civilian control.
</P>
<P>
   While the president may have appeared weak or vacillating in
terms of his personal command, he did emphasize the supremacy of
law in the first of his statements Sunday, placing the general's
fate in the hands of the attorney general, placing the issue in the
hands of the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the right to change my ministers,'' the president said.
``But we have to abide by the law. If the results of the report
implicate him, then he must resign, as I have already said
before.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what he has said is that he wanted the general to
resign immediately, even before any results or preliminary findings
are made. But he has declined to exercise his right to fire his
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Those who see cunning in Wahid's seemingly off-the-cuff style
say it seems to have the effect of pummeling his targets in his
chosen direction with a mixture of verbal rabbit punches, jokes and
expressions of personal regard. He is a difficult man to understand
or to grapple with.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no problem,'' Wahid said at his first news conference
Sunday. ``Wiranto and I are good friends. It is the media that
perceives us to be enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president must be held responsible for the perceptions
of the media, said Dewi Fortuna Anwar, a political analyst who was
a top aide to former president B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   The past two weeks had created unnecessarily a sense of
nervousness and uncertainty, including a surge of coup rumors to
which Wahid had himself contributed directly, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are the losers here,'' she said of the president and the
general. ``And it was quite unnecessary. And it could all have been
done in a more dignified way.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the president had stated that one reason he
wanted the general to resign was to strengthen confidence among
foreign investors and financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the effect, in the short term at least, may have been the
opposite. Jakarta's stock exchange and the value of its currency
have slipped during the past two weeks and some analysts said they
expected further slippage in the coming week following the seeming
retreat by the president.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his seemingly impulsive verbal fits and starts, however,
there is a consistent direction to the president's policies, toward
democracy, openness, tolerance and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to rule by fiat, Wahid is revolutionizing leadership
in Indonesia after 32 years of autocratic rule by former president
Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   By delegating the outcome of his standoff with Wiranto to his
highly respected attorney general, the president seemed to be
subordinating both the executive and the military to the rule of
law.
</P>
<P>
   But then on Sunday, in a style that continues to keep
Indonesians off balance, he seemed to have a late-night change of
mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
