<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SUHARTO-NYT &LR;      02-14 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SUHARTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SUHARTO AS SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Feb. 14:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During his 32-year rule over Indonesia, former President Suharto
is widely believed to have amassed billions of dollars in illegal
wealth for himself, his children and his political cronies. An
investigation of Suharto was one of the loudest demands of
opponents whose demonstrations helped bring an end to his
military-backed dictatorship in May 1998. But until now, no serious
effort had been made to bring Suharto to account.
</P>
<P>
   So the announcement last week that Indonesia's new government
named Suharto as a suspect in a widening corruption inquiry came as
encouraging news. It is further evidence that President Abdurrahman
Wahid is taking seriously the importance of coming to terms with
past abuses as he tries to construct a new democratic society based
on the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation of Suharto carried out by his successor and
friend, B.J. Habibie, was half-hearted and ultimately was dropped.
The decision to abandon the case contributed to Habibie's defeat in
last year's election. The new attorney general, Marzuki Darusman,
is examining whether Suharto laundered millions of dollars through
charitable organizations he owned. Investigators also want to
question Suharto about monopolies in cloves and fruits that were
run by his children.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's lawyers say their client is too infirm to face
prosecution. The former president, 78, was hospitalized twice last
year after suffering a stroke. It will be for Indonesian courts to
weigh that claim if charges are filed. Wahid may have been
premature in promising to pardon Suharto if he is convicted, but
the issue before Indonesia is not so much whether Suharto spends
time in prison as whether the law applies equally to all citizens.
His conviction, if warranted by the evidence, would affirm that
principle.
</P>
<P>
   The rule of law must also apply to General Wiranto, Indonesia's
most powerful military figure. A government human rights commission
recently found him responsible for much of the violence carried out
by pro-Indonesian militias on East Timor last year. Sunday, Wahid
initially dropped his demand for Wiranto's immediate resignation
from the cabinet, saying he would wait until the attorney general
determined whether to indict him. Hours later Wahid suspended the
general. The human rights commission's findings were sufficient
grounds to dismiss Wiranto. The continued development of democracy
in Indonesia requires that Suharto and Wiranto be held accountable
for any proven misconduct.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
