<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-TOILETS-NYT &LR;      02-14 0264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-TOILETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK'S MISSING FACILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Feb. 14:
</P>
<P>
   A decade would seem to be an excessive amount of time to wait
for public toilets in New York City. But as Clyde Haberman reminded
us in Friday's New York Times, this somewhat mysterious delay has
left many New Yorkers and perhaps even more tourists stranded
without some of the most basic facilities of a civilized world.
</P>
<P>
   Several mayors have circled this problem but never found a
solution. The plan that disappeared about three years ago under
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's watch would have added toilets to small
public oases around the city, where a visitor could use the phone,
buy a newspaper, wait for the bus or use a modern outdoor privy.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, when the mayor asked the City Council to extend a
contract for bus shelters, City Council Speaker Peter Vallone
announced he also wanted some $5 million for about 50 public
toilets. The proposal is still in the concept stage, Vallone's
office reports, but the idea was to think less grandly at the
start.
</P>
<P>
   How this would be done is still a mystery, both at the council
and in the mayor's offices. But if both the mayor and the speaker
want toilets, as one aide suggests, the whole thing could
presumably hapen pretty quickly, perhaps by the end of the summer.
As late as that is, it is worth the effort. The powers at City Hall
ought to ensure that a necessity finally becomes a reality on the
streets of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
