</P>
<P>
   _ By JILL ABRAMSON
</P>
<P>
   The Return of Mortadella &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, the traditional pork sausage of Bologna,
mortadella, was as illegal in the United States as Cuban cigars
and, accordingly, just as valued by connoisseurs.
</P>
<P>
   Mortadella lovers have been known to sneak the delicacy past
U.S. customs inside metal containers to hide the scent from
meat-sniffing dogs.
</P>
<P>
   To advance trade negotiations with the increasingly intransigent
European Union, the Agriculture Department lifted its ban, a
long-awaited reversal that was greeted in Italy as a moral
vindication along the lines of the exoneration of Alfred Dreyfus.
Italian pork products were banned in America after an outbreak of
African swine fever in Italy in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Mortadella costs more than twice as much in Italy as
American-made bologna, and Italian producers say that most
Americans have no idea what the real thing tastes like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even try it,'' Rino Brini, 80, a co-founder of the
Alcisa pork factory in Bologna, said of American bologna. ``It
looks so sad.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALESSANDRA STANLEY
</P>
<P>
   A Setback in North Ireland After Delay in Disarmament  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 weeks after it began, the power-sharing government of
Catholics and Protestants in Northern Ireland came to an end,
aborted by the continuing conflict over the issue of paramilitary
weapons. Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson said
he acted because the Irish Republican Army refused to give any sign
that it was going to dismantle its arsenal. He expected the
government to return ``on an even firmer footing,'' he said, if the
long-running dispute could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, tried to
deflect blame for the action, saying the breakdown increased the
complications surrounding guerrilla disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   1990s' Productivity Makes It Best Decade Since 1960s
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s economic expansion, now the longest expansion in the
nation's history, draws its staying power from various wells _ the
two most important being the booming stock market and labor's
rising efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market makes people feel wealthy, encouraging them to
spend. To help satisfy this rising demand, America's workers are
managing to produce more goods and services in each hour of work.
Their rising output keeps the economy growing and plays a big role
in extending the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows just why workers have become more productive
in recent years, or for how long they will continue to grow more
efficient, as they did in the last six months of 1999. The Labor
Department announced last week that productivity, or output per
hour, had risen at an annual rate of 5 percent from June through
December, the best performance in seven years. And the expansion
marches on.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LOUIS UCHITELLE
</P>
<P>
   Hijacking Ends
</P>
<P>
   The four-day hijacking of an Afghan airliner at Stansted Airport
outside of London ended peacefully and with no injuries when the
hijackers surrendered unconditionally on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But more than half the people on the plane, Afghans who had been
on a domestic flight from Kabul when the Ariana Airlines Boeing 727
was seized, asked for political asylum. The Home Office pledged to
decide their cases as soon as possible, with a view toward ejecting
the Afghans from Britain. Twenty-two people were arrested and will
be charged under hijacking and terrorism laws.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SARAH LYALL
</P>
<P>
   LAPD Blues  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A brutal police corruption scandal that had largely been
contained to one anti-gang unit is now threatening to engulf the
Los Angeles Police Department, with the district attorney having
declared for the first time that the investigation has broadened to
other police divisions and that the police have been dragging their
feet.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 40 tainted cases now overturned, the new
disclosures of abuse have led to demands for an outside
investigation, perhaps by federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES STERNGOLD
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: JAMES STERNGOLD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Big Bang Reproduced Small  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The birth of the universe is looking less mysterious all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists in Geneva announced that they had recreated a bizarre
form of matter that probably filled the entire universe when it was
a mere 10 millionths of a second old and expanding as a fireball.
The scientists, at the CERN particle physics laboratory, succeeded
in getting the reclusive particles called quarks to roam freely for
the first time in an experiment. Quarks are normally locked inside
protons and neutrons and cannot be knocked loose.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement could help scientists understand what ignited
the Big Bang explosion that they believe created the universe in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES GLANZ
</P>
<P>
   Getting a Day in Court
</P>
<P>
   Victims of gay-bashing, wife-beating and other crimes based on
gender or sexual orientation could have an easier time in court if
the Illinois General Assembly approves a bill introduced in the
House of Representatives that would enable them to sue any person,
company or organization responsible for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is modeled on the federal Violence Against Women Act, a
1994 law that enables women to sue their attackers in federal
court. The Illinois law would extend similar protections to crime
victims singled out because of their sexual orientation or gender.
The Supreme Court is now considering a challenge to the federal
law; the main issue is whether jurisdiction for such laws should
lie with the states.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBYN MEREDITH
</P>
<P>
   Adjusted Auction Fees
</P>
<P>
   Faced with class-action lawsuits and a three-year-old antitrust
investigation into possible collusion between Sotheby's and
Christie's, the world's two largest auction houses, Christie's said
it was changing its fees. The English-based house has raised its
buyer's commissions, charging 17.5 percent on the first $80,000 and
10 percent of any amount over that. Since 1993 both Christie's and
its archrival Sotheby's charged buyers 15 percent for the first
$50,000 and 10 percent for everything after that.
</P>
<P>
   Though it may now be pricier to buy at Christie's, the company
is making it cheaper to sell. Previously, sellers paid a fixed
scale ranging from 2 percent to 20 percent. Now it will give
customers who buy a lot of art cheaper rates when they sell.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's is expected follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAROL VOGEL
</P>
<P>
   No Untested Pills For Mothers-to-be  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Food and Drug Administration recently announced that
dietary supplements could be marketed for morning sickness, experts
in birth defects were outraged. They reminded the agency of how, in
the 1960s, it refused to approve thalidomide, a drug that maimed
thousands of babies whose mothers took it overseas. The arguments
worked; the FDA forbade supplement manufacturers from marketing to
pregnant women until the risks can be studied.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG
</P>
<P>
   A Ban for a Gay Club
</P>
<P>
   A high school gay tolerance group in the conservative community
of Orange, Calif., held its first meeting in school Wednesday over
the objections of the school district, which argues that the club
should be banned because its issues of sexuality are inappropriate.
On Thursday, school officials banned noncurricular clubs in
elementary and middle schools.
</P>
<P>
   Until the matter is settled in court, a federal court order
enables the students to continue meeting. In the meantime, school
officials are considering new requirements for participation in
noncurricular clubs in high school organizations.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA WHITAKER
</P>
<P>
   A Charge of Corruption
</P>
<P>
   Sick, reviled and in seclusion, former President Suharto of
Indonesia faces a legal threat from the government, which said it
would charge him for corruption in the amassing of illegal wealth.
The government's move seemed part of a serious effort to come to
terms with the abuses of the past.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH MYDANS
</P>
