<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 20)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WHILE I WAS GONE &LR;  By Sue Miller. Ballantine, $12.95. The
heroine of this fictional meditation on marital fidelity is a New
England veterinarian torn between her complex feelings for her
husband (a minister) and her equally complex fantasies about
another man (an old housemate). The result is ``a beautiful and
frightening book, one that many readers will find it difficult to
forget,'' Jay Parini wrote in The New York Times Book Review last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THROWIM WAY LEG: Tree-Kangaroos, Possums, and Penis Gourds _ On
the Track of Unknown Mammals in Wildest New Guinea &LR;  By Tim
Flannery. Grove, $14. A celebrated Australian scientist recounts
his many long research excursions into the wilds of New Guinea,
harrowing journeys during which he encountered cannibals, ghastly
diseases, a giant gold mine, shrieking frogs and a hungry 10-foot
black python. He still managed to identify at least 17 new species
of mammals. ```Throwim Way Leg' is more than an account of his
fieldwork,'' D.J.R. Bruckner wrote last year. ``It is an
enthralling introduction to the mountain people of New Guinea _
unimaginably remote, charming, cunning, cruel, subtle and appealing
_ and to their magnificent land.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ORIGINAL BLISS &LR;  By A.L. Kennedy. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
In this novel, a Scottish woman, suffering from a loss of faith and
hungry for love and human touch not to be had from her brutish
husband, falls into a dark romance with a pop-psych guru. ``Kennedy
is a world-class fiction writer'' whose ``characters inhabit her
text in full flesh,'' Thomas Lynch wrote in The New York Times Book
Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RAY CHARLES: Man and Music &LR;  By Michael Lydon. Riverhead,
$14.95. This biography seeks to portray the many faces of the
rhythm-and-blues legend: drug addict, womanizer, blind man, black
man, self-reliant businessman and, above all, musical genius. Last
year the reviewer Nelson George praised ``Lydon's dogged detailing
of Charles' rise, triumphs and bittersweet old age.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SINGERS AND THE SONG II &LR; , by Gene Lees (Oxford University,
$15.95), combines material from the author's 1987 collection of
essays on jazz and popular song, including profiles of Frank
Sinatra and Peggy Lee, with seven new essays on Ella Fitzgerald and
other artists of the pre-rock era. ``The earlier pieces have been
expanded ... to good effect,'' Terry Teachout wrote in 1998,
``while the later ones are of uniformly high quality.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY GERMAN QUESTION: Growing Up in Nazi Berlin &LR;  By Peter Gay.
Yale University, $10.95. A cultural historian and Freudian scholar
recalls his youth in 1930s Berlin as part of a Jewish family who
believed themselves to be virtually assimilated. In 1998 the
reviewer Frank Kermode called Gay ``a quietly remarkable character,
civilized, learned, yet incapable of wholly forgetting or forgiving
the hideous cruelties that threatened his life as a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FREEDOM SONG: Three Novels &LR;  By Amit Chaudhuri. Vintage
International, $14. These three willfully plotless narratives
explore the allure of everyday life in Calcutta, Bombay and Oxford.
``Chaudhuri is an immensely gifted writer,'' Alice Truax wrote last
year. His novels are ``crammed with breathtaking sentences ... and
melancholy grace notes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SISTER OF MY HEART &LR; , by Chitra Banerjee Divakaruni (Anchor,
$13), is the tale of two cousins who grow up in the same
upper-class Calcutta household and whose lives diverge after they
are forced into arranged marriages. In 1999 the reviewer Anderson
Tepper called this an uneven novel but admired ``Banerjee's
poetically embroidered storytelling powers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MR. DARWIN'S SHOOTER &LR;  By Roger McDonald. Penguin, $13.95.
Charles Darwin's assistant aboard the Beagle is portrayed as a
devout sailor who becomes embittered by Darwin's failure to
recognize his contributions to ``The Origin of Species'' and
worried that the scientist was out to prove there is no God. The
result is a ``fully imagined'' novel ``imbued with intellectual
curiosity,'' Emily Barton wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOING TO MIAMI: Exiles, Tourists and Refugees in the New
America &LR;  By David Rieff. University Press of Florida, $14.95. This
civic portrait captures a melting pot in full boil, a city of
competing ethnic communities in the process of being transformed by
its Cuban exile population. ``Rieff gives Miami the treatment it
deserves: an anti-travelogue that tours states of mind and basks in
projected images,'' John Krich wrote in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAVING GRACES: Images of Women in European Cemeteries &LR;  By David
Robinson. Norton, $15.95. The wilting, swooning maidens depicted in
this collection of black-and-white images of mostly 19th-century
statuary embody the Romantic link between love and death. ``The
photographs are beautiful, and beautifully reproduced,'' Sarah
Ferrell wrote in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VERONICA &LR;  By Nicholas Christopher. Spike/Avon, $12.50. This
tale of a New York photographer who is recruited by the daughter of
a time-traveling magician to rescue her missing father is ``a hip,
sexy, trendy fantasy novel,'' David Guy wrote in 1996.
``Christopher is a superbly lyrical and descriptive writer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
