<HEADER>
A6129 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-VILE-VALENTINES-REVIE     02-14 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VILE-VALENTINES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POISON PEN LETTERS: HAPPY VALENTINE'S DAY, YOU FATHOUSE PIG 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tomorrow Is Valentine's Day, a time for champagne, roses and
sappy expressions of affection.
</P>
<P>
   But such sentiments are no match for the venom that gets spewed
when romance turns sour. Herewith some notable authors demonstrate
their ability to wield the poison pen.
</P>
<P>
   _ By THOMAS VINCIGUERRA
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) With colon-punctuated bile, George Bernard
Shaw let fly at his paramour Stella Campbell in 1913 when she
announced that she would marry George Cornwallis West: (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Bah! You have no nerve: you have no brain: you are the
caricature of an 18th century male sentimentalist. . . . ((Y))ou
know nothing. God help you, except what you know all wrong:
daylight blinds you: you run after life furtively and run away or
huddle up and scream when it turns and opens its arms to you: you
are a man's disgrace and infatuation, not his crown ``above
rubies'' . . . ((Y))ou are an owl, sickened by two days of my
sunshine: I have treated you far too well. . . . Go then: the
Shavian oxygen burns up your little lungs: seek some stuffiness
that suits you. You will not marry George! At the last moment you
will funk him or be ousted by a bolder soul. You have wounded my
vanity: an inconceivable audacity, an unpardonable crime.
</P>
<P>
   Farewell, wretch that I loved.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) You'd think Shaw had made his point with
the above. But the dramatist wasn't quite through with Stella. He
wrote her a follow-up letter the same day: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Oh, my rancor is not yet slaked: I have not said enough vile
things to you. What are you, miserable wretch, that my entrails
should be torn asunder hour after hour? . . . Come round me all the
good friends I have neglected for her. Even her slanderers shall be
welcome: I shall say, ``Spit your venom; heap up your lies; vomit
your malice until the air is poison: you will still fall short of
the truth.'' And to her friends, her dupes, her adorers, I will
say, ``All that you say is true and not half good enough for her;
and yet it is all nothing: she would tear the strings out of an
archangel's harp to tie up parcels: she has done that with my very
heart strings.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) James Thurber could dish it out too. Before
joining The New Yorker, he presaged his obsession with the war
between the sexes in this 1920 letter to his sweetheart, Eva Prout:
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   A woman is often a wonderful thing. . . . But in you, as in all
of them, is the indifference of Carmen, the joy in cruelty of
Cleopatra, the tyrannical marble-heartedness of Katherine de
Medici, and the cold glitter of all the passionless despots of
men's warm souls since sex first originated _ since Eve broke the
heart of humanity forever and laughed with sadistic joy at Adam
sweating blood on the rack she made for him. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I'm not blaming you. I'm blaming the ages of women gone before
you who handed such legacies down, blaming the radiant and
sparkling and fidgety ladies of history who kissed in a moment of
coquetry and saw men die, kings dethroned and nations fight in
blood because of that careless caress. Men are fools, weak,
wine-blooded, deeply-devoted darn fools. What have women done for
them ((that is)) half so intense and potent as what they have done
to them?
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) But women could give as good as they got,
as Dorothy L. Sayers showed. The mystery novelist as much as called
her ex-beau John Cournos a wimp for insisting on using birth
control, in a letter she wrote in 1925 after having an illegitimate
child with another man: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Give me a man that's human and careless and loves life, and one
who can enjoy the rough-and-tumble of passion. . . . I like to die
spitting and swearing, you know, and I'm no mean wrestler! But
there again _ Precautionary measures cramp the style. Bah! If you
had chosen, I would have given you three sons by this time _ but
you are one that will do your wooing and begetting by proxy. . . .
Now, which of us do you really think is the more cynical, O divine
Perfection?
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In their long affair, Henry Miller and
Anais Nin pretty much personified hot and heavy. But after Miller
started badgering an indecisive Nin to join him in California in
1941, she called the sensualist rather a cold fish in one
department: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   You can do whatever pleases you, but your letters now sound
exactly like the letters you sent me from Greece, which almost
estranged us for good. They are cold, egotistical and concerned
purely with pleasure. All you can answer to my emotional attitude
when I think I can leave and then cannot leave is thoroughly
inhuman and mechanical. . . . Everything would be all right if you
wrote the right kind of letters. But you write the worst letters,
letters bad enough to estrange anyone. I have never seen more
expressionless, pan-faced letters, in regard to whether I come or
do not come etc. More self-centered letters either. That's what
creates distance, not time or a trip. The real distance and
separation were always created by your letters.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Early in 1936, Sinclair Lewis sailed for
Bermuda without telling his wife, Dorothy Thompson. He then wrote
her a letter complaining about their unsatisfactory life together
in New York. She fired back: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ((I))f I ever pulled anything on you like that I would never
hear the last of it. . . . Your letter about New York, which was
really vituperative, all about I shouldn't interfere with your
life, and let you alone, etc., rather hurt my feelings. . . . You
are so terrible, so terrifying when you are angry. . . . When you
are like that you freeze something in me.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In his fiction, Ernest Hemingway often
conveyed emotion between the lines. But not in correspondence.
Shortly before marrying Martha Gellhorn, Papa in 1940 drew up a
crow-eating ``contract'' for her to sign, to atone for a recent
separation from him: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I, the undersigned Mrs. Martha, or Mrs. Fathouse Pig . . .
hereby guarantee and promise never to brutalize my present and
future husband in any way whatsoever. . . . I recognize that a very
fine and sensitive writer cannot be left alone 2 months and 16 days
during which time many trying and unlikely things are put upon him
voluntarily and involuntarily, and that I . . . was a great cause
for his uneasiness of mind during this long period of solitude . .
. I am deeply sorry therefore and shall attempt . . . to make up to
him for the wretchedness he has gone through and shall also attempt
to protect him against same wretchedness in the future. This
statement is given of my own free will and in my rightest mind and
with love.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) And the poet Anne Sexton rebuffed the
romantic overtures of Philip Legler by suggesting in 1966 that he
seek professional help: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, Phil baby, everyone is wrong here. Your love, your
abundance for me is partly sick. I can tell you this because I am
the healthiest, wisest sickest human you'll meet outside the nut
house (patient or doctor/nurse). The sanest thing in this world is
love. And what is important is honesty. . . . I feel in my heart
that if you concentrate (as you have been doing) on your Anne
Sexton campaign that you'll run off into a tornado. . . . You're
sick. You need help. . . .
</P>
<P>
   First, foremost, Phil, work out your constant need for
affection, closeness with students, or with this poet. . . . Phil,
take the pills and start on the road to growing. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Bernard Shaw and Mrs. Patrick Campbell: Their
Correspondence,'' edited by Alan Dent (Knopf, 1952); ``James
Thurber: His Life and Times'' by Harrison Kinney (Henry Holt,
1995); ``The Letters of Dorothy L. Sayers, 1899-1936: The Making of
a Detective Novelist,'' edited by Barbara Reynolds (St. Martin's,
1995); ``A Literate Passion: Letters of Anais Nin and Henry Miller,
1932-1953,'' edited by Gunther Stuhlmann (Harcourt Brace
Jovanovich, 1987); ``Sinclair Lewis: An American Life'' by Mark
Schorer (McGraw-Hill, 1961); ``Hemingway'' by Kenneth S. Lynn
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1987); ``Anne Sexton: A Self-Portrait in
Letters,'' edited by Linda Gray Sexton and Lois Ames (Houghton
Mifflin, 1977).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
