<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 08:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6132 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-LYNCHING-REVIEW-(TRIM     02-14 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCHING-REVIEW-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IMAGE LEFT TWISTING IN THE WIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) 
 (ATTN: Ind., Ky., Ala., Wis., Ga.)  (bl) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a photograph washed in sepia tones that lend
its scene _ the 1930 lynching of Tommy Shipp and Abe Smith and an
approving white mob _ an otherworldliness. Perhaps it was my father
who first showed it to me. Yet, growing up black in Kentucky, with
its not-so-distant past of lynching and other violent expressions
of racism, I knew that this picture depicted a hatred that was
embedded in my country. This lynching occurred in Marion, Ind., 24
years before I was born, but that gave me little comfort as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   I recently visited the Roth Horowitz Gallery in New York City to
gaze again at that photograph, and 59 other images of lethal
brutality meted out to blacks by the vigilante's noose. For weeks,
thousands of visitors have crowded in for a glimpse of a dimly lit
chapter of American history.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, titled ``Witness,'' documents lynchings from
1883 through 1960 mostly with picture postcards from the collection
of James E. Allen and John Littlefield. Originally scheduled to
close Feb. 12, the show will move to larger quarters at the
New-York Historical Society in March.
</P>
<P>
   And while ``Witness'' has dramatically renewed awareness of a
rite almost exclusively reserved for blacks, it only hints at why
lynching still haunts America's collective psyche. Although the
physical act has all but disappeared in this country, lynching
continues to be used as a stinging metaphor for profound injustice.
It represents, as Harlem-based author Albert Murray calls it,
``American terrorism'' at home.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At his troubled confirmation hearing for the Supreme Court,
Clarence Thomas effectively silenced his critics in the Senate,
accusing them of leading a ``high-tech lynching'' to derail his
nomination. The Ramsey family, white and wealthy, invoked the
L-word last fall to describe, perhaps too glibly, the unwanted
media attention since the unsolved murder of JonBenet Ramsey as a
``public lynching.'' Last December, when the New York City Board of
Education voted against extending Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew's
contract, he stayed home because ``he prefers to be lynched in
absentia,'' his spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lynch law, which owes its name to Charles Lynch, a Virginia
farmer who administered a rough justice to outlaws and Tories
during the Revolution, is a contradiction in a country grounded in
laws and rights. Unlike other outward spasms of racial, ethnic or
religious violence, the lynching of black people was not an
isolated incident to be blamed on an individual or a political
group. It was part of a culture in which those who upheld the law
looked the other way or, in many instances, participated.
</P>
<P>
   The memory of lynching brings Americans face to face with ``our
problematic history with due process and the rule of law,'' said
William Kornblum, sociologist at the City University of New York's
graduate school, ``Even today we can't face part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The faces of white men, women and children gathered at these
scenes express a certain satisfaction. What is more chilling is the
unmistakable air of celebration, evil posed as righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   And the white mobs did not stop at merely murdering their
victims. They often tortured and mutilated them, occasionally
burning them (``this is the barbecue we had last night,'' one
witness wrote). The victims, carrion left hanging from trees as a
warning, some castrated, were officially less than human. On the
other hand, the frontier hangings of white victims rarely included
castration or mutilation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is one of atrocity,'' said Murray, who was born
near Mobile, Ala., in 1916. He cautioned blacks to be careful not
to get entangled in the act's accompanying messages of
powerlessness and victimhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't grow up terrified of lynching,'' he said. ``I have no
scars from it that I know about. While I was growing up, I was
thinking about how to conquer the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But James Cameron, an 85-year-old writer and retired building
engineer in Milwaukee, Wis., disagrees. ``It is a part of history
that should be told,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron was almost part of the Horowitz exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   He, Tommy Shipp and Abe Smith, the two young men in that
photograph from my youth, were arrested for the robbery and murder
of a white man and the rape of a white woman in Marion. Whites
stormed the jail to lynch them. Cameron was beaten but released
when someone in the crowd vouched for his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know that such a thing could happen,'' Cameron said.
``I was ignorant.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1882 to 1968, the Census Bureau counted the lynchings of
4,742 blacks. Historical references often include the victims'
alleged crimes, from rape to murder. But records also show blacks
hanged for little more than suspicion. In the act of lynching,
white women won respect, black men were emasculated and white men
made themselves omnipotent.
</P>
<P>
   The institution of lynching influenced men as dissimilar as
W.E.B. Du Bois, one of America's foremost equal rights activists,
and Elijah Muhammad, founder of the Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   In 1899, Sam Hose, a black farmer, killed a white man in an
argument over a debt. He was summarily hanged and then burned. Du
Bois, teaching at Atlanta University, was taking a letter of
protest to The Atlanta Constitution when he passed a downtown shop
window. In it was a trophy: the charred knuckles of Sam Hose. Du
Bois later helped found the Niagara Movement in 1905, breaking with
the strategy of accommodation and demanding immediate rights for
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy in 1903, Elijah Muhammad was traumatized when a neatly
dressed white man approached him on the street, opened his palm and
showed him the ear of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   I knew these stories as a child. My father insisted that I
understand that such cruelties formed part of African-American
history. They were cautionary tales all too true, he would say.
</P>
<P>
   As I eagerly started out for my first newspaper job more than 20
years ago, I drove to a quiet and friendly town in northern
Indiana. Once settled in my apartment, I called a cousin who was
finishing college at an Indiana university.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you tell me?'' I asked him about my new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said after a long pause, ``Marion is one of the
last places there was a public lynching of black folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a sudden confluence of memory and image. I drove to
the courthouse to remember how and where white justice was meted
out to two young black men and I wept. Most whites prefer to forget
lynching, seeing it as peculiar to another place and time. But most
blacks will continue to remember this ritual, in reality and
metaphor, until their own collective sense of vulnerability fades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
