<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 09:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6134 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-VOTING-GROUPS-REVIEW-     02-14 1782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTING-GROUPS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MELTING-POT: POLITICS OF 2000 ARE TRULY SOUPY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
(DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also sent with `p' code) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pity the poor presidential campaign strategists.
With make-or-break primaries fast approaching, they're frantically
trying to cobble together winning strategies to appeal to an
electorate so diverse, cacophonous and in flux as to make the folks
trying to build the Tower of Babel sound like a harmonious glee
club. With no big issue like war, recession or incumbency to give
the 2000 race some shape, America looks more than ever like an
indistinct montage of contending groups _ some new, some old
standbys.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, there are hero-admiring dads to take into
consideration along with angry white males, single moms along with
soccer moms. There are seniors whose politics are shifting ever
rightward and _ perhaps most important _ a growing number of
independents who, as their name suggests, are hardly a monolith.
Cutting across everything is a schizophrenic view of President
Clinton, who is both loved and loathed at the same time _ sometimes
by the same people.
</P>
<P>
   It's a niche marketer's dream, and a pundit's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot going on out there,'' said David Axelrod, a
Democratic political consultant in Chicago. ``There is no one thing
that was driving everything as there was in '92 or '80 or '84.
There are times when single issues overwhelm everything else. This
isn't one of those times.''
</P>
<P>
   Handicapping the key electoral demographics is a tricky
business, but here goes anyway:
</P>
<P>
   THE GUY'S GUY. In some ways, the last few years have been tough
for white guys. Sure, they're making money, either through overtime
at the auto plant or overdrive in the stock market. They've got
SUVs and IPOs. But in the political arena, they've had nobody to
look up to. Four years ago, the thought of a Colin Powell candidacy
made many weak in the knees. But he took a hike on them. Now
they've suddenly got two straight-talking heroes _ John McCain and
Bill Bradley _ from the realms of war and sport.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls conducted by the Los Angeles Times during the New
Hampshire primary illustrate what could be the makings of a gender
gap involving both McCain and Bradley. According to the polls, 50
percent of men voting in the Republican primary backed McCain while
only 29 percent went for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. Among men
voting Democratic, Bradley beat Vice President Al Gore among men by
about four points (while he trailed Gore by five points among
women).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all those guilty male boomers who didn't go to Nam,'' Lou
DiNatali, a senior fellow with the John W. McCormack Institute, a
Boston-based research organization, said of McCain's appeal to men.
``First, they went with Clinton, the anti-war guy. Now they go for
the POW.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the gender gap has helped McCain more than Bradley.
That's because so many more men vote in Republican primaries than
in Democratic ones.
</P>
<P>
   Should McCain win the Republican nomination, his male-based
appeal will probably widen the already cavernous gender gap between
the Republicans and Democrats, since Gore draws much of his
strength from women. That situation might favor the Democrat, since
there were 7 million more eligible female voters than eligible male
voters in 1998. And women tend to register and vote in higher
proportions than men.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENTS' DAY. In the New Hampshire primary, unaffiliated
voters helped power McCain to a 19-point victory over Bush, and
kept Bradley close enough to Gore to remain in the race. The
independents' role there has stirred interest in how much of a
force they will be in other primaries and the general election.
After all, they make up about 13 percent of the electorate
nationally, 25 percent in the Rocky Mountain states and 34 percent
of registered voters in New England.
</P>
<P>
   But the independents are hardly a bloc. There are so-called
``prosperity independents,'' affluent, generally white,
college-educated, Internet-savvy, stock-buying voters who tend to
be pro-environment and socially liberal yet fiscally conservative.
They were a hefty slice of McCain's support in New Hampshire, but
in national polls they also tend to like Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also roped in his share of independents in New Hampshire
as well. But his independents, while also well educated, tended to
be less affluent, earning less than $50,000 annually, according to
polls conducted by RKM Researchers Inc. of Portsmouth, N.H. These
voters tend to be more liberal when it comes to government
spending.
</P>
<P>
   There is a third large group of independents: people who aren't
particularly interested in politics. More than 7.1 million people
were added to the voter rolls in 1997 and 1998, as a result of the
so-called ``motor voter'' law, which made it possible to register
to vote when renewing a driver's license, applying for welfare and
conducting business with other government agencies. Many of these
new voters have registered as independents. Who these disaffected
voters will vote for _ if they vote at all _ is an open question.
</P>
<P>
   BIFURCATED BLACKS. The black vote, as always, will be critical
for Democrats. But while 55 percent of blacks live in the South,
they tend to turn out in lower proportions than Northern blacks,
who tend to be more affluent and better educated and are less
likely to live in hard-to-organize rural areas. Indeed, except for
1992, Northern blacks have voted in higher proportions than
Southern blacks in every presidential election since the Voting
Rights Act was passed in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Some political strategists say that unless this changes, the
black vote may be more of a factor in closely fought states in the
industrial Midwest like Michigan, Illinois and Ohio than in Deep
South states like Alabama, Georgia and Mississippi, where
Republicans have had a lock.
</P>
<P>
   THE GIANT SLEEPS TONIGHT. For years, Hispanics have been
described as the sleeping giant of U.S. politics, and George W.
Bush has trumpeted the fact that he can appeal to this group. Yet
when it comes to presidential races, there are no signs this giant
is stirring or that Hispanics will have much of an impact on the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics make up about 10 percent of the voting age population.
But half of that group is concentrated in two states _ California
and Texas. In 1996, Bill Clinton got 71 percent of the Hispanic
vote in California and won the state. He got 76 percent of that
vote in Texas and lost. Most strategists do not expect a markedly
different result this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-VOTING-GROUPS-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WASHINGTON: this year. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Besides, about 40 percent of Hispanics of voting age are not
U.S. citizens, and only 26 percent of those eligible to vote did so
in 1996 _ far fewer than non-Hispanic whites and blacks _ despite a
major effort by the Democratic Party and Hispanic leaders to get
out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The one state where Hispanics may be crucial is Florida. Four
years ago, Bob Dole, the Republican presidential nominee, won only
46 percent of the Hispanics who voted there, mainly conservative
Cuban-Americans. That was the lowest draw of any Republican
candidate in recent memory. Vowing not to let that happen again,
the Republicans _ particularly Bush, whose brother, Jeb, is the
governor _ are vigorously courting Cuban-American voters. But
Democrats, noting that the Cuban-American community is younger and
less vehemently anti-Castro, sense an opening.
</P>
<P>
   OLD STORY. It used to be that the band would strike up the
Roosevelt-era anthem ``Happy Days Are Here Again'' and elderly
voters would feel all nostalgic and troop off to vote Democratic.
No more. Quite simply, many of those seniors who remember the New
Deal have passed away, and many more of the voters now over 65 are
people who were swept up in the Reagan Revolution and have remained
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The senior vote today is a different group of people than it
was four years ago and eight years ago,'' said John Rother,
director of legislation and public policy for the American
Association of Retired Persons, who is not publicly supporting any
candidate. ``They didn't go through a life experience like the
Depression that brought everybody together and they don't have the
same view of government.''
</P>
<P>
   THE YOUNG AND THE LISTLESS. Despite efforts like MTV's ``Rock
the Vote,'' young people continue to be among the most politically
apathetic groups in the country. In 1996, only 32.4 percent of
people 18 to 24 years old cast a ballot _ the lowest level since
1972, when the voting age was lowered to 18.
</P>
<P>
   A close race and a maverick candidate like Bradley or McCain
might bring out more young voters. But it's unclear if anything can
break through this group's lack of interest.
</P>
<P>
   STILL ANGRY AFTER ALL. The angry white males are still around.
They tend to be college grads, relatively affluent and over 50
years old. They are more likely married, living in the South and
are often ex-Democrats turned Republican. They hate Clinton with a
passion. According to Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Center for
People and the Press, they make up about 10 percent of the
population and 12 percent of registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   They had a moment in the sun in 1994, when they helped power the
Republicans to control of Congress. But even as their economic
status has improved and their influence has waned, their anger has
not diminished. ``Many still feel that the cultural winds are
blowing against them,'' said Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster in
Atlanta. ``That creates the sense that the forces of political
correctness are working against them and what they believe.''
</P>
<P>
   I DO, I DO. The gender gap has been a hardy perennial in
analyses of the electorate. But perhaps as important in determining
who is wed to which party is a voter's marital status. Exit polls
indicate that married men supported the Republican over the
Democrat in every presidential race since 1984, and that except for
1996, when they backed Clinton over Bob Dole, married women did the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Unmarried men have a more checkered recent history, backing
Ronald Reagan in 1984 and George Bush in 1988, and flocking to
Clinton in 1992 and 1996. On the other hand, Democrats since 1984
have set single women's hearts aflutter. And in Kohut's survey,
60.7 percent of unmarried women with children _ so-called waitress
moms _ said they supported Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about soccer moms, but, really, for Clinton and
Gore, it's single moms,'' Kohut said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0901EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
