<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6138 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-APPRECIATION-SCHULZ-B     02-14 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRECIATION-SCHULZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEANUTS' CARTOONIST A GENTLE MESSENGER TO THE END 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good ol' Charles Schulz.
</P>
<P>
   Like Charlie Brown, the moon-faced and ill-fated cartoon
character he created half a century ago, Charles Monroe Schulz
persevered. When he died of a heart attack in his sleep on Saturday
night at the age of 77, it was just hours before Charlie and the
rest of the ``Peanuts'' crowd made their final original appearance
in print. It was as if Mr. Schulz, who was suffering from colon
cancer and had announced the retirement of both the comic strip and
himself in December, was waiting for Charlie, Linus, Schroeder, Pig
Pen, and Snoopy to depart so he could go with them.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when pop icons change with the click of a remote
control or a mouse, Mr. Schulz and ``Peanuts'' endured. One of the
major blessings of the strip _ the most widely read in history _
was that it didn't change to fit the times. Charlie Brown always
reacted to his misfortunes with a low-key ``Good grief!'' (Can you
imagine him saying ``Bummer?'' Please.) Lucy was seldom nice, even
when she was charging a nickel for advice. (Can you imagine her fee
being affected by inflation? Not likely.) Snoopy never upgraded his
aircraft from World War I vintage to supersonic jet. (Can you
imagine him traveling at the speed of sound? Not at all.)
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, no one could ever imagine Lucy actually leaving
the football on the ground and letting poor, hapless Charlie Brown
kick it. Not ever.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Schulz's contract reportedly ensures that no one else will
draw ``Peanuts.'' Good thing. He was, by all accounts, a true
gentleman who was able to imbue his characters with gentle souls
despite their anxiety, angst, and frustration. ``AACK! I can't
stand it!'' Charlie Brown would gripe, but it wasn't his style to
haul off and slug someone. Maybe that's why we haven't seen a
``Peanuts'' video game.
</P>
<P>
   Critics complained early in Mr. Schulz's career that his
artistic style was too primitive, and he subsequently altered it
somewhat. Later he was chastised for the simplicity of ``Peanuts''
itself, something he didn't change. Good for him. After all, he
wove together a tapestry of psychology, philosophy, and theology
that was as rich as anything the comics field has ever seen.
Anybody who thought that ``Peanuts'' was about a boy falling down
while trying to kick a football was missing the point.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Schulz arrived on the scene at a time when superheroes were
the comic rage, and he created a bunch of pre-adolescent
anti-heroes. But although ``Peanuts'' was supposedly about a gaggle
of kids, we knew better than that, even though there were no adults
in the strip. We knew that ``Peanuts'' was also about us grown-ups
who grew up after World War II and spent an inordinate amount of
time fretting about our insecurities. (Mr. Schulz may not have
invented the term ``security blanket,'' but he certainly
popularized it.) Like us, Charlie Brown struggled mightly just to
get through the day. He was Everyman, not Everyboy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't create humor out of happiness,'' Mr. Schulz once
wrote, adding: ``I'm astonished at the number of people who write
to me saying, `Why can't you create happy stories for us? Why does
Charlie Brown always have to lose? Why can't you let him kick the
football?' Well, there is nothing funny about the person who gets
to kick the football.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mr. Schulz was no pessimist. Charlie Brown may have
struggled, but he never gave up. He was truly an American hero _ or
at least the kind of hero Americans admire _ repeatedly pulling
himself off the canvas after getting whacked around by the pitfalls
of life. ``You've just got to let things go along, ride them out,
and see how they turn out in the end,'' Mr. Schulz explained once.
``There's no use trying to solve all your problems in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Schulz often compared himself to Charlie Brown, describing
himself as someone who tries to do the right thing but for whom
things often go wrong. And although his biographer, Rheta Grimsley
Johnson, wrote that he grappled with depression and anxiety, he was
an indefatigably decent person whose kindness and modesty were
unaltered by his success and the millions of dollars it fetched.
The cartoonist was known as ``Sparky,'' treated his fans with
outmost respect, and took only one vacation in his professional
life.
</P>
<P>
   His survivors include his wife, Jeannie, and five children from
his first marriage. A private funeral is scheduled for this week.
</P>
<P>
   There's always been a tendency to do Mr. Schulz by the numbers:
2,600 newspapers in 76 countries, more than 1,400 books, some 40
animated television specials, 355 million readers. But that's not
the point.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schulz created a comic strip that did what it was
supposed to do: It was funny. Alas, that's not as common as it
sounds, and Mr. Schulz knew it. In an interview about five years
ago, he lamented the ``rollicking sense of humor that we don't
have'' in our comics and other media.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he had it, and so did the entire ``Peanuts'' crew. We
thought Charlie Brown and Charles Schulz would go on forever, and
now we've lost both in the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Good grief is right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
