</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Haiti a bad scene gone worse
 &HT;    (For release Feb. 16, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before a chilled, rain-soggy South Carolina picnic audience last
weekend, Republican presidential contender John McCain played his
military hand. He called for greater benefits for our veterans,
taking precise note that the veterans of World War II _ ``the last
great generation,'' he quoted Tom Brokaw's book _ were dying out
and were entitled to better treatment from our government.
</P>
<P>
   Then, staying on a military theme, he targeted the Clinton
administration's foreign policies, where it is quite vulnerable.
McCain wanted to know what has changed in Haiti since we sent
20,000 troops there in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   (Along the way, the Vietnam war hero slipped into a bit of
demagoguery when he commented that the current president, secretary
of defense and secretary of state have never worn a military
uniform. Neither did Franklin D. Roosevelt, Woodrow Wilson or
Abraham Lincoln; so what?)
</P>
<P>
   It has been 5 1/2 years since Clinton sent troops into Haiti to
oust an unelected ruler and to relieve the chaos that was Haitian
politics, human rights and economy.
</P>
<P>
   As McCain rightly asks, what has changed?
</P>
<P>
   Presently, Haiti does not have a legislative body, it being
dissolved more than a year ago by President Rene Preval. Elections
to restore a parliament are scheduled for March and April, thus
prompting more chaos. Voter registrations have been hampered by the
inability of mny registration offices to even open their doors. In
some areas, political thuggery has returned.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti's economy does not exist. Its forest lands stripped by
residents, its factories impeded by a lack of production and
acceptance in a global market, Haiti remains decades if not
centuries behind the times.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the last U.S. soldier left Haiti, taking with him
15,000 pounds of equipment. True, a U.N. mission remains there, but
someone tell me about a successful U.N. mission.
</P>
<P>
   Where is Haiti today? One need look no further than the Central
Intelligence Agency World Factbook for that answer: ``About 75
percent of the population lives in abject poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few, the times are good. Those are the ones who have gone
into the export business _ exporting drugs. The CIA World Factbook
says Haiti is a transshipment point for cocaine and marijuana en
route to the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That is most evidenced by recent discoveries that small Haitian
freighters coming to South Florida are bringing in tons of illegal
drugs, squirreled into hard-to-find locations in the ships' hulls.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti's other chief export is refugees. Desperate for economic
opportunities, Haitians regularly make the difficult voyage to
Florida, only to be interdicted by the U.S. Coast Guard and
immediately repatriated.
</P>
<P>
   So, back to McCain's criticism: What has been accomplished by
sending 20,000 American troops to Haiti in 1994? Could the money
spent on that and on their maintenance since then have been better
used to help Haiti with its economy, its agriculture, its
educational facilities?
</P>
<P>
   One only can imagine how much is being spent annually by the
U.S. to fight the drug traffic from Haiti and to patrol the seas
interdicting and returning refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti, with an unemployment rate of 60 percent, a life
expectancy average of but 51.6 years, an illiteracy rate of 55
percent and a birth rate of 32.5 births per 1,000 population, is a
pathetic dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the answer to world matters is not easily solved by
the use of military troops. It didn't work in Haiti or Somalia, it
is not working in Kosovo, and even Grenada, which Ronald Reagan
supposedly saved from the clutches of Fidel Castro, is back
sleeping with the Cuban dictator.
</P>
<P>
   If there really is a Third World, then Haiti is in a Fourth
World. It needs stability, it needs an economy and it needs a
respite from voodoo politics.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-thousand American soldiers weren't the answer. McCain
said so. But he didn't say what was the answer.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
