</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Watch Austria carefully but don't overreact
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, we're all on record as thinking it thoroughly appalling and
a bit scary that the minority party in Austria's new governing
coalition is a right-wing hard case led by a man who is the next
thing to a neo-Nazi and maybe even the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   With the point made, we'd probably do best now to wait, before
making any more moves against Austria, to see if the resulting
government in fact misbehaves intolerably.
</P>
<P>
   European Union countries have, variously, downgraded their
diplomatic missions, canceled trade plans and pulled out of
international conferences in Austria to protest the decision of the
right-center People's Party to partner with the Freedom Party led
by the noxious Joerg Haider.
</P>
<P>
   Haider himself is not in the government, but he has parlayed his
party's 27 percent showing in October's election into six Cabinet
positions for his partisans.
</P>
<P>
   There's a painful conundrum here. Democratic values presume
respect for democratic outcomes, even unwelcome ones. But how do
you handle politicians who use democratic means to potentially
fascist ends?
</P>
<P>
   Europe's grandparents remember that Adolf Hitler leveraged an 18
percent showing in German elections into a dictatorship that led to
conquest, world war and holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Haider's apology for his latest Nazi-sympathizing comment never
lasts longer than until his next similar utterance. Too, Austria,
unlike Germany, has little pondered or regretted its past
enthusiasm for Nazism _ and as recently as 1986 elected as
president the oily Kurt Waldheim despite evidence that as a German
officer in World War II he was at best indifferently proximate to
war crimes if not directly culpable.
</P>
<P>
   But the Freedom Party was elected for more reasons than Haider's
anti-immigrant demagoguery. It would free up much of Austria's
state-burdened economy and has posited itself as an alternative to
the winking deal by which for decades the country's two mainstream
parties have divvied up power and privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The unease of all democratic nations at Haider's involvement in
Austrian governance, even at arm's length, is heartfelt, but
Europe's has a bit of whistling-past-the-graveyard to it as well.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every EU nation has a worrisome, similarly xenophobic
party _ Germany's People's Union, Jean-Marie Le Pen's National
Front in France. Italy's National Alliance is led by an actual
Musollini, his granddaughter Alessandra. Even the Scandinavian
countries, once famously tolerant, have new racist parties.
</P>
<P>
   With Europe experiencing unfamiliar immigration and inching
toward confederation _ a parliament of sorts, a multinational
bureaucracy, softening borders, common currency _ more such
reaction is likely.
</P>
<P>
   Can those emotions be managed, even reconciled, by the manners
and means of democracy? If not, can they be suppressed or would
they only be exacerbated by exclusion? The trick is to not harry
Austria into a defensive extremism but to be ready to act firmly if
it goes there on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 0940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
