u l BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0215     02-14 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0215-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   JonBenet movies expose TV's ugliest side
</P>
<P>
   By Diane Holloway
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Just when you think commercial television can't
sink any lower, it does. Free falls past the gutter and down into
the sewer.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next couple of weeks, two TV movies will air on the
short life and brutal murder of JonBenet Ramsey, the tiny beauty
queen found dead in her home Christmas night 1996. The case remains
unsolved, although suspicion swirls around JonBenet's parents and
brother.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that this true story has no end doesn't seem to bother
the so-called ``creative'' people at the networks. Nor does it
bother them that they are seeking to capitalize on a 6-year-old
child's tragedy. The prospect of watching the horrors leading up to
the murder, as well as fleeting scenes of the murder itself, is
disgusting. It's tantamount to abusing this child all over again
and exploiting her in the grave.
</P>
<P>
   I'm slamming these movies sight unseen, something I've never
done in my 20-year career as a critic. I always felt it was
unprofessional to write about something without seeing it all the
way through. But I'm making an exception here for two reasons.
First, the concept is so awful that execution is almost beside the
point. Second, the networks, no doubt sensing that response would
not be favorable, did not provide preview tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday at 8 p.m., Fox drags out ``The JonBenet Ramsey
Story,'' a mini-movie that runs an hour instead of the usual two.
Press material touts it as ``form-breaking,'' but it may have been
cut short because even the producers were grossed out by it. The
Fox film claims to present the facts of the case provided by
investigating detectives and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is going all out with a four-hour miniseries, ``Perfect
Murder, Perfect Town,'' that's scheduled to air Feb. 27 and Mar. 1.
This one is based on the book by Lawrence Schiller. Viewers, we are
told, will have to draw their own conclusions about the killer's
identity from several theories that are posed.
</P>
<P>
   Titillation and exploitation sell, and not just on television.
JonBenet has become a cottage industry for the tabloids as well as
many legitimate publications. But television is the only medium
that's turning the story into entertainment with actors, sets,
cinematography, ominous music and dozens of commercials.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that these two movies come during the
February rating period, when stations use the ratings to set their
ad rates. That's why murder stories dominate newsmagazines and
movies this time of year and why those revolting ``World's Worst
...'' specials do so well on Fox. They appeal to prurient
interests, and that's big business.
</P>
<P>
   People who watch these things get what they deserve. But the
networks ought to draw the line, no matter how much commercial gain
is at stake, when it comes to exploiting the murder of a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``What social good can possibly be served?'' wonders Ellen
Wartella, dean of the University of Texas's college of
communications and a long-time researcher into TV's content and
impact. ``It doesn't strike me, given that the case hasn't been
resolved, that there are any lessons to be learned here. All these
films can do is publicize the lurid aspects of a very sad case, and
I can say that without seeing the treatment. At the very least,
they're in very poor taste.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way we'll be able to get rid of this garbage is to stop
watching it. The networks aren't going to produce shows that don't
draw a crowd. No audience, no sordid stories. It's as simple as
that, so send these folks a message and stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
