<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reform bill passes House
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia House of Representatives approved Gov. Roy
Barnes' education bill by an overwhelming margin last week. The
House voted 136 to 41 to pass the bill. The Georgia Senate also
must agree to the bill before it can become law.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's education bill calls for signing bonuses for
teachers in hard-to-fill schools, cash bonuses for teachers whose
students perform above expectation, and reductions in some class
sizes. The new law also would make it easier for teachers to be
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Many teacher groups are unhappy about the bill, because they
feel they are losing protection for their jobs. The bill is
expected to have some trouble passing the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   `BLUE'S CLUES' AND `BILL' MAY MOVE TO CBS
</P>
<P>
   Some of Nickelodeon's most popular children's shows soon may be
airing on CBS on Saturday mornings. It is one of the changes you'd
see if a merger between CBS and Viacom goes through as expected.
(Viacom owns Nickelodeon.) The merger would unite the two
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The networks haven't determined which shows would air on CBS,
but ``Blue's Clues'' and ``Little Bill'' are considered likely
bets.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement would help both networks because Nickelodeon
would promote CBS' shows and CBS would do the same for Nick.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon's popular Saturday morning lineup shouldn't be
affected because it is geared toward a slightly older audience.
</P>
<P>
   GRIFFEY TRADED TO THE REDS
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. (above) is returning to the city where he played
Little League ball, starred for his high school baseball team and
watched his father play pro baseball: Cincinnati. The 10-time
All-Star wanted to leave the Seattle Mariners. He took less money
than other teams were willing to pay so he could play for the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter how much money you make. It's where you're
the happiest,'' said Griffey, wearing the jersey and cap of his new
team. ``I thought Cincinnati is the place I would be happiest.
Hopefully, I can have the same luck my father had here and win some
championships.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, who played for the Reds, is now a coach for the
team. The Mariners received four players to give up Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   S.C. PRIMARY HEATING UP
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina Republican primary is this Saturday, and the
Michigan and Arizona Republican primaries follow on Tuesday. Keep
track of the delegates that are awarded with each win. There are 37
Republican delegates up for grabs in South Carolina, 30 in Arizona
and 58 in Michigan. Republican candidates need 1,033 delegates to
capture their party's nomination for president. Recent polls show
that Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Texas Gov. George W. Bush are
running neck and neck in South Carolina. Who do you think will win?
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina 37
</P>
<P>
   Arizona 30
</P>
<P>
   Michigan 58
</P>
