<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite snags, AirPort system good for wireless connections
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It almost sounds too good to be true. There's an easy
way to wirelessly connect two Macs for sharing or transferring
files or to connect several Macs from anywhere in a house through
one Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   But you can do this and more with Apple's new AirPort wireless
system. The bad news is that AirPort, as should be expected, is a
work in progress. The speed of connections is so-so, and there are
some glitches in the setup and ease of use.
</P>
<P>
   AirPort is the first wireless home system for personal
computers. It works through software, a base station, an antenna
and an installation card.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the AirPort has been incorporated in three models _
iBooks, G4s and iMac DVs. Each of these models has a special
built-in wireless antenna and special software.
</P>
<P>
   You still have to buy a $99 card that easily slips into each of
these models to enable AirPort.
</P>
<P>
   The last part of the system is a white-and-blue disc called the
AirPort base station. It serves as a wireless modem that lets up to
10 AirPort-equipped Macs connect to the Internet. And they can do
so from about 150 feet away. That means you can jump wirelessly
onto the Internet from just about anywhere in your house.
</P>
<P>
   Configuring the AirPort software is easy. There's an assistant
that walks you through the process. The software is intuitive
enough to import your existing online configuration, if you want.
</P>
<P>
   The software includes a separate control strip that runs along
the bottom of your screen. It monitors the strength of the AirPort
signal. It also lets you choose whether to connect via the base
station or with another Mac. You don't need the station to just
connect two Macs.
</P>
<P>
   One hitch is that AirPort won't work with America Online. That's
a big problem, given that AOL is the largest single provider of
Internet access. Hopefully, Apple will soon strike a deal with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that, while AirPort connections were highly
reliable, they were slow. That was especially true compared to the
standard connection, the 10BaseT Ethernet port built into most
Macs.
</P>
<P>
   The speed of the connection slows even further if more than one
Mac is using the base station.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is transferring files among Macs through AirPort speedy. It
takes two to four times longer to transfer a file wirelessly than
through an Ethernet connection.
</P>
<P>
   And a final peeve. Apple has made it cumbersome to restore a
lost connection through AirPort's current setup.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these drawbacks, AirPort is off to a good start. Surely
it will only get stronger with the inevitable upgrades. Indeed,
AirPort software upgrade 1.1 has just been released.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
