<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0215-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Discovery lures TV crowd to Web
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yahoo is now, and probably will be for the foreseeable
future, the country's most popular Web site. It is one of the most
recognizable brands on the Web and offers users everything from
searches to auctions, fantasy baseball, online shopping and
greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   But stand back Yahoo, traditional media are hot on your trail.
You've got serious competition from some pretty big names,
targeting an audience that may like Yahoo but really loves
television. One day, that could make all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Discovery Networks, best known for its popular cable
channels, took its Web site and turned it into a full-fledged
portal for families and fans of the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The new site offers users information about programming on the
Discovery Channel, the Travel Channel, the Learning Network, Animal
Planet and Discovery Health Online. A second area called Web
Express is a well-designed portal site that will link users to a
variety of search engines (including Yahoo). Users can also check
stock prices, read horoscopes, chat or look up information on
everything from cars to careers or even visit a special area for
kids.
</P>
<P>
   Michela English, who heads up Discovery's online ventures, said
the evolution from a Web site simply promoting TV shows to a unique
family/portal/TV/e-commerce site was a steady process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We launched our first Web site in 1995, in support of our TV
networks,'' she said. ``Now it's a set of tools, not necessarily
focused on Discovery. The launch marks an evolution of our strategy
and our company's commitment to make the Discovery brand an
Internet brand. We say we want to help people to explore their
world, but we want to also be relevant to everyday life. Using the
Discovery brand means we can throw the weight of the TV and retail
stores behind that brand to build a family of sites under the
Discovery gateway.''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery.com wants to move the fans of the cable channels onto
the Web site, something NBC has been doing with its online
properties including the NBC Web site, the portal site Snap, the
community/home page site Xoom.com, and news and information site
MSNBC.com, a joint venture with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Media executives say the move to take a loyal TV audience and
turn it into a loyal Web audience is something at which traditional
media companies excel. They say the goal of a media company working
to establish a Web presence is to take the viewer, turn him into an
Internet user, then into a member, then a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Discover seems to be following that plan. It already has deals
with online retailers including Amazon.com., moviephone.com, CDNow
and others to add e-commerce to the site's revenue stream. The
Discovery Store online also offers a variety of gifts and goodies.
</P>
<P>
   Both NBC Interactive and Discovery.com have the right
demographics for online Web success. NBC television has a young,
hip audience that uses the Web either at home or at work and has
enough confidence in the network to check out its Web sites, which
are promoted both in programming and commercials for its various
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery also has the right demographics for Web success. Its
core audience includes everyone from hard-core science junkies to
kids looking for homework help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We draw really a broad audience,'' English says. ``We have the
hard-core science aficionados. When we follow space shots, we'll
get families and a traditional male audience that is interested in
that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   English says the revamped Discovery site isn't limited to
science lovers and students. She wants to attract the widest
audience possible. ``We think of ourselves as family-oriented,''
she said, adding that the new users coming online _ especially
women and kids _ will want to log on to familiar brands and find
what they want with a minimum of fuss. ``We want to meet that need
to offer general interest and offer them the opportunity to
transact business or subscribe to a service,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery has no illusions it's the next Yahoo, but if it can
bring its loyal TV audience to the Web and keep it there, the
company might be on to something.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
