<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Desktop Translator still not as good as it should be
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Desktop Translator, in its latest version, boasts
Internet capabilities and will not only attempt to translate your
writing but your spoken words.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the attempts at translation have not
significantly improved since the last time I looked at it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps if one confines one's translating requirements to
international business, which is really what the publisher,
Transparent Language, intends the program for, it might be
acceptable. However, no one writes business letters to me in
anything but English, and they don't write them for long because I
don't answer them in any language.
</P>
<P>
   So in order to check out Desktop Translator, I must take to the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   The program can be used in a window mode, in which one pastes
the copy to be translated into one window and the translation
appears below. In this mode, the translation can also be spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Other modes for accessing the program include a toolbar and a
place on the taskbar; in these configurations Desktop Translator
can be used to translate an entire Web page, no matter which
browser you're using. Still another mode is used when the user
wants to dictate to the program.
</P>
<P>
   The program can be used to translate between English and
Spanish, French and German, and from English to Portuguese and
Italian.
</P>
<P>
   I tried Spanish to English.
</P>
<P>
   From a Spanish Web page providing a brief biography of Pablo
Picasso, I excerpt one translated paragraph from the section on his
cubist period:
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspired by the processing volumEtrico of the forms pictUricas
of Paul CEzanne, Picasso and Georges Braque they painted in 1908 a
series of landscapes inside a style that a critic described later
as if had been based on facts 'small buckets', being imposed thus
the term cubismo. Among 1908 and 1911 they worked in narrow
contribution inside this line of disorder and analysis of the
forms, developing juntos the first phase of the cubism,
acquaintance as cubism analytic.''
</P>
<P>
   While anyone with a smattering of knowledge of Picasso's work
can muddle through that to a fair degree, I certainly wouldn't want
to risk having something I wrote put through that sort of mangler.
</P>
<P>
   On the same site with the Picasso biography there was a short
biography of Salvador Dali. But instead of quoting from a
translation of that text, I bring you something more surreal than
anything Dali ever painted. It is Desktop Translator's version of
the story of ``El Largarto de la Catedral,'' which DT entitled
``The Lizard of the Cathedral.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that in a section of the Cathedral of Seville one can
find hanging from the roof ``a crocodile of natural size, a bite of
horse and a cane of command.'' The genesis of this bizarre trio, it
is said, came in the year 1260, when ``the sultan of Egypt sent an
embassy to the King Alfonso X the Wise one to ask the hand of its
daughter Berenguela.
</P>
<P>
   ``The embassy brought diverse presents, among them a beautiful
eyetooth of elephant, a crocodile of the Nile alive and a giraffe
domesticated with its setting and its brake and flanges.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso, it goes on to say, was loath to give the hand of his
daughter to this sultan, as well he should have been, I might add.
Anyone who sends me crocodiles alive and a giraffe with brake and
flanges is not apt to get my daughter's hand. Next thing you know
it might be hanging from his turret. At any rate, Alfonso sent back
gifts for the sultan, and, according to DT, ``here they remained
the crocodile and the giraffe. Past the time, and dead person the
crocodile, was dissected, and their skin fills of paja went hanging
of the Patio of the Nranjos together with the brake of the giraffe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years later, hung like remembrance the stick of the Spanish
ambassador that returned from Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no further mention of the ``bite of horse.'' Perhaps a
bite of horse is synonymous with a giraffe flange. I don't know,
and I don't think Desktop Translator is going to tell me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
