<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moms offered intellectualism
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Talk to women who left jobs to raise children, and
some say they miss the office camaraderie, the chance to talk to
someone not wearing diapers.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet can bring the small talk and the big talk to your
home. Salon, an online magazine, has an online discussion group
called Mothers Who Think. The site, which can be reached from a
link off www.salon.com, offers several topics for discussion,
including: ``Why Marriage?,'' ``Mommy or Joseph Stalin,'' and ``Dr.
Laura is a despicable, guilt-mongering hypocrite; why would anyone
seek her opinion on anything?''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more popular topics is called ``How long are you
going to do that? And other breast-feeding topics.'' A person with
the screen name of Jody2ms started the discussion in August 1998
with this post:
</P>
<P>
   ``My father in-law asked me, `When are you going to stop that
nonsense?' I replied, while nursing my 4-month-old, `I hope to have
him weaned by the time he starts college, because we would like him
to attend out of state if he wants.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Steele started this discussion thread in January:
``Stay-At-Home Moms: How do you have an intellectual life with
other women?
</P>
<P>
   ``When most of the women you meet in mothers' groups want to
talk about kids and consuming? I mean, I take care of her and
that's enough, I don't want to talk about it as well. I need to
discuss adult things when I'm around other adults. I miss the
discussion of ideas and culture I used to have with my old
co-workers ... sigh.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the recent posts dealt with a book, ``The Playgroup,''
by Nina Barrett. Such as this one, from RobinM:
</P>
<P>
   `` ... I have been telling all my friends, the other moms in my
play group, and here about this book, and finally someone actually
reads it too ... I was struck by finding women who were just as
ambitious as I was/am, but rattled by how much good mothering is
important to me and how hard it is to define it. I was/am (unhappy)
that my husband didn't have to deal with the same self-doubts
regarding his work and his fatherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon is a free online magazine. Participation in the discussion
groups requires registration, which is also free.
</P>
<P>
   RAY LEWIS' STORY, RIGHT FROM THE START
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is an interesting place.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Jan. 31, Baltimore Ravens All-Pro linebacker Ray
Lewis is jailed in connection with the slaying of two men. Three
days later, two Ravens fans in suburban Baltimore start the process
of setting up a Web site designed to get the word out to people
interested in the topic.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.freeraylewis.com, offers Free Ray Lewis T-shirts,
a brief biography of Lewis, links to news Web sites that carry
stories on the slayings and a place for people to talk about the
issue. The site also features a poll. Last Wednesday, 550 of the
612 votes were from Ravens fans. Of those, 60 percent, 367, don't
think Lewis did it.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Silberg, the 27-year-old who started the site with friend
Michael Snyder, said the meaning of the Web site address
(freeraylewis.com) is not a statement of innocence but simply a
desire that Lewis be freed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that you can only judge a person on what they've
done up to this point,'' said Silberg. ``And up to this point, he's
showed an amazing amount of determination, not only as a player but
in his personal life. We know that from hearing his story.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if he is found guilty, all bets are off. We're just trying
to create a forum so when people sit down and have a conversation
about this, they do it on facts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silberg and Snyder are selling T-shirts but only to recover the
few thousand dollars they paid to have the site built, Silberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
