<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE0215-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A broad and fruitful field for gardeners
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's something especially appealing about mixing
the new with the old, whether it's in the garden or in life. Now
that it's time to start planning for spring, you have a chance to
use the newfangled Web to plan your old-fashioned garden.
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start is with two traditional seed and plant
catalogs that also have an impressive presence on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever planted a seed, surely you've heard of Burpee.
You'll find the online version of the venerable gardening catalog
at www.burpee.com/, at a page called Burpee Seeds Home Gardening.
Once there, you'll have a multitude of choices, including taking
the old-fashioned way out and ordering the company's print catalog.
You also may browse the online catalog, check out some recipes and
read the company's regional newsletter to learn about plants and
planting for your neck of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The other familiar name on today's garden tour is Gurney's.
You'll find Gurney's Seed &AMP; Nursery Co. nicely represented on the
Web at www.gurneys.com/. This site is not as elaborate as the one
run by Burpee. You can learn a little about the climate zone you
live in, order a print catalog or learn a little about the company.
</P>
<P>
   But the main purpose of this page is to allow you to order stuff
_ to literally take your print catalog, key in the product number
of what you want and order. Since garden catalogs _ both print and
online _ are such great dream books at this time of the year, this
site will mostly appeal to the hard-core Gurney's customer.
</P>
<P>
   But there are dream books on the Web for gardeners _ places
where you can read descriptions and learn about your choices and
then either place an order or just use the data you learned to shop
at your local garden center.
</P>
<P>
   An example of a dream book online can be found at www
.chefsgarden.com/ and is called The Chef's Garden _ Herb Gardening
and Vegetable Gardening. For instance, if the unromantically named
506 Bush Tomato strikes your fancy, you can learn, just in the
ordering information, that it offers ``bright red fruit on vines
that only reach 18 inches tall. Plants are tolerant of sporadic
watering and yield very well. This is a good patio container plant.
Medium-large size tomatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all. You'll get growing tips, learn about insects and
bugs (there's even a Bug of the Month) and get recipes here. If you
love plants, this is a good place to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Richter's Herbs _ Medicinal, Culinary and Aromatic _ Plants &AMP;
Seeds at www.richters.com/ is, as you would guess from the name, a
little out of the ordinary. It's also a little out of the United
States, located in Ontario, Canada. But it ships products all over
the world. Besides, the products that it offers are unusual and
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for organic seeds (obviously all are organic,
but these are grown to suit the specifications of organic
gardeners) or herbs, it's a good place to go shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Since this is a Web site that appeals to a specific type of
gardener, it's also rich in resources. For instance, you can take
online courses _ for free _ on the site. When last visited, the
topic was on how to make sure that your seeds germinate properly,
something that would interest gardeners of any type.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's Heirloom Seeds and Rare Seeds at
www.Heirloom-Seeds.com/.
</P>
<P>
   As you would expect, this is the place to go to find seeds for
plant varieties that your grandparents would know and recognize.
There's a good selection.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because it's an old-fashioned joint, you will notice that
pages open very slowly here. But gardeners already know about
patience.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
