<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PC World provides the lowdown on upgrading to Windows 2000
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Working
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you're considering upgrading to Windows 2000,
Microsoft's latest operating system, check out the March issue of
PC World. The cover story tells how to install, as smoothly as
possible, this latest operating system, due out Thursday. The good
news is that the magazine says Windows 2000 is Microsoft's most
stable and capable operating system yet. It offers, for example,
vastly improved hardware and software compatibility.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the bad news: The magazine found that, depending on your
computer, upgrading to Windows 2000 is either a breeze or a
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   You can explore the New World again as a band of Europeans in a
game called ``1602 A.D.'' You establish settlements, expanding them
through trade, diplomacy and war. The game lets you play against
the computer or against up to four people on a network. You can
also customize the world you want to explore and the campaign you
lead. Published by GT Interactive Software, ``1602 A.D.'' is
available only for PCs with Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Once you create a city, you can create the people who live in it
_ all part of the latest simulation game from Maxis. Called ``The
Sims,'' this game lets users create a character and move in it
through the world. Win friends by throwing pool parties. Go after a
well-paying job and buy a big house. ``The Sims'' is available only
for PCs with Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Financial services are a large and growing presence on the
Internet. Some let you pay bills online. You pay a monthly fee, say
$9, and the service notifies you of when bills come in and even if
you have enough money to pay them. One of these services that has
gotten good reviews is Paymybills.com. Check out the review in the
March issue of PC World. You'll find the site at
www.paymybills.com/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
