u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-WOODS15-CO     02-14 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-WOODS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fast 50: Woods seek return to glory
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUART, Va. _ When Eddie Wood saw David Pearson walk into the
Wood Brothers' shop to help start the team's 50th year in NASCAR,
the afternoon of Feb. 15, 1976, seemed like only yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, Pearson outran Richard Petty to give the Woods one
of their most memorable victories and one of NASCAR's most exciting
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Wood is the son of team founder Glen Wood and the nephew
of Leonard Wood, who was the mechanical genius behind the team that
has won 96 races and 112 pole positions. Their 80 superspeedway
victories are a NASCAR record, as are their 53 500-mile race
victories, 87 superspeedway poles and 26 superspeedway races won
from the pole.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, the Woods were dominant on the big tracks. While
driving their No. 21, Pearson won 43 times, finished second 29
times and won 51 poles.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, most teams had only one crew member in contact
with the driver; today, numerous team members have radios. Eddie
Wood had on the headset to talk to Pearson for the '76 Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember every word that was said on that last lap,''
Wood said. ``When they got the white flag, David was behind
Richard. They went into turn one, and he hasn't said anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off turn two, he said, `I'm going to try him here.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``They get into turn three. We can't see from the pit area, but
we're watching the crowd standing up, so you know he's doing
something. (Pearson) said, ``I got him.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then (Pearson) goes up the track a little bit, and Richard
goes to the bottom and gets back under him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go all the way to the exit of turn four, and (Pearson)
said, 'He's under me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That lasted for a second or two, and then he said, `The
(expletive) hit me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd is up, and the car's spinning backward, and he said,
`Where's Richard?', just as calm as we're sitting here talking,
maybe calmer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I come back and say, `He's up here. He stopped.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And (Pearson) said, `Well, I'm coming.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had any emotion in his voice as far as excitement or
being mad. That's why they called him the Silver Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson's wrecked Mercury limping past Petty's crumpled Dodge to
take the checkered flag has been shown over and over through the
years. For the Woods, it was one of their two best days at Daytona;
the other was in 1963 when the late Tiny Lund drove their car to
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Lund was a last-minute substitute. He earned the ride after he
helped pull Woods' driver Marvin Panch from a burning sports car
during a race at the speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson and the Woods continued to win races, but they split up
after an unfortunate incident on pit road during a race at
Darlington. Pearson didn't know the team planned to change four
tires and drove off when the crew, after changing right-side tires,
dropped the car. It came to rest on pit road when the left-side
tires fell off.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson was released as the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Wood said he waited nearly 30 years before he told
Pearson that he and Glen wanted to back out of firing him but were
pressured into going ahead with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were already making plans for what we were going to go to
Martinsville (the next race), but the sponsor wanted to go through
with (the firing),'' Leonard Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson said he harbors no hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd gotten to where we didn't agree on things, so a break-up
was coming,'' Pearson said. ``But we've always been friends, and we
always will be. These people are like family.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson ran a limited schedule before retiring. His best
post-Wood Brothers run came as a substitute for the injured Dale
Earnhardt, then a Winston Cup rookie. Pearson won the Southern 500
at Darlington in Earnhardt's car.
</P>
<P>
   The Woods, without Pearson, lost their stranglehold on the
superspeedways. The highlights since Pearson, the Woods say, have
been putting Kyle Petty and Dale Jarrett in Victory Lane for the
first time in their careers. The Woods last win came at Atlanta
Motor Speedway in 1993, with Morgan Shepherd at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Today their driver is fellow Virginian Elliott Sadler, who hopes
to return the No. 21 Ford to the glory days. Sadler had a slow
start in 1999, his rookie year, but he improved as the circuit made
its second-round stops at the major tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The caliber of the team was always there, but the driver had
to learn and go through some bumps and bruises,'' Sadler said.
``We're looking forward to the 2000 season and hope the 50th
anniversary gives us some momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   The Woods aren't expecting a win just yet, but a few top-five
fiand a pole would be satisfying, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The Woods will commemorate their 50th year by having five
different paint schemes _ one for each decade the team has
competed. The first special look will come at AMS in March when the
car's paint scheme will flash back to Shepherd's win in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The second special paint job will be for the April race at
Talladega. That car will carry the same colors as the one driven by
the late Neil Bonnett in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   For the World 600 at Lowe's Speedway in May, the car will look
like the one Pearson drove from 1974-1979, a time in which he won
12 consecutive poles and three races at the Charlotte track.
</P>
<P>
   For the Daytona race in July, Lund's colors will be on the car,
and when the circuit travels to the Woods' home track,
Martinsville, in October, the No. 21 Ford will be painted like the
car that team founder Glen Wood drove in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Glen started racing by chance. He was part owner of a car, and
the driver didn't show up for the race, so Glen filled in.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``I never thought it would have been like this 50 years
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NTSB-BEHINDTHESCENES1     02-14 2782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NTSB-BEHINDTHESCENES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waiting for the sound of disaster
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The voices.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cash is in his small, windowless laboratory on the sixth
floor of the nondescript Washington office building where the
National Transportation Safety Board is headquartered. Cash is the
NTSB man who listens to the cockpit voice recorder _ one of two
``black boxes'' that collect voice and mechanical data on
commercial aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   He's surrounded by reel-to-reel tape recorders and punctured,
gouged and crumpled steel alloy boxes. They're red, not black. The
boxes held the recorder that made the tapes that carry the last
words of airline crews _ ValuJet Flight 592, TWA Flight 800, a
California commuter jet brought down by a gun-wielding passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Cash will soon listen to the pilots' last words as Alaskan
Airlines Flight 261 fell toward the Pacific Ocean on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard more than 500 cockpit recorder tapes since joining
the safety board in 1982. He's heard screams, pops, thumps,
mysterious bangs, pilots grunting as they pull on the stick.
Gunshots. And always, silence _ sudden and final silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to me once, the voices,'' Cash says. ``That was the
first tape, a commuter plane. Prop flew off. I can't let the voices
get to me. I have to let them talk to me, let them tell me what
happened, but I can't let them get to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Airplanes speak.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall from Cash's lab, in another windowless room,
information from flight data recorders is downloaded by NTSB
technicians. The data recorder is the other black box on civilian
aircraft. It records anywhere from 11 to more than 300 data
parameters, including engine oil pressure, airspeed, altitude,
cockpit controls and heading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legal minimum for older planes is 11 parameters, 28 on new
planes,'' says Cash. ``European planes can monitor hundreds of
systems. But our fleet ... usually the minimum. Eleven is often
enough to get an idea of what happened to a plane. But if we
monitored 200 to 300 parameters, the planes could really talk to
us. Every time a recorder comes in I think, `Please, let it have
more than 11.' But if it's a U.S. plane, it's usually 11.'' The
flight data recorder on Alaska Airlines 261 monitored 48 systems.
The rear horizontal stabilizer _ thought to have been instrumental
in bringing the plane down _ was one of the 48. Monitoring the
stabilizer is not required, and Alaska Airlines had told the safety
board it did not know if Flight 261's box monitored the stabilizer.
Investigators are now examining the data for clues to the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Broken metal sometimes speaks loudest of all, a lexicon of metal
fatigue, stress, microscopic imperfections and hairline fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wildey, head NTSB metallurgist, transcribes the metallic
messages with electronic scanning microscopes. He examined the
crumpled fuselage of TWA 800, charred fragments from the forward
cargo hold on ValuJet 592. His job boils down to determining
whether burns, fractures and cracks in metal occurred before,
during or after an airline accident. Or caused the crash.
</P>
<P>
   A report Wildey's now working on will form the technical
backbone of a safety board investigation that began on Sept. 12 in
West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   On that Sunday morning, Continental Airlines Flight 1933 _ bound
for Houston with 84 passengers and five crew members _ took off to
the east from Palm Beach International Airport. About 20 seconds
after takeoff, as the Boeing 737 was climbing through 800 feet at a
speed of about 190 mph, a turbine seal in the left engine
fractured, and the engine blew apart. The pilot took the plane
safely back to PBIA. Engine parts rained down into the neighborhood
below. Nobody on the ground or on board the plane was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Within two hours, Jeff Kennedy, one of six NTSB investigators
based in Miami, was on the scene and in charge of the
investigation. The safety board is the lead agency in air crashes,
unless a crime has been committed. In that case, the FBI takes
over.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy knew that Jim Wildey and his metallurgical skills would
come into play.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a big investigation, but it's important. They're all
important, says Wildey.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the NTSB's job _ as spelled out by Congress _ is
to solve transportation accidents _ civil aviation, buses,
interstate trucks, trains, even gas pipeline mishaps. Once it
solves a case, the board makes safety recommendations to regulatory
agencies, the FAA in the case of air transport.
</P>
<P>
   BEST IN THE BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   It's a small agency, fewer than 400 employees, a budget of less
than $55 million _ or about 18 cents per U.S. citizen. It has
solved almost all of the country's 110,000 civilian aviation
accidents and incidents since 1967. Its investigators are the best
in the business, according to pilots, aviation engineers and a
recent audit conducted by the RAND Corporation at the request of
the NTSB.
</P>
<P>
   But changes may be in the air at the agency. Political, social
and scientific forces and theories _ some untried and perhaps
untrue _ may push the board in new directions:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1996, Congress made the NTSB the lead agency in meeting the
needs of families and victims of an air crash, including
translation services, family counseling and victim identification.
</P>
<P>
   The move toward family services is seen by some as a move away
from the board's primary mission of investigating crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the cancer in the NTSB,'' says William Langewiesche, a
former commercial pilot, Atlantic correspondent and author of
numerous essays and ``Inside the Sky,'' a book on air safety,
flying and aviation accident investigation. ``It may sound cold,
but unless a body has some bearing on the cause of a crash _ powder
burns or a bullet hole _ it's not relevant to the investigation.
I'm sorry about the victims, but I want the NTSB to find the cause
in order to prevent future accidents, future victims. Safety, not
solace, is their job.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The party system of investigating crashes, which can include
carriers, manufacturers and pilot unions and can result in
conflicting agendas, should be changed, according to the RAND
audit.
</P>
<P>
   _ The complexity of modern aircraft has outstripped traditional
investigative methods. The board should engage in less reactive and
more ``pro-active'' research, the audit said, and seek the help of
research labs at universities and the Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board's job is to react,'' says Langewiesche. ``To
accidents. The government already has an aviation research branch:
NASA. And it has an aviation regulatory branch: the FAA. These
investigators are not academics. They don't conduct research
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at the investigation of the West Palm Beach accident
brings some of those concerns and suggestions into focus.
</P>
<P>
   The Continental engine failure contains no compelling elements
of human drama or mystery, as with TWA 800 and ValuJet 592. The
cause was quickly found.
</P>
<P>
   But, as a senior NTSB official said, ``We were really very
fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not hyperbole. Safety board officials avoid speculation
like pilots avoid thunder clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The engine that blew up on Sept. 12 was a General Electric model
CFM56-3, one of more than 4,000 built since the mid-1970s and one
of 2,000 still in use on Boeing 737 aircraft. It suffered an
``uncontained failure'' over West Palm Beach, according to the
NTSB.
</P>
<P>
   Uncontained failure is engineering jargon that means it
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Past uncontained failures have led to chains of events that
brought down airplanes. In the mid-1970s, aircraft companies
estimated the odds of an engine failure leading to loss of control
at more than a billion-to-one. Yet within 12 years, five
uncontained engine failures led to loss of control and four
crashes, including the crash in July 1989 of a United DC-10 that
lost all hydraulic controls. The crash, in Sioux City, Iowa, killed
111 of the 286 people on board.
</P>
<P>
   Uncontained engine failure is of particular interest to the
NTSB, said a senior investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Planes are made to fly after an engine loss. They are made to
fly with some damage to the controls, flaps, slats, stabilizer and
rudder, all the systems that keep a plane flying. Back-up systems _
multiple hydraulic lines _ lead to control surfaces so that failure
in one line won't endanger the pilot's ability to fly the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Yet an unpredictable series of events can lead to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft may be the most complex part of such a sequence, so
complex, says RAND, that the safety board may not be able to figure
out what went wrong when something does: ``When a complex system
fails, the number of potential scenarios rises proportionally.''
</P>
<P>
   And: ``The crash of a single airplane, killing hundreds of
passengers, would all but consume the NTSB staff.''
</P>
<P>
   COMPLEX SYSTEMS THEORY QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   Complex systems theory is a current high fashion in academia. At
its core is a thesis _ a belief, really _ that engineers can build
technologies that no single engineer understands, systems so
complex they invite accidents by defying the best efforts of humans
to keep them safe. RAND includes big passenger jets in that
category and cites TWA 800 as an example of the failure of a
complex technology that stumped the safety board.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds reasonable to the layman, but some experts disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is highly questionable think-tank blather,'' says
Langewiesche. ``Big does not necessarily mean more complex. Modern
jets are simpler from the pilots' standpoint, easier to fly. Flight
data recorders can monitor hundreds of factors in the aircraft. The
mystery of the spark in the fuel tank of TWA 800 was buried in the
fireball, not buried in the engineering of a 747. The lack of a
final answer has nothing to do with so-called complex systems. The
evidence burned.''
</P>
<P>
   All the evidence needed to investigate Continental Flight 1933's
engine failure fell to the ground in chunks, shards and slivers.
The parts gave the safety board an opportunity to take a clean look
at an uncontained failure and recommend changes, if necessary, to
engine maintenance procedures. Enough metal was found to give
General Electric and board investigators their answer.
</P>
<P>
   The parts in question underwent about 48 man-hours of
microscopic examination carried out over two or three weeks,
including a week at GE.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case like this, we look for pre-existing cracks,'' said
Wildey. ``Possible material defects, fractures that can lead to
failure, where they're located, how long they may have been there.
Discoloration can tell us the age of a fracture. We want to put it
all into the right sequence. I think we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   The GE engine component that flew apart is called the forward
turbine air seal, a metal alloy disc that keeps high-velocity and
super-heated air from bleeding back from the rear of the engine
into the forward, compressor part of the engine. It is a rotating
part, vs. all those engine parts that are subject to pressures and
stress yet do not spin.
</P>
<P>
   Rotating parts hold special interest for the NTSB. The Sioux
City crash sequence began when a rotating part flew out of the
engine _ an uncontained failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see more regular inspections by the aviation
industry of rotating parts,'' says Bob MacIntosh, 12 years with the
safety board, 22 years with the Air Force and aircraft
manufacturers _ and chief investigator of the Sioux City crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say that only in the context of my role as an
investigator,'' he says. ``More inspections mean more data for me
to analyze. But you could force the industry to go broke by
demanding too many inspections. The industry is safe. Our job is to
make it safer. We start with an accident, not with an idea. We kick
tin, ask questions, get answers. That's how we approach safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The CFM56-3 engine is one of the safest ever built. More than
4,000 have flown more than 82 million hours without a catastrophic
failure. The West Palm Beach incident was the first uncontained
failure of that model in 25 years of operation. The engines have
been subject to hundreds of oil leaks, bird strikes and other
routine glitches over the years, resulting in some engine shutdowns
and unscheduled landings _ but no uncontained failures, according
to Service Difficulty Reports kept by the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   Because the final safety board report has not been released on
Continental 1933, Wildey and the board won't say what caused the
air seal to fail.
</P>
<P>
   GE did say, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to determine that a crack had developed,'' said
GE spokesman, Rick Kennedy, on Nov. 29. He also said the failure
was a ``random event'' and ``the part had aged badly.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a comment the NTSB may take exception with. Parties to
investigations are prohibited from making probable-cause statements
before the board issues its final report.
</P>
<P>
   And, the turbine seal in question was a ``life-limit'' part,
that is, a part replaced at regular intervals but not necessarily
inspected at regular intervals. Many aircraft systems _ such as
flaps, rivets, controls, electronics _ are inspected regularly and
replaced or repaired when necessary. That leaves a maintenance
trail for investigators to follow, as with the stabilizer on Alaska
Airlines 261.
</P>
<P>
   But GE could deduce the part had aged badly only after it had
fallen apart.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, GE could make its claims with certainty
because the safety board structures its accident inquiries in a
fashion unique to investigatory agencies: the party system. The
party system brings subjects of NTSB investigations on board as
parties to the investigations, as participants in the
investigation. GE laboratory technicians working at the company's
Cincinnati jet engine plant did much of the research into the
engine failure, under Wildey's supervision.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a major crash _ like Alaska Airlines 261 _ the
NTSB will set up as many as 15 working groups, each dedicated to a
facet of the airplane and the overall investigation, including
fuselage, systems, pilots and weather. NTSB group leaders select
experts _ not lawyers or marketing people _ from unions, carriers
and manufacturers to sit on those committees.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY SYSTEM `WORKS, AND WORKS WELL'
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into the GE engine failure was focused solely
on the engine. That's why GE engineers examined the engine parts.
They then gave Wildey their version of how and why the explosion
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like the party system lets the fox in the chicken
coop, but it works, and works well,'' says Langewiesche. ``The NTSB
is one of the few government agencies that does exactly what it's
supposed to do. It's a saintly agency. They want the facts and
don't care what the legal or public relations fallout might be for
carriers or manufacturers or pilot unions. Sure, the NTSB knows
parties to the investigation have their own agenda. They're not
naive. Does it make sense for GE or Boeing or Pratt to take part in
an investigation of their products? You bet. These are the best
technicians in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Wildey agrees: ``The NTSB has 400 employees. GE has some
stunning equipment and 400 technicians in that factory alone. We
need their input.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a random event, says GE. That led the company to issue a
service advisory to its customers: When next inspecting CFM56-3
engines, use a more advanced electronic scanning process to look
for imperfections in the forward turbine seal.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines declined to comment when asked whether it
had since inspected the right engine on the plane that departed
from PBIA on Sept. 12, but said the airline operates in strict
compliance with all FAA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers have up to two years to do the inspection, according to
the GE advisory.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board may recommend a shorter inspection timetable
when its final report is issued.
</P>
<P>
   Its ``probable cause'' statement will be the final word on the
accident, the ``ball game'' for lawyers and manufacturers. When the
board speaks, everybody listens.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA may approve any recommendations made by the safety
board. Eighty-two percent of the agency's recommendations are
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   But one word will probably not appear in the final NTSB report:
random.
</P>
<P>
   ``Random implies an event is not connected to anything, out of
the blue,'' said MacIntosh, the senior investigator. ``It's not our
type of word. An event may be rare, but there's always a cause.
Somewhere there's a cause. We find the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
