<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Vultures congregated to feed on a deer carcass in the woods
near our house. One large, prehistoric-looking bird perched on the
porch railing and eyed our cat. It easily could have attacked the
cat, so I scared the bird off. Now I'm uncomfortable letting the
cat out. Do vultures pose a hazard to small pets? _ M.F.
</P>
<P>
   A: They are not really a threat to household domestic animals,
says Chris Shackelford of the Texas Parks and Wildlife. Vultures
are carrion eaters (they clean up our land of dead animals). It is
pretty impressive that vultures can consume rotting meat with no
ill effect. If the vultures were very hungry, a wounded living
animal or very defenseless one (a newborn gerbil, for example)
might be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you identify the narrator of the movie ``My Dog Skip''? I
watched the credits, but I must have missed it _ it sounds like
Bruce Willis. _Pat A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sounds like Bruce Willis, but it's not. The crooning tone
belongs to musician and actor Harry Connick Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When my father-in-law was in town recently, he noticed that
on some Texas license plates the flag was on the left side, on
others the right side of the plate and on others there was not a
flag at all. We thought you might be able to help clear up this
mystery. _David Triplett
</P>
<P>
   A: Plates issued before December 1998 have the flag on the left
and sport letter, letter, letter, number, number, letter. When this
series was exhausted, ``we converted to a new alphanumeric scheme,
which is letter, number, number, letter, letter, letter and shifted
the flag to the right,'' says Texas Department of Transportation's
Mike Viesca. The not-so-popular plates celebrating 150 years of
statehood do not have a Lone Star flag at all. Q: Are you supposed
to acknowledge sympathy cards? _M.A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Personal letters along with flowers, donations or other
assistance should be recognized with a handwritten note. No one
expects the acknowledgement to be timely or lengthy. If the
condolence card was printed, adds the doyenne of etiquette, Emily
Post, with no personal message added, you are not obliged to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We recently moved into a house with sliding glass doors as
the only source of access to our back yard. With a dog alone inside
our home all day, and no standard wood door in which to install a
dog door, we are in a bind! I have been running home on my lunch
break, but I can't keep this up forever. Is there such thing as a
dog door that attaches to a sliding glass door? _G.G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yep. These glass panels come in small, medium, large and
extra large. Order one through Bark N Purr, 4604 Burnet Road, and
your pooch will enjoy new freedom in a couple of days. Armchair
shopper? Order from Pet Expo at (888) PET EXPO or online from Pet
Doors at dogdoors.com. Be prepared to pay more than $100, but the
lunchtime freedom will be well worth it.Q: My husband never washes
chicken before cooking. He unpacks it from the containers and
throws it straight into a pot or marinates and grills it. I can
hardly stand that. He says the cooking will kill whatever's on it.
Can you ask your experts their opinion on the matter? (The funny
thing is, he is totally paranoid about uncooked chicken touching
anything in the kitchen!)
</P>
<P>
   _ Margarita F.
</P>
<P>
   A: The ultimate poultry source is the USDA Meat and Poultry
Hotline at (800) 535-4555. To wash or not to wash? The hotline
experts said it does not make any difference from a health
standpoint. Caveats? The chicken must be in its original wrap and
fresh (no more than two or three days in the refrigerator) and
never been left more than two hours at room temperature. Q:
Recently, I paid a station clerk inside for my gasoline, but when
my bill arrived, a $50 charge in addition to the gas price had been
added to my bill. Can this happen when a credit card is used at the
pump instead of paying inside? _ Robbie L.
</P>
<P>
   A: According to CreditComm, gas stations do not have access to
card numbers or expiration dates when a card is used at the pump
(wait for your receipt). When a credit card is used inside a
station, the information is available to the clerk.
</P>
<P>
   The negative about a card at a pump? No way to verify you are
the card's owner. Inside? The account number could be accessed.
Bottom line? Keep track of your card, read your statements and
immediately challenge any discrepancies
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several times a year blue wasps seem to hatch, and for a
couple of weeks I kill six to 10 per day, usually around bathroom
lights and a window in the master bedroom. I have searched for
their nest but cannot find it. I have sealed all noticeable cracks,
bathroom vents and have added screens at the heat/air conditioning
vents. All to no avail. Pest exterminators have nothing to offer.
How can I get rid of these pests?
</P>
<P>
   _ David Waugh
</P>
<P>
   A: These are probably not wasps but dirt daubers _ beneficial
because they eat spiders and other insects (yum, yum). Daubers make
long cigar-shaped nests. They are probably in the crevices of the
attic rafters, says bee and wasp remover Al Kinser. Hardware cloth
does not keep them from getting in and nesting in odd holes. Check
the tops of recessed lights and attic vent holes. Remove the nests
with a paint scraper (nests contain dead spiders and eggs only).
You may have to do this several times until they get the idea to
move on.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Turns out Valentine's Day is not just about lovebirds. The
``Giant Book of Superstitions'' notes the first bird you see on
this day of love portends your future mate. Check out these birds
and prophecies. See a blackbird, marry a member of the clergy;
goldfinch, marry a millionaire; yellowbird, marry a reasonably rich
spouse; a bluebird, poverty; a sparrow, love in a cottage; a
redbreast, marry a sailor; and a flock of doves, good luck in
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
