<HEADER>
A6189 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX     02-14 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locals' thoughts on presidential primary
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It's business as usual this morning at the
local cafe. My retired farmer buddies are talking politics over
their first cup of decaf. As is also usual, nobody's agreeing on
anything other than they'd all sooner vote for Tiny Hodelman than
for Al Gore or ``Little George.'' ``If the rest of Ohio feels the
way you guys do,'' I warn them, ``the upcoming primary is going to
knock the pollsters for a loop...and who's Tiny Hodelman?''
</P>
<P>
   Amos has to laugh just thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiny was an okay guy,'' he says, ``just not real blessed in
the brains department. Once he loaded a couple of pigs in the back
of his pickup and headed for the fairgrounds. Then he got to
thinking about how dirty the pigs were and how much better they'd
look clean, so he drove 'em through the carwash. The pigs came out
clean but scared. They wouldn't quit squealing and Tiny had to
drive 'em back home so they'd shut up. Missed the whole fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Benny says we can't vote for Tiny anyway because he's been dead
for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   I tell him that shouldn't make much difference. Back where I
lived in Georgia, dead folks voted all the time. Whenever a liquor
referendum came up, they crawled out of the cemeteries to vote it
down. If dead folks can vote,
</P>
<P>
   they sure ought to be able to hold office.
</P>
<P>
   Cal brings up the Reform party and chuckles. Says there isn't
much left of it since they had that brawl in Nashville and dumped
their chairman. Amos asks where he thinks that leaves Ventura and
Trump, and Cal's answer is: OUT! he hopes. ``Guys like that make us
look sillier than we already are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I think'd happen if Trump got elected?'' Cal
asks. We can't guess, so he tells us. ``First thing he'd probably
do is mortgage the whole dang country to finance some real estate
scheme. Then he'd lose us in the next
</P>
<P>
   market slump and that'd leave the country up for grabs. We'd
probably end up the property of some third-world country that can't
even keep the buses running on time.''
</P>
<P>
   While we're thinking that one over, Benny tells us how he was
never against the notion of Trump running, but thought he ought to
get married first because it just wouldn't be dignified for our
country to have a ``Model of the Week'' instead of a First Lady.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder out loud how anybody in his right mind would consider
forking over tax money to a guy who brags about being $900 million
in debt and sells $100,000 memberships in his vacation home
(Mar-a-Lago, formerly Marjorie
</P>
<P>
   Merriweather Post's Palm Beach castle) to keep his creditors
from foreclosing. No way this guy could make it on a measly
$400,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   What does bother Benny though is Hillary in New York. Amos
reminds him she's running for the Senate, not for President.
</P>
<P>
   Benny storks his neck out at us and jabs an index finger on the
table a few times just to make sure we're paying attention. ``Oh
yeah. That's this year. Give her time. She wants Bill's old job -
wants to rub his nose in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal whispers something to Amos and they both cackle. When I ask
what's so funny they brush me off saying it's an Oval office thing.
I tell them their smutty geezer minds are working overtime. They
tell me they like it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Amos says McCain's okay with him, both of them being veterans.
Benny kind of likes Bradley, and Cal says he's real sorry Forbes
dropped out because, ``He was the only guy running who wasn't any
better looking than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   And there you have it, folks. It may not be official, but
believe me, this is how elections are made. Forget the polls and
get over the hype. New Hampshire and South Carolina mean nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, California, and New York? They're up for grabs,
but come March 7, Super Tuesday, I can tell you how Ohio will be
voting.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear it for Tiny Hodelman!
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
