</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stomp on the gas, or stomp on the cityscape
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Rockstar Games is back, and the winter lineup of Playstation
games totally kicks. To start, Grand Theft Auto has
beenreincarnated as GTA2 ($50; www.gta2.com). If you played the
controversial first one, you know the drill. You play a criminal
intent on stealing cars and killing people. In the sequel, the
purpose is to endear yourself to one of three street gangs by
``offing'' members of other street gangs and doing ``errands.'' You
perform these tasks to a rocking soundtrack and smooth game play.
This overhead driver/shooter game is irreverent and violent, but
it's totally fun and worth the flak you might get from an
anti-violence group. Rockstar's other title is Thrasher: Skate and
Destroy ($50; www.skateanddestroy.com). This skating game is good
enough to brandish the name of Thrasher, the ultimate skater's mag.
In the game, you are an up and comer armed only with a skateboard
and a couple of tricks. Through the levels, you join competitions
and kickflip, nollie and tailgrab your way into other competitions
and sponsorships. This game is addictive and will make you set
aside Activision's ``Tony Hawk: Pro Skater.''
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   It's only fair to judge a game by what it hopes to accomplish,
so criticizing Slave Zero (Infogrames, $30) for a lack of depth
would be like criticizing Pokemon for being unrealistic. That's the
point. Zero is about living the universal childhood temper-tantrum
fantasy of being an invincible 100-foot-tall monster who stomps
mightily through an endless cityscape, crushing and smashing
anything in its way. In Zero, you're a rampaging robot with a
mission. Cars on endless interstates swerve to avoid you or smash
into 20-car pileups as tiny frightened citizens scream and cower or
run. Helicopters and buildings are shattered with one blow from
your mighty fist or a blast from your rocket launcher. On the
downside, too few weapons options, an initially confusing control
setup and maddening ammunition shortages slow the game needlessly.
And it has no multiplayer option. But once you get up to speed, the
anime-style hero, fluid movement, beautiful cityscape and furious
pace add up to tons and tons of rampaging excitement. Which is all
``Slave Zero'' ever wanted. Stomp on with your bad self.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
