<HEADER>
A6192 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TECH-KIDGEAR15-COX     02-14 0240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-KIDGEAR15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Simon &AMP; Schuster encyclopedia both helpful and hard to use
 &HT;    By Joe Stafford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There are things to like about the Simon &AMP;
Schuster New Millennium Children's Encyclopedia and Home Reference
Library (Deluxe 2000 Edition; $21; www.simonandschuster.com), but
its giggly rainbow of typography and ``For Ages 8-12 Years'' on the
cover belie its hard-to-fathom interface and a dizzying array of
options that will daunt most adults and overwhelm its target
audience. The program lets the user download books and updates from
the Internet (at additional cost), organize content in dozens of
ways or study books in several languages, among many customizing
tools. Other pluses include a built-in dictionary, atlas, animal
encyclopedia and book of world cultures, all well-illustrated. But
even the handy voice-over tour of scrollbars and options can't hide
the giant learning curve required to master the interface. The
articles are written in clear, kid-friendly language and
accompanied by a fairly generous selection of illustrations, short
films and audio recordings. It's not a bad tool for kids' research
projects, but the bottom line is that without the dedicated
supervision of a librarian or other adult, this complex program
will probably just drive most children bonkers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
