tools. Other pluses include a built-in dictionary, atlas, animal
encyclopedia and book of world cultures, all well-illustrated. But
even the handy voice-over tour of scrollbars and options can't hide
the giant learning curve required to master the interface. The
articles are written in clear, kid-friendly language and
accompanied by a fairly generous selection of illustrations, short
films and audio recordings. It's not a bad tool for kids' research
projects, but the bottom line is that without the dedicated
supervision of a librarian or other adult, this complex program
will probably just drive most children bonkers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
