<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-TERMITE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TERMITE COULD BE HEADED YOUR WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDWARD M. EVELD  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If termites come chewing at your doorframes this year, just
thank your lucky stars they aren't Formosan termites.
</P>
<P>
   You know about killer bees, but have you heard about this
hyperactive brand of wood munchers?
</P>
<P>
   An ecologist, writing in an issue of the ``Bulletin of the Royal
Entomological Society,'' recently labeled the Formosan termite the
``most important'' structural pest of the new millennium _ as if
you needed one.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, ``important'' means ``bad.'' Formosan termites are
eating their way up and down the Gulf Coast, from Texas to Florida.
They've made tracks into Georgia, the Carolinas, Tennessee and
California, said Mark Hunter, an ecologist and associate professor
at the University of Georgia in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   While they currently are going gangbusters mostly in moist
climates, Formosan termites could theoretically survive farther
north, including Missouri and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the worry?
</P>
<P>
   Formosan termites have several endearing characteristics. They
are champions at adaptation _ they can use the condensation around
a pipe as a water source rather than the soil _ and they create
enormous colonies. Eradicating them is a serious challenge.
Chemical barriers in the soil are no match.
</P>
<P>
   ``This termite can set up house in your attic,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   While most termites feed on dead trees and wood, Formosan
termites will attack living plants. About 30 percent of the famed
live oak trees around New Orleans are infested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worry is that they will attack other hosts and perhaps
even crop plants,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Already the United States is spending $1 billion a year trying
to control Formosan termites and prevent their spread. The U.S.
Department of Agriculture is engaged in a major research project to
rein in the species.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that they haven't staked a claim to Missouri or
Kansas _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness,'' said Steve Ashe, entomology professor at the
University of Kansas. ``They're really aggressive. They have such
huge colonies they can render a house virtually unlivable in just a
few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Formosan termites have been in the United States at least since
the 1960s, by way of Asia and the Pacific islands. Humans are
responsible for their introduction here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get transported around when people move wood,'' Ashe
said. ``Apparently old railroad ties are good for transporting
these termites.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
