A6211 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STORMS-GA-SIDE-COX     02-14 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORMS-GA-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'A roar, woo-woo-woo,' then disaster in Southwest Georgia
 &HT;    WITH STORMS-GEORGIA
 &HT;    FOR MONDAY PMs
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    and Mike Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Vox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terrified residents described deafening thunder, continuous
lightning that lit the sky and roaring winds as tornadoes swept
through Southwest Georgia shortly after midnight, killing at least
12 people.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest hit area was in Mitchell County, south of Albany,
where a twister cut a five-mile path through a residential area of
mostly mobile homes about 12:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very scary,'' said Ron Gilliard, Mitchell County
hospital administrator, whose home was damaged shortly after
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliard, his parents, his brother and a cousin live in an area
south of Camilla devastated by the tornados. ``My wife and I ran to
the bathroom, held each other and prayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilliard said his first cousin suffered lacerations when his
mobile home was destroyed. ``It was in a pecan grove, where every
tree was uprooted,'' he said. ``He was bleeding profusely. I put
him in my car and drove him to the hospital. It took us 45 minutes
to go the three miles because of downed trees and power lines.''
</P>
<P>
   The small, 33-bed hospital quickly became ``a war zone,'' he
said, as more than 120 injured people poured in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hallway was lined with patients; we took mattresses off
older beds and put them on the floor; we had patients in chairs, on
cots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what hospitals do; we triaged the most seriously
injured first,'' he said. ``My entire medical staff responded,
including off-duty people, and a lot of our folks have damaged
homes, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Trees were blown down, a brick house was lifted off its
foundation and witnesses said a tractor-trailer was flipped on its
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you heard was a roar, woo-woo-woo,'' said Johnny Jones,
whose mobile home about two miles south of Camilla was lifted by
winds and landed on its side.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he was able to free his 14-year-old son, who was
pinned under a washing machine, and they crawled out a window.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could see was that everything was demolished. People
were hollering and crying 'Where's my child?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He took four of his neighbors to the hospital in his car. ``They
were skinned up, cut up and one guy got his leg broke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like somebody took a bulldozer and leveled it,'' said
Mikie Newsome, a volunteer firefighter who rushed to the scene to
help search through the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his father watched as lightning lit the sky and a
large dark funnel cloud dipped down about three miles from their
house.
</P>
<P>
   Perlist Wallace, 38, lives about a block from the devastated
area. ``I saw trees on top of house trailers. Everything was just
torn apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
