</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEN-AFFLECK-IN-REINDEER-GAMES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEN THERE, DONE THAT: BEN AFFLECK ON FILMS, FAME AND `REINDEER
GAMES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Ben Affleck with Charlize Theron in a
scene from ``Reindeer Games.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Ben Affleck's beefcake photos had been carefully clipped out and
taped onto the wall, occupying a place of honor above Matt Damon
and below Leonardo DiCaprio.
 &HT;    Somehow, though, Affleck wasn't pleased.
 &HT;    The actor wasn't visiting the bedroom of some teen-age fan,
after all, but touring the cells in a maximum-security Canadian
prison, researching his role as a convict in his latest film, John
Frankenheimer's ``Reindeer Games.''
 &HT;    ``Let's just say that, going through a cellblock, I began to
regret every single hunky pose,'' Affleck says with a laugh. ``I
couldn't believe it when I saw my cover of GQ up on a few walls.
 &HT;    ``I kept thinking about how my friend Matt Damon wore that green
Speedo in `The Talented Mr. Ripley' _ I thought, `If the positions
were reversed, he'd be in real trouble!'''
 &HT;    He'd planned to spend the night in the prison, the better to
grasp a convict's point of view, but he changed his mind.
 &HT;    ``The warden called me over and said, `Ben, a lot of these guys
really liked you in ``Good Will Hunting.'' We're worried that, if
you stay over, you might be taken hostage,''' he recalls. ``I said,
`Yes, thank you, I'll be sleeping at home.'''
 &HT;    Relaxing in a gray sweater and blue jeans for an interview at
Manhattan's Essex House, Affleck is a long way from the hoosegow,
but he says it doesn't seem all that far.
 &HT;    ``You know,'' he says, ``when I was in jail, most of the inmates
had two questions, `Did you sleep with Liv Tyler during
``Armageddon?'' Are you still dating Gwyneth?'''
 &HT;    He laughs.
 &HT;    ``You know, prisoners and celebrity journalists have a lot in
common!''
 &HT;    Affleck has never been hotter, with two films about to be
released: ``Boiler Room,'' which will open on Feb. 18, casts him as
a fast-talking corporate recruiter at a shady stockbrokerage, while
he stars in ``Reindeer Games,'' due a week later, as an ex-convict
who, in a case of mistaken identity, is taken hostage by a band of
thugs.
 &HT;    ``Yes, I have work,'' he says. ``But the real question you want
to ask is, `Are you happy, Ben?'''
 &HT;    Actually, he says, that depends.
 &HT;    ``I think I'm lucky,'' he concedes, ``but I'm not always happy.
As far as fame and fortune go, I generally believe one should
understand that none of it is deserved.
 &HT;    ``Look, the phone has stopped ringing for better actors than
me.''
 &HT;    Even after he and Damon won a screenwriting Oscar for ``Good
Will Hunting'' (1997), Affleck says, things still didn't sit right
with him.
 &HT;    ``I've found it difficult to enjoy success,'' Affleck admits.
``It's strange, because when you're a young, struggling actor you
have to convince yourself that someday, when you get to the point
where you have money and roles, you'll relax and be happy.
 &HT;    ``But I've got those things,'' he says, ``and now I've found out
something depressing: The struggle is more satisfying than getting
what you want _ it's the struggle that makes you happy.''
 &HT;    For now, the struggle is definitely over. Affleck is not only in
demand with top directors and producers, but he's a certifiable
Hollywood hunk _ a status not likely to be diminished by ``Reindeer
Games,'' in which he shares an explicit sex scene with co-star
Charlize Theron.
 &HT;    ``I did not use a butt double,'' the actor swears. ``That's a
point of pride with me _ it will always be my own butt. Although I
do have a flat a--. It was one time when an actor was glad the
camera puts on 10 pounds.''
 &HT;    Affleck began acting at an early age, as a child growing up in
Central Square, the non-affluent part of Cambridge, Mass. His
parents divorced when he was a small boy, and for support he turned
to his best friend, Matt, who lived a block away.
 &HT;    Though Affleck was the first to get an agent and find work on
PBS and in local television, his agent eventually signed Damon as
well. Soon the two high-school students were taking the train to
auditions in New York.
 &HT;    For a while, things didn't go well. Affleck landed small roles
in ``School Ties'' (1992) and ``Dazed and Confused'' (1993), but
college stints in Vermont and California led nowhere and, after
breaking up with his girlfriend, he found himself homeless.
 &HT;    He headed for Los Angeles, where he crashed with Damon in a
small, two-bedroom house they shared with another friend. In their
spare time, they wrote ``Good Will Hunting'' (1997) _ and the rest
is history.
 &HT;    But not history Hollywood-style, Affleck insists.
 &HT;    ``I can't imagine myself getting to the point where I'm saying
things like, `This bleeping limo had better be a stretch!''' he
says, laughing. ``In fact, Matt and I are constantly saying, `Let's
scale things down.'
 &HT;    ``We look at each other and say, `Man, I don't care if it's a
limo _ I'm just glad I have a ride.'''
 &HT;    It's sometimes been a bumpy ride, though, especially when it
comes to his private life. All a woman has to do is say hello to
him, it seems, to start the tabloid rumors swirling.
 &HT;    ``I swear there is some guy in L.A. who looks like me,'' Affleck
says. ``And he's dating all these beautiful women.''
 &HT;    The most prominent beautiful woman in his life is Gwyneth
Paltrow, the on-again/off-again girlfriend about whom Affleck will
say nothing more than ``she's a wonderful actress'' and ``we're
very close.''
 &HT;    That may be an understatement, according to ``Reindeer Games''
co-star Clarence Williams III.
 &HT;    ``Ben's lady Gwyneth flew in to see him all the time on the
set,'' Williams says in a separate interview. ``They would be
standing in the snow and tundra, holding hands. People would gasp,
because it was like the Golden Couple had arrived.
 &HT;    ``Standing there were two Oscar winners,'' he adds. ``They're
gorgeous. They have lots of money and fame. You almost wanted to
bow to them!''
 &HT;    The speculation is bound to continue, because Affleck's next
movie is ``Bounce,'' a love story about survivors of a plane crash
due to open this summer. His co-star: Paltrow.
 &HT;    Plane crash notwithstanding, Affleck says that the worst part of
the shoot was the makeup: Because he spends much of the movie
shirtless, he had to have extensive work done to cover the multiple
tattoos that are souvenirs of his restless youth.
 &HT;    ``They have this huge, flesh-colored spray paint,'' he says.
``You just stand there, and they sandblast you for 10 minutes. The
tattoo thing was a good lesson in decisions that have long-lasting
repercussions!''
 &HT;    ``Long-lasting'' is actually a key word for Affleck, who aspires
to a long career.
 &HT;    ``I don't think you've really made it until you can say you've
had career longevity,'' he says. ``I want decades.''
 &HT;    He wouldn't mind a few more awards, too. Unlike many actors, he
admits that he cherishes his Oscar.
 &HT;    ``My Oscar is on a bookshelf in my apartment in L.A.,'' he says.
``I was going to slap it on the dash in my '69 Cadillac under the
fuzzy dice, but I figured it would probably get ripped off. I could
imagine getting carjacked.''
 &HT;    In fact, he speculates, he might even know the carjacker from
his tour behind bars.
 &HT;    ``I would be like, `Buddy, it's me _ your friend, Benny! Take
the car. Take Matt. But could I please keep my Oscar?'''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
