<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGERS-NAOMI-AND-WYNONNA-JUDD-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DAWN OF THE JUDDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singers Naomi and Wynonna Judd.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Ask Wynonna Judd if she ever again expected to sing with her
mother, Naomi, and she doesn't say no.
 &HT;    ``Not no, but hell no,'' the 36-year-old singer says. ``That's
my answer for everything when it comes to the Judds being back. I
am absolutely somewhere between in awe and `God, you certainly have
a sense of humor' to `I can't believe this is happening.'''
 &HT;    She isn't the only one surprised. So is the country-music
industry, not to mention the legion of fans who scooped up more
than 20 million copies of Judds albums during the 1980s and early
1990s.
 &HT;    As far as the Judds themselves knew, however, the duo was
history after Naomi was diagnosed with hepatitis C in 1990. She
retired from music, expecting to die within a few years, while
Wynonna launched a successful solo career.
 &HT;    But then something unexpected happened: Naomi, relying mostly on
holistic- and alternative-healing methods, staged a miraculous
recovery. Today, her doctors can find no trace of the disease.
 &HT;    ``I'm just enjoying this medical miracle that I am,'' the
54-year-old Naomi says, ``and everything came all of a sudden into
a confluence from that.''
 &HT;    ``Everything'' includes a Judds reunion performance last New
Year's Eve in Phoenix, hosted by Wynonna's younger sister, actress
Ashley Judd. Exhilarated, the Judds decided to mount a full
reunion, the two-month ``Power to Change'' tour, and also returned
to the studio to record four new songs that are included as a bonus
on Wynonna's new album, ``New Day Dawning'' (Universal Music,
2000).
 &HT;    The whole chain of events has left her reeling, Wynonna admits.
 &HT;    ``I'm really, quite frankly, just now starting to get used to
it, because it's taken me almost a year to sort of process and
filter the different emotions I've been experiencing through all of
this,'' the singer says. ``She's not supposed to be here _ people
forget about that.
 &HT;    ``For whatever reason, people think we have a perfect formula
for everything,'' Wynonna says. ``But I remember when she didn't
get out of bed for days _ I used to have to go visit her, and she'd
be in her pajamas and I'd be like, `Mom, don't you want to put
clothes on?' and she'd be, `No, I don't feel like it.'
 &HT;    ``Now I'm looking at her onstage, singing and dancing around,''
Wynonna says with a shrug. ``Go figure. It doesn't make any sense
to me _ I'm just happy with the way it's all turned out.''
 &HT;    The intervening years have brought about a much better
relationship between the two singers, she adds. Naomi's drive is
legendary _ she left her husband while her children were young and
struggled to raise them on a nurse's salary while fostering their
artistic interests, then joined Wynonna to form a singing act
which, after years of lean times, broke through to stardom in the
1980s _ but she was never the easiest person to live or work with.
 &HT;    ``We are, as you know, very emotional and very spiritual,'' says
Wynonna, who admits to having resented her mother's relentless
ambition throughout their early career, ``and we can sometimes suck
the energy out of a room pretty fast. It's like, bring your own
oxygen when you're with the Judds.''
 &HT;    By her own account, Naomi found it hard to combine show-business
professionalism with raising an ambivalent, depressive teen as both
daughter and co-star.
 &HT;    ``In one sense it was actually maddening,'' she says, ``because
if she was late _ which 99 percent of the time she was _ it just
sent me to the moon, because I'm the organized, prepared, punctual
one, and I just wanted everybody to love her. So I had to make
excuses for her, and then I'd jerk her on the bus and threaten to
pull her hair out.''
 &HT;    Nowadays, however, Naomi says ``it's just a lot more fun.''
 &HT;    The two women cut what she calls ``that psychological umbilical
chord'' following their 1991 farewell tour, a 10-month trek that
grossed more than $21 million. Now Wynonna is an established star
in her own right, with more than 9 million albums sold, six No. 1
hits and four Grammys of her own.
 &HT;    And in a role reversal, it's Wynonna who's now the working
mother of two _ divorced, she's currently dating her longtime
bodyguard, Dan Roach. She's also the one who now controls the
collaboration, having co-produced the four Judds songs that appear
on ``New Day Dawning.''
 &HT;    ``I'm looking at my kid, going `What do you think about this
harmony part, boss?''' Naomi says with a laugh. ``I love it. I'm in
awe of Wynonna Judd _ she's the voice of her generation, and for me
to get to stand next to her, to even be on the same stage and lend
harmony to her, just blows my mind.''
 &HT;    Her daughter laughs.
 &HT;    ``I love it,'' Wynonna says, ``because we're communicating now
as a family, and it's pretty awesome. I have a new appreciation for
my mother that I didn't have when I was 18 and trying to get off
the bus.''
 &HT;    Which means goodbye to the flamboyant Judd-vs.-Judd rumor mill,
she adds.
 &HT;    ``We work so well together and we get along so well that, quite
frankly, it's pretty boring for the tabloids and the people out
there who want some juicy story,'' Wynonna says. ``Though we're
talking about getting her a little hair extension, so that next
time we're on TV we can get into a fight and I can pull it out,
just to get people talking!''
 &HT;    Their fans shouldn't count on a long-term professional reunion
between Wynonna and Naomi _ who live, along with Ashley, on farms
in an area outside Nashville they refer to as Peaceful Valley. Both
see their current collaboration as a short-term thing.
 &HT;    Having established her own star, Wynonna no longer wants to
sublimate her identity in a team, while Naomi, who made her acting
debut last fall in the television movie ``A Holiday Romance,'' has
a crowded slate of projects that includes writing books, hosting a
weekly self-help radio show, ``Heart to Heart,'' and working to
bring about a cure for hepatitis C.
 &HT;    ``I am so fiercely committed to that, I can't go back into music
full time,'' Naomi says. ``I've been freed of a virus, but I'm not
going to feel free til we lick this whole thing.''
 &HT;    Wynonna, meanwhile, says that she's satisfied to enjoy working
with her mother in the present, without worrying about the future.
 &HT;    ``This is a vacation for me,'' she says. ``People think that I'm
taking this back step or that I'm sitting back and relaxing with
Mom again. They think I'm doing this for professional reasons.
 &HT;    ``Uh-uh _ I'm doing this because I want to, and because I can,''
she says. ``She's my mother. I've been on the road half my life
with this woman, and I wanted to take time out to say `Thank you'
and to celebrate the Judds' music.
 &HT;    ``And I don't think anybody believes me,'' Wynonna admits.
``They think we have to stay separate. I don't see it that way _ as
long as I keep myself intact about who I am, with and without her,
I'll be OK.
 &HT;    ``I don't get lost in her anymore, and I don't feel like the
Judds are taking over,'' she says. ``But they're a heck of a lot of
fun to be with, lemme tell ya.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
