w e BC-ROB-LOWE-IN-THE-WEST-     02-14 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROB-LOWE-IN-THE-WEST-WING-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROB LOWE GOES `WEST' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Rob Lowe in a scene from ``The West
Wing.'') 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before Feb. 20. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rob Lowe is used to life in the public eye. Actually, few people
have known the pluses and minuses of fame more thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   But even he admits to being amazed at the reaction to his role
on NBC's hit series, ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Lowe knew the show was hot, but he was surprised to find
that even jaded Tinseltown types can't get enough of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has truly been wild,'' Lowe says with a smile, nursing a
giant cappuccino in the cafeteria adjacent to the ``West Wing''
set. ``I've felt the momentum just from running into people. I went
to the premiere of `The Talented Mr. Ripley' a while back, and I
was just staggered with the amount of people coming up and telling
me they watch the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, Harvey Weinstein and Kevin Spacey love it,'' he says,
grinning. ``People want me to tell them what's going to happen
next. And I know a lot of these people aren't necessarily watching
every new TV show. It's quite exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lowe, who is making his maiden voyage in television after
more than a decade of film stardom, the speed with which ``The West
Wing'' has connected with its audience is remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's one of the most unique things about our show _
it reaches people,'' he says. ``Viewers are investing in the show
emotionally. They can only do that when a TV series or a movie is
very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a distancing in film _ and I speak from experience
here _ but on TV there's a sort of mesh with viewers,'' he adds.
``That's the beauty of television, that's what makes it special.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its September launch, ``The West Wing'' _ the
behind-the-scenes saga of a White House administration headed by
strong-willed President Josiah Bartlet (Martin Sheen) _ has become
a smash hit, regularly rating in the top five shows.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe plays Deputy Communications Director Sam Seaborn, a slick
political animal with an eye for the ladies, based loosely on
former Clinton advisor George Stephanopolous.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read the pilot, I was drawn to it because it was
exactly like a movie,'' Lowe recalls. ``Ironically, on any given
week we're more like a movie than some movies _ and if you watch a
lot of movies today, they're like MTV videos now.
</P>
<P>
   ``On our show, there're very long scenes _ we'll do five pages
of dialogue in one take!''
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected on a hit series with such a high-octane
cast, the tabloids are already buzzing with rumors that Lowe is
unhappy with his amount of camera time and has threatened to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says writer/executive producer Aaron Sorkin, the
playwright and screenwriter _ best known for ``A Few Good Men''
(1992) and ``The American President'' (1996) _ who co-created ``The
West Wing'' with television kingpin John Wells of ``ER'' and
``Third Watch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a single conversation about that,'' Sorkin
says. ``Rob hasn't come to us, he hasn't said that. Those
conversations haven't happened. That shouldn't be reported, because
we haven't talked about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's new status as a television star marks a full-circle
turnaround from where his career stood a decade ago. In fact, the
actor has virtually reinvented himself.
</P>
<P>
   To backtrack, he was a star from his film debut in the 1983
drama ``The Outsiders,'' which also featured future stars Tom
Cruise, Matt Dillon and Patrick Swayze. He was a founding member of
what the media dubbed ``the Brat Pack,'' which also included Ally
Sheedy, Emilio Estevez, Judd Nelson and Molly Ringwald.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe continued to turn out solid film work in movies such as
``The Hotel New Hampshire'' (1984), ``St. Elmo's Fire'' (1985) and
``About Last Night'' (1986). But things took a weird turn in 1989,
when a videotape surfaced, shot by Lowe himself and showing him
having sex with an underage girl while attending, of all things,
the 1988 Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother pressed statutory-rape charges, and Lowe was
ultimately sentenced to probation and 20 hours of community service
_ a light sentence, but his career suffered from the public
perception that he was a sex maniac.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the actor has continued to work steadily, albeit in
less high-profile roles. He's also settled down considerably after
marrying makeup artist Sheryl Berkoff in 1991. Today they have two
sons, 7-year-old Matthew and 5-year-old John Owen.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Lowe has been seen mostly in comedies, including
``Wayne's World'' (1992), ``Tommy Boy'' (1995) and ``Austin Powers
2: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' (1999), generally cast as a klutzy bad
guy.
</P>
<P>
   That's another reason the 36-year-old actor signed on for ``The
West Wing'': He relished the chance to play a more mature
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``This show definitely skews a lot older than the people who've
been watching me in, say, `Austin Powers,''' he says. ``Sam is a
very interesting guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that, Sorkin gradually has been delving deeper into
Lowe's character over the past few months. Viewers have learned,
for example, that Sam had an affair with a pricey call girl _
although he didn't know she was a hooker.
</P>
<P>
   We've also learned that Sam is fiercely protective, which he
demonstrated when he attended a subpoena hearing to defend his
co-worker and friend, Deputy Chief of Staff Josh Lyman (Bradley
Whitford).
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam is a back-room brawler,'' Lowe says gleefully. ``You can
see that in the scene where I took the guy and put him against the
wall and said, `I'll break you like a pinata.' There's shades in
him of what people used to say about Bobby Kennedy _ that he was
this nice guy, then the doors would close and he would just frost
you. That's a fun flavor to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, what Lowe enjoys most these days is the chance to get in
there and mix it up on a daily basis. He insists that making ``The
West Wing'' is a lot more satisfying than sitting in his trailer on
a film set, waiting for his call.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a major film actor,'' he says, ``you might get to
really act _ I mean, really get down to the words and emotions _
maybe 15 days out of the year, if you're lucky. On this show, you
act every single day, five days a week, 22 weeks a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, there are no freebies here,'' Lowe says cheerfully.
``This isn't an action movie. And my acting muscles, not
surprisingly, are stronger now than they've ever been _ because I'm
in that gym every day.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor at TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ont.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The West Wing,'' consult the
NBC Website at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
