<HEADER>
A6234 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-THE-STORY-OF-LITTLE-R     02-14 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-STORY-OF-LITTLE-RICHARD-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG STORY OF LITTLE RICHARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Leon as Little Richard in a scene from
``Little Richard.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Little Richard is rocking, rolling and practically screaming
into the telephone.
 &HT;    ``I am the architect of rock 'n' roll!'' he says. ``When I came
on the scene there wasn't no rock 'n' roll _ it was swing and sway
with Sammy Kaye! There were `Pennies from Heaven,' but they weren't
falling in my neighborhood!
 &HT;    ``So I a-wop-bop-a-loo-bop, a-wop-bam-boomed with `Tutti
Frutti.'''
 &HT;    Richard laughs.
 &HT;    ``See, there really is no such thing as rock 'n' roll,'' he
says. ``Rhythm and blues had a baby, and somebody named it rock 'n'
roll. I came out with all this wailing and hollering and banging on
the piano. There wasn't nobody else doing it _ there's wasn't no
Bill Haley, there wasn't no Jerry Lee Lewis, there wasn't no Elvis.
There was nobody when I started.
 &HT;    ``I am the originator,'' he exults. ``I am the emancipator! I am
the architect, the true architect of rock 'n' roll! Without any
doubt!''
 &HT;    At 67, Richard still has the outsized personality that made him
a music legend, a member of the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and,
now, the subject of a television biopic, ``Little Richard,'' set to
air Feb. 20 on NBC.
 &HT;    Speaking by telephone from somewhere on the road, the Artist
Formerly Known as Richard Wayne Penniman says that the movie comes
at a good time.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to see it while I was still here,'' he says,
laughing. ``You know, they had started to do the movie without me.
They were doing an unauthorized version, then I came in on it.''
 &HT;    Leon, star of the miniseries ``The Temptations'' and the films
``Cool Runnings'' (1993) and ``Bats'' (1999), not to mention
Madonna's controversial music video ``Like a Prayer,'' plays the
title role in ``Little Richard.'' The original admits that he had
another candidate in mind.
 &HT;    ``Prince said he wanted to do it,'' Richard says. ``He came to
me two weeks after the deal came together with NBC, but it was too
late.
 &HT;    ``I think Leon did a good job of (playing) me in that period,''
the singer concedes. ``He's a very good actor. I wasn't on the set
a lot because I was on tour, but it was hard to watch someone play
me.''
 &HT;    Directed by Robert Townsend, the film covers Richard's
childhood, his tortured relationship with his father (Carl Lumbly),
the emergence of the brash, daring, gender-bending Little Richard
look, his early successes and, ultimately, his 1962 decision to
retire and devote his life to God.
 &HT;    On one set visit, the singer found himself watching a
re-creation of his father's funeral.
 &HT;    ``That was really touching,'' he says. ``It was strange to go
back to that time, but I would like for the audience to see the
struggle I went through.
 &HT;    ``In fact,'' he adds, ``Robert could have made the struggle a
little more prominent. My daddy used to whup me and draw blood out
of me when I was a child. He used to beat me so bad _ he couldn't
stand me.''
 &HT;    Richard stops for a moment, his customary bravado fading almost
to a whisper.
 &HT;    ``Through all of the odds I still came through,'' he says. ``It
was very hard for me, but I still came out OK.''
 &HT;    For his own part, Leon says he nearly turned down the role.
 &HT;    ``At first I wasn't at all interested,'' he says, speaking by
telephone from a friend's New York apartment. ``I thought, `Why
would I want to play Little Richard? He's still around. He's so
flamboyant, and everybody thinks they know him already. Why would I
put myself up against that scrutiny?'
 &HT;    ``But once I realized the story ends 38 years ago, once I
realized that the young guy I play became Little Richard, it became
quite interesting to me,'' he says. ``Also, I got to sing, dance,
cry, wear a bra, have a pompadour and be totally outrageous. I
could put all of my talents on display in one movie, which is very
rare.''
 &HT;    The actor didn't spend much time with Little Richard, he says,
to avoid feeling too pressured to imitate him. Instead he plastered
vintage photos in his trailer, listened to the old records and went
with the flow.
 &HT;    ``I think Richard's most important accomplishment is the music
he gave the world, and more important was the time at which he gave
it,'' Leon says. ``His music brought people, black and white,
together, and it opened the doors for so many other people.
 &HT;    ``What intrigued me most about the film, though, was that it's a
family story,'' the actor adds. ``It's about someone who cared
deeply about his family and religion, and gave up everything at the
height of his career for religion.
 &HT;    ``That's a bit of a unique story, especially among rock 'n' roll
legends,'' Leon says. ``Usually they fall prey to drugs or hook up
with the wrong women, rather than give it up over a deep feeling
for God.''
 &HT;    After quitting the business, Little Richard preached at the
church of his youth in Macon, Ga. A few years later, however, he
was tricked into appearing at a rock concert. The old fever struck,
and ever since he has sought to strike a balance between music and
religion.
 &HT;    ``God is still as important to me today,'' the singer says. ``He
still works through me. It was very troubling at first, though _ it
took a while for me to learn the difference between my work and my
religion, to learn that there's a price for everything.''
 &HT;    As for the possibility of a sequel to ``Little Richard,'' the
title character is all for it.
 &HT;    ``Without any doubt!'' he shouts. ``The story in the second half
would pick up where this one leaves off. The first half doesn't go
far enough because they couldn't go far enough _ they were so
limited with time.
 &HT;    ``The hardships came again in my life,'' he says. ``Things were
hard. Then `Down and Out in Beverly Hills' brought me back from
that.''
 &HT;    Paul Mazursky's 1986 comedy thrust Little Richard into the
spotlight again. Not only did he act in the film, but he hit the
pop charts for the first time in nearly two decades with a
soundtrack song, ``Great Gosh A-Mighty.''
 &HT;    ``Paul got all these people with hardships like myself, Bette
Midler, Nick Nolte and Richard Dreyfuss,'' he says. ``We were all
down and out until that film came out.''
 &HT;    Since then Richard has been on the road almost constantly,
pausing only to make an occasional television guest appearance or
to film a commercial. He doesn't record, however, and doubts that
he will again any time soon. The record market, he says, has turned
to younger artists.
 &HT;    ``I am still the architect,'' he says. ``There's just a lot of
new people out here now. This is a new day and a new way _ what can
I say?''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, all he needs to do to regain his self-confidence is
to step onto the concert stage.
 &HT;    ``Everywhere we go the crowds are still there,'' he says.
``People still like the old music. I think they like it better than
the new stuff. If you notice, even the rappers use old music _
there's nowhere else to go.''
 &HT;    And, in case anyone was wondering, he insists that he's still
the prettiest man in rock 'n' roll.
 &HT;    ``Without any doubt!'' he says, turning it on one more time.
``Without any doubt, I sing and shout!''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Little Richard,'' consult the
NBC Website at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
