<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     02-14 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPRAH WINFREY WINS, BUT FOOD LIBEL LAWS STILL A THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas cattlemen's lawsuit against Oprah Winfrey is over. The
cattlemen lost the legal battle _ as they should have. But their
lawsuit sent a warning to the news media and members of the public:
Don't criticize agricultural products or you may find yourself in
an expensive legal wrangle that can continue for years.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1996, the ``Oprah Winfrey Show'' aired a program
focusing on the hidden dangers in food. The discussion with the
television show's guests turned to Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease, a
fatal brain disease diagnosed in England, and attributed to beef
infected with Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE), or Mad Cow
Disease. Scientists in England determined that BSE is caused by
feeding cattle parts of dead cattle and sheep.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the ``Oprah Winfrey Show'' aired on local TV
stations, cattle prices temporarily plunged. It didn't take long
for a group of Texas cattlemen to sue Oprah Winfrey and the show's
producer, Harpo Productions Inc., under the Texas food
disparagement act. The cattlemen claimed they had lost millions of
dollars because of statements made on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Although in March 1996, the U.S. Department of Agriculture had
put a voluntary ban on the practice in our country, some cattle
operations continued to feed cows to cows. Many months after the
``Oprah Winfrey Show'' aired, the USDA and the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration finally ordered a total halt to feeding cattle the
bone and ground-up scraps of sheep and cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Lyman, a former rancher, was a guest on the ``Oprah
Winfrey Show.'' At the time, he was working for the Humane Society
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions from Winfrey, Lyman talked about the
potential for Americans being struck with the brain disease from
infected U.S. cattle. He was also named in the cattlemen's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 26, 1998, after a six-week trial, the U.S. District
Court for the Northern District of Texas ruled against the
cattlemen. An Amarillo jury, steeped in a cattle and ranching
culture, found that Winfrey, Lyman and the show's producer did not
libel cattle. Under the Texas food disparagement act, a person
bringing the libel lawsuit must prove that the defendant knowingly
disseminated false information about a food product. The cattlemen
could not prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there was no way for them to prove it. The statements
critical of cattle feeding practices in the United States made on
the ``Oprah Winfrey Show'' were based upon factual information.
</P>
<P>
   The cattlemen appealed to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
Fifth Circuit. They lost again. On Feb. 9, the appellate court
affirmed the lower court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, neither court's decision reached the
constitutional free speech question involved because the case was
decided on statutory law.
</P>
<P>
   However, both federal courts indicated that the First Amendment
would have protected Winfrey and her guests even if they had
violated the Texas disparagement law.
</P>
<P>
   The cattlemen could petition the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals
for a rehearing before all the Fifth Circuit judges. Petitions for
en banc hearings are rarely granted.
</P>
<P>
   The cattlemen could appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court. However,
less than one-half of 1 percent of requested appeals are granted by
the high court each year. It is safe to say that the lawsuit has
come to the end of its long and expensive road.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the Texas Legislature, the president of
Harpo Productions said the lawsuit had already cost his company
over $1 million. In an interview on Feb. 11, Lyman said that one
would ``need to have close to a million dollars in pocket'' to
fight such a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In our interview, Lyman said, ``This was not about food
disparagement. This was about the Golden Rule. This was about
people with a lot of gold who thought they could go and make the
rules. All I can say is, thank God that Oprah Winfrey didn't just
turn around and write them a check and had the nerve and the guts
to stand up for all the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyman, who was a rancher in Montana for 45 years, said of the
trial, ``I've been in some stressful situations in my life, but
nothing reaches this plateau. When you end up with a thousand head
of cows that are calving and you're in the middle of a blizzard and
then the sun starts shining and you end up with sunburned bags and
the cows start kicking the calves off, that's stress. But it
doesn't reach the level of being in that courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Babcock, the attorney for Winfrey in this lawsuit, said in
an interview, ``I can't imagine that anybody is going to try to go
through what these cattlemen went through to rely upon this (food
disparagement) statute. It's a very hard thing to prove, as they
found out. I just doubt there's going to be much appetite for using
this statute in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Babcock said the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals reaffirmed a
long-standing legal principle: ``People in this country, including
Oprah Winfrey, have the right to express their opinions about
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   One might add, if they have the money to back them up.
</P>
<P>
   By any reckoning, the cattlemen must have spent nearly $2
million in the lawsuit in order to attempt to recoup the $4 million
they claimed to have lost when cattle prices fell. Bad strategy _
if that were the real intent.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Collins, head of the FoodSpeak Project of the Center for
Science in Public Interest in Washington, D.C., makes sense of the
cattlemen's expensive strategy. He sees the result of the lawsuit
differently than Babcock.
</P>
<P>
   Collins claims the cattlemen sent a message to the American
public: ``If anyone wants to say anything critical about our
product in the future, they better be prepared to litigate for 45
months, better be prepared to spend untold amounts of money in
attorney fees, better be prepared for a lot of courtroom
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins added that even if one wins, ``It's the kind of winning
that would bankrupt most people.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen states have passed food disparagement laws since 1991.
However, agricultural interests have not won a single case in the
courts under these statutes. Obviously, the laws do not help
farmers or ranchers recoup losses from statements damaging to their
products.
</P>
<P>
   These food libel laws were created for one purpose: to
intimidate critics, to shut them up. And the Oprah Winfrey lawsuit
only accentuates that point. This nation's cherished tradition of
free speech isn't only for those wealthy enough to defend their use
of that right. It's for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Food disparagement laws are undemocratic and clash with the
bedrock concept this nation's founders gave us concerning the
people's right to govern themselves. We, the people, must be able
to debate any public issue without fear of legal repercussions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
