<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STORMS-GEORGIA14-COX-     02-14 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORMS-GEORGIA14-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'A roar, woo-woo-woo,' then disaster in Southwest Georgia
 &HT;    (Eds: Fixes and updates throughout. This stands for
STORMS-GEORGIA and STORMS-GEORGIA-SIDE. For Monday PMs.)
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis and Mike Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Terrified residents described deafening thunder,
continuous lightning that lit the sky and roaring winds as
tornadoes swept through Southwest Georgia shortly after midnight,
killing at least 11 people.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest hit area was in Mitchell County, south of Albany,
where a twister cut a five-mile path through a residential area of
mostly mobile homes about 12:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Six people were killed in Mitchell County, said Buzz Weiss of
the Georgia Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Another four were killed in Grady County, and one died in
Colquitt County, Weiss said. He said there were unconfirmed reports
of another person dead in Grady County. The Associated Press
reported 13 dead in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In Grady County, the four died in three different homes, said
Toby Roland, the county's emergency management director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tornado hit in the northeast corner of the county, in an
area that's mostly farmland,'' he said. ``Our preliminary count
indicates at least 15 homes were damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said at least 100 people were injured by the storms. Gov.
Roy Barnes and Gary McConnell, GEMA director, flew down this
morning to assess the damage and the governor was expected to ask
for a federal disaster declaration for the four counties _ Grady,
Mitchell, Colquitt and Tift _ where the worst damage occurred,
according to Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross opened shelters in Moultrie and Camilla, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 120 people were treated during the early morning hours
at the 33-bed Mitchell County Hospital, which sent dozens of
seriously injured patients to other area hospitals in Albany,
Thomasville, Moultrie and Tallahassee, Fla., said administrator Ron
Gilliard. Many of the injured had head injuries, broken limbs and
severe lacerations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very scary,'' said Gilliard, whose home was damaged
shortly after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliard, his parents, his brother and a cousin live in an area
south of Camilla devastated by the tornados. ``My wife and I ran to
the bathroom, held each other and prayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilliard said his first cousin suffered lacerations when his
mobile home was destroyed. ``It was in a pecan grove, where every
tree was uprooted,'' he said. ``He was bleeding profusely. I put
him in my car and drove him to the hospital. It took us 45 minutes
to go the three miles because of downed trees and power lines.''
</P>
<P>
   The small, 33-bed hospital quickly became ``a war zone,'' he
said, as more than 120 injured people poured in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hallway was lined with patients; we took mattresses off
older beds and put them on the floor; we had patients in chairs, on
cots.''
</P>
<P>
   Trees were blown down, a brick house was lifted off its
foundation and witnesses said a tractor-trailer was flipped on its
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you heard was a roar, woo-woo-woo,'' said Johnny Jones,
whose mobile home about two miles south of Camilla was lifted by
winds and landed on its side.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he was able to free his 14-year-old son, who was
pinned under a washing machine, and they crawled out a window.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could see was that everything was demolished. People
were hollering and crying `Where's my child?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The storms were spawned by a strong weather system that
developed ahead of a cold front sweeping eastward from the
Mississippi Valley region, the Weather Service said.
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching Georgia, the storms caused scattered damage in
much of Alabama, downing trees and leaving thousands of Alabamians
without power.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado apparently touched down in south Montgomery County,
downing power lines, overturning mobile homes and destroying a
business, a Sheriff's Department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   An officer who lives in the area reported seeing the twister
Sunday afternoon and said it ``was a quarter-mile wide,'' said
Melvin Turner, assistant chief deputy.
</P>
<P>
   He said no injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Marshall County, a church was blown into the middle of the
road near Boaz, according to local EMA officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Cullman, several houses and businesses were damaged and power
lines were downed, a police spokesman said. He said the damage was
``pretty widespread'' throughout the town but no injuries had been
reported. The Cullman Electric Cooperative estimated that 15,000 of
its 36,000 customers were without power.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
