<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6249 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CALDWELL-part3-NYTSF &LR;      02-14 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALDWELL-part3-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CALDWELL JOURNALS: MALCOLM X 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: For Black History month, which begins on
Monday, Feb. 1, The New York times Syndicate is offering a
five-part feature, ``The Caldwell Journals,'' an account of major
moments in the civil-rights movement of the 1960s by Earl Caldwell,
the nationally acclaimed black journalist whose early career was
shaped by that dynamic era. Caldwell, a former New York Times
reporter, was witness to some of the most important events of the
last 40 years. He covered the riots that swept many American cities
during the summer of 1967. In 1995, the National Association of
Black Journalists presented Caldwell with its President's Award,
saying his record of professional achievement made him ``one of the
most important journalists in the last 50 years.'' Caldwell is
currently a writer-in-residence at the Robert C. Maynard Institute
for Journalism Education in Oakland, Calif.s writing ``The
Caldwell Journals'' for the institute's Web site. For purchase
information _ on an individual part or the entire package _ contact
New York Times Syndicate Sales Representative DEBRA WEYDERT by
phone, 732-390-4480, or fax, 732-390-4697.)
</P>
<P>
   (PLEASE NOTE: All five parts have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle and ``a'' general news category codes.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EARL CALDWELL &QL; 
 &UR; (Worldwide rights) &QL; 
 &UR; c.2000 the Robert C. Maynard Institute for Journalism Education &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   PRELUDE TO PART THREE: Hours after the Harlem riot, thousands of
blacks streamed into the streets of Rochester, N.Y., in frenzied
mobs. They were followed by a horde of reporters. Still in his
hotel room in Harlem, Earl Caldwell received a frantic phone call
from Dick Dougherty, the city editor at the Democrat and Chronicle,
who ordered him to return to Rochester to cover the breaking
events. Here, Caldwell describes the social unrest that gripped
Rochester after the street rioting ended, his chance to meet and
talk with Malcolm X, and one of the most important lessons he
learned about being a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   A lot happened in Rochester before I was to say my last
good-bye. The riots had shifted the dynamic there. Blacks savored a
newfound power to force the white leadership to address
longstanding grievances. Whites were scared. Would future rioting
be confined to the ghetto, or would it spread downtown to white
areas of the city?
</P>
<P>
   Anxieties mounted when a coalition of religious groups brought
in Saul Alinsky, already a legend as a white organizer who taught
confrontational politics to ghetto activists. From this emerged
FIGHT, a militant direct-action group whose members were soon
marching into executive boardrooms demanding jobs and investments
in the black neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Rochester was getting a reputation. The ultimate confirmation of
that came when Malcolm X accepted an invitation to address a black
church there in February 1965.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Malcolm was involved in a dispute with Elijah
Muhammad's black Muslim organization. Four days before his
scheduled appearance in Rochester, his home in Queens, N.Y., was
firebombed.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Autobiography of Malcolm X,'' Alex Haley told of how
Malcolm, ``barking commands and snatching up screaming frightened
children, got the family safely out of the back door into the
yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm was sure that his enemies in Elijah Muhammad's group
were responsible for the attack. That feud seemed to be turning
lethal.
</P>
<P>
   In Rochester, there was speculation that the speech would be
canceled. But Malcolm arrived at Corn Hill Methodist Church on Feb.
16 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   I was stunned when my editors assigned another reporter to cover
Malcolm's speech. They pulled me aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be trouble,'' I was told. ``We need you to handle
the street action.'' Although devastated, I accepted the
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the speech, a huge crowd was at the church. A
source whispered to me that Malcolm X wanted to meet later with
some local people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like you to be there,'' I was told.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm delivered a powerful speech, which I watched from the
back of the church.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he stood up, he was saying, ``My reason for being
here is to discuss the black revolution that is going on, that's
taking place on this earth. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone jammed into the church hung on his every word.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the problems of the black man here in this country today
have ceased to be a problem of just the American Negro or an
American problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a professor, he delivered his analysis in lecture style.
Then, about halfway through, he zeroed in on his target of the
night: the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're not against people because they're white. But we're
against those who practice racism. ... And because we're against
it, the press says we're violent. We're not for violence. We're for
peace. But the people that we're up against are for violence.''
</P>
<P>
   His voice, at first professorial, began to rise. ``This is what
the racists have always done ... And then they use the press to
make (it) look like the victim is the criminal, and the criminal is
the victim. ... They take the press, and through the press they
beat the system ... They use the press to get public opinion on
their side. ... They take statistics, and through the press they
feed them to the public. They make it appear that the role of crime
in the black community is higher than it is anywhere else. ... And
the whites go along with it. Because they think that everybody over
there's a criminal anyway. This is what the press does.''
</P>
<P>
   Through most of an hour, Malcolm X cited example after example
of how the press was used against black people. As he made his
case, many in the crowd stood and shouted their approval.
</P>
<P>
   I began to feel relieved that I was not covering his speech. I
also realized that I could not go to his hotel later with the
others. He was so damning in his indictment that I was convinced
that the meeting would be a ``get the press'' session. As a
representative of the local paper, I did not feel that I should be
there.
</P>
<P>
   As much as I wanted to meet Malcolm, I did not go.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, on Feb. 21, a cold and snowy Sunday, I was at
work at the Democrat and Chronicle. Sundays were always slow and I
was standing in the wire room, watching the various stories come in
over the teletype machines.
</P>
<P>
   I was there when the teletype bell began to ring, alerting
editors that a very important story was about to move. And that
day, when the bell began to ring, I hovered over the machine and
watched in horror as the bulletin came in that Malcolm X had been
shot and killed just as he was starting to deliver a speech at the
Audubon Ballroom in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the lesson driven home was that a reporter's job
required toughness and that journalism was not the place for one
easily embarrassed or intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   I had missed my chance to meet and talk with Malcolm X. I vowed
never to make a similar mistake.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: WHITE REPORTERS OUT
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Earl Caldwell is a writer-in-residence at the Robert C.
Maynard Institute for Journalism Education in Oakland, Calif.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6250 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CALDWELL-part4-NYTSF &LR;      02-14 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALDWELL-part4-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CALDWELL JOURNALS: WHITE REPORTERS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: For Black History month, which begins on
Monday, Feb. 1, The New York times Syndicate is offering a
five-part feature, ``The Caldwell Journals,'' an account of major
moments in the civil-rights movement of the 1960s by Earl Caldwell,
the nationally acclaimed black journalist whose early career was
shaped by that dynamic era. Caldwell, a former New York Times
reporter, was witness to some of the most important events of the
last 40 years. He covered the riots that swept many American cities
during the summer of 1967. In 1995, the National Association of
Black Journalists presented Caldwell with its President's Award,
saying his record of professional achievement made him ``one of the
most important journalists in the last 50 years.'' Caldwell is
currently a writer-in-residence at the Robert C. Maynard Institute
for Journalism Education in Oakland, Calif., and is writing ``The
Caldwell Journals'' for the institute's Web site. For purchase
information _ on an individual part or the entire package _ contact
New York Times Syndicate Sales Representative DEBRA WEYDERT by
phone, 732-390-4480, or fax, 732-390-4697.)
</P>
<P>
   (PLEASE NOTE: All five parts have been sent to the ``l''
lifestyle and ``a'' general news category codes.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EARL CALDWELL &QL; 
 &UR; (Worldwide rights) &QL; 
 &UR; c.2000 the Robert C. Maynard Institute for Journalism Education &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In Harlem on the Sunday that Malcolm X was killed, two
reporters, Stan Scott and Gene Simpson, were right up front in the
Audubon Ballroom, so close to the podium that when the shooting
started, they had to dive to the floor for cover.
</P>
<P>
   Being there changed a lot for Scott and Simpson. But how they
came to be in the ballroom that afternoon played a large part in
ushering in a whole new era for black reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In the epilogue to ``The Autobiography of Malcolm X,'' the
writer Alex Haley explained that on the day he was killed, Malcolm
X had specifically ordered that no press be allowed inside the
Audubon Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   When Scott and Simpson arrived for Malcolm's meeting, their
press credentials were in clear view. At the door, the men were
greeted by one of Malcolm's lieutenants. ``No press allowed,'' he
told them.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned, the two stood pondering the ``no press'' edict.
Malcolm's aide pointed to their credentials and offered a
suggestion. ``Put 'em in your pocket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They complied. ``As black citizens, you can go on in,'' the aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   And that afternoon Stan Scott and Gene Simpson got what
reporters dream of _ the experience of being there, of being
wherever it is at the precise moment that something truly important
happens.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence in the Audobon Ballroom that day changed the two
reporters' professional lives, for the better. Scott, who was
working for United Press International, was lured away to join
WINS, New York City's leading all-news radio station. Simpson, a
reporter for WMCA radio, left to join CBS radio's all-news
operation.
</P>
<P>
   But more significant than what happened to those news reporters
was the action taken by Malcolm X's supporters in the wake of his
murder. What the supporters did brought a swift, definable change
to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm's aides had concluded that their leader's ``no press''
order was proof that the time had come in which the black community
and black meetings should be off limits to white reporters. And
they also believed that if Malcolm had made an exception for black
reporters, so should they.
</P>
<P>
   So, grieving and wanting to honor their slain leader, they made
it their cause to keep white reporters out of meetings among
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long after, as a reporter for the Herald Tribune, I
witnessed nothing more shocking than the tense confrontations that
ensued when white reporters showed up in Harlem and other black
communities to cover meetings and rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom did anybody ever bar them at the door. The reporters
would be allowed inside and even get seated. It was like baiting a
trap.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the meeting was about to begin, someone would shout,
``Wait, wait, wait,'' and, pointing toward the reporters who were
white, would ask: ``What are they doing in here?''
</P>
<P>
   And then the show was on. Voices got louder, people jumped to
their feet, and immediately they began shouting the demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``White reporters out! White reporters out!''
</P>
<P>
   When the white reporters did not leave fast enough or dared to
argue a right to stay, they would be grabbed and roughly ushered
out the door. Those of us who were reporters and black discreetly
put our notebooks and pencils away, but we did not budge from our
seats and nobody ever tried to force us out.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, already embarrassed at being scooped by
UPI on the assassination of Malcolm X, responded by opening a news
bureau in the heart of Harlem. Gil Scott and Hollie West, both
blacks, were the two reporters assigned to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Scott, born and raised in Brooklyn, N.Y., began his career
in journalism in 1957 as a desk assistant at CBS. In 1959, he moved
to the Reporter-Dispatch in White Plains, N.Y., where he worked as
a sportswriter. His career was interrupted briefly when he was
recalled to active duty in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he joined the Newark News, where he and John Dotson
were the only black reporters on staff. Gil Scott stayed there
until he was hired by the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma native, Hollie West, in 1963, became the first black
reporter on a daily newspaper in the San Francisco Bay area. That
paper was the Oakland Tribune. From Oakland, West went to New York
to work at the AP not long after Malcolm X was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the AP's Harlem bureau was up and running, the
summer of 1965 was fast approaching. Many news organizations
pondered the same question: ``What are blacks going to do?'' Little
did they know that black culture was about to take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   NEXT INSTALLMENT: BLACK IS BEAUTIFUL
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Earl Caldwell is a writer-in-residence at the Robert C.
Maynard Institute for Journalism Education in Oakland, Calif.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
