<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6257 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     02-14 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Monday, Feb. 14, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DIALLO-MOTHER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Kadiatou Diallo sits in a hotel
room at the Crowne Plaza wearing a violet-colored gown with ivory
trim at the neck and embroidery at the cuffs, a black turtleneck, a
head wrap and slippers on her feet. Inside the lamp-lit suite, she
talks about her first child. Did she find it difficult to take care
of her infant son when she was only 16 years old? ``It was like we
grew up together,'' she says. ``That's why I say it's very
painful.'' By THEOLA S. LABBE.
</P>
<P>
   INDENTURED-SERVANTS (San Francisco) _ Nobee Saeieo thought she
was coming from Thailand to the United States as a $240-a-month
cook, but she got much less than she bargained for. She was forced
to fix meals, give manicures and serve guests on her knees, 18
hours a day, seven days a week. Dung, a 13-year-old from Vietnam,
was sold to a Silicon Valley executive, who planned to bring her
here to satisfy his sexual demands, federal prosecutors say. These
are just two of the 150 people who federal prosecutors say have
been victims of slavery or indentured servitude in the past five
years. By ERIC McCORMICK and JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DEMS (San Jose, Calif.) _ California Democrats haven't
decided whether to nominate Vice President Al Gore or former Sen.
Bill Bradley for president, but they do agree on whom they want the
GOP to nominate: Texas Gov. George W. Bush. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOIS-CONVENTION (San Antonio) _ The last time the name Lois made
it onto any sort of popular baby names list was back in the 1930s,
when it ranked an admirable 18th. Ethel, Margaret and Harold were
on that list also. Yet this week, San Antonio will have the largest
concentration of women named Lois in the world. Maybe even a couple
of guys. It's the annual convention of the National Lois Club. By
IHOSVANI RODRIGUEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SF-DEVELOPMENT (San Francisco) _ As Internet millionaires and
their lucrative dot-coms redefine the Bay Area, residents are
sharing in the boom times but also finding themselves victims of
their own success. Urban sprawl and traffic congestion, poverty and
homelessness, the quality of public schools and a host of other
issues worried many of the 500 Bay Area residents recently polled
by the Pew Center for Civic Journalism in Washington, D.C. By ANNIE
NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   TARZAN-MINISTER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Fans of Tarzan creator Edgar
Rice Burroughs can thank Henry Heins, a retired Lutheran minister,
for some new reading material. It was Heins who helped bring into
print recently two unpublished Burroughs works, a 1924 novel,
``Marcia of the Doorstep,'' and a 1927 play, ``You Lucky Girl!'' By
PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   CINNABAR-LACQUER (Undated) _ To restore cinnabar carvings in the
original technique can be costly, requiring up to 100 thin coats of
lacquer. A less expensive repair would be to fill in with a
composition material in the approximate coloring before recarving
the design. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ Just because Steve Young and
Jerry Rice are among 40 players the 49ers have under contract after
the great Salary Cap Purge of 2000 does not necessarily mean they
will be with the team next season. That's because the club is not
through tweaking its roster in the wake of its worst season in 20
years. Between now and the draft in April the 49ers will attempt to
sign their own free agents and, cap room permitting, pursue players
on the free agent market. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-GIANTS (San Francisco) _ A new era of Giants baseball is
here, an era in which the Giants aren't even the top draw in their
own ballpark. The park itself is the real draw, judging by the
phenomenon that the
</P>
<P>
   entire 2000 season will probably sell out by Opening Day. By
JOHN SHEA.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ How can the outdoor experience
be improved in the San Francisco Bay Area? At the Sportsmen's Expo
last weekend, hundreds of people provided suggestions for bettering
hiking, fishing, boating, biking and conservation. By TOM
STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-WALKERS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Go ahead and laugh at the
funny racewalkers. Everyone else does. But with resting heart rates
of around 40, they will be swiveling their hips and striding across
the graves of those who mocked them. That's a lot of ground to
cover. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The corner of Polk and Ellis in
San Francisco, a block from the X-rated O'Farrell Theater, is an
unlikely place to hear this sentence, but this is what Tom Nolan
said: ``What we're about is re-creating small-town America in a big
city.`` By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Democratic Party organization
in Albany County is one of the best political operations in the
country. If Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign staff had let the
local party people run one of the Senate candidate's recent
fund-raising affairs, they would have left with the same money, at
least. And they might have left with a few friends. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   PORT-CHICAGO (San Antonio) _ Two years ago, President Clinton
called for a dialogue on race. How about a congressional debate on
the World War II explosion at Port Chicago in California, the
catalyst for the Navy to become the first service branch to
desegregate and a racial issue that remains unresolved to this day.
By BOB RICHTER.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-WARS (Mill Valley, Calif.) _ While in Washington,D.C.,
recently, I visited the National Endowment for the Arts. A
Traveling Jewish Theatre _ the non-profit theater I helped found
and still co-direct _ would probably not have survived for over two
decades had it not been funded in its formative years by the NEA.
During my visit, I was confronted with tangible evidence of what it
means to be on the front lines of the so-called culture wars. By
COREY FISCHER.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
