<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Violence increasing off the field in NFL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Violent acts by NFL players this season created so much
controversy that critics are calling it the National Felony League.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every day it seems as if another player is being charged
with a crime, making the league a convenient target for criticism
from those who believe the owners are more concerned with making
money than cleansing the NFL of the criminal element that provides
a bad role model for the youth of America.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's public relations machine counters with statistics that
show the percentage of crimes committed by players is less than
society in general. The league contends that because the NFL is so
popular, it is going to be under the microscope more than other
industries and that everything is going to be magnified.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've definitely got to be careful in this league,''
Jacksonville offensive tackle Leon Searcy said. ``Any time we do
something, it's public. Association brings on assimilation. The
people you associate with can put a damper on your reputation.
We've got to be careful about who we hang out with. We've got to
let them know, `When you do something, it reflects on me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Players have to avoid those situations and learn not to get
involved in circumstances that lead to consequences. Everything you
do is going to be magnified by 100, whether you're innocent or
guilty. And you're going to be perceived as guilty until proven
innocent because of your stature. It's unfortunate, (but) we know
coming into the NFL that we have to use better judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of NFL players are being branded by the actions of
a few, which doesn't sit well with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of players who aren't involved in anything
illegal or violent,'' Buffalo guard Ruben Brown said. ``That should
let you know there isn't some trait in a football player to be that
type of violent person society knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who don't play football commit those crimes.
To think we're exempt is ridiculous. We're no different from the
rest of society in that some of us are good and some of us are bad.
Just because we play football doesn't mean we're going to run
around killing people or doing things of that nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Violent crime is not new in the NFL. Former Carolina receiver
Rae Carruth wasn't the first player to be charged with committing a
murder during the season. In 1951, Pittsburgh Steelers receiver
Jerry Nuzum was arrested for allegedly murdering a waitress in New
Mexico. A judge dismissed the case for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Murder accusations get the attention of the news media, not just
the sports media. It also attracts the interest of non-sports fans.
The media fuel interest.
</P>
<P>
   When Carruth was charged with first-degree murder in the
shooting death of his girlfriend, who was pregnant at the time, it
received worldwide publicity. She died, but the baby lived.
</P>
<P>
   When Baltimore middle linebacker Ray Lewis, who had been voted
as a starter in the Pro Bowl, was charged with double murder
resulting from a fight outside an Atlanta nightclub after Super
Bowl XXXIV, interest skyrocketed. And the media feeding frenzy
began.
</P>
<P>
   Like Carruth, Lewis remains in jail. Many have an opinion about
why they are there and what they could have done to avoid their
situations, but Cleveland Browns owner Al Lerner might have put it
best.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about Lewis, Lerner said: ``He was trained to be a great
athlete. He was never trained to be a multimillionaire. He was
never trained to handle that kind of exposure and the things that
got shoved in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times do we remember walking away from an incident
and it was good that we did? These kids may not know enough about
just walking away.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams have programs to educate and help players.
Psychologists and doctors participate in the programs, which cost
each team about $1 million a year to provide.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis plays for the Ravens, who had a seven-part lecture series
during the last offseason on how players should conduct themselves.
Topics covered in the series involved drug counseling,
accountability both personally and professionally, and
relationships with women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't tolerate and we don't condone misconduct,'' NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue said. ``We do strike a balance between
that and giving people a second chance, recognizing that some of
the misconduct by NFL players has occurred before they were NFL
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have in place a very comprehensive, very active set of
programs, and they focus on prevention, and they are all tied
together. We have counseling on a league-wide basis. We have
treatment. We have prevention and we have discipline, and I think
the players respond in a very positive way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we separate ourselves from society? Of course not. Can we
predict when a player such as Rae Carruth is going to have a
problem? Of course not. We can't predict that any more than others
in society can predict that students are going to shoot other
students or that workers are going to shoot other workers in the
workplace. You can't predict when there is going to be aberrant
behavior. Nor can you understand it after it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL players have been involved in many other recent incidents,
but fans have become almost immune to them.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Indianapolis defensive back Steve Muhammad was
charged with battery in the beating of his pregnant wife. He was
cleared in the deaths of his wife and stillborn child that resulted
from a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Miami rookie running back Cecil Collins, who was on probation,
was charged with two counts of burglary of a dwelling. The married
woman whose apartment he entered said Collins had been stalking
her. Collins, who was waived by the Dolphins, remains in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City receiver Tamarick Vanover repeatedly has been
mentioned in a federal investigation involving a huge cocaine and
marijuana ring that has been smuggling drugs into Kansas and
Missouri. Vanover hasn't been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Former Chiefs running back Bam Morris was a passenger in a Ford
Expedition that pulled out of Vanover's driveway and was stopped by
police. The Expedition had been stolen. The driver, Morris' friend
and former college teammate, Dewayne Bryant, was charged with
felony theft.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who was on probation, retired from the Chiefs in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina running back Fred Lane's car was stopped. He was
arrested on drug and weapons charges. New York Jets receiver Wayne
Chrebet and Indianapolis fullback Keith Elias were arrested outside
a New Jersey bar at 4 a.m. last Sunday. They had been involved in a
fight that some witnesses described as a melee. Chrebet was charged
with disorderly conduct. Elias was charged with disorderly conduct
and resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Many players who get into trouble off the field are involved
with friends or acquaintances, not with teammates. Alcohol or drugs
also can play a role. So can where the players hang out, not just
with whom they hang out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friendship goes out the window when the law gets involved,''
said former 49ers/Raiders/Jets defensive back Ronnie Lott, who is a
member of the Pro Football Hall of Fame class of 2000. ``Many of
the problems guys have are because of people they're surrounded by.
Guys have to understand the law doesn't care if you're with your
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys say, `I'm not going to turn my back on my friends.'
That's a tough thing for other people to understand. I'm not saying
don't hang with old friends. But when a moment of truth comes, you
have to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee rookie defensive end Jevon Kearse, who was voted to
the Pro Bowl, grew up in Fort Myers, Fla. His father was murdered
before he was born. One brother was shot to death. Another brother
is in prison. When Kearse goes home, he's careful to avoid people
and situations that could get him in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no proper way to teach people,'' he said. ``Sometimes
it's hard to not associate with the friends you grew up with.
Everybody knows right from wrong, but they don't always do the
right thing. I can be walking down the street with regular Joe
Blows and get into trouble. We have to realize that most people
don't have as much to lose as we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go home, there are some friends I could get in trouble
with if I'm not careful, but I'm careful. I might just drive by
them and say, `What's up?' and keep going. I know that's not a
place for me now, and they pretty much understand it. I've moved on
from that part of my life. If I'm with guys like that and something
goes down, they'll probably just get a slap on the wrist, but it
could ruin my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Some sociologists who study the NFL say violent behavior off the
field is to be expected because the players are coached to play
violently. Players disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough man's game, but you can't take it home with
you,'' said Tampa Bay safety John Lynch, who is one of the league's
hardest hitters. ``You learn how to separate the two as you get
older. The best way to stay out of trouble is to stay away from
places where trouble can find you.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
