</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOUSTON-SAINTLOUIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Saint Louis outshoots Houston 82-70
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ This one wasn't in much doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Cougars allowed too many open 3-pointers to a team
that couldn't miss for much of the game and lost to the Saint Louis
Billikens 82-70 Saturday at Kiel Center.
</P>
<P>
   In winning for the seventh time in its last nine starts, Saint
Louis (14-8, 6-4 Conference USA) connected on a season-high 11
treys after virtually eliminating any chance of a UH comeback with
an early wave of 3-pointers before a crowd of 13,247. The Cougars
(8-15, 2-8) sagged too much in their zone defense and paid dearly
at the outset, then couldn't sustain a second-half rally against
the Billikens' man-to-man pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Robertson (3-of-4), Dave Fergerson (2-of-3), Justin Love
(3-of-7), Maurice Jeffers (1-of-1) and freshman Chris Braun
(2-of-2) tormented Houston from long range. Saint Louis has made 27
3-pointers in its last four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were making their 3s against the zone, but they were also
getting open shots in transition and that's unacceptable,'' UH
guard Gee Gervin said.
</P>
<P>
   Gervin's 3-pointer with 53 seconds remaining kept the Cougars
from going without a trey for the first time in two seasons. Gervin
(23 points on 10-of-18 shooting) and freshman George Williams (20
points on 8-of-11) carried the scoring burden.
</P>
<P>
   Love, a 6-2 senior guard, scored a game-high 25 points for the
Billikens, who received 37 points from their bench, including 10
from Braun and nine from Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played outstanding man defense and took us out of our
offense at times, and we didn't get open 3s most of the day,''
Gervin said. ``They were hitting uncontested shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Gervin and Love entered the game as the league's top two scorers
and ended the day in a virtual tie, with Gervin at 19.3 points a
game and Love at 19.2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played great defense and shot it well. They had
everything going for them,'' UH coach Clyde Drexler said. ``They
had some open shots and knocked them down when we went to our
halfcourt trap. Lorenzo Romar (SLU's first-year coach) is doing a
great job, and they're definitely going to the (NCAA) Tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The Billikens, No. 43 in the latest Ratings Percentage Index,
are tied for second in the C-USA's American Division.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule doesn't get any easier for the Cougars, who have
lost five in a row and 10 of the past 12 games. Next up is a
Thursday night game at Hofheinz Pavilion against No. 1 Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Saint Louis got an early lift by making five of its first seven
3-pointers, which helped expand a 20-16 lead to 32-20 midway
through the first half. The Billikens shot 7-for-10 from long range
and took a 44-32 lead to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Love helped Saint Louis widen the gap when he hit a pair of 3s
and scored nine points in an 11-4 run that gave the Billikens a
55-36 lead only 3:21 into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Saint Louis' margin swelled to 62-41 before UH's trapping
defense helped cut the lead to 64-51. But after Redden scored in
the lane, Love cashed in off a loose ball and Braun connected on
two consecutive baskets, and the Billikens were back on top 72-53
with seven minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't shoot well this season for a long time,'' Romar said
of his team, which was hitting 44.4 percent for the season. ``I
don't like talking about it because who knows what will happen
next?''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
