<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6280 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-LANDRY-HNS &LR;      02-14 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LANDRY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Legendary Dallas Cowboys coach Landry dies
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Tom Landry, who built the Dallas Cowboys into America's Team and
guided them to five Super Bowls during his 29-year coaching career,
died Saturday after a lengthy battle with leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, 75, had been undergoing treatment since May for acute
myelogenous leukemia, a form of cancer that produces abnormal
growth of blood cells. He died at 6 p.m. at Baylor University
Medical Center in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, whose 270 victories are third on the NFL's all-time list
behind Don Shula and George Halas, was surrounded by his family,
including Alicia, his wife of 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shaped my philosophy on everything,'' said Atlanta Falcons
coach Dan Reeves, who played and coached for Landry before
embarking on his first head coaching job at Denver. ``I followed
his philosophy on football and how he handled himself on and off
the field. He was a tremendous influence on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was something unique to the NFL. He was someone who had
tremendous knowledge of the NFL, but he was also a man of such
integrity. He had a strong Christian faith that was unusual at that
time. And he didn't just talk it. He walked it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry, a member of Pro Football Hall of Fame, was the Cowboys'
first coach, hired by owner Clint Murchison in 1960. Landry,
general manager Tex Schramm and personnel director Gil Brandt spent
almost 30 years together helping the Cowboys become the most
popular team in NFL history. During their tenure, the Cowboys won
two Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always the epitome of fairness, honesty, integrity and
all the virtues and values people talk about,'' said Mike Ditka,
who played and coached under Landry before becoming a head coach
with Chicago and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Although Landry's death wasn't a surprise, the Metroplex will be
in mourning over a coach who changed the lives of fans, players,
coaches and the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Landry's familiar presence on the Dallas Cowboys' sideline
for three decades represented the NFL at its best,'' NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue said. ``He will always rank as one of
the all-time great coaches and as an architect of one of the most
successful teams in sports history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be remembered for many special reasons, including his
record as a coach, the innovations he brought to our game, and the
personal integrity he displayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry's teams posted a league-record 20 consecutive winning
seasons and won 13 division titles, but after suffering three
losing seasons in a row, he was fired in 1989 when Jerry Jones
bought the team from Bum Bright. Jimmy Johnson replaced Landry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never be able to measure the complete significance of
coach Landry's contributions to the Dallas Cowboys,'' Jones said.
``Simply stated, he's the single most important figure in the
history of this franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry's unemotional, stone-faced sideline demeanor belied his
uncanny ability to create and innovate, but few coaches in pro
football history contributed more to the way the game is played.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, who grew up in Mission, Texas, and played at the
University of Texas, was an outstanding defensive back for the New
York Giants. He was the Giants' defensive coordinator when
Murchison hired him to coach Dallas' expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   During his career, Landry was credited with developing the 4-3
defense and, in essence, created the middle linebacker position.
Later, he developed the read-and-react flex defense that was the
foundation of the Cowboys' ``Doomsday Defenses'' of the 1970s and
'80s.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Landry used the quarterback shuffle in the 1960s.
He installed the spread formation and was one of the first coaches
to use the shotgun. He loved gimmick plays, too. Two of his
favorites were the halfback option pass and the throwback play in
which the halfback took the handoff and lateraled back to the
quarterback, who threw downfield.
</P>
<P>
   Landry was the first coach to have his offensive linemen raise
up before they were set, a movement that he said caused the
defensive players problems with sight adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole Cowboys image came from him,'' said former
quarterback Roger Staubach. ``I think Tom will always make the
Dallas Cowboys more than a football team.``
</P>
<P>
   When Staubach was inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in
1985, he asked Landry to present him. When Landry was inducted in
1990, he asked Staubach to present him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was somewhat of a shyness about him, but he was always
there when you needed him,'' Staubach said. ``I don't know anyone
who didn't have respect for him as a person. As a human being,
coach Landry is right there among the very best. There was nothing
phony about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry's record with the Cowboys was 270-178-6 (.601 winning
percentage). However, his first team went 0-11-1, and after four
years the Cowboys were 13-38-3. Fans and media members wanted him
fired, but Murchison showed his support by signing Landry to a
10-year contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt found the players, and Landry coached them. Schramm
handled the business and promotional side of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were totally different,'' Schramm said. ``We were never
close socially, but we got along very well because he had his
domain and we each knew where the lines were. I respected him, he
respected me and things worked perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry was a devoted Christian who promoted the Fellowship of
Christian Athletes, among other organizations. After he was fired,
he remained in the background and didn't attend Cowboys games
except when he was inducted into the Ring of Honor at Texas Stadium
in 1993. Rather than a player's jersey number, a small hat is
displayed beside his name and the years he coached (1960-88).
</P>
<P>
   When Dallas had a ``Hats Off to Tom Landry Day,'' that featured
a parade, an estimated crowd of 100,000 showed up to cheer him.
That day, Landry let down his guard and show some rare emotion. He
called it the ``most exciting and meaningful'' day in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you played for him, he was the boss,'' said Ditka, who
played for four years and coached nine years under Landry. ``When I
coached for him he was the boss, too, but when you played for him
there was a fear in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to be more like him, but I'm an emotional
person and I can't be what I'm not. To be that stoic and that under
control and that disciplined is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Landry was criticized by some of his players.
Former receiver Pete Gent wrote North Dallas Forty, which became a
popular film starring Nick Nolte. In the book and film, a character
based on Landry was portrayed as an unfeeling, uncaring coach whose
philosophy was to win at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   Former running back Duane Thomas also took shots at Landry, who
never responded because he remained above it all.
</P>
<P>
   During the early 1980s, Landry eased up and drew positive
attention for television commercials. His most famous was an
American Express ad that poked fun at the Cowboys-Washington
Redskins rivalry, which was the hottest in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys didn't have a winning season until 1966, when they
lost the championship to Green Bay, which continued on to win Super
Bowl I.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, the Cowboys defeated Cleveland for their first
playoff victory, which gained them a revenge game against the
Packers. In one of the most famous games in NFL history, the
Cowboys visited Lambeau Field for what became known as the Ice
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay quarterback Bart Starr scored on a quarterback sneak
for the winning touchdown with 13 seconds left and a 21-17 victory.
The Packers went on to win a second consecutive Super Bowl for
Vince Lombardi, who was an assistant coach with Landry with the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that call, the sneak,'' Landry said at the
time. ``It wasn't a good call. But now, it's a great call.''
</P>
<P>
   The next two seasons the Cowboys were eliminated from the
playoffs by Cleveland. They reached their first Super Bowl but lost
in January 1971 to Baltimore on Jim O'Brien's field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Landry finally won his first Super Bowl the next season when the
Cowboys defeated Miami 24-3. Landry's players carried him off the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still see that image of him being carried off the field,''
Staubach said. ``I think that was a big deal to him, the best in
his life. Seeing that smile on his face showed how happy he was to
finally get over that hump.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
