<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-PORT-CHICAGO-HNS &LR;      02-14 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORT-CHICAGO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIME FOR DEBATE ON PORT CHICAGO `MUTINY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB RICHTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ For nearly 50 years Freddie Meeks suppressed
discussing the most important event in his life. At Christmastime,
President Clinton pardoned him for it.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks, now 80, was one of 50 black sailors court-martialed for
mutiny for refusing to load ammunition at the Port Chicago, Calif.,
naval weapons depot after an explosion there July 17, 1944, that
killed 320 men and wounded 390 others.
</P>
<P>
   Port Chicago has been a barnacle on the Navy's butt for 55
years. Last Father's Day, I wrote about Raye Adkins, whose father
died in the Port Chicago explosion 3 1/2 months before she was
born.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, in 1944, loading ammo was vital to the war effort.
The rub at Port Chicago was that safety was secondary to speed, and
white officers wagered on whose black crew could load the most the
fastest.
</P>
<P>
   After the explosion, the officers got 30-day leaves; the
surviving ammo loaders picked up body parts.
</P>
<P>
   There was no psychological counseling. No time to grieve. The
men were ordered back to loading ammo under the threat of being
shot if they refused. When 50 said no, they were court-martialed
and sentenced to up to 15 years in the brig.
</P>
<P>
   Even the dead were abused. Rep. John Rankin, D-Miss., upon
learning that two-thirds of the victims were black, succeeded in
reducing death benefits for their survivors from a proposed $5,000
to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then Port Chicago went into the dirty laundry hamper of history.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins, the principal at Schulze Elementary School in San
Antonio and a doctoral candidate, says her family elders wouldn't
discuss her dad's death, that she grew up thinking he'd done
something bad. That she ``cried for days'' when, as an adult, she
learned of the injustices at what was clearly a Jim Crow base.
</P>
<P>
   About that time (the early 1990s), the truth about Port Chicago
began to ventilate. Robert L. Allen wrote ``The Port Chicago
Mutiny.'' Studs Terkel interviewed mutineer Joe Small in ``The Good
War.''
</P>
<P>
   There were movies and TV shows and, in 1994, the Navy admitted
the mutineers were victims of racial prejudice but refused to
overturn their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Now only two of them are still alive, Meeks of Los Angeles and
Jack Crittendon of Montgomery, Ala. While Meeks sought the pardon,
and praised Clinton for giving it to him, Crittendon remains
defiant.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the half-century after Port Chicago, Crittendon told
people he had been in the Army, to avoid talking about that part of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meeks isn't thinking about the other sailors or the
congressman who cut the death benefits in half,'' Crittendon said
with conviction. ``Giving me a pardon now is like getting one after
you go to the electric chair. What is the benefit?''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he says, Congress should restore those Rankin-trimmed
death benefits, with interest, to the survivors of the Port Chicago
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins, who would benefit from such a stipend, agrees, but not
for reasons you might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the worth of these men still less because of the color of
their skin? she asks. ``We must remove the barriers of our past and
rectify injustices in ways that underscore the value and dignity of
all people for all times. Each time an injustice is removed, the
gap between racial equality and violent prejudices narrows.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it will be an uphill battle. Rep. George Miller,
D-Calif., a hero in obtaining the Meeks pardon, seems to be spent.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 7 letter to Adkins, he writes: ``For the moment ...
let us note the victory we have achieved. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Some people contend the Port Chicago mutineers deserved to be
punished. If they got what they deserved, then so too should the
families of the patriotic black (and white) men who died on July
17, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the president called for a dialogue on race. How
about a congressional debate on Port Chicago, the catalyst for the
Navy to become the first service branch to desegregate? Reopening
the death benefit debate won't make the wrongs and the hurtfulness
of 55 years of quashed history go away. But it could be a signal
that this great and usually decent nation has a conscience.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Richter is deputy editorial page editor of the San Antonio
Express-News. Call him at 210-250-3477 or e-mail
brichter(at)express-news.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
