<HEADER>
A6310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CINNABAR-LACQUER-HNS &LR;      02-14 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINNABAR-LACQUER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CARING FOR LACQUERED CARVINGS MAY TAKE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lacquer has been produced since prehistoric times in Asia to
protect and decorate furnishings and objects such as boxes, trays
and snuff bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnabar is made from a toxic refined sap, which is highly
irritating or poisonous to humans before it has cured. The color
comes from bright red mercuric sulfide. A single piece can take
years to complete: From 50 to 100 or more layers of lacquer form a
single substructure. The finished pieces feature embedded materials
or deeply carved decorations such as landscapes, animals and
plants.
</P>
<P>
   As the layers of lacquer are applied, they are periodically
punctuated with a layer of black or another color to act as a depth
guide for carvers, according to Lark Mason, senior vice president
of Sotheby's and director of the auction house's on-line services.
</P>
<P>
   Incised and colored lacquer is also the same sort of cinnabar
color, according to Mason. He said other colors may be featured, as
well as gold leaf inlay, which disguises irregular cut edges of the
design.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnabar lacquer is resistant to heat and is a great insulator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinnabar is impervious to most anything,'' Mason said. ``It
won't melt like plastic imitations or keep a fingernail print like
rubber simulations.'' However, damage from cracking or chipping can
expose the core, which is often wood, causing it to expand and
contract and further damage the surface.
</P>
<P>
   To restore cinnabar in the original technique can be costly,
Mason said. Restoration uses the same materials and 100 thin coats
of lacquer built up to the adjoining surface. Each coat of lacquer
takes three days to dry and the missing decoration must be
recarved.
</P>
<P>
   A less expensive repair would be to fill in with a composition
material in the approximate coloring before recarving the design. A
fine antiques house can recommend a person to do the restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnabar lacquer pieces produced in the Yuan and Ming Dynasties
remain rare, highly priced and very collectible, Mason said. Pieces
made in Imperial workshops of the 18th and 19th century may be
found for under $5,000, and pieces not made in the workshops are
valued at between $500 and $3,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
