<P>
   &UR; THE CAST OF CHARACTERS IN IRAN'S FEB. 18 ELECTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear: when people cast their ballots in Iran's
parliamentary election on Feb. 18, most of them will be voting for
change. The point at issue is the pace of change, and the degree to
which the Islamic system should be altered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Feb. 18) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-IRAN-CANDIDATES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IRAQ: GOOD NEWS FOR A FEW, BAD NEWS FOR MANY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any newspapers?'' Iraqi border guards ask
travellers arriving from Jordan. Like most of their countrymen,
they are anxious for any information, especially about Iraq itself,
that is unfiltered by government propagandists. But recently, as
Iraq has faded from the world's headlines, the pickings have been
thin. No news may be good news for Saddam Hussein, but it is a
disaster for the bulk of his citizens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 150 words; total uncut is 1,025) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-BAGHDAD-BOOM-325&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRITAIN &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BAFFLING AFGHAN HIJACKING ENDS IN MYSTERY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the early morning hours of Feb. 10 the hijacking of an
internal flight from Afghanistan was peacefully resolved, thousands
of miles away at Stansted Airport outside London. The end of the
hijacking promised to resolve the mystery of just why the plane was
seized in the first place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-HIJACK-MOTIVE?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 149-YEAR-OLD REUTERS EMBRACES THE 21ST CENTURY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One almost believes the Internet was created for Reuters,''
said Peter Job, the company's chief executive, at a briefing for
analysts on Feb. 8 when he announced the company's new
Internet-centered strategy. Indeed, the Internet and Reuters have
much in common _ in fact, so much so that it is easy to imagine how
the Internet could replace Reuters. And that is the danger Reuters
is now moving very quickly to avoid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 250; total uncut is 1,100 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-REUTERS.COM-275&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAVE FACTORY, WILL TRAVEL: THE NEW `VIRTUAL' FACTORIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the electronics factory near Guadalajara looks
like any other. But look more closely and you might notice
something odd. One of the lines churns out Web TV set-top boxes,
which connect television to the Net, for Philips, a Dutch
consumer-electronics giant. The line next to it makes the same
device for Sony, Philips's arch-rival.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of a trend sweeping electronics: factories for hire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 225 words; total uncut is 1,200 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-FLEX-FACTORIES-750&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
