been 20 points behind a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   A poll in Michigan, which votes three days after South Carolina,
showed the two in a dead heat. In January, Bush had been 34 points
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the two biggest states which go to the polls on March 7,
McCain narrowed yawning gaps: in California, he halved Bush's lead
to 19 points and, in New York, cut it to a mild nine points.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers suggest one advantage that McCain has over
previous insurgents. Buchanan's support had been concentrated among
angry blue-collar workers worried about their jobs. McCain's
reaches out into a variety of different groups. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 150 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 500) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, turning an initial display of interest into real votes
requires organization. Here, McCain has an advantage over Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Having won New Hampshire in 1984, the Colorado senator was
flooded with offers of money and help. But, having been a virtual
unknown before the vote, he had no organization.
</P>
<P>
   The envelopes with the checks in them piled up unopened at Hart
headquarters. He failed to capitalize on his early win.
</P>
<P>
   McCain too is being inundated with cash. He has raised over $2
million in a week. But this has come over the Internet. The money
can be banked electronically and used immediately. And he knows
what to do with the volunteers. An amazing 26,000 have signed up in
the past week alone. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Hart, McCain was a national figure when the campaign
opened. He had raised $15 million by January, and already had the
rudiments of an organization to put those volunteers vigorously to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he will never be Bush's equal in sheer volume of
money and organization. So the essence of his strategy is to bring
new voters _ not necessarily all registered Republicans _ to swing
the primaries his way.
</P>
<P>
   Wordsworth and Coleridge said that they had to create the taste
by which their poetry was enjoyed. McCain is trying to create the
electorate by which his candidacy will be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire showed how powerful this approach can be. Some 40
percent of those who voted were either independents or former
Democrats. McCain won their votes by three-to-one, or 40 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's campaign manager, dismissed these people as
``quirky, maverick, liberal independents.'' His problem is that the
past week has shown how many of them there are, all over the
country.
</P>
<P>
   By good luck, several of the next primaries, including South
Carolina's and Michigan's, are ``open'': anyone may vote in the
Republican poll. In other big states, including California and
Massachusetts, former Democrats may vote if they switch their
registration.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts secretary of state, William Galvin, says he is
swamped by calls from Democrats asking to drop their party
affiliation so that they can vote for McCain in the Republican
primary on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Independents and those who cross party lines have a lot of
clout. Bill McInturff, McCain's pollster, explains how.
</P>
<P>
   If independents cast a third of the votes and McCain wins them
by 40 percentage points, as he did in New Hampshire, that gives him
a 12-point margin overall. To overcome that, Bush has to win the
two-thirds who are registered Republicans by more than 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   This is a formidable task if voters start thinking of the race
as a contest of equals _ as they are now doing.
</P>
<P>
   So the main questions about the primary season are becoming: How
many independent voters are there? And can McCain prevent Bush from
winning big among registered Republicans? &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 1,000, OR CONTINUE TO 1,450) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   In the country as a whole, only about 15 percent of voters are
independents (many states do not keep party registrations, so there
is no sure figure). Their numbers are rising but this would not be
enough to sustain a McCain insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   If you look state by state, though, McCain's chances look
better. In California, says Bernd Schwieren, 21 percent of voters
are independents, up from 12 percent in 1992. Among those
registering for the first time, independents outstrip Republicans
three-to-one.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush retains his lead in the state, McCain won himself
many friends when he addressed the annual gathering of the
Republican Party just after the New Hampshire vote.
</P>
<P>
   One party stalwart described the response as the most
enthusiastic since Ronald Reagan addressed the party 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, the potential McCain constituency is bigger: almost
a third of those planning to vote in the Republican primary are
independents. This state is home to the so-called ``Reagan
Democrats,'' industrial workers who usually lean towards the
Democratic Party but voted for Reagan because he appealed to their
social and economic conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has set about renewing that appeal. At a meeting in
Macomb County in the Detroit suburbs, he talked for the first time
of ``McCain Democrats,'' and claimed that ``the whole essence of
the Republican Party should be to reach out across party lines.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a remarkable statement from someone contesting a primary
election. This suggests that McCain might _ just might _ be able to
win Michigan and even California. But both races are likely to be
close, and strongly influenced by South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the opinion polls suggest that no fewer than 37 percent of
voters are independents _ a motley bunch including ex-servicemen
(the state has proportionately more of these than any other state)
and retired Yankees (who outnumber native Southerners on the coast,
says Mark Sanford, the congressman who represents most of that
region).
</P>
<P>
   Yet, at the same time, a third of voters describe themselves as
religious conservatives, twice as many as in Michigan or
California. This was the only group of Republican voters that
McCain lost in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   So South Carolina will be vital in two ways: it will test the
relative strength of independents and religious conservatives, and
it will set the scene for two big states, Michigan and California,
that McCain needs to win.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago he stood no chance in either place. Now, the fact
that he has even an outside chance is testimony to his
extraordinary powers of attracting support from way beyond the
party's traditional ranks. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
