<SLUG> BC-GUTSY-KING-MOROCCO-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW KING ACTS TO DRAG MOROCCO OUT OF ITS FEUDAL ERA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from Fri., Feb. 11)   (This excellent 850-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RUPERT CORNWELL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A rise in the legal age of marriage from 15 to 18; polygamy only
with the express permission of a man's first wife; an equal right
to divorce, and a fair division of assets between the separating
parties. What could sound more reasonable?
</P>
<P>
   In Morocco, however, these very notions are enough to have wise
men warning of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The end of January 2000 will go down as when the new Moroccan
revolution was obliged to wake up to reality.
</P>
<P>
   It was when Islamic activists shouted down ministers at meetings
in the capital, Rabat. And when a government plan to haul the
treatment of women from the Middle Ages to somewhere near the 21st
century became the litmus test of King Mohammed VI's ambitions for
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, one of the most stable Arab countries has become the
latest battleground between modernizers and the forces of
conservative Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Little was expected from a shy and untested crown prince,
Mohammed, when he succeeded Hassan II last July. But in the few
months since, ``M-6'' has transformed the mood of his country.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed the return from exile of Abraham Serfaty, the
country's most prominent dissident and erstwhile political
prisoner, and then sacked his father's dreaded interior minister,
Drissi Basri.
</P>
<P>
   He has twice already travelled to the desperately poor Rif
region, the largest source of cannabis for Europe where 90 percent
of the population is illiterate _ and where Hassan II never deigned
to set foot in his 38 years on the throne.
</P>
<P>
   On the Western Sahara dispute, which has weighed on Moroccan
international relations for a quarter of a century, the king hints
at a new flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Unprecedented in the Arab world, he has launched a commission to
probe human-rights abuses, above all the disappearance without
trial of hundreds of political dissidents into Basri's prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Long muzzled, the Moroccan press is enjoying a previously
unknown freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the 36-year-old king has governed by dramatic gesture
_ none more dramatic than last November's sacking of Basri, ``the
top cop of the kingdom'' who for 20 years had been Hassan II's iron
fist.
</P>
<P>
   But the clash with militant Islam over women's emancipation will
be a first, perhaps decisive challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this fails,'' Prime Minister Abderrahman Youssoufi recently
warned a visitor, ``the whole reform project fails.''
</P>
<P>
   Morocco, mercifully, is not Algeria. A different history,
culture, and ethnic composition make any rerun of the ghastly civil
war which has engulfed its neighbor unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But if Morocco's Islamists are a minority, they are a determined
one. They have the backing of conservatives in Youssoufi's
eight-party coalition, and a natural recruiting ground in the
mosques and universities. And Morocco's dire economic problems give
them ammunition galore.
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients which have stoked Islamic movements elsewhere in
the Arab world are only too visible here also: massive
unemployment, $19 billion of foreign debt whose mere servicing
consumes a third of the annual budget, rampant corruption and vast
disparities between a tiny, super-wealthy elite and masses who live
in grinding poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The overall illiteracy rate is 50 percent; as many live on
(pounds sterling)1 ($1.60) a day or less. Among women in the
countryside, deprived of schooling, jobs and basic legal rights,
those figures rise to 80 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   This is the background of the battle over Morocco's women, and
the family code, the moudawana, which enchains them.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamists are claiming for all they are worth that
emancipation of women as envisaged would lead to the collapse of
the family, the destruction of Islamic values, and debauchery of
every sort.
</P>
<P>
   And the government is by no means sure of victory. Hamstrung by
differences within its own ranks, it has not dared to challenge the
Islamists head-on.
</P>
<P>
   And, as one former provincial governor wondered, ``Who do the
peasantry more easily identify with _ the religious parties, or a
Westernized governing elite which has scant experience of how they
actually live?''
</P>
<P>
   Once more, all roads lead back to the king, change's best
guarantee. The youth of Mohammed VI and his closest aides could be
a vital asset in a country 50 percent of whose population is under
25.
</P>
<P>
   But not only does he wield vast temporal powers in his
semi-feudal kingdom. He is also Morocco's supreme religious
authority: the Commander of the Faithful, the Sword of the Lord on
Earth, directly descended from the Prophet, and such a man
religious activists will take on at their peril.
</P>
<P>
   To show his commitment to Islam, the king has grown a beard
since he ascended the throne.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his father who survived at least two attempted military
coups against him, the king so far has the full loyalty of the army
and the police: without it, he could never last.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan to help women will be his sternest test. ``I am not
exaggerating,'' insists Serfaty, ``this is capable of leading us
into civil war.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 850-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
