<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6372 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TARZAN-MINISTER-HNS &LR;      02-14 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TARZAN-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FAN OF `TARZAN' AUTHOR IS A HERO AMONG LOYAL READERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Calif., N.H., N.Y.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Fans of Tarzan creator Edgar Rice Burroughs can
thank Henry Heins, a retired Lutheran minister, for some new
reading material.
</P>
<P>
   It was Heins who helped bring into print recently two
unpublished Burroughs works, a 1924 novel, ``Marcia of the
Doorstep,'' and a 1927 play, ``You Lucky Girl!'' With introductions
written by Heins, the pair of never-before-published books are
available now in a $60 deluxe limited edition with slipcase or $30
for a standard hardcover.
</P>
<P>
   What began for Heins as a boyhood fascination with the prolific
writer's books blossomed into a middle-age obsession and, at 76,
has finally come to fruition for the former pastor of St. Mark's
Lutheran Church in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels nice to see them in print,'' Heins said. ``I feel
like I nurtured them along for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   A lifetime, actually.
</P>
<P>
   When Heins was an elementary school student in New York City,
his parents rewarded each A in his report card with a new Burroughs
book. Heins was a good student and his stack of Burroughs grew.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Burroughs died in 1950 at age 74 in Encino, Calif.,
he had become one of the most popular writers of his generation. He
churned out nearly 60 books in a variety of genres from a
science-fiction series on Mars to Hollywood pulp fiction to the
wildly successful Tarzan stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The books have enduring appeal because their simple plots and
easy language made them accessible to kids, but they're also good
escapist fiction for adults,'' said Heins, who continues to read
Burroughs seven decades after first encountering the guilty
pleasure of the author's low-brow style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I eventually had to tell the members of my church I had this
offbeat interest,'' Heins said. ``They accepted it.''
</P>
<P>
   The clergyman's interest was almost derailed early on. When
Heins went to seminary school, his parents cleaned out his room and
tossed out boxes of his Burroughs books. Heins has since collected
valuable first editions of every Burroughs title, which he keeps in
meticulous condition in a cluttered basement office alongside a
model-train layout and books on railroad history.
</P>
<P>
   One volume that didn't get discarded by his parents is a first
edition of the 1938 ``Tarzan and the Forbidden City.'' It sold for
$2 at the time and now fetches a hundred or more times that.
Burroughs inscribed the book to the young Heins, who regrets he
never met his literary idol. The inscription was part of a
mail-order-book-club arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The long prologue to Heins' assistance in discovering two
unpublished Burroughs manuscripts began in earnest in 1962, when
Heins was researching an unrelated project at New York State
Library. He stumbled across an archive of Library of Congress
catalog cards that had never been printed, including a year-by-year
Catalogue of Copyright Entries.
</P>
<P>
   Heins immersed himself in those remote stacks for months and
emerged with his first book, ``Golden Anniversary Bibliography of
Edgar Rice Burroughs.'' It was published in 1964 by Donald M.
Grant, a small publisher in Hampton Falls, N.H. Fans snapped up all
1,000 copies of Heins' detailed documentation of Burroughs' writing
at $10 apiece in a few months. (The out-of-print bibliography now
sells for $200 to $300.) With his royalties from the bibliography,
Heins bought a manual Royal typewriter he's still using.
</P>
<P>
   Heins' archival digging uncovered the unknown ``You Lucky
Girl!'' Burroughs copyrighted the love story in three acts under
number D81617 on Nov. 3, 1927.
</P>
<P>
   Heins corresponded about his discovery with Hulbert Burroughs,
the author's son, who invited Heins to investigate the family safe
in the Burroughs compound at Tarzana, Calif. ``Hulbert and I were
sitting on the floor in front of the open safe,'' Heins recalled of
the visit in 1963. ``We had a pile of manuscripts we'd pulled out
and there was the play in a small binder of 78 pages.''
</P>
<P>
   Heins later learned that Burroughs wrote ``You Lucky Girl!'' for
his daughter, Joan, an aspiring actress, in an attempt to boost her
career. The plan failed and the play, the only drama Burroughs
completed, was forgotten. It was staged for the first time at the
Palmdale Playhouse in California in 1997, after Burroughs' daughter
had died.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, nearly 40 years after his find, Heins shared in the
achievement by being asked by the publisher (Donald M. Grant again)
to autograph the endpapers of 1,000 copies of the deluxe limited
edition of ``You Lucky Girl!'' along with Burroughs' grandson,
Danton Burroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Grant's simultaneous publication of ``Marcia of the Doorstep''
(Burroughs' longest book at 125,000 words, a novel of blackmail and
high society bridging Broadway and Hollywood) is more interesting
to Heins for its historical significance than its literary merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play and the novel are OK, but I still think his Mars
series is the best,'' Heins said. ``I enjoyed the Tarzan books, but
the movies cheapened them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heins' wife of 51 years, Marie, does not share her husband's
fascination with Burroughs. ``I've tried to read him a few times,
but his books never held my attention and I couldn't finish,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she devours two or three science-fiction or
historical-fiction volumes each week, particularly the books of
Anne McCaffrey and Andre Norton. The Heins' modest bungalow
overflows with thousands of books _ hers on the main floor and his
in the basement and filling 14 bookcases in the attic. Roaming
among the shelves of books are two cats, Lady and Contessa.
</P>
<P>
   Heins' devotion to Burroughs has been recognized by the writer's
legion of fans, who have posted dozens of Web sites to honor the
author. They also produce a Burroughs newsletter, Fan Directory.
</P>
<P>
   Heins was presented with a plaque in 1990 by Burroughs
Bibliophiles, a fan group, for ``outstanding achievement and
devotion to the memory of Edgar Rice Burroughs.''
</P>
<P>
   Heins' boost in getting the lost manuscripts published was a way
of repaying that honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it for the fans,'' Heins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
