<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK TWICE ABOUT SELLING BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. My mother prefers to invest conservatively and has done
quite well with tax-exempt municipal bonds. However, the return on
these bonds has dropped significantly since the 1970s and '80s. In
reviewing her year-end statement, I noticed that each fund dropped
steadily in value per share. She ended up with an overall balance
of $33,000 _ less than at the beginning, despite reinvesting all
earnings. She currently does not need the proceeds of this account,
but it seems $500,000, conservatively invested, should do better
than a $33,000 loss. Assuming she keeps the half of the account
that's in individual bonds, how would you advise her to invest the
other half to earn 6 percent to 7 percent, while keeping the
principal out of harm's way?
</P>
<P>
   G.C., Portland, Ore. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your mother probably had about as tough a year with her
individual municipal bond holdings as she did with her funds. I
tally an overall loss of 6.6 percent; my guess is that unless a
couple of the poorly performing funds represented a large amount of
the fund positions, there were substantial losses in the individual
bond accounts, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the funds you list (both classes of the Smith Barney High
Income fund) eked out small gains for 1999. The Class B shares of
the Smith Barney Total Return fund, with a portfolio of long-term
bonds, lost 6.3 percent. Smith Barney Managed Municipals (which is
what I presume you meant by Smith Barney Managed) lost 7.7 percent,
also with a long-term portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the Total Return fund, which is not rated by
Morningstar, compare to an average loss of 2.8 percent for its peer
funds in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the Managed Municipals fund also compared
unfavorably to an average loss of 4.8 percent for its peers. But
that's not necessarily mismanagement. As Morningstar Mutual Funds
puts it, the fund makes aggressive interest-rate plays, and its
longer-term trailing returns are among the muni national long
category's best.
</P>
<P>
   Even if these two money-losing funds represented positions of
nearly $125,000 each, the combined loss they delivered would be
only about half of the total portfolio loss for the year. And when
you factor in the gains from the High-Yield funds, even more of the
red ink must be spread among the individual municipal bond
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unhappy results, I would think twice about selling.
With Class B holdings, your mother would face a redemption charge
of up to 4.5 percent if she sold, with the level of the charge
depending on how long she has held the positions. She could,
indeed, achieve a safe yield in the 6 percent to 7 percent range _
the highest rate in the nation for a five-year jumbo bank CD was
7.7 percent entering this week _ but if she sells she'll lose the
chance to recoup some of her losses.
</P>
<P>
   I don't see any particular prospect for a short-term rebound in
the bond markets. But I think our record economic expansion will
end sooner rather than later, and once that becomes certain, the
remedy will be lower interest rates _ which rewards the owners of
bond funds. And such funds can be as volatile on the upside as they
are when interest rates go against them. Since your mother doesn't
rely on income from these funds, she can afford to wait until the
worm turns in the bond market _ and in the meantime, avoid the
galling prospect of paying a redemption fee on funds that have been
losing money.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at some of the individual municipal bond accounts,
which generated a good deal of the red ink. These holdings can be
sold without fees anywhere near the size of redemption fees for the
funds, so one of them may be a good candidate for being swapped
into a CD position.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does a defined-benefit lifetime pension negate the need for a
bond portfolio? My husband and I married two years ago and have no
dependents. Current living expenses are $65,000 to $75,000, apart
from taxes; we'd like to increase this to $75,000 or more in
retirement, if our portfolio is up to it. Are we on track to retire
at 53? Do we need a bond portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   N.G., San Luis Obispo, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems you'll be in very nice shape to retire at 53. You
can certainly forget about a bond portfolio for quite a few years.
In eight years, with contributions at current levels _ including
some estimates on my part for contributions to 401(k) and 403(b)
plans _ your savings would grow from $259,248 currently to $998,325
_ provided your portfolio has average annual growth of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since your combined pensions would supply a little more than
$65,000 _ the lower end of your current spending estimate _ all you
will need from your portfolio at retirement is cash to boost your
income a bit and to deal with taxes. You might handle that upon
retirement or shortly before, by moving about a quarter of the
total accumulation _ specifically, funds in the tax-deferred
accounts _ into fixed-income holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Since you will meet your targets with such a wide margin, it
seems silly to think about buying fixed-income holdings at this
point. Your position with all of your savings in stocks is
aggressive, but your portfolio is nicely diversified. And with
those pensions looming, you can afford to ride out the vagaries of
the stock markets. So I suggest no change at all.
</P>
<P>
   I do wonder about the large difference in the dollar value of
your pension at ages 53 and 55. To most people, it would probably
seem worth chugging away at the old job for another two years to
get a $13,000 annual increase in your lifetime pension, complete
with annual adjustments. (Might I suspect a typo somewhere in your
letter?)
</P>
<P>
   In any event, wait until you're about 50, and then survey the
situation. Decide then if working the extra two years is worth the
extra $13,000, and calculate how much money in addition to your
pensions you might need. If you decide to retire at 53, you could
slowly develop the fixed-income side; if you decide to hang on to
age 55, you could wait a few years and then reassess. It could be
that if you retired at age 55 you would have very little or no need
of any bond holdings.
</P>
<P>
   I hasten to add that the luxury of holding no fixed-income
assets is generally limited to people with substantial assets _ and
those two pensions represent very substantial assets. For most
people, whether or not they will draw upon retirement savings
immediately upon retirement, the element of risk becomes a large
part of the formula. They may be able to forgo the yield from bond
holdings, but they can't accept the risk that goes with an
all-stock portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money Musings: The stock market, at least as estimated by the
Standard and Poor's 500 Index, has not suffered a losing election
year since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
