<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAGIC NUMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; So, what's the number? Not the lottery pick, but the financial
peace of mind number _ call it the magic number _ that allows a
person to look at the monthly bank and investment statements and
say: ``Whew. I made it. Now I can relax.''
</P>
<P>
   The magic number used to be $1 million. For many people it still
is, although that pile has lost some of its luster, now that TV
game show contestants are raking it in so easily.
</P>
<P>
   Savvy investors, though, are doing the same in the soaring stock
market, which has encouraged a kind of casino mentality. The dice
are definitely rattling in stratospheric circles, where high
rollers call their magic number a ``hunge'' _ short for $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   Low-rollers may think they could be outrageously comfortable
with half a hunge, or a quarter, or a couple of million. But maybe
that's only because they don't have it yet.
</P>
<P>
   Magic numbers are tricky. They slide around. They expand and
contract with weather and mood swings and new bank balances.
Today's good life can easily become tomorrow's ``not exactly,'' as
people who always thought they'd be happy making $2 million find
they aren't. Or as investors who were once delighted with a 10 or
15 percent return now figure they're losers if they don't make at
least 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not money management,'' says a sales manager, describing
his work at the Boston offices of a top Wall Street investment
banking and brokerage firm. ``This business is about managing
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows people who have no money in their checking accounts and
who put it all in stocks, because that's what makes them feel
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard of people taking out second mortgages to invest in
technology start-ups. ``People have unbelievably diluted
conceptions as to what normal is,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   For him, peace of mind is having six months' to a year's worth
of mortgage payments on hand in a liquid account, such as a money
market account or Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
   For Larry DiCara, a former Boston city councilor who's now a
partner at Nixon Peabody, peace of mind will mean being able to put
away $1 million dollars, after taxes, by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   That's the ``round number'' his financial adviser came up with
when DiCara wanted to know what it would cost to put his triplets
through college. ``That's a lot,'' he says glumly, noting that he
worked his way through Harvard University when tuition was about
$2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some people define their financial comfort zone in the
vernacular. The polite version is ``take a hike money,'' which
allows a person to walk away from a job, a relationship, or
whatever situation deserves the epithet.
</P>
<P>
   The amount one needs to walk depends on lifestyle and on the
next step: retirement or another job.
</P>
<P>
   John Spooner, an investment adviser at Salomon Smith Barney Inc.
in Boston, says someone who needs $75,000 a year after taxes must
put $1.5 million in the pot, meaning liquid assets and investments.
</P>
<P>
   Another financial planner offered this rule of thumb: Figure
$100,000 a year after taxes and multiply it by expected life span.
A person age 65 multiplying the $100,000 by 20 would need $2
million in the pot. A 55-year-old would need $2.5 to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may find these numbers impossibly big _ and
depressing _ and choose to seek financial comfort in much smaller
goals: keeping a $500 cushion in the checking account, not letting
a credit card balance go over $1,000, putting $20 a week in the
cookie jar till there is $100 to invest.
</P>
<P>
   For others, the magic number is not a number at all, but an
achievement: founding a company and taking it public, making
partner at the firm, getting the degree, a better job offer, or
finally having some free time.
</P>
<P>
   What's the number? The answer is in the eye of the calculator.
The work sheet is in the psyche, and the math is optional.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Susan Traush is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
