<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Jeff Jacoby is not writing today.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6396 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-TATE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-BO     02-14 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-TATE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LONDON: ... notably philistine.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Broadly speaking, architects have two options when converting
existing buildings into art museums. They can leave as much as
possible of what's already there: old brick walls, old machinery
that suddenly takes on a sculptural air, even old layers of paint,
to suggest the structure's past. Or they can gut the place, erasing
prior identities. With some exceptions, Swiss architects Herzog &AMP;
de Meuron are taking the latter route in transforming the interior
of the former Bankside Power Station. ``Power'' describes the
building's architecture as well as its original output. Designed in
1947 by Sir Giles Gilbert Scott (also the designer of Britain's
famous red telephone booth), its heftiness is relieved by jazzy
verticals on its exterior and an immensely tall chimney, the visual
signature that dominates its Thames-side site.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the huge scale that artists prefer nowadays,
especially in installations, Bankside is being turned into a series
of 81 gargantuan galleries, one a double-height space with a
40-foot ceiling, many with white walls and pale oak floors. At the
moment, still under construction, they look like generic
contemporary art spaces. A new glass box on the sixth and seventh
levels of the building will, among other things, house a restaurant
with spectacular views of St. Paul's and other London landmarks. A
pedestrian bridge by architect Norman Foster and sculptor Anthony
Caro will link the two sides of the river.
</P>
<P>
   Chunky steel beams painted licorice black are among the few
holdovers from the building's past. The biggest reminder, though,
is the biggest space _ the ground floor's Turbine Hall, a 500-foot
expanse, which makes it 50 feet longer than the vast boat-shaped
gallery at the Guggenheim Bilbao. It may well be the world's
largest permanent indoor space for art. Turbine Hall will serve as
the new museum's main entrance and a space for immense sculptures.
Thanks to a $2 million grant from Unilever, the Tate will
commission one new work a year for the Hall for the next five
years, the first by the 87-year-old American sculptor Louise
Bourgeois. Thanks to a rolling gantry at the top of the Hall, quite
a site in itself, workers will be able to move the giant pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wide range of exhibits
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mix of exhibitions at the Tate Millbank during my recent
visit gives a clue to the immense popularity of the place. There
are always the Turner paintings, of course, the main draw for
first-timers. The temporary shows I saw included the Turner Prize
exhibition, featuring work by McQueen, Emin, Steven Pippin, and
Jane and Louise Wilson. (Work by the Wilson sisters is currently on
view at MIT's List Visual Arts Center.) ``The Art of Bloomsbury,''
now finished at the Tate but coming to the Yale Center for British
Art in New Haven in May, attempts to show that the movement most
closely associated with Virginia Woolf and her fellow writers was
equally strong in the visual arts, thanks, in the beginning, to
painter-theorist Roger Fry going gaga over French painting and
subsequently shaking up British art.
</P>
<P>
   Most inventive of all the shows was ``At Home With Art,'' for
which nine leading British sculptors, including Anish Kapoor and
Richard Deacon, created practical household objects, wall pegs to
shower curtains, meant for mass production. Most intriguing of the
shows, and a particular favorite of Christoph Grunenberg's, is
``Mark Dion: Tate Thames Dig,'' up through Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Dion, an American who is part artist, part scientist, led a team
of volunteers on a beachcombing excavation by the Thames at both
Millbank (once the site of a huge prison) and Bankside, which
housed brothels and bear-baiting pits in the 16th century. The
amateur archeologists collected broken centuries-old glass and
indestructible plastic; shells, bottle caps, buttons, teeth,
toothbrushes, and credit cards. They sorted, labeled, and
categorized it all, neatly installing it in a huge, 19th
century-style wooden cabinet of the sort once found in
natural-history museums. Visitors are invited to open the drawers
and doors and examine the contents, an experience that eventually
leads to an inevitable ``Yuck!'' But what a delightful way to
conjure up the history of the two London locations that are home to
one of Europe's most dynamic museums.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
