<HEADER>
A6398 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-OSCARS-BOS &LR;      02-14 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-OSCARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNREELING AN EARLY TAKE ON THE OSCARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're all clueless about the Oscars. Let's be clear about that.
Even last year, when everybody (including me) picked ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' we were wrong. And everything, every category, is
up for grabs in this year's Oscar race. Not a single clear-cut
front-runner in the lot. Which makes it more fun to guess at. So
we're doing it twice. Before we get around to guessing the winners,
there's the irresistible impulse to first guess the slate of
nominees, who'll be announced Tuesday. At least we won't have to
wait long to see how right or wrong we were. Here goes: &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST PICTURE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' is as close as we get to a certain nominee,
here as well as in the acting categories. The only question is
whether this brilliant black comedy of family dysfunction and
self-detonation is going to be this year's ``L.A. Confidential,''
uniformly praised, but perhaps a little too apocalyptic to go the
distance with the Academy. ``Being John Malkovich'' is the small
indie that seems too original to ignore, especially since the
Academy is bent on showing the world that it still is relevant. Its
original narrative techniques and envelope-pushing performances
should command what I think of as the upstart slot. ``The Cider
House Rules'' has a good shot, given the Academy's predilection for
emotion. This film has plenty of warmth, skillfully and tenderly
brought to the screen by Lasse Hallstrom. It will, I think, edge
``The Green Mile'' for the warmth slot because comparisons to ``The
Shawshank Redemption'' will cost the latter film. ``The Insider''
is too heavy-handed and misshapen to be considered a good film, but
its impeccable political correctness makes it a natural for a group
that tends to favor films that will reflect well on it and the biz
in general. ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' made some people queasy,
and it stumbles at the end, but it's so jagged with style that it's
a throwback to the days when Hollywood films shimmered with
glamour, to which the Academy could respond, to say nothing of the
film's quintet of wickedly entertaining performances. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST DIRECTOR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Usually, there's a one-to-one picture-director correspondence.
But one need only look back to last year, when Steven Spielberg
took this award, only to see ``Saving Private Ryan'' upset by
``Shakespeare in Love'' as best picture. Sam Mendes is a certain
nominee for ``American Beauty,'' a stage director who made the most
of the stage savvy of his two leads and a darkly coruscating
script. Michael Mann is good bet, not so much, frankly, for the
excellence of ``The Insider,'' as for his bold position on the
right side of the David-and-Goliath battle against Big Tobacco.
Anthony Minghella did such a sleek and sophisticated job of guiding
``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' through some tricky psychological and
geographical territory that his finesse can't be ignored. Neither
can Spike Jonze, whose reinvention of ``Alice in Wonderland'' for a
celebrity culture in ``Being John Malkovich'' make it the year's
most original film. But ``The Sixth Sense,'' which I think made too
much money to nail a best picture nomination, was too strong a
presence to be ignored. Giving its writer-director, M. Night
Shyamalan, a slot is one way to recognize it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST ACTRESS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Swank swept the critics' awards. The question is whether
enough Academy voters will have seen her heart-stopping performance
as a transsexual in peril in ``Boys Don't Cry,'' a small indie.
Annette Bening was a large part of the reason for the brilliance of
``American Beauty.'' Her angry, tightly wound suburban wife about
to explode is acting perfection. Sigourney Weaver has her best role
in years, perhaps ever, as a farm wife and mother whose life falls
out from under her in ``A Map of the World.'' What she's up against
is the fact that the film was distributed by a small company, which
will cost her the visibility of a big studio push. Ditto for my
next two picks. Janet McTeer is both adorable and compelling as a
loose cannon of a single mom careening cross-country from one
disastrous romance to the next, but unwavering in her love for her
teenage daughter, who's starting to tire of the whole routine, in
``Tumbleweeds.'' Frances O'Connor, the most interesting actress to
come out of Australia since Judy Davis, would be the long shot here
if she's nominated, but she's at the center of the latest
successful Austen screen adaptation, ``Mansfield Park.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST ACTOR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Spacey is a certain nominee for his performance as a man
who escalates a midlife crisis into a personal apocalypse in
``American Beauty.'' Every moment of his performance tingles with
perverse rebellion and a sense of mischief on the way to hell.
Russell Crowe is the main reason ``The Insider'' is as powerful as
it is. Even though the film puts too much focus on the TV producer
who told his story, Crowe is riveting as the conflicted tobacco
industry insider who blew the whistle. Denzel Washington will only
add to the reservoir of career respect he's amassing for his role
as the wrongfully convicted Rubin Carter in ``The Hurricane.'' In a
remarkably internalized performance, he makes the camera come to
him as a man who survived years in prison by migrating to his own
interior. Richard Farnsworth is known as an old charmer and rightly
so. But it isn't charm that makes the ex-cowboy and stunt rider
turned actor so moving and persuasive as an aging man determined to
end a family feud in David Lynch's ``The Straight Story.'' It's
character. Whether American once stood for the integrity he seems
to embody, he persuades you it did and that straight shooting and
self-reliance are what he's all about. Matt Damon deserves a shot
for flying in the face of his golden boy persona to play a young
man who slides down the slope of corruption from opportunism to
murder in ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.'' There's a slipperiness in
his make-it-up-as-you-go-along scheming that we didn't know he had
in him. Even his gaucherie seems calculated. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST SUPPORTING ACTRESS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julianne Moore has done too much excellent work to be ignored,
although it may not help that she spread it across several films.
Her anguished wife in ``Magnolia,'' her conflicted chum of
Sigourney Weaver in ``A Map of the World,'' and her suavely
sparkling adventuress in ``An Ideal Husband'' each would qualify
her. Put them together, and a nomination seems inevitable. One
reason Swank is as good as she is in ``Boys Don't Cry'' is because
she has Chloe Sevigny to bounce her desperate neediness off. As the
only local with enough sensitivity to empathize with Swank's
yearnings in their forlorn Nebraska backwater, she's haunting.
Angelina Jolie, a comer in any case, is the reason electricity
flies off the screen in ``Girl, Interrupted.'' Her charismatic
sociopath is a twisted force of nature you can't take your eyes
off. Catherine Keener's razory eyes-on-the-prize businesswoman is a
big part of the reason ``Being John Malkovich'' has the edge it
has. The cold sizzle in her character will probably give her the
nod over Cameron Diaz's frumped-down animal lover in the same film.
Cherry Jones is the long shot here, and it's probably wrong to
single her out from what clearly is an ensemble effort in ``Cradle
Will Rock.'' But her Hallie Flanagan shiningly restores to view an
angel of theater in the '30s, who put in place a tradition of
activism still alive today and who is embodied here with brains,
dignity, and character. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST SUPPORTING ACTOR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As with Julianne Moore, Philip Seymour Hoffman did too much good
work in 1999 to be bypassed. Probably his starring role in
``Flawless'' shouldn't be discussed here, and his sympathetic nurse
in ``Magnolia'' was part of an ensemble performance, but his
obnoxious snob in ``Ripley'' will do very nicely as a solid
qualifier. Michael Caine is a nonstop source of heart and soul in
``The Cider House Rules,'' contributing mightily to its humanity
and tenderness. As a Maine doctor in charge of an orphanage, he
leaves us convinced that he really cares. Haley Jon Osment was the
big reason ``The Sixth Sense'' proved so haunting to so many
moviegoers. His portrayal of the boy weighed down with baleful
uninvited visions represents this film's best shot at an Oscar.
Similarly, Michael Clarke Duncan represents the best chance ``The
Green Mile'' has on Oscar night. Tom Hanks's performance as a
prison guard is excellent but understated, and Duncan's gentle
giant with mysterious powers is able to avoid the potentially
disastrous redemptive dimension built into his character and emerge
as enormously sympathetic. Christopher Plummer won several critics'
awards as Mike Wallace in ``The Insider.'' Well, why not? He's only
one of the world's best actors. Word is that Wallace was displeased
with the film. If so, he was led astray by his ego. If Christopher
Plummer plays you, you should probably just shut up and watch him.
You'll learn how to play yourself better. This is the most crowded
category, which means equally worthy work by Chris Cooper
(``October Sky,'' ``American Beauty''), Jude Law (``The Talented
Mr. Ripley''), and Tom Cruise (``Magnolia'') will be bypassed for
no good reason other than arithmetic. Or not. We'll see Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
