<HEADER>
A6399 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-DOCTOROW-BOS &LR;      02-14 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DOCTOROW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STRUGGLES OF BELIEVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
CITY OF GOD 
By E.L. Doctorow. Random House. 272 pp. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine, first, the Big Apple as the ultimate city of forbidden
fruit _ a post-Edenic metropolis of sin, temptation, and humanity
unbound, where The Fall might mean either a roller-coaster in
Queens or a particularly bad night in an alley on the East Side.
It's a place blessed with performance art on every corner and the
magnificence of culture on every other block; it's also an
anti-Mecca cursed with the colliding fears of millions of
strangers, where misery sleeps in the mud tracks left by the
stretch limos. Good morning, New York! Now whistle a little tune to
accompany our metaphor of infinite paradox: something with a little
swing, say, something that would work in the piano bars _ those
comfort dens of melancholy and smoke and excess insight. Because
that's the one common denominator about New York; it's all, God
help us, just too much.
</P>
<P>
   Holy hell, in other words, delivered, willy-nilly, in the
postmodern primordial soup that is ``City of God.'' With his
deliberately fractured narrative and his forays into sex, religion,
history, science, and popular culture, E. L. Doctorow has produced
a novel that seeks to be about everything. He has instead given us
something where the parts are greater than the whole _ a vast
territory marked by brilliant tributaries, but lacking a cohesive
center. ``City of God'' is both showy and exasperating, continually
demonstrating the intellectual fluency of its author but lacking
the aesthetic reach _ call it literary generosity _ that imbued
``Ragtime,'' ``World's Fair,'' and ``Billy Bathgate.'' With his
firebrand conscience and a brainpower available to few of his
peers, Doctorow has always used history to literary advantage; in
some cases, though, he has been used by it, and this is one of
them. ``City of God'' is imaginative without being creative, its
disparate themes containing the swirls and crescendos of great but
incomplete jazz riffs _ the last notes wandering off into the
night, leaving you dizzy and not a little lonely.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, that's New York, right? The usual argument for this
kind of prismatic approach to fiction, where several stories and
narrative detritus coexist without intersecting, is that the
fragmented work mirrors the culture it records _ where time and
space collide on a million computer screens, where linear narrative
itself belongs to the past. However intellectually tempting this
radical aesthetic may be, it almost always bears the risk of
blowing up the novel in order to save it.
</P>
<P>
   What Doctorow has managed are a couple of old-fashioned,
beautifully wrought stories lurking within his expressionistic
whole. ``City of God'' opens with a narrator awed and horrified by
the facts of modern science and theology: an infinitely expanding
universe; a world where evil and God no longer even bother to argue
with each other; the muck of human consciousness that may well have
invented the whole enchilada. Cut to a pickup scene at a New York
dinner party; cut to a renegade Episcopal priest named Thomas
Pemberton whose church has been vandalized. Eventually a thread
reveals itself: This is the workbook of a writer named Everett,
who, casting about for the plot of a novel, weaves together his
rough drafts, his meetings with the real people who will become his
characters, and various diatribes on subjects from birdwatching to
film criticism (with walk-ons by Wittgenstein and Einstein).
Everett is a kind of casual Pirandello, wandering on and off stage
but still in charge; he's also the ultimate secular antihero _ a
disaffected intellectual who wants to believe in something beyond
the dark legacies of history. No wonder he's drawn to Pemberton, or
Pem, whose struggles with faith and modern doctrine become the
novel's central story as well as its cri de coeur.
</P>
<P>
   The sacking of Pem's church leads the priest to a brownstone on
the Upper West Side, where two married progressive rabbis, Joshua
Gruen and Sarah Blumenthal, are launching the Synagogue of
Evolutionary Judaism out of their living room. The 8-foot brass
cross from St. Timothy's has somehow been deposited on the rabbis'
roof; is this a felonious mystery, or a religious one? So begins
the interweaving of sacred and profane that provides the link of
``City of God,'' where the idea of ``omniscient narrative,'' in
both the religious and literary sense, poses the greatest question.
Faced with the onslaught of evil and chaos _ of Hitler, Stalin, the
black holes of science as well as history _ how do we create moral
order in the world?
</P>
<P>
   That's the theoretical path to the central story of Doctorow's
novel, which is a recounting by Sarah's father, reimagined by
Everett, of the Jewish ghetto in Lithuania where he was a boy _
where he watched as his parents, and then his caretakers, were
hauled away or murdered, where he served as a runner for the
ghetto's council leaders, where he helped smuggle out the forbidden
journals that recorded both Nazi atrocities and the private
triumphs of daily Jewish life. This story is not only stunningly
relayed in Everett's (and Doctorow's) hands; it also possesses the
thematic attributes that the rest of the novel circles. With young
Yehoshua a witness to one of the worst moments in human history,
his capture and delivery of that story become a courageous act of
salvation. Passed into memory, then journal narrative, then
Everett's (and Doctorow's) reimagining, the mythicized account of
what was, in fact, the Kovno ghetto takes on a gravitas that can
outlive the evil done there.
</P>
<P>
   That somber task reappears in several complementary war
narratives in the novel: Everett's father surviving no man's land
in France; his older brother as a flier in the Second World War; an
anonymous Vietnam vet _ something of a wounded one-man Greek chorus
_ delivering his lamentation from a bar. There are a few passages
of recitation and revelation in ``City of God'' that are momentous;
one of the most haunting is a Nazi curator's inventory of the
property of the dead. But when these narrative experiments have
slighter subjects, they work against the power of the novel;
riveted upon the story of little Yehoshua Blumenthal, we are
wrenched into, say, a visit by Pem to his ex-wife, or Everett's
account of a day spent watching the nest of a white gyrfalcon. It
probably doesn't help that the brief biography we have of the
writer Everett so closely resembles that of the writer Doctorow.
This similarity, whether or not it's meant to be self-referential,
has the unfortunate consequence of making you wonder just whose
unfinished workbook we're reading.
</P>
<P>
   Doctorow has always been a sort of alchemist of narrative; at
his best, his appropriation of history results in a reification of
myth _ where fact, uplifted by fiction, ascends to a higher plane
of literary memory. But his own righteous brilliance has eclipsed
Doctorow the artist in ``City of God''; even Pem, that impassioned
ex-priest of the streets, winds up delivering a petition to God
that sounds more like Southern revivalism than lapsed Christianity.
``City of God'' seems to yearn, however haphazardly, to be a novel
of ideas. And one is left with the creak and whir of intellect,
rather than the pure light of vision.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
