<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6400 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-14 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SMALL-TOWN CARE FROM A BIG-CITY GROCERY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The corner of Polk and Ellis in San Francisco, a
block from the X-rated O'Farrell Theater, is an unlikely place to
hear this sentence, but this is what Tom Nolan said: ``What we're
about is re-creating small-town America in a big city.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan is the executive director of Project Open Hand, which was
started 15 years ago by Ruth Brinker, whose idea was to provide
good food to San Franciscans sick at home with AIDS _ the way small
town residents take soup and casseroles to their sick neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   This concept of covered-dish care and neighborliness grew to one
of the shining examples of San Francisco's response to AIDS,
inspiring similar volunteer meal-delivery programs in 95 other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Project Open Hand, with huge modern kitchens at Polk
and Ellis, began delivery of meals to people in San Francisco and
Alameda County who are incapacitated at home with any kind of
disease or injury, not just HIV or AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``For about 15 years, we've been telling people `You have the
wrong disease,''' said Open Hand's program director, Michael
Kossman. ``Now we don't have to say that, and that's an incredible
place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is, San Francisco and Oakland are not small
towns, and no one knows how many people are sick and homebound.
That's why I'm writing this.
</P>
<P>
   If you live in San Francisco or Alameda County, and you're stuck
at home because of illness or injury (and you're under 60, thus not
eligible for Meals on Wheels), give Project Open Hand a call at
1-800-551-MEAL.
</P>
<P>
   You can have nourishing meals delivered by someone who cares.
</P>
<P>
   It's a very special small town that Project Open Hand has at its
headquarters of three years at Polk and Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Germaine Herr and Georgia Kirkpatrick have volunteered for Open
Hand for a decade. They were having lunch after their shift
packaging meals on a spiffy little production line.
</P>
<P>
   They're part of a regular Tuesday morning club of women
volunteers. ``We've become so close we get together on the
outside,'' Kirkpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   In the staff dining area, nutritionist Carol Friedman was eating
tofu while Terry Young, who works in the grocery center, joshed her
about finding Cocoa Puffs to distribute.
</P>
<P>
   The grocery center is where people can order and pick up
groceries _ quality ones, from all the food groups, including a few
items from the snack food group. Why shouldn't the elderly and the
sick have American enjoyments? In the kitchen, cooks Benjamin
Rodriquez and Li Jin Quan were preparing thousands of orders of
broiled chicken with marengo sauce, flank steak, fried fish fillets
and steamed fresh vegetables. Daisy Becerra, the special orders
cook, was stirring a big enough pot of couscous to star in one of
those funny TV couscous ads.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the key thing for anyone who's ever worked in a
restaurant. The kitchen was sparkling clean, loaded with the best
equipment and filled with luscious smells and good-hearted
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good place.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
