<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-14 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREEDING _ BETWEEN THE LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Lonely SF, 30s, sensitive, fun, music and animal lover, looking
for someone to love. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   A modest little ad in the Boston Globe personals, tucked among
many that promise so much. ``Attractive.'' ``Dynamic.'''
``Gorgeous.'' ``Great figure.'' ``Awesome.'' ``Striking.'' Even
``articulate.''
</P>
<P>
   I hope Lonely SF finds someone to love, or at least a likely
candidate, someone tall, with manly features and the right sort of
pheromones. Because that is what love is all about. Forget romance.
When it comes to sexual attraction, it seems we are at the mercy of
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   A story in a recent U.S. News and World Report collected some
recent findings about the biology of love between the sexes. Men
and women follow codes of attraction and beauty that may be
millions of years old, codes that have evolved to help us find the
healthiest mate and thus give us the best chance to pass our genes
to the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   We may not be conscious of evolution when we're trolling for a
significant other, but it has us in its grip, even if we think we
have no intention of reproducing.
</P>
<P>
   Women are drawn to the visible signs that a man is brimming with
testosterone. Height. Craggy chin and brow. Muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Men look for signs that a woman is fertile. A youthful face with
widely spaced eyes and a small chin. A high waist-to-hip ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have also found that men and women are attracted to
potential mates whose faces and bodies are symmetrical, a sign of a
strong constitution. They also prefer those whose scents are most
unlike their own, an indication that their genes are dissimilar.
</P>
<P>
   Are the great love stories no more than a matter of evolutionary
biology? ``O Romeo, Romeo! Wherefore art thou Romeo? / Deny thy
father and refuse they name / Or, if thou wilt not, be but sworn my
love / Because we do not smell the same.''
</P>
<P>
   And love at first sight? The love that makes sense at all, that
leaves you eager to make an abject fool of yourself for no apparent
reason? Blame it on his chin.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's New York Times Magazine, Alain de Botton writes
amusingly about ``The Schopenhauer Method,'' the 19th-century
German philosopher's ``answers to love in three easy steps.''
</P>
<P>
   According to de Botton, Schopenhauer anticipated just about
everything modern science is now discovering about the biology of
love. He theorized that the unconscious self is governed by ``the
will to life,'' i.e., to reproduce, and that the conscious self,
the intellect, ``understands only so much as is necessary to
promote reproduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Schopenhauer also understood that the unconscious self is
attracted to those who will increase the chances of producing
beautiful and intelligent offspring. And de Botton summarizes the
great pessimist's analysis of love and the urge to procreate: ``The
pursuit of personal happiness and the production of healthy
children are two radically contrasting projects, which love
maliciously confuses us into thinking of as one in the same for a
requisite number of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Schopenhauer wrote that this explains ``why we often see very
rational, and even eminent, men tied to termagants and matrimonial
fiends, and cannot conceive of how they could have made such a
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   And, needless to add, it explains why we see so many nice women
mixed up with impossible men.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Lonely SF should consider rewriting her ad to include
something about her symmetrical features and good hip-to-waist
ratio. Or maybe not. I hope she finds someone to love and doesn't
have to learn the hard way that there's something worse than being
lonely alone: being lonely with someone you once loved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
