<HEADLINE>
HE DIDN'T EVEN GET POT ROAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Douglas Tyrrell is no naif. For 25 years he has worked as a
motion clerk at the Suffolk County Courthouse, a Boston venue
decidedly short on wide-eyed innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced nine years ago, he has seen enough of love and loss at
age 45 to proceed with caution in matters of the heart. But who
among us has never been too blind to see that what seems too good
to be true probably is?
</P>
<P>
   Tyrrell offers a cautionary tale from the brave new world of
cyber-dating. ``I got suckered good,'' he says, as candid as he is
chastened about the downside of looking for love on line.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown weary of the bar scene and skeptical of personal
ads that promise ``everyone is slim and attractive until you met
them,'' he says he turned to the Internet, where online dating
services and Web sites with names like Match.Com are attracting
millions of cyber-visitors.
</P>
<P>
   From his apartment, Doug began surfing the Internet and
corresponding with dozens of women in chat rooms. He dated several,
but no one clicked quite like Jennifer from Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Doug ``met'' Jennifer just before Christmas on a Web site
designed for singles in their 40s. They exchanged e-mail about
sports, about work, about the difficulty of dating in midlife. Soon
enough, they exchanged telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer would call Doug before he left for work at the
courthouse. At night, they would watch ``Who Wants To Be A
Millionaire'' in apartments separated by half a continent but
tethered by the Web. They talked so often by telephone that
Jennifer sent Doug a prepaid phone card out of deference to his
civil servant's salary.
</P>
<P>
   She could afford it, she told him; she owned her own company and
a luxury apartment overlooking Lake Michigan. Why had a woman as
successful as she never married? She was engaged once, Jennifer
told him tearfully, but her fiance had been killed in a motorcycle
accident.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Jennifer asked Doug to come visit. She would book
his flight. She knew the airline schedules because she traveled so
much herself, on business. She would be happy to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Doug drove through a snowstorm to Logan Airport a few weeks ago
to pick up his ticket and board a flight to Milwaukee. The ticket
wasn't there. That was easy enough to explain, Jennifer said when
Doug called her at work. She was so busy, she'd neglected to make
the reservation. He should just buy a ticket at the counter and
plan to arrive in time for dinner; she was making pot roast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pot roast,'' says Doug, sounding most aghast at the specifity
of the deceit. ``She told me she was making pot roast. Who would
lie about a pot roast?''
</P>
<P>
   Doug flew to Milwaukee, his head stuffed with visions of romance
and homecooked pot roast. Jennifer was not at the airport. She had
gotten tied up at work, she said when he called. Give her a few
minutes. She'd be right there. He gave her 30 minutes, then 60.
``Just go home,'' she said when he called again. ``This was a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   How could he ``just go home?'' It would be embarrassing enough
to face his friends at work without being able to explain what had
happened with the woman who sent him the potted plant he kept
carefully watered on his courthouse desk.
</P>
<P>
   He took a taxi to the address Jennifer had described as a
lakeshore high-rise. What he found, instead, was a rundown
two-family bungalow in a neighborhood not distinguished by its
scenic views.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no Jennifer lives here,'' said the woman who answered the
front door. ``No, I'm not Jennifer,'' his cyber-date confessed when
Doug called her a final time at work. ``My real name is Jill and I
always answer the phone because I'm the receptionist here.'' She
was sorry, she said; she hadn't meant for it to go so far. She
would repay him.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrrell returned to Boston, knowing he would never see
Jennifer/Jill or his money. Cyber-dating and personal ads turned
out to have more in common than he had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be anyone they want on line,'' says Doug, who is more
skeptical now about the claims of his correspondents, more careful
to move slowly, but no less optimistic about the chance of finding
love on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got burned, but you have to take a chance. If you don't
you'll never know,'' he says. One thing Doug Tyrrell knows is that
when he finds true love, on or off the Web, he'll find it locally.
``No more road trips for me,'' he says. ``If I can't drive to her,
she's not the one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
