<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-DEMOCRACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIANS, RIGHT AND LEFT, ASSAIL EU MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA _ The worldwide condemnation of Austria's far-right
government is provoking a backlash among Austrians themselves, many
of them far removed from Joerg Haider and his anti-immigrant
Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   Even the European Union, which for the first time injected
itself last week into the internal politics of a member country by
denouncing Austria, has divisions among its nations over the degree
of distance it should keep from Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Each country's response has been shaped by its own history, the
ideological bent of its current government, and the potential
strength of far-right movements within its borders.
</P>
<P>
   The discomfort of Austrians was evident one morning in the Cafe
Sperl, where a young Adolf Hitler used to spout racist views.
Sipping coffee, Viktor Eder was quick to say he was no racist and
did not vote for Haider's far-right Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Eder, a 42-year-old financial manager, voiced deep
resentment of the European Union's decision to slap punitive
sanctions on Austria after the Freedom Party became a junior
partner early this month in a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who,'' Eder asked indignantly, ``are the Belgians and the
French to lecture us?''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just the French and Belgian governments, however, that
have expressed concern at the rise of Haider, particularly for his
rhetoric and his sympathetic remarks about Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Many leaders in the 15-member European Union have denounced not
only Haider but the conservative chancellor, Wolfgang Schuessel,
who agreed to form a coalition with the far right after he was
unable to reach an accommodation with the Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel's People's Party and the Social Democrats had ruled
Austria in coalition for most of the past half-century, a time when
Austria became stable and prosperous.
</P>
<P>
   But as the EU wades into uncharted waters, the French and German
governments, which have traditionally been the engine driving
European integration, and which both keep a watchful eye on
far-right parties in their midst, have been the most outspoken in
their condemnation of the Freedom Party's rise. The Danish and
Swedish governments were muted, and mainstream conservatives across
Europe were skeptical of the EU's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Even liberals, such as Patricia McKenna, leader of Ireland's
environmental Green Party and a member of the European Parliament,
questioned the wisdom of ganging up on Haider.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just wonder: Is this actually feeding the flames of
xenophobia?'' McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   Polls in Austria have found that the majority of Austrians, more
than double the 27 percent who had voted for the Freedom Party,
opposed the EU's involvement in what they saw as Austria's domestic
affairs. The support for Haider's party rose as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The episode is shaping up as a major test for the very concept
of the European Union, which has molded itself into a federation of
states that have gradually surrendered some of their sovereignty to
create a political and economic bloc to rival the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Turning that theory into reality is proving to as difficult as
skeptics had predicted. Only 11 of the EU's 15 members have decided
to sign up for the single currency that was launched last year. And
as the Austrian affair has proved, putting forth a united front on
foreign policy, even within its own borders, could be far more
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the European Union's response to Austria say it was
exaggerated and counterproductive, serving only to bolster Haider's
popularity at home. Like Viktor Eder, many Austrians who did not
vote for his party have been loudly resentful of other countries
meddling in their affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance that eventually became the European Union was
founded after World War II, mainly with the aim of preventing a
repeat of the two wars that destroyed much of Europe in the first
half of the 20th century. The alliance's founding fathers, such as
Jean Monnet of France, were determined to stop the spread of
fascism, and adopted the mantra of Holocaust survivors: ``Never
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who defend the European Union's response say the EU has a
moral duty to express opposition and to apply sanctions when the
governments of any of its member nations express views that are
widely seen as anathema to the reasons the EU was founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of principles and values,'' said the
Portuguese prime minister, Antonio Guterres, whose country holds
the rotating European Union presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany dismissed suggestions
that by publicly registering their disgust with Haider and his
party's policies, European leaders were interfering in Austria's
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an expression that we stand for a Europe based on values
and that Mr. Haider has constantly violated those values,''
Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the quiet coffee shop of the Jewish Museum, Georg
Haber, a leader of Vienna's Jewish community, applauded the EU
reaction, even while acknowledging that it had given a boost to
Haider in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a signal, it is important,'' Haber said. ``It says you
can't do whatever you want and hide behind the claim of
sovereignty. I hope it will keep the government here on its toes,
and make it conform to the standards of democracy and human rights.
The EU's intervention has helped Haider in the short term, but I
think in the long run the EU has put us on notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Austrians acknowledge that they have not done enough to
confront their country's complicity with the Nazis during the Third
Reich. Even Haider, in an interview with the Globe, admitted as
much.
</P>
<P>
   But many Austrians also point out that 73 percent of voters did
not vote for the Freedom Party, and that they have a point when
they argue that their country has been singled out for sanctions.
They say the Freedom Party should be given a chance to prove that
it will adhere to the rules of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The National Party, successors to Mussolini's fascists, joined
an Italian coalition government in 1994 without EU objections, and
its members are now accepted as genuine democrats. Part of the
Spanish government today hails from a party founded by one of
Franco's totalitarian lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   The French government includes communists who have been accused
of ignoring or excusing the crimes of Stalin. And the EU has been
the biggest cheerleader of the Northern Ireland peace process, in
which former IRA commanders like Martin McGuinness have joined the
local government and, in McGuinness's case, have become government
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives like Schuessel argue that it is better to tame the
far right by holding it up to the scrutiny of democracy than to
allow it to snarl on the sidelines of opposition, pandering to
voters' pet peeves without enduring the liabilities of trying to
respond to them.
</P>
<P>
   Most French would seem to think otherwise. When five
conservative regional presidents won office in 1998 by entering
into pacts with the rightist National Front, they were thrown out
of their party.
</P>
<P>
   The EU's willingness to suppress the normal weight of
majorities, giving small nations like Ireland a disproportionate
level of power in EU decision-making compared with big nations like
Germany, will also force the EU to tread lightly with Austria if it
wants to enlarge.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Haider sees the attacks by the EU as unfair and
politically motivated. In an interview, he said the EU's response
was orchestrated by the liberal Social Democrats, whom his party
threw out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Britain was initially reluctant to embrace the sanctions against
Austria. But now Foreign Secretary Robin Cook is saying that the
EU's aggressive intervention forced Haider and Schuessel to agree,
at President Thomas Klestil's insistence, to sign a pledge in which
they acknowledged Austria's complicity in the Third Reich and
committed the country to upholding human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we cease our fight against xenophobia and racism, then we
put at risk the union that has actually given Europe 50 years of
peace,'' Cook said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
