</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRACE-ASBESTOS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
W.R. GRACE CO. RESISTED ASBESTOS LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Attn.: Mont.; a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE APPEL AND NEIL SWIDEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   W. R. Grace Co. sold millions of bags of home attic insulation
that contained asbestos, but the company never warned the public,
documents obtained by The Boston Globe show.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Grace, whose Cambridge, Mass. Construction
Products Division oversaw Zonolite Attic Insulation until it was
discontinued in 1984, knew as far back as 1963 about the asbestos.
But they were worried that a warning label would hurt sales, memos
from high-ranking Grace officials show.
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos has been linked to several diseases, including lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Because there was no labeling requirement at the time, Grace did
not break the law. But documents show the company lobbied hard to
keep its product free from warning labels and scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In public testimony and letters to government regulators, Grace
executives consistently argued that the attic insulation was safe.
In internal memos, they:
</P>
<P>
   --Discussed such options for keeping regulators at bay as
``obstruct and block.''
</P>
<P>
   --Tracked mounting lung cancer deaths of workers at the Grace
mine and mill where the main ingredient used in the insulation came
from.
</P>
<P>
   --Drafted a press release in 1977, citing ``health hazards'' as
their reason for discontinuing the attic insulation. The release
was never issued, however, and Grace continued to sell the
insulation for seven more years.
</P>
<P>
   W. R. Grace, a $1.5 billion multinational chemical and
construction products company, was thrust into the spotlight by the
1995 book and 1999 movie ``A Civil Action.'' Both were based on a
1982 lawsuit concerning chemical contamination and high leukemia
rates in East Woburn.
</P>
<P>
   At least three government agencies knew there was asbestos in
Grace's attic insulation while it was on the market. Current
government officials have a hard time explaining why the agencies
did not do a better job of following up on their initial concerns
with Grace's product.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency warned in a 1981
study that consumers of products made from the mineral used in
Grace's attic fill ``may be particularly vulnerable and unprotected
due to ignorance of the potential hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until earlier this month that the EPA warned
homeowners to hold off on handling Grace's attic insulation,
believed to still be in thousands of homes.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA made its decision during its emergency investigation of
widespread asbestos contamination in Libby, Mont., where the
material used in the Grace insulation was mined and milled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recommend, to the extent possible, that you hold off on any
remodeling until we know about the asbestos content of the Zonolite
insulation and any potential health effects,'' the EPA said.
</P>
<P>
   Why it took the EPA nearly 20 years to issue a public warning is
unclear. ``That's a grand question,'' said Paul Peronard, the
coordinator of the EPA's Libby team.
</P>
<P>
   William Corcoran, Grace's vice president for public and
regulatory affairs, said, ``We didn't think the product was a
health hazard.'' Despite the new EPA warning, he said, Grace
officials continue to believe the product poses no risk.
</P>
<P>
   Zonolite is a loose-fill insulation that was poured between
attic rafters, under floor boards, and behind walls. It is made
from a gold-colored mineral called vermiculite, mined in Libby,
Mont., and processed at one of 32 plants around the country,
including one in Easthampton.
</P>
<P>
   Tremolite asbestos was naturally present in the Libby
vermiculite and the products made from it. Grace removed some, but
not all, of the asbestos, company memos show.
</P>
<P>
   Tremolite asbestos is a particularly dangerous form of the
mineral, said Dr. Jacqueline Moline, an occupational and
environmental health specialist at Mount Sinai School of Medicine.
Mesothelioma, a form of lung cancer linked to asbestos, can develop
from low exposures to tremolite, she said, ``the kind that women
got shaking out their husbands' clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   John Russell, a Cambridge, Mass. homeowner, recently spent three
days removing Zonolite insulation from his attic in preparation for
a renovation. He said he did not know the insulation contains
asbestos. Though he wore a mask, he said he would have been more
careful had he known about the asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disarming to learn at this late date how potentially
dangerous it is,'' he said, adding, ``I was surprised how long the
dust stayed in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said he does not know how he should dispose of the
insulation, which now sits in 20 or so garbage bags in his garage.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA estimated in 1985 that 940,000 American homes contained,
or had contained, Zonolite attic fill, and that Grace held about 85
percent of the market for vermiculite insulation. ``You open up a
wall and it pours out,'' said Eric Anderson, owner of Anderson
Insulation in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just blow right over it,'' said Janet Baronian, assistant
director of Menotomy Weatherization, an Arlington, Mass.
weatherization program for low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   All of Grace's Zonolite attic fill came from Libby vermiculite.
Vermiculite from other mines, including one operated by Grace in
Enoree, S.C., is used to make products such as cat litter and
potting soil. Those mines do not appear to be similarly
contaminated, according to Peronard, the EPA study coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos was once considered the most effective fireproofing
material available. But that changed dramatically by the mid-1970s,
as public fears grew about the health hazards of asbestos. As the
number of cases of ailments and diseases linked to the mineral
climbed, asbestos was ripped out of schools. Spackling compounds
and spray fireproofing that contained asbestos were banned, and
hair dryers with asbestos filters were voluntarily withdrawn from
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's Zonolite insulation, however, remained largely
untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran said that was because his company cooperated with
government agencies and was producing a safe product. ``We never
tried to hide it from anyone,'' he said. The only asbestos
standards in the 1970s were for workers, enforced by the
Occupational Safety and Health Administration. Zonolite Attic
Insulation was designed for consumers, he said, who would have
limited exposure to it compared with workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We complied with that OSHA target at our plants, but it's a
different exposure when Harry Homeowner is involved,'' Corcoran
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet OSHA cited Grace for excessive asbestos levels as early as
1976. That kind of violation involving a consumer product such as
Zonolite ``gives you an indication that there could be a problem
downstream, with other workers and consumers,'' said John Martonik,
director of OSHA's office of program evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Egilman, a clinical associate professor in the
Department of Community Health at Brown University, has been a paid
expert witness against the asbestos industry. Though he has not
testified against Grace, he has conducted extensive research on the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace has known about the hazards of asbestos since they
bought the mine in 1963. They knew the asbestos was there and how
toxic it was,'' said Egilman, who has worked a lengthy unit on
Grace into his medical ethics course. He added, ``They've engaged
in a coverup of the toxicity of their products and knowingly failed
to warn people for the purpose of making money and to avoid
lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Corcoran, ``We completely reject his theories.''
</P>
<P>
   A review of hundreds of company memos shows that Grace officials
argued publicly against tougher government standards while
privately discussing their concerns about liability and the
potential dangers associated with their product.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
