<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6425 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     02-14 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM STOCK JUST KEEPS SINKING AND ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Reform Party just keeps getting more pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   You might have figured that this political circus act founded by
Ross Perot had hit rock bottom when Pat Buchanan emerged as the
leading candidate for the party's presidential nomination. Or when
Donald Trump stepped forward as the most viable alternative to
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Reformers lost their top elected official and
only bona fide celebrity when Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura quit the
party and dismissed it as ``hopelessly dysfunctional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unworthy of my support and the support of the American
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's declaration that the Reform Party is unworthy of
support surely came as no shock to most Americans. The voters left
little doubt where they stood on the issue of the party's
worthiness when they all but ignored Perot's presidential candidacy
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, in fact, had fared much better when he ran as an
independent four years earlier. It was obvious to most Americans
that he conjured up the Reform Party for no reason except to prop
up his second run for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The party was a joke when Perot founded it, and it's still a
joke. Ventura was kind when he described the Reform Party as
``dysfunctional,'' since the term suggests that the party actually
functioned somewhere along the line.
</P>
<P>
   It never did. It never will.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we find ourselves caught up in an unproductive endeavor,
it is wise to cut our losses and move on,'' Ventura said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why so many Americans appreciate Ventura. He's no Rhodes
scholar, but he has ``common sense'' to spare.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-wrestler says he has no plans to run for president, but
he's been around the block. He knows that politicians who deny any
interest in running for president sometimes change their minds _
and he knows that only a fool would try to get himself elected
president on the Reform Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Which might tell us all we need to know about Pat Buchanan.
Donald Trump is another story; early reports Friday suggested that
he wouldn't seek the Reform nomination in the wake of Ventura's
desertion of the party.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it doesn't matter all that much whether the Reform
Party nominates Buchanan, Trump or even the party's founder and
resident scheming weasel, Ross Perot. This outfit will make no
meaningful contribution to the political process and will have no
impact on the presidential election in 2000 _ or any other year,
for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   The folks who keep trying to palm off the Reform Party as a
legitimate participant in the process would like us to believe that
the party was created for the purpose of providing voters with an
alternative to the policies of the Democratic and Republican
parties. But that's a difficult premise to buy into when you
consider that the Reform Party has no policies of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the Reformers' idea of an alternative is: ``We're
not them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's catchy. But it's not much for voters to hang their hats on,
policy-wise.
</P>
<P>
   One of the popular rationales for third parties and independent
candidacies in this country is that there's not a ``dime's worth of
difference'' between the Democrats and the Republicans. But that
complaint just doesn't hold up.
</P>
<P>
   It's plain to see, even at this early stage of the presidential
campaign, that on most issues Democrats and Republicans have very
different ideas and have very different approaches to solving the
nation's problems. And it's even plainer to see that the Democratic
president and the Republican leadership in Congress are miles
apart, not just in terms of partisan politics but in terms of their
beliefs about the appropriate role of government in the lives of
the American people.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that both parties need to be more responsive
to the people. But the people have the power to make them more
responsive by being more involved.
</P>
<P>
   The major parties will get better if the voters demand
improvement. The Reform Party will just keep getting more pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
