<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6430 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-REAR-WINDOW-BO     02-14 1581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-REAR-WINDOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW OPENING FOR `REAR WINDOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDFORD HILLS, N.Y. _ Robert Harris leans over a workbench in his
office, surrounded by strips and spools of film, unwinding one reel
until he finds the frame he's looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at this,'' he says, placing it under a magnifying
lens. It's the famous close-up near the beginning of Alfred
Hitchcock's ``Rear Window,'' where Grace Kelly leans over and
kisses a sleeping Jimmy Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The frame is from a print of the original 1954 negative. It's
grainy, dark _ you can barely see Stewart's face _ and drenched in
a murky yellow-green.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it looked like when we received it,'' Harris says.
``That's &UR;  &LR; what we were dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he shows me a print of the same frame after he and his
colleague, Jim Katz, were done with it. Stewart is in Kelly's
shadow, but his features are clear, flesh tones are natural, and
the background is well detailed. There's a crisp air to the image.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Harris says, with a satisfied grin, ``is what it's all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Katz are co-proprietors of the Film Preserve Ltd.,
located an hour's train ride north of Manhattan, and known as the
most fastidious firm involved anywhere in the art and science of
film restoration.
</P>
<P>
   There are other exceedingly careful workers in the field, most
notably at the Library of Congress, the UCLA Film Archives, the
Academy of Motion Pictures, and the Wright-Patterson Air Force Base
in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Pollock, chairman of the American Film Institute and a
former head of Universal Pictures, says of Harris and Katz,
``They're, by far, the best at what they do. They're
perfectionists.''
</P>
<P>
   Their restoration of ``Rear Window'' is their latest project _
sponsored, as is all their work, by the studio releasing it (in
this case, Universal) _ and when it opened last month at Film Forum
in Manhattan, critics were agog at its lifelike beauty. It opens
nationwide on Friday, when it will screen at the Brattle Theatre in
Cambridge, where it will run through Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Katz have restored just four other feature films in
the past 14 years _ ``Lawrence of Arabia'' (which Harris worked on
solo), ``My Fair Lady,'' ``Spartacus,'' and ``Vertigo.'' They spend
two years, day in and day out, on each project, at a cost to the
studio ranging from $650,000 (for the 35mm ``Rear Window'') to $1.2
million (for the wider-screen ``Vertigo'' and ``My Fair Lady'').
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of reissues called ``restorations'' out there,
but many are misleadingly labeled _ new prints of old films, maybe
scrubbed down a bit, but, Harris insists, ``They're not
`restorations.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do,'' he says of his own practice, ``is restore the
film from the ground up. We deal with problems on a shot-by-shot,
frame-by-frame basis. Our edict is to produce a new negative and a
new print that make the film look as much like it did when it first
came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Their purity often takes them to extremes. Unless they are kept
in cold, dry storage (and until a decade or so ago, they rarely
were), color films fade with time. So when Harris and Katz restored
Hitchcock's ``Vertigo,'' they obtained a chip from a 1957 green
Jaguar _ the car Kim Novak drives in the film _ in order to restore
the color to exactly the right shade of green. ``There's green, and
then there's green,'' Harris notes.
</P>
<P>
   When they did ``My Fair Lady,'' they went to Gene Allen, the
film's production designer, to find out the exact shade of white
used on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Rear Window,'' they found Georgine Darcy, the actress who
played the scantily clad dancer that Stewart watches frolicking in
her apartment across the way. She had kept the pink shorts she wore
in the film, and let Harris and Katz borrow them so they could get
that color exactly right.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no other film restorers go to such lengths. Ask Harris
why they bother, and he looks puzzled. ``If you know what you're
doing,'' he replies, ``why not do it right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude is, we're sitting down with the filmmaker and
we're saying, `Thank you for what you're done in making this film.
Here's some way of giving it back to you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 54, grew up in Scarsdale, N.Y. His father had friends in
the movie industry, and would receive cartons and cartons of 16mm
film reels, films from the '40s, which Harris would stay up and
watch all night. By age 10, he was a movie buff.
</P>
<P>
   He went to film school at New York University, got involved in
film distribution, and helped Kevin Brownlow piece together Abel
Gance's long-lost silent classic, ``Napoleon,'' the mother of all
film restorations and, as it turned out, a fabulous success.
</P>
<P>
   He developed a crusader's passion for saving old films. His
favorite was ``Lawrence of Arabia,'' which he knew had been
shortened from 222 minutes to 187. He wanted to find that missing
35 minutes and release it in full.
</P>
<P>
   The executives at Columbia, who didn't even know anything was
missing, let him into their vaults. He tracked down the film's
editor, Anne Coates, who put him in touch with the director, Sir
David Lean, who ended up working at his side.
</P>
<P>
   Around this time, Katz, who was president of Universal's
classics division, struck a deal with Alfred Hitchcock's estate to
reissue the five films _ ``The Man Who Knew Too Much,''
``Vertigo,'' ``Rope,'' ``The Trouble With Harry,'' and ``Rear
Window'' _ that had reverted to family ownership decades ago and
had been out of circulation ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a real ballyhoo, with big premieres that Jimmy
Stewart attended, but the thing that struck me,'' Katz recalls,
``was that the condition of these films was terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz had also just signed to release ``Napoleon,'' and met
Harris. When he started bemoaning the dreadful condition of the
Hitchcock films, Harris said he could do something about that.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, they became business partners. ``Bob's the technical
guy, I put the deals together,'' explains Katz, who also has a
production company in Hollywood. ``I have a lot more contacts than
he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Both are frustrated, mournful even, that the guardians of the
jewels, the heads of the studios, have shirked their
responsibilities over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``These films are antiques,'' Harris says. ``You can have a
Shakespeare folio that's 400 years old and, if you're careful, you
can turn the pages, you can read it. But you look at a film from
1964 _ it's fading, the perforations are cracked, it's falling
apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Some studios try. ``If you go through Universal's vaults, those
films are stored at 34 degrees Fahrenheit and 25 percent
humidity,'' he says. ``On the other hand, in 1986, at Columbia,
when I started `Lawrence,' the vaults were in a converted bowling
alley at 68 degrees. My jaw dropped. If you know anything about
photographic emulsion, you know that's too hot.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of the problems date back to a decision made by the
studios in the early 1950s. Until then, Technicolor movies were
shot on three strips of black-and-white film stock. The strips _
each containing the information for yellow, cyan, and magenta, the
full range of the color spectrum _ were run through three dyes and
then printed, one layer on top of another, in a way that
corresponded to the degrees of light and dark on the negative.
</P>
<P>
   The point here is that the original negatives were not in color,
and so, they have not faded.
</P>
<P>
   Making prints from these dyes was a slow process, however, and
in 1950, Eastman Kodak came up with a color film you could load
right in the camera. For a while, the studios continued to print
even Eastman film with Technicolor dyes, but, from then on, the
original negatives would be in color. And over time, they have
faded.
</P>
<P>
   With the ``Rear Window'' restoration, Harris took the Eastman
color negative, filtered it onto three separate strips of
black-and-white film stock _ the yellow, cyan, and magenta _ then
printed the mix with special dyes at Technicolor's lab.
</P>
<P>
   There were two remarkable things here. First, it marked the
first time anyone has used Technicolor's three-dye process since
Francis Ford Coppola shot ``The Godfather Part II'' in 1974.
Second, because the Eastman negative had faded, Harris and
Technicolor's engineers had to fiddle with the colors, varying the
degree of yellow, cyan, and magenta. And because the levels of
distortion on the negative were far from uniform, they had to alter
the mix hundreds of times _ ``literally from shot to shot,'' Harris
says.
</P>
<P>
   The studio vaults are apparently crammed with horror tales. The
original negative for ``Citizen Kane'' is gone, burned in a fire,
as is the three-strip Technicolor negative for ``Singing in the
Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   The disasters are not limited to vintage films. ``Chinatown''
and ``The Godfather'' are fading fast. The special effects for
``Star Wars,'' ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' and
``Superman'' were printed on a film stock that, it turned out,
fades after seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Studios are paying more attention to preservation than in the
past, partly because of the rise of DVDs, which have much sharper
images than laser discs or VHS tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hide a multitude of sins on video, which you can't
do so easily on DVD,'' Harris says. ``The question is, how long
will it take to rescue all these films? Will the rescue come too
late?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
