<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gertrude and Claudius'' by John Updike (Knopf, $23). Imagining
the back story to ``Hamlet,'' our contemporary Renaissance man
weaves the history of ideas into an intelligent novel of whimsy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonzero: The Logic of Human Destiny'' by Robert Wright
(Pantheon, $27.50). A broad and erudite survey of human cultural
evolution, arguing that we do indeed have the capacity to shape a
kindly future. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Missing World'' by Margot Livesey (Knopf, $23). A
psychological suspense story handled with acumen, a riveting sense
of timing, and a dazzlingly intelligent structure. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Enduring Roots'' by Gayle Brandow Samuels (Rutgers, $25).
These ``encounters with trees'' turn into meditations on the facts,
folklore, and myth connected with America's trees.
</P>
