<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE'S THORNY RED ROSES FOR HORNY VALENTINE'S LOVERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Valentine's Day)   (This 375-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
  
 By ALEX DUVAL SMITH  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE _ As most of the millions who are sending and receiving
roses for Valentine's Day today (Monday) know only too well, the
path of true love is a rough one.
</P>
<P>
   The rose growers of Zimbabwe, where many Valentine roses began
their journey, will tell you that the path from tropical farm to
British florist is not particularly smooth either.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Brown and his staff toiled for long days under the African
sun, overcame chronic diesel shortages caused by the country being
at war in the Congo, and had a brush with the airline hijacking at
Stansted Airport outside London.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might not think of rose growing as an exciting, breakneck
business but we have three days to get our roses from here to shops
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around Valentine's Day every minute counts,'' said Brown. He
manages 87 pickers and other staff on the 100-hectare (250-acre)
Bartlett Farm, situated 90km (60 miles) from Zimbabwe's capital,
Harare.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is immense. ``We have to deal with downy mildew,
powder mildew, red spider and aphids, and that is before we have
picked the roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when we think our problems are over, we hear of the
Stansted hijacking and planes being diverted. That kind of thing
can be a disaster for our timing,'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time in its 11 years of rose growing,
Bartlett Farm hit Valentine's Day ``spot on,'' said Brown. That
meant getting a peak number of red roses, as opposed to yellow,
pink or white, to early maturity and on to a cargo flight by last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The feat required impeccable timing but also the less
predictable cooperation of the sun. ``A week of overcast weather
can change everything,'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   So can the calendar: the weekend that has preceded the lovers'
feast this year means Zimbabwean roses on sale in Britain Monday
were cut last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The pickers emerge from their houses, walking through the long
grass surrounding the rose plantation, just as dawn gives way to
the first rays of sunlight at 6 a.m. They earn slightly more than
the minimum wage, but with housing and water provided by the farm.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment at record levels in Zimbabwe, most people are
just grateful for a job.
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
