<HEADER>
A6435 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-SOBIN-BOS &LR;      02-14 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SOBIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOBIN'S LUSH LANGUAGE BRINGS OUT THE SCENT OF TRUFFLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE FLY-TRUFFLER 
By Gustaf Sobin 
Norton, 155 pp., $19.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After his young wife dies, Philippe Cabassac, a middle-aged
professor of a dying Provencal language, loses interest in
everything except hunting for black truffles on the land his family
has owned for generations. From November through March he truffles
the age-old way, trying to spot the tiny flies that lay their eggs
in the earth just above the precious, richly-scented fungi.
</P>
<P>
   For Cabassac the truffles are more than just a winter delicacy.
Eating them enables him to enter a vivid dream world in which he is
reunited with Julieta.
</P>
<P>
   Gustaf Sobin is an American poet and novelist who has lived in
Provence for 35 years and clearly has come to know his adopted home
as intimately as any outsider could hope to. His style is
poetic &UR;  &LR; and &UR;  &LR; richly symbolic, so evocative of the Provencal
landscape that, reading certain passages, you can almost smell the
truffles.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time Sobin's poetic prose turns a tad purple, as in
this passage, when Cabassac imagines he and Julieta are making love
during a dream facilitated by ``an especially succulent truffle
omelette'': ``Slowly, languorously, without the least trace of
precipitation, they'd moved for hours, it seemed, cradled by a
rhythm as telluric as it was corporal. Like some kind of mild
earthen pulsation, that rhythm beat _ syncretic _ through their
very bodies. Throbbed, unabated, through the furthest reaches of
their being.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of ``The Fly-Truffler'' isn't as overwrought as that
particular paragraph, but Sobin's writing style does tend to the
exquisite. But his lush style suits his story, a haunted, haunting
tale of obsessive love.
</P>
<P>
   Cabassac first sees Julieta sitting in the back of the dark,
gloomy auditorium during his introductory lecture on Provencal
linguistics. For weeks he watches her in class: ``Taking note after
note, she'd glance up, occasionally, less with her eyes, it seemed,
than with her tall mineral forehead.''
</P>
<P>
   That tall mineral forehead may puzzle some readers (which
mineral?), but to Cabassac, it marks her as ``Alpine Provencal.''
Everything about her embodies the landscape he loves. She is
``redolent of altitude . . . spoke of rocks and cascades, of wild,
resinous stands of pinewood.''
</P>
<P>
   Julieta is an orphan, convent-reared, her background a mystery.
She is strangely quiet and passive, inspiring Cabassac to want to
``fill her with sound, sprinkle her long silences with a plethora
of spoken particles.''
</P>
<P>
   She tells Cabassac that she has always been drawn to the
mountains. Before long the two are living together platonically
(``His love had taken on the form of a chaste veneration from the
very first'') in his rambling old farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends they travel to Haute Provence, to persue a shared
passion for recording what Cabassac calls ``breath relics,''
vestiges of the old Gallo-Romanic language preserved in certain
high, isolated Alpine communities. They interview old men and
women, peasants, sheepherders, and silkworm farmers. Cabassac
realizes that Julieta has more than an academic interest in
linguistics. She is looking for her identity in the obsolescent
language.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably Cabassac's ``chaste veneration'' of Julieta falls
away. (What kind of story would this be if it didn't?) She becomes
pregnant. Everything changes. Cabassac is so besotted with Julieta
that he wants her all to himself. He hides an unworthy secret: He
resents the child she's carrying.
</P>
<P>
   Julieta miscarries, grieves, dies. Cabassac loses interest in
everyday life. He stumbles through his lectures. His classes
dwindle. He's forced to sell off his estate, piece by piece, to
support himself. He lives only for his truffle dreams of Julieta:
``Come those winter nights, he'd ingest a dark, savorous tuber and
enter what he himself called that dispousicioun. Dreaming entire
episodes _ whole glossy sequences that unreeled like film strip and
lasted, it seemed, like little eternities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fly-Truffler'' is not so much about love as about
obsession, a subject Sobin explored in his two previous novels,
``Venus Blue'' and ``Dark Mirrors.'' It's also about the limits of
communication and the power of secrets. (And it may be the first
novel that deals with the pathology of truffle abuse.) Mostly,
though, it's about Sobin's carefully crafted sensuous prose, which
is wonderful, if you like that sort of thing. If you don't, a
little goes a long way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
