<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6441 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-FAULKNER-BOS &LR;      02-14 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FAULKNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRACKING THE CITADEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
IN GLORY'S SHADOW 
Shannon Faulkner, The Citadel, and a Changing America 
By Catherine S. Manegold. Knopf. 352 pp. $26.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1993, perhaps on a whim, high school senior Shannon Faulkner
of Powdersville, S.C., applied to the all-male, state-supported
Citadel College. With the help of a guidance counselor and a little
White-out, Faulkner eliminated all mention of her gender in the
college application and her high school transcript.
</P>
<P>
   Unknowing Citadel officials sent Faulkner a letter of acceptance
that triggered an ugly, nearly three-year legal battle to allow her
to attend the school and march in the corps of cadets, which
Faulkner finally did briefly in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   All of that should be fodder for an interesting magazine article
and maybe a good book. But the problem with Catherine Manegold's
treatise, ``In Glory's Shadow: Shannon Faulkner, The Citadel and a
Changing America,'' is that the heroine is no Susan B. Anthony. Nor
is she very interesting.
</P>
<P>
   So Manegold, instead of writing about Faulkner and what she went
through to get into the school, turns this tale into a sweeping
history of the South, its military culture, and the men who led the
Citadel.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the story is no match for the way a similar
technique was used by Robert Timberg in ``The Nightingale's Song,''
the seminal work about five US Naval Academy graduates whose lives
intersected during Ronald Reagan's presidency and the Iran-Contra
scandal. Neither does it live up to the likes of Richard Ben
Cramer's ``What It Takes,'' the ultimate account of six men running
for president in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   I interviewed Faulkner in Powdersville for the Globe not long
after the Citadel realized it had mistakenly admitted a female to
the historically all-male school. Faulkner appeared awkward and
rather inarticulate, a simple teenager who never anticipated the
uproar her prank would spark.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why she had applied to the Citadel, Faulkner had
difficulty answering. When asked why she thought the Citadel should
include men and women in its bachelor's program, she was similarly
unresponsive. Her mother, on the other hand, was brimming with
enthusiasm for the coverage the story prompted.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Manegold's story recounts, the excitement of all that
attention turned quickly to fear for the Faulkners.
</P>
<P>
   There were anonymous, threatening letters. Hostile phone calls
bombarded the family. Bumper stickers proclaimed ``Save the
males.'' And then, as Faulkner gained weight, other bumper stickers
said ``Shave the whale.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brigadier, the campus newspaper, speculated on her
sexuality, suggesting she was a lesbian and then contending she was
romantically involved with a black cadet. Company marching chants
used lyrics that talked about electrocuting her. She was also
referred to as ``the divine bovine.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, a few days before Faulkner left Powdersville, a man
came up behind her in the grocery store, Faulkner said, putting his
hand over her mouth. He said, ``I can't touch you while you're on
that campus. But I can get to your parents. I know a place where I
can watch them burn.''
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy and exhausting legal battle that went all the
way to the US Supreme Court and cost the Citadel $10 million, the
gates opened, and Faulkner was allowed on campus as a cadet. She
had her own room, a private bathroom, and protection from federal
marshals.
</P>
<P>
   And then, Faulkner remembers hearing the voice of the man from
the grocery store again: ``The heat in Charleston makes some folks
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   She never figured out who said it. But that incident may have
been the point at which Faulkner's will to fight the forces arrayed
against her faltered, according to Manegold. She didn't even last a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner spent most of her five days in the infirmary, suffering
from heat exhaustion and stress. Eventually, she decided to leave
and the men on campus exulted, singing, ``Hey, hey, the witch is
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' Faulkner told her supporters. ``All I can say is
I have to think about my own health right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Other women cadets have since followed her, the first graduating
last year. As for Faulkner, she finally graduated herself last year
from Anderson College, 200 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jill Zuckman covers politics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6442 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-KIDS-BOS &LR;      02-14 1610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE OF THE BEST TV SHOWS FEATURE BELIEVABLE YOUNG PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the life of your average preteen or teenage kid were a TV
show, there would be no shortage of storylines.
</P>
<P>
   There's first love, of course, often followed by first
heartbreak. School corridors are filled with rival cliques that
carry on like Montagues and Capulets, and daily life is charged by
collisions with parents and other authority figures. On a regular
basis, kids taste the thrill of victory or the agony of defeat on
the soccer field, in the classroom, or on the dance floor. All of
this, of course, occurring in a context of excruciating
self-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   In short, puberty and adolescence furnish no end of raw material
for drama, not to mention awkward slapstick moments of comedy (that
are not usually a laughing matter at the time). Oddly enough,
though, television has historically shown only sporadic interest in
the dramatic and even comedic possibilities of those turbulent
years, largely relegating preteens and teenagers to supporting
roles in family programs.
</P>
<P>
   This season, though, kids occupy center stage in two of the best
new shows on television: NBC's ``Freaks and Geeks'' and Fox's
``Malcolm in the Middle,'' and are playing an increasingly
prominent role in another new gem, ABC's ``Onceand Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, the three programs don't have much in common.
``Malcolm in the Middle'' is a gonzo comedy, ``Once and Again'' is
an introspective relationship drama, and ``Freaks and Geeks'' is a
quirky hybrid of sitcom humor and emotional poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   But what the three share is a gallery of richly individual
portraits of believable kids _ unlike, say, the miniature adults
who inhabit teen soap operas such as ``Beverly Hills 90210'' and
``Dawson's Creek,'' or the superwoman fantasy of ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' _ and an honest effort to look at an
often-confusing world from a youthful point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Not so incidentally, all three programs feature some of the most
talented and appealing young stars to light up the small screen
since the mid-1990s heyday with the likes of Fred Savage (``The
Wonder Years'') and Claire Danes (``My So-Called Life'').
</P>
<P>
   One of them is 14-year-old John Daley, who plays geeky but
soulful high school freshman Sam Weir in ``Freaks and Geeks.'' In a
telephone interview, Daley said the strength of the program is that
``we cover a lot of the topics you'll find in a high school, and we
talk like kids, not adults, in the way things are expressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not dealing with birth-control problems; we're dealing
with bully problems,'' said Daley.
</P>
<P>
   To 10-year-old Meredith Deane, who plays Zoe Manning on ``Once
and Again,'' it's only logical that stories spotlighting the
younger characters have begun cropping up more and more in what
began as a show about middle-aged love. After all, Deane said, in
her age group ``there's so many things going on. There's the
transfer to middle school. There's divorce. There's all kinds of
preteen issues for girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Muniz, the 14-year-old actor who plays the title
character, a child genius, of ``Malcolm in the Middle,''
emphatically believes that his and other current shows are ``more
real'' depictions of childhood and adolescence than the standard TV
fare of ``perfect families singing carols to their grandma in front
of the Christmas tree.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking back and ahead
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, the creators of the three new shows _ baby
boomers all _ said they were drawn partly by the opportunity to
portray youngsters more realistically, and partly by the chance to
create stories that comment on their own youth or on the lives of
their children.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Feig, the 37-year-old creator of ``Freaks and Geeks,''
acknowledged that he modeled the character of Sam on himself. But
he also draws freely from the young cast. ``Half the time I'll be
hanging around on the set, listening to the kids,'' he said. ``They
tell me `I'm afraid to say or do anything because it will end up in
the script.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sam has a crush on an unattainable girl _ a crush that Neal, one
of Sam's fellow geeks, advises him to drop. ``She's a
cheerleader,'' he explains. ``You've seen `Star Wars' 27 times. Do
the math.''
</P>
<P>
   In another episode, the ``freaks'' are so desperate to get into
a bar to see a hot rock band that they purchase fake IDs from a
scary ex-con. Meanwhile, the ``geeks'' befriend a pretty new girl
in school and are giddy that she wants to spend time with them,
only to see her slowly but surely abandon them for the company of
the jocks and cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, adolescence. ``It's a time when your emotions are at their
highest _ and your worldview is at its most narrow _ and it's
excusable,'' remarked Feig. ``It's much easier for me to summon up
the feelings I had then than it is to write about grown-up
feelings. I write about things that were terrible at the time, but
can be funny now.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar approach is taken by Linwood Boomer, creator of
``Malcolm in the Middle,'' a midseason show that has exploded into
a top-10 hit. Like the title character, Boomer was labeled
``gifted'' as a child, which led to ``one of the truly worst times
in my life, not funny at all at the time. But if you think about
most comedies, it wouldn't be funny happening to a real person.''
</P>
<P>
   From his childhood travail, the now-43-year-old Boomer has drawn
the material for an uproariously funny comedy. Malcolm is ashamed
of his 165 IQ and wants nothing more than to be a regular kid, but
no such luck. A teacher solicitously spells it out to the rest of
his class: ``Malcolm may not look different than the rest of us,
but he is. Verydifferent . . . in his brain.'' At a science fair
where Malcolm does a dazzling series of computations involving
numbers from credit cards, one classmate sighs: ``Following you is
like following Streisand.'' His normally voluble family is stunned
into silence by Malcolm's brilliance. ``Is Malcolm a robot?'' asks
his kid brother.
</P>
<P>
   Boomer said adolescence is fertile terrain for comedy or drama
because it's ``that time when you've got all the physical powers of
an adult, and none of the common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fork in the road
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That duality can lead to pratfalls, as in ``Malcolm,'' or it can
lead to intense soul-searching. That's where Edward Zwick comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Zwick, along with fellow ``thirtysomething'' creator Marshall
Herskovitz, helped pioneer the teen-angst genre with ``My So-Called
Life'' in 1994. The program made a star out of Claire Danes, who
played 15-year-old Angela Chase, and legitimized teenage life as
the stuff of serious drama, with plots involving guns in school,
the harassment of a gay student, and Angela's sexual awakening.
</P>
<P>
   But ``My So-Called Life'' lasted only half a season before being
canceled. So when Zwick and Herskovitz began writing ``Once and
Again,'' a drama about the romance between two divorcees, they knew
from the start that the program would place increasing emphasis on
14-year-old Grace and 9-year-old Zoe Manning, the daughters of Lily
Manning, and on Rick Sammler's two children, 16-year-old Eli and
12-year-old Jessie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt there was still a lot more to say,'' said Zwick, 47.
``To be the parents of older children, as both Marshall and I are,
and to spend a disproportionate amount of time thinking and talking
about that: We wanted to write about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, adolescence is a universal experience with
which viewers can identify. ``In every life, not only in a writer's
life, those years have a kind of lasting resonance,'' he said.
``Witness the number of people who evoke high school as the seminal
moment, even sometimes the defining moment, of their lives. It's a
time when everything is amplified: your passions, your fears,
connections, alienation. You're in a kind of hormonally induced
hallucination.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks on ``Once and Again,'' little Zoe learned that
her parents were getting a divorce on Christmas Eve at the same
moment she made another devastating discovery. Virtually an entire
episode was devoted to Eli's attempts (ultimately unsuccessful) to
find a sensitive way to break up with his girlfriend. On numerous
episodes, the children's uncertainty and tentativeness is matched
and mirrored by their parents' own faltering attempts at romance: a
subtle reminder that in some ways, we all remain teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   But as good as these shows are, they won't survive long without
an audience. For instance, ratings are ominously (and inexplicably)
low for the irresistible ``Freaks and Geeks''; it currently ranks
103d out of 154 shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teenagers loved `My So-Called Life,' but it could not draw
older viewers,'' observed Alex McNeil, the author of ``Total
Television.'' ``You have to have another segment of the viewing
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Nielsen has in store for them in the long term, the
fact that ``Freaks and Geeks,'' ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' and
``Once and Again'' are on the air is heartening to Robert J.
Thompson, author of ``Television's Second Golden Age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These blue-chip creators have finally begun to realize that
this is a great place to tell American stories,'' said Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing it took television so long to figure out we
shouldn't be doing just cop shows or hospital shows or detective
shows,'' he added. ``The clash between generations in the year
2000: I can think of few stories that are more interesting, more
potentially dramatic, and more universal than these stories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
