<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-TATE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TATE GALLERY, NEW BRANCH RADIATE ENERGY OF A MODERN MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Christoph Grunenberg was rather ungraciously forced out
of his position as curator of Boston's Institute of Contemporary
Art last year. After a couple of figurative somersaults, he landed
quite gracefully on two feet, at the Tate Gallery, where, since
September, he's been curator of contemporary collections.
</P>
<P>
   He's moved from farm team to the major leagues. The ICA
currently has 13 full-time employees, a schedule of half a dozen
shows a year, annual attendance of 75,000, and a plan (which some
knowledgeable observers feel is iffy) to build a new waterfront
facility. The Tate staff is 500 strong; the main museum at Millbank
in London's Westminster mounts a half-dozen shows at any one time,
along with jaw-dropping displays of the permanent collections.
Millbank attendance is 2.4 million annually, with another million
visiting the museum's branches in Liverpool and St. Ives, and more
than two million more expected to visit the new Tate Modern, which
will open in May in the former Bankside Power Station on the South
side of the Thames.
</P>
<P>
   Millbank, now undergoing its own dramatic expansion, will house
the museum's collection of British art, 1500 to the present; the
Tate Modern will present Britain's national collection of
international modern and contemporary art, plus a menu of temporary
shows. A shuttle boat on the Thames will ferry visitors the mile
and a half from one Tate to the other _ not a perfect solution, but
there wasn't an eligible site or structure any nearer to Millbank.
Harvard, which hopes to build a new Renzo Piano-designed museum in
Cambridge, Mass., will doubtless keep a close eye on how the double
venue works out for the Tate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tate's ambition is to be one of the top three or four
modern museums in the world,'' says Grunenberg, sitting in his
spacious corner office located in a historic building adjacent to
the Millbank museum, which is bursting at the seams. ``It's not as
big a collection as the Museum of Modern Art's or the Guggenheim's.
But the only modern art museum in competition with it in Europe is
the Centre Pompidou'' in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   German by birth, Grunenberg, 37, is no stranger to London,
having trained at the city's famed Courtauld Institute, where the
Tate's dynamo director, Nicholas Serota, also studied. Grunenberg's
special subjects were the American painter Mark Rothko and the
history of the white cube as the classic setting for 20th-century
art. At the Tate, he revisits both. He'll be in charge of
installing the series of nine magisterial burgundy and black
Rothkos the artist gave to the Tate after deciding that their
intended setting, the Four Seasons restaurant in the Seagram
Building in New York, wasn't sufficiently spiritual. One room at
the Tate Modern will be designed around them, and the BBC is doing
a special solely on the Rothkos _ which arrived at the Tate the
very day the artist committed suicide, in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Grunenberg's brief Boston career? He was hired
by former director Milena Kalinovska, whose replacement, current
director Jill Medvedow, ``has a serious lack of affinity for
contemporary culture,'' Grunenberg says. ``She didn't support my
commitment to international programming and to an interchange with
contemporary popular culture.'' She also brought in another
curator, Jessica Morgan, in effect shunting him aside. It was clear
that Grunenberg and Medvedow couldn't work together. (Medvedow
declined to comment on Grunenberg for this story.) He applied for
other Boston curatorial vacancies. Then the call came from the
Tate.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the two institutions are extreme. ``At a
small institution like the ICA there's an improvisational, hectic
pace,'' he says. ``You can't do things thoroughly. You just get the
show up on the walls. Here, the schedule is planned three to four
years ahead of time and there are archives, libraries, and
conservation and publications departments to back up curators.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunenberg is in the Tate's collections department, which means
he's in charge of the contemporary part of the permanent collection
_ maintaining and installing it, as well as adding to it, both by
shopping and through the bequests in lieu of inheritance taxes that
British law allows. The Tate recently acquired a Brancusi and
Mondrian through the bequest law. The Tate's collections are its
collateral, and make getting loans from sister museums fairly
simple. ``Because the ICA doesn't collect and has nothing to offer
in exchange,'' Grunenberg says, ``getting loans there is a
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the Tate generates excitement over new
art in a way Grunenberg's former employer never has been able to.
The Rachel Whiteread show he organized, one of the finest the ICA
has ever presented, attracted a scant 3,000 visitors. His 1997
``Gothic'' show, a complex meditation on the macabre, drew only
6,000, despite its obvious appeal to youthful followers of ``Goth''
culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Tate has no such attendance problems for new art, especially
around the time of the annual Turner Prize show, which draws well
over 100,000 visitors a year and is reliably controversial. The
winner of the $32,000 award _ this year, it's 30-year-old filmmaker
Steve McQueen _ _ is announced, Academy Awards-style, on live TV.
``There was one week during this year's show of the short-listed
artists when you couldn't turn on the television without hearing
about it,'' says Grunenberg, who is about to take over the Tate's
Patrons of New Art, the group that started the Prize in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   It was the unmade panty-hose-strewn bed at the heart of Tracey
Emin's installation that sent viewers over the edge at this year's
show, which closed last week. Maybe it offended the British love of
tidiness? Grunenberg doesn't think it was the implication of sex.
The British public, he says, doesn't get riled up over sexual art.
</P>
<P>
   Britons thought the American reaction to ``Sensation!,'' the
show of work by young British artists that caused the mayor of New
York to threaten to close down the Brooklyn Museum, ``was
typical,'' Grunenberg says. ``It reinforced the stereotype about
American puritanism. It was very telling that the fuss was over
religion'' _ over Chris Ofili's painting of the Virgin with knobs
of dung affixed to it. ``That's a shift in the culture wars. It
used to be sex that caused controversy in America. Now you can show
work that is actually obscene.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tate, partly through Serota's vigorous efforts, has
developed the kind of global constituency an institution such as
Boston's Museum of Fine Arts, perceived as ``regional,'' can only
envy _ and will have to develop to carry out its own ambitious
expansion plans. The Tate's International Council includes 100 top
collectors, ``the creme de la creme,'' Grunenberg calls them,
including a number of Americans. (No members from Boston yet.)
</P>
<P>
   When he left London in 1993, ``it was still a hostile place for
contemporary art,'' Grunenberg recalls. ``It's changed enormously,
with loads of new galleries and much more serious arts coverage in
the press, which used to be notably philistine.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
