<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Feb. 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Grozny) _ Russian authorities shut down the
capital city. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ASSESS (Jakarta) _ A news analysis on the political
confrontation between President Abdurrahman Wahid and General
Wiranto. The president fired the military chief from the Cabinet
just hours after saying the general could stay. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-TERROR (Istanbul) _ A burgeoning scandal stemming from
the breakup of a religious terror group has led to accusations that
the group may have received weapons from the Turkish government. By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-HIJACK (London) _ Developments on the hijackees-turned
asylum-seekers. Seventy-three people returned home to a hero's
welcome in Afghanistan on Monday, but 74 remained in Britain,
awaiting the government's decision on whether to grant them asylum.
By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHASIA-RIGHTS (United Nations) _ Human rights organizations
and Asian diplomats, watching India and Pakistan battle over the
attention of President Clinton as he plans his trip to South Asia
in March, question why the focus of debate is on the rights and
democracy record of Pakistan _ and whether Pakistan should be
declared a terrorist state _ when India has been involved in
fomenting insurrections in the region for decades and has one of
the worst human rights records of any democracy. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-CRASH (Washington) _ What is going on with the MD-80
style airplanes? By Matthew L. Wad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GA-STORMS (Camilla, Ga.) _ Tornadoes slash through southwest
Georgia, killing at least 12 people and injuring more than 100. A
housing development here was hard hit. ``It's like somebody took a
bulldozer and leveled it,'' a volunteer firefighter said.
Developing. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-TEENS-SHOT (Denver) _ Two teen-agers are found shot to
death at a sandwich shop just two blocks from Columbine High
School, the scene of a massacre last year in which 15 people were
killed, police said. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Developments at the trial: The
New York City officers accused in the shooting death of an unarmed
man begin their testimony. By Jane Fritsch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SC-REPUBS (Dateline to kum, S.C.) _ The Republican party settles
a primary dispute with the Justice Department, agreeing to pay the
state board of elections to run the primary. The move will be
costly, but will ensure that polling precincts are open everwhere.
By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY (San Francisco) _ Bill Bradley attacks Al Gore on
environmental By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Dateline to kum, S.C. ) _ With George W. Bush in South
Carolina. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes along the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DRY-CLEANERS (Undated) _ For more than a decade, the dry
cleaning business has looked like a tantalizing opportunity for
environmentally minded entrepreneurs. Despite increasing
regulations not to mention criticism from groups like Greenpeace
and Consumers Union, a vast majority of the nation's roughly 33,000
dry cleaners persist in using toxic chemicals linked to cancer,
nervous system ailments and other health hazards. ``Green
cleaners'' using water and new biodegradable detergents sprang up
in many communities in the 1990s. But few existing dry cleaners
were inclined to switch because ``wet cleaning'' takes longer,
increases labor costs and can easily lead to shrinkage or other
quality problems. Now the green spotlight is being claimed by
Hangers Cleaners, which is trying to sell the industry and its
customers on a radically different technology. A look at the
hurdles Hangers has encountered underscores how constant
improvements in existing technology and numerous other competitive
wrinkles can slow environmental innovation, even in industries that
look simple to outsiders. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-APPOINT (New York) _ Merrill Lynch names chief financial
officer E. Stanley O'Neal to be president of its U.S. private
client group, putting the former investment banker in charge of
day-to-day operation. O'Neal, 48 and one of the highest ranking
African-Americans on Wall Street, replaces John L. Steffens, who
has been promoted to the new post of chairman. O'Neal becomes the
first non-broker to run the brokerage firm. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were mixed in mid-afternoon trading.
At 2:10 p.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 66
points, the S&AMP;P 500 down 3 points and the Nasdaq composite index
down 29 points. Treasury prices were slightly higher. European
stock markets were slightly higher for the most part, except
London, which was down 2.33 percent. The Nikkei closed down 0.78
percent; Hong Kong, down 1.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MAYTAG-OUTLOOK (Chicago) _ Maytag warns that it expects
first-quarter profit to fall more than analysts had expected as the
company spends more money on research, development and Internet
commerce. Its shares fall 6 percent. By David Barboza/
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHEON-ACQUIRE (Undated) _ Healtheon/WebMd will pay about
$4.9 billion in stock for software maker Medical Manager Corp., and
its subsidiary, CareInsite Inc., Healtheon's largest rival in the
race to link doctors, patients and insurers through the Internet.
By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-TELECOM (Singapore ) _ Looking at a possible battle for
Cable &AMP; Wireless's Hong Kong unit. C&AMP;W says it is still talking
with Singapore Telecommunications about a possible merger. A
possible spoiler, Pacific Century CyberWorks of Hong Kong,
meanwhile, says it plans to raise as much as $1 billion in a share
sale to help finance a merger with Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT Ltd. By
Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-TAKEOVER (Tokyo) _ A deal that was billed as Japan's first
indigenous hostile takeover, the effort by Yoshiaki Murakami, a
former government official, to take over the Shoei Co., has ended
in what Americans would call a failure. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
