<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, Feb. 15,
2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   STORMS-GEORGIA _ CAMILLA, Ga. _ Tornadoes slashed through
southwest Georgia early today, killing at least 12 people and
injuring more than 100. The Mitchell County town of Camilla
appeared to be hardest hit, with tornadoes cutting a 5-mile path
through a housing development south of town. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STORMS-SOUTH _ The killer tornadoes that struck Georgia early
Monday grew out of a line of thunderstorms that swept across the
South during the night and by morning extended all along the East
Coast. Thunderstorms also ripped off roofs and knocked down trees
in parts of Alabama, and earlier strong wind destroyed at least six
houses in Arkansas and injured two people. Trees and power lines
also were down in parts of Mississippi and Tennessee, where one
woman was injured by wind-blown debris. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STORMS-WEATHER _ How these storms formed. How unusual is it to
have mid-Feb tornadoes? Any relationship to mild winter? (Morris,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   STORMS-MOBILEHOMES _ Mobile home storm safety. Does Georgia
require tiedowns, as some states do? If not, why not? What lessons
from other states? Are there any tips for surviving in a mobile
home except to leave? And if you leave, where can you go? (Davis,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STORMS-SCENE _ Color on physical damage, probably centered on
devastated neighborhood in Camilla, Ga. (Harvey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15,2
</P>
<P>
   STORMS-WARNING _ How much warning did hard-hit areas have? The
National Weather Service had the area under at least a tornado
watch earlier. Are there sirens? Does NWS weather alert radio
system cover these areas? A state commission was formed after '98
tornadoes and grants are being made now for sirens and weather
radios. Any of this in the hit areas? (Harvey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-HEARING _ ATLANTA _ A bond hearing was held Monday for
Baltimore Ravens All Pro linebacker Ray Lewis in the post-Super
Bowl double slaying in Atlanta. Defense called Ray's mom and other
witnesses who say Ray is a good person. Also, Joseph Sweeting
turned himself in before noon EST today. He was accompanied by two
lawyers. His first appearance hearing will be Tuesday at 8 a.m.
EST. (Longa, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB-BEHINDTHESCENES _ Jim Cash is in his small, windowless
laboratory on the sixth floor of the nondescript Washington office
building where the National Transportation Safety Board is
headquartered. Cash is the NTSB man who listens to the cockpit
voice recorder _ one of two ``black boxes'' that collect voice and
mechanical data on commercial aircraft. A behind the scenes look at
the man who listens for the sound of disaster. (Reid, Plam Beach
Post). 77. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE-ADVANCE _ Advancer for tonight's GOP debate in South
Carolina. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE-LARRYKING _ Larry King: The wives, the suspenders, the
heart attacks, the schmoozing. King may get knocked for not being a
tough enough interviewer, but he defends his style quite
adequately. A look at this 66-year-old TV institution, based on an
interview in Los Angeles, who celebrates his 15th anniversary on
CNN in June, as he prepares to moderate the Tuesday night's GOP
presidential debate in South Carolina. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (l) Lifestyle and (a) General News categories.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ Gov. George W. Bush campaigns in South Carolina Monday as
the candidates hit the home stretch before Saturday's primary.
Developing. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FLIGHTS _ WASHINGTON _ Evan as George W. Bush attacks John
McCain's credentials as a reformer, federal records studied by the
Center for Responsive Politics show he accepted more than twice as
many flights on corporate planes borrowed from 35 companies.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MONEY _ WASHINGTON - Florida is shaping up to be a key
state in this year's battle to determine which party will control
the next Congress. with chart material (Lipman, Cox News Service).
15.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-INTELLIGENCE _ WASHINGTON _ Representatives from eight
federal agencies release the General Counter-drug Intelligence Plan
in response to congressional mandates. National Drug Control Policy
Director Barry McCaffrey and Attorney General Janet Reno speak.
(Turay, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
