<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following feature
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients for use Tuesday,
Feb. 15. For questions about stories, please contact Steve
Rosenberg at the Daily News, (818) 713-3752.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-RIBISI-FEATURE _ The sleepy-eyed Giovanni Ribisi is wide
awake when it comes to his movie career. At the age of 25, he has
already been a crack medic in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' a
parenthood-obsessed brother to Phoebe in ``Friends,'' and a
mentally challenged man in ``The Other Sister.'' We can almost
forget about ``The Mod Squad,'' especially now that Ribisi is
playing a cutthroat, cold-calling stockbroker in ``Boiler Room.''
By Bob Strauss (story moving on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-VAGINA-MONOLOGUES _ Playwright Eve Ensler says ``The
Vagina Monologues'' is ``all about talking about, discussing and
remembering vaginas.'' For the play's Los Angeles performance on
Wednesday, Hollywood A-list types are lining up to be in it:
Gillian Anderson, Roseanne, Winona Ryder, Calista Flockhart and
Melissa Etheridge are taking part in the Wiltern Theatre show. By
Marla Matzer Rose (story moving on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   OLDER-YOUNGER _ At 44, Van Nuys writer Leah Komaiko thought life
was passing her by. ``I thought, `Is this all there is?''' Leah
said. ``What a letdown. Do we just sit and wait to get old?'' Then
she volunteered to visit an older woman in a local nursing home, a
woman who was blind. Now, three years later, Leah feels young again
and knows it's her friendship with Adele, 96, that's keeping her
that way. By Carol Bidwell (story moving on the ``l'' lifestyle
wire). ART IS MOVING TO NYTNS CLIENTS.
</P>
</TEXT>
