<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6475 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CARNEGIE-HOME-COX     02-14 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARNEGIE-HOME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `You don't own a house like this... you get to live in it a
while and then pass it on.'
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ John and Kay Ziegler made Lucindia their
permanent home in 1997, almost three-quarters of a century from the
time William Carnegie _ nephew of steel tycoon Andrew Carnegie _
built the house on a 35-foot rise above the St. Lucie River in
1924.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Zieglers are only the home's sixth owners, they
view their time at Lucindia this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't own a house like this,'' says John Ziegler. ``You're
a trustee and you get to live in it awhile and then pass it on,
hopefully, to someone who'll appreciate the tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   And a grand tradition it is.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, their home was the crowning jewel of 50 acres of
prime Sewall's Point land that stretched from the St. Lucie River
to the Indian River (hence the name Lucindia, a hybrid of the
rivers' names). During the property's early years, William and
Alice Carnegie added 10-acre parcels here and there until they had
fashioned a grand estate, complete with a packinghouse, boathouse,
guest and caretakers' houses, a greenhouse, pool and poolhouse.
There was even a windmill.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing their own quarters was a little more complicated. Soon
after the Carnegies bought the first acres of land in 1923, they
built a grand, formal mansion. Almost immediately afterward, they
fell in love with what was to become known historically as
``Mizner-style'': Mediterranean-like stucco homes with barrel-tile
roofs, pecky cypress woodwork and wrought-iron hardware designed by
famed Palm Beacher Addison Mizner.
</P>
<P>
   So the Carnegies tore down their first home and commissioned
architect Jack Yates to design a new one. Yates included many
Mizneresque touches, from exposed pecky cypress ceiling beams to
odd-shaped windows and doors. All of the wrought ironwork in the
house was made in Mizner's own factory.
</P>
<P>
   Although subdivision of the estate began in the 1960s (Lucindia
is now a 3-acre parcel), that ironwork has survived, from sconces
and chandeliers to hinges and gates. So have the cypress beams of
the living room, the oak floors and a 40-foot gumbo limbo tree in
the back yard _ rare to see at that size.
</P>
<P>
   The Zieglers credit longtime Lucindia residents Marjorie and Bud
Jordan _ well-known champions of the St. Lucie River's fragile
ecosystem _ with maintaining the home's character while improving
its use. The Jordans lived in the home for nearly 20 years, just
prior to the man who sold it to the Zieglers after a brief stay.
They added a two-story, glassed-in sun porch that floods the
original living room with light. They turned two small, separate
kitchens into one big one with a built-in breakfast nook and a view
of the river, an ideal renovation for John Ziegler, who loves to
cook. And they turned two bedrooms into a master suite with a
whirlpool tub that overlooks the river.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Lucindia has become a tranquil retreat for the
Zieglers, who also maintain homes in New York, Michigan and London.
John Ziegler, president of the National Hockey League from 1977 to
1992, is semi-retired, but still works as a sports business
consultant. But he finds it harder and harder _ especially at this
time of year _ to visit his office in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised by (this) lifestyle, in terms of the
tempo, coupled with the weather,'' he says. Lucindia allows him _
maybe even forces him _ to slow down and relax, slip on boat shoes
and putter around the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Lucindia also works its magic on Kay, an antiques appraiser who
spent 11 years as a flight attendant for Pan Am's presidential
charters. She worked on airplanes that ferried White House staff,
the Secret Service and press corps, a demanding job that took her
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   At Lucindia, life is quieter. She tends to roses beside the pool
and plays with the King Charles spaniels she breeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wake up here in the morning,'' she says, ``And you just
feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Graulich writes for the Palm Beach Post. e-mail:
heathergraulich(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
