<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 
 &HT;     Winnie the Pooh CD-ROM shows learning can be fun 
 
 &HT;    By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winnie the Pooh is one of the co-stars of Walt Disney's ``The
Tigger Movie.'' The honey-loving bear is the star of a new CD-ROM:
Disney's Activity Center, Winnie the Pooh. The CD (Windows,
Macintosh; about $30) is designed for children age 6 and up. It's
based on ``The Blustery Day,'' the third story in A.A. Milne's
``The Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the company's popular activity-center series, Winnie
the Pooh features arcade-style games, problem-solving activities
and reading. There are six separate activities, most of which have
multiple levels of difficulty:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tigger's Hillside Hop is for one or two players. Tigger and
Rabbit compete in a bouncing/hopping contest to collect presents.
</P>
<P>
   _ Come Fly a Piglet is a side-scrolling arcade-type game in
which kids help Pooh fly Piglet through the Hundred Acre Wood.
Piglet must navigate around debris while kids must lead Pooh over
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Find the Bees is an animated story. Parents can read along
with children and help them find hidden bees. At the end of the
story, Pooh tells players whether they've found all the bees. The
next time the child plays the game, the number of bees increases to
keep it interesting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eeyore's House Hunt helps develop logical reasoning as
children try to build a bridge across the river by using building
blocks from the stream.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heffalumps and Woozels (the animals Pooh dreams about when
he's asleep) is a matching game, also designed to build logic
skills, that lets children design a Heffalump. Their goal is to
determine which Heffalump doesn't match others on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Owl's Decorating lets children select and place items for
decorating Owl's new tree house.
</P>
<P>
   The program is on the shelves now, and will be joined Feb. 25 by
Disney's first venture into the 3-D arena, Disney's 3-D Adventure,
Tigger's Family Tree.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor at The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com.)
</P>
