<HEADER>
A6520 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     02-14 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 
 Cartoon Network runs afoul of China's doctrine
 &HT;    By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dan Quayle can rail all he wants about the TV show Murphy Brown,
but when it comes to censorship, nobody can touch the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the government in Beijing banned the broadcasting of
the highly subversive Cartoon Network on Chinese television.
</P>
<P>
   How Scooby-Doo and the Smurfs found themselves on the Communist
Party hit-list is a bit of a mystery, according to a Reuters story.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner, who manages to annoy just about everyone, including
his wife, and Time Warner Inc., which owns Turner Broadcastings TNT
&AMP; Cartoon Network, has also had a bumpy relationship with the
Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman in Hong Kong for Turner Broadcasting System
Asia Pacific said the company was given no reason for the ban,
which took effect last month. ``Their actions violated relevant
Chinese rules,'' said an official with China's State Administration
of Radio, Film and Television. ''They know very well what they
did,'' he said, without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, leaves it to the decadent,
counter-revolutionary, hegemonistic, running-dog Western press (me)
to speculate on the real reasons behind this ban.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, I would just like to say that Cartoon Network is
the best thing on TV, with the possible exception of Judge Wapner
and that crazy Australian guy who wrestles the crocodiles. Space
Ghost has a Fellini-esque quality about it and Cow &AMP; Chicken has
distinctly Orwellian overtones, only with more sight gags. It is
all well worth the $275 a month, or whatever, that Time Warner now
charges me for its basic cable service.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to one possible problem the Chinese may have
with bringing decadent, imperialistic American cable-TV into their
country: The cost. A month of cable service now costs more than the
average Chinese spends on cigarettes in a year, and that does not
include the cost of installation, TV-Guide subscriptions, universal
remote controls, VCRs, DVD players and, of course, one or more
large, flat-screen digital TVs.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting around for days at a time for a service technician to
hook up the cable would also result in a severe decline in
productivity, something the Chinese government cannot afford if it
is to successfully accomplish the Great Leap Forward, or sideways
or up-and-down or whatever direction China's leaders say the
country should be leaping these days.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the matter of the content of the shows on Cartoon
Network, some of which may run afoul of official Communist
doctrine, such as it is at this particular moment. The Flintstones
is one of the shows on Cartoon Network, and I can certainly see how
the Chinese government could have problems with that. Fred, Barney,
Wilma and Betty make the Chinese ''Gang of Four'' look like
cultural visionaries. As China struggles to be accepted as a modern
society, a cartoon about cavemen who bowl with rocks and propel
their cars with their feet would be decidedly unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   Bugs Bunny, of course, would be a poison worse than unfiltered
cigarettes and air pollution to the Chinese people. Indeed, Bugs'
snotty attitude and blatant disrespect for authority makes me
wonder why he hasn't been singled out for censorship by American
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Bugs' sidekick, Daffy Duck, has plenty of energy and speaks in a
strange way that could conceivably have Mandarin roots. Still,
there's no guarantee that any number of re-education camps would
straighten out this screwball and make him fly right.
</P>
<P>
   I don't follow Bubbles, Blossom, Buttercup, Dexter and Boomerang
as closely as I should, but I feel sure that there are more than
enough decadent and/or politically incorrect scenes in these
cartoons to make them unacceptable to the powers-that-be in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only cartoon that the Chinese government might
identify with is Johnny Bravo, which features a clueless,
muscle-bound bully who thinks he's wonderful but everyone else
recognizes as a jerk.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he sounds like Elvis, which never hurts.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
