<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6522 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-RIBISI-FEATURE-L     02-14 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RIBISI-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIOVANNI RIBISI TURNS UP TEMPERATURE IN `BOILER ROOM'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sleepy-eyed guy isn't the type who immediately commands
attention. But as Giovanni Ribisi builds a character bit by
painstaking bit on screen, he becomes increasingly mesmerizing.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley-raised actor can already claim a remarkably diverse
body of work at the age of 25. Ribisi has proven equally adept at
searing drama (as the dedicated medic in Steven Spielberg's
``Saving Private Ryan'') and crack character comedy (as Lisa
Kudrow's zonky, parenthood-obsessed brother on the smash sitcom
``Friends''). He's convincingly played mentally challenged (``The
Other Sister'') and creatively eccentric when nothing else creative
was going on around him (last year's ``Mod Squad'' feature
debacle).
</P>
<P>
   And now, the sweet-tempered, unfailingly polite young family man
is about to show you why you should never, ever trust him with your
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boiler Room,'' opening Friday, offers Ribisi his biggest
opportunity yet to strut his versatile stuff. He plays an
intelligent but wayward New Yorker, Seth Davis, who's torn between
his desire for the approval of his harsh judge of a father (Ron
Rifkin) and his talent for making quick, illegitimate bucks. A
college dropout, Seth does all right running an illegal casino in
his apartment. But when a chance to become a stockbroker presents
itself, he jumps at the chance to make even more money in a way his
father won't criticize.
</P>
<P>
   Except ... the brokerage Seth trains at is a chop shop, a high-
pressure, cold-calling outfit dedicating to selling suckers
essentially worthless securities. As Seth learns to excel at
working the phones and exploiting his faceless ``clients''' greed
and fear, he also discovers that he might have the one thing
neither he nor his heartless colleagues need: a conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show Seth becoming this other kind of person,
whether it be more confident or, the other side of that coin, more
decadent,'' says Ribisi, dressed like a millionaire in a
four-button suit jacket and matching gray shirt and tie. ``Him
starting to hate himself more but being caught on this tidal wave
of success. He doesn't know what's happening or if he's doing the
right thing, and I tried to keep my attention on his progression
into that.'' Seth was also a technically demanding performance that
required Ribisi to pitch fast over telephones while a dozen other
people caused distractions all around him. Doesn't look it,
perhaps, but that's an extreme test of an actor's concentration. To
rehearse, Ribisi would spend up to 12 hours a day at an audition
theater in New York, getting his phone technique down pat.
</P>
<P>
   According to fellow Valley actor Lisa Kudrow, that's typical of
his work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing he can't do, it feels like,'' Kudrow says.
``I've only worked with him on the TV show, and that's one kind of
acting. But with that, no problems. Whatever he needs to do, there
are no obstacles. And that's one of the most important things about
acting, to just be open to everything, and everything that needs to
get done is just incorporated and justified to make it look like
all is reasonable and working. He just makes everything work.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that needed to get done for the ``Boiler Room'' gig
was understanding the ethically undernourished mindset of the
hard-sell brokers. Writer-director Ben Younger, who had been
recruited for the kind of chop shop the film depicts when he was
struggling to make the transition from cameraman to auteur, could
provide some observations and contacts. But research was no cinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to go find a chop shop, much less call 'em up and
go, `Hey, can I come down and watch you guys for a film that I'm
doing?''' Ribisi says with a laugh. ``But some of the people
Younger put me in touch with wanted the movie to get it right. One
of the guys was still a broker who had worked for another firm that
the FBI had shut down. He'd lost somebody who'd lived in Texas
$60,000, and his viewpoint was, `These people are just faceless
voices. The idea is, if they're stupid enough to give me that much
money over the phone, then they shouldn't have it anyway.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that morals are like a personal deal for every
individual. I suppose those guys could justify it by saying it's a
dog-eat-dog world out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the kind of values that have come down to Ribisi through
three previous generations of Sicilian-American forebears.
</P>
<P>
   ``My great-grandfather came over and settled in the Bay Area,
which had a big Italian community,'' he explains. ``They were
farmers, proletariat; the lifestyle was the work ethic, get your
education, family. It's the Sicilian way, what can I tell you?''
</P>
<P>
   Ribisi's father, Al, was also drawn to the arts. Working in the
San Francisco one-hit wonder band People led him to L.A., where he
later went into the printing business. Giovanni initially planned
to follow in his father's footsteps _ a dedicated guitarist, he has
his own recording studio _ but acting seemed a natural career path
for a kid who grew up in North Hollywood. Ribisi says that his
mother, Gay, a producer-manager, entered show business around the
same time that he did.
</P>
<P>
   But while living here was what sparked his interest in acting,
Ribisi also credits his Valley childhood with instilling a valuable
degree of common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that I didn't grow up in Hollywood and get into that
whole scene type thing, like, `Yeah, I know this person and that
person,''' he says. And while Ribisi had a reputation as something
of a party scenester in his younger days, since marrying actress
Mariah O'Brien Ribisi three years ago and the birth of their
daughter, Lucia, he could arguably claim to have the most settled
lifestyle of any actor in his age group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about my wife and daughter, and trying to be better as an
actor,'' he says. ``If I'm not working or whatever, I'm probably
jumping around with Lucia and singing different songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ribisi also credits the Church of Scientology with helping out
in the success and stability departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really say I was born a Scientologist, although my
parents were members,'' he says of the sometimes controversial
church. ``It's an applied religious philosophy for me, and it's
something very pragmatic that works. I know it's been in the press
and all that stuff, but it's helped me immeasurably in all aspects
of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, on the career front, is racing ahead at top speed. Ribisi
has a major role in the Nicolas Cage summer action spectacular
``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' for which he learned how to hotwire cars in
half the title time and build a '69 Camaro from parts. He kept the
muscle car, too, although, ``We have a nice Suburban for driving
the daughter around in,'' he notes with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Ribisi also provides the off-screen narration for Sofia
Coppola's acclaimed feature debut ``The Virgin Suicides'' and is
currently filming the Billy Bob Thornton-scripted Southern drama
``The Gift'' with Cate Blanchett, Keanu Reeves and Hilary Swank.
</P>
<P>
   All of which means, of course, that there's an increasing amount
of income to be managed. Ribisi admits that that's something he's
never paid a lot of attention to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea,'' he confesses. ``I knew that I did movies, and
someone else handled the money, you know what I'm saying? Now I'm
very conscious of money, so I'm trying to save it up and be smart
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is in the stock market, his ``Boiler Room'' experience
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very conservative about it,'' he explains. ``I asked that
broker, the one who lost the guy $60,000 and didn't care. I
figured, this guy was all over the place and would be a good one to
ask how he would personally invest in the market. He said, `Just
blue chip.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But no, the movie didn't scare me away from investing. It did
scare me away from buying things over the phone, but that's easy
for me anyway. People don't know how to pronounce my name, so when
a cold caller says, `Is Gy-oh-ven-I Rob-a-sy there,' I just say,
`No, he's not.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
