<HEADER>
A6525 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-THEATER-VAGINA-MONOLO     02-14 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-VAGINA-MONOLOGUES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE ALL KNOW WHERE SHE GOT THE INSPIRATION ...
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eve Ensler doesn't mince words, though some people wish she
would. The mere title of her play, coming to L.A. for one
star-studded benefit performance on Wednesday, is enough to stir
controversy: ``The Vagina Monologues.''
</P>
<P>
   Explained Ensler in a phone interview from her home in New York,
``The title is really important. It's not to shock or titillate
anyone, not to get them into the theater under a false pretense.
It's all about talking about, discussing and remembering vaginas.''
</P>
<P>
   So ... what does that mean? The play, which Ensler developed as
a one-woman show, draws on interviews she did with real women who
talked about their relationship with their most private and
seldom-discussed body part. Among the larger issues drawn out:
shame, abuse, pleasure and the wonder of bringing new life into the
world. Ensler contends that women talking about sex and their
bodies is central to ``our ability to exist or not to exist. To me,
if you can't talk about it, it means you don't have one.''
</P>
<P>
   Ensler contends that the word penis, on the other hand, is
positively accepted. ``I don't think people have a problem
discussing that at all,'' she said. ``You can say `penis' on
television, but not `vagina.'''
</P>
<P>
   Famous actresses and musicians by the dozen apparently agree
with Ensler. The performance of ``VM'' at the Wiltern on Wednesday
will include such notables as Gillian Anderson, Roseanne, Winona
Ryder, Calista Flockhart and Melissa Etheridge. A benefit
performance in New York last year attracted Glenn Close, Susan
Sarandon and Rosie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person I can think of who I'd really like to do
('VM') and hasn't is Meryl Streep. She did another of my plays,
`Necessary Targets,''' Ensler said. ``I've been very happy with the
response. So many amazing women have done it.'' She admits there is
also some buzz about Jane Fonda, recently separated from Ted
Turner, doing the play as well. Fonda herself mentioned the
possibility at a benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Ensler is no stranger to celebrity. In addition to attracting
stars who have appeared in her plays over the years, Ensler is the
adoptive mother (though she's only a few years older) of ``The
Practice's'' Dylan McDermott. Ensler wrote him his first part in a
New York play and has remained close to the actor, even after
divorcing his father years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``VM'' is proving to have a life far beyond starry galas like
Wednesday's, presented as a charity benefit by the Step Up Women's
Network and Lifetime Television. The show, which Ensler has mainly
performed solo, continues off-Broadway in New York. Ensler says
about 150 colleges and universities are participating in ``V-Day''
activities this week, including a Valentine's Day performance at
California State University, Long Beach, to help raise awareness
and money to support organizations that combat violence against
women (for more information on these activities, go to
www.feminist.com).
</P>
<P>
   Ensler adds that though she can't yet announce it or discuss the
details, there's a good chance ``VM'' will be taped to air on a
premium cable channel ... where you can say the word ``vagina.'' &QL; 
_____
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vagina Monologues,'' 8 p.m. Wednesday, Wiltern Theatre,
3790 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles. Tickets ($68 to $375) available
through all Ticketmaster outlets or by phone at (213) 365-3500.
Special VIP benefit tickets ($500 to $2,500, including priority
seating and after-party) available by calling Step Up Women's
Network at (323) 549-5347. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
