<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6528 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SF-DEVELOPMENT-HNS &LR;      02-14 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-DEVELOPMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SPRAWL IS MAJOR CONCERN IN BAY AREA, POLL SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANNIE NAKAO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As Internet millionaires and their technology
companies redefine the San Francisco Bay Area, residents are
sharing in the boom times but also finding themselves victims of
their own success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Development is out of hand,'' said Barbara Harper, 61, a
resident of the east Contra Costa community of Bay Point. ``The
traffic on Highway 4 is horrendous, but they just keep building and
building. What are all these people going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Urban sprawl and traffic congestion, poverty and homelessness,
the quality of public schools and a host of other issues worried
Harper and many of the 500 Bay Area residents recently polled by
the Pew Center for Civic Journalism in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   While the vast majority of respondents enjoyed living here,
nearly half, or 47 percent, cited sprawl, growth and traffic as
``far and away the most important problem in the region,''
according to a report on the findings, titled, ``Straight Talk From
Americans 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The six-county Bay Area was one of four metropolitan areas
surveyed by Pew to accompany a national poll on the state of the
nation and its communities. Details of the national findings are to
be released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll, which has a margin of error of plus or minus
4 percentage points, surveyed residents in Alameda, Marin, San
Francisco, Contra Costa, San Mateo and Santa Clara counties from
Oct. 29 to Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Conducted for Pew by Princeton Survey Research Associates of
Washington, the poll showed the Bay Area led the other cities _
Denver, Philadelphia and Tampa, Fla. _ in the number of residents
who said their area was an excellent place to live.
</P>
<P>
   By another measure, though, they seemed less enthusiastic about
where they lived. Some 62 percent said they were satisfied ``with
the way things are going in the San Francisco area,'' compared to
74 percent of Americans overall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the robust economy, it was clear that Bay Area residents
were concerned that not everyone shared in the current prosperity:
14 percent cited poverty, homelessness and hunger as the
second-most-important problem facing the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a remarkable finding in a time of substantial
prosperity nationwide and in at least parts of the San Francisco
Bay Area,'' the report said. ``This challenges the common
perception of the area as flush with the prosperity generated by
Silicon Valley and the Internet revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bay Area residents were decidedly critical of the police and
local government, handing in the lowest rankings of all four cities
when asked if they thought those two institutions treated people
fairly. Only 47 percent thought the police ``treated everyone the
same, while 59 percent felt local government did.''
</P>
<P>
   _ There were sharp racial divisions in the perception of how
people are treated by various institutions, a pattern that has been
long been documented nationwide. For example, while 69 percent of
Bay Area whites felt there was ``an equal chance for a good
education in public schools,'' only 33 percent of African-Americans
did.
</P>
<P>
   _ Attitudes toward immigrants were divided, with a third of
respondents saying immigrants either contribute to the community or
caused problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sixty-three percent said the quality of public schools was a
problem, although 50 percent of parents said they were very
satisfied with their children's schools. Also, 74 percent of those
polled said they believed the schools should teach ``values,
respect and courtesy'' in addition to academic subjects.
</P>
<P>
   _ While 38 percent of respondents said crime was a big problem
in their communities, an overwhelming majority said they believed
either ``very'' or ``somewhat'' safe at home or in their
neighborhoods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
