<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6534 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-DIALLO-MOTHER-HNS &LR;      02-14 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-MOTHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DIALLO'S MOTHER SPEAKS OF THE PAIN OF LOSING HER CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By THEOLA S. LABBE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Kadiatou Diallo, the mother of the young man
gunned down by police in the Bronx last year, talks about her son
in a hotel room at the Crowne Plaza here. Asked about Amadou, her
first child, whom she bore at age 16, she says simply, ``It was
like we grew up together. That's why I say it's very painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a violet-colored gown with ivory trim at the neck, she
remembers the phone call from New York that came to her in Guinea,
West Africa, a year ago. It was early in the morning, New York
time, and if the call was not from Amadou, then she knew it was
about him.
</P>
<P>
   He had been in America for a few years. He was killed in front
of his Bronx home by four police officers, shot 19 times. He was
holding a beeper and a wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Now the officers are on trial in Albany, and Amadou Diallo's
mother had come to the courthouse every day since jury selection
began Jan. 31. But last Tuesday, when she knew the medical examiner
would testify about precisely how her son was killed, she chose to
stay in her room at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what was going on. My lawyers prepared me,'' Kadiatou
says.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom, a prosecution witness, Dr. Joseph Cohen, used
projector-enlarged images of a human body pocked with bullet holes
to explain which ones he believed hit Amadou Diallo first and which
ones did the most damage. In her hotel room, Kadiatou spent the day
reading messages from a condolence book started by Raz Chowdhury, a
friend of her son from Manhattan, and signed by New Yorkers from
all parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The kind words gave her comfort. ``It was very touching,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   She also talked by phone to her three other children. She
chooses now, being interviewed, not to say where they are living.
</P>
<P>
   And as required by Muslim tradition, Kadiatou prayed five times
that day, kneeling on a prayer mat that faced east toward Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's evening. Her religion, Kadiatou says, has been crucial
in getting through this past year, and her days in Albany. She
folds up her prayer mat and carries it inside the courtroom so she
can pray with family members _ men separate from the women as
required by Muslim custom _ in a third-floor room in the courthouse
during breaks in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time we pray, we make a special prayer to the deceased,''
Kadiatou says. ``It's like a message sent to my son. It's very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   She explains that the Muslim faith discourages mourners from
constantly crying about their dead loved ones. The deceased can see
you and your tears, she says, and may also become sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that if you want the deceased to rest in peace, you
have to be strong, not to cry all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   As if someone has already posed the question, she continued.
``It's impossible to say that you cannot cry, but after that, you
pray also.''
</P>
<P>
   Kadiatou Diallo never saw her son after he left Guinea for the
United States in September 1996, intent on going to college to
study computers. Although she had a visa and could have visited,
she chose to stay in Guinea, keeping in touch by phone at least
three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, I realized he wanted to be responsible and
wanted to be a man,'' she says. ``I didn't want to try and
intervene so much because I was proud of him. I decided to let him
be a man.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months after arriving in America, Diallo saved enough
money to ship a computer back home to his mother. He wanted her to
set it up so the two could e-mail, Kadiatou explains. With watery
eyes, she says the computer is in her home in Guinea. ``It is very
precious,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   The last time they spoke by phone, the Sunday of the week he was
killed, he had called her. She was not expecting to hear from him.
</P>
<P>
   He was very proud to talk about himself that day and had called
with good news. He had done manual labor and was working as a
street vendor in Manhattan, and now he planned to go to school.
</P>
<P>
   ```Mom, I will do it,''' says Kadiatou, recalling her
22-year-old son's words.
</P>
<P>
   Kadiatou would not comment on the trial, except to say she feels
it's the ``first time that we are observing the justice system
doing (its) job.'' She has declined to say what she believes would
constitute justice in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Her life in Albany revolves around the trial, prayer and talking
with her family, with little time to see the city outside of the
hotel and the courthouse. In that regard, her lawyers have taken
her out to dinner on occasion, which has been helpful, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys Robert Conason and Anthony Gair will represent
Kadiatou Diallo in any civil procedure, which would come later. The
criminal trial, which has drawn national attention, may conclude
this week or early next week. Her lawyers accompanied her for the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   She talks of a legend that a member of the Diallo family will
bear a child that the world will talk about. Kadiatou says her
father told her the story repeatedly when she was a girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is Amadou, it's very sad,'' she says, ``but everybody's
talking about this.''
</P>
<P>
   In the face of immense sorrow and scrutiny, Kadiatou wants to
maintain her composure. ``I believe in having dignity,'' she says.
``Even if I am suffering, I want not to show it somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for him,'' she adds, ``for my family, it's us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
