r a BC-MCCAIN-BUSH-NECK'N'NE     02-14 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BUSH-NECK'N'NECK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN GAINS ON BUSH ACROSS AMERICA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for S.C. primary, Sat., Feb. 19)   (This 600-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON _ George W. Bush is struggling to keep his campaign
ahead of his rival John McCain, as the challenger makes gains on
him across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bush remains publicly calm. But behind the scenes, his campaign
and its backers are fighting frenziedly to ensure that the
front-runner maintains his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   They are ditching visits to other states, boosting spending and
trying to reshape the way their candidate is seen in the crucial
contest in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has tried to reorientate his campaign, appearing more
active, more engaged and less self-assured of his own victory.
``It's good for me to have a good fight,'' said Bush on a
television discussion program Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was going to win, he said ``Yes Sir.'' Then he
interrupted himself to say: ``I take nothing for granted. I want
you to know that.'' In New Hampshire, he was seen as arrogant and
presumptuous.
</P>
<P>
   Bush lost the New Hampshire primary, and if he loses South
Carolina, he will also lose all of his lustre as the party's
heir-apparent; McCain will start to look like the victor rather
than just a successful insurgent.
</P>
<P>
   The two are in a dead heat in the Southern state, which votes
this Saturday. A poll in Newsweek shows Bush at 43 percent and
McCain at 40 percent, which given the margin of error makes it too
close to call.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is recruiting among the state's independents and
Democrats; Bush has a firm base in the Republican establishment.
</P>
<P>
   The race will turn on how many independents McCain can actually
bring out to vote, and his campaign is aimed at mobilizing this
constituency _ Democrats and independents can vote in the
Republican primary in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The event brought out 278,000 voters four years ago; this year,
the Republicans expect it to bring out between 350,000 and 400,000.
The higher the number, the more likely a victory for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Negative advertisements by both sides have dented McCain's
ratings since he was ahead a week ago. They may also damp down
turnout.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has now dropped his own negative ads, but Bush has said
that he will not: his publicity simply states his case against the
arguments which McCain has made. ``I'm not going to get defined,''
he said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, McCain gained the upper hand by depicting
himself as a rebel and an outsider, and Bush as the favorite of the
governing elite.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has now run up a surprising lead in Michigan, the next
primary state, which votes days after South Carolina. The Detroit
News shows him leading Bush by nine percentage points, having been
34 points behind.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seems to have lost the respect of some voters, to put it
mildly. ``He's just a wealthy, wimpy, whiny sniveller,'' Carl
Bellmer, a 66-year-old retired car worker from Lansing, told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Bush's lead over McCain is down from 44 percentage
points to twelve. Yet Bush has cancelled some appearances to shore
up his position in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that his campaign is starting to deal with the
possibility that he might actually win the election, speculation is
starting to appear about a McCain presidency.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News and World Report says that possible vice-presidential
candidates might be drawn from the ``digerati.'' Jeff Bezos,
founder of Amazon.com, Jerry Yang, founder of Yahoo!, and Andy
Grove of Intel are mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   McCain wants a retired flag officer as secretary of defense and
Colin Powell as secretary of state, it says. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
