<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6545 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CALIF-DEMS-HNS &LR;      02-14 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DEMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOME DEMOCRATS WOULD PREFER BUSH AS GOP NOMINEE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ California Democrats appear to favor Texas
Gov. George W. Bush as the rival to their party's nominee,
believing that Arizona Sen. John McCain would be a far more
formidable foe in the November general election.
</P>
<P>
   Party regulars interviewed at the state Democratic convention
over the weekend overwhelmingly said they would rather face Bush
than McCain, who beat Bush in the New Hampshire primary and has
made gains in South Carolina, which holds its Republican primary
this Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think McCain is a more formidable opponent,'' said Humberto
Lujan, 75, a longtime party activist who supports former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic nomination. ``He appears to be
far more substantive than George W. Bush. I think we can blow all
kinds of holes in Bush, but that's a lot harder to do with
McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   While some Democrats fear Bush's ability to raise money for his
campaign, party activists said McCain's background as a prisoner of
war in Vietnam and his image as a straight talker make him a
tougher potential foe for the eventual Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a war hero. How can you attack him for that?'' said Gene
Crabb, 73, a lifelong Democrat and retired Army master sergeant
from Modesto. Crabb said he watched some of the early Republican
debates in Iowa and New Hampshire and believed McCain was a
stronger debater with a better grasp of the issues than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Crabb, who supports Vice President Al Gore as the Democratic
nominee, said he thinks the vice president would fare better
against Bush. Bush, he said, is ``something of a political novice.
He's never been on the national stage before.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's surprising surge after winning the New Hampshire
primary on Feb. 1 has compelled Democrats and Republicans alike to
ponder the idea of McCain as the possible GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Bush and his supporters suggested that
Democrats in open primary states like New Hampshire were
mischievously crossing party lines to vote for McCain in the GOP
primary because he would be a weaker opponent in November. McCain
countered that the Bush camp's accusation ``flies in the face of
the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Top officials of California's Democratic Party, who are staying
neutral in the Bradley-Gore race, said they don't care who becomes
the Republican nominee. Both Bush and McCain are beatable, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both have substantial liabilities,'' said state party
chairman Art Torres, who criticized both as anti-choice on
abortion, pro-gun and lax on environmental protections. ``They're
the Siamese twins of Republican ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders clearly are paying more attention to McCain
because he has moved up in polls in California and elsewhere. When
Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., attacked Bush's abortion record as
Texas governor in a speech at the convention Saturday, she quickly
followed by criticizing McCain for casting 82 pro-life votes in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Party strategist Bob Mulholland said McCain's
rise reminds voters of Bush's vulnerabilities as a candidate. And
if McCain wins in South Carolina, he could be seen as the new GOP
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins, Mulholland vows that the party will pound away on
issues such as abortion and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Democrats are more focused on picking their own
nominee. Bradley and Gore both addressed the convention, but the
feeling among delegates was that Gore is a heavy favorite. A Field
Poll last week in California showed Gore leading Bradley 54 to 13
percent. The state primary is March 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
