<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6550 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-COLUMN-ROCKER-COX     02-14 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-ROCKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why Rocker? Is he a chip off our own?
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a new poll out in Newsweek, and it fascinates me.
</P>
<P>
   It's about John Rocker. Remember him?
</P>
<P>
   He's the Atlanta Braves pitcher who shot off his mouth to a
magazine reporter and ranted about kids with purple hair and gays
with AIDS and women with more than one baby and Italians who speak
Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Italians who speak Italian! Now that's outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   How revolting!
</P>
<P>
   But what's even more revolting is that I know John Rocker's
name, can roll it off my tongue like I were saying, ``Sit up and
eat your breakfast.'' It's that easy.
</P>
<P>
   But Ray Lewis? Rae Carruth?
</P>
<P>
   I had to look those names up in the archives _ couldn't recall
them to save my tired soul.
</P>
<P>
   And they're charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   The whole Rocker thing is nuts. Some sports guy spouts, and we
go ballistic. We gasp. We dial up the AM talk-radio guys. We read
every little morsel about his transparent apology and his visits to
a shrink. We applaud his month-long suspension from baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But we should be gasping at ourselves. Why should we care what's
rattling around in John Rocker's empty head?
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that's why Newsweek asked this question:
</P>
<P>
   What would happen to your job if you talked like John Rocker?
</P>
<P>
   Forty percent said they'd be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Another 13 percent said they'd be suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one percent said they'd be ostracized by their workers.
</P>
<P>
   And 26 percent said nothing would happen to them.
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine even thinking the things John Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, I can't imagine predicting what would happen if Italked like John Rocker did.
</P>
<P>
   See what I'm saying? Those 1,300 people who answered the
Newsweek poll, isn't it possible _ indeed, probable _ that they're
saying: I can't really speak my mind at work because I might get
fired. Or suspended. Or ostracized by my colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   And I find that a whole lot scarier than John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that fascinates me about Rocker, and our reaction to
him, is that we're outraged by all the wrong things. We'd much
rather go along pretending that people don't think the things that
Rocker was stupid enough to say.
</P>
<P>
   People can do whatever they want, and it doesn't seem to stick
to us.
</P>
<P>
   Robbery? Drugs? Some football player getting arrested for
murder? It just isn't that shocking anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But have you heard about John Rocker? He called gay guys queers!
He picked on foreigners. He made fun of women with lots of babies.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Rocker won't be with his team when it reports to
spring training in Orlando next week. He's been suspended for 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a shame. He shouldn't be allowed to miss one single
day of his penance.
</P>
<P>
   Which is mainly to put on his uniform, take the field and allow
all the John Rockers of the world to heckle him and boo him _ all
season long.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post. e-mail:
emilyminor(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1612EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
