<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6552 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-LASVEGAS-CULIN     02-14 2789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LAS </SLUG>
 VEGAS-CULINARY BOOM-LADN  
Bon appetit on the Strip 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
With art 
With side story on fine art 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Eric Noland, Travel Editor
</P>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS -- Fresh chestnut soup. Lobster risotto with white
truffles. Flaky, tasty vol au vent -- at a buffet station. Dry-aged
strip steak in seven spices, stuffed with Bulgarian feta cheese.
</P>
<P>
   This is the dining experience in Las Vegas?
</P>
<P>
   It is now.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, this city has expended a great deal of
energy redefining itself -- constructing hotels that mirror
European retreats, opening lavish spas, stocking exotic products at
chi-chi boutiques, lifting the curtain on Broadway kick lines. It
was bound to work up an appetite.
</P>
<P>
   As a direct result, the inclination to dine in comfort and
elegance can be indulged at dozens of establishments along the
Strip. Why, it seems a dealer can't sweep the chips off a roulette
table without accidentally jabbing an elbow into a celebrity chef.
The famous cooks who oversee kitchens here (or at least lend their
names to enterprises) include Julian Serrano, Emeril Lagasse,
Wolfgang Puck, Joachim Splichal, Mark Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Two establishments just received coveted five-star ratings from
the Mobil Travel Guide: Serrano's Picasso (at Bellagio) and
Alessandro Stratta's Renoir (at the Mirage).
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles diners, meanwhile, can seek out the familiar:
Matsuhisa of Beverly Hills has reincarnated as Nobu at the Hard
Rock Hotel; Santa Monica's Border Grill has popped up under that
name at Mandalay Bay; a derivation of Studio City's Pinot Bistro
can be found here as Pinot Brasserie at the Venetian; Santa
Monica's Valentino has surfaced under that name at the Venetian.
</P>
<P>
   Food is an important component of Las Vegas' ongoing bid to
attract business from the tourist industry's mid- to upper markets
resort travelers and white-collar conventioneers. But the city's
eats aren't entirely clustered at the high end of the price scale.
</P>
<P>
   To complement their fancy restaurants, several chefs have also
opened cafe establishments, where the food and wine are priced more
accessibly and the most casual of attire is accepted. Buffets at
the new hotels -- priced a bit higher than Strip tradition, but
still reasonable -- are offering gourmet items. And there are
several new restaurants that are directly targeted to kids,
featuring gimmicky surroundings and hefty portions of American
classics.
</P>
<P>
   Can't quite part with such Las Vegas standards as the $5.99
buffet, the 32-ounce rib-eye steak or the casino hot dog? Don't
worry. For people with cast-iron boilers, those classics aren't
going anywhere. You just have to wander far from the glitz of
re-created Italian villas and Polynesian hideaways to find them.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit here, nine of the Strip's establishments were
sampled over a period of three days -- from the top of the scale to
near the buffet bottom, with several stops in the intermediate
ranges. At that, I felt as if I'd I just nibbled around the edges
of the city's culinary renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ---Roots
</P>
<P>
   Here's where it all started: Spago and Spago Cafe in the Forum
Shops at Caesars Palace.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than seven years ago, Puck and the executives who
manage his Los Angeles-area establishments reasoned that Las Vegas,
long thought to be peopled by impatient, undiscriminating gamblers
who ate on the run, was ripe for something a little more exalted.
The restaurants opened under the same roof (and awning) in December
1992, and experienced such exponential success that casino bosses
all over town scrambled to corral household-name chefs of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   It's obviously still a popular spot. The dining room is dressy,
with a menu to match. Many visitors seem to gravitate to the cafe,
which is outdoors but only in Las Vegas' trademark sense of
suspended reality. It's a sidewalk setting in the upscale indoor
mall that is the Forum Shops. You sit beneath a movie-set sky in
climate-controlled comfort. Picture fine dining in the Galleria.
During our dinner, we counted four sunsets in the distance near the
animatronic statues.
</P>
<P>
   There are no standards of decorum at the cafe. Near our table
were two women in elegant black evening wear and jewelry, next to
them a table of teens in sweatshirts and baseball caps. A guy in a
suit. A kid in a hockey jersey. Thus, people from L.A. will feel
right at home.
</P>
<P>
   David Robins is the executive chef here, and he does a
commendable job of maintaining Spago's West Hollywood traditions.
Yes, the menu includes smoked-salmon pizza with a generous dollop
of osetra caviar in the center of each slice. A homemade
pappardelle pasta was served slightly al dente, with grilled
shrimp, tomatoes and a basil pesto. The Caesar salad, big enough to
split, was refreshingly without gimmicks -- with thick shavings of
Parmesan cheese and an anchovy laid out helplessly across its
crest. The seafood in the Maine crab cakes appetizer was remarkably
fresh.
</P>
<P>
   And here was a revelation: excellent California wines that
weren't priced through the fake roof. A pinot blanc from Au Bon
Climat in the Santa Ynez Valley cost only $34. Dinner for two (two
starter courses, two main courses, a bottle of wine, one dessert,
plus tax and tip) came in at $135.
</P>
<P>
   Advisory: A table along the exterior railing is desirable in
most sidewalk cafes, but you might want to request a table set back
a bit. Las Vegas is still wrestling to achieve a measure of
sophistication, and the effect hasn't fully set in yet. We observed
passers-by slowing down and openly gawking at diners' plates, as if
watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   ---Southwest sensations
</P>
<P>
   Coyote Cafe, the creation of Southwest wizard Mark Miller, is
another casual, reasonably priced establishment that complements an
upscale cousin (the Grill Room). They share the same frontage in
the gargantuan MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   As at Spago Cafe, this is a sidewalk setting, though along an
indoor walkway, and ambiance, accordingly, takes a beating. During
our lunch there, the electronic bleeps and blurks of the nearby
casino games bled down the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   But the food was spicy and savory, representing clever
variations on familiar items. The Southwest tasting platter
featured a chicken enchilada made with a blue-corn tortilla and
smothered in salsa verde, a duck quesadilla and a gordita -- a
thick, pitalike corn tortilla pocket stuffed with pork and other
goodies.
</P>
<P>
   From the Baja portion of the menu, a Cabo-style tostada boasted
a generous complement of shrimp, plus asadero cheese, black beans
and roma tomato slices. If you're looking for a light course at a
Southwest-Mexican restaurant, this is it.
</P>
<P>
   For the slaking of a thirst, the bar serves four Mexican beers,
plus 32- ounce margaritas that come in glasses 2 feet tall. Lunch
for two with beer was $46.
</P>
<P>
   Advisory: When the waiter first arrives and asks if you'd like
chips and salsa, be advised that they don't come complimentary.
You'll pay $3 for this snack.
</P>
<P>
   ---Prime cut
</P>
<P>
   What is it about being in the desert that stirs a craving for a
generous cut of grilled, juicy beef? In its frontier-theme days,
Las Vegas had steakhouses in every block. In the rejuvenated
stretch of the Strip, it still does; they're just better.
</P>
<P>
   Choose from among Delmonico, Gallagher's, Morton's of Chicago,
the Palm or Smith &AMP; Wollensky. Or Charlie Palmer Steak, which
opened at the Four Seasons just a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Like the hotel itself, the restaurant is blissfully removed from
the clamor of casino gambling. And it shamelessly plays to Rat Pack
Revival: dark, clublike, comfortable, with tables well-spaced. At
the adjacent bar, there is overstuffed living-room furniture, a
generous supply of Bombay Sapphire and martini glasses the size of
candy dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Steaks and chops are difficult to foul up. A restaurant just
needs to track down thick, exceptional cuts and then keep a close
eye on the grill. Two of the offerings here were impressive,
particularly the filet mignon, which was perhaps 2 1/2 inches
thick, extraordinarily tender, lightly charred on the outside and
garnished with two roasted shallots.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the side dishes that distinguish this restaurant. Two
of the favorites at our table: a double-baked potato with truffle
cream and sauteed spinach (we were considerably less impressed with
the oven-roasted potatoes). Don't worry about feeling like a
Philistine if you ask to share an item; the restaurant expects it,
and in fact positions the side dishes family-style, in the center
of a table for two.
</P>
<P>
   The experience here was marred only by the wine manner of the
sommelier, who was tardy in producing a requested bottle of
Ravenswood merlot, then disappeared, opened the bottle at a
sideboard, poured some in a glass, sniffed it and tasted it. When I
protested that this should be my responsibility, he said, ``I
wanted to make sure it was good. Some people have had an entire
bottle not knowing that it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, when the steak arrived, it didn't have a bite out
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner for two (two starters, two main courses, three side
dishes, a bottle of wine, a shared dessert, plus tax and tip) was
$180.
</P>
<P>
   ---French elegance
</P>
<P>
   Napa, a restaurant at the Rio, just west of the Strip, has one
feature that isn't easy to come by in the casino-bound restaurants
of Las Vegas: windows. Over dinner here, you can actually look out
over the pool and its bordering greenery, and watch the setting sun
fire the desert sky.
</P>
<P>
   The management of this hotel was among the pioneering element in
fine dining in Las Vegas, and this restaurant, the province of chef
Jean-Louis Palladin, is superb. It combines country French cookery
with an exhaustive wine list, often featuring more than 100
offerings by the glass.
</P>
<P>
   The room is seductively lit, with the walls adorned with
abstract art and the kitchen open to view. The service was
unfailingly attentive, yet discreet thankfully, no one conforms to
a popular restaurant trend of trying to be your best buddy (or,
worse, a stand-up comic) for two hours. The waiters are trained not
to reach across your body to place a glass or a fork, and they
don't remove one person's empty plate while the other is still
eating (my wife says that practice always makes her feel as if
she's being pressured to hurry up).
</P>
<P>
   Lamb chops were cut thick two rib bones per chop and cooked
perfectly: Here, medium rare was actually medium rare, not rare, as
is common in so many restaurants these days. One of the main-course
specials was exquisitely rich: risotto sauteed in truffle butter
and cooked in truffle consomme, then served with Parmesan cheese
and Maryland lump crab and topped with shaved truffles. Four
different kinds of breads were offered during the first course,
including a warm brioche.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the extensive wine-by-the-glass offerings, we were
able to complement our disparate dishes properly and also match
wines with courses. Dinner for two (two starters, two main courses,
three glasses of wine, one dessert, plus tax and tip) was $174.
</P>
<P>
   ---Belly up
</P>
<P>
   A whiplashing contrast to these restaurants and cafes was found
one morning deep in the bowels of the Sahara, at the northern,
not-so-chic extremity of the Strip. It was the classic casino
buffet: $4.99 for all the breakfast you could fork down.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost all. Posted signs warn that patrons will be limited
to a ``maximum two-hour dining experience.'' Five late-teen men in
line in front of us seemed crestfallen to receive this admonition.
(When we were pre-paying, one actually hollered to a comrade,
``Hey, Dan, gimme that nickel.'')
</P>
<P>
   This Vegas tradition is strictly for power eaters. It's not
unusual to see people gobbling items from their plates while
standing in line.
</P>
<P>
   The fare here was only a slight step up from a college dorm
cafeteria, and the place was thick with large families,
international travelers (we heard a great number of foreign
tongues) and budget seniors. Highlights: an outstanding selection
of fresh fruit (mostly ignored), an impressive array of doughnuts
(attacked mercilessly) and decent offerings from the omelet
station.
</P>
<P>
   ---Tres bon
</P>
<P>
   For a considerable step up in buffet fare, try one of the new
theme hotels. Sunday brunch at Paris Las Vegas' Le Village Buffet,
for example, was a pleasant surprise
</P>
<P>
   and reasonably priced at $21.95 per person, including
unexceptional champagne (it might be better to stick to orange
juice). This is obviously a popular feast; the wait was about 50
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The various stations are set up to roughly conform to various
regions in France mussels, scallop salad and a delightful seafood
quiche at Normandy, for example; prime rib and veal at Burgundy;
sausage at Alsace, etc.
</P>
<P>
   You can probably imagine the other choices: a crepe and waffle
bar, an omelet bar (it was billed as Alsace, but had more the feel
of Marriott), an impressive selection of cheeses (including cantal,
Camembert and a delicious Roquefort), king crab legs stacked nearly
to the ceiling and a decadent array of French pastries and
made-to-order bananas Foster at the dessert station.
</P>
<P>
   ---Just for fun
</P>
<P>
   The hope on this trip was to sample the intriguing WB Stage 16,
a new restaurant that promises re-created backdrops from Warner
Bros.' Burbank lot, including such film settings as ``Batman'' and
``Casablanca.'' The restaurant trumpeted a December opening, but in
the first week of January it was still under construction, and only
recently got around to its grand opening. It is located at the
star-crossed Venetian, which has been plagued by chronic
construction delays since its hurried opening last spring. (Rival
hotel officials have taken to calling it The Incompletion.)
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, we sought out the America Restaurant at New
York-New York. This is a fun place for kids -- it is big, open and
airy, with a giant relief map of the United States forming a canopy
for it all. Characteristics of each state are embedded in the
papier-mache map, and it's fun to peruse the stereotypes: cheese,
beer, cows and Harley-Davidsons in Wisconsin; cotton, Elvis, a
guitar in Tennessee; potatoes and a hunter (or is that a
survivalist?) in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The menu features an exhaustive array of lunchtime items,
ostensibly tied to regions of the country. There's an Oklahoma
chicken-fried steak, a Rhode Island traditional turkey dinner
(shouldn't that be Massachusetts?), a Betty Crocker tuna melt from
Minnesota, and of course, a Philadelphia cheesesteak sandwich. As
you might imagine, there were also half-pound all-American burgers,
with an impressive array of fixings. The children's menu alone has
eight items ($4.95 each, including a drink and ice cream).
</P>
<P>
   Kids sitting at tables nearby often contorted in their seats,
peered upward and asked questions about the vast geography lesson
overhead. Not a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someday they'll be able to look at the southern reaches of
Nevada ... and spot an embedded knife and fork.
</P>
<P>
   ---IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of some of the intriguing restaurants on the Las
Vegas Strip, and where they can be found:
</P>
<P>
   Aqua (Bellagio)
</P>
