<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6554 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      02-14 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     If you don't have time to read this, take an elevator By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any day now, I expect to answer the telephone and be greeted by
the unmistakable sound of someone tinkling in the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   You may think that's silly or gross, but mark my words: Sooner
or later, people eager to find new ways to save time will conclude
that there's really no good reason they can't use the facilities
and talk to you on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it may already be happening, halfway around the world.
Some years ago, my wife and mother-in-law took a trip to China when
it was first opening its doors to Western tourists. The Chinese
chamber-of-commerce types had a fairly accurate notion of what
those of us on this end of the globe like in the way of creature
comforts. Sometimes, though, things got lost in the translation.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, there was the matter of the phone by the toilet.
My wife and her mom found just such a convenience in a hotel they
stayed in. Apparently, the people who ran the place believed we
Americans are so fond of yammering that we can't even go to the loo
without calling up someone we know to say toodle-oo.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, I've begun thinking the Chinese are onto something.
There doesn't seem to be a limit to the lengths to which some of us
in the good ole U.S. of A. will go to free up more seconds in our
days.
</P>
<P>
   Auto makers, as you've probably heard, are manufacturing a line
of spiffy new vehicles equipped with Internet access. I might have
placed this item a bit farther down the list of priorities for
research and development, below _ say _ creating better fuel
mileage and finding a less crunchy type of metal. But apparently
there's a great consumer demand to surf and drive.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we'll be able to cruise down the road, talk on the cell
phone, comb our hair in the rearview mirror, munch on a Big Mac,
and have our e-mail _ ads and all _ read to us by a computerized
voice.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of the exciting new ways we can save time.
Recently two companies, the ubiquitous Otis Elevators and an
upstart called Captive Network Inc., began installing Internet
screens in elevators in office buildings and hotels in several U.S.
cities. The plan is to go nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   No longer will we have to waste time trying not to make eye
contact with anyone else while we silently watch the little numbers
above the door. Now we can use those lost 30 seconds to check our
stocks, read a paragraph or two from the morning paper, or download
our e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   For my money, the greatest new timesaving innovation comes from
Southern California, where five McDonald's restaurants have joined
forces with a local transportation authority to devise a way for us
to breeze through drive-through windows without having to stop to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement makes use of antennae and little gizmos that
already enable drivers to travel on toll roads and have the tolls
automatically deducted from a pre-paid account. Now, folks can
place an order at a McDonald's window, pick up the bag at the next
window, and have the bill added to their gizmo, just like a toll.
</P>
<P>
   This, according to McDonald's, will shave 15 whole seconds off
the normal 131-second wait at a drive-through window.
</P>
<P>
   ``With today's lifestyles, everyone's on the go,'' McDonald's
spokesman Antonio Hernandez told Reuters news agency. ``If they can
omit any time having to wait in the drive-through line, they would
welcome that.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I'm thrilled with the time I'm going
to save in my car, on elevators and in fast-food lines. In fact,
I've already figured out what to do with the extra _ what? _ 3 1/8
minutes: I'm looking for more ways to save time.
</P>
<P>
   At this very moment, in fact, I'm changing my cat's litter,
typing this column on a laptop strapped to the cat's back,
downloading my e-mail, dialing up a business contact in China to
purchase the U.S. rights to the toilet phone, and cleaning my oven.
</P>
<P>
   I already have a few ideas for an ad campaign for the toilet
phone: ``Give it a swirl! It's flush with time-saving
possibilities!'' and ``Finally, a merger of laboratory and
lavatory: Microsoft meets Angelsoft!'' and, of course, ``The
Commode-A-Phone: Reach out and flush someone!''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it sounds stupid now. But when I strike it rich, don't
bother calling me to ask if you can invest. Especially if you're
using the bathroom. That would be disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.
Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
