<HEADLINE>
ON THE WEB, MAGAZINE IS ALL THE BUZZ 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects name of editor of Mothers Who Think site to Jennifer
Foote Sweeney; a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buzz snakes through our culture like millennial mist. People and
institutions rise and fall on their ability to generate the stuff.
For more than a decade, Tina Brown was the fin de siecle queen of
buzz. As editor of Vanity Fair and The New Yorker, she and her
publications dominated table talk at All The Right Places.
</P>
<P>
   But today Brown is in eclipse. The latest pretender to her
throne is David Talbot, creator of Salon.com, the randy, San
Francisco-based online magazine. Talbot's house of buzz has cooked
up a daily gumbo of news and opinion, arguably hotter than anything
on the Internet. Anchored by outstanding cultural coverage, it
presents a sexed, edgy confection that attracts readers like moths
to a back porch light.
</P>
<P>
   And it has done so in cyberspace, not on the newsstand. ``Salon
is the first really successful new media site on the Net,'' says
media critic Jon Katz. ``It is the first to figure out how to fuse
content and interactivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Its craving for attention is matched by its penchant for
controversy. Salon is in the news for its lapses in judgment as
well as its scoops. Its writing, says Washington Post media critic
Howard Kurtz, ranges from superb to sophomoric. The editorial
product can be as uneven as it is insouciant.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this unhinged approach has legs is unclear. ``Salon's
strength and weakness is that it takes all kinds of editorial
chances in an age when most publications are cautious and overly
polite,'' Kurtz says.
</P>
<P>
   When Salon is good, it is very good. Salon reporter Daniel
Forbes made headlines last month when he uncorked a story
documenting the White House Office of National Drug Control
Policy's searching of network television scripts for antidrug
messages. It was a superior piece of journalism and a clean score
for Salon.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks later, Talbot ran a piece by Dan Savage, an
openly gay Seattle-based writer bent on giving then-presidential
candidate Gary Bauer the flu because of Bauer's antipathy toward
gays. Savage, who had come down with the virus, posed as a Bauer
volunteer in Iowa and fraudulently voted as a Republican there.
</P>
<P>
   Loyal readers howled about the piece, which they considered
beyond the pale even for Salon. Talbot printed a sampling of their
e-mail tirades along with an editor's note in which he stood by the
article without condoning what Savage claimed to have done. Today,
Talbot remains unchastened by l'affaire Savage: ``My only
difficulty was not to have put an editor's note on the piece when
it ran.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon, then, is the gifted adolescent who dazzles a crowd yet
forgets to clean up his room. And it couldn't care less about
criticism. ``There is no bad buzz,'' says David Weir, its
Washington bureau chief, updating P.T. Barnum's famous dictum.
``We're not The New York Times. We're not gatekeepers of what
should be published.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the point. Salon's sense of propriety is elastic, its
pursuit of cheek singleminded. ``The primary reason Salon exists is
because of the frustration I felt by the confines of daily
journalism,'' explains Talbot, a former arts editor of the San
Francisco Examiner. ``It has become increasingly formulaic and
focus-group driven _ simply dull. I came of age with the gonzo
journalism of Hunter Thompson in Rolling Stone. It was risk-taking,
provocative journalism. We've done that here.''
</P>
<P>
   No question about that. Salon is still recovering from the
firestorm it created in 1998 over the story it ran, on the eve of
impeachment proceedings against President Clinton, about a
34-year-old extramarital affair of House Judiciary Committee
chairman Henry Hyde. All 57 journalistic organizations that were
offered the story turned it down. Salon's Washington correspondent,
Jonathan Broder, left over Talbot's decision to run it.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot was pilloried for leaky ethics and a pro-Clinton agenda.
There were bomb threats at the office and death threats at home. He
wrote at the time that ``ugly times call for ugly tactics'' and has
never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Salon is also a feast of guilty pleasures. It produces stories
as illicit in this earnest world as Godiva chocolates to a weight
watcher. High in this category are the 53 episodes of ``Nancy Chan:
Diary of a Manhattan Call Girl.'' This fictional romp catches with
a gimlet eye the lust in the Imperial City with chapters like
``Thighs Wide Shut.'' Salon also has a regular sex column. One
recent offering by Susie Bright titled ``The Randy Bellboy''
provided tips on how lonely female hotel guests can get serviced by
staff.
</P>
<P>
   But Talbot also craves serious credentials. Salon's political
reportage, notably its award-winning work on the Whitewater
scandal, has been solid. Last summer, Weir opened a Washington
bureau that will soon have nine reporters. (There are 56 on the
editorial staff, 10 in New York and the rest in San Francisco.)
</P>
<P>
   Jake Tapper, its lead political reporter, provides a steady
stream of smart, wry coverage of the presidential campaign. The day
after the New Hampshire primary, while the rest of the media herd
focused on South Carolina, Anthony York had a strong piece
detailing how the arcane rules in the California primaries will
hinder the transfer of raw votes among independents for John McCain
and Bill Bradley into convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of the day, sex trumps politics at Salon.
Grown-up discussion of it is Salon's long suit and is marbled
through the 11 Salon sites, which include Arts &AMP; Entertainment,
Books, Health &AMP; Body, Media, News, Politics2000, and, Technology.
</P>
<P>
   One of the strongest is Mothers Who Think, edited by Jennifer
Foote Sweeney, devoted to intelligent exploration of real life for
women with children. Two weeks ago, it ran a piece asking, ``Is
this child pornography?'' about the trend among photo labs to call
police over film of naked children in bathtubs.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot celebrates sex because no one else does. He considers it
an effective tool to distance Salon from online competitors. ``The
question for new media operations is: What do you do that no one
else does?'' he asks. ``Most publications in America can't answer
that effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   But more fundamentally, Talbot chafes at the way sex is treated
in this country. ``The US is childish as a culture in dealing with
it,'' says Talbot, who wrote a book on the subject. ``It is treated
either in a snickering sophomoric way or a harrumphing prudish way.
I find that inexplicable.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Weir, ``I can't think of a dinner party when sex doesn't
come up along with politics, books, and movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbot started Salon in 1995 as a weekly cultural digest. Books
were its windows to the world. ``At the beginning, we concluded
that the focus on new ideas in arts and culture and politics tended
to emerge through books,'' Weir says. Salon's book section remains
a superior admixture of knowing reviews covering an eclectic range
of books and illuminating interviews with authors.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, Talbot realized that Salon could not survive as a
weekly given the speed of the Internet, and in February 1997 took
it daily. ``We realized that news drives traffic,'' Weir says.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, news coverage mushroomed, driven by the elections
that year and seismic events like the death of Princess Diana that
drew huge spikes in readership. Talbot sees running room covering
the entertainment industry. Because publications like Entertainment
Weekly are owned by conglomerates, he argues, they will be less
likely to pursue aggressive investigations than the independent
Salon.
</P>
<P>
   Salon had revenues of $6.2 million last year and expects to turn
a profit sometime next year. It raised $27 million in a public
offering and $15 million from private investors last year to pay
for its current hiring spree. But profits are elusive for dotcoms.
Buzz does not automatically morph into dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot hopes to open a European operation based in London later
this year. CEO Michael O'Donnell is now in Europe talking to
institutional investors. He salivates over the $800 million worth
of online ads in the United Kingdom alone last year and remains
sanguine that an American operation can thrive in a cultural
collision with the Euros.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Salon sold 10 percent of itself last year
to Rainbow Media Holdings, the holding company for the Bravo
Network, the Independent Film Channel, and American Movie Classics.
It plans to air its own television show on Bravo in late summer.
Salon Radio, accessible on its home page, is also ramping up its
audio stream of talk and music to augment the online offerings. By
the end of the year, a reader will be able to hear Salon reporters,
reviewers, and columnists read their work.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Salon readership is soaring, according to its own
figures. It claims that 3.4 million people visited it in December,
up fivefold from the 650,000 during the previous December. Slate,
the more traditional online magazine of politics and commentary run
by former New Republic editor Michael Kinsley, disputes the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   This food fight is based on dueling statistics. The industry
yardstick has been Media Metrix, the New York company that projects
totals based on a sample of users. By that measurement, Salon had
1.4 million in December; Slate had 900,000.
</P>
<P>
   Salon says that the sample system grossly underestimates the
true numbers. As for Slate's charges? ``Sour grapes,'' says Patrick
Hurley, Salon's vice president for marketing. ``When's the last
time you heard someone talk about Slate?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Slate won't go around licking doorknobs,'' snaps Kinsley.
</P>
<P>
   But it does advertise on Salon. Even more delicious for Salon
was CNN's refusal last year to air its television ad campaign on
the grounds that an online site was a direct competitor to the TV
network.
</P>
<P>
   Love that buzz. At the end of the day, though, Salon will rise
or fall on its credibility. ``Buzz is their ideology,'' Broder
says. ``Once the fascination in the Web ends, the old rules still
apply.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
