<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Aggressive Crickets &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What makes the elephant charge his tusk,  &LR;   &UR; In the misty mist
or the dusky dusk?  &LR;   &UR; What makes the muskrat guard his musk?
Courage! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For the Cowardly Lion, who posed those questions in ``The Wizard
of Oz,'' aggressive behavior was a function of just one thing,
which he sorely lacked. Scientists, however, know that it is not
that simple, and indeed, what makes animals aggressive is not fully
understood.
</P>
<P>
   Now German and American researchers, writing in Nature, have
provided new insight into aggression, at least among one species.
What puts the fight in crickets? Not courage, the researchers say,
but flight.
</P>
<P>
   Cricket fighting was a royal sport in ancient China and has
persisted in some Chinese cities and in Chinese communities
elsewhere. Gamblers bet on whether their insect will prevail in a
fight that involves fencing with antennas, locking mandibles and
wrestling. The losing cricket retreats, usually losing its will to
fight.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the gamblers know, a defeated cricket can regain its
aggressiveness if it is shaken in cupped hands and thrown into the
air a few times.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists studied this effect, showing that it was not
dependent on how long the insects were in the air, and not
transitory _ aggressiveness remained restored for hours. Other
stressful activity, like being tumbled in a rotating tube or
walking in a wind, had no effect.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggest that the specific motor pattern of
flying produces some kind of command in the nervous system that
resets aggression in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tiniest Chemical Sensor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Nanotubes, those cylindrical molecules of carbon atoms, are
steadily becoming much more than just a laboratory curiosity, as
researchers develop potential applications for them.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest possible uses for nanotubes is as tiny
chemical sensors. Researchers at Stanford report in the journal
Science that they have used nanotubes to detect minute amounts of
gases quickly and at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers used a single-walled nanotube, one in which just
a single layer of carbon atoms forms the cylinder walls. These
nanotubes are on the order of a billionth of a meter wide, and
about three-millionths of a meter long. The structure of the
molecule is such that it acts like a semiconductor if a charge is
placed across it. This quality is what makes it useful as a sensor.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the electrical resistance of the
nanotubes increased or decreased greatly when exposed to small
amounts of nitrogen dioxide or ammonia. Nitrogen dioxide is found
in car exhaust, among other sources, and gaseous ammonia is toxic,
so tiny devices capable of detecting these gases would serve a real
need.
</P>
<P>
   The nanotubes were more sensitive than existing sensors. They
also operated at room temperature. Most sensors currently used
require heating to at least 400 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Mighty Nanotube &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Before sensors or other devices based on nanotubes can be
produced commercially, more has to be learned about the basic
properties of these molecules. Scientists at Washington University
in St. Louis have taken a step in that direction, determining for
the first time the force needed to break one by stretching.
</P>
<P>
   The study, reported in Science, used multiwalled nanotubes
consisting of 10 to 40 single-walled tubes nested inside each
other. The stretching occurs inside a scanning electron microscope,
and the electron beam is used to fuse the ends of the nanotube to
tiny cantilever tips that do the stretching.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists said the force needed to break the nanotube was
many times greater than would be required to break a similar-sized
structure of steel, if it were possible to create one. Next up for
the researcher: to break a single-walled tube.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
