<HEADLINE>
LETTERMAN DUE BACK ON MONDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Top 10 reasons to skip ``The Tonight Show With Jay Leno'' next
week.
</P>
<P>
   No. 10: David Letterman will return to ``Late Show With David
Letterman'' on Monday, giving CBS a potential bonanza in the last
days of the February ratings and relegating Leno to the pale
imitations list. Letterman will ease back into the routine, taping
two shows, maybe three, a week, until he's fully recovered from a
quintuple heart bypass operation.
</P>
<P>
   No. 9: Letterman's first guest will be frequent ``Late Show''
contributor Regis Philbin, who was the last guest before Letterman
had the surgical procedure on Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   No. 8: Depending on how he feels after the first taping (which
will be done this Friday), Letterman is expected to tape and air
his second show Wednesday, Feb. 23, with Julia Roberts as principal
guest.
</P>
<P>
   No. 7: While Letterman is building up his stamina, the show will
use guest hosts in his absence. Bill Cosby goes first, on Tuesday,
Feb. 22. Philbin will guest-host on Thursday, Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6: Dave is aching to get back, although executive producer
Rob Burnett says that, since the operation, Letterman has had to
give up his first love, the rodeo. Though calf-roping is out of his
life forever, Burnett says Letterman ``got a rare opportunity to
experience what it would be like not to do'' a late-night talk
show. ``Late Night'' has aired on CBS for seven seasons. Before
that, Letterman was on NBC for 11 seasons in the spot now occupied
by Conan O'Brien. ``The experience,'' Burnett says, ``has
absolutely made him miss the job.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 5: Guest hosts probably won't do Top 10 lists.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4: Letterman is in great shape, hiking a mile to a mile and
a half a day to get his strength back. Burnett says that one huge
benefit, according to Letterman, is that bypass surgery is now so
non-invasive that the surgeons actually went in through his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3: The possibility exists that, in the manner of Johnny
Carson when he hosted ``The Tonight Show,'' Letterman may choose to
do four nights a week and have a guest host do the fifth. ``Dave's
been on the air for 18 years now,'' Burnett said. ``Four nights a
week is a conversation that makes sense having whether or not this
(operation) would have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 2: Carson himself might be a candidate for guest host, but
Burnett wouldn't bet on it. ``Dave is very fond of Johnny,'' he
said, ``but my guess is that Dave would feel uncomfortable imposing
on him.'' Carson underwent bupass surgery last year.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1: Dave may cut back on the number of guests for a while,
going with just one person in the chair and then a musical act at
the bottom of the show. ``We often do that,'' Burnett said, ``in
particular after vacations or weekends, whenever there are times
Dave will have a lot to talk about. After five weeks of gathering
stories, I imagine Dave will have a lot to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
