<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6566 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      02-14 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PATTERNS: Slacker Jr.: Not So Bad, by Comparison &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adults who like to think of America's young as a bunch of lazy,
cigarette-packing television addicts may be disappointed by a major
new study that finds that adolescents in the United States smoke
and watch television less than those in many other industrialized
nations.
</P>
<P>
   That still leaves lazy _ or, at least, sedentary _ and the
study, conducted by the World Health Organization, finds that
American teen-agers exercise less than their peers elsewhere. And
they eat more junk food.
</P>
<P>
   But American young people measure up rather well, certainly
better than they are depicted in much of the mass media, said Dr.
Mary Overpeck, an epidemiologist for the National Institutes of
Health, which ran the United States portion of the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worry about our kids,'' Overpeck said. ``This report really
gives us perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time American officials took full part in the
study, conducted every four years and involving 120,000 adolescents
in 26 countries and regions. In this country, 15,000 children, ages
11, 13 and 15, were interviewed at schools, and the data from 5,000
of them were included in the international study.
</P>
<P>
   American children fared well, or at least in the middle, in at
least two respects. Eleven-year-olds tried cigarettes at about the
same rate as children in other countries. But the 15-year-old
Americans smoked less than their counterparts, ranking 24th of 28
in the daily rate of smoking (about 12 percent). The highest rates
were in Austria and France.
</P>
<P>
   American youths also watched a little less television than most
of their counterparts: 15-year-olds ranked 20th and 11-year-olds
ranked 6th.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NUTRITION: For Some, Vegan Diet Relieves PMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Those who champion the low-fat vegetarian diet known as vegan
have long made broad health claims for the regimen. Now one of the
diet's biggest advocates is making a new claim; he says it can
greatly reduce menstrual pain and the symptoms of premenstrual
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the 33 women studied reported benefits, but most did,
said Neal D. Barnard, the diet's advocate and the president of the
Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine, which helped conduct
the study. ``In some of them, it was quite profound,'' Barnard
said.
</P>
<P>
   On average, researchers said, the women reported having pain one
and a half fewer days a month. The study, by Georgetown University
Medical Center researchers, appears this month in Obstetrics &AMP;
Gynecology.
</P>
<P>
   The vegan diet includes grains, vegetables, legumes and fruits,
but no animal products, which include dairy and eggs. Barnard said
those women who benefited saw improvements in a month.
</P>
<P>
   The women studied were divided into two groups. One ate a vegan
diet, and the other ate normally, but its members were given
placebos. The women then switched.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said they had based the study on their theory
that if women reduced the fat in their diets, their bodies would
produce less prostaglandin, a chemical implicated in menstrual pain
that is made from fat traces stored in cell membranes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REACTIONS: When Alcohol Knocks You Off Your Feet &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Falling-down drunk, as the expression has it, is the kind of
condition that on its face would seem to require little in the way
of explanation. One drinks too much, one tries to stand up, one
does not succeed. The rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers at the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota, seeking
insights into broader questions about how the brain and the nervous
system control blood pressure and the heart, decided to study how
alcohol could knock people off their feet.
</P>
<P>
   They found that alcohol, combined with the stress caused when
one stood up, could cause a drop in blood pressure, even among
young people who drank a relatively moderate amount (two or three
beers an hour). And that, in turn, can lead to faintness. Their
findings appeared in the journal Circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Under ordinary circumstances, when someone sands up, blood
vessels constrict, maintaining the blood pressure that keeps blood
pumping to the brain and organs. Alcohol seems to stop the blood
vessels from constricting normally, the researchers at Mayo and at
the University of Iowa found.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Virend K. Somers, a Mayo cardiologist and co-author of the
study, said the researchers' only interest in alcohol was how it
illuminated the overall working of blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the message here is not whether or not people
should drink,'' Somers said. ``It's merely to understand what's
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSEQUENCES: An Ominous Obsession at Women's Gym &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When Dr. Amanda J. Gruber, a Massachusetts psychiatrist, meets
with patients, the last thing she wants to do is discourage them
from exercising.
</P>
<P>
   She tells them to go to the gym and offers compelling reasons:
``It decreases depression. It decreases anxiety. It decreases the
risk of osteoporosis.'' Then, she adds a caution: ``Don't get
caught up in whole body-image thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Gruber has found, many women do just that.
</P>
<P>
   In the current issue of Psychotherapy and Psychosomatics, she
reports that 50 of 75 weightlifters interviewed said they had used
potentially dangerous substances like anabolic steroids or
ephedrine. And many had eating and body-image disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers focused on women, most in the Boston area, who
had competed in at least one bodybuilding or fitness contest or who
said they lifted weights five or more days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five of those who admitted drug use said they had taken
steroids. Many reported side effects like kidney problems,
deepening voice, inappropriate hair growth and changes in
genitalia.
</P>
<P>
   Gruber, of McLean Hospital, an affiliate of Harvard, said many
of the women felt that the side effects were simply the price they
paid to achieve athletic goals.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that 65 of those interviewed were extremely
dissatisfied with their bodies. Gruber said she had met
professionals who had become immersed in gym culture and taken jobs
as trainers to spend more time in the gym.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PREVENTION: Watching Gallstones Prepare for Attack &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By the time most gallstones make their painful presence known,
there are not always a lot of options. An estimated half a million
Americans a year, mostly women, end up having to have their
gallbladders removed in what is the most common operation in the
nation, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers using new, high-powered equipment report that
they have photographed gallstones as they form, raising hope that a
better understanding of their origins may help prevent them.
</P>
<P>
   The research was done at the Technion-Israel Institute of
Technology and is reported in the current issue of the journal
Hepatology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research aims to answer why and how gallstones form, so
that physicians can direct their efforts toward inhibiting the
process at the onset through medication and dietary changes,'' Dr.
Yeshayahi Talmon said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, researchers looking into gallstone formation had to
rely a video-type technology with a relatively low resolution.
Using advanced cryo-transmission electron microscopy, they said,
they can see in thousand-fold greater detail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
