</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6578 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BODIES-SIZES-COX     02-14 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BODIES-SIZES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For many with eating disorders, photographer's sessions a ray of
hope
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The pecan tree outside photographer Holly Sasnett's
studio bears the marks of life _ knots, bumps, bulges,
discolorations from diseases and everyday wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   She points out that tree when the subjects she's capturing on
black and white film berate their own bodies for being too fat, too
flat, too this, too that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if the tree was perfectly straight and thin,'' she
tells them, ``it wouldn't be so pleasing to the eye. Imperfection,
if that's what you want to call it, is what makes the tree so
beautiful to me.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, Sasnett has photographed women who
suffer from a variety of eating disorders. Some are painfully thin
and recovering from anorexia. Others wrestle with compulsive
overeating or bulimia, throwing up after they eat.
</P>
<P>
   All are nude.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the women loathe their bodies to the point of
self-mutilation. The decision to bare them at all, let alone to the
permanence of photographs, is a form of therapy that appears to be
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I've talked to has been totally transformed by it,''
says Dina Zeckhausen, a psychologist who specializes in counseling
people with eating disorders. She decided to try the photography
idea with clients after hearing about a similar project in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some don't necessarily love what they see at first,'' she
admits. ``But the women have been able to see themselves
differently or at least with more compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   The portraits that Sasnett calls ``Body Revisited'' will be on
display for the first time during Eating Disorders Awareness Week,
which features numerous art events and seminars through Feb. 26.
The presentations are coordinated by the Atlanta Anti-Eating
Disorders League that Zeckhausen founded three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, it's estimated that between 5 million to 10 million
women and 1 million men suffer from the eating disorders of
anorexia, bulimia or compulsive overeating. Anorexia, characterized
by intentional and significant weight loss, afflicts as many as one
in every 250 girls and young women. Of the sufferers, between 5
percent to 9 percent of them will die of starvation, cardiac arrest
or suicide, according to the American Psychiatric Association.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the disorder is rampant among girls in private
schools, Zeckhausen says. ``Media images are getting thinner and
thinner. Grocery stores are full of lite, non-fat, low-fat versions
of everything. Kids are bombarded with messages that fat is bad,''
she says. ``The pressure, especially at private schools, to be thin
is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some people have mistakenly assumed Sasnett suffers
anorexia because of her tiny dimensions ( 5'4'', 100 pounds; size 0
or 2) she says she just comes from a small, thin family, and that
she's never experienced any food obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My size does create a problem for some of these women,
though,'' says the 35-year-old Sasnett. ``I can see it in their
faces when they open the door and see me for the first time. It's
like, `Oh.'''
</P>
<P>
   A commercial freelance photographer and an Atlanta native,
Sasnett's usual work is shooting boardrooms and executives for
annual reports, brochures and catalogues of corporations and
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   For this undertaking, she has to be two-parts therapist,
one-part artist.
</P>
<P>
   Each woman is photographed individually in a safe environment;
sessions can last up to four hour for one session. One woman did
request a subsequent session one year later after she had lost 35
pounds. ``She cried and cried. It was still hard for her to look at
herself. But later she called and said she felt okay about them,''
Sasnett says.
</P>
<P>
   Before getting out her Hasselblad 2 1/4-inch medium format
camera, Sasnett talks to the women at length about their particular
eating disorders and which part of their body most bothers them.
Women can choose to leave their clothes on. Sasnett also takes
Polaroid shots throughout the session so women can see themselves
in the poses they choose.
</P>
<P>
   She also meets with the women to provide positive reinforcement
when viewing the developed film. That's important, Sasnett says, to
tune out the endless ``negative tape recordings'' that play in
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Sasnett charged $300 for the portrait sessions and
development of prints. But when she saw how much it benefitted the
women, she began offering the service for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money issue was an easy way for people not to do it,'' she
says. ``And after working with a few women and seeing how cathartic
it was for them, and after hearing their stories, it became part of
my heart, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasnett would like to publish a ``Body Revisited'' book that
would include the women's struggles in their own words.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, she decided to drop her original idea of using
shadowed faces, and now rarely shoots above the shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``These women have shared so many stories with me. I feel
incredibly protective of them,'' she says. ``A lot of them are
sexual abuse survivors and many have abandonment issues. Some cut
on themselves, and many start apologizing for things even before
they begin to undress.''
</P>
<P>
   Anonymity also allows the portraits to be universal, Sasnett
believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the purpose of not showing faces or heads is so people
can project their own thoughts and images on the photographs. Maybe
someone with an eating disorder who views them will think, `If
these women are strong enough to do this, maybe I should get help.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
