<HEADER>
A6581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     02-14 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Feb. 15. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Grozny) _ After suffering through long nights
of bombing and shootouts the residents of Grozny on Monday faced a
new problem: Russian commanders ordered that their city be sealed
and its population evacuated. Soldiers were ordered to turn away
any civilians who tried to return to the city. Thousands of
civilians who endured the war will be instructed to leave. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GA-STORMS (Camilla, Ga.) _ Tornadoes slashed through southwest
Georgia early today, killing at least 22 people and injuring more
than 100. The Mitchell County town of Camilla appeared to be
hardest hit, with a tornado cutting a five-mile path through a
housing development south of town. (Summary from wires.) By Kevin
Sack.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-TEENS-SHOT (Littleton, Colo.) _ Two Columbine High students
were found dead early today after a shooting at a sandwich shop
about two blocks south of the school, still reeling from the worst
school shooting in U.S. history. Investigators could not offer a
motive but ruled out murder-suicide. (Summary from wires.) By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUS-POLLUTION (Undated) _ Buses powered by compressed natural
gas _ long viewed as the cleanest alternative to diesel buses _
don't provide any more environmental benefits than buses powered by
a combination of diesel and electicrity, according to a study that
could have broad implications for vehicle fleets nationwide.
Municipal bus fleets around the country have come under pressure to
switch to compressed natural gas as a way to reduce pollution, with
Los Angeles and other municipalities converting their whole fleets
to this technology. But New York City, which has enormous influence
on the bus market because of the size of its purchases, has held
off switching to compressed natural gas, citing costs and questions
about the technology. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-STYLE (Columbia, S.C.) _ As much John McCain's openness
is about free publicity, more and more now it appears to be about
something broader _ a half-thought-out effort to turn back the
clock on how American presidential campaigns are conducted in
search of a more personable, less antagonistic, less scripted time.
Indeed, there are whole days now when his entire candidacy revolves
not around issues like tax cuts or foreign policy but on questions
of how political campaigns should be waged. The senator's signature
drive to ban big money from politics is just the start of it.
McCain has announced unilaterally that he will no longer run
negative ads and the decision seems cathartic, lightening his mood.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The price of crude oil jumped over
$30 a barrel for the first time since the Persian Gulf war in
January 1991 as the fear of tight inventories leading to actual
shortages trumped traders' hope for an increase in crude oil
production from major oil producers. The price neared $30 in
mid-January and then slipped. But in the last week it made another
run, only to be held back, apparently, by comments from some OPEC
officials, who suggested that the major producers would decide to
increase production when they meet at the end of next month. But on
Monday there were several reports that put a damper on the prospect
of an OPEC production increase and the price of crude for March
delivery jumped 81 cents, to $30.25 a barrel. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Washington) _ In a vigorous defense of their
shuttered gene therapy program, officials at the University of
Pennsylvania on Monday said that while there were lapses, they did
not in any way contribute to the death of an 18-year-old patient
and amounted to little more than ``minor deviations'' in
bookkeeping. In a 28-page written response to the FDA's decision to
shut down all human gene therapy experiments at Penn, scientists
there pledged to draft new procedures that will allow them to
better track patients in their studies. But at the same time they
challenged the food and drug agency on several crucial points. By
Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ELDERLY-CANCER (Undated) _ Though post cancer patients are
over 65, most tests of possible cancer treatments bar people that
age. Now researchers are the National Institutes of Health are
trying to rectify that situation. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ His head low and his voice
halting, Officer Sean Carroll broke a year of public silence Monday
to describe how he led his three partners into the shooting of
Amadou Diallo, who was struck by 16 of 41 police bullets fired at
him as he stood, unarmed, in the lobby of his apartment building in
the Bronx. With Diallo's parents and his own family in the front
row of the court room, Officer Carroll choked out his testimony as
he described his realization of his mistake. The testimony is the
centerpiece of the defense in the trial of Officer Carroll and his
three colleague, who are charged with Diallo's murder. By Jane
Fritsch.
</P>
