<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-CO     02-14 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Bar-fightin' in the East Texas
woods
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A hilarious chapter in Larry McMurtry's 1970
novel, ``Moving On,'' recounts a Houston bar fight that begins with
a dispute over whether a bowl of chili contains a sufficient
serving of beans and ends with sustained gunfire by any number of
participants.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I hired a Yankee reporter at the newspaper in my little
hometown of Lufkin, I'd make that bit of McMurtry writing required
reading for the newcomer _ and just short of a requirement, I'd
suggest he stay out of the local bars.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what we're talking about aren't bars like they have
back East. These are East Texas honky-tonks, where the honkies go
to get tonked.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one of my favorite honky-tonk stories, not fiction like
McMurtry writes but true. (Everything I tell is always the truth,
or at least the way I remember it.)
</P>
<P>
   This fellow was an accountant, had called on a client in a
neighboring small town and was heading back home through a remote
portion of the Pineywoods when he decided to stop at a roadside
tavern for a few beers at late evening.
</P>
<P>
   He was dressed in a suit and tie, as accountants do, and most
likely the only recent customer so attired.
</P>
<P>
   He was sitting at the bar, sipping his suds and smoking a
cigarette when a quartet of log haulers, as grouchy as they were
grimy, arrived on the scene, their overalls soaked through with the
sweat of honest labor. No pencil pushers were they _ they pushed
down pine trees for a living.
</P>
<P>
   One of their number, in the process of lighting a cigarette
himself, reached over and snatched the closest ashtray on the bar,
the very ashtray that the accountant was tending.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at them, they looked at him. From that point, there
was probably nothing anybody could have done. Eye contact had been
made. Such are the prelims of honky-tonking's favorite contact
sport.
</P>
<P>
   The log haulers gathered in a booth. After a moment, the
accountant walked over, retrieved his ashtray and returned to the
bar. Not a word was spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Another moment passed and the ritual was repeated in reverse,
the ashtray trophy now back at the booth. Then, the accountant
stepped to the booth once again to claim what was rightfully his.
</P>
<P>
   But as he grabbed for the ashtray, a log hauler grabbed him by
his necktie, smashed his face into the table and then, rising to
the occasion, jerked him longways along the bar, scattering stools,
spilling their beer and his blood, along with his briefcase full of
papers inscribed with important numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The accountant didn't distinguish himself, but neither did he
die trying. He lived to tell about it through fat, swollen lips the
following day, explaining his battered face to a friend at the
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time I'll know better,'' he said, nodding his aching
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hope so,'' the friend said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, before I go in, I'm taking off my necktie.''
</P>
<P>
   Moral to the story: At an East Texas honky-tonk, make sure they
check you at the door for dangerous weapons. If you don't have any,
they'll give you some.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
