<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6584 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-DNA-BEADS-NYT &LR;      02-14 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DNA-BEADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINY BEADS ALLOW CLOSE STUDY OF DNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The more biologists understand of living cells, the more
daunting seems the task of figuring out everything they do. The
average human cell is too small to be seen, yet at any moment up to
30,000 of its 100,000 genes may be flicking on or off, executing
the cell's housekeeping needs or responding to messages from other
cells.
</P>
<P>
   How can a machine so tiny and so intricate ever be analyzed? And
even if by prodigious effort one human cell were ever completely
understood, there are at least 200 different types in the human
body.
</P>
<P>
   The invention of a series of ever more ingenious methods _
techniques to splice genes, produce them in bulk and measure the
activity of individual genes _ has taught biologists not to
despair. Now a new technique may be about to join this array of
powerful tools, although it remains to be seen if its effectiveness
will match its conceptual elegance.
</P>
<P>
   The method, described in the Feb. 15 issue of Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences, involves attaching very large sets of
DNA molecules, such as all of a cell's active genes, to invisibly
small plastic beads five microns (millionths of a meter) in
diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Once anchored to the beads, the genes can be compared, sorted
and even sequenced en masse, meaning the order of the DNA units on
each bead can be determined. Since thousands of genes are handled
at a time, the bead system can generate vast amounts of
information.
</P>
<P>
   The bead system operates on a test-tube scale, avoiding the
expensive machines and labor of conventional technology. And much
of the processing is done by interactions of the DNA itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Let the DNA work for us instead of us working for
the DNA,''' said Dr. Sydney Brenner, the inventor of the technique.
Brenner, a biologist, has been a major figure in efforts to
decipher the workings of the genetic code.
</P>
<P>
   Brenner's ideas have been put into practice by scientists at
Lynx Therapeutics, of Hayward, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. George Church, a DNA sequencing expert at
Harvard University, the new technology should in principle be far
cheaper than the conventional methods being used to decode the
entire human genetic inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Church said he did not know in practice how far advanced the new
method might be. ``The question is whether they have something
really amazing or whether they hit a little more trouble than they
thought,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barbara Mazur, director of genomics and bioinformatics at
DuPont's agricultural division, which is using the new technology,
said work was going well and ``is giving us a global view of gene
expression in plants.'' As with most novel methods, there had been
``glitches,'' but the technique's inherent advantage was its
sensitivity to gene transcripts produced in small quantity, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The basis of Lynx's technology is to attach large sets of DNA
molecules _ which can be all of a cell's active genes, or all the
fragments of a genome _ to minuscule beads. The process exploits
the fact that DNA likes to exist in the form of a double-stranded
molecule, with the sequence of chemical letters in one strand
exactly matching a counterpart sequence in the other. Strands of
complementary sequence will bind tightly to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Lynx's method for attaching the genes to beads is ingenious and
complicated, but in essence involves building up 32-letter
sequences of DNA on a set of beads. These sequences are known as
anti-tags. The counterpart tags are attached to the genes under
study.
</P>
<P>
   One use of the beads is to compare large sets of genes that
differ in only a few genes of interest, for example, those that are
active in the normal and cancerous versions of a cell.
</P>
<P>
   First, a library of beads is made containing all the active
genes from both types of cell. The bead-linked genes are then
rendered single-stranded so that each is ready to bind with its
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Single-stranded copies of genes are then obtained again from
both types of cell, but this time a red chemical dye is attached to
all the cancer cells' genes and a blue dye to those of the normal
cells.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the beads, when exposed to the colored genes, will
attract both red and blue versions. But a few beads will capture
only red genes, which are those expressed just in the cancer cells,
and a few will bind only blue genes, which are those the cancer
cells have suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   Though existing gene chips can also be used to track the
expression of genes, they require knowing in advance the DNA
sequence of the genes to be monitored. Brenner's method does not
depend on knowing any gene's structure, but captures almost all of
a cell's 30,000 or so active genes.
</P>
<P>
   The same method can be applied to searching for defective genes
that contribute to disease. The conventional approach, based on
searching for SNP's (pronounced ``snips''), or single nucleotide
polymorphisms, requires identifying some 100,000 SNP's across the
human genome, an extremely costly task. The bead method focuses
directly on the genes that differ between the normal and a diseased
population.
</P>
<P>
   When genes of interest have been isolated by the bead system,
the next step is to identify them. Brenner has invented a method
for sequencing all the genes on a set of beads in parallel, meaning
that all the beads are sequenced at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The method depends on adaptors that bind to a specific sequence
of the four DNA letters on the tail of each bead's gene. The
adaptors, of which there are 256 different kinds, are identified by
fluorescent probes, whose presence on the immobilized beads is
recorded by a camera.
</P>
<P>
   Four such cycles are required to identify the first 16 letters
in the tail of each gene. This is enough to identify every gene
whose DNA sequence is known and all genes once the human genome is
completed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
