<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Program provides mapping tools for business &LR; 
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   By LONNIE BROWN &LR;  &QC;  &QL; 
 &UR; The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla. &LR;  &QC;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeLorme, the company that publishes maps on CD-ROMs for home
users, is offering a mapping program for that lets businesses
generate mailing lists, locate customers and plan delivery routes.
</P>
<P>
   XMap Business carries a suggested retail price of $99.95 and
covers the entire United States on seven disks. Business users who
have customer data on ACT!, Goldmine, Microsoft Access, Excel or
other programs can import the data directly into the mapping
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xmap Business is the answer for our long-time customers who
have called on us to create mapping and data tools to assist them
in their business activities,'' said David DeLorme, chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a cost of just $99.95 for the entire U.S., they can not
only see their current and potential business geographically, but
they can mark out territories, create targeted mailing lists from
the program's built-in database, plan business travel and even make
maps to post on their Web sites.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLorme is marketing the software with professionals in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Real-estate brokers, for instance, can create customized maps of
neighborhoods and provide clients with driving routes between
properties. Owners of upscale stores can use the business database
to select business and residential addresses from geographic areas
with upper-income levels.
</P>
<P>
   The program, like Street Atlas USA and Topo USA 2.0, can be
loaded on a laptop computer and connected to a GPS receiver so the
user's exact location can be pinpointed on the map.
</P>
<P>
   The program is available for Windows computers running at 120
MHz or faster and with a minimum of 32 megabytes of RAM. The
program also requires 130 megabytes of hard disk space.
</P>
<P>
   For information, visit the company's Web site: www.delorme.com
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor at The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
