<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-(TRIM     02-14 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS ORDER EVACUATION OF GROZNY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ The residents of Grozny faced a new trial
Monday: Russian commanders ordered the city sealed and its
population evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers were instructed to turn away any civilians who tried to
return. Civilians who endured the war will be told to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Nikolai A. Zaitsev, a senior Interior Ministry officer
here, said the city has become too dangerous for its inhabitants.
It will be off-limits for two weeks while Interior Ministry troops
comb the city for weapons, unexploded bombs and booby-traps.
</P>
<P>
   But the move was also a precaution against rebel infiltration,
the Russian military conceded. And Monday, leaflets were
distributed in the city warning that militants were planning a
guerrilla campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movement to Grozny will be restricted until March 1,'' Zaitsev
said, waving an order from the high command. ``Those civilians who
are already in the city will be gradually evacuated. There are
refugee camps, and if someone does not have permanent residence we
will send him there. We will provide transportation for those that
cannot walk.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan to quarantine and evacuate Grozny was a surprise to
shellshocked residents who only recently left their basement
shelters to try to rebuild their lives. The rebels were unable to
defy the Russian military, but many elderly people here said they
had no intention of obeying the authorities and heading out of
town.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a matter of civil disobedience. Many simply said they
have no place to resettle and little desire to end up in an
overcrowded refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not leaving,'' said Tamara N. Zheromyskaya, a 57-year-old
veterinarian. She said she was not well enough to travel and wanted
to stay with her son. Beyond that, she added, ``I have nowhere to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   To anyone but the stubborn residents hanging on, Grozny seems
beyond restoration. Some of the half-destroyed buildings are so
rickety that demolition teams have been blowing them up. Huge
explosions rock the city, sending dust billowing into the sky. With
each explosion, Grozny seems to melt into the earth as more of its
cityscape is erased.
</P>
<P>
   Looting has been a serious problem and law and order is just
being established. The first complement of pro-Russian Chechen
police arrived Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian aid convoys have begun to snake through the city, but
food and water are in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Still, thousands of civilians who braved the war seem determined
to endure the peace. They do not have much: a one-room apartment,
perhaps, and maybe some furniture. But they are determined to hold
onto the little they have, despite the hazards.
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty. Zaitsev said, for example, that Russian
soldiers had found 11,000 explosive devices in the last few weeks.
Some are booby traps laid by the departing rebels, he said. Others
are unexploded ordnance, like the 500-pound Russian bomb that was
found across from the militia in the Zavodskoi district.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fear of renewed fighting is another concern. After the fall of
Grozny, most of the fighting shifted to the south. The Russian
troops blazed a path of destruction as they chased the remnants of
the rebel force in Grozny through towns like Katyr-Yurt and
Shaami-Yurt. Trying to regain the initiative, the rebels briefly
took the town of Gekhi-Chu. After they left, Russian artillery
pounded the settlement, causing numerous civilian casualties,
according to Russian media reports from the area.
</P>
<P>
   Leaflets distributed in Grozny on Monday warned that the
militants might strike on Feb. 23, the anniversary of Stalin's
attempt to deport the Chechen people to Kazakhstan. Stalin's move
was eventually reversed by Nikita Khrushchev, but not before it
fanned the rancor between the Russians and many Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commanders of the illegal armed formations want to draw
your towns, settlements and streets into the chaos of war and
violence,'' the leaflets read. ``Stay quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Akhmed Khizriyev, a 47-year-old construction engineer, and Asya,
his wife, fled during the war but returned to Grozny on Monday to
try to retrieve some of their belongings. They were surprised when
soldiers told them the checkpoints around the city were being
closed to prevent the militants from infiltrating and carrying out
partisan attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Viktor Kazantsev, the commander of Russian forces in
the North Caucasus, drove the point home Monday in an appearance
before Russian television reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bandits are sneaking through disguised as civilians in order
to take out their wounded who are still here and to strengthen
their positions in Grozny,'' Kazantsev said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Having suffered through several wars, however, Grozny residents
seem more concerned about the Russian evacuation plan than the
possibility of more fighting. They do not want to part with what is
left of their home or end up in a refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   Klavdiya M. Nefyodova, 88, summed up the prevailing mood: ``I do
not want to leave my belongings here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
