   But perhaps most important, while the programmers were slaving
away in Redmond, another system emerged: Linux, the open source
operating system with its roots in Unix which has been
commercialized by companies like Red Hat.
</P>
<P>
   Linux's share of the server market more than doubled to 17
percent last year from 7 percent in 1997, while Windows NT remained
steady at 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the market has been basically content with the idea of
Windows 2000, but it had a scare at the end of last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner Group, a technology consulting firm, said that one in
four corporations would run into problems with compatibility
between the new system and its existing software. Its advice was to
wait until the company has ironed out the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   And Michael Dell, chief executive of Dell Computer, said that
Linux was gaining ground. ``We don't see a massive immediate
acceleration due to Windows 2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither development told the market anything it didn't know, but
both emphasized Windows 2000 is anything but a sure thing. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 800) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company faces other key strategic issues this year. There
are still some big questions about Windows Millennium, the consumer
operating system, with the latest reports indicating that the
company has scaled back some very large and ambitious plans to
something more manageable.
</P>
<P>
   Windows Me, as it is known, is itself a stopgap before the more
advanced product, code-named Whistler, which is due next year.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Windows CE (for Consumer Electronics), its
operating system for handheld devices and set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   A new version, CE 3.0 is also due this year, but it has been
relatively disappointing so far, and again, MS is by no means alone
in this market. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company's restructuring, and Bill Gates' shift earlier this
year, are part of a redrawing of Microsoft to adapt to what
analysts call the post-PC age: towards the higher end of the
market, the servers which make the Internet run, and the smaller
devices which power the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   In both, Windows gives it a steady but by no means dominant
position, ironically, in view of the antitrust suit that is still
winding through the courts. The difference is that the antitrust
suit, fundamentally, focuses on the past, and on the company's
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The new questions are about its very soul, the technology that
has driven its dominance. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
