<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6597 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWSSTAND15-COX     02-14 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time takes a look at the 21st century
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one expects us to live like the Jetsons in the 21st century,
but some of the experts whom Time ($3.50) solicited for its
``Visions 21'' report foresee everything from underground houses to
electric cars in a world dominated by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cox staffers Priscilla Painton and Richard Zoglin edited
the collection of essays by people such as theater director Julie
Taymor, author Nicholas Lemann and musician Moby.
</P>
<P>
   Taymor predicts that live theater will still thrive in a society
of couch potatoes, Lemann foresees capitalists as the country's
next elite, and Moby expects compact discs to disappear and music
to be reproduced digitally on demand. Other predictions? Medical
breakthroughs will practically eliminate the need for makeup,
teenagers will disappear as children grow up faster, and kitchens
will become smaller as we get most of our food from the home-meal
industry. All will not be rosy, however: Novelist Mark Leyner
predicts that professional wrestling will be the single most
powerful influence on sports.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hefty reading: In a special 75th-anniversary double issue, The
New Yorker ($3.95) celebrates its past with a treasury of fine
writing. In a surprisingly favorable essay on Martha Stewart, Joan
Didion considers all of the criticism leveled at the style maven
and concludes that, instead of epitomizing the 1950s housewife,
Stewart actually represents the female pioneer spirit. ``The dreams
and the fears into which Martha Stewart taps are not of `feminine'
domesticity, but of female power, of the woman who sits down at the
table with the men and, still in her apron, walks away with the
chips.''
</P>
<P>
   Other entertaining reading includes Woody Allen's first piece of
fiction published in the magazine, in 1980, Roger Angell's memories
of growing up with a daring dad, Wendy Wasserstein's account of
midlife motherhood and 10 selections from great New Yorker writers
including E.B. White, James Baldwin, John Cheever, Janet Flanner
and Vladimir Nabokov.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vanity fare: Yes, there is the predictable celebrity profile _
of Madonna and Rupert Everett _ in the March issue of Vanity Fair
($3.95), but, as usual, there are more substantial articles as
well. Sam Kashner's account of Natalie Wood's final hours, while
inconclusive, is compelling reading, as is Sam Tanenhaus' tale of
adultery and suicide at Hillsdale College.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Net loss: Last week, Yahoo, eBay and several other giants of
e-commerce were shut down by hackers. Can such hostile invasions be
stopped? Newsweek ($3.50) looks at the future of Internet
disruptions and follows the government's efforts to catch the
cybervandals. In a sidebar, Internet architect Bill Joy suggests
ways to keep from getting hacked: Don't open e-mail attachments
unless you know the source, he says, and use a hard-to-guess
password that contains a mixture of numbers and letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  No barriers: What happens when the doctor becomes the patient?
Biography ($2.99) offers an uplifting answer in a profile of Dr.
Alicia Conill, 42, a physician who was diagnosed with multiple
sclerosis more than 10 years ago. She had to give up her practice,
but she has since opened a nonprofit institute where those with
chronic illnesses and their caregivers are assigned roles and sent
on field trips in wheelchairs to learn what disabled people
encounter every day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Back in the saddle: Penelope Cruz, who stars opposite Matt
Damon in the upcoming film ``All the Pretty Horses,'' took her
debut American role seriously. According to GQ ($3), the Spanish
actress, who plays a wealthy Mexican ranch heiress, rode horses
five hours a day for weeks. Cruz even wore her Western outfit when
she went bowling.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
