<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6600 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-DINOSAURFIND-1100(2Ta     02-14 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAURFIND-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSSIL HUNTERS UNCOVERING NEAR-COMPLETE FOSSIL OF JUVENILE T. REX
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by DINOSAUR FIND-INSIGHTS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was fossil fever, surely, that led him stumbling around the
Black Hills of South Dakota for six years, dodging snakes,
scorpions and prickly pear cactus spines on a relentless and
finally successful search for the bones of the most fearsome
dinosaur that ever stalked the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he hunted only for Tyrannosaurus rex, the
dinosaur that paleontologists say most captures the public
imagination for its ferocity, its scarcity and its guest
appearances in ``Jurassic Park'' and ``The Lost World: Jurassic
Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 23 ``T. rex'' fossils have ever been found _ most in South
Dakota _ since the first was discovered in 1904. All are fossils of
adult rexes; most of the fossilized skeletons are not even halfway
complete.
</P>
<P>
   The rarity of finding the almost-mythological beast inspired
self-taught bone hunter Kim Hollrah to look only for T. rex.
Through the 1990s, the Iowa native got to know Texans Ron Frithiof,
an Austin condominium developer and rancher, and Mike Harrell, a
Houston fossil trader, who were as enchanted by T. rex as he and
eventually became his partners.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollrah was alone in the heavily eroded black and gray hills
of western South Dakota that day in July 1998, the day that would
change their world.
</P>
<P>
   Following a tip from another fossil hunter, Hollrah walked along
the back expanses of a private ranch, his eyes toward the ground. A
claw from a T. rex appeared at his feet. It was raining and so
muddy that if he hadn't been watching, he would have stepped on it.
It could have stuck to the bottom of his shoe, so that at night,
when he took his shoes off and found it, he would have pulled his
hair out, saying ``Where? Where did this T. rex claw come from?''
It would have been maddening to be so close and miss it.
</P>
<P>
   The claw. It was obviously T. rex. But it was half the size of
the claw of a mature T. rex. He picked up the telephone and called
his partners in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a really hot lead here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What the three would eventually unearth is something never
before found. They located the first nearly complete fossil of a
juvenile T. rex and brought it home, where its jumble of bones is
being chipped out of earth that held it for millions of years. The
find stands to rewrite whole chapters of what we know about
dinosaurs and, possibly, make its discoverers multimillionaires in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The back story here goes very far back. It goes back 66 million
years, to the day of a violent death in the then near-tropical
bayous of South Dakota. Investigators say it may have happened like
this:
</P>
<P>
   A young T. rex is left alone in the nest. He's probably between
5 and 10 years old; no one in this day and age can tell. He weighs
just 1,500 pounds, far less than his 7,000-pound parents. He is 23
feet long and 10 feet tall. As such, he probably isn't strong
enough to go on the kinds of hunts that attract a grown T. rex.
</P>
<P>
   T. Mom is a killer at the top of the food chain, the meanest
animal in the bayou. In an Upper Cretaceous-period display of
family values, she drags parts of her kills back to the nest to
share with her youngster. She must have loved her boy (and later,
when his pelvic bone is examined, it is determined he is a boy).
</P>
<P>
   She may have begun to teach her kid rex how to hunt on earlier
trips. He has already broken a rib and had time for the bone to
reknit. Every T. rex found has been found with broken and healed
rib bones, probably the result of ramming into a kill or bashing
another T. rex for dominance or simply running too fast and falling
down.
</P>
<P>
   The kid rex gulps his dinner of hadrosaurs, the duck-billed
dinosaur, a dinosaur large enough that only Mom or Dad could have
killed it.
</P>
<P>
   A T. rex has jaws that detach, somewhat like a snake's. He can
swallow large chunks of food. He has just chomped and swallowed a
whole hoof, one that will be found 66 million years later
compressed as if chewed, and also etched with stomach acid as if it
has been in the digestive track. The kid rex is apparently in
midmeal, with the remainder of his uneaten dino dinner scattered
around him.
</P>
<P>
   The scent of blood hangs in the swamp air. That's dangerous. T.
rex had an exceptionally large channel in his skull to carry
olfactory nerves, meaning the dinosaur likely had a highly
sensitive sense of smell. And T. rex dads may have been similar to
modern-day carnivorous animal dads. Like polar bears or lions, they
may have killed their young to get rid of any future competition
for food or mates.
</P>
<P>
   The kid rex is attacked, possibly by his dad, and torn apart,
chewed up and spit out. Pieces of him are left stacked one atop
another, in far worse shape than the average Thanksgiving turkey
carcass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a suicide,'' Hollrah says, shaking his head over a
pile of bones that look as if they'd been carried around in a
garbage bag before they fossilized. ``This was a homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just a theory, of course. Maybe the kid rex was torn
apart after he had already choked on the duck-bill hoof and died.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he died first of a respiratory infection. Paleontologists
have several leading theories on what caused the extinction of
dinosaurs. Some believe an asteroid collided with the Earth,
causing mass dinosaur death. Others say migrating dinosaurs spread
diseases that rapidly infected and killed off the population.
</P>
<P>
   But he did die. Eventually, his bones were covered up with
leaves, and finally a sandy loam. The coverage might have happened
quickly, because bones that are covered quickly are the bones most
likely to fossilize and survive. It may have been a flood that
deposited earth and created a grave site undisturbed for millions
of years. Until wind and rain and cycles of freezing and thawing
and the shovels of self-taught bone hunters began uncovering his
story.
</P>
<P>
   His story already is telling dinosaur hunters this: that T. rex
may well have been warm-blooded (like a mammal) _ a hunter that
cared for her young. This hypothesis debunks earlier theories that
T. rex was cold-blooded (like a reptile) _ a scavenger with
offspring that had to make their own way.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   What followed after Hollrah found the claw were leases and
lawyers and a $2,000 payment to the ranch owner to establish the
claim.
</P>
<P>
   Hollrah, 40, Frithiof, 51, and Harrell, 36, sank shovels into
the hardened sandy loam above where dinosaurs once walked. T. rex
roamed the Canadian and American West, particularly the Rocky
Mountain region and south as far as the Big Bend region of Texas.
Other Tyrannosaurus lived in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   South Dakota, on the fringe of the T. rex range, has proved to
be rich in fossil finds because of the large expanses of open
spaces where erosion has torn away layers of earth and time.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear to the team that this site held not just the
rarity of a juvenile T. rex, but also the rarity of a nearly
complete skeleton. Somewhere between 70 and 90 percent of the bones
were emerging. As they dug, they knew that they were on the brink
of something so astounding that it might be a good idea to call in
a well-known scientist who could help verify their find. They
needed the kiss of credibility from some big name in science.
Hollrah has a ninth-grade education, although he learned volumes
about fossils by reading and by making discoveries in the field.
Frithiof had been trading in fossils for only a few years, and this
was his first dig. Hollrah hiked to a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bakker, a Yale-educated scientist known as ``Bob the Bone
Hunter,'' picked up his telephone at his Boulder, Colo., home.
</P>
<P>
   The excited voice on the other end of the phone was calling from
near Belle Fourche, S.D. Bakker felt skepticism rising. It wasn't
likely that this fossil hunter had really found a nearly complete
fossil of a juvenile T. rex. Imagine the odds on that one. It would
be easier to win a lottery, Bakker said.
</P>
<P>
   Bakker booked a flight to South Dakota, and once there he was
stunned. But not for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me from between 7 to 7.5 seconds to recognize the
significance of the find.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The team wasn't halfway done digging out chunks of earth
containing bones when the winter of 1998 approached and the threat
of frozen ground caused them to stop. They decided to replant the
4-foot-deep dig with native vegetation and throw some cow chips
down to disguise the site. They dug trenches to keep water away.
What if there were a winter flood to damage the site? What if
freezing and thawing damaged the bones? After all, this kid rex was
a million-dollar baby they couldn't leave exposed to the South
Dakota winter.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1999, the kid rex bones were found to be
undisturbed. In all, the crew carried out 39 plaster-coated
packages of T. rex bones still surrounded by earth and shipped them
to Texas for further excavation. In the tradition of fossil
hunters, they gave a nickname to their kid rex. They called him
Tinker, after Frithiof's own childhood nickname.
</P>
<P>
   The bones were shipped to Harrell's Houston home. On the day
that a prefabricated shed arrived to serve as an excavation lab,
Harrell, only 36, died of a massive heart attack caused by a
pre-existing condition. His wife, Melody, today continues his work
as a partner in the kid rex team. She has to, she says. The kid rex
find was something her husband had called the pinnacle of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   So what now? The bones have been moved from Houston to a remote
Hill Country ranch for excavation. What does one do with T. rex
bones out in a shed behind the house?
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the McDonald's and Walt Disney corporations bought
another T. rex, Sue, an adult, for $8.4 million at an auction held
by Sotheby's in Manhattan. That skeleton was donated to the Field
Museum of Natural History in Chicago, with proceeds going mostly to
the private owner of the land where the fossil was found.
</P>
<P>
   The kid rex is far more rare and presumably would carry a higher
price tag than Sue.
</P>
<P>
   The team that found the kid rex, however, isn't so sure yet what
it will do with the bones.
</P>
<P>
   Frithiof has had calls expressing interest in the dinosaur from
museums around the world, including the Smithsonian Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Frithiof is counting on what he says is a binding agreement with
the landowner to allow Kid Rex Inc. to keep its find and come up
with ways to share it with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may want to start our own nonprofit museum,'' Frithiof
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be worth more to keep it and cast it than to auction it
off,'' Frithiof says of Tinker's bones.
</P>
<P>
   Fossil hunters Alan and Robert Detrich, owners of a T. rex that
has been for sale on an Internet auction site (lycos.com), say a
good-quality T. rex fossil could bring in $40 million in annual
revenue to a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Frithiof figures they will likely make and sell full-size casts
of the fossil, and they are already positioned to make some money
with advertising on their new commercial Web site, www.kidrex.com.
The crew is posting photographs of Tinker's bones on its Web site
as each is cleaned, and the site is attracting advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Tinker may turn into a valuable learning tool, Hollrah says.
Inexperienced fossil hunters often go out looking for full
skeletons, laid out nicely as if the animal had lain down for a nap
and died. But Tinker was found as a jumble of bones. Hollrah wants
to make a cast showing how his bones lay in the site so students
can learn what to look for when hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Frithiof is out of the Austin real-estate business now. He's
devoting much of his time to the business of getting Tinker in
shape. The crew scrapes away earth, pulls out the old bones,
photographs them, and keeps logs of how they were found. Someday,
Tinker will be reassembled. Frithiof estimates it will take about
two years to clean the bones. They already have cleaned major
bones, including the skull, ribs, pelvis, legs and tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have pieces from the snout to the tip of the tail and in
between,'' Frithiof says. They may have 90 percent of a juvenile
rex.
</P>
<P>
   His ranch outbuildings hold other fossils Kid Rex Inc. sells to
help finance their work.
</P>
<P>
   And Hollrah is no longer following his heart into the Black
Hills to pursue an enthusiasm that started in his youth, back in
1968 when he found his first fossil of a crinoid _ a small sea
creature _ one day while he was out fishing on an Iowa pond.
</P>
<P>
   Hollrah makes his home in Texas now, to be close to this kid
rex, to use a small paintbrush and dental picks and hand tools to
gently chip away time and reveal what he hopes will be more stories
about life long ago.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
