<HEADER>
A6603 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-DINOSAURFIND-INSIGHTS     02-14 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAURFIND-INSIGHTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETHINKING T. REX
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies DINOSAUR FIND) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1998 discovery of a juvenile T. rex by a partnership of two
Texans and an Iowa fossil hunter already is yielding new insight
into dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the kid rex adds weight to the theory that
rexes were warm-blooded hunters, not cold-blooded scavengers, as
paleontologists have long debated.
</P>
<P>
   The kid rex had the same teeth as his parents. That means he ate
the same food, says paleontologist Robert Bakker, consultant to the
excavation project. That means adults were dragging food back to a
nest, because a juvenile would be too small to kill the same food
that its parents could.
</P>
<P>
   Animals that feed their young are hunters, not scavengers,
Bakker says. With a hungry mouth to feed, parents can't wait to
just happen upon some food. They have to be aggressive. Aggressive
hunters must be swift, regardless of climate. Aggressive hunters
are likely warm-blooded.
</P>
<P>
   T. rex laid eggs, like a bird, and had hollow bones like a bird.
Birds are warm-blooded. The new discoveries reinforce the argument
for a warm-blooded T. rex.
</P>
<P>
   The kid rex discovery also has helped scientists look at the
dinosaur as an animal that established a sense of family, a social
structure not previously considered for T. rex, Bakker says.
</P>
<P>
   It has also helped scientists properly classify a type of
dinosaur. Before this kid rex was found, scientists thought perhaps
fossils of nanotyrannus were really young T. rex. Now, with the
discovery of the kid rex, they know that the nanotyrannus is really
a separate species.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the kid rex crew has discovered a fossil of what Bakker
says is a new species of carrion beetle that fed on the dead kid
rex. They named the beetle Jimmy, after the corporate lawyer who
came on board to help them incorporate as Kid Rex Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy the lawyer will not be offended to learn this, the crew
says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Another dig
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas at Dallas geoscientists are leading a dig at
Big Bend National Park, where they expect to unearth one of the
largest dinosaurs, if not THE largest dinosaur, ever found in
Texas. The dig, suspended for the winter, has so far unearthed a
fossilized skeleton of a dinosaur neck about 30 feet long. One neck
vertebra uncovered weighed 470 pounds. The dinosaur may be an
Alamosaurus, scientists say, but if it is, they say it is far
larger than any of that species ever found. The site is not open to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
