<SLUG> BC-SPORTSBRAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS SUPPORT: HOW TO CHOSE A GOOD SPORTS BRA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember when sports bras were no big deal? You'd grab a cotton
halter-top bra at the store and hit the gym _ it was that simple.
But if you've shopped for one lately, you know that simplicity in
sports bras is gone.
</P>
<P>
   The options! There are heavy-duty super-compression models,
little-bitty Lycra tops with built-in shelf bras, bras with
racerbacks and zip-fronts, and microfiber performance tanks with
anti-chafing action. What is all this stuff?
</P>
<P>
   We asked some women's fitness experts that very question. Once
they're broken down and defined, the myriad options seem more
necessary and less daunting. Below, Sports Bras 101: What you need
to know before you drop any cash.
</P>
<P>
   1. WHY YOU NEED ONE
</P>
<P>
   Much of today's fancy workout gear is unnecessary; you don't
need to have special pants or a T-shirt with a swoosh to get a good
workout. But you really do need a special bra for working out _
without a sports bra, you run the risk of damaging your breasts.
And you need one no matter what your size, says Leigh Crews, a
Reebok master trainer and spokeswoman for the American Council on
Exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even a very small-breasted woman should still wear a sports
bra of some type,'' Crews says. ``Skin is very elastic, and if
you're doing any kind of impact activity, there's going to be
jarring _ whether you're big or small.''
</P>
<P>
   That can cause tissue breakdown and sagging. Fibrous materials
called Cooper's ligaments support the breast internally, and this
tissue is nonelastic; a sports bra prevents some of the jarring
that stretches the tissue and damages it permanently.
</P>
<P>
   2. KNOW WHAT YOU NEED
</P>
<P>
   Before you buy, consider two factors: your body and the type of
activity you'll be doing.
</P>
<P>
   One style doesn't fit all body types, so there are two major
types of sports bras: compression bras and encapsulation bras.
Compression bras are the most common _ they're designed ``to press
the breasts flat against the chest so they don't go anywhere,''
Crews says. Encapsulation bras are best for larger-busted women,
she says. These look less like halter tops and more like regular
bras _ some even have underwires _ but they provide much more
support than an everyday bra. Encapsulation bras harness each
breast individually instead of compressing your chest as a single
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Both types of bras should support you and limit motion as much
as possible without causing discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, consider how strenuous your exercise will be. ``It
needs to be really tailored to the activity that you're doing,''
says Shannon Forsythe, fitness coordinator for YMCA of Metropolitan
Fort Worth. ``If you're running, you're definitely going to want
something very supportive to be able to hold you.''
</P>
<P>
   When you try on a bra, test its capacity for motion control. Try
a few jumping jacks and you'll know what this bra is going to do
for you. To make it easier to decide, some brands offer styles with
varying degrees of motion control. Champion sports bras, for
instance, feature a rating system _ the tag tells you if the bra is
designed for strenuous or moderate activity.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel you need more support than sports bras offer, some
experts recommend wearing two compression bras at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's going to be recommended for bustier, heavier
(women),'' Forsythe says. ``Everything comes down to more
support.''
</P>
<P>
   3. MATTERS OF STYLE
</P>
<P>
   You can find bras with thick straps or thin straps, racerback
bras, scoop-back bras, tank tops with built-in shelf bras and more.
Nike alone makes about 20 types. There's not a single best kind, so
if you're confused, try on several styles and see what feels best.
</P>
<P>
   Read tags. Jump around in the dressing room. Wave your arms and
see what happens to the straps. All of this might take some time,
but there's no other way to find out which bra is best for you.
</P>
<P>
   A sports bra should be comfortable from the very beginning.
Motion control is important, but make sure the bra's not too
constricting. Take deep breaths and make sure the bra allows you to
breathe properly.
</P>
<P>
   4. SPECIAL MATERIALS
</P>
<P>
   Reebok has Hydromove, Nike offers Dri-Fit, Dupont produces
CoolMax, Adidas features ClimaLite. These special materials, mostly
nylon and polyester combinations, are designed to wick away
moisture and keep it from irritating your skin. Do they work?
Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're wonderful fabrics, and they really do what they say
they're going to do,'' Crews says.
</P>
<P>
   An all-cotton bra doesn't handle moisture as well; cotton gets
soggy, and then you've got wet material against your skin. The new
materials absorb moisture and transport it to the surface, where it
can evaporate quickly. This prevents discomfort and skin
irritations.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE COST QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   At athletic stores, it's nearly impossible to get a good sports
bra for less than $25, and most of the newer, better models are $30
to $35. But you probably wouldn't think twice about spending twice
as much on a pair of shoes, and these are just as important.
</P>
<P>
   However, national chain stores such as Target or Wal-Mart will
often put their labels on bras that are almost identical to the
expensive brands. The materials are sometimes less expensive, but
the designs are the same. Look for these, and you often can get a
high-quality sports bra for less than half the cost.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
