<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
CAMPAIGN DILEMMA ENSNARES McCAIN 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Money in politics may be evil, as John McCain
has constantly tried to hammer home, but it is also the lifeblood
of a presidential campaign, as he very well knows.
</P>
<P>
   And no amount of rhetoric on the campaign stump has been able to
dislodge the inherent conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Although it will be impossible to catch up in cash with George
W. Bush, the $68 million (and still counting) man, McCain,
nevertheless, will need to raise lots of money to keep his own
presidential race alive for many more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Winning New Hampshire's Republican primary was no small feat for
the Arizona senator. But remaining competitive is an even more
difficult task and _ if he survives this week's South Carolina
primary _ will require millions of dollars for advertising alone in
the more populous states, like California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   McCain began the year with only $1.5 million in the bank,
compared to $31.4 million that Bush had left over from the $68.7
million he had raised since last March. McCain qualified for an
additional $4.1 million in federal matching funds in January and
$1.7 million in February. Bush isn't accepting federal matching
funds for the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   So fund raising is crucial for the senator, who already has seen
a significant boost in funds _ by mortal standards, anyway _ since
his New Hampshire victory.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's key fund-raisers from around the country were with him
in Nashua, N.H., when the New Hampshire returns came in, and they
wasted no time.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few days, even Bush supporters in Austin, including a
former member of the governor's staff, had received fund
solicitations from the McCain campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The senator also saw an immediate increase in donations over the
Internet and went online with the first-ever ``cyberfund-raiser''
</P>
<P>
   He also appeared via satellite at simultaneous fund-raisers in
several cities, including Washington, last week. Paying tribute to
McCain _ the Senate committee chairman and veteran Washington
insider _ were many of the special interest lobbyists whom McCain _
the ``outsider'' candidate _ loves to bash for being a corruptive
influence on government.
</P>
<P>
   To be precise, McCain hasn't been campaigning against special
interest political contributions per se. The primary target of his
reform effort _ shot down in the U.S. Senate last fall _ was the
so-called ``soft money'' that wealthy individuals, businesses and
other special interests funnel to political candidates through the
major political parties.
</P>
<P>
   These contributions, which McCain has vowed to reject if he wins
the Republican nomination, circumvent limits on direct donations to
candidates for federal office and the ban on direct corporate
contributions to a candidate or officeholder. They provoked public
outrage with revelations that President Clinton had rewarded major
Democratic soft-money donors with overnight stays in the Lincoln
bedroom in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   McCain loves to declare on the campaign trail that Clinton
``turned the White House into a Motel 6, and he was the bellhop!''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also has attacked Bush for not endorsing his reform
proposals and has painted the Texas governor as a defender of a
political system driven by big-monied special interests. Bush, in
turn, has accused McCain of being hypocritical for raising money
from the system that he bashes.
</P>
<P>
   Even a crusader like McCain _ no less than Bush or any other
officeholder or candidate who accepts special interest money, in
the soft or direct form _ can raise questions.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, for example, it was revealed that McCain, who
chairs the Senate Commerce Committee, wrote a letter urging the
Federal Communications Commission to act on a television station
purchase being sought by a company whose employees had contributed
$20,000 to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he did nothing wrong and only requested that the FCC
act on the application by Paxson Communications. He said he didn't
urge the commission to approve the sale.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``We're all tainted because there is so much money
washing around, and that's an argument for campaign finance
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is. And we can all hope that McCain will continue
his reform efforts, either in the Senate or as president, should he
beat the odds and capture the big prize.
</P>
<P>
   But if most people aren't holding their breaths for real reform,
who can blame them?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
