<HEADER>
A6622 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-R-SCI-PEREGRINE-FALCO     02-14 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-PEREGRINE-FALCON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE NEAR DEATH, A COMEBACK BIRD THRIVES IN CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add graphics note)  
 (Attn: N.Y. Wis. Calif. Minn.)   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a story about a man and a bird. The man is Dr. Tom Cade,
admired for his vision, ingenuity, passion and persistence, who
defied naysayers and spearheaded the rescue of the bird.
</P>
<P>
   The bird is the peregrine falcon, admired for its power, speed,
nobility and hunting prowess, which 30 years ago was perched on the
brink of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Though, over all, conservationists say the war to save
endangered species is being lost, the rebounding of the peregrine
falcon is perhaps the most stunning success to date. The American
peregrine now has perhaps 2,000 wild pairs nesting in the United
States and Canada, up from 39 in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the 1900s drew to a close, the peregrine blithely flew
off the federal list of endangered species in what Secretary of the
Interior Bruce Babbitt called a ``spectacular'' moment for one of
America's great birds and the law that fostered its recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most other endangered and threatened species whose demise
is the result of lost habitat, killings and other direct forms of
human disturbance, peregrines are not put off by people. Just give
them enough space to perform their swooping courtship displays and
spectacular high-speed dives to spear their prey and a good supply
of birds to fill their bellies and they will thrive almost
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Equally at home on skyscrapers and bridges as they are on
mountainside cliffs, peregrines have become celebrated denizens of
New York City, where they have a steady food supply of pigeons,
starlings and sparrows and no threat from predators like the great
horned owl.
</P>
<P>
   While not quite faster than a speeding bullet, the peregrine is
reputed to be nature's most remarkable flying hunter, capable of
diving at 200 miles an hour for a midair attack, knocking the prey
out with its terrifying talons, then swooping down to catch the
falling bird.
</P>
<P>
   The falcon is not the lone comeback bird _ the American bald
eagle has done well too and without direct human intervention _ but
experts say that if not for the likes of a Cade, an emeritus
professor of ornithology at Cornell University and founder of the
Peregrine Fund, the peregrine falcon might not have survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Cade inspired people all over the world,'' said Brian
Walton, who took up the peregrine's cause on the West Coast. ``He
made believers out of people that this could be done, the peregrine
could recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Through his infectious enthusiasm for the peregrine, Cade
managed to harness a huge cooperative venture, getting
universities, government agencies, industries, conservation groups
and the public to participate in its rescue.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, when Cade began captive breeding of falcons in a huge
barn Cornell built for the purpose, there were no wild pairs of
breeding peregrines east of the Rockies and a pathetic few with
failing nests to the west. On Aug. 9, 1970, a New York Times
Magazine article, ``Death Comes to The Peregrine Falcon,'' lamented
a demise that many thought was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Cade, who said he had been fascinated by falcons from childhood
and who did his PhD dissertation on the peregrine and gyrafalcon in
Alaska, recalled that at first the peregrine's plight was
mistakenly attributed to overdevelopment, molestation by falconers,
collection of its brown speckled eggs by admirers and wanton
killing by people who simply did not like falcons.
</P>
<P>
   But at a conference at the University of Wisconsin in 1965,
experts realized that the crash of falcons was a worldwide problem,
and, as Rachel Carson suggested in ``The Silent Spring,'' DDT was
probably the main culprit.
</P>
<P>
   DDT is an organochloride compound that breaks down into DDE, a
highly persistent chemical that is stored in the fat of animals
that consume it, especially predators like peregrines that are at
the top of the food chain. DDE interferes with the deposition of
calcium in the shells of the birds' eggs, leaving them too fragile
to survive incubation by females weighing two or three pounds.
</P>
<P>
   When the rescue effort began, no one was sure falcons could be
bred on the large scale needed to restore them to their former
haunts. And, until DDT was banned in the United States in 1972,
there was little to be gained by reintroducing the bird into the
wild.
</P>
<P>
   As Stanley Temple, the wildlife ecologist at the University of
Wisconsin who helped direct the falcon reintroduction program while
a research associate at Cornell, recounted in 1980, ``First they
said, `You can't breed falcons in captivity.' We did it. Then it
was, `Well, if you can breed them in large numbers, you can't
reintroduce them into the wild'; `If you can reintroduce them into
the wild, they'll never survive'; `If they survive, they'll never
be able to form normal pair bonds'; `If they form pairs, they'll
never produce fertile eggs.' The peregrines have done all of those
things, and year by year the critics have fallen by the wayside.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the breeding program at Cornell got off to a false start.
``We quickly learned that trying to unite wild adults was not the
way to do it,'' Cade said. ``They may have been too stressed by
captivity to mate.'' What did work was to take young birds from
Western and Northern peregrine nests and raise them together in
captivity in broods, to prevent them from imprinting on humans.
Then, when the birds reared in captivity reached sexual maturity,
at ages 2 to 4, they were paired in the Cornell breeding barn.
</P>
<P>
   The breeders also succeded with laboratory hatching of
thin-shelled eggs taken from the nests of wild birds. Cade and his
crew would remove the thin-shelled eggs and replace them with
artificial eggs made of plaster to maintain parental interest in
the breeding process. Then when the laboratory-incubated eggs
hatched, the chicks would be returned to their parents' nests.
</P>
<P>
   In the restoration project headed by Walton, coordinator of the
Predatory Bird Research Group at the University of California at
Santa Cruz, researchers sometimes removed thin-shelled eggs from a
nest and replaced them immediately with captive-bred young, which
the adult falcons readily accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Workers also added laboratory-hatched chicks to the nests of
falcons that managed to produce one or two of their own and removed
healthy eggs for laboratory hatching, prompting the adults to lay a
second clutch.
</P>
<P>
   But problems remained. Even now there are occasional egg shell
failures caused by DDT contamination from wintering grounds south
of the border and from still-hot dump sites here. Besides, DDT was
not the falcon's only enemy.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, at least, the great horned owl has an insatiable
appetite for falcons, adults as well as nestlings, and the owl
population had increased where falcons once dwelled, like the
accessible cliffs in central New York state.
</P>
<P>
   This forced the rescuers to move above the owls' range in the
Adirondacks in northern New York and in the Green Mountains and
White Mountains of New England. They also turned to two unusual
environments for the falcon: coastal regions and cities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   As a result, New York City is now home to far more breeding
falcons than any city in the world, and New York state has more
breeding pairs, 38 at last count, than any state east of the
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Getting laboratory-hatched orphans back into the wild, a process
called hacking, was a daunting task. While still flightless, three
or four chicks were housed in a screen-protected box that was
erected on a high ledge, with a stove pipe extending from the top
of the cliff to the box so that humans could feed them unseen.
</P>
<P>
   Hack-box watchers, who did the job more for love than money,
were hired to monitor the birds 24 hours a day, seven days a week
and to drop food down the tube every day until the chicks were old
enough to fly and hunt for themselves. Unlike many other species,
falcons and other birds of prey do not need to be taught how to
hunt by their parents.
</P>
<P>
   After Cornell's early successes, in 1981 another captive
breeding project got under way, at the Raptor Center at the
University of Minnesota. Pat Redig, director of the Minnesota
center, recalled his frustrations in trying to repopulate the
cliffs along the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   With poles and other equipment supplied by Northern States
Power, hack boxes were erected on the adjacent sand dunes and the
birds moved on their own to the cliffs. But every one of six
nesting attempts made from 1984 to 1986 failed because of predation
by great horned owls.
</P>
<P>
   Even peregrines themselves proved troublesome. One aggressive
female dubbed ``Jaws'' would fly as far as four miles from her
aerie to harass young falcons as they tried to emerge from the
riverside boxes.
</P>
<P>
   So, with each new falcon introduction costing more than $2,000,
the Minnesota team decided to set up hack boxes on an office
building in downtown Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we moved to the city, we were successful beyond our
wildest dreams,'' Redig said. People and businesses contributed
money and time to the effort. And the birds thrived, with
Minneapolis pairs moving on their own as far as the Wacker Building
in Chicago and to a cliff on the north shore of Lake Superior.
Natural enough, since the name peregrine means wanderer.
</P>
<P>
   Urban peregrines have captivated their human neighbors, many of
whom admit they are addicted to watching their comings and goings.
A Minneapolis lawyer whose office faced a nest had to turn his desk
around so he could get his work done.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Carl R. Howard, who can see pairs that nest on the
Brooklyn Bridge from his downtown office, keeps a daily peregrine
diary during nesting season, recounting his observations in ``The
Urban Audubon,'' the newsletter of the New York City Audubon
Society.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, restoring the original Eastern population of 250
nesting pairs of peregrines was considered an unlikely goal. But by
1998, there were at least 238 and counting, and throughout their
current range they are holding their own or increasing in number,
even though some are still being lost to thin egg shells, owls and
urban accidents with windows and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But in places like New York City, these emblems of avian
nobility have inspired great respect. For example, bridge repairs
and paint jobs are typically postponed until the fledglings have
left their rudimentary nesting sites, and not just because the
workers fear parental attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The techniques developed for saving the peregrine are now being
applied to other species, including the Mauritius kestrel native to
an island in the Indian Ocean, the aplomado falcon that disappeared
from Texas in the early 1950s and the harpy eagle in Panama. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FALCON FACTS
</P>
<P>
   SIZE: The adult peregrine is a crow-sized bird, about 15 to 21
inches long with a wingspan of 36 to 44 inches, a hooked beak and
curved talons that can spear prey. Adult males weigh about one and
a half pounds, females more than two pounds.
</P>
<P>
   RANGE: Peregrines inhabit every continent except Antarctica, a
distribution rivaled only by the osprey and the raven.
</P>
<P>
   SPEED: A peregrine's cruising speed _ about 40 to 55 miles per
hour _ is matched by many birds, but its high-speed dives after
prey can exceed 200 miles an hour, which may make it the fastest
animal on earth.
</P>
<P>
   HUNTING: When it spots a potential meal, it partially folds back
its wings and plunges into its vertical power dive called a stoop.
Upon contact, it whacks its victim with its feet, a blow that is
often fatal. Prey that survive are killed by a toothlike projection
in the upper jaw that is used to dislocate the neck vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   MATING: A male peregrine normally requires about 10 square miles
of sky to perform its acrobatic courtship flight. Once birds are
three or four years old they begin producing viable eggs.
</P>
<P>
   The peregrine nests by making a shallow scrape in soil. On
cliffs, bridges and buildings, it commonly nests on fallen gravel.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESPAN: Half or more of hatchlings die in the first year of
life, but adult mortality is much lower _ about 10 percent to 15
percent a year. Their average life span is seven to eight years;
some have lived to 18.
</P>
<P>
   PROTECTIONS: Although no longer on the federal list of
endangered species, the peregrine will continue to be protected by
the Migratory Bird Treaty Act, which prohibits the taking, killing,
possession, transport or import of migratory birds, their eggs,
parts and nests without permission from the Department of the
Interior. The Peregrine Fund, at the World Center for Birds of Prey
near Boise, Idaho, has successfully bred, raised and released
peregrines.
</P>
<P>
   USES: There are 3,000 to 4,000 licensed falconers in the United
States who keep peregrines and hunt with them. Trained peregrines
have been used at airports to terrorize other birds that can
jeopardize aircraft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
