<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6635 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BUSH-FLIGHTS15-COX     02-14 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FLIGHTS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH CAMPAIGN USES CORPORATE JETS MORE THAN McCAIN, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    460&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as George W. Bush has attacked Sen. John
McCain's record as a reformer, the Texas governor's campaign has
flown aboard corporate jets twice as often as his rival, says a
study by the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   The non-partisan group, using Federal Election Commission
records, said the Bush presidential campaign accepted 78 flights on
executive jets last year. Many of the 35 companies that provided
the planes have business dealings with the state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, McCain last year took 35 flights on jets provided
by 13 companies. Many of the firms have dealings before his Senate
Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took up the jet issue as part of his attempt to snatch the
reformer's mantle from the Arizona senator in the Republican
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that I worry about is what we call
Washington double-talk, to say one thing and actually do another,''
Bush told a Chamber of Commerce gathering in suburban Detroit last
week as he mentioned his opponent's use of jets owned by companies.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Center for Responsive Politics, which advocates
campaign finance reform, concluded that ``Bush benefits from the
same special interest favors that he has chastised McCain for
taking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp stresses the fact that its candidate flies only on
chartered aircraft paid for by his campaign. However, his campaign
regularly borrows aircraft to fly the governor's ``surrogates,''
including his wife, Laura; his father, former President George
Bush; his mother, Barbara Bush; former Republican candidate
Elizabeth Dole, and Gov. John Engler of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the private jets has been a sore point for critics of
special interest money in politics. By law, the campaigns are
required to reimburse the companies the equivalent of first-class
tickets, but that is only a fraction of the cost of using the
private planes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Bush campaign reimbursed companies more than
$152,000 for the flights, and McCain reimbursed corporations just
over $77,400.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said Monday that Bush
will continue make McCain's use of jets an issue. ``When people
advocate reform, it's important to live up to the reform they
advocate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said that he traveled by corporate jets because his
cash-poor campaign could not afford chartered aircraft. Last week
he announced that thanks to the funds raised since his victory in
New Hampshire on Feb. 1, he is now traveling on a campaign charter.
</P>
<P>
   The group's study of 1999 records, the latest available, did not
examine flights taken by Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies that provided aircraft for McCain last year
was BellSouth Corp., which provided four flights.
Telecommunications is a major concern of McCain's Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, Westfield Corp., a shopping center developer,
also provided four flights. The Center for Responsive Politics
noted that despite Westfield's assistance, McCain has sought a
permanent ban on sales taxes for Internet purchases, a position the
company opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Another jet provider, Paxon Communications, provided four
flights that became a campaign controversy last month when it was
disclosed that McCain urged the Federal Communications Commission
to make a long-delayed decision on Paxon's purchase of a Pittsburgh
TV station.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the campaign filings showed that Enron Corp., a
Houston-based energy company, provided eight flights. Enron has
numerous dealings with the state on the issues of electric utility
deregulation and pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies that provided planes for Bush's campaign include
the Dallas-based Occidental Chemical Corp. and Pilgrim's Pride, a
chicken processing company, each of which provided a jet five
times. Union Pacific, a railroad company, provided a jet four
times.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
