<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDER-YOUNGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO WOMEN CLOSE THE GENERATION GAP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: ART is moving to NYTNS clients. Caption below) 
 
 
Caption: 
Writer Leah Komaiko, left, visits Adele, 96, several times each
week at a local retirement home. Tom Mendoza/Daily News 
 
 
 
 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you feel younger? Hang out with older people.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Komaiko, a Van Nuys writer of children's books who'd just
hit 44, hoped that might work. A baby boomer who grew up with the
Beach Boys and the Rolling Stones, said she was feeling old,
ancient, as if life was passing her by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Is this all there is?''' Leah said. ``What a
letdown. Do we just sit and wait to get old?''
</P>
<P>
   Then she volunteered to visit an older woman in a local nursing
home, a woman who was blind.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three years later, Leah feels young again and knows it's
her friendship with Adele, 96, that's keeping her that way.
</P>
<P>
   And she's shared those feelings _ as well as tidbits of wisdom
on aging and more from her elderly friend _ in a book about the
unlikely pairing of the two women of different generations. ``Am I
Old Yet?'' (St. Martin's Press; $20) might help other baby boomers
ease their own fears about aging, Leah says _ and Adele (who asks
that her last name not be used, either in the book or this article)
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made me stop being so self-centered about my fear of
aging,'' said Leah, who visits Adele at a Van Nuys retirement home
several times a week, takes her to lunch and on trips to the
hairdresser and the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adele's taught me not to be so stupid as not to live your life
fully every day. She taught me to take care of myself because you
don't know who or what is going to take care of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Adele, who worked as a secretary (she was one of the first to
use Thomas Edison's Dictaphone) despite her lack of vision, married
in her 20s and gave birth to two daughters and a son. She's been a
widow nearly 40 years, and one of her daughters has died. She's
lived in the retirement home, in a room that's as impersonal as a
motel room, for nine years, and wishes her family would visit more
often.
</P>
<P>
   While she'd rather live on her own, she's realistic _ and
philosophical _ about her life. There are still things to enjoy,
like singing, listening to books on tape, dancing, visits with
Leah.
</P>
<P>
   The friendship began somewhat shakily, arranged by a local
volunteer agency. Neither had ever had a friend so far from their
own age. Both were a little afraid they'd have nothing in common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinarily, if I come across somebody young, I'd figure they
wouldn't want to bother with me. I'm too old for them,'' Adele
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was apprehensive, but hopeful,'' Leah recalled. ``I didn't
know what I was getting myself into. It scared me that I liked
her.''
</P>
<P>
   But just like women the same age, they discovered they liked
eggplant parmesan, good haircuts, new purses and taking walks.
</P>
<P>
   And books. Leah writes them and Adele, with the help of a tape
player, listens to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like true stories, not made-up ones,'' Adele said. ``And I
like that there's a book about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Leah got the idea for the ``book about us'' as she realized her
friendship with Adele had become more than a once-a-week courtesy
visit to an lonely old lady. The two women had begun to share their
lives as Leah visited more often, and Adele told Leah about her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd visit Adele, and I realized that I felt so young when I
left,'' Leah marveled. ``I was intrigued because I was waking up a
certain part of myself that had been dead. I was so jaded. Now I'm
hanging around someone who's old but not jaded. I'd found the
antidote.''
</P>
<P>
   Adele loves Leah's visits and hopes the book will encourage
other people to visit the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Both women have grown along with their friendship. And Leah
found the answers to her fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I knew,'' Leah wrote in her book. ``No matter how old
a person is, if she has love in her life, there is only one age _
alive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
