<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6661 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SHINGLES-THERAPY-     02-14 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SHINGLES-THERAPY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING INROADS IN FIGHT AGAINST SHINGLES PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.Y., Calif., Colo.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For John V. Cody, 77, an artist in Lynnfield, Mass., it has been
two months and counting since his personal introduction to one of
the most unpleasant and underpublicized rites of getting older: a
bout of the shingles.
</P>
<P>
   At first the clustered blisters that sprouted on the left side
of his chest, then spread to his back, were just an annoyance. Now
the blisters are long healed, but they have left behind a
squeezing, crushing pain ``like a medieval torture device,'' he
said, that encases his chest and left upper arm, making sleep
difficult and work impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of doing the drawings he had planned to finish this
winter, Cody is spending his time doodling caricatures of his
shingles personified as a massive taloned monster gleefully
crushing its victim's left side.
</P>
<P>
   Cody is one of an estimated one million Americans who develop
shingles every year. Most are over 50, and many go on to suffer
months or even years of incapacitating pain. Behind their distress
is exactly the same virus that kept them out of school for a week
or two when they were children: the chickenpox, or varicella-zoster
virus, the only one of the common childhood bugs to develop a
malevolent second wind in later life.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, just as the fever and itchy blisters of
chickenpox were an inevitable part of childhood, shingles were
considered an unavoidable risk of old age, impossible to predict or
prevent and often accompanied by pain doctors have found
notoriously difficult to control.
</P>
<P>
   Now, new research into the mechanisms of the pain are slowly
enabling better treatments. At the same time, researchers are
eagerly searching for older volunteers to help confirm a hunch that
the newly available chickenpox vaccine may not only prevent
chickenpox in children, but also the pain of shingles in adults.
</P>
<P>
   When children catch chickenpox, their rash scabs over within a
week or so and heals, but the virus does not leave the body. It
only retreats from view, moving from the skin back to large
clusters of nerve cells that lie on either side of the spinal cord.
There it lies dormant, kept in check by the body's immune system.
</P>
<P>
   If something goes wrong with the immune system years or decades
later _ something as serious as cancer or AIDS, or as common and
subtle as the normal changes in immunity that occur with aging _
the chickenpox virus can reactivate in a cluster of nerve cells and
begin to reproduce again, heading back out along delicate branching
filaments of the nerves to the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Once back in the skin, the virus causes exactly the same kind of
blisters as it did during the chickenpox, but only in the patch of
skin where the nerves with the virus have endings. The result is a
collection of blisters in one band of skin on the body, the result
of reactivated infection along the branches of a single group of
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   The name ``shingles'' is thought to derive from the Latin
``cingulum,'' a band or belt, describing both the bandlike form the
rash most commonly takes and the crushing vise-like pain that can
follow.
</P>
<P>
   For unknown reasons the varicella virus prefers to hibernate in
the nerves that transmit pain and other sensations from the skin to
the spinal cord (where a second relay of nerves then transmits the
information to the brain for processing). As the virus reactivates
in these nerves, it can interfere with their normal functioning.
</P>
<P>
   Unless shingles is on the face and affects the eye, the rash
usually goes away after several weeks without complications. But
about 50 percent of people over age 60 have persistent pain in the
area that lasts long after the shingles fade.
</P>
<P>
   This pain means that shingles can undermine health as profoundly
as any life-threatening illness, said Richard T. Perkin, president
of the V.Z.V. Research Foundation, a nonprofit advocacy group for
patients with chickenpox and shingles in New York City. Severe,
profound debilitation, depression and even suicide may follow the
shingles, Perkin said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Neurologists are still trying to figure out why the pain of
shingles can be so persistent, and often so difficult to treat.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the pain may result from a chaotic tangle of ``crossed
wires'' in the brain and spinal cord, said Dr. Anne Louise
Oaklander, a neurologist and pain specialist at Harvard Medical
School.
</P>
<P>
   The reactivation of the varicella virus in nerves that control
pain and sensation often winds up destroying those nerves.
Oaklander's research has shown that people with severe
post-shingles pain have lost 80 percent or more of sensory nerve
endings in affected skin.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of so many nerves may cause an electrical chaos in the
spinal cord that is interpreted by the brain as overwhelming pain.
In fact, Oaklander has started calling post-shingles pain ``phantom
skin pain,'' an analogy to the neurologic paradox called ``phantom
limb pain,'' in which people feel they are experiencing
excruciating pain in an arm or leg that has been amputated.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Oaklander said, other nerves in the skin that
normally transmit sensations of temperature or pressure, but not
pain, can become confused after an episode of shingles and start to
transmit pain too. As a result, patients with post-shingles pain
can find the light pressure of bedclothes, and even the touch of
clothing, excruciatingly painful.
</P>
<P>
   The pain from shingles is complicated enough that doctors are
learning not to expect ordinary painkillers like aspirin or
ibuprofen to help. Instead, a double-barrelled approach to pain
control often works best.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael C. Rowbotham, a neurologist who directs the Pain
Clinical Research Center at the University of California at San
Francisco, often starts treatment with a newly available device
called a lidocaine patch, a stretchy bandage that holds a
long-acting topical anesthetic next to the skin. That quiets the
affected nerve endings so that at least the patient can wear
clothing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rowbotham usually adds oral treatments. Antidepressant
drugs and drugs that control seizures can help stabilize
erratically functioning nerves and can be effective in taking the
edge off shingles pain until it goes away by itself (ususally
within six months). Narcotic drugs related to codeine and morphine
can also help. Still, while these treatments often ease pain, they
seldom abolish it entirely, Rowbotham said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers think they may already have the tool for eradicating
post-shingles pain before it begins. That tool is the chickenpox
vaccine, which was licensed for use in the United States in 1995,
is already reducing cases of chickenpox in some communities by as
much as 90 percent, epidemiologists at the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine contains a weakened strain of the chickenpox virus
that research suggests is still strong enough to boost older
adults' waning immunity against the chickenpox virus. When adults
who have received the vaccine develop shingles, they appear to have
notably mild cases, without protracted pain.
</P>
<P>
   An ambitious plan to see if this pattern holds is now under way,
as researchers call for 37,000 volunteers from all over the country
to join a study of the chickenpox vaccine in men and women over 60
who had chickenpox as children.
</P>
<P>
   A toll-free phone number (1-877-841-6251) will direct those
interested in participating to the nearest enrollment center. Half
the enrollees will be given the chickenpox vaccine and half a
placebo vaccine, and the rates of shingles and pain afterward will
be monitored in both groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shingles can be a very painful and long-lasting illness,''
said Dr. Myron J. Levin, a professor of medicine and pediatrics at
the University of Colorado Health Sciences Center in Denver, who is
overseeing the study.
</P>
<P>
   The best testimonial that he thinks the vaccine is safe and may
work: ``I'm in the study myself,'' Levin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
