<SLUG> BC-GA-STORMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO WHIPS THROUGH SOUTHWEST GEORGIA, KILLING MORE THAN 20 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Will be updated.) 
(ART ADV:  Photos  NYT8 and NYT13 are being sent to NYT photo
clients.  Map  is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMILLA, Ga. _ Tornadoes tore through a section of southwest
Georgia overnight, killing more than 20 people and injuring at
least 100, shearing off roofs, uprooting statuesque pecan trees and
snapping off pines like toothpicks.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy E. Barnes flew over the hardest-hit areas in a
helicopter Monday and reported that an estimated 200 to 300 houses
had been struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a swath about 10 miles long and 1 and a half miles
wide,'' Barnes said. ``There's a mobile home park on the south side
of town that just looks like a bomb drooped. It's just flattened,
nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the area, heavily forested with pine, is fairly rural
and sparsely populated, the few available hospitals were flooded
beyond capacity, and victims were sent as far as 100 miles away to
Tallahassee, Fla., for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the damage and fatalities occurred here in Mitchell
County, but the governor said one of the deaths took place in Grady
County and another in Tift County. The worst destruction and
injuries were in Camilla in the mobile home park, which was
off-limits to the press Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of rescue workers, law enforcement officers and utilities
technicians were called in from surrounding counties to help.
Search and rescue operations were continuing Monday under a hot sun
and puffy clouds as residents surveyed the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Near the mobile home park, in a neighborhood of mostly brick
ranch houses, several roofs had been completely torn off by the
tornado, which struck at about midnight on Sunday. It blasted
through the middle of one house, obliterating the center section
but leaving a wing standing on either side.
</P>
<P>
   Harry J. Woodward, 57, a retiree, said he and his wife rode out
the storm huddled in a closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like it lasted forever,'' he said of the tornado,
``but it was probably pretty quick. I've never prayed so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   He said bad weather was what drove him and his wife to move to
Georgia from the St. Petersburg area. ``We moved up here from
Florida to get away from the hurricanes. We got flooded out twice
by the storm surges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said only three or four of the 39 trees on his one-acre
lot remained standing Monday morning. Windows were broken, a
section of a pine tree lay on his roof, and a gray plastic trash
can was suspended from the eaves.
</P>
<P>
   The storm also felled trees and caused minor damage to the home
of Gail G. Swindle, 60, a self-employed image consultant. ``I heard
popping, then the shingles flying off the roof and then the
roaring, like a train but louder. Then I heard all the trees
snapping. I got my pocketbook, the cell phone, the car keys and got
in the tub'' for safety, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrifying. It's the most helpless feeling because
there's nothing you can do. You just have to go with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
