<SLUG> BC-RACE-WALKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RACEWALKERS ARE WORTH THEIR WEIGHT IN OLYMPIC GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Go ahead and laugh at the funny
racewalkers. Everyone else does.
</P>
<P>
   But with resting heart rates of around 40, they will be
swiveling their hips and striding across the graves of those who
mocked them. That's a lot of ground to cover.
</P>
<P>
   Usually held in ridicule as a second cousin once removed from
traditional track and field events, racealkers soldier on in their
unwavering heel-toe style in near absolute obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of them braved horrendous conditions Sunday morning as
they competed for three spots on the U.S. Olympic team in the
50-kilometer racewalk trials held along a 2.5-kilometer course on
State University Drive on the Sacramento State campus.
</P>
<P>
   In this part of the world, accomplished with a rigid form that
requires the heel of one foot and the toe of the other to be in
contact with the ground at all times. Failure to do so results in
warnings (two) followed by disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   The favorite, 32-year-old Curt Clausen of Chula Vista in San
Diego County, slogged through wind and rain and temperatures that
felt much colder than the listed 50 degrees to become the country's
first track and field Olympian for Sydney 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He crossed the finish in 3 hours, 56 minutes and 16 seconds. On
a day in which earthworms could be seen floating along in tiny
rowboats, it was remarkable that Clausen and runner-up Andrew
Herman (3:57:54) broke four hours, the ``A'' qualifying standard
for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the absolute worst conditions I've ever raced in,'' said
Herman, also of Chula Vista. ``The wind is what killed us. We lost
so much time on that. That could have affected times by as much as
five or six minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Clausen and Herman were motoring along in metronomic
fashion _ heel-toe, heel-toe, heel-toe. Take note, recreational
joggers: Clausen's winning pace averaged about 7:30 per mile ...
for 31 consecutive miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, at the finish, I broke into tears,'' Clausen said. ``I
was happy to be over with it, happy to make the team. There's lots
of time to train hard with my teammates, race against the best in
the world and kick butt in Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Clausen, Herman and third-placer Philip Dunn (4:07:00) all live
and train at the Olympic Training Center in Chula Vista, where they
are coached by an Ecuadorean Enrique Pena, who is regarded as among
the best in the world at his profession.
</P>
<P>
   Starting late in 1998, Pena got Clausen to change his training
and technique to become more efficient at both. Clausen altered the
carriage of his arms, which accounts for the swiveling of the hips,
and stepped up the intensity of his workouts to 166 heartbeats a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   The results? Clausen stunned the racewalking community (pop. 27)
by finishing fourth at last year's World Championships in Seville,
Spain. It was the highest finish by an American in World or Olympic
competition in 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 100 percent responsible for my making the jump to the
international level,'' Clausen said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 35 kilometers of Sunday morning's race, Clausen,
Herman, Dunn and another Chula Vista teammate, Al Heppner, formed
the lead pack and took turns leading into the wind to make it
easier on the others.
</P>
<P>
   Then Dunn was hit with screaming pain in his right hamstring at
36 kilometers. He rested a few seconds, then continued on, slowly,
until he was able to return to form. Along the way, Dunn passed the
fading Heppner, who dropped out after 40 kilometers with acute
hypothermia that required medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very sudden,'' Dunn said. ``I literally had to stop, it
was such severe pain. I stopped for about five or 10 seconds, then
very slowly started marching again. I spent the next two k's
working myself back into it. Mentally I never gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   After crossing the finish in third place to earn a trip to
Sydney, Dunn said he felt ``pure elation. Absolutely thrilled. The
work I put in this year made it all worthwhile for spending the
last seven years dedicated to racewalking.''
</P>
<P>
   You might question the sanity of these men for stepping out in
such hellish conditions but for what they do and how they do it,
they are to be admired, not mocked.
</P>
<P>
   Walk on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
