<HEADLINE>
A SHALLOW VIEW OF GAYS IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ASSAULT ON GAY AMERICA 
Produced by: Claudia Pryor Malis 
On: WGBH, Tuesday at 10 p.m 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To probe the nature of homophobia in the nation, Tuesday's
``Frontline'' report, ``Assault on Gay America,'' recounts the 1999
murder of Billy Jack Gaither. A solid citizen of Sylacauga, Ala.,
the 39-year-old Gaither was well-liked, hard-working, and discreet
about his homosexuality, though not closeted. Last February, he was
beaten and stabbed to death in a horrible homicide that seems like
an outtake from ``Goodfellas,'' although the pair of men convicted
in the killing, and now serving life sentences, weren't mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   Both allege in interview footage shown in the program that
Gaither died because of sexual advances he made that offended their
manhood. Steven Mullins, who apparently wielded the murder weapons,
clearly implies he did the correct thing under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   According to research on homophobia that this ``Frontline''
reviews, his attitudes are woven into the fabric of contemporary
American culture.
</P>
<P>
   This assertion hardly comes as a surprise, and, unfortunately,
the conclusions of the experts who appear on the program are just
as predictable. Dr. Karen Franklin, for example, explains that
young males display hostility toward gay men ``to prove their
masculinity.'' On the basis of a questionable-looking study, a
Georgia psychologist demonstrates what Freud long ago suggested _
that many of the most vehement antigay males have homosexual
impulses themselves. (And, as it happens, Mullins may have had a
secret homosexual life himself.)
</P>
<P>
   The murder story at the heart of ``Assault on Gay America'' is
sad and shocking, but the program doesn't tell us much more about
the roots of this crime and others like it than we already know.
Furthermore, it raises several questions it has an obligation to
address, but never does _ notably, why have antihomosexual hate
crimes increased in recent years and what is being done, and can be
done better, to combat them?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1759EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
