u a BC-SCI-FEMALE-ASTRONOMER     02-14 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FEMALE-ASTRONOMERS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WOMEN ASTRONOMERS, A GLASS CEILING IN THE SKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By NATALIE ANGIER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before they could even vote or control their own property, women
had reached for the stars _ and rigorously picked them apart. For
more than a century, they have earned at least 10 percent of the
doctorates in astronomy, often to luminous ends. In 1908, for
example, Henrietta Levitt discovered Cepheid variable stars, which
have proved crucial to the measurement of cosmic distances. Some 25
years later, Cecilia Payne-Gaposchkin determined that stars are
composed mainly of hydrogen _ a finding that her colleagues at
first refused to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with all that history and momentum behind them, female
astronomers still have not soared to professional heights in the
numbers that might be expected. At a recent meeting of the American
Astronomical Society in Atlanta, researchers presented results from
new surveys of the status of women in astronomy, including one that
canvassed virtually all astronomy departments in the United States
and another that focused on 36 of the nation's larger and more
prominent astronomy graduate programs. They compared the latest
data with similar surveys taken in 1992, and thus were able to
assess women's progress during a span that has been a boom time for
astronomy as much as it has for the economy over all.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Hubble Space Telescope and other advances, there's a
lot of excitement in the field now, and a lot of stuff for people
to do,'' said Dr. C. Megan Urry, an astronomer at the Space
Telescope Science Institute in Baltimore, who conducted the surveys
and presented the data in Georgia. ``We're in a golden age of
astronomy and cosmology.'' As a result, she said, the total number
of people with Ph.D.'s in astronomy rose 40 percent in the last
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for aspiring female astronomers, even the gold age
appears to be alloyed with disparities. And though many observers
in and around the discipline have the impression that affirmative
action programs in particular, and academic ``political
correctness'' in general, unfairly give women the edge when it
comes to hiring and promotion decisions, the new survey results
suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young men, and some young women, often think that women are
being preferentially hired these days,'' Urry said. ``Our data show
that's not the case. If anything, it's the opposite.'' Women at the
highest levels of the field remain a rarity: only 5 percent of the
nation's full professors in astronomy are female. Among newcomers
to the field, though, women abound, currently accounting for 25
percent of the doctorates awarded in astronomy each year.
</P>
<P>
   But women start leaking out of the career pipeline early on.
About 43 percent of the men who were in graduate school in 1992
managed to obtain postdoctoral fellowships in the institution of
their choice, compared with only 26 percent of the women. Among the
elite universities, 60 percent of the male graduate students won
coveted postdoctoral appointments in the same institution, while
only 50 percent of the female Ph.D.'s were selected to stay on as
postgraduates.
</P>
<P>
   When young astronomers seek tenure-track faculty positions, a
few more women vanish; they go from being 17 percent of the
nation's postdoctoral fellows to 15 percent of the new assistant
professors.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows why women are not advancing swiftly in a discipline
that has long attracted them. Conference presenters admitted that
conditions for women are vastly better today than they were 50
years ago, when the great astronomer Margaret Burbidge was refused
a Carnegie fellowship because women were not allowed to use the
Mount Wilson telescope or any of the other Carnegie observatories.
</P>
<P>
   And astronomy is hardly alone among the sciences in its poor
showing of women at the top. According to a study published in The
New England Journal of Medicine last week, women who teach in
medical schools are less likely than men to be promoted at each
step along the career path from assistant to full professor, even
though they are more likely to go into academic medicine to begin
with.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that any effort to push women ahead even faster is
doomed to fail, because, they say, the female talent and desire
just is not there. In the January issue of Status, a biannual
report on women in astronomy published by the American Astronomical
Society, the editors reprinted an article by David Gelernter, a
professor of computer science at Yale University, which originally
appeared in the conservative Weekly Standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If women aren't being kept out of science by force, they must
be choosing not to enter, presumably because they don't want to,''
Gelernter wrote, ``presumably because (by and large) they don't
like these fields or (on average) don't tend to excel in them,
which is nearly the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're also less prone to the intense, cut-throat
aggressiveness that usually marks the successful research scientist
or engineer,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Urry does not buy either the free choice or the wilting lily
arguments. ``Getting a Ph.D. in a science like astronomy is very,
very difficult,'' she said. ``You have to be in love with it, and
be really interested in it and dedicated to finish. The notion that
after spending five, six, seven grinding years working like dog,
and then saying, `oh, that was fun, now I choose to do something
else' _ well, I don't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Overt discrimination is rare or absent, Urry and others said.
Instead, they point to small slights and acts of benign neglect as
the likeliest culprits in women's career lag _ the molehills that,
as Virginia Valian put it in her book, ``Why So Slow? The
Advancement of Women,'' (MIT Press, 1999) gradually accrete into
mountains.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The publication Status presented some women's testimony in its
two most recent issues, which can be found online at www.aas.org: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _``I am on a postdoctoral search committee at a university
astronomy department. I read about 100 applications, each of which
has typically three letters of recommendation. One letter, written
by a male faculty member for a female applicant, emphasizes twice
how tiny, sweet and charming the applicant is, and gives a specific
example of how amusing and cute it is to watch the applicant in the
laboratory wrestling with astronomical equipment larger than she.''
</P>
<P>
   _``A new chair has been hired for our physics and astronomy
department. Three of the 40 faculty members are women. He addresses
his very first faculty memo to `Dear Gentlemen ...'
</P>
<P>
   _``A senior scientist and fellow Italian citizen, whom I know
well but have not seen in several years, visits the institution
where I am on the faculty. I say hello, and he replies, asking if I
could take his clothes to the dry cleaner. ... I declined to run
his errand.''
</P>
<P>
   _``At a conference I approach two male colleagues in my field,
wanting to introduce myself to the senior astronomer whose work
closely parallels mine. I hope to join their conversation about a
science issue with which I am very familiar. After continuing their
conversation for a few minutes, the senior astronomer finally turns
from his counterpart and addresses me, saying, `Ah, but we are
boring this sweet young girl. What can I do for you, dear?'
</P>
<P>
   _``I have just passed my Ph.D. oral exam, a follow-up to the
written exam which was taken days earlier. A well-intentioned
senior male faculty member approaches me with a handshake and
remarks, `I am very proud of your accomplishment, knowing how hard
astronomy and physics is, especially for a woman ...'''
</P>
<P>
   _``As a young postdoc in a high-powered physics department, I
attend a colloquium by a famous French man in which the opening
slide is a topless dancer in a grass skirt on a Hawaiian beach.
Some guys laugh and one female graduate student leaves quietly from
the back. I myself am torn _ I do not want to appear humorless or
to overreact (cultural norms being different in France, for one
thing), and I want very much to hear the talk, but after 20 minutes
I realize I have not heard a word he said after that awful picture.
. . . The speaker, by the way, later wins a prestigious prize named
for a famous woman scientist.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this surprises Urry. Recently, she said, as she was
putting together materials to bolster the case for her promotion to
full astronomer, Urry was advised by a colleague to exclude mention
of her work on behalf of women in astronomy. ``Normally, taking a
leadership position is seen as a plus,'' she said. ``It's good to
be a leader in anything but this.''
</P>
<P>
   Urry ignored the advice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
