<SLUG> BC-TV-LETTERMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERMAN PLANS RETURN TO `LATE SHOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the reigning ironist of our time, David Letterman has always
affected a blase air about hosting a network TV show. His shrug
seemed to say: Hey, it's only television.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't know what you've got till it's gone, as the song
goes, and Letterman apparently missed ``The Late Show with David
Letterman'' so much that he will return Friday, just five weeks
after undergoing open-heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave got a rare opportunity to experience what it would be
like not to do this,'' Rob Burnett, executive producer of ``The
Late Show,'' said Monday. ``The experience has absolutely made him
miss the job completely.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, slated to air Monday night, will kick off a gradual,
step-by-careful-step comeback by the 52-year-old comedian. In a
nicely symmetrical touch, Letterman's first guest will be Regis
Philbin, the last guest he had before his Jan. 14 surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But Letterman himself will clearly be the star of the show, and
yes, the fabled ``Top Ten'' list will be stocked with jokes about
Dave's surgery.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call with TV critics, Burnett predicted that
Letterman will ``have a lot to say about everything that's been
going on.'' After all, he noted, ``You have an unusual circumstance
and you have five weeks of gathering stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Unusual circumstance is right. Fans were rocked last month by
the news that Letterman, who has shaped the late-night landscape
for two decades with a stream of innovations and a nonchalant
persona that appealed to a young audience, had undergone emergency
quintuple-bypass heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman's relatively speedy return will gladden the hearts of
CBS executives, since the comeback show, with an expected huge
audience, will fall within the February ratings ``sweeps'' period.
</P>
<P>
   However, the long-term picture remains unclear. Burnett
indicated that he and Letterman may discuss whether it makes sense
to switch to a four-nights-a-week schedule a la Johnny Carson.
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, Letterman is easing back into the host's chair
very gradually, and will not be back at work full-time for an
indefinite period.
</P>
<P>
   The show he tapes on Friday will air next Monday night. Then, on
Tuesday, Bill Cosby will fill in as guest host _ the first time in
Letterman's 18 years in late night that he has relied on a guest
host for an all-new program. (Cosby will not do the Top Ten list,
however. ``Cosby did not want to do one; he feels that's Dave's
material,'' said Burnett).
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Letterman is expected to be back as host, with
Julia Roberts as a guest, before he gives way Thursday night to
Philbin, who will sit in as guest host. It's unlikely that
Letterman will host next Friday's show, but it's not yet known who
the guest host will be.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of many unknowns as Letterman completes what
Burnett acknowledged is ``an extremely quick recovery'' that has
involved daily 90-minute hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett said that Letterman ``medically is fine, couldn't be
better, perfect,'' but added that ``what he doesn't know is how
well he'll feel after hosting a network television show.''
Letterman and his doctors will decide how many nights per week he
hosts the show. ``We'll work our way back as slowly as Dave needs
to work back,'' said Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   The producer indicated that the alternation of Letterman and
guest hosts will continue for some time as the host and his doctors
monitor his recovery. Also, Burnett said, the program is unlikely
ever to revert to its old practice of taping two shows on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   During his recuperation, Letterman has received cards and good
wishes from President Clinton, from Carson, and from numerous
celebrities and fans. ``I told him that personally I believe he has
become a national treasure, and he tried to fire me,'' joked
Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``The Late Show'' without David Letterman has
subsisted surprisingly well in the ratings, thanks in part to a new
format adopted in the past week where celebrities taped new
segments that were juxtaposed with reruns of their previous
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   One of the rerun segments was Philbin's guest appearance on Jan.
13, during which Letterman _ who was about to undergo an
angioplasty that eventually led to surgery _ anxiously queried
Philbin about the latter's experience with the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett said that the new format ``was a nice little twist in
sweeps.'' He said CBS executives have emphasized that Letterman's
health is their top priority, but acknowledged television's
bottom-line reality by saying of the comeback shows: ``Sweeps is
sweeps, and it's a business. It'll be a nice boon to everybody that
probably the last eight days of sweeps, we'll achieve powerful
ratings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
