<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6682 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-14 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOW TO HELP THE OUTDOOR EXPERIENCE IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How can the outdoor experience be improved in
the San Francisco Bay Area?
</P>
<P>
   At the Sportsmen's Expo last weekend, hundreds of people
provided suggestions for improving hiking, fishing, boating, biking
and conservation. Along with some of my own suggestions, here is a
synopsis of the comments:
</P>
<P>
   _ The San Francisco watershed lands should immediately be opened
up to hiking on existing service roads, just as already the case at
many water district lands in Marin and the East Bay foothills. That
would provide access to 23,000 acres of land on the Peninsula and
38,000 acres of land adjacent to the Ohlone Regional Wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   _ Supporting Proposition 12, the Safe Parks Bond Act, is the No.
1 thing hikers can do for parks and greenbelt, protecting open
space in the foothills from urban sprawl, as well as providing
funds for parks, recreation, and fish and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   _ The addition of back-country hike-in camps at parks throughout
the Bay Area foothills would provide outstanding and needed
close-to-home opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the 10 parks along Skyline managed by the Midpeninsula Open
Space District, leashed dogs should be permitted on the trails,
just as is the case on lands governed by the Marin Water District
and East Bay Regional Park District.
</P>
<P>
   corral
</P>
<P>
   _ An aquatic habitat program can be established for San
Francisco Bay, starting with the barren South Bay, where concrete
from roadbed projects can be used to construct underwater reefs,
which can then be marked with buoys.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trout plants can be doubled at 10 lakes in the Bay Area
foothills by the Department of Fish and Game simply by providing
fingerlings in submerged net pens in the fall, then having local
clubs grow the fish out to larger sizes for release in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   _ At another 10 lakes now offering zilch, a warm-water fisheries
program can be established that would provide abundant prospects
for bass, bluegill, crappie and catfish.
</P>
<P>
   _ The perfect location to construct new boat ramps, marinas and
parking areas is the undeveloped area south of the Bay Bridge along
the San Francisco waterfront. Such a plan should be advanced
immediately by the Department of Boating and Waterways.
</P>
<P>
   _ While they're at it, grants should be ordered for maintenance
dredging of boat ramps in the South Bay at Palo Alto and Alviso,
closed for years from the influx of silt.
</P>
<P>
   _ These projects can be easily paid for by the perpetual budget
surplus of Boating and Waterways, the result of guaranteed income
from 900,000 boat registrations and too few places to spend the
dough (and commonly raided by other agencies).
</P>
<P>
   _ And, of course: The oil companies must be forced to
immediately get the additive MTBE out of the gas.
</P>
<P>
   _ In order to find a place to play (and a solution for current
trail conflicts) a bike-only park with narrow one-way trails should
be created for highly skilled mountain bikers who are capable of
ripping at warp speed on single track. Similar one-use parks for
motorcyclists with dirt bikes have been created in the Central
Valley with great success.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the same time, park rangers should enforce existing laws
with zero tolerance and high penalties if bikers are caught on
closed trails.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only creating bike lanes on the country roads in the Bay Area
foothills will end the dangerous encounters between bikes and
speeding cars.
</P>
<P>
   _ How about a coordinated, first-ever crackdown by all
enforcement agencies on littering, that is, sticking it to the
litterbugs with the maximum $1,000 fine, with the worst problem
areas being parking areas with views and at lakes with shoreline
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Any inhumane treatment of animals must be stopped, the
violators arrested and punished, starting with the Chinatown
markets in San Francisco and Oakland, where live turtles, frogs and
even armadillos are often treated in horrendous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Any driver of a personal watercraft endangering other boaters
or wildlife should be quarantined in the Mojave Desert.
</P>
<P>
   _ All tidepools on the coast should be off-limits to the take of
snails, hermit crabs, starfish and other invertebrates. Groups of
10 and 15 people, each with a 5-gallon bucket, have been seen
combing through the tidepools, taking every living thing they can
find.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
