<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6690 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LONG-RELATIONSHIPS-CO     02-14 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-RELATIONSHIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secrets to Lasting Love Shared
 &HT;    By STEPHANIE ALLMON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When Marjorie and A.A. Hyden sit down to eat, they
light a candle on the table, just as they have since their first
Christmas together in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do candles make eating more fun, the Hydens say, but
they also help fan the flames of romance after 52 years of
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our love is still growing,'' Marjorie Hyden said. ``The
wonderful thing about us is we are roommates, we're friends, we're
sweethearts and we're lovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun. Romance. Togetherness. All are characteristics _ and habits
_ that help love to mature over the years, said Ben Dickerson,
director of the Institute for Gerontological Studies at Baylor
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think love certainly deepens,'' he said. ``I think the love
matures, and it's important to have both a romantic love and a
mature love.''
</P>
<P>
   Most couples' love changes as their lives do, he said. When they
are young, they may focus on their children or their careers and
not as much on each other. But when they retire and the kids move
out, their relationship may take on altogether new dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Ed and Ruth Murff, who celebrated their 50th wedding anniversary
in October, said they enjoy the activities they can do together now
that their four children are grown. Ed, 70, and Ruth, 68, like to
play bridge, travel and just sit down and talk.
</P>
<P>
   The way they converse with each other is different now, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more open because it's just us two now,'' Ruth Murff
said. ``We have more time. We don't have as much pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Murffs say their fairy-tale continues to come true every
day. Growing up as children of strict farmers, divorce was not a
word they heard.
</P>
<P>
   Having that commitment level and having respect for each other
helped them celebrate the high points and endure the low points of
their marriage, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you make the commitment, you have to give a lot and take
a lot,'' Ruth Murff said. ``There's good and bad times for
everybody, but these times can be worked through. It's important to
be open-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hydens agreed that being honest and respecting each other's
opinions are paramount to making love last through the years.
</P>
<P>
   They got married when they were both in their 30s and never had
children. So they focused their attention on their careers _ hers
as a counselor and teacher, and his as a college administrator _
and on each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing important for young people is to have a general
interest in each other's welfare,'' A.A. Hyden said. ``We have
enjoyed helping each other and we enjoyed sitting down at night and
talking about our professions.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in their post-retirement years, Marjorie and A.A., both in
their 80s, enjoy entertaining together and watching their favorite
sports teams, the Baylor University Bears, the San Antonio Spurs
and the Denver Broncos. And they take care of each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was thinking about retiring, a lot of people said,
`What will you do?' '' A.A. Hyden said. ``I think it's just a real
joy to help (Marjorie).''
</P>
<P>
   They agreed before they were married that they would never go to
bed angry at each other. And they say they never have reason to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never had a fuss,'' Marjorie said.
</P>
<P>
   And even they are surprised at that, since they say they are
both forthright and opinionated.
</P>
<P>
   One more ingredient to the Hydens' recipe for lasting love is
affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we kiss once, we kiss a hundred times,'' Marjorie said,
patting A.A. on the hand. ``We're the kissingest people.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey by the American Association of
Retired Persons, seniors say affection is an important element in
their relationships. According to the survey, 67 percent of men and
61 percent of women reported their partners as ``extremely'' or
``very'' satisfying in a physical relationship. And 70 percent of
men and 62 percent of women reported high emotional satis- faction.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the AARP magazine Modern Maturity,
psychologist James Hillman said the capacity for love to deepen is
almost a mysterious phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learn to give one another more space, to take more interest
in what's going on in each other's life,'' he said. ``Not what
medications we're taking, or what our pulse rates might be, but
what we're reading and dreaming about, what memories are returning
to us, what peculiar reflection just turned in our minds _
something we haven't thought of for years. We become more
interested in each other's souls; that's the interesting part.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hydens still have the candle from their first Christmas
together. In 1947, Marjorie made the ``drip candle'' by placing a
candle inside a can. Every time it burned, the wax would drip down
the sides and create a hole in the middle for a new candle. For 52
years, they have been adding candles, which have melted and dripped
into one that stands about 6 feet high on a coffee table in their
living room.
</P>
<P>
   They Hydens say their ``friendship candle'' is a metaphor for
how their love continues to evolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we go another 50 years, it'll hit the ceiling,''
Marjorie said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Allmon Writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached at sallmon(at)wacotrib.com .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
