<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6691 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MARRIAGE-COX     02-14 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Compatibility key to long-term unions
 &HT;    By STEPHANIE ALLMON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ There's a new status symbol in America, and it
can't be bought with plastic or polished with wax. Long-term
marriages are now as coveted as designer clothes and luxury cars,
the Wall Street Journal has reported.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no wealth or privilege attached to the luxury of a
long-term marriage. In fact, the chances of achieving it are the
same for everyone _ about 50/50.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half of all marriages end in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, according to the Coalition for Marriage, Family and Couples
Education, Americans say that a happy marriage is their No. 1 goal,
and 85 to 90 percent will get married at least once.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a formula for overcoming the odds and reversing the
divorce trend, marriage and family experts say it must include
better preparation before the ``I do's'' and stronger commitment ``
'til death do us part.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (marriage) is going to be alive and well,'' said
Preston Dyer, professor and chairman of the school of social work
at Baylor University. ``But I think it will be a lot harder to make
long-term marriages work in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyer, who team-teaches a marriage and family course at Baylor
with his wife of 40 years, Genie, said demanding work schedules and
the fast pace of life can take its toll on marriages. And with
Americans working longer hours than ever and putting increasing
importance on careers, married couples in the future will have to
consciously make more time for each other, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marriages just gradually fall apart,'' he said. ``All of a
sudden, people wake up and they're just not connected to each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition for Marriage, Family and Couples Education reports
that by the time people make it to marriage counseling, it is
usually too late to save the marriage. Only 50 percent who go to
therapy are helped, the coalition reports. Of these couples, 30
percent relapse within two years, which means that only 20 percent
receive lasting positive results.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of ``saving'' a marriage, couples should take
measures to better prepare themselves for married life, Dyer said.
</P>
<P>
   In their book, Saving Your Marriage Before It Starts,
husband-and-wife team and psychologists Les and Leslie Parrott say
marriage problems arise because ``we marry an image and only later
discover the real person.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also the premise behind the new book, The Marital
Compatibility Test. Author Susan Adams, who has been married three
times herself, suggests that often it's the seemingly little issues
in life that turn marital bliss into marital discord. Her book
poses hundreds of questions about everyday life _ from how long
leftovers should remain in the refrigerator, to how much stereo
equipment should cost.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is not for couples to agree on everything but to
understand each other's habits and prepare to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have different definitions for words, like a `clean
house' and `early,' '' Adams said. ``I like to think (the test) is
to show that both people have equal input and both people's needs
are going to be considered in each decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Concepts like a compatibility test and premarital counseling
demonstrate a smarter kind of love that Dyer predicts couples in
the 21st century will practice. Instead of getting wrapped up in
romance and red roses, he predicts people will take a more mature
approach and think about long-term implications of getting married.
</P>
<P>
   And this attitude, he says, is one manifestation of a more
educated, independent generation of men and women getting married
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``(A young adult is) having a sense, particularly for a woman,
that I can make it by myself, I don't have to get married, but I
can freely make the choice to join my life with another person,''
Dyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Because people are more cautious about marriage and want to live
independently, the average age of a person's first marriage has
continued to increase. Now at age 26 to 27, it's higher than it's
ever been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting married around (age) 26 or 27 seems to be the age that
correlates highest with marital success,'' he said. ``People's
values have settled down, they have more financial security, they
are probably a bit more independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason people are waiting longer to marry, Adams said,
is that they have lived through devastation from their parents'
divorce. Statistics say that children of divorced parents have a
greater chance of getting divorced themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That's another reason for people to be smarter about love, and
about the person with whom they choose to share their life, Dyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I am convinced of is that more marriages fail as a
result of faulty mate selection than because of anything that
occurs after the marriage actually takes place,'' he said. ``The
first step in having a good marriage is being careful about
choosing a marriage partner.''
</P>
<P>
   He tells his students that when they choose a partner, they
should rely only 50 percent on hormones, and 50 percent on
intellect and logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we base so much of our mate selection on physical
attraction,'' he said. ``And so in many ways, we ignore other signs
that would say this is not a good relationship or doesn't have good
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   What are those signs?
</P>
<P>
   Having some differences, but being alike in a lot of ways.
Couples don't have to share all of each other's interests and
activities, but they must have enough in common to provide some
bonding enjoyment, Dyer said.
</P>
<P>
   One mistake couples make is marrying a best friend or someone
with whom they are sexually compatible, Dyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Other frequent mistakes people make are marrying someone so a
child can have a parent, marrying for financial stability and
marrying someone only after a long-distance courtship, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good motive doesn't make a good marriage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So some people are finding other options for their
relationships. In her book The Future of Love, author and therapist
Daphne Rose Kingma predicts that new forms of committed
relationships will emerge both inside and outside the boundaries of
matrimony.
</P>
<P>
   Co-habitation, same-sex marriages, sacred friendships,
cross-generational pairings and triangle relationships are other
forms of commitment that people will seek to fulfill their souls'
desires for relationships, she says in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Dyer would add commuter marriages, voluntary childlessness and
voluntary singleness to that list.
</P>
<P>
   But overwhelmingly, the American dream still includes marriage
and family, even if it seems like another gamble to take in an
already insecure world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think marriage ought to be a port in a storm,'' Dyer said.
``We live in the storm from day to day with deadlines and meeting
quotas and competitiveness. But there needs to be a place in our
lives that can serve as a port in a storm for us, and that means
partners being available to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Allmon writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached at sallmon(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
