<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6692 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-FEATURE-RUBYBRIDG     02-14 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-RUBYBRIDGES0215-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Children who changed the world
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When 7-year-old Brittany Fuller told her mother that
she wanted to meet her idol, Ruby Bridges, it didn't click.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany's mother, Kamala Burton, remembered the name vaguely
but couldn't put her finger on it. Was she a singer? An actress? A
WNBA player?
</P>
<P>
   The tiny second-grader reminded her mother that in 1960, at age
6, Bridges became the first black child to attend William Frantz
Public School in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   And because she was black, Bridges had to be escorted to school
every day by members of the National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went into the school, all of the white parents moved
their children out,'' Bridges said. ``They boycotted, and none of
the teachers would teach me.''
</P>
<P>
   Brittany felt like she could relate to some of Bridges'
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the only African-American in my class,'' Brittany said.
``I think I could have done what she did.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridges was in Atlanta recently to talk to young people about
what it was like to go to school under those conditions.
</P>
<P>
   She was joined by Ernest Green and Elizabeth Eckford. Green and
Eckford participated in the integration of Central High School in
Little Rock, Ark., in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   For many students today, it's hard to imagine what Eckford,
Green and Bridges went through.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk to students,'' Eckford said, ``I have to paint a
picture because segregation is so alien to them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1896, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld a law that said blacks
and whites could not ride in railroad cars together. It meant that
``separate but equal'' would be acceptable in keeping blacks and
whites apart in housing, jobs and education, too.
</P>
<P>
   But separate wasn't equal; blacks suffered in poor, unequipped
schools. So in 1954, another case, Brown versus Board of Education,
forced the desegregation of public schools. It meant blacks and
whites could go to school together.
</P>
<P>
   But in places like New Orleans and Little Rock, change took
time.
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock, Arkansas Gov. Orval Faubus refused to let black
students in the school, so President Dwight Eisenhower sent in
1,200 federal troops to guard the students.
</P>
<P>
   Eckford, who still lives in Little Rock and is a probation
officer, said the experience was so painful that she refused to
talk about it for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot of pain, but I guess I have an obligation
now. If students can talk to older people, it makes what I am
trying to tell them more immediate and real,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Eckford's stories, it is easy to understand why she
refused to talk for so long. Imagine going to school every day and
getting called names by almost everybody. Eckford and Green were
spit on by other students. Eckford was pushed down the stairs once,
and her mother was fired from her job.
</P>
<P>
   At a book signing that featured Eckford, Green and Bridges,
Brittany waited patiently to meet her idol.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she made it to the front of the line. She hugged and
kissed Bridges, then sat in Bridges' lap as her mother took a
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are so overwhelmed by the story, and for me that is an
inspiration,'' Bridges said. ``It tells me there is hope and that
they are interested in things they should be interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
