<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6700 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-14 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHO ARE THESE GUYS? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pow. Take that, you loony liberal fraud. Pow right
back. Take that, you phony religious panderer.
</P>
<P>
   And so the name-calling goes in the unseemly GOP primary fight
between Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain in South Carolina,
currently one of the bloodiest Southern political battlefields
since the Civil War. If politics is a game in which the players are
supposed to make voters like them, someone threw away the rule book
here.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing likable about the way Bush and McCain are
behaving. Mutually frantic, they are mutually out to kick each
other's backside even if they have to fib to do so. There is not
even much pretence that they are above the fray while their allies
do the dirty work.
</P>
<P>
   I paraphrase some transparent bobbing and weaving:
</P>
<P>
   Bush: What? A veteran standing by my side accused McCain of
ignoring veterans? I know nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Phone bank callers are claiming McCain is a phony, a liar and a
hypocrite? That can't be from my operation. It must be from Alan
Keyes'. It's ridiculous. I'd fire the culprits if I could find
them.
</P>
<P>
   When I appeared at Bob Jones University, I was merely talking to
the students, not endorsing the school history of segregation or
its policy of forbidding interracial dating. It's unfair to ascribe
some doctrine to me just because I try to attract votes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain: What? A publisher who supports me prints segregationist
material? I know nothing about it. I'm not a racist.
</P>
<P>
   My advisers are saying Bush is daddy's boy and are comparing his
National Guard uniform to my own heroic conduct in Vietnam? Never
heard that before, and I don't flaunt my military background.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfair to call me a waffler just because I've changed my
mind lately and now oppose the most extreme aspects of
anti-abortionism and of protecting the tobacco industry. I'm still
a conservative. I'm just not an ideological nut.
</P>
<P>
   There are laughable lines in this fakery, but it is not fun.
This is brutal politics _ hand-to-hand combat not just over a
primary victory but over the very heart and soul of the Republican
Party. If McCain wins the GOP presidential nomination, he may well
free the party of the stranglehold of the religious right, the
dominance of the old Reagan-era establishment and the blind
ideological devotion to tax cuts in the face of all reason.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bush has been moving ever rightward, consolidating
his support in the Christian right and the standard hard-core GOP
conservative base to counter McCain's popularity with independents
and moderates. Bush is unmistakably the party's establishment
candidate, no matter how hard he tries to deny it.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much difference between the two men on major
national issues, but a canyon yawns when it comes to attitude,
image and openness to change.
</P>
<P>
   So they have been tearing at each other's throats rather than
using those vocal chords to debate presidential priorities.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was correct to kill one of his commercials that described
Bush as just as politically slippery as President Clinton. It was
so harsh that it was backfiring, undercutting McCain's image as a
good guy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, plans to go ahead this week with equally harsh
ads that paint McCain as a double-talking fake who promotes
campaign finance reform but takes big bucks from Washington
lobbyists. This is unfair, since Bush has raised many times more
than McCain has from those same lobbyists. This message may also
backfire since the thrust is that it is okay for an establishment
darling who can dominate the system but not okay for a competitor
who dares to think about eventually shaking it up.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also calls McCain a certifiable liberal, a political
pejorative that his father used to devastating effect against his
own 1988 challenger, Democrat Michael Dukakis. The current charge
is a total distortion of McCain's congressional record, as Bush
knows. McCain is a rock-ribbed conservative, except where he has
chosen to disagree with his party's orthodoxy on selected issues
like campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush strategy is to steal McCain's image by claiming to be
the real outsider and the real reformer, but it won't work. The
outsider claim is patently silly for the son of a president who has
the endorsement of most GOP governors and members of Congress and
who has raised so much campaign money that he refused to take
public funds. The reformer pose doesn't stand up either because
Bush talks only about his so-called ``reforms'' in Texas and he
doesn't have any great plans to transform the federal government
should he be elected.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is also trying on the openness mantle, talking more freely
to audiences and to the media. But his concept of informality is
rolling an orange down the aisle of the campaign plane, a gesture
Nancy Reagan used to make when things were tense between the White
House and the media. Rather inadequate, that.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, for his part, abandoning the attack ads, is now back to
reinforcing his own identity as an outspoken free-thinker who will
rid the Republican Party of its most outrageous baggage and
revitalize the political system. Nobody has to urge, ``Let McCain
be McCain.'' He is who he is.
</P>
<P>
   Bush contends that Democrats have a plot to vote for McCain in
South Carolina on Saturday and then go back to their own party in
the general election, having destroyed his candidacy. Nonsense. Any
sensible Democrat who wants the party to win the White House
suspects that Gore would do better running against Bush, a
traditional Republican, than the magical McCain.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
