<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6706 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBN-GIANTS-HNS &LR;      02-14 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     UNANSWERED QUESTIONS FOR THE 2000 GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN SHEA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new era of Giants baseball is here, an era in
which the Giants aren't even the top draw in their own ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The park itself is the real draw, judging by the phenomenon that
the entire 2000 season will probably sell out by Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   As Terence Mann told Ray Kinsella on an Iowa cornfield, ``People
will come, Ray. People will most definitely come.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendance _ 3 million is a cinch _ is no longer based primarily
on how the Giants fare on the field, but how swell the Bay looks
from those charter seats. The trick is to convince everyone that
the home team is worth watching, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants finished second the past two seasons and anticipate
Pacific Bell Park will help accelerate their quest to win the
National League West. But some weighty questions need to be
answered first. Here are five:
</P>
<P>
   _ Can the Giants win despite a lack of winter moves? Ask that
question enough times, and you're liable to get bonked on the head
by the people responsible for the lack of winter moves.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Brian Sabean, with a nudge from ownership,
insists there was little reason for major roster reshuffling
because the core players already were signed through 2000. They had
hoped for better luck finding a catcher and third baseman but
seemed satisfied with the late signing of Russ Davis, who'll
challenge Bill Mueller at third.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and catcher Bobby Estalella are the only newcomers while
the list of departed players is long _ Julian Tavarez, Jerry
Spradlin, Chris Brock, Rich Rodriguez, Brent Mayne, Scott Servais,
F.P. Santangelo and Charlie Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite it all, management insists it's an improvement over the
club that entered spring training last year, largely because Livan
Hernandez and Joe Nathan have arrived and Russ Ortiz became an
established winner.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the Giants argue, what moves have the first-place
Diamondbacks made?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Robb Nen throw 100 mph again? Will it matter? Possibly
not.
</P>
<P>
   That's if you believe the company line, that Nen will become a
more complete pitcher this season, that decreased velocity caused
by his worn-and-torn elbow will prompt him to improve his control
and hit the corners rather than simply firing heaters down the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   The truth will come soon enough, perhaps the first week of the
season when Nen is summoned to save a one-run lead in the ninth
with Chipper Jones, Brian Jordan and Andrew Jones coming up.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, it'll come later in the year after Nen has had a
chance to develop his new approach. For the record, he has an ``all
is well'' attitude, but it's no secret management is genuinely
concerned about the fragile closer who posted career highs in blown
saves (nine) and losses (eight) and his highest ERA (3.98) since
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Nen will have extra incentive to bounce back from surgery
because he's due to be a free agent next winter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who in the name of Dennis Littlejohn will catch? Kirt
Manwaring, anybody?
</P>
<P>
   The Giants seem to need somebody, anybody, so long as he's
experienced, even if he's just a warm body. They say they're
confident with Doug Mirabelli and Estalella, but those guys have
played a combined 134 games.
</P>
<P>
   They lost Mayne and Service, both to Colorado, and failed to
lure veteran Joe Girardi, who signed with the Cubs. The remaining
free agents are past-their-primers Benito Santiago and Manwaring,
neither considered a great mentor.
</P>
<P>
   There's still time to make a deal, if only to provide leadership
and teach Mirabelli and Estalella about big-league do's and don'ts.
Of course, Mirabelli and Estalella could end such talk by proving
themselves in spring training, by handling a promising rotation and
generating a base hit now and then.
</P>
<P>
   Mirabelli is potentially a dynamic defender and Estalella has a
history of hitting home runs in bunches. But ponder this: How many
teams have won championships with a couple of pledges behind the
plate?
</P>
<P>
   _ Is the rotation young and talented or just young? There are
reasons to believe talent accompanies the youth, from 1 to 5.
Outgoing pitching coach Ron Perranoski predicted this rotation will
be the league's best, if and when the Braves' guys ever slow down.
</P>
<P>
   That puts pressure on new pitching coach Dave Righetti, but the
young chaps are the reason Righetti said he took the job in the
first place. He wants to be there when they peak.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be this year? There are two sides to every story.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez (the Opening Day starter) broke into the majors 9-0
and was the 1997 World Series MVP, but he's 18-24 since then.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz won 18 games in his first full season, but he led the
league in walks.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Rueter has the second-highest winning percentage among
lefties in the last 20 years, but he rarely goes deep into games.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan shined in his first tour of duty, but he's untested over
a full season.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Estes was a 19-game winner three years ago, but what have
you done for me lately? The club was relieved that, for the first
time in recent memory, it didn't need to acquire a veteran starter
in the offseason. Long gone are the days of Danny Darwin, Orel
Hershiser and Mark Gardner (all born in the black-and-white TV
era), though Gardner remains on call as the No. 6 starter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hershiser would still be in the mix if he hadn't
decided to play closer to his Florida home and sign in ... Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's up with His Barryness? Once the richest man in
baseball, Barry Bonds has become an afterthought now that $100
million is the magic number. He's no longer on the top-10 salary
list, though he's not exactly living in the streets, given he'll
make $10.7 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   And his game isn't burnt toast, either. In fact, the ingredients
are in place for a monster season. For starters, he'd like to play
his usual 155 to 160 games after missing two months in 1999
following elbow surgery. Also, he wants to make a splash,
literally, at the new park, where his home runs could land in the
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the Junior factor. Ken Griffey Jr. did what
Bonds did in 1993, leave his long-time team to play for his
home-town team. Bonds was an MVP his first season with the Giants,
and Griffey seeks similar fortunes in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds, who battled Griffey for player-of-the-'90s honors, has a
ton of pride and watched from the disabled list as Griffey hit
another 48 homers last year. Now that they're in the same league,
Bonds wouldn't mind teaching Griffey, who's five years younger, a
little something about NL ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
