<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6714 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NASCAR-FORECAST-NYTR &LR;      02-14 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-FORECAST-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOBBY LABONTE APPEARS READY FOR A CHAMPIONSHIP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA, Fla. _ With the 2000 NASCAR season opening with
Sunday's Daytona 500, a huge year could be ahead for Bobby Labonte
and a much-improved one for his older brother Terry.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1999, about the only competition Bobby Labonte and
rookie Tony Stewart had was each other. The two Pontiac drivers who
are teammates at Joe Gibbs Racing dominated the final 10 races of
the year, with Bobby Labonte especially impressive.
</P>
<P>
   In the final 10 events, Labonte won once and finished in the top
three eight times. Stewart won three times and was second in two
other races. So, going into 2000, many feel this is the team to
beat for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, second to Dale Jarrett in last year's championship
chase, had a characteristically low-key comment about the season
ahead. ``We've got everybody back in place like we need to,''
Labonte said. ``The team is really excited about starting the year
off and so am I. That doesn't always count for everything, but at
the same time, we're coming off a great season and looking forward
to beginning this year and not letting up any.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, more intense than Labonte and a driver with his feet
solidly on the ground when they're not pumping pedals in a race
car, is more pragmatic. ``We don't worry about it,'' Stewart said.
``I worry about getting in the car and doing my job. That's for the
media to speculate on and get into the `what if' syndrome. My job
is just to get in the car and drive,'' Stewart said. ``As long as
we keep our focus where it was at the end of last year _ what we
were doing at the end of last year was working for us. So it's one
of those deals, if it's not broke, don't try to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   They may both have a leg up on the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three cars which compete in Winston Cup, Chevy, Ford and
Pontiac, only Pontiac is coming back with the same body style.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, that means Labonte and Stewart's teams have a
base to build on. The minus is that they might not be able to get
the car much better, which could be a problem if the new Chevy
Monte Carlo or redesigned Ford Taurus makes big gains.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the pick here to win the 2000 Winston Cup
championship is Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte and crew chief Jimmy Makar are among the sport's best at
their respective jobs, and NASCAR will make sure that no one car
make, Chevy, Ford or Pontiac, has a decided edge on the track.
</P>
<P>
   All things being equal, this team is positioned to win. It came
close last year and knows what it has to do. It has outstanding
direction at the top in Gibbs, a proven winner, and he will see
that his teams have everything they need to be competitive, and
Labonte and Makar will make sure they get the most out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Other Top Contenders
</P>
<P>
   2. JEFF GORDON, Chevy: People are writing this guy off much too
quickldon's team has undergone major changes and he has
assumed more of a leadership role, but he was far more competitive
last year than the point standings show and he will fall off very
little, if any.
</P>
<P>
   3. MARK MARTIN, Ford: Over the last three years, three drivers
have set themselves apart from the rest, Gordon, Martin and Dale
Jarrett. Extremely steady and healthy for the first time in a long
time, Martin has an excellent chance of winning it all.
</P>
<P>
   4. DALE JARRETT, Ford: The defending champion, it all went right
for this team a year ago but that wasn't luck, that was dedication
and hard work and with a crew led by Todd Parrott, Jarrett will be
tough to knock off. The fire's still there.
</P>
<P>
   The Longshots
</P>
<P>
   5. JEFF BURTON, Ford: Watch out. Over the last three years, this
guy has made marked and steady improvement. He had his best season
in 1999 and is on the verge of championship contention. He could
break through this season.
</P>
<P>
   6. TONY STEWART, Pontiac: Some already believe that Stewart is
the most talented driver in NASCAR, and that is after only one
year. He is with a championship quality team but even more
importantly, he is the best in the business at assessing his
strengths and limitations, and he does not have many limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Best of the Rest
</P>
<P>
   7. DALE EARNHARDT. Chevy: Still very tough, but too far behind
the leaders to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   8. TERRY LABONTE, Chevy: Has crew chief Gary DeHart back, which
will bring him back.
</P>
<P>
   9. RUSTY WALLACE, Ford: See Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   10. MIKE SKINNER, Chevy: Has shown improvement, but many think
he has about peaked.
</P>
<P>
   So let the racing begin.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, Stewart's ready. ``I'm tired of talking about it, to
be honest,'' Stewart said. Everybody wants to talk about it. Let's
quit talking about it and let's just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
<P>
   (Patrick Zier writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. The Ledger
is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
