<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6717 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-MENTAL-HEALTH-SUICIDE     02-14 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-HEALTH-SUICIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Activist on suicide-prevention crusade
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kay Redfield Jamison spent more than 20 years researching and
writing about mental illness and suicide with scholarly detachment.
That changed with the 1995 publication of ``An Unquiet Mind: A
Memoir of Moods and Madness,'' a personal account of her own battle
with manic-depressive illness and her suicide attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Since the book became a best seller, Jamison, a professor of
psychiatry at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, has been one
of the nation's most passionate advocates of suicide prevention and
access to mental health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every 17 minutes, an American commits suicide,'' she told a
U.S. Senate hearing last week. ``Where's the public outrage?''
</P>
<P>
   Cox writer John Head spoke with her by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Q: People are commonly told to take it seriously whenever
someone they know talks of wanting to commit suicide. Is there a
way to know when our own thoughts of suicide should be taken
seriously?
</P>
<P>
   A: Thoughts of suicide should always be taken seriously. If
someone is concerned about it, they certainly should see somebody _
see a doctor, see a psychologist, a psychiatrist or an internist.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, is it common?
</P>
<P>
   A: Thinking about suicide is not that uncommon. Maybe 15 percent
of people will think about suicide at one point or another in their
lives. But it's still something that, if it continues, it's
certainly something to be concerned about.
</P>
<P>
   Q: U.S. Surgeon General David Satcher has focused on what he
calls the nation's suicide epidemic, and he's said he wants to make
suicide prevention one of his priorities. What impact do you see
from his doing this?
</P>
<P>
   A: He's been terrific. ... He has made the public health
community much more aware of how common suicide is. He has added
the respect of both his office and himself, which are considerable.
And he has put together a report, which is the first report from
his office on suicide as a major issue for the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Q: More than 30,000 people commit suicide in the United States
every year. It's the third leading cause of death among those 15 to
24 years old, and the rate among teenagers has quadrupled in the
last 45 years. Given those numbers, do you think the government
response to the problem to this point has been adequate?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Not at all. Until very recently, the government has not
really paid a great deal of attention to it. ... It's changing, but
to date I don't think there's been enough money invested in
scientific research. I don't think there's been enough money or
public proclamation about how devastating it is, because it's a
particularly devastating kind of death.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Some people might argue that suicide is such an intimate,
individual act that the government can really have very little
effect on it.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't agree with that for a moment. It's an intimate act in
that, of course, it's an individual who kills himself or herself.
And, of course, there are a lot of individual feelings and
experiences that go into it. But we know a lot about suicide, and
we know a lot about how to prevent suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Q:W hat sort of actions would you like to see?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would like to see a lot more public discussion of it _ a
lot more discussion of it in churches and in universities and in
communities. I would like to see much more focus on depression and
the recognition and treatment of depression.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Getting back to the surgeon general, he has been particularly
concerned about the increased rate of suicide among
African-Americans, a group that historically has recorded lower
rates. Do you have any theories about this increase, especially
among young African-Americans?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several theories out there.
</P>
<P>
   One is that access to alcohol, drugs, firearms _ the same things
that make suicide more likely in young white men _ are now making
it much more likely in young African-American men. (Another
explanation may be) a lack of access to good medical and
psychiatric care (in black communities).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
