<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HEMOPHILIA-FUND-NYTR &LR;      02-14 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMOPHILIA-FUND-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULL FUNDING FOR RICKY RAY TRUST DELAYED 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CATHERINE HOLLINGSWORTH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite White House assurances that it would seek
full funding of a program to compensate hemophiliacs infected with
HIV, President Clinton's new budget leaves the Ricky Ray trust far
short of the necessary $750 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., who wrote the legislation creating the
fund, blamed the White House for dashing hopes in the hemophilia
community. The president's budget would only partially fund the
program at $100 million a year for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed and I frankly think the White House
let those folks down,'' Goss said. ``There's no reason in the world
we can't get this done.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund as named for the Florida teen whose death from AIDS led
to a national crusade on behalf of hemophiliacs who were
unknowingly infected with HIV through contaminated blood in the
1980s. The compensation program was launched under a law signed by
Clinton in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   When initial funding for the program was in doubt last year,
Ricky's mother, Louise Ray, and others pressed the White House to
come up with the money based on Clinton's longstanding support of
their efforts. John Podesta, White House Chief of Staff personally
pledged the administration would eventually provide the requested
amount.
</P>
<P>
   After last year's appropriation came in at $75 million, the
hemophiliac advocates again met with Podesta and received further
encouragement that the full amount would be sought. A White House
official confirmed Podesta's conversation with Ray and two other
activists.
</P>
<P>
   The president himself in January wrote to a hemophilia advocacy
group about last year's appropriation, saying, ``while I recognize
that this does not fully fund your requested amount, I believe it
serves as a significant down payment on the full funding amount.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goss said the president was doing ``a lot of talk.'`
</P>
<P>
   Louise Ray, who flew to Washington from her home in Sarasota to
meet with Podesta in January, was not overly critical of the
administration, saying she did not want to appear ungrateful for
what the president has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what we expected but it's another step forward,'' she
said of the new budget request. ``I really would have liked to get
the full $750 million, but government doesn't always work that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray has led a 17-year battle to get the federal government to
acknowledge it caused an estimated 20,000 individuals to contract
the AIDS virus through tainted donated blood.
</P>
<P>
   She said it is crucial that victims are compensated as quickly
as possible, since AIDS-stricken hemophiliacs are dying at a rate
of one person a day. Many want the money to pay medical bills and
other expenses before they die.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 20,000 who are believed to have been infected with HIV,
only about half are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``To drag out these payments seems to be a little cruel when
there are people dying,'' Goss said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hemophilia Foundation was clearly disappointed with
the incremental funding in the president's budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were obviously hoping for full funding,'' said Patrick
Collins, director of government affairs at the foundation. ``It's
unfortunate. It's looking like a drawn-out process.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana Kuhn, legislator director of the Committee of Ten Thousand
_ a group representing the nearly 10,000 hemophilia victims still
alive _ and committee president Corey Dubin were present at the
Jan. 30 White House meeting with Ray and Podesta.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta told them full funding became complicated when Congress
housed the money in the Health and Human Services Department rather
than in the Justice Department, where such claims are typically
handled.
</P>
<P>
   The White House source confirmed the current funding structure
is tying up the money.
</P>
<P>
   But Goss called that explanation ``gobbledygook.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy a bit of that,'' he added. ``To say they've been
detoured or derailed by the process, that's a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Other congressional critics said the president could have found
the money, given the large amounts of new spending in his budget
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The agency responsible for administering the funds, the Health
Resources and Services Administration, is also taking heat because
it could take at least seven months to get the program off the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The committee says that is too long. ``This is torture,'' Dubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Morford, deputy administrator at the Health and Resources
Services Administration, said it was working to get checks in the
mail as soon as possible, but must abide by the federal process to
ensure the program runs smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing everything humanly possible to be expeditious
within the confines of the law and regulations,'' Morford said.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: Catherine Hollingsworth is a correspondent for the
Washington Bureau of the NYT Regional Newspapers Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
