<HEADER>
A6723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-TAKEOVER-NYT &LR;      02-14 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TAKEOVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILED TAKEOVER BID CALLED SUCCESS BY JAPANESE STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A deal described as Japan's first indigenous hostile
takeover attempt ended in what Americans would call a failure on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But here, the effort by Yoshiaki Murakami, a former bureaucrat
who had made a bid to take over Shoei Co., a little-known real
estate and electronic parts company, is seen as the most striking
effort to challenge longstanding practices in corporate Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami's bid, to buy Shoei's shares for 1,000 yen, or about
$9.17, apiece, expired Monday. He increased his stake to 6.52
percent from 2.78 percent, far less than needed to veto even the
most basic of management decisions, but he said he considered it a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very happy,'' Murakami said in an interview Monday
evening. ``I created a debate about shareholder value and
management's responsibility for creating shareholder value, and
that was what I wanted to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition fund established by Murakami, a 40-year-old
former official of the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry, has been widely followed by investors as a barometer of
corporate Japan's willingness to change. His effort to acquire a
controlling stake in Shoei is considered the first instance of a
Japanese investor's having tried a hostile takeover of a Japanese
company.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of his bid raises questions about the prognosis for
another unsolicited takeover effort under way in Japan, a tender
offer by Boehringer Ingelheim, a German drug manufacturer, for a
controlling stake in SS Pharmaceuticals, which is set to expire
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami's bid for Shoei exposed the impediments that Japan's
system of cross-shareholding among banks and corporations pose for
investors. Shoei is a member company of Fuyo Group, a cluster of
companies, or keiretsu, that orbit around Fuji Bank and its related
financial institutions, which together control 60 percent of
Shoei's shares.
</P>
<P>
   The keiretsu system has long been seen as one of the biggest
barriers to foreign investment in Japan, as well as a significant
contributor to Japan's lack of global competitiveness. Inside the
keiretsu, companies are not forced to compete for financing and
have little incentive to make decisions based on profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Many investment strategists and analysts have assured investors
that global market forces are pressuring the keiretsu to disband.
Yet the Shoei case suggests that keiretsu power is still strong.
Although the president of Fuji Bank has been widely quoted as
saying that he intended to sell off Fuji's stakes in various group
companies, Fuji and its sister insurance companies and trust banks
refused to sell their shares in Shoei.
</P>
<P>
   Murakami demonstrated that Shoei served as a place to give
former directors of Fuji and its sister financial companies, Yasuda
Trust and Banking Co., Yasuda Fire and Marine Insurance Co. and
Yasuda Mutual Life Insurance Co., a second job and a means of
maintaining their golf club memberships and chauffeured car service
after retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He also exposed the longstanding Japanese practice of
undervaluing assets, finding 70 billion yen, or more than $648
million, in value over book value in Shoei's real estate holdings,
a situation he says suggests that the company should turn a far
better profit than it has in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My motivation in this was not to seize management control but
to increase shareholder value,'' he said. ``I want the existing
management to do its job.''
</P>
<P>
   Murakami said he planned to take his case to the March annual
shareholders' meeting. He said several shareholders, including the
fund management company Arnhold &AMP; S. Bleichroeder, which has a 7.7
percent stake in Shoei, have asked him to serve as their proxy.
</P>
</TEXT>
