<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6724 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-POLITICAL-RE     02-14 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLITICAL-REPORTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVERING THE CAMPAIGNS FOR THE CITIZEN-BROWSER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every reporter who has ever dreamed of a world without editors
might see Jacob Weisberg as a man who has achieved nirvana. Every
libertarian Internetophile who believes that the World Wide Web
will democratize information might see Weisberg, Slate magazine's
leading political correspondent, as the man to unlock the medium's
revolutionary potential.
</P>
<P>
   How, then, would the restless reporters feel if they knew that
Weisberg has thousands of editors _ readers who react instantly and
viscerally to his work? And how would the Net libertarians take it
if they knew that the political news media see Weisberg as one of
their own?
</P>
<P>
   Many old-media hacks, whose conventions (objectivity, anyone?)
were supposed to be exploded by the Web, read his online Ballot Box
submissions regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Slate, the liberal magazine Salon.com and the Web site of the
conservative National Review are cited regularly in The Hotline,
the Washington-based online bible of who wrote what about whom.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, said one old-media correspondent, Weisberg and
some of his online magazine competitors _ Jake Tapper, who reports
for Salon.com, and the National Review's Richard Lowry, John J.
Miller and Ramesh Ponnuru _ are using the Web to create national
alternative newspapers, which publish early and often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day to day,'' said Dan Balz, a reporter for The Washington
Post, the Web magazines offer ``the ability to be very irreverent
about all aspects'' of the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, whose armies have laid waste to the conventional
beliefs of retailing, brokerage houses and help-wanted advertising,
has had a more subtle impact on political journalism so far.
</P>
<P>
   The Web's growing legions of campaign reporters have married
into the local population, spreading Web culture in a way
comparable to the way Alexander the Great's troops spread Greek
culture. They wear the local costumes: Daily dispatches on
MSNBC.com seem like wire service wrap-ups; ABCNews.com's brief,
daily reports read like campaign diaries.
</P>
<P>
   Weisberg's elegant satire and analysis would seem at home in The
New Republic. Tapper could have dominated an alternative
newspaper's cover with his dogged pursuit of Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, for example, in writing about the Republican candidate's
appearance at a fundamentalist university that bans interracial
dating.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a difference. If this column had been written for
the Web, for instance, by now you might have seen hot links to
everything from a map of Alexander's campaigns to the Bob Jones
University home page. If this had been written for the Web, the
writer's e-mailbox would be clogged with missives from readers
reacting to these ideas.
</P>
<P>
   As Weisberg said last week on the telephone, ``At New York
magazine'' _ where he worked before joining Slate in 1996 _ ``I had
to be finished with a story Wednesday morning that would not be
read by people until the next Monday. It was an exercise in
guessing what was going to happen, bluffing, pretending you knew
the results of things you couldn't possibly know.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, he said, ``you're unscoopable. If you have a
good idea, there is no reason not to put it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Slate's editor, Michael Kinsley, lets Weisberg post his
writing unedited. ``He has the car keys,'' Kinsley said. (Weisberg
does have old-media ties as a contributing writer for The New York
Times Magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   This year's political coverage in the online magazines is far
closer to mainstream journalism than Hunter Thompson's manic 1972
work for Rolling Stone or the blaring of talk radio in 1992. Still,
the reader-reaction ``threads'' on the Web sites have talk radio's
visceral feel.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And both Slate and Salon.com have actively tweaked tradition
this year.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the New Hampshire primary, Slate flouted the media
pact to withhold exit-polling data until the polls closed; its
readers learned of projections of the lopsided win by Sen. John
McCain of Arizona in the Republican primary by 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com assigned its contributor Dan Savage to the Iowa
caucuses. He posted a piece saying that, while nursing the flu, he
had licked the doorknobs of the campaign headquarters of Gary
Bauer, the conservative Republican candidate, then licked a pen and
presented it to Bauer. Reader reaction reflected the Web's
emotionalism and ambiguity: If the account was a spoof, one person
wrote, ``it is hugely amusing and creative''; if not, he said, ``it
violates my definition of media ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web journalists do take advantage of their medium. Weisberg,
who at 35 is the dean of the lot; Tapper, 30; and the members of
the National Review's staff, who range in age from 25 (Ponnuru) to
31 (Lowry, the editor), all have their articles forwarded by e-mail
to friends, competitors and sources. All use hyperlinks, which
allow them to make a shorthand reference to an issue, then, via
links, send the reader to the appropriate position paper.
</P>
<P>
   Weisberg believes ``the format doesn't have to be as rigid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more spontaneous,'' he said. ``I was someone who never
used the personal pronoun in writing. In the Internet, your being
there is such an important part of your readers' experience.''
</P>
<P>
   As a weekly columnist for MSNBC.com, Howard Fineman, the
Newsweek columnist and political commentator, is getting to know
the Web's horde of impromptu editors. ``My byline is hot-linked,
meaning that as soon as I send my words of wisdom to the world, I
am immediately brought up short by people e-mailing me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponnuru, one of the National Review's on-again, off-again
campaign correspondents, said the medium lends itself to analysis
with attitude; it ``does scramble expectations about what one is
supposed to do and one isn't.'' On Friday, after examining Bush and
McCain's claims and counterclaims in their tax proposals, Ponnuru
and Miller wrote, ``Maybe it's a pointless exercise: McCain knows
that he can wing it and then spin his way out of trouble because
voters aren't thinking about issues. It would be nice if a few
journalists were.''
</P>
<P>
   Such barbs are hardly revolutionary. John Heilemann, who in 1996
was Hotwired.com's campaign correspondent, believes political
coverage on the Web missed its revolutionary moment, because it
transformed from an alien presence to a conventional one so fast.
</P>
<P>
   The moment may have come and gone in 1998, he said. There was no
presidential campaign then, but during the Lewinsky scandal, Matt
Drudge nipped at journalists' flanks, biting off a mixture of
gossip and fact. This time around, Drudge's Web site has been the
dog that did not bark.
</P>
<P>
   Heilemann, who is writing a book on Silicon Valley, said in an
interview, ``So much has happened in the last four years that the
Web doesn't feel avant-garde anymore. We went from the year when it
was off the charts to the year when it was mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to a point. Salon.com's Washington bureau chief, David Weir,
believes that Web-based political journalism has a new emotional
immediacy. And, he said, there is ``an accountability factor _ how
fast your audience can come back to you,'' or check a writer's
documentation.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign coverage, he said, shows that ``the whole
relationship between the journalist and the audience is undergoing
a gradual, subtle transformation. But we don't know where it all
leads.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
