A6730 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-GAYS-THERAPY-COX     02-14 0239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-THERAPY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Therapy may not be the answer for homosexuals
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As reports circulated again of ``reparative
therapy'' to help homosexuals become heterosexual, the American
Psychiatric Association emphasized last week that there is no
clinical evidence of this happening and some evidence that it can
be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual orientation, like gender identity, appears to be
established early in life,'' the APA said in an updated fact sheet
Feb. 5 on ``Homosexual and Bisexual Issues.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging anecdotal reports that psychotherapy has
helped change gay men and lesbians' sexual orientation ``for some
motivated individuals for limited periods of time,'' the
association also said ``such changes often are accompanied by
depression, anxiety and other symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   The most useful therapy for homosexuals tends to be that which
deals with the self-hatred that is bred by living in a homophobic
society, said the APA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relief of homophobia allows for better psychological
functioning,'' the statement explained. ``Those who have integrated
their sexual orientation into a positive sense of themselves
function at a healthier psychological level than those who have
not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Web site: for the American Psychiatric Association is
www.psych.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
