u i BC-AFGHAN-HIJACK-NYT &LR;      02-14 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-HIJACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN ARRESTS 13 IN HIJACKING OF AFGHAN AIRLINER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Thirteen men were charged Monday with hijacking the
Afghan airliner that spent last week parked on a remote runway at a
British airport with more than 150 people aboard. The men, all
Afghans ages 18 to 36, could face long prison sentences if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   A 14th suspect is still being questioned, the police said, and 6
others arrested in connection with the hijacking were not charged
and will join a group applying for political asylum in Britain. The
Ariana Airlines Boeing 727 was seized while on a domestic flight on
Feb. 6, and landed at Stansted airport, outside London, after stops
in three other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that 73 other passengers from the plane who have
also sought asylum are being interviewed about their reasons in
their temporary accommodations, a fire service training center in
Moreton-in-Marsh, a picturesque village in the Cotswolds. And 73
others _ 58 men, 8 women, and 7 children _ left on a chartered
flight for Kandahar, Afghanistan, early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities originally said that only about half that number
actually wanted to go home. But they explained Monday that when the
Afghans began to realize how difficult it might be to gain asylum
here, many more decided to leave. And Monday evening, Channel Four
news reported that officials, sensitive to the perception that
Britain is an easy target for refugees, leaned heavily on the 73 in
an effort to convince them to go home.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining passengers have a long road ahead of them,
beginning with hours of interviews by immigration officers, who are
hardly inclined to be sympathetic to their plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeking to ascertain whether they are really seeking
asylum, or whether they want to stay for any other reason,'' a
spokesman for the Home Office said of the 73 passengers in
Moreton-in-Marsh. The interviews, conducted with the help of
freelance translators, give asylum applicants the chance to explain
why they fled their country and why they are afraid to return. The
Afghans have to remain on the fire service campus during this time
and are being giving food and clothes, but no money.
</P>
<P>
   If they are not immediately ejected, the Afghans will be settled
somewhere by the government while their applications are being
processed, or while they are appealing their decisions. Also, the
government has been reportedly approaching third countries,
including Pakistan, and asking them to take the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the British home secretary, Jack Straw, said he would
personally rule on the Afghans' asylum requests and would try to
eject them from Britain as soon as possible. But on Sunday, he
seemed to backtrack slightly, telling the BBC that ``everybody
knows that what I do is make the initial decision in asylum cases,
but there is a right of appeal thereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   Asylum applications can be tied up for years in the complicated
appeals process. Ann Widdecombe, the shadow home secretary for the
opposition Conservative Party, accused Straw and the Labor Party
government of deliberately prejudicing the case by his strong words
last week because, she said, he knew all along that any decision to
eject the Afghans would invariably be overturned on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take much gumption to figure out that he is trying
to sound tough while relying on the courts to overrule him and let
these asylum seekers stay,'' she said. ``You can't believe a word
that this Labor lot say.''
</P>
<P>
   The men charged with hijacking the plane, who the police say
were armed with handguns and less powerful weapons, are not
scheduled to reappear in court until March, and then probably will
not be tried for several more months, the police said. Under
British law, there are no minimum sentences for hijacking, but the
suspects could face sentences as long as life in prison if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reuters reported that the hostages who elected to
leave Britain were welcomed with paper flowers, new clothes and
warm words from the Taliban, the Islamic group that controls most
of Afghanistan, when they flew back to the country after their
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Hugging the passengers as they left the plane, the Taliban
foreign minister, Wakil Ahmad Muttawakil, accused those who
remained in Britain of seeking a better way of life, not fleeing
political repression at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are economic asylum seekers, not political refugees,'' he
told reporters at the Kandahar airport. And he denied reports that
the hijackers would have been put to death under the harsh Taliban
code of justice had they returned home. ``They would have faced
sentences of seven years in jail if found guilty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The returning passengers called Britain an ``infidel'' country
and said they were relieved to be back in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a Muslim country _ how could we stay?'' one
passenger told Reuters. ``And the weather was depressing and the
food was awful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
