<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YOUNG, RICE REMAIN IN LIMBO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Just because Steve Young and Jerry Rice
are among 40 players the San Francisco 49ers have under contract
after the great Salary Cap Purge of 2000 does not necessarily mean
they will be with the team next season.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the club is not through tweaking its roster in
the wake of its worst season in 20 years. Between now and the draft
in April, the 49ers will attempt to sign their own free agents and,
cap room permitting, pursue players on the free agent market.
</P>
<P>
   The team's most immediate needs are at quarterback, cornerback,
defensive end and offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the event Steve would not be with us, if he retires, we're
going to be ready to know who we're going to pursue,'' coach Steve
Mariucci said. ``A lot will depend on if Steve surprises us and
says he's going to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's agent, Leigh Steinberg, said the 38-year-old quarterback
will make a decision on his football future in April.
</P>
<P>
   As for Rice, it appears the 49ers would like him to return for a
16th season, but not at his current salary cap number of $5.49
million. If Rice does not agree to a restructured contract, it
would not be surprising if the 49ers waived him after June 1, when
roster moves impact the salary cap in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jerry has made up his mind to play for this contract and
this contract only, we'll have to decide if we can absorb that,''
general manager Bill Walsh said. ``We want him back. We would like
very much to have Jerry playing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Because negotiations between the 49ers and Rice's agent, Jim
Steiner, stalled, the club decided to put off contract talks until
another day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll address Jerry Rice's circumstances further and then come
to an agreement as soon as we can,'' Walsh said. ``There's no
timetable. It will be our job, and Jerry's representatives, to come
to an agreement. We have to reach agreement. We're not going to
publicly state what has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's 37 and two years removed from a serious knee
injury, Rice was the 49ers' best wide receiver in 1999, catching 67
passes for 830 yards and five touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to know what interest he has in playing for the 49ers
again,'' Mariucci said. ``He assured me he would like to play again
and I assured him we would like to have him back.''
</P>
<P>
   More cap room must be cleared if the 49ers are to sign their own
free agents, in particular defensive tackle Junior Bryant, tight
end Greg Clark, safety Zack Bronson and kicker Wade Richey. Of the
four, Bryant is the only unrestricted free agent; the 49ers made
contract tenders to Clark, Bronson and Richey to secure their
negotiation rights.
</P>
<P>
   Young restructured his contract in such a way as to save the
49ers a little more than $3 million in salary cap money. The club
is now about $3.5 million under the cap, which should be enough to
make a serious offer to Bryant, who is free to negotiate with any
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in the process of as soon as possible reaching an
agreement,'' Walsh said. ``I know personally he would like to play
for the San Francisco 49ers. We'll be in competition for Junior but
we feel confident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
