<HEADER>
A6742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-ASSESS-NYT     02-14 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY A TORTUOUS PATH, INDONESIA'S PRESIDENT OVERTAKES HIS GENERAL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In the end, President Abdurrahman Wahid got
just what he wanted Monday: the suspension of his troublesome
general along with new affirmations of support from the country's
querulous military.
</P>
<P>
   He took a long, zigzagging road to get there, but the hairpin
turns themselves now seem to have been part of the plan, a method
one expert called ``confuse and rule.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Put yourself in his shoes,'' said Daniel S. Lev, an expert on
Indonesia who is a professor at the University of Washington.
``What would you do?''
</P>
<P>
   This is a president without a personal power base, presiding
over a fractured political scene, who has taken on the institution
from which his predecessors drew their power: the military.
</P>
<P>
   So he bobs and weaves, pushes and retreats, cracks a joke or two
and leaves his opponents to try to figure out what he is up to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw what appeared to be all kinds of uncertainty,
ambiguity, ambivalence,'' said Lev, speaking of Wahid's two weeks
of verbal jabbing and poking as he tried to get his stubborn
security minister, Gen. Wiranto, to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the president is pragmatic, changeable and impulsive by
nature, often exasperating even his own subordinates. ``But what is
important here,'' Lev said, ``is that Wiranto was bamboozled, he
was in a corner and didn't know how to get out, and now he's out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid had begun calling for the resignation after an independent
commission recommended the general's prosecution for his role in
the deaths of hundreds of people in East Timor after the former
Dutch colony voted in August to become independent of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   In a final flurry of confusion _ experts here are now arguing
over whether the president was consistent or inconsistent _ Wahid
first told Wiranto that he could stay on as coordinating minister
for security affairs, then told him he must step aside as an
``inactive'' cabinet minister.
</P>
<P>
   Bravely bearing the burden of spokesman for this confusing
president, Marsilam Simanjuntak asserted Monday morning that there
had been no change in policy. He seemed to be trying to pronounce a
tongue twister.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reversal of the decision,'' he said. ``He is not
in an active status now, so practically or theoretically he is
still a nonactive member of the cabinet. I'm not playing with words
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The general accepted his suspension gracefully, and the chief of
the armed forces restated the military's allegiance to civilian
control _ clear and significant victories for the president.
</P>
<P>
   And they were the result of planning, not impulse, said
Aristedes Katoppo, an editor who is a leading political analyst.
Wahid is like a winding river, he said, twisting and turning to
avoid obstacles but flowing consistently downhill toward its goal,
the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gus Dur looks as if he is meandering neither east nor west,''
he said, using the president's nickname. ``But in fact he has two
consistent principles. One is nonviolence and the other is
democratization, which includes demilitarization.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's brother, Salehudin Wahid, was quoted by local newspapers
last week as saying, ``I think it is impossible for the president
to express inconsistent statements because I know that whatever he
says, there is an underlying meaning which we do not understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's behavior may be particularly confusing to
non-Indonesians, Katoppo suggested. Mostly, people here seemed more
amused than upset over Wahid's seemingly erratic behavior, and less
concerned over the possibility of a coup than foreign investors,
who drove down the value of the currency, the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for most Indonesians the outcome was fairly clear from
the start,'' Katoppo said. ``It was kind of a soap opera, maybe
intended as an education in the rule of law, but there was no real
suspense.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama weakened the general, who seemed sometimes bewildered
by two weeks of ``suggestions'' that he resign, issued from
successive stops on a 13-nation tour by the president.
</P>
<P>
   But his suspension from the cabinet is, in principle,
reversible. It depends on the outcome of the investigation by the
attorney general into the general's responsibility for the deaths
in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   After repeatedly denying culpability as he refused to step down,
Wiranto appeared to reverse field on both counts Monday, admitting
command responsibility for the abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say I was involved in human rights violations,'' the
general said, according to local reporters. ``Instead, as long as I
was responsible for national security, I am responsible for those
human rights violations in East Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   His statement generally conforms with the accusations against
him.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The timing of both Wiranto's removal and his concession of
responsibility seemed significant, coming on the eve of the arrival
here of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has separately investigated the abuses in
East Timor, and Wahid has said he wants to pre-empt an
international war crimes tribunal by conducting a credible
investigation and trial here. The Indonesian commission named 33
military and civilian figures, including Wiranto, as responsible
for the killings and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Singapore on Monday, Annan made it clear that the
Security Council could still step in with its own tribunal if it is
not satisfied with Indonesia's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased that the Indonesian government seems determined to
hold those responsible accountable,'' he said. ``The council, which
also has a report, is going to keep an eye on this process, and at
this stage it is not going to set up a tribunal.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Without a strong traditional power base, Wahid derives much of
his support from the fact that for now he seems to be the only hope
Indonesians have for real reforms. Other potential leaders are less
democratic and more divisive in their outlooks and positions.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly two years after the fall of President Suharto, there
is still clearly an urgent national consensus for thoroughgoing
change.
</P>
<P>
   Public support, kept alive by his very open style of leadership,
is Wahid's strongest source of power, experts here said. But by
speaking off the cuff and by staking out positions and then
abandoning them, he does risk losing the fear and respect he needs
to govern.
</P>
<P>
   A number of his supporters have warned him to be more careful _
to count to 10, as it were, before he speaks. On the other hand,
lightness of being seems to be his main weapon, and shield, in the
dangerous game he is playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my remarks were misunderstood, then I apologize,'' he said
last year, after offending someone with one of his jokes. ``What's
the big deal? There's no need to be angry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
