<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6746 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SCHULZ-BOS &LR;      02-14 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SCHULZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES SCHULZ, 1922-2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN WASSERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Schulz labored for 50 years over a cartoon strip whose
name, chosen by his syndicate, he vehemently disliked. Once
``Peanuts'' took off, he was stuck with it, and he proceeded to ink
the mistitled feature to the greatest success of any comic strip in
the history of newspapers. It was the sort of irony that Schulz not
only appreciated but savored in more than 18,250 strips that
appeared from 1950 until Sunday, the day he died.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to forget how revolutionary ``Peanuts'' was when it
landed in the 1950s comics landscape. Suddenly, real children were
set free alongside the ``gagged'' worlds of Dagwood, Blondie,
Beetle Bailey, and the exploits of various caped crusaders. Charlie
Brown, Lucy, Linus, and the rest of the cast were by turns anxious,
dreamy, sadistic, jealous, lonely, and in love. In a gray flannel
culture congratulating itself on the steady march of success, there
_ on the funny pages _ was a meditation on the meaning of failure.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of Schulz's half-century of graphic theater was the
pursuit of grace through perseverance. That was the theme of his
own craftsmanship, as well. He never hired inkers to do his drawing
or writers to feed him gags. He honed a drawing style that looked
naive but hid a keen sense of balance, design, and economy of
expression. He studied the timing of earlier cartoonists and
comedians and wrote as sparely as he drew.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Schulz remained deeply insecure. ``I'm a nonentity.
Except that I draw,'' he told his hometown paper, the Santa Rosa
(Calif.) Press Democrat in 1997. But when he drew or talked about
drawing, his Charlie Brown neurosis was erased. ``I'm sorry for
people who have to live through others. We see so much of that. I
guess I think about it when I go to a concert and hear a pianist
play a Brahms concerto or when I saw Willie Mays make a great
catch. I think at least I have something I can do. And I'm doing it
as well as anyone's ever done it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans of the comics pages offer our standing ovation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6750 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CHILE-BOS &LR;      02-14 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MISSING TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is never too late to learn the truth about certain things.
Recently declassified documents about the CIA's shameful role in
the murder of Charles Horman and Frank Teruggi in Chile, during the
repression that followed General Augusto Pinochet's 1973 military
putsch, ought to be welcomed by every American who understands how
fragile democracy can be.
</P>
<P>
   A part of Horman's story was told in the 1982 Costa-Gavras
movie, ``Missing.'' The film dramatized how US officials withheld
information about Horman's murder from his family.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after Pinochet's security forces murdered Horman and
Teruggi, the State Department conducted two internal reviews of the
crime and a subsequent coverup. The reviews were prompted by a
former Chilean intelligence officer who said he was present when
Pinochet's intelligence chief said Horman knew too much _
presumably about US involvement in the coup _ and had to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rafael Gonzalez, the eyewitness, someone he took to
be an American was present when that verdict was passed on Horman.
The files of the two State Department reviews were heavily blacked
out by CIA censors in 1976. The uncensored files, described in
Sunday's New York Times, say: ``US intelligence may have played an
unfortunate part in Horman's death,'' either by providing and
confirming information about him or by doing ``nothing to
discourage the logical outcome of government of Chile paranoia.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton did the right thing when he ordered the files
declassified after Pinochet was indicted in Spain for crimes
against humanity. The next step should be an effort to identify the
Chilean who gave the order for Horman's murder and any Americans
who knew about it. There should also be a wider search for the full
story of Washington's complicity in Pinochet's coup.
</P>
<P>
   The terrible truth about those old crimes is that they disclose
a dalliance with fascism abroad. Horman and Teruggi perished
because of that betrayal of American ideals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1854EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6751 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HEART-SCAN-COX     02-14 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-SCAN-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   New computerized scans on cutting edge of cardiac care
</P>
<P>
   By Kevin Lamb
</P>
<P>
   KETTERING, Ohio _ Through special glasses, the picture on the
computer screen looks like a model of a heart. The distinct,
three-dimensional chambers, the thicket of arteries heading toward
the lungs, the spine in the background _ it is all very lifelike.
</P>
<P>
   To be more precise, it's alive. The image in Kettering Medical
Center's radiology department compiles advanced X-ray scans of a
person's heart, resting between beats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at the heart and turn it around as if it's in
your own hands,'' said Dr. Ziwar Karabatak, a Kettering
cardiologist who saw the image last week for the first time. ``It's
something like a dream that you thought could happen one day. But
it's reality now.''
</P>
<P>
   Karabatak and the other doctors who first see this computerized
tomography (CT) image ``want to use it tomorrow,'' says Bilal
Ezzeddine, Kettering's imaging project director, who has two
Ph.D.s. But stunning as it is to see a heart jump off the screen in
three dimensions, Ezzeddine says Kettering's researchers ``aren't
there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   They plan to develop a safer, faster and cheaper way of
discovering early stages of heart disease and diagnosing the
symptoms that send people to hospitals. As Ezzeddine envisions it,
the CT technology will be an interim step. The ultimate goal is to
use a single magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) device not only for
``virtual heart'' replications, but also to perform the gamut of
cardiac diagnostic tests that now require four machines.
</P>
<P>
   Working with manufacturer Siemens Medical Systems of Iselin,
N.J., Kettering is one of only five hospitals worldwide
investigating digital imagery to find out if it can assess
cardiovascular disease as reliably as an angiogram, the diagnostic
gold standard performed through a catheter to the cardiac arteries.
</P>
<P>
   The drawback to angiograms is they involve sticking a tube
through the patient's arteries and shooting dye through it. That
carries risks. But unless digital imagery can predict heart disease
as accurately as an angiogram, it won't matter how much safer it
is.
</P>
<P>
   To determine that, Kettering researchers are examining both
types of pictures of the same patients, and comparing how well they
illustrate the extent of the patients' heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Cardiologists already use high-speed CT scans to look for heart
disease in patients without symptoms. The Dayton Heart Hospital has
been doing that since it opened in September, Kettering will start
using its scanner for screening soon and Good Samaritan Hospital
has ordered a machine for the same purpose _ giving the Dayton area
one of the highest ratios of fast scanners to population in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The screening CT scans can detect heart disease in people who
feel fine, enabling them to change their diets or add medication so
it doesn't become serious.
</P>
<P>
   Kettering's research is aimed more at people whose hearts
already are causing problems. When they come to the emergency room
with chest pains, faster diagnosis makes for faster medical
treatment _ maybe drugs to dissolve a blood clot, maybe balloon
angioplasty to open a blocked cardiac artery, maybe surgery to
bypass the clogged artery. The faster the treatment, the less
damage to heart muscle, says Dave Seidel, Kettering's director of
cardiac services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only able to do this because we have the imaging
infrastructure already in place,'' Ezzeddine says. Siemens brings
people to Kettering from all over to see its system for storing and
transmitting medical images on computer disks and a faster, lighter
MRI machine that's one of about 10 in the country.
</P>
<P>
   MRIs have traditionally been too slow to capture a heart's image
between beats, but the new unit displays the beating heart more
seamlessly than streaming video on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   After focusing its MRI energy on brains for the last few years,
Kettering is just beginning to turn its attention to the body's
other command center. ``You could argue the heart is the more
important one,'' Ezzeddine says, ``because heart disease is the
leading cause of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Where CT scans can display the geographic layout of an organ, an
MRI also can depict the chemical activity within that geography.
High activity of certain chemicals in the brain indicates a tumor.
Low activity of other chemicals in the heart indicates dead muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The MRI uses colors to show how much of a chemical is present,
so it can illustrate a diseased heart with the rainbow spectrum
from robust red areas to dead violet areas. It's comparable to a
color-coded U.S. map that shows high concentrations of population
on the East Coast and low ones in Wyoming and Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have other ways of showing a muscle's viability, but this
way we can see it earlier,'' says Mehdi Adineh, Kettering's
Ph.D.-level senior MRI physicist. And only the MRI can show the
geography of a cardiac artery blockage and the inactivity of dead
heart muscle on the same image.
</P>
<P>
   They're a relevant package, says Seidel, because hospitals waste
millions of dollars uselessly rerouting blood vessels to nourish
heart tissue that is already dead.
</P>
<P>
   Those millions aren't there to waste anymore. In fact, with
health plans reimbursing hospital services at ``40 to 45 cents on
the dollar,'' Seidel says there aren't enough profits to fully fund
this imaging research, being overseen by cardiologist Dr. Robert
Kiefaber and radiologist Dr. Richard McKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to seek external funding,'' Seidel says, making
Kettering's partnerships with Siemens and Wright-Patterson Air
Force Base all the more valuable.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in the MRI research is making the cardiac arteries
more visible, Ezzeddine says. When the scientists figure out how to
show them clearly on MRIs, the resulting one-station diagnoses will
be not only safer, faster and cheaper, but also less confusing,
with all relevant information on a single image.
</P>
<P>
   Ezzeddine is eager to see how the heart doctors apply all this
information. He knows they won't close down the catheterization
labs just because diagnostic angiograms become obsolete. Caths will
still be needed for balloon angioplasty, for example, in which
tubing is run through the arteries to open up a narrowing heart
vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians have so many intricate, new ways of navigating blood
vessels to repair cardiovascular disease that it is spawning a new
specialty, cardiac intervention, in which Karabatak is
board-certified. They snake their instruments through the vessels
and fix them from the inside without surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Without cutting the patient open, though, the doctor can't see
what he or she is doing. The angiograms and other two-dimensional
images don't show exactly how the blood vessels are twisted or
bent. So Karabatak says he tries to visualize what a stack of
two-dimensional CT scans would look like in three dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the computer does that for me,'' he says of the image that
so excited him last week. ``You can see and anticipate possible
complications before you get to them. It takes away a lot of
guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton (OH) Daily News. E-mail him at
kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
