<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BACH-COMPLETE-NYT &LR;      02-14 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACH-COMPLETE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: TAKEOUT ORDER _ BUCKET O' BACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Teldec company hasn't offered to send me its recorded
collection of Johann Sebastian Bach's music complete, but if it
does, I have a gracious letter of refusal ready. Never mind when I
would listen to it; where would I put it?
</P>
<P>
   Think of the expanse: 153 compact discs released in 12 volumes,
71 CDs of the sacred cantatas alone, 35 more for organ and other
keyboard pieces. Volume 7 has motets, songs and 371 chorales.
According to my crude powers of calculation ``Bach 2000,'' as this
project is trademarked, competes with Genesis: a creation-making
seven days of listening and no seventh day of rest. No time out for
naps or bathroom breaks either.
</P>
<P>
   If each plastic jewel box measures 3/8 inch in thickness, allow
for almost 2 yards of music. Eleven hundred ninety-nine dollars and
97 cents, please. A less caloric package, minus the cantatas
(described by one representative of the company as ``Bach Light''),
will cost you $849.97.
</P>
<P>
   Teldec has let loose an avalanche of greatness that few of us
are ready to dig our way out of. Having these items assembled on
the shelf is a comfort, I suppose. To get them that far, the record
company has thoughtfully arranged Bach complete into a musical
suitcase, equipped with handle for carrying. Music enters the 21st
century with luggage in its hand.
</P>
<P>
   Once the contents are home and in place, all cultural bases will
be covered. Sudden world shortages of ``Actus Tragicus''? Some
unforeseen market run on the ``Coffee Cantata''? All of Bach will
be there waiting for us, like the canned goods we prudently stocked
in our backyard bomb shelter.
</P>
<P>
   There is the pride of ownership, but this is a nettlesome
problem in music. We can show friends a good piece of Wedgwood or
Rose Medallion china, buoyed not only by its beauty but by knowing
it belongs to us and not them. We can pick it up, feel its surface
and know it is downstairs on the sideboard when we go to bed at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Music is hard to own. It's out there in the ether. The
collector's thrill of possession has been taken away. Composers own
the performance rights (for a while); performers own some of the
profits from record sales. But how do we collect the Bartok Fourth
String Quartet? I count 10 versions of it now in print. We can buy
a copy, but then so can everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   There is even the minute possibility that we could own the
original manuscript, but a printed score available in any reputable
music store will (or should) give us the same messages and is
probably easier to read.
</P>
<P>
   I still have the first long-playing record I ever bought: Book
I, Volume 1 of Wanda Landowska playing ``The Well-Tempered
Clavier'' (RCA Victor LM1017). Maybe an antiques dealer would
admire the patina on that old cardboard cover. As to the vinyl
surface, ``scratched'' might translate into ``charmingly
distressed.'' I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I can hear the identical performance spruced up and
available on compact disc and sounding better than it did before.
The only thing to collect is the cardboard and the vinyl, and
neither is music.
</P>
<P>
   One calming thought: Bach complete on one shelf is the
equivalent of an Encyclopedia Britannica or another New Grove
Dictionary spinoff. It is there with what we want, if and when we
need it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sensation is not the same. An encyclopedia or
dictionary is dormant. Both are built to be passive. They wait
patiently to be paid attention to. A recording has a latent energy.
It sits on the shelf wanting to be heard; thumbing past it leaves
us with a twinge of guilt: ``Shouldn't we be taking the `Musical
Offering' for a walk now and then?''
</P>
<P>
   The principal trauma in receiving Bach 2000 and the reason I
graciously demur from having it in my house (although the Teldec
people still haven't offered) is the suddenness. It is having so
much, so fast, with such brutal simultaneity.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have the dubious advantage of receiving CDs in the mail;
they come unbidden and often in volume. When I was young and poor
and eager for musical information, each purchase _ one a week with
every paycheck _ was a new wonder, a treasure to be examined and
re-examined. Having one Bach record made me listen over and over.
Having 153 is so intimidating, so engulfing, I might not listen at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Teldec, to be fair, doesn't expect many customers to be walking
out of record stores suitcase in hand. But that depends perhaps on
how many of Wall Street's current bonus babies are interested in
Bach. Twelve hundred dollars, after all, will buy them a couple of
nights at a good Paris hotel, or three or four made-to-order
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Bach 2000 will be coming at you in waves: first, five volumes of
cantatas (four with 15 CDs each); then Volumes 6 and 7 (Passions,
Masses, motets, chorales and the Magnificat: about 22 CDs); at high
tide, expect the organ and other keyboard works (Volumes 8, 9 and
10). The waters will ebb with chamber and concerto pieces. The
items will also trickle individually. Some of these recordings are
new; many are old releases recycled.
</P>
<P>
   The performers and performing groups (Thomas Hampson and Barbara
Bonney are exceptions) represent a firmament of historically
informed music making. Nikolaus Harnoncourt, the archangel of early
music, hovers over Bach 2000. Gustav Leonhardt and Ton Koopman are
scarcely less blessed.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere on the rosters do I find Leopold Stokowski and his
marvelously Technicolored big-band transcriptions. There is no
Bach-Busoni or Bach-Liszt, no ``Switched-On'' Bach, no Jacques
Loussier giving the Inventions a boogie beat.
</P>
<P>
   Teldec gives us the composer from one point of view: the closest
approximation possible to the instruments Bach heard and how they
were used by him and his colleagues in the first half of the 18th
century.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is powerful and powerfully argued, and Bach 2000 is
entitled to it. But as we make our way through the 250th
anniversary of his death, we should not forget that Bach belongs to
all of us; researchers into the long ago are not necessarily his
exclusive agents.
</P>
<P>
   It is sometimes said that any literary epoch of the last 400
years can be precisely described by a reading of its Shakespeare
criticism. Our interpretations of the plays seem to change
drastically according to who we are and when. Maybe Bach, like
Shakespeare, is another of the proverbial mirrors we can hold up to
ourselves. He is not back there. He is about us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1903EST &QL; 
