<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6779 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-JUVENILE-DIABETES     02-14 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-JUVENILE-DIABETES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIABETES MEMOIRS BRING THE DISEASE OUT OF THE CLOSET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Mo., Mass., Iowa)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By LESLIE BERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in her memoir on living with diabetes, Lisa Roney
describes a hike through the Great Smoky Mountains and her
frustrating inability to keep pace with her group. Elevated blood
sugar, probably from eating too much gorp, was making her lethargic
and confused, and she had to keep sitting down to rest along the
narrow trail.
</P>
<P>
   Only her best friend's older brother had the decency to hang
back and ease her along, and the rest of the group teased her over
his attention. But humiliating as their taunts were, Roney recalls,
it was better to be seen as manipulative than medically flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a male could rescue me the situation seemed outwardly
almost normal, as though I were simply a weak female, not a sick
person,'' she writes in her first book, ``Sweet Invisible Body:
Reflections on a Life With Diabetes'' (Henry Holt &AMP; Co.).
</P>
<P>
   When Roney was 11, she learned she had diabetes, the most
serious form in which the pancreas fails to produce any of the
hormone needed to process sugar. Now 39, Roney has been giving
herself daily glucose tests and insulin injections for nearly three
decades. Though she is ostensibly healthy, blindness, heart disease
and life-threatening infection are among the potential
complications she faces as a diabetic woman.
</P>
<P>
   She has not always been careful. A heavy dose of denial meant
that for years, she avoided checkups, indulged in eating binges and
juggled three jobs at once.
</P>
<P>
   And she was not alone in slighting her disease. Doctors plied
her with platitudes. Even close friends were insensitive, showing
up late for lunch dates when irregular meals can wreak havoc with a
diabetic person's blood sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Now pursuing a doctorate in American literature at Pennsylvania
State University, Roney said she began her book after deciding that
society had denied diabetes its stature as a serious illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I tried to learn to understand myself, it was natural for
me to look to books and there was not much out there,'' Roney, who
grew up in Tennessee, said recently in a telephone interview. ``All
kinds of other ailments have figured in literature and cultural
studies. But for some reason, diabetes was not included.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, there is now a handful of diabetes memoirs
that suggests a similar awakening in others. Last August, when Holt
released Roney's book, W.W. Norton &AMP; Co. published ``Showdown With
Diabetes,'' by Deb Butterfield, an account of her successful
pancreas transplant and her anger over what she sees as the
traditional view that diabetes should be managed rather than cured.
In 1998, Scribner came out with ``Needles: A Memoir of Growing Up
With Diabetes,'' in which Andie Dominick describes her complicated
relationship with her older sister _ both siblings were found to
have diabetes as children _ and the reckless behavior, including
drug abuse, that contributed to her sister's death.
</P>
<P>
   All three authors, whose cases were diagnosed as juvenile, or
Type 1, diabetes, address the burden of having a potentially fatal
condition they say they were expected to keep under wraps. All
three recall growing up in an era of excess _ of drugs, sex and
gourmet food _ and having to restrain themselves. And all three
memoirs detail how relentless diabetes management is.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield became so adept at taking her insulin shots amid the
demands of her former Wall Street career as an executive recruiter
that she would inject herself under her desk, through her clothes.
If blood started seeping through her blouse, she simply put on her
blazer to conceal it. Today, no longer dependent on insulin because
of a pancreas transplant, she advocates wider use of the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been portrayed as a manageable disease _ that if people
take insulin, if they follow their diet and if they follow all
their regulations and restrictions, everything will be fine,'' said
Butterfield, who is 40 and now lives in St. Louis and New York.
``Therefore the implication is, if things go wrong, it's because
the person who had diabetes did something wrong. It's the disease
that's the problem, not the person.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional toll of living with chronic disease may partly
account for the flurry of memoirs, said Dr. C. Ronald Kahn,
president of the Joslin Diabetes Center in Boston, a research and
treatment center. But Kahn said that only 5 percent to 10 percent
of the nation's 16 million diabetics have the extreme,
insulin-dependent condition described in the books. Most people
have Type 2 diabetes, the adult-onset form that is often milder and
can be managed by diet and medication. In addition, Kahn said,
pancreas transplants are still difficult procedures performed on
less than 1 percent of diabetes patients. For now, he said, a
controlled diet and medication remain the best way for most
diabetes patients.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kahn agrees that diabetes has not gotten its due. About
two years ago, he led a committee asked by Congress to look at the
state of diabetes research. The resulting 145-page report urged
huge increases in financing, from the current $430 million a year
to, eventually, $1.6 billion a year. If that figure seems high,
Kahn said, it represents only 1 percent of the annual cost to the
nation for diabetes health care.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes is the leading cause of nontraumatic amputations, of
blindness in working-age adults, and of dialysis, he said.
Moreover, Type 2 or adult-onset diabetes has grown nearly sixfold
over the last 40 years, because of the nation's aging population
and sedentary lifestyle. ``People don't realize how much impact it
has on patients and the health of the nation as a whole,'' Kahn
said. ``It doesn't get the same respect as other diseases where the
impact is more acutely dramatic, where people die very quickly.
With diabetes, it's a very slow and complex process and takes many
years for the complications to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the three authors, Butterfield suffered the most
complications, including kidney damage and a heart attack, before
receiving her successful transplant six years ago. Her memoir
recounts them all, including the alarming discovery of neuropathy,
or death of the nerves, in her feet and lower legs.
</P>
<P>
   A diabetic since age 9, Butterfield walked out of one shoe one
morning as she left her apartment and did not feel it. The stares
of pedestrians prompted her to look down and, to her horror, see
she was standing on one bare foot. The next day, she forced herself
to buy a cane and practiced holding it in front of her mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how I looked at myself,'' Butterfield wrote, ``I
looked crippled. After 19 years of hiding my diabetes, my life as
an undercover diabetic was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominick, a 28-year-old English teacher at Iowa State University
at Ames, also received a diabetes diagnosis at 9 and developed
severe retinopathy, or eye disease, after 15 years of diabetes had
weakened the blood vessels behind her eyes and caused them to
hemorrhage. To repair her failing vision, she has had seven laser
surgeries and a major operation in which the blood-filled gel
behind the eye lens was sucked out and replaced with saline
solution.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the 1993 death of her older sister Denise that
prompted her to begin her book, Dominick said in an interview. The
pair shared a deep connection despite the 12-year age difference,
from the matching color of their hair and eyes to a birthmark on
their abdomens. Dominick so idolized Denise that she would play
with her discarded needles.
</P>
<P>
   When Dominick's diabetes was diagnosed as well, Denise became
even more fiercely protective. The two sisters were living together
in Des Moines, Iowa, when Denise died from a combination of
diabetes-related heart disease and chronic cocaine abuse, said
Dominick, who found the body. Dominick wrote that in her grief, she
recognized that her sister had been self-destructive because of a
subconscious desire to take her own life before diabetes did.
</P>
<P>
   Roney also describes a constant awareness of mortality that
begins the moment she wakes up and follows her in her sleep. Even
today, she gets a daily, long-distance wake-up call from her mother
to make sure she has not slipped into a low-blood-sugar coma
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so, even though I adore sleeping,'' Roney writes, ``I
usually do so only tentatively, skimming on the surface out of fear
of not waking again...I try to remain aware of myself while I sleep
because it is then, during the stillness of eight or seven or six
hours' slumber, that my body is most vulnerable to these hideous
lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though my doctor reassures me that, aside from situations
related to alcohol and automobiles, few people actually die of
hypoglycemia...these episodes shame and haunt me, the most apparent
shadow on my semblance of a normal life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
