<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-TAILPLANE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSPECTION REVEALS 23 JETS WITH TAIL PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An urgent weekend inspection of more than 1,000 airplanes with
the same tail design as the Alaska Airlines MD-80 which crashed off
California two weeks ago has found at least 23 airplanes had some
problem with the mechanism which moves the stabilizer, the Federal
Aviation Administration said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In at least 13 cases, the mechanism _ which drives the
horizontal stablizer up and down in order to control the pitch of
the plane's nose _ was replaced, according to the FAA. In another
six cases, lubricant was added to the jackscrew which moves the
stabilizer and limits its movement in any one direction.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said airlines had until Wednesday to report what
corrective action was needed, and another week to report if no
action was taken, so the number of affected airplanes could
increase, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The jackscrew has been the focus of much attention of federal
accident investigators since the the two-foot-long shaft was
recovered Feb. 8 from the crash site of Alaska Airlines Flight 261
in the Pacific Ocean. The jackscrew was damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board disclosed Sunday night
that the Alaska Airlines plane that crashed Jan. 31 killing all 88
on board underwent a heavy maintenance check on Sept. 29, 1997. At
that time, mechanics found the mechanism _ known as the jackscrew
and gimbal nut assembly _ was worn and written up to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to replace the gimbal nut came after mechanics
performed a test known as an ``end-play check.'' That test revealed
the gimbal nut had ``maximum allowable end play limit'' according
to the plane's maintenance records. In other words, the nut was
close to failing to meet its specifications.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB chairman James Hall said that decision was reviewed the
next day, Sept. 30, and the maintenance record indicates that the
system ``fell within the specified tolerances. The record further
reflected that it was rechecked five times with the same result.
The entry also indicated that these results were signed off by an
Alaska Airlines maintenance inspector.''
</P>
<P>
   One long-time aviation maintenance specialist who spoke on
condition of anonymity said if the inspector was a supervisor
overriding the concerns of a mechanic, it could indicate that the
airline was trying to to get the plane back in service quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The specialist said that if there were concerns about the part,
it would either be replaced, or written up to be put on an
accelerated watch, so that mechanics would have to check it again
within a certain number of flight hours. It is not clear whether
that was done, or if the inspector was a supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines officials did not return a telephone call and
the NTSB had no further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said Monday that the visual inspection ordered on Friday
of all MD-80, MD-90, DC-9 and Boeing 717 jackscrew assemblies be
finished by midday Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,103 affected aircraft, jackscrews were replaced on at
least 13 planes: four on Alaskan Airlines planes, three on AirTran
planes, two on Hawaiian, and one each on Continental, Delta,
Northwest, and TWA.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Air Transport Association, the industry
trade association, said the repairs may have resulted in a few
sporadic cancellations of flights, but expected any inconvenience
to be minor.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA emergency order to inspect the mechanisms also
accelerates the timetable _ from every eight months to every 650
flight hours _ for re-inspecting the jackscrew assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The maintenance specialist said that the mechanism which moves
the horizontal stablizer on other types of aircraft is similar in
design to that on the MD-80 family of airplanes. However, FAA
spokesman Paul Takemoto said the agency had no plans to expand its
order to other types of aircraft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
