<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      02-14 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH AND MCCAIN IN CLOSE S.C. RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN and STEWART M. POWELL 
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWOOD, S.C. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain
entered the home stretch of their increasingly bitter battle for
South Carolina's nominating delegates Monday with polls pointing to
a close vote in Saturday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   The tight race put the spotlight on independent voters and
Democrats who can vote in the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   `At this point, I think it will be very close,'' said Harvey
Bell, Republican co-chair of Saluda County. The prospect of
independent and Democratic voters participating `doesn't sit well
with me,'' said Bell. `I hope it doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell's prediction of a close contest was borne out by late
polls.
</P>
<P>
   In a Los Angeles Time poll of likely voters in the South
Carolina released Monday Bush had 42 percent and McCain had 40
percent, a dead heat. A Newsweek poll released over the weekend had
Bush leading McCain 43 percent to 40 percent in the state.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by Rasmussen Associates showed the importance of
independent and Democratic voters in the Republican primary here.
</P>
<P>
   Among South Carolina Republicans, Bush leads by 19 percentage
points, according to the poll. However, among independents and
Democrats, McCain leads by a whopping 74-percent-to-18-percent
margin.
</P>
<P>
   By that calculus, a larger-than-average turnout among
independents and Democrats could throw the primary to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sought to capitalize on his experience as a two-term
governor of Texas, telling an admiring crowd that McCain had
`served his country well'' as a Navy flier and POW in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``This party needs somebody who can lead a proven leader with a
record of reform,'' Bush said. He asked for the support of `tire
kickers'' _ undecideds who had turned out to hear him speak.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm in a hard contest here,'' Bush said. Nevertheless, when
asked what he would do if he lost in South Carolina, Bush responded
confidently: `I'm not going to lose here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters acknowledged that if independents and Democrats
turn out in large numbers, Bush could leave South Carolina a loser.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was put on the defensive when Bush's campaign aides
accused him for favoring government-financed elections for members
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said that he opposes taxpayer financed federal
elections but has supported similar provisions in the past as part
of legislative compromises to reform the system. McCain said he
voted 11 times against public financing of federal elections. But
he said he might have voted for some measures that contained
provisions for public financing of federal campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather have something that may have some public
financing in it than the present system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing frustration at the cross-state debate, McCain said:
``This kind of savagery is not necessary in an American political
campaign,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Miles away, Bush replied, `That's not savagery. That's what we
call full exposure, full disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also responded to criticism from the National Rifle
Association that he had dropped his opposition to trigger locks on
handguns after a series of killings at the nation's schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``When kids go to school and start killing other kids, obviously
sometimes you rethink your position,'' McCain explained.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insisted that he _ and not McCain _ could attract enough
conservative Democrats and independents to beat either of the
Democratic contenders in November.
</P>
<P>
   For a Republican to draw Democrats and independents, `there must
be a clear philosophical difference'' between the Republican and
Democratic nominees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, speaking to reporters after a rally here in the
southwestern portion of the state, the home region of James Bonham
and William Travis _ heroes of the Alamo and major figures in Texas
history, cited former President Reagan's success against former
Vice President Walter Mondale in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In that race, voters had a clear choice between Reagan's
advocacy of lower taxes and less government and Mondale's statement
that he would raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   `There must be a clear philosophical difference,'' Bush said.
`There's no difference between McCain and (Vice President Al)
Gore'' on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is targeting conservative Democrats and
independents with mail and phone calls as part of its effort to
reach as many as 400,000 voters in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said he was not tailoring his message to those voters.
`I don't change my pitch,'' he said. `My pitch is give me a chance,
I can lead the country to a better tomorrow. My pitch is if you're
sick of Washington, give me a chance to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged that it is `hard for me to quantify
enthusiasm'' of voters in South Carolina, Bush said. `I thought I
was doing well in New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
