<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DOCTOROW-BOOK-REVIEW-     02-14 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOROW-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CITY OF GOD': TAKING READERS INSIDE THE WRITER'S IDEA NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Midway through ``City of God,'' E.L. Doctorow's fractured,
fragmentary new novel, a character observes that ``as a writer, I
am only fascinated by the power of this hodgepodge of chronicles,
verses, songs, relationships, laws of the universe, sins, and days
of reckonings'' _ a ``scissors-and-paste job'' that is ``terse,
inconsistent, defiant of common sense, and cryptically inattentive
to the ordinary demands of narrative.''
</P>
<P>
   While Doctorow means for this description to apply,
flatteringly, to the Bible, it might just as well apply, in far
more pejorative terms, to the author's own self-important novel.
</P>
<P>
   The novel, which takes its title from St. Augustine's classic
text, purports to be the journal of a writer named Everett. It is
filled with ideas for stories and movies, chapters of a novel,
transcripts of interviews, poems, song fragments and seemingly
random musings on everything from physics to metaphysics, the
feeding habits of birds to the spiritual life of Ludwig
Wittgenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these passages have enormous flash and dazzle: they
attest to Doctorow's virtuosic talents as a writer. Other bits are
emotionally engrossing, immersing us in such disparate worlds as a
Jewish ghetto during World War II and the Allied trenches of World
War I. The power of these sections, however, is deliberately
undercut by other passages that self-consciously call attention to
Doctorow's narrative method. The result is an oddly stilted novel
that tries to substitute pretension for ambition, avant-garde
gestures for a genuine authorial vision.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant story in ``City of God'' concerns the maverick
rector of a small New York City church, a man by the name of Thomas
Pemberton who is in the throes of a spiritual crisis, trying to
reconcile the myriad evils of the world with the existence of God.
When the crucifix from Pemberton's church is stolen and
mysteriously resurfaces on the roof of an uptown synagogue,
Pemberton takes the act of vandalism as a sign whose meaning he
must decipher. In the meantime he befriends the two rabbis of the
synagogue, a married couple named Joshua Gruen and Sarah
Blumenthal. After Joshua suddenly dies, the victim of a vicious
assault, Pemberton begins courting his widow and contemplates a
conversion to Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   As Doctorow tells it there are two Pembertons, two Joshuas and
two Sarahs: the ones who exist in real life and who have been
interviewed by Everett, and their fictionalized counterparts who
exist in the pages of Everett's novel-in-progress. The point of
these doppelgangers is to underscore two favorite Doctorow themes,
namely the interpenetration of fact and fiction (embodied most
successfully in his 1975 novel, ``Ragtime''), and the mechanics of
storytelling (embodied most prominently heretofore in his 1984
book, ``Lives of the Poets'').
</P>
<P>
   The ordering impulse of storytelling, in fact, is the main
leitmotif in this musically structured novel. In one way or another
nearly all of Everett's journal entries concern the importance of
narrative in our lives. Physics, Doctorow suggests, is a kind of
storytelling, providing an explanation for the physical workings of
the cosmos, just as various religions lay out different stories
meant to explain the moral underpinnings of the world. God can be
seen as the greatest of all narrators, conjuring the world into
being and presiding over it from afar; or He can be seen as the
ultimate creation of the writers of the Bible, intent on turning
``the human condition into a sequential narrative of how it came to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biblical stories, the Gospel stories, were the original
understandings,'' Pemberton declares, ``they were science and
religion, they were everything, they were all anyone had. But they
didn't write themselves. We have to acknowledge the storytellers'
work.''
</P>
<P>
   While some of the stories in Everett's journal are highly
compelling _ including one documenting the struggles of Sarah's
father and other Jews to survive the barbarities of the Nazi
occupation of their city _ the reader's attention is continually
distracted by Everett's weaker efforts. These lesser tales are just
the sort of trial balloons that writers jot down in their journals
and later, for good reason, put aside: a ludicrous treatment for a
movie about a man who plots to assume the identity of his mistress'
wealthy husband; another equally unbelievable story about a former
reporter who becomes an avenging angel of death. No doubt these
lesser stories are meant to illustrate the notion that weak
narratives, like strong ones, represent the human rage for closure,
our desire to force the messy ingredients of life into some sort of
order.
</P>
<P>
   What is ironic about ``City of God'' is that a book that
ostensibly celebrates storytelling should so willfully eschew
linearity and old-fashioned narrative itself. Doctorow, of course,
has used experimental techniques to impressive effect in earlier
books: ``The Book of Daniel'' used a highly elliptical narrative to
tell the story of the Rosenbergs (or a couple much like the
Rosenbergs) from their son's point of view, and ``Lives of the
Poets'' gave us the portrait of a writer refracted through the
fictions he's created.
</P>
<P>
   While the premise of having this novel take the form of a
writer's journal may seem similar to that of ``Lives of the
Poets,'' while Pemberton's struggles to find an authentic faith
recall the struggles of that earlier book's hero to find an
authentic mode of living, the two books differ enormously in
effect. ``City of God'' sorely lacks the neatly interlocking puzzle
pieces of ``Poets,'' _ the emotional through-line and organic sense
of coherence that lay beneath its innovative structure.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, in fact, ``City of God'' bears more of a resemblance
to a different Doctorow novel, ``Loon Lake'' (1980) _ another
pretentious and abstract novel that for all its flashes of
brilliance remains little more than a ``scissors-and-paste job,'' a
novel of ideas that may be packed with ideas but that fails as a
satisfying work of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL; 
`CITY OF GOD'  &QL; 
By E.L. Doctorow  &QL; 
272 pages. Random House. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
