u f BC-AOL-CABLE-BOS &LR;      02-14 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-CABLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL HALTS LOBBYING FOR CABLE BROADBAND LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a corporate policy change that largely brings it in line with
onetime rival AT&AMP;T Corp., AOL has called off lobbying efforts for
new state and local laws to require access to cable broadband
systems. It said it will seek instead to achieve those goals by
negotiations ``in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL has been among the fiercest proponents of opening fast cable
access systems such as MediaOne's RoadRunner service to competing
Internet service providers, calling it an issue of consumer
fairness.
</P>
<P>
   But it has widely been expected to lose heart for the fight
after announcing its $120 billion takeover of Time Warner, the
nation's leading cable provider. Under AOL's previous philosophy,
Time Warner's high-speed access systems would have been forced open
to rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Largely confirming reports over the weekend, AOL spokeswoman
Kathy McKiernan said Monday, ``Our focus is on making open access
real for the consumer in the marketplace. We are not pushing
legislation at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior AOL official confirmed that McKiernan's comments apply
to Massachusetts' proposed November ballot question, which AOL ``is
not opposing but is not actively pushing'' now.
</P>
<P>
   AOL officials also said they have no plans to try to unwind an
exclusive contract Time Warner has in place through 2001, similar
to MediaOne's Massachusetts arrangements, to make RoadRunner the
affiliated Internet service provider for Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's absence from the ballot fight leaves backers with
virtually no rich giant to counter a flood of money being poured by
AT&AMP;T into opposing the question. AT&AMP;T, which has announced plans to
buy MediaOne this spring, already has thrown $1.1 million into
opposing the question, saying the issue should be left to cable
providers and Internet service providers, or ISPs, to negotiate
without regulatory interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're looking at going ahead, but no matter what
kind of backing we have, we have always been looking at a David vs.
Goliath fight,'' said Stephen Allen, spokesman for the committee
organizing the ballot question. He reiterated that question
organizers would back off if AT&AMP;T and MediaOne negotiate ``a real
deal'' to open up to other ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Allen's group include local ISPs Berkshire.net,
HarvardNet and Shore.net, which have nothing close to the financial
might of AT&AMP;T and MediaOne. Boston venture capitalist J.
Christopher Grace, a large AOL stockholder, has put $600,000 into
backing the question, but he has not said whether the AOL-Time
Warner merger will cause him to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Among ISPs in the same league as AT&AMP;T and MediaOne, GTE
Internetworking of Burlington, Mass. has spoken out for open
access. But in Massachusetts, GTE officials are expected to stay
out of the ballot fight because Bell Atlantic _ which is merging
with GTE _ is seen as wanting to save political capital for its
quest to enter the $2 billion Bay State long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   GTE spokeswoman Briana Gowing said recently that the company
continues to support the cause of open access, but ``we haven't
specifically endorsed that ballot question.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Farrah John, spokeswoman for the MediaOne-backed group
opposing the November ballot question, said the AOL-Time Warner
combination ``proves that this is a dynamic market that is creating
choices for consumers. Government doesn't need to get involved.
We're going to continue to fight the petition because it's bad for
consumers and taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   The November ballot question would require owners of cable modem
systems _ in Massachusetts chiefly MediaOne and some upgraded
Adelphia franchises _ to allow ISPs to resell high-speed access
over those networks to their own subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   McKiernan said AOL has changed only tactics, not philosophy, in
backing off legislation-based open access. ``AOL is as strongly
committed to open access today as we were the day before we
announced our merger with Time Warner. Where we have moved is in
how to get from here to there,'' McKiernan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1908EST &QL; 
