<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-TALLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI TO PAY $920M FOR CONNECTICUT E-COMMERCE FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another week, another acquisition for the Internet company CMGI
Inc. This time, the Andover, Mass. company will pay $920 million in
cash and stock for Tallan Corp., a Connecticut electronic commerce
firm with roots that go far deeper than the Internet's.
</P>
<P>
   Tallan was founded in 1985, long before millions of people
started shopping online. It specializes in complex ``back-office''
computer systems retailers use to keep track of inventory,
deliveries, and customer preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly known as Business Data Services, Tallan changed its
name this year and today places a heavy emphasis on building
computer support systems for online retailers. Tallan's customers
include the name-your-own-price retailer Priceline, the online
bookseller Barnes &AMP; Noble.com, and the toy merchant eToys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been around for 15 years, we've been profitable, and the
work we do transcends the Internet focus,'' said Bruce Guptill,
vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI will pay $340 million in cash, the rest in CMGI shares and
options. Tallan will become part of CMGI Solutions, a unit that
specializes in providing complete e-commerce systems for large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of CMGI Solutions, Ron Spears, said his
company needs Tallan's expertise in heavy-duty retail data
processing. ``There are just a large number of enterprise-type
clients . . . that have come to CMGI and are asking us to fulfill
these kinds of requirements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guptill said the deal with CMGI gives his company ``an immediate
market presence that would be very time-consuming and
resource-consuming to get on our own.'' Besides, he added, ``they
paid a good price for us. It's a nice way to reward a lot of people
who worked a decade and a half to build this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallan, of Glastonbury, Conn., recently filed for an initial
public stock offering. This will be converted into an offering of
stock for the entire CMGI Solutions business unit sometime in the
next 120 days, Tallan and CMGI officers said.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI stock closed at 115 1/2, up 3 7/16, on the Nasdaq stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI has spent $6.5 billion buying stakes in 24 Internet and
software companies in the past year, Bloomberg News reported.
</P>
<P>
   It owns 16 companies and holds minority interests in 49 others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
