A6798 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RETAILEX-WEBSITE-BOS &LR;      02-14 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAILEX-WEBSITE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE TO OFFER EXCESS INVENTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ RetailExchange.com, an independent offshoot of Gordon
Brothers Group LLC of Boston, has launched a Web site where
manufacturers can sell excess inventory to retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Did Tommy Hilfiger make too many yellow golf shirts? This Web
site would serve as a marketplace that links designers with retail
chains interested in taking overruns off designers' hands.
</P>
<P>
   Some regard Gordon Brothers as the mortician of retail. When a
chain fails, Gordon Brothers often arranges its liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, we couldn't spell the word Internet, but we
knew it was going to somehow impact our business,'' said Kenneth
Frieze, a Gordon Brothers alumnus who runs RetailExchange.com.
</P>
<P>
   RetailExchange.com was conceived during a brainstorming session
on how Gordon Brothers might address the online world.
</P>
<P>
   Other entrepreneurs have rushed to set up Web sites that match
buyers and sellers, but only RetailExchange.com has a unique
``merchant's perspective'' on retail inventory, said Frieze, who is
also a son of Gordon Brothers chief executive Michael Frieze.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other dot-com companies, RetailExchange.com isn't
duplicating online what it does in the brick-and-mortar world.
RetailExchange.com is not about online liquidation. Nor is it an
auction site where merchandise is sold to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Designers have more concerns than just getting the best price on
excess shirts; they also need to protect their brands. If their
shirts ``wind up in schlocky stores,'' it can undermine a
designer's brand, Frieze said. So a designer may want to deal only
with retailers that agree to sell the shirts overseas.
</P>
<P>
   At the RetailExchange.com Web site, a designer can enter
negotiations in private chat rooms with potential buyers on exactly
how their goods will be sold.
</P>
<P>
   RetailExchange.com aims to make money by taking a small
percentage of transactions negotiated at its site.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world of designers and jobbers, buying and selling
excess merchandise can be a lengthy, cumbersome process.
</P>
<P>
   But Web site search features can squeeze much of the cost out of
the process. Instead of many phone calls and plane trips to see
what excess merchandise is available, a retail chain's buyer can go
to RetailExchange.com's Web site and search listings and photos for
the kind of goods the buyer is interested in.
</P>
<P>
   At Bradlees Inc. of Braintree, the chain's buyers are always
prowling for good deals. Not only may RetailExchange.com save time
and money, it gives Bradlees access to a far wider universe of
sellers and merchandise, said Bradlees chairman and chief executive
Peter Thorner, and that could mean that Bradlees customers could
see better values on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   To date, RetailExchange.com has received $11 million in venture
capital funding from Internet Capital Group, Dorset Capital,
Castile Ventures, and Gordon Brothers, and the hope is to take
RetailExchange.com public some day. To alert the players in the $25
billion US market for excess retail goods, Frieze hired Boston ad
agency Holland Mark Edmund Ingalls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1919EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
