<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6805 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RAYTHEON-ORION-BOS &LR;      02-14 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-ORION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON SCHEDULE LAG BLAMED IN NAVY CONTRACT LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Navy has cancelled a contract with Raytheon Co. to upgrade
some P-3 Orion ocean patrol aircraft after the defense contractor
fell behind schedule on the work.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes at a bad time for Raytheon, which is trying to
improve performance at its disparate units and turn around its
faltering profits and share price.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Navy nor Raytheon would discuss the financial impact
of the cancellation. The contract could have been worth more than
$200 million to Raytheon if it had been completed.
</P>
<P>
   The contract was part of what the Navy calls a ``sustained
readiness program'' being carried out in Greenville, Texas. The P-3
is a four-engine Lockheed Martin design that went into service in
the 1960s. Like many of the Navy's planes, its airframes and
electronic components are being modified or upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   The contract had called for Raytheon to repair 32 of the old
planes, but the Navy told the Lexington, Mass. defense contractor
to stop work after it finished repairs on the 13th aircraft,
according to a Jan. 21 letter sent to the company by a Navy
contract officer and obtained by The Boston Globe. The Navy told
Raytheon to prepare the remaining planes to be flown to another,
unspecified facility within the United States for maintenance or
other options.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy reached its decision after conducting a review of the
program and despite a Raytheon proposal to restructure the
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the Navy no longer views the (program), as
originally conceived, as the best and most economical approach to
extending the service life of the P-3 aircraft,'' said Raytheon
spokesman Dave Shea.
</P>
<P>
   According to the letter, the Navy determined that concluding the
program early is ``in the best interest of both the US Navy and
RSC,'' meaning Raytheon Systems Co.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was signed by Diane Balderson, a contracting official
in the Naval Air Systems Command headquarters in Patuxent River,
Md. The letter does not detail the reasoning behind the Navy's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Balderson referred questions to a Navy public affairs official,
Rob Koon, who confirmed the substance of the letter but said
neither Balderson nor others would discuss the decision Monday or
its impact on the Navy's P-3 fleet. Raytheon will continue to
provide some components and maintenance, the letter stated. Last
fall Raytheon had said its work on some P-3 planes was lagging, but
until Monday it hadn't disclosed the end of the program.
</P>
<P>
   The cancelation may not have a major financial impact on
Raytheon, given its revenue of $19.8 billion in 1999. But the
problems are only the latest in a series for the country's
third-largest defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Its shares have sunk to a fraction of their high of last summer
as the company has disclosed a series of financial problems and
difficulties integrating acquisitions it made during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The company's problems with the P-3 seem to fit the same
description. The work is being done in facilities in Greenville,
which Raytheon acquired as part of its $2.3 billion purchase of
Dallas-based E-Systems Inc. in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Balderson's letter also makes reference to a proposal Raytheon
made in November to restructure the program. According to the
letter, Raytheon alleged that government actions ``impaired'' its
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's Shea declined to elaborate. Balderson also wrote the
Navy hoped to negotiate a settlement agreement by Tuesday. Raytheon
eclined to discuss whether talks are under way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
