<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6806 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-RAPPER-DUPRI-COX     02-14 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPPER-DUPRI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court:Jermaine Dupri owes Ga. county 3 jail days
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia Court of Appeals says millionaire rapper
Jermaine Dupri should go to jail for three days.
</P>
<P>
   The court upheld a ruling by Fayette County Superior Court Judge
Chris Edwards, who became upset when Dupri skipped out on jury
duty. In May, Edwards found Dupri in contempt of court and
sentenced him to three days in the Fayette County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri's lawyer appealed and says he'll keep appealing to the
Georgia Supreme Court, meaning Dupri remains free while the higher
court considers the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in fundamental disagreement with the opinion issued by
the Georgia Court of Appeals,'' attorney Michael Tyler said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler said in court documents that Dupri had not willfully
disrespected the court.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri showed up for the first day of jury duty March 1 and was
excused for March 2 with the rest of the jury pool. Dupri had
received waivers from jury service in the past and wrongly assumed
Edwards would grant a waiver for the rest of the week, Tyler said.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri left town to perform March 3 at the Meadowlands in New
Jersey. Dupri offered to perform some sort of community service as
compensation for missing three days of jury duty, such as a benefit
concert, but Edwards turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   Fayette County District Attorney Bill McBroom said the ruling
sends a good message.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they let this guy disregard his jury summons, what will
stop other people from doing the same thing?'' McBroom said.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri is a giant in the world of rap and hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri's success as producer of the pre-teen rap duo Kris Kross
made him a millionaire before he turned 21. He produces acts such
as TLC and Usher and has written million-sellers for Mariah Carey
(``Always Be My Baby''), Usher (``You Make Me Wanna'') and himself
(``Money Ain't a Thing'').
</P>
<P>
   In recent years he's expanded by starting his own label, So So
Def Records, and started a sports management firm. In October, he
threw a star-studded 27th birthday party for himself that lasted
four days and occupied large venues such as the Atlanta Civic
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
