<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-2000-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN DEFENDS RECORD ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDERSON, S.C. _ John McCain defended inconsistencies in his
congressional record and rhetoric on campaign finance Monday while
George W. Bush complained that Democrats were working to defeat him
in the upcoming Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain repeated his opposition to public financing of
political campaigns, he conceded he had voted for measures before
the Senate with a public-financing component.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let the perfect be the enemy of the good,''
the Arizona senator said. ``I will make compromises; that's the
essence of legislating. ... I'm saying that I would rather have
something that had some public financing in it than the present
system.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain expressed disdain that Bush would challenge him on the
issue and declared that ``this kind of savagery'' is unnecessarily
negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there any doubt I'm the leader for campaign-finance reform
in America? Is there any doubt?'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides distributed a list of 11 amendments to three
campaign-finance reform measures in 1990, 1991 and 1993 on which
McCain voted against public financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of me putting out a major difference certainly isn't
savaging,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did he call it savagery? The man made five votes,
legitimate votes, on the floor of the Senate. It's what we call
full exposure, full disclosure,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will continue to press McCain on ``differences of
opinion'' when they meet Tuesday night in a debate, four days
before the South Carolina Republican primary, for which the battle
between the two men has become more bitter by the day.
</P>
<P>
   Bush declined to say how aggressive he will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be short of savagery,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called public financing of campaigns the ``incumbent
protection act.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush wins the nomination, he will take about $60 million in
taxpayer money for his general election campaign. Each nominee
receives that much, while the Reform Party nominee will receive $12
million.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush defended such financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because there's federal funding in presidential elections
doesn't mean there should be federal funding in congressional
elections,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also suggested that Democrats may flood South Carolina's
open primary to vote for McCain, putting a twist on the
conventional wisdom that McCain gathers some of his support from
independents and Democrats because of his reformist message.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said a Democratic state lawmaker, Rep. Todd Rutherford, had
urged voters to back McCain. Bush said the GOP nomination should be
decided by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a primary to search our souls in the Republican Party
to make up our minds,'' Bush told the 200 Republicans in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had nothing against Democrats voting in the
Republican primary for legitimate reasons, ``I just don't want
Democrats coming into vote against me because they think my
opponent will be easier to beat in November.'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford on WIS-TV Sunday had urged black voters to back the
``weaker candidate'' in the GOP primary. Rutherford originally said
that was McCain, but he later said Bush may be the weaker candidate
by Saturday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If by Saturday Bush is the weaker candidate, we encourage
those people who want to go vote in the Republican primary to vote
for Bush,'' Rutherford said.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain picked up the endorsement Monday of conservative Jim
Miles, the South Carolina secretary of state. The backing was
intended to counteract a stepped-up Bush campaign to question
McCain's conservative credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a prototype conservative,'' Miles told a McCain town-hall
meeting at an American Legion hall in Greenwood. Questions the Bush
campaign is raising about McCain's ideological leanings ``offends
me,'' Miles said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it was different when South Carolina Democrats flooded
into the GOP primary in 1980 to vote for Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why Democrats came to Ronald Reagan in 1980 was
because of a stark philosophical difference. They heard his call
for tax cuts,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be philosophical differences in order to win the
general election,'' he said. ``There is no philosophical difference
on tax cuts between Vice President (Al) Gore and John McCain. They
essentially take the same position.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain sparred frequently in New Hampshire over tax
cuts. Bush portrayed his $483 billion tax cut plan as a cut for all
Americans, while McCain said his $240 billion plan would use more
of the federal budget surplus to shore up Social Security and pay
down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tried Monday to retool his tax cut message, saying its
purpose is to maintain the nation's healthy economy by giving
entrepreneurs money for investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not call it the tax debate any more. Let's call it the
growth debate,'' Bush said. ``Let's have someone who's been an
entrepreneur carrying the banner of our party, someone who's met a
payroll waving that banner of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been a businessman, while McCain has been in Congress
for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
