<SLUG> BC-ARMED-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE FOREST RANGERS SEEK RIGHT TO USE DEADLY FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maine's forest rangers, whose duties in the woods have expanded
from fire prevention to enforcement of a growing number of
environmental and criminal offenses, will know within weeks whether
their public role will move in the direction of Smokey the Bear or
Smokey and the Bandit.
</P>
<P>
   A bill now before Maine's legislature would supply the state's
75 rangers with firearms. For years, rangers have complained that
their growing mission is leading them into tense standoffs with
timber thieves, violent drunks and armed criminals.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal has met with opposition from Governor Angus
King and from the commissioner of the Department of Conservation,
who say guns would alter the rangers' overwhelmingly friendly
public image, thereby exposing them to more danger, not less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is akin to arming your fire department,'' said Conservation
Commissioner Ron Lovaglio, whose agency oversees the rangers.
``They enjoy tremendous public support. In terms of the good guys
of government that people meet on a daily basis, they're probably
at the top of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument over who forest rangers should be has split Maine's
legislature along lines that are perplexing even to the bill's
sponsors. Everyone agrees that their identity has drifted over the
years _ from 1950, when Austin Wilkins decided to boost the
rangers' prestige by instituting the first-ever uniform, to the
early 1990s, when they started carrying handcuffs, to the decision
five years ago that they should train at the Maine Criminal Justice
Academy among freshly-minted state troopers, police officers and
sheriffs.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers say the most important change came with the Forest
Practices Act of 1991, which charged them with investigating a new
list of environmental offenses, including timber theft and arson.
At that point, rangers found themselves drifting into the territory
of police work whether they liked it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does bother me. I think you'll find that most rangers
became forest rangers not necessarily for law enforcement but for
the environmental aspect,'' said Ranger William Greaves, a 14-year
veteran from Island Falls who estimates that a third of his time
now goes to enforcement of environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think how we're perceived is changing,'' Greaves said.
``We're out there doing so much more than we were 15 years ago. We
represent so much more. We were firemen 15 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Greaves has a particular stake in the question of ranger safety,
since he was shot in the hip 10 years ago by a suspect while
assisting a sherriff's deputy, armed with a borrowed gun. He thinks
the incident could have been avoided if he had been properly
trained. In 1997, another ranger was held at gunpoint when he
responded to a complaint of burning without a permit, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a Forest Service report that 24 rangers had received
physical or verbal threats over the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next question is, what are we going to do, wait until a
ranger is killed?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of World War Two, when German prisoners of war
and coastal patrols made Maine's North Woods ``a kind of a
frontier,'' it was common for forest rangers to carry guns,
according to Charles Gadzik, director of Maine's Forest Service
until last year. But in the 1960s, as the state professionalized
the rangers' mission, guns were deemed unneccessary to the rangers'
primary duties of fire prevention and environmental compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the rangers' demands for arms were almost
gratified. The state legislature passed a measure that would have
armed the rangers, but ran into trouble when the Appropriations
Committee balked at the plan's cost, which was estimated at
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the proposal's opponents say the cost is less
important than the question of whether arming rangers would really
contribute to their safety. Issuing guns to a group of public
servants would nudge the rangers further into the realm of police
work, requiring a revolution in screening and training as well as a
potentially dangerous change in the way they interact with the
public, Lovaglio argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when the friendly state trooper stops to give you a
ticket, you look at that weapon and it changes the situation,'' he
said. ``Conflict can escalate very quickly and make it more
confrontational. Introducing the firearm itself adds as many risks
as it takes away.''
</P>
<P>
   That thought comes as as small comfort to Smith, who fears that
rangers will only encounter more and more hostility from the public
in coming years. If King vetoes the bill, he said, the rangers will
return to the issue next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in situations where we need to wait for another agency
to back us up,'' Smith said. ``Well, there are a lot of areas where
backup is two or three hours away. If we show up at a campsite and
a guy is beating on his wife, what are we going to do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
