<SLUG> BC-HEALTHEON-ACQUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHEON TO ACQUIRE 2 COMPETITORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a strong bid to dominate health care on the Internet,
Healtheon/WebMD Corp. agreed Monday to buy two competitors, Medical
Manager Corp. and CareInsite Inc., both headed by financier Martin
J. Wygod, for $5.2 billion in Healtheon stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal increased the potential of Healtheon, a start-up that
has yet to make a profit. Its goal is to connect doctors, patients
and insurers online and to slash the enormous nonmedical costs of
paperwork and administration in the nation's trillion-dollar health
care system.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction also raised the multimillion-dollar stake in the
Internet companies of a New York hospital association and four
insurance companies based in New York and Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes Healtheon the 800-pound gorilla in the marketplace,
without a clear No. 2 player,'' said William McKeever, a health
care analyst at PaineWebber Securities. ``Now they have to
execute,'' he said, meaning recruit enough doctors and health plans
to make the business profitable.
</P>
<P>
   In Nasdaq trading, Medical Manager shares soared $21.75, or 33
percent, to $86.75 Monday. CareInsite rose $4.125, to $72.
Healtheon/WebMD was up $1.625, to $56.625.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon, which is based in Santa Clara, Calif., was founded
four years ago by the Internet pioneer James H. Clark of Netscape
fame. It grew by making 80 alliances, acquisitions and partners in
the last 18 months. Two weeks ago, it agreed to buy Envoy, the
largest electronic processor of medical bills, for $2.5 billion in
stock. Medical Manager has provided software to 185,000 of the
country's 777,000 doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, all of a sudden, they are the largest electronic
processor of claims transactions and they will have the largest
access to physicians,'' said Claudine Singer, an analyst at Jupiter
Communications, a New York-based Internet research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have their tentacles in every established health care
connectivity player that's out there,'' she added. ``The biggest
challenge is to get the rest of the doctors online. Their biggest
competitor is inertia,'' the reluctance of many doctors to
computerize their practices.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was the latest in a string of health business coups for
Wygod, the New Jersey financier who said in a phone interview that
his stake in the merged company would be ``eight or nine million
shares.'' That would be valued at $400 million to $500 million,
based on Monday's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   He said computer links could help keep health plans viable,
connect doctors to patients and rescue physicians from a quagmire
of managed care bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's world you have so many health plans, so many plan
designs, guidelines and formularies (drugs that are covered by
insurance),'' he said, ``that it is impossible for a physician to
function without the right connectivity, without having all that
information at the time he is seeing the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that creating such links would not be easy. ``My
biggest question is how quickly we can get there,'' said Stephen
FitzGibbons, an analyst in San Francisco at Chase H&AMP;Q. ``It's not
the type of problem that will be solved in two years.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that there was a huge potential for cost cutting.
``One insurance company has 12,000 employees taking telephone
calls'' to approve or reject claims from doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Wygod sold an earlier venture, Medco Containment Services Inc.,
to Merck &AMP; Co. for $6.6 billion in 1993. He came away with $250
million in stock and fees. He created CareInsite, based in Elmwood
Park, N.J., around a Medco unit he bought back from Merck. He
merged CareInsite into Medical Manager last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Merck filed a lawsuit last March against Wygod and other former
Medco employees, charging that they had violated noncompete
agreements. CareInsite filed counterclaims against Merck. A Merck
spokesman said its suit was still pending in Superior Court in
Morris County, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Medical Manager, which owns 68.8 percent of
CareInsite, will each be exchanged for 1.65 shares of Healtheon.
CareInsite's other shares will each be exchanged for 1.3 shares.
Healtheon has issued 95 million new shares, valued at $5.2 billion,
based on last Friday's price.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Arnold, chief executive of Healtheon, and Mike Long, chief
operating officer, will keep those posts. Wygod and Long will be
co-chairmen of Healtheon/WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   The minority shareholders also include a group of New York
hospitals and health insurance companies that recently sold their
plan for an electronic network to Wygod for a total of 3.6 million
shares of CareInsite. Similarly, New Jersey Blue Cross and Blue
Shield joined the CareInsite network and received warrants for
811,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Raske, president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association, said Monday's deal could ``provide information
technology, capital and access that never existed before.'' A
nonprofit unit of his association and the insurers, Empire Blue
Cross and Blue Shield, HIP and Group Health Inc., each received
about 900,000 shares, which would translate to 1.19 million shares
of Healtheon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
