<HEADER>
A6818 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-THEOLOGIANS-APPROVAL-     02-14 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEOLOGIANS-APPROVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME CATHOLIC TEACHERS SAY THEY'LL DEFY `MANDATE' RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Catholic theologians, including the chairman of Boston
College's theology department, say they plan to defy a church
requirement that they seek approval of their teaching from their
local bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Dietrich, the theology department head, and Peter
Beisheim, a professor of religious studies at Stonehill College,
say they consider the expected requirement for church permission to
teach Catholic theology a violation of their academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine most folks here would not seek a mandate...and
my own personal plan would not be to seek a mandate,'' Dietrich
said. ``My thinking is that a university is a university, and is an
autonomous entity that should be supportive of free thought in the
American tradition. You can't have free thought if there's a
mandate and some kind of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Beisheim used even stronger language, saying: ``I have no fear
about getting a mandate if I was to present myself, but I see it as
a form of ecclesiastical McCarthyism. I don't need to take a
loyalty oath.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston College is a Catholic, Jesuit-run university in Chestnut
Hill, Mass.; Stonehill is a Catholic college in Easton, Mass.
operated by the Congregation of the Holy Cross, which also runs the
University of Notre Dame. There are seven other Catholic colleges
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The requirement that Catholic theologians get approval, known to
Catholics as a mandate, from their local bishop was adopted by the
US Catholic bishops last November, and is now awaiting approval by
the Vatican. The bishops have said that once the proposal is
approved by the Vatican, they will spend a year discussing how
exactly to implement it.
</P>
<P>
   Some Catholic theologians contacted Monday said they were
willing, or even eager, to get approval, called by Catholics a
mandate, from the church. Others said they will wait to see the
specifics of the process before deciding what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Many Catholic theologians have been on edge since the US bishops
last fall submitted to the Vatican a new proposal that would
require Catholic theologians to get a mandate to teach from the
church. But the theologians have been particularly abuzz for the
last week, since a prominent Notre Dame theologian, the Rev.
Richard McBrien, wrote an essay for the Jesuit magazine America
that was featured on the cover with the headline ``Why I shall not
seek a mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, theologians have been e-mailing and calling one
another and their professional associations, intensifying a
discussion that has been under way in various forms since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very worried about it,'' said Sister Margaret
Farley, a professor of Christian ethics at Yale Divinity School and
the president of the Catholic Theological Society of America. ``I'm
getting lots of messages, most from individuals, but in some major
Catholic universities, whole departments are trying to decide what
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Theresa Moser, the head of another professional
association, the College Theology Association, said the bulk of her
members are taking a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hot-button issue,'' she said. ``There are some
people that are thinking about requesting a mandate because they
see themselves as in communion with the church, but there are other
people with strong positions like Dr. McBrien's.''
</P>
<P>
   The requirement for a mandate was approved by the bishops in an
effort to comply with ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae,'' a document dealing
with Catholic higher education issued by Pope John Paul II in 1990.
In addition to requiring approval of theologians, the document
recommends that Catholics make up a majority of the faculty and the
trustees of Catholic universities.
</P>
<P>
   Among the unanswered questions about the mandate requirement:
what happens if a Catholic theologian refuses to seek, or is
denied, a mandate from the local bishop? Some academicians are also
debating whether the rule would apply to theologians who teach in
religious studies departments, as opposed to theology departments,
and whether the rule would apply retroactively to anyone now
teaching theology, or only to people who started teaching after the
requirement was put in place.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Cardinal Bernard Law, who would be responsible for
deciding whether to approve the teachings of Catholic theologians
at colleges within the Archdiocese of Boston, had no comment
Monday. The Rev. William Leahy, president of Boston College, plans
no action against faculty members who refuse to seek a mandate,
according to a spokesman, John Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Leahy met with the theology department and is leaving
it up to them,'' Dunn said. ``The university's position is it's an
individual Catholic theologian's decision to seek a mandate or not
to seek a mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Catholic theologians said they are willing to comply. In
most cases those theologians had trained in Europe, where they said
theologians regularly seek mandates from the church hierarchy and
academic freedom is unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no more an obstacle to serious intellectual
scholarship than would be the requirement that someone who gets a
doctorate in law has to pass a bar or someone who gets a medical
degree has to be certified,'' said the Rev. Matthew Lamb, a Boston
College theologian, who complained that many people teaching
theology at Catholic colleges have received inadequate training at
non-Catholic schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Roger Corriveau, a theology professor at Assumption
College, a Catholic college in Worcester, Mass., also expressed a
willingness to get a mandate, saying ``I'm a Catholic priest and
it's my intention to be teaching the church's teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Harvey Egan, a Boston College theologian, said he
expects to seek a mandate but that he considers the requirement a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a mistake...it's causing unnecessary confusion
and trouble and the results are going to be nil,'' Egan said. ``But
I would get it. It's truth in advertising. To be a Catholic
theologian means you have to respect the magisterium (authority to
teach religious doctrine).''
</P>
<P>
   Other theologians said they would wait to see the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're watching it very carefully, but there's been no decision
about where we will stand,'' said Ernest Collamati, a professor of
religious studies at Regis College, a Catholic college in Weston,
Mass. ``I'm basically counting on our professional societies to do
a good job, and I hope whatever will emerge will be palatable and
good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
