<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6819 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-DEBATE-LARRYKING-COX     02-14 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-LARRYKING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The face of CNN just lets it roll in interviews
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry King leans forward when he talks, off-camera as well as
on. Talks, sometimes, in quick, incomplete spurts, like those
little observational blippets in his much-mocked USA Today column.
</P>
<P>
   Here's King's answer to ``How are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt better in my whole life. Just had my annual
physical. Heart's fine. Baby's 10 months old, another one coming in
June. Can't believe it. Amazing. I woke up this morning in Beverly
Hills and said I can't believe it. At this age. Really nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy to make fun of. Impossible to ignore. The wives, the
suspenders, the raspy voice, the heart problems, the schmoozing,
the memoirs, the microphone. King, 66, probably has close to the
least formal journalistic training of anyone at CNN, yet he is the
news network's heart in some ways, its most recognizable face and
the host of its most popular show.
</P>
<P>
   He moderates a Republican presidential debate at 9 tonight in
South Carolina, in a 90-minute edition of ``Larry King Live.''
Candidates George W. Bush, John McCain and Alan Keyes are scheduled
to appear in the session, four days before the South Carolina
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   King says he'll bring his famous-infamous unpreparedness with
him tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let the tide take it,'' he says. If he asks a question of
Candidate A, he explains, and notices that during A's answer
Candidate B shows some reaction, he'll immediately follow up with
B.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I sit there with 14 prepared questions, I'm not
listening to their answers, because I'm thinking about Question No.
3. Wherever it goes, that's where it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   No way any of those questions will be as brutally tough as
Bernard Shaw's famous 1988 toss to Michael Dukakis, asking him if
his wife Kitty were raped and murdered, would he support the death
penalty for the murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Not for King the gruffness of Mike Wallace, the prickly
intelligence of Bryant Gumbel, the bluster of Sam Donaldson. He's
an affable kind of interviewer, a style his detractors knock and
King defends.
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning New York Times columnist Maureen Dowd
once called ``Larry King Live'' ``the resort area of American
journalism, the media's Palm Springs, where politicians and other
figures of controversy or celebrity go to unwind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Softball questions,'' his media critics call them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that,'' King says. ``I don't know what the term
means. My role as I see it is to be me. To ask the best questions.
To ask short questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Softball to me is, 'Whats your next movie?' `What do you dream
of?' ``How do you feel about love?' I never ask that.''
</P>
<P>
   King is leaning forward, not belligerent, but on a roll. It's a
recent afternoon in a Los Angeles hotel room, where King is
answering questions, something he likes much less than asking them.
But he's warmed to the topic of softball questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sinatra's one of those people, he laid down a rule the first
time I interviewed him I couldn't ask him about his son's
kidnapping. And he wound up telling me about it, cause I asked him
a question about the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Dan Quayle would he support his daughter if she had an
abortion? Would he go with her to the hospital? It's how you do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose I said (and he starts to bark like Walter Winchell on
his old radio show): `You're against abortion, Mr. Quayle! What if
your daughter had an abortion!?'
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of answer do you think I'd get?
</P>
<P>
   ``The stupidest question was the guy (a New York radio deejay)
who asked Hillary Clinton if she'd had an affair. It sounds like an
aggressive question. But it produces what? No answer.''
</P>
<P>
   A few answers about Larry King:
</P>
<P>
   _ He was born Larry Zeiger in Brooklyn, 1933, and grew up poor.
``New York City bought my first pair of glasses. I'll never forget
that,'' he says, and in many of his 11 books he recounts stories of
how poor he was as a youth. He changed his name to King when he
started working as a radio deejay at age 23.
</P>
<P>
   _ He's been married seven times (twice to the same woman, a
former Playboy bunny), and has been a prolific dater throughout his
life. Current wife Shawn Southwick-King 26 years his junior, is
pregnant with the couple's second child, which will be King's
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   _ He quit smoking after his heart attack in 1987. He also had an
angioplasty in 1997, and now exercises religiously. (He was on his
treadmill at home when he first heard about the AOL-Time Warner
merger.)
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, King was host of a national radio call-in
program, working out of Miami. CNN's 9 p.m. talk show was hosted by
a woman named Sandi Freeman. When CNN decided not to renew
Freeman's contract, Turner called King and asked him if he'd like
to join CNN, then a five-year-old network that was still struggling
to achieve respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a sports freak,'' King recalls. ``And my first reaction
was, I'm not going to be able to see basketball. I'm not going to
be able to see hockey. I didn't know CNN. I didn't have CNN in my
house.''
</P>
<P>
   King took over, but it wasn't until 1992 that ``Larry King
Live'' became the place for newsmakers to sit and schmooze. That
was the presidential election year when Ross Perot announced on
King's show he would run as an independent if his supporters got
him on the ballot in all 50 states, and interviews with President
George Bush and candidate Bill Clinton and his running mate Al Gore
followed.
</P>
<P>
   King will celebrate 15 years on CNN on June 1, the same night
CNN celebrates its 20th anniversary. He'll do special shows, June
1-2, two hours each, with retrospective clips and special guests;
the only one booked so far is Turner.
</P>
<P>
   His current contract runs through 2002, when he'll be 68. CNN
News Group chairman Tom Johnson says he wants to keep King on as
long as he can, and King says, ``I never think of retiring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Turner and I were talking about this the other day, and he
asked how many more years `Larry King Live' might have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think you'll make 20?'' Turner asked King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, if I stay healthy,'' King told his boss. ``Five more
years sounds good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember interviewing John Steinbeck, and I asked him if
when he wrote `The Grapes of Wrath,' if he knew he was writing a
book that was revolutionary and would change the way we look at
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I just wrote a book.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went on the air. All the rest just sort of happens.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
