<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6820 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BAXTER15-COLUMN-COX     02-14 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER15-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ganging up on McCain may backfire
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain has attracted notice for his campaign's agility
in raising money over the Internet after his big win in New
Hampshire. But the surging Republican candidate owes more to
Gutenberg and that early forerunner of the information age, the
book, than any reputed innovation of Al Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   Gazing contentedly Sunday afternoon at a line the length of
Peachtree Battle Shopping Center, McCain's co-author and aide, Mark
Salter, said the former POW's book, ``Faith of My Fathers,'' has
rebounded onto The New York Times Top 10 best sellers list after
New Hampshire, with total sales approaching 350,000. When
high-priced consultants counsel corporations about synergy, this
apparently is what they're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The big crowd at the book-signing Sunday suggests that Georgia,
like South Carolina and Michigan, could be susceptible to McCain
fever, marked by sudden shifts in the polls and the introduction of
foreign bodies into the Republican bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   The strangest interpretation of this enthusiasm for McCain is
that it's good for Democrats. There is such a thing as brand
loyalty, and the sight of so many of their number waiting patiently
in nippy weather to have their books autographed by a Republican
ought to give any thinking Democrat pause.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't necessarily follow, however, that the McCain ground
swell will in the long run be good for Republicans. The next five
days will help to determine that, and could play a pivotal role in
the way the election turns out this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Awakened to the implications of a second McCain upset in South
Carolina, the Bush campaign has pulled out all stops, dipping
generously into its fabled war chest and setting the candidate to
pummeling at the upstart.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bush badly needs to defeat McCain in South Carolina,
however, there could be some political cost to be paid for shooting
down Luke Skywalker, as McCain as been styling himself in recent
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The media may be sweet on him, as Gov. George W. Bush's camp
grumbles, but McCain, more than any other candidate this year, has
unleashed a current of political excitement in the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush could somehow win the nomination without capping that
ground swell _ most obviously, by ending things on a note whereby
McCain winds up on the ticket _ he could benefit from it. But since
New Hampshire, the race has not headed in such an amiable
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Pat Robertson, once the nemesis of Bush's
father, announced the Christian Coalition would sit out this
election if McCain is the nominee. That's the kind of comment bound
to send more Democrats and independents scurrying to the bookstore
to find out more about McCain.
</P>
<P>
   And it illustrates Bush's dilemma. To win in South Carolina,
Bush has to circle the wagons, but not so tightly that he leaves
his campaign no room to expand later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to watch the third candidate, Alan Keyes,
when the newly winnowed GOP field meets in a debate tonight. Keyes
threw the incendiary abortion question at McCain in the last New
Hampshire debate, and in diluting anti-abortion votes he hurt the
recently departed Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes has said some critical things of Bush, too. But if tonight
the debate looks like two against one, and McCain's the one, he's
pulled off a remarkable feat of political jujitsu. And he gets a
great chance to play Luke Skywalker.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
