<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baby born after twister
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMEGA _ A baby boy was in critical condition in a Macon hospital
after a tornado caused his premature birth.
</P>
<P>
   The infant _ called ``Miracle Baby Varnadoe'' by his family _
was delivered by emergency C-section early Monday after his
20-year-old mother was taken to Tift General Hospital in Tifton.
Jenny Varnadoe, her husband, Buck, 22, and two children were inside
their mobile home when a twister touched down on Mitchell Store
Road around 1:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny was in her 28th week of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The house was blown from its base and landed on the road,
injuring the couple, 2-year-old Bud and 3-year-old Britney. The
couple and two children remained hospitalized Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went up to check on them and found them outside in their
car,'' said a cousin, Danny Varnadoe. ``They were in real bad
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Another cousin, Lee Varnadoe, said the doctors at Tift decided
to take the baby because the boy's heart rate ``went way high.''
</P>
<P>
   The newborn was airlifted by helicopter to Medical Center of
Central Georgia because of its neo-natal intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe in luck,'' the family said in a statement.
``The praise for our children still being alive goes to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
