<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6826 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SYMPHONY-SPANO-COX     02-14 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMPHONY-SPANO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From Atlanta with love: Spano toast of the town
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was no surprise that on Valentine's Day, Atlanta's
new conductor stole a few hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Spano, the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra's newly appointed
music director, blew into town from an opera-conducting gig in
Wales for a celebratory round of toasts and introductions Sunday
night and Monday. Hopscotching among a champagne reception, a press
conference and a marathon run of meetings and greetings, Spano
confessed that he'd had a crush on the ASO long before the match
was finally made last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I want to cancel everything on the schedule, and I
want to be here,'' Spano told a captive champagne-swigging clutch
of ASO musicians, board members, staffers and patrons at the Four
Seasons Hotel on Sunday night. Gesturing toward giant posters of
himself that decorated the front of the room, he deadpanned that
his mother told him never to get a ``big head.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a whirlwind tour in which the 38-year-old maestro seemed
genuinely humbled by the outpouring of affection.
</P>
<P>
   He sang ``America the Beautiful'' at the Downtown Rotary Club
meeting. He greeted Donald Runnicles, the ASO's new principal guest
conductor, via Internet camera hookup. He got e-mail from Atlanta
Mayor Bill Campbell. He tossed a bouquet to ASO concertmaster
Cecylia Arzewski by scratching the Wagner scheduled for the May 4-6
concerts in favor of Rimsky-Korsakov's ``Sheherazade,'' a star turn
for the violinist. And, at a Georgia Citizens for the Arts luncheon
Monday, he was introduced by Lt. Gov. Mark Taylor, who filled in
after Gov. Roy Barnes was called away to the South Georgia tornado
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most significantly, Spano praised ASO music director
Yoel Levi, whom he replaces in September. ``This orchestra is
excellent, and there's no way they would be that without Mr. Levi's
stewardship over the last 12 years,'' Spano said later.
``Orchestras tend to reflect their music director, and this
orchestra is a really refined instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he is committed to taking the ASO on tour _ and to
building a new Symphony Hall. ``We are going to find a way to make
that happen. An orchestra of this caliber blossoms in a hall that
is meant specifically for orchestral music, and that should happen
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Spano also invited the public to give him feedback before he
even gets started. ASO board Chairman A.D. Frazier Jr. presented
him with a new laptop computer _ and a Woodruff Arts Center e-mail
address.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they say in the movies, `You've got e-mail,''' Frazier
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, when he logged on for Spano, there was a big red
heart from the Atlanta Symphony Associates and the mayor's
greeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This e-mail stuff isn't half bad,'' the conductor joked.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
