<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush renews McCain jabs
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALUDA, S.C._ Gov. George W. Bush returned to South Carolina on
Monday and renewed verbal sparring with Arizona Sen. John McCain,
his prime foe in a Saturday primary that could go a long way toward
deciding who gets the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In Anderson, S.C., McCain complained that Bush is intentionally
misrepresenting McCain's record on public funding of congressional
races. McCain has cast five Senate votes in favor of the concept,
though he says he opposes it and cast the votes only as part of
``the essence of legislating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of savagery is not necessary in an American
political campaign,'' McCain said at a town hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush refused to retreat, saying, ``It's not savagery. It's
what we call full exposure, full disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm respectful of his votes. I disagree with his votes. I
think it's important for us in the Republican Party to understand
that our candidate is going to have to weather a savaging attack if
Al Gore is the (Democratic) nominee,'' Bush told reporters. ``The
idea of me pointing out a major difference certainly is not
savaging.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he opposes public funding of congressional
elections, but endorsed it as part of overall reform packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let the perfect be the enemy of the good. I
will make compromises,'' he said. ``That's the essence of
legislating.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes public funding of congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Bush and Alan Keyes, the remaining GOP presidential
contenders, meet tonight in Columbia at a debate to be televised by
CNN. It's the last scheduled joint appearance before Saturday's
primary. Polls indicate a tight race. A big win here by either
candidate could have a major effect on Michigan and Arizona
primaries three days later.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, in North Augusta, S.C., Bush repeated his charge
that McCain insulted him by saying he twists the truth ``like
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also continued his new format of extended
question-and-answer sessions with voters. At an event at the
National Guard Armory in Saluda, one man wanted to know what Bush
considers the biggest misconception about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's the perception I can't stand on my own two
feet,'' Bush said, after pausing to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Republicans oftentimes ask am I tough enough to
win,'' he said. ``I guess my answer is just ask Ann Richards.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of three times Monday that Bush pointed to his 1994
win as evidence to his ability to win a tough race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe taking on Ann Richards is going to be tougher than
taking on Al Gore,'' he said at a community center in North
Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
