u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      02-14 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: U.N. AIDE QUITS
</P>
<P>
   The director of the ``oil for food'' program in Iraq resigned
effective March 31, saying he had lost hope of being able to help
Iraqis living under an embargo imposed in 1990. Hans van Sponeck, a
German, has been sharply criticized by the United States and
Britain for his opposition to the sanctions and to the linking of
resumed arms inspections to the program that allows Iraq to sell
oil to buy civilian goods. Another director who was critical of the
sanctions, Denis Halliday of Ireland, quit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT: INVASION ENVOY PICKED
</P>
<P>
   Yuli Vorontsov, a former Russian delegate to the United Nations
and envoy to the United States, was named a U.N.
undersecretary-general with responsibility for solving the problem
of about 600 missing Kuwaiti prisoners and millions of dollars in
property still unaccounted for from the Iraqi invasion in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: WEIZMAN CHARGES UNLIKELY
</P>
<P>
   The state is unlikely to prosecute President Ezer Weizman for
accepting substantial cash gifts from a French executive, the state
attorney, Edna Arbel, said. The investigation is drawing to a close
and she does not forsee filing charges, she said.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET RULING TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   The High Court moved forward its scheduled Thursday ruling to
Tuesday on the demand by Belgium and six rights groups that Britain
disclose the doctors' examination of Gen. Augusto Pinochet that was
the basis for its finding that he was medically unfit to be
extradited to Spain on torture charges. Even if the decision goes
in favor of Chile's former dictator, appeals could further delay a
prompt return home.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: HOME RULE DISCORD
</P>
<P>
   A disagreement between Britain and Ireland emerged over the
urgency of resurrecting the power-sharing home rule government in
Belfast suspended by London. Brian Cowen, Ireland's foreign
minister, urged resumption within 48 hours based on a new
disarmament commitment by the IRA, but Peter Mandelson, secretary
for the province, said more time was needed to clarify the IRA
offer.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: TROOPS FOR EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Worried that they will be cut out of Europe's future defense
plans because they remain outside the European Union, Turkish
leaders have offered to contribute a brigade to the European
defense force to be formed in 2003. The Turkish brigade would
reportedly be about 3,000 strong. It would be part of a combined
force expected to include about 50,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: IMMIGRANT LABOR DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Moroccans ended their strike and returned to work
in the greenhouses of El Ejido, a week after anti-immigrant
violence led to dozens of injuries and arrests in the town. Local
growers, who reported mounting losses from unpicked vegetables,
agreed to improve housing for the farmworkers and pay for their
damaged property and mosques.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: U.S. AIDE VISITS
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in six months, Thomas R. Pickering, the
State Department's third-ranking official, has arrived for meetings
with government leaders to discuss details of an emergency $1.6
billion aid and equipment package favored by the Clinton
administration that is under consideration by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: CITIES REJECT CHARTER
</P>
<P>
   Voters in the biggest cities rejected a new constitution
championed by President Robert Mugabe that would strengthen the
power of his office and give the government the right to seize
white-owned land without compensation. With ballots tallied from
under half the districts, it was clear that, to be adopted, the new
charter will need a big push from remaining districts, many in
rural areas that are the base of Mugabe's power.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO: ARMY DRIVE
</P>
<P>
   The government of President Laurent Kabila announced a new
recruiting drive for its army, which has been fighting against
rebel, Rwandan and Ugandan forces despite a cease-fire signed half
a year ago. Kabila has been increasing the size of the military
since the current war began in 1998, in part by enlisting child
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO: PLEA TO REBELS
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has called on rebels in Congo to allow a local
archbishop to return home after he was banned for reportedly making
statements inciting violence against ethnic Tutsi. Vatican
officials said the banning of the archbishop of Bukavu, Emmanuel
Kataliko, ``weighs heavily on the rights of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: SUHARTO A NO-SHOW
</P>
<P>
   Pleading ill health after a stroke, former President Suharto
failed to appear in court to face charges of corruption during his
32-year rule. A lawyer said his absence was due to ``doctors'
suggestions,'' an assessment prosecutors say they will challenge.
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: HANDOVER TO U.N.
</P>
<P>
   Australian-led peacekeeping troops pulled out of the capital
city, Dili, handing responsibility for security to United Nations
forces that included troops from Brazil, Portugal and Kenya. The
shift, five months after their arrival, will end in a formal
military handover to the United Nations at the end of February.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: FACING THE REBELS
</P>
<P>
   President Chandrika Kumaratunga, who survived an assassination
attempt by Tamil rebels, made a surprise appearance in Parliament
to propose a sharp rise in the amount budgeted for defense spending
to combat the rebels, even as she pressed for a peace plan giving
Tamil-dominated areas a measure of autonomy.
</P>
</TEXT>
