<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Booksellers honor `Green Valley,' `Ecology of a Cracker
Childhood'
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A memoir about growing up in a South Georgia junkyard and a
novel about a North Carolina teacher's homecoming took two of the
top honors in the Southeast Booksellers Association Book Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Janisse Ray's ``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood'' (Milkweed
Editions, $19.95) won in the nonfiction category, while Fred
Chappell's ``Look Back All the Green Valley'' (Picador, $24) was
named best novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bugs &AMP; Critters I Have Known'' by Ann Heiskell Rickey (Old
Canyon Press, $12.95) won in the children's category, and ``Elegy
for the Southern Drawl'' by Rodney Jones (Houghton Mifflin, $20)
was the poetry winner.
</P>
<P>
   The awards were announced Monday. Winners will be honored at a 7
p.m. dinner April 1 at the Westin Peachtree Plaza hotel in Atlanta.
Tickets are $30 for SEBA members and $50 for nonmembers.
Information: 1-800-331-9617.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
