<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NKOREA-TOURISM-ART-11     02-14 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-TOURISM-ART-1145(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH AND SOUTH KOREANS MEET ON A MOUNTAIN PATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT KUMGANG, North Korea _ The last time Yoon Chun-ok and Yoon
Chun-sook climbed this majestic mountain, which Koreans consider
sacred, was 1948, when the Korean peninsula had not yet been
divided by war.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, just before the North turned communist and
closed its borders, the Yoon family fled south to Seoul, but the
sisters never lost hope of returning to their birthplace and
scaling the summit one more time.
</P>
<P>
   So when North Korea began allowing commercial tours to Mount
Kumgang in late 1998, the sisters signed up. Today not even
advancing age, subzero temperatures or icy paths could keep them
from reaching the mountaintop, which offers a stunning view of
snow-capped peaks, gorges and waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Since North Korea opened parts of Mount Kumgang to South Korean
tourists in November 1998, about 150,000 people have visited the
scenic mountain region north of the eastern end of the
demilitarized zone separating the two Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   The tours have become the hallmark of South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung's so-called sunshine policy of constructively engaging
North Korea in an effort to hasten reconciliation between the two
nations. While these tours have been a breakthrough in the
long-frozen relations between North and South, they also illustrate
how difficult it would be to reunite the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, as of this month, non-Koreans are allowed to
go on the tours, which provide the only access _ although limited _
to this hermetic, bellicose country where 24 million people live
under a hard-line Stalinist government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been waiting 50 years to come home, and it feels so
good to be back that my body is very warm and peaceful even though
it's freezing cold out here,'' Chun-sook, 68, said as she made the
climb. But Chun-ok, 72, said the homecoming was bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy to be back, but our village looks nothing like we
remember,'' she said. ``There are soldiers posted at every corner.
The people don't look happy, and we couldn't get off the bus and
talk to them. Everything has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   South Koreans are not allowed to travel freely to the North,
because the two countries have no formal relations and are still
technically at war. Under Kim's policy, South Korea has eased
restrictions on doing business with North Koreans and increased its
fertilizer and food aid to the North.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea is struggling to rebuild its tattered economy and
feed its starving people, hit hard by food shortages and floods in
recent years, so it is in desperate need of hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for opening parts of the mountain region to tours,
which are operated by Hyundai Co., a South Korean conglomerate,
North Korea is expected to receive hundreds of millions of dollars
in payments over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the North Korean government tightly controls what
visitors to Mount Kumgang see and where they go, the tours provide
a glimpse of what life is like in North Korea, one of the most
isolated and oppressive countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe people are still living under these conditions
in the new millennium,'' said D.L. Kim, a South Korean tourist, who
owns a retail shop in Seoul. ``It breaks my heart to see our Korean
brothers suffering, especially in this place of such great
beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   During a trip last weekend, there was a constant uneasy feeling
of being watched, from the time visitors arrived in the North
Korean port of Changjon aboard a Hyundai cruise ship from the South
Korean port of Tonghae.
</P>
<P>
   Navy boats are always on patrol around the cruise ships, and
their crews can enter the tour vessels at any time to search them.
Changjon is a strategic military port for North Korea, and visitors
are forbidden to take photos of any military installation or
personnel. If a tourist breaks that rule, the film may be
confiscated or the offender may be fined or even detained.
</P>
<P>
   After coming ashore and passing through immigration, the
visitors were taken by tour bus through a winding road leading to
the village of Onjongi, once a hot spring resort that is now the
starting point for these Mount Kumgang tours.
</P>
<P>
   The road was lined with barbed-wire fencing and grim-faced North
Korean soldiers wearing green military uniforms and carrying
automatic rifles.
</P>
<P>
   Tour guides said that during the initial tours in 1998, there
were no fences and that tourists often had contact with the
residents of Onjongi. North Korea installed the fences after South
Korean tourists started giving milk, snacks and clothing to the
North Koreans, especially children, who looked malnourished, the
guides said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fences was a bleak landscape of unkempt fields and
rows of prefabricated concrete houses that tour guides said
belonged to farmers. Tour buses and military vehicles were the only
automobiles on the roads.
</P>
<P>
   Village residents, in drab black and blue clothing, were walking
or riding bicycles. Most smiled and waved at the tour buses.
</P>
<P>
   On what tour guides described as municipal buildings there were
pictures of President Kim Jung Il, who assumed control of North
Korea after the death of his father, Kim Il Sung, in 1994.
Immigration and other government officials wore small red pins
bearing the image of North Korea's leader.
</P>
<P>
   While tourists have almost no contact with local residents, they
are permitted to speak with North Korean officials, especially the
environmental guards and inspectors who monitor the mountain paths
and attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The guards and inspectors were generally friendly and seemed
happy to meet non-Koreans, although most of them did not speak any
English and tried to communicate in Korean or Russian.
</P>
<P>
   But South Korean tourists said they had difficulty speaking with
some North Koreans because they used ``old-fashioned words'' and
did not understand many modern terms like ``instant noodles,''
``compact disc'' and ``microwave oven.''
</P>
<P>
   Some North Korean officials monitoring the mountain trails
reacted with great surprise at meeting this visitor _ a person of
African descent, which they had never encountered before.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look like Paul Robeson,'' said a North Korean inspector.
``May I know your country?''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the South Koreans seemed reluctant to go much beyond
niceties, perhaps because of the detention last year of a South
Korean housewife on one of these tours, they said.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea accused her of trying to entice a North Korean tour
guide to defect to the South. The official North Korean news agency
quoted her as saying, ``North Korean defectors to South Korea are
leading decent lives and if you come to the South you will live in
happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea released her only after the South Korean government
threatened to suspend the cruise tours and the lucrative monthly
payments to the North.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stiff fines have been imposed on foreigners who fail to abide by
North Korea's rules while on the tour. In recent months, fines have
been levied against foreigners for urinating and smoking in
unauthorized areas, spitting, and throwing items like milk and
snacks from tour buses.
</P>
<P>
   According to the South Korean Unification Ministry, North Korea
has collected $8,250 in fines for 290 rules violations in Mount
Kumgang since the start of the tours in 1998. The fines ranged from
$15 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean tour guides said they often have to negotiate with
North Korean guards and monitors to allow some older tourists to
relieve themselves behind bushes or to use lavatories restricted to
military use.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day's tour, visitors return to the cruise
ships, where they spend the night in considerable luxury compared
with the residents of Onjongi, the local village, which has no
electric power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish there was something more we could do to change this
situation,'' said Yl Hung-woo, a South Korean tourist, standing on
the brightly lighted deck of the ship. ``But I think these tours to
Mount Kumgang are a good beginning because they remind us that
despite the division of North and South, Koreans are still one
people and share an appreciation for beauty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
