<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE SILLY-CANDIDATE SHORTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donald Trump has dropped out of the presidential race. This will
not have any impact on our actual search for a new chief executive,
but it will be a terrible blow to the second-most-important
function of a national election. Which is, of course, comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of ridiculousness has leaked out of the campaign over the
last few days, as people like Steve Forbes, Gary Bauer and Orrin
Hatch trotted off into the sunset. They at least hung around until
their humor potential was pretty well exhausted. Trump slipped away
so suddenly that we did not even have time to discuss how his hair
has come to resemble some sort of artificially flavored dessert
topping.
</P>
<P>
   The country was enamored of faux candidates like Trump and
Warren Beatty a few months ago, when it looked as though we were in
for 10 or 11 months of Bush vs. Gore and would need all the
diversion we could get. But now we're happily engaged in real,
competitive contests involving people who are actually more or less
qualified for the jobs they seek. Even though none of them have
ever inhabited the same sentence with the term ``his galpal, the
leggy lingerie model,'' I am pretty confident in saying they are
fulfilling all our current needs.
</P>
<P>
   If we want gossip, there's always the New York Senate race.
Hillary Clinton got into trouble last week for failing to leave a
tip at a restaurant where she received a free meal, a mistake Trump
would certainly never have made. ``It's unfortunate people want to
politicize this,'' said her spokesman, in campaignspeak for total
admission of guilt. Clinton's likely opponent, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, responded by leaving his next waitress $60 for a $35
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gov. George Bush was dashing around South Carolina
attempting to explain how his campaign has managed to spend the
bulk of that fabled $70 million war chest (big tips?) and to
demonstrate that he can ride buses and hold town meetings just as
well as John McCain. In Massachusetts Bush's organization explained
his poor showing in recent polls there by saying that voters had
not yet been exposed to ``the new Bush of South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazing how fast these things turn around. The new Al Gore, who
by now is the old Al Gore, should soon have as much money as the
new George Bush. Gore's opponent, the same old Bill Bradley, is
coming closer and closer to running as the candidate who has been
endorsed by Michael Jordan _ a political Nike campaign. Bradley,
who is now one of the few males in America who doesn't seem to
enjoy watching basketball, even spent Sunday at the NBA All-Star
Game with his new favorite player.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who used to have the misfortune of falling in with the
wrong politicians whenever he set foot in New York, managed to have
a meeting with the Rev. Al Sharpton that could not have been more
low-key if they'd held it under a Cone of Silence.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, Bush and McCain are fighting like cats.
McCain recently withdrew his attack ads, though his forces are
still leading in negative e-mailing to reporters. (``Bush Empties
the Gutters on McCain,'' ``Greenville Mayor's Wife Incensed by Bush
Push Poll.'') But I was pleased to see that they cheerfully gave a
Bush spokesman, Ari Fleischer, points for creativity when he called
McCain ``a few french fries short of a Happy Meal.''
</P>
<P>
   We have conspiracy theories! The far-right wing, in a unique
reading of McCain's record as a heroic POW in Vietnam, has been
demanding to know whether the senator is some sort of ``Manchurian
candidate.'' And we are certainly looking forward to an
about-to-be-released movie called ``The Skulls,'' in which a thinly
disguised version of Bush's college fraternity runs the nation
through a sinister and occasionally murderous web of political
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, who was last an entrepreneurial role model when Beatty
was last a sex symbol, seems superfluous at a moment when there's
so much action. But if the March primaries lead us back to seven
months of Gore-Bush, I'm prepared to take a serious look at that
boomlet for Cybill Shepherd. Or even Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
