<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6840 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-STYLE-NYT     02-14 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-STYLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S UNSCRIPTED STYLE HARKS BACK TO A LESS PARTISAN TIME
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ John McCain often says he wants to imitate his
hero Ronald Reagan and broaden his party's appeal. But it is one of
those odd twists of politics that he is trying to do this by
running against the controlled, high-gloss techniques that Reagan
as much as anyone brought to presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain is still brandishing as his main campaign weapon his
relentless accessibility _ from his freewheeling encounters with
the public to his anything-goes news conferences aboard his bus.
Much of this openness is a way to get free publicity to counter the
financial advantage of his main competitor, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But more and more, McCain drops suggestions that his campaign
style is about something broader _ a half-thought-out effort to
turn back the clock not just on presidential campaigning but on
governance, in search of a more personable, less confrontational
time. As he held town hall meeting after town hall meeting on
Monday, he declared once again that his campaign ``is being run on
vision and hope'' and pledged that ``we're not having anything to
do with negative campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has told reporters he is convinced that some of the
corrosive antagonism in Washington between press and the White
House during the Clinton years was the result of restricted access
and a dearth of news conferences. Presidents make mistakes, he
contends, ``when they insulate themselves, then the tensions build,
the pressure builds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go back to the days when FDR used to invite
everybody in to the Oval Office for a chat,'' he said one day.
``But you certainly could go back to the Kennedy thing,'' he added,
saying that he would hold weekly news conferences like John
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kennedy in `60,'' McCain said Sunday, drawing a parallel to
his own campaign, ``had the media with him at all times.'' McCain
also remembered how he thought his friend Bob Dole made a terrible
mistake when he started withdrawing from the press in his losing
1996 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   McCain even thinks the president could borrow from Britain and
institute a version of ``question time'' when the prime minister
has to answer questions from Parliament. He envisions a delegation
from Congress holding weekly televised grillings of the president.
``That kind of exchange would be good for America,'' he said,
``with the full knowledge that the president would be
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this uncontrolled access is a counterpoint to both Reagan
and President Clinton. It was Reagan, the former actor, who
perfected the campaign as video image _ sticking carefully to his
lines and even standing at the exact spot on the floor where his
aides had marked with masking tape to get the perfect camera angle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ran a more open campaign in 1992 and had his own bus
tours. But by 1995, with the public seeing his talks on MTV about
underwear preferences as not befitting the White House, he began
studying video clips of Reagan to learn how to seem more
presidential. His 1996 re-election campaign became just as
scripted, controlled and gauzy as Reagan's.
</P>
<P>
   And in a year of public disillusionment with Clinton, there
seems to be public disillusionment with an arms length campaign
style too.
</P>
<P>
   There was no better sign that McCain's bus rides have captured
the voters' imagination than when he showed up to sign books in
Atlanta on Sunday. Autograph seekers started clambering onto the
bus as if it were a museum exhibit and taking pictures of its
seating areas.
</P>
<P>
   In his years in Congress, McCain was well known among reporters
for returning phone calls and generally answering even the most
pointed questions. And when he began his campaign his aides
consciously used that style to draw contrasts with the race they
guessed Bush would wage: a highly scripted incumbent-style
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what front-runners do,'' John Weaver, the senator's
political director, said, saying the McCain campaign saw their
candidate's counter-style as ``a tactical advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it is immutable. McCain remains committed to his campaign
style even though in South Carolina, the drives on the ``Straight
Talk Express'' can stretch two or three hours. The candidate and
the press journey limbo-like between stops _ in a more
claustrophobic closeness than ever existed on the shorter jaunts
around New Hampshire. McCain can get testy and reporters simply run
out of anything to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, there are whole days when the entire Republican
presidential race seems to revolve not around issues like health
care or foreign policy but on questions of how political campaigns
should be waged. In some ways this is because, except on tax cuts,
there are not large ideological differences between Bush and
McCain. And so campaign style as a measure of character has come to
the fore.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's signature drive to ban big money from politics is only
a part of it. He says over and over that his mission is to end the
cynicism that keeps young people from voting. And last Friday,
McCain announced unilaterally that after a week of harsh, televised
attacks by the two campaigns, he would no longer run negative ads.
The decision seemed cathartic, lightening his mood. He cried out
against the technique of push-polling as the ``real bottom fishing
of a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of this may have been needed repositioning. McCain was
running a harsh ad against Bush last week and had others ready to
go if necessary. But there were signs that the tactic was hurting
his image as a reformer. And, given the tight nature of the race,
he could not risk turning off voters, particularly Democrats and
independents, through a negative-toned campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain also said he was moved by a woman, Donna Duren,
who stood in one of his audiences last Thursday and told how her
teen-age son had been distraught when he received a polling call
telling him that McCain was a fraud. ``I'm not so jaded and old and
hardened and stupid,'' McCain said. ``Something like that mother
the other day impacted me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign too has become preoccupied with the conduct of
politics _ McCain's conduct that is. Day after day the governor or
his surrogates dig up some past statements of McCain's or
contradictory votes by the senator, to try to portray him as a
hypocrite on his signature issue of campaign finance law.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always judge where a politician is going by where
they've been,'' said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush, charging
that McCain on campaign finance reform has ``a very long record of
saying one thing and doing another.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator countered Monday that his votes reflect the
give-and-take of congressional compromise. ``I'm not going to let
the perfect be the enemy of the good,'' McCain said. ``I will make
compromises; that's the essence of legislating.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens in Saturday's South Carolina primary,
McCain may at least be able to say that he's had some measure of
success in changing politics.
</P>
<P>
   One lesson Bush seems to have drawn from his drubbing in New
Hampshire is that, even as others proclaimed him inevitable, he was
never accessible. So across South Carolina, Bush has been
proclaiming himself a ``reformer with results,'' holding town hall
meetings and even running a bus _ though he has not been holding
the long, free-form news conferences that his rival holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's wonderful,'' the senator said of news that Bush had a
campaign bus. ``That would be a great thing for American
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   He was only half kidding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
