<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6844 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-STORM-WEATHER-COX     02-14 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-WEATHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Havoc was ripe in the sky
 &HT;    By Mike Morris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meteorologists at the National Weather Service office in
Tallahassee had plenty of warning that the storms bearing down on
the southwest corner of the state early Monday could be trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That was because atmospheric conditions were ``just right'' for
an outbreak of tornadoes, said meteorologist Matt Volkmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a strong upper-level trough, and a strong upper-level
jet stream moving into South Georgia,'' Volkmer said. ``Coupled
with that, at the surface we had a moist, southerly flow off the
Gulf of Mexico which brought a lot of low-level moisture across the
area.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a recipe for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have the low-level moisture, an upper-level system
and some colder air aloft working in as well, and when the wind
direction is changing at different heights, it can create an
environment that will support rotating thunderstorms, and those can
cause tornadoes.''
</P>
<P>
   The string of thunder cells spawned several killer tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Volkmer said outbreaks of severe weather are common across South
Georgia this time of year. ``In late fall as we get out of the
warmer season and start having some cold fronts come down, and
again in the early spring, those are times when we see a fair
amount of severe weather events.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm system responsible for the deadly tornadoes had a
history of causing damage ``all the way back earlier in the day
Sunday in Arkansas, Mississippi and Tennessee,'' Volkmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the system reached Georgia, high winds and hail
caused scattered damage in much of Alabama, downing trees and
leaving thousands of people without power.
</P>
<P>
   A possible tornado struck south Montgomery County, Ala., downing
power lines, overturning mobile homes and destroying a business.
</P>
<P>
   In Marshall County, a church was blown into the middle of the
road near Boaz, Ala. according to local EMA officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Cullman, Ala., several houses and businesses were damaged and
power lines were downed, a police spokesman said. He said the
damage was ``pretty widespread'' throughout the city but no
injuries had been reported.
</P>
<P>
   As the storms continued to push eastward at speeds of up to 45
mph, the Storm Prediction Center in Oklahoma posted a tornado watch
for South Georgia at 6:10 p.m. Sunday, and at 11 p.m. continued the
watch through 5 a.m. Monday, Volkmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tallahassee Weather Service office issued 55 tornado and
severe thunderstorm warnings for specific counties late Sunday and
early Monday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Doppler radar indicated a possible tornado in southeast
Georgia, Volkmer's office issued a tornado warnings for Mitchell,
Colquitt and southern Worth counties at 12:01 a.m. Monday,
effective through 1:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Volkmer said preliminary reports showed the Mitchell County
tornado struck south of Camilla about 12:09 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   After devastating areas of southwest Georgia, the weather system
took a turn up the East Coast, Volkmer said, and was threatening
parts of the Carolinas Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's storms were Georgia's deadliest outbreak of tornadoes
since April 16, 1944, when 41 Gainesville residents were killed.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Weather Service, the counties hit by Monday's
storms are among the state's most tornado-prone
</P>
<P>
   From 1950 through 1998, 23 tornadoes were reported in Colquitt
County. During the same period, Tift County had 17, Mitchell County
16 and Grady County 11, according to the Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
