A6848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLO-TEENS-SHOT-ART-7     02-14 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-TEENS-SHOT-ART-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 STUDENTS AT COLUMBINE HIGH SCHOOL ARE FOUND SHOT TO DEATH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT18 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Less than a year after the massacre at
Columbine High School, two sophomores were found shot to death on
Monday in a sandwich shop near the school.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies were discovered just before 1 a.m. when an employee
of the shop happened to drive by, noticed lights still on almost
three hours after closing time and went inside to see why. The
authorities said she found the bodies behind the counter. They were
later identified as Nicholas Kunselman, 15, an employee of the
shop, and Stephanie Hart, a 16-year-old girl he was dating.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's office, Steve
Davis, said investigators had neither determined a motive for the
shootings nor a time of death, although they ruled out a
murder-suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said they had no suspects but wanted to question a white
male in his late teens or early 20s wearing a red jacket and flared
pants, whom the employee said she saw leaving the area when she
arrived. He said investigators were also reviewing videotape from a
surveillance camera inside the shop.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he did not know whether investigators had found money
in the cash register, but one law enforcement official said he did
not believe robbery was the motive and said he would not be
surprised if the killer turned out to be another Columbine student.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings had the immediate effect of reopening the
psychological wounds of 10 months ago, when two Columbine students
shot and killed 12 other students and a teacher and wounded two
dozen other students before killing themselves in what became the
worst of a recent series of shootings at schools around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The incident set in motion scenes that have become all too
familiar in this middle-class community just south of Denver. After
students arriving for classes on Monday morning were told of the
killings, many began crying, and some were so upset they left
school immediately. Several dozen drove to the parking lot near the
sandwich shop to leave flowers, balloons and other mementos and
write messages with chalk on the blacktop. One said, ``Stop the
Hate.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings also prompted school district officials to react
as they had after the shootings last April, calling in extra
security and mental health workers for students who needed
counseling. When the principal, Frank DeAngelis, walked from the
school to a park, where he read a statement to reporters, he was
accompanied by a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our school community hurts a great deal,'' he said. ``We're
trying to keep normalcy at our school.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Romanshyn, an 18-year-old senior, who left school early for
the day, said: ``Lots of kids are really distraught.''
</P>
<P>
   The sandwich shop, a Subway franchise, is less than a half-mile
from the high school and about twice that distance from a Dumpster
where two weeks ago the authorities found the body of an
11-year-old Denver boy, Antonio Davalos, who had been missing for
several days. He had been strangled.
</P>
<P>
   The shop is also less than a block from the Trinity Christian
Center, where several memorial services were held last year for
victims of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities did not disclose who owned the Subway shop. A
spokeswoman for the company, Annie Smith, said she would not
provide the information.
</P>
<P>
   In the parking lot, students and former Columbine students
milled around outside an area cordoned off by crime-scene tapes.
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Hodack, 22, a 1996 Columbine graduate who works at the
Subway, said that Nicholas was often entrusted with closing the
shop and that Stephanie often came by near closing time to keep him
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really a nice kid,'' Hodack said. ``He made the time to
talk to you, to see how you were doing. He was a really friendly
type.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodack said that if the killings had occurred as part of a
robbery, the gunman would not have gotten much money. Large bills,
he said, are removed from the cash register every hour. ``So the
only thing he possibly got was change or maybe $50,'' he said.
``That's not worth a robbery.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing with a group of friends, Hodack said: ``I don't know
what to make of it. There's been a whole bunch of this stuff _
anger, hate, sadness. We've had enough.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nathan Grill, 15, a classmate and co-worker of Nicholas', said
he and other friends had been in the shop Sunday night but had left
just before the 10 p.m. closing time as Nicholas was waiting on a
customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wake up this morning, and he's dead,'' Nathan said, shaking
his head. ``I don't know what to think or what to do. There are
just bad people out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Scott, 18, also came to the parking lot on Monday.
Stephanie was her cousin. ``She loved school,'' Courtney said.
``She had a lot of friends, she loved sports, like swimming. She
was just a real good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the sheriff's spokesman, said that many of the
investigators at the sandwich shop had worked on the Columbine
killings last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the community hasn't even had time for the first
wounds to heal,'' he said. ``And now, it's pouring salt onto those
wounds. It's traumatic for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
