<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-REPUBS-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGE TO SOUTH CAROLINA PRIMARY IS DROPPED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ A legal challenge that sought to block
Saturday's Republican presidential primary in South Carolina was
dropped Monday after the state Republican Party agreed to open
every available polling place in the state, including those in
heavily Democratic and black areas that were closed in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
   In order to win a federal court's approval to hold the primary,
the state party has spent the last few weeks scrambling to assemble
more than 5,000 volunteers to staff the polling places, far more
than in any previous primary. The party also agreed to pay state
election workers $45 a day to work at polling places where
volunteers cannot be found.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, more than 1,500 polling places will be open on
Saturday, compared with about 800 in 1996. The increased statewide
access in non-Republican areas could make voting easier for
Democrats and independents, many of whom have said they are
planning to support Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the unintended consequences of the lawsuit,
which began last month as a bit of mischief by Democrats in a state
where shoulder pads are a necessary part of the political uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party persuaded two black state legislators to
complain that the Republicans were blocking access to their primary
in mostly black districts. Republicans acknowledged that in
previous years they had not opened polls in areas where Republicans
were not likely to vote, which included black districts because
most blacks in South Carolina are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, of course, were not really interested in creating
greater access to the Republican primary; they mostly wanted to
embarrass and distract the Republicans while the national media
were in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like pulling the fire alarm,'' said Henry
McMaster, chairman of the state Republican party. ``You might be
joking, but the fire department doesn't know that, and it sets off
serious consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   After complaining to the Justice Department that the Republican
primary violated the federal Voting Rights Act, the Democrats
realized they too would be unable to open all polling places in the
state. So they canceled their primary on March 9, which was too
late to be of consequence in the nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   (They will instead hold a rather inconsequential caucus on March
9, another reason that many Democrats may vote in the far more
crucial Republican contest.)
</P>
<P>
   But Lee Parks, the Atlanta lawyer retained by the Democrats, who
normally brings lawsuits against affirmative-action programs,
pressed on with the lawsuit in federal court, forcing the
Republicans to make a massive effort to recruit volunteers and even
pay state workers.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement between the two sides was approved Monday by a
panel of three federal judges here. The Justice Department also
issued a separate opinion Monday saying that the primary meets the
requirements of the Voting Rights Act because of the number of
polling places that will be open.
</P>
<P>
   Several state legislators have said they will now seek to have
the state government supervise the administration of party
primaries, as is done in almost every other state.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richard Harpootlian, the chairman of the state Democratic party,
said the lawsuit was worth it, and not just because of the pleasure
of watching his opponents spend a great deal of effort and possibly
money to hold their primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the Republican candidates go around the country claiming
they want an inclusive party for all races and creeds,'' he said,
``we were able to show that in South Carolina, where the rubber
meets the road, they only opened up polling places in minority
areas when they were facing the threat of a federal court
intervening or shutting down their primary.''
</P>
<P>
   But McMaster bravely insisted that the effort had backfired on
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw their voters drifting away to us, and tried to stop
our primary,'' he said. ``But what really happened is that their
lawsuit created more interest and more publicity about the primary.
And I think they're just sick about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 2009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OIL-MARKETPLACE-ART-N     02-14 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: THE $30 BARRIER IS BREACHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of crude oil jumped to more than $30 a barrel Monday
for the first time since the 1991 Persian Gulf war, and a sharp
runup in gasoline prices looks increasingly likely this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil neared $30 in mid-January, slipped and
then rallied again last week. All the time, traders were weighing
concerns about declining inventories of crude oil, home heating oil
and gasoline against the possibility of a production increase from
major oil producers when they meet at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   As new data showed some inventories tightening last week, only
promises of increased production by unnamed OPEC officials kept the
price of crude oil from piercing $30.
</P>
<P>
   But several reports Monday put a damper on the prospect of a
production increase, and the $30 barrier was breached. The price of
crude oil for March delivery on the New York Mercantile Exchange
jumped 81 cents to $30.25 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, new comments from OPEC officials holding out the hope
of production increases could depress the price again. In fact,
Monday's comments contradicted what appeared to be clear signals
last week that Venezuela and Saudi Arabia would ask for an increase
by June at a meeting of OPEC countries at the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the producers relent, the production cuts that began
last March _ equal to 4.3 million barrels a day _ may have already
set the stage for a sharp rise in gasoline prices later this year
and a stronger political response from the United States and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If OPEC eases in June, it's too late,'' said Irene King,
senior oil markets analyst for J.P. Morgan Securities, referring to
peak gasoline demand in the summer travel season. Because of the
lag time between increased crude oil production and the refining of
gasoline, she said, ``we will have to go through all the holidays
with very low gasoline inventories. That would make the heating oil
squeeze we had a few weeks ago look like a piece of cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Retail gasoline prices, according to the Department of Energy,
rose to $1.356 a gallon this week, up 48 percent in the last year
and the highest since late 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In the futures market, the price of unleaded gasoline for March
delivery rose 2.3 cents Monday to 83.41 cents a gallon. Gasoline is
now well above the price of home heating oil, which rose 1.5 cents
to 75.70 a gallon Monday. But it is far below the 95.20 a gallon
price of Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has no plans now to dip into
the United States' Strategic Petroleum Reserve, although he is
being pressured to do so by Northeastern politicians, including
Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. A spokesman for the Energy Department
said Monday that this was ``not an option in the current
environment and the last four words are key.'' While the weather
has moderated for now in the Northeast, reducing concern about home
heating oil inventories, gasoline prices could be thrust into the
spotlight as the California presidential primary nears.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is scheduled to meet with energy officials in Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait at the end of the month but had to cancel a
meeting with Venezuelan oil officials because of a scheduling
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating what OPEC _ and the price of oil _ is going to do
is complex in part because of politics, both in OPEC and the United
States. The Iranian elections are this week, and some analysts have
said that OPEC wants to look determined to bolster oil prices to
help moderates win there. An OPEC that bowed to the West by
increasing production, analysts argue, could be used against the
moderates. In addition, the United States does not want to threaten
Saudi Arabia and lose its support, which could happen if the
Clinton administration dipped into the the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible that OPEC members would argue for a
production increase once the price of crude topped $30 a barrel and
world inventories fell. At this point, they may find it easier to
persuade members that a modest production increase of about 1
million barrels a day would not send crude oil prices tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   But even if this is the goal, analysts say, OPEC leaders like
Saudi Arabia do not want oil prices to climb too quickly. A sharp
rise could prompt a stronger reaction from U.S. and European
leaders who have to worry about the impact of higher prices on
consumers, voters and the economy. So the recent comments from OPEC
officials may have been intended to keep the price of crude oil
from rising too fast.
</P>
<P>
   A report from Venezuela helped jar the oil market Monday, said
James R. Steel, energy analyst at Refco Inc. Alvaro Silva, the vice
oil minister of Venezuela, told Dow Jones Newswires that there were
no plans to ask for a crude oil production increase at the March
OPEC meeting. His comments contradicted the signal Friday of a
production increase from an unnamed Venezuelan official. Dow Jones
also reported that Shokri Ghanem, the director of OPEC's research
division, said that ``support is growing among OPEC members for an
extension of the cuts'' beyond March. And over the weekend, Iraq
repeated its threats to cut its oil production.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really pouring cold water on this idea that took hold
last week that Saudi Arabia would allow a production increase,''
said Steel.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp decline in inventories of crude oil and products
showed up in a report by the International Energy Agency on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that oil inventories among the 29 countries in
the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development were at
the lowest month-end level since February 1997 and the lowest
year-end level in a decade. ``Without more oil from producers who
are limiting output,'' the report said, ``the first quarter
stockdraw will be even larger, increasing the risks of spot outages
and price volatility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
