<SLUG> BC-CANADA-US-BORDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO RECOMMEND RELEASE OF TERRORISM SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The federal government will recommend Tuesday the
release of Lucia Garofalo, arrested for illegal entry into the
United States Dec. 19, because ``it is evident she has no
connection to terrorism,'' according to her lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to dispel any notion that my client struck a deal, that
she is cooperating with the government by exchanging information
for her release,'' the attorney, Maryanne Kampmann said. ``This
simply is not so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For my client's safety, it is imperative that the public
understand she has struck no deal with the goverment,'' Kampmann
said.
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Charles Tetzlaff declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kampmann said prosecutors will recommend Garafolo's release at a
hearing scheduled for 1:30 p.m. in US District Court in Burlington,
Vt. Judge William K. Sessions III is scheduled to preside, and will
have the final word on the government petition.
</P>
<P>
   The next step will be ``somewhat bureaucratic'' should Judge
Sessions agree to the release, Kampmann said. Because Garofalo is
being held on charges of immigration violation, she will be
detained by the US Immigration and Naturalization Service for
perhaps a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really just a matter of red tape,'' Kampmann said.
</P>
<P>
   As to why her client was arrested for attempting to smuggle a
man with an altered French passport at a remote border crossing _
and had a record of appearing at other remote crossings with other
men at odd hours of the early morning _ Kampman said: ``This will
all become clear at (Tuesday's) hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year old Garofalo, who lives in Montreal and has two
daughters, was arrested Dec. 19 and charged with trying to bring an
Algerian national named Bouabide Chamchi into the United States at
Beecher Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors later alleged that ``it is likely that her actions
were taken on behalf of an Algerian terrorist organization or
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Her arrest came just five days after another Algerian, Ahmed
Ressam, was taken into custody in a rental car near Seattle trying
to smuggle a trunkful of explosives from Canada into the United
States. The incidents led authorities to speculate terrorists might
have been targeting New Year's Eve celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 20, a federal grand jury handed up a nine-count
indictment charging Ressam with conspiring ``to destroy or damage
structures, conveyances or other real or personal property within
the United States.'' Ressam, whose trial is scheduled to begin July
10, has pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of an association between Ressam and Garofalo were
based on something akin to telephone tag, but the police took
possible links seriously. On Dec. 14 _ the day of the Seattle
arrests _ Garofalo used her mobile phone to call a mobile phone
belonging to a man in Queens _ whose calls to another mobile phone
led to one Abdel Ghani.
</P>
<P>
   Ghani, of Brooklyn, N.Y., has been charged with being Ressam's
co-conspirator.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondet Jeffrey Good contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
