<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6869 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-WORLD-ACCESS-COX     02-14 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-ACCESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World Access extends European reach with three deals
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ World Access took another step Monday toward becoming
a major player in international telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company announced the $900 million purchase of
Communication TeleSystems International, which does business as
WorldxChange. At the same time, World Access announced both an
agreement to purchase Star Telecommunications for $500 million and
the closing of the $185 million purchase of Long Distance
International. The companies had previously signed a letter of
intent on the Star purchase.
</P>
<P>
   All three purchased companies have strength in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The series of acquisitions is in line with Chairman and Chief
Executive John D. ``Jack'' Phillips' goal of quickly growing into a
world-class competitor _ especially in Europe _ by offering a
bundle of local, long-distance and data services. Phillips compares
Europe's deregulated telecom business to the U.S. long-distance
markets several years ago, when changes in the rules lured hundreds
of competitors to AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   It took more than a decade for the U.S. long-distance industry
to consolidate into the hands of just a handful of companies.
Europe is moving faster than that, he said. ``I think this whole
thing could be over in two years.''
</P>
<P>
   That projection has spurred urgency at World Access, and the
company's buying binge is not finished, he said. ``By the end of
the year, depending on negotiations and how much (regulators) slow
us down, we are looking to be twice the size we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the three most recent deals will give the
company annual sales of about $2.5 billion. World Access had
revenues of just $152 million in 1998, before its shopping spree
began.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, World Access bought FaciliCom International, a
provider of long-distance services in Europe, for $740 million. At
the time, Phillips promised to ratchet up the company's growth
through more acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The company also recently moved to focus on telecom services and
leave the equipment business. To that end, World Access has shed
its $250 million-a-year equipment group, which includes Telco
Systems of Massachusetts and Utah-based NACT Switching. An
Alpharetta unit is also being sold.
</P>
<P>
   Facilicom gave World Access a Europeanwide network. Star
provides a solid base inside Germany while WorldxChange has
strength within Britain. Meanwhile, LDI provides a large customer
base, Phillips said. ``This fast-forwards us about two years.''
</P>
<P>
   World Access is 8 percent owned by MCI WorldCom, a
Mississippi-based telecom giant that was built in similar fashion
through a series of takeovers as it became the second-largest
long-distance company.
</P>
<P>
   World Access has about 400 employees. The companies being
purchased have 1,500. Shaping a cohesive work force is the greatest
challenge now, Phillips said. ``The hardest thing is always
integration. A network doesn't have a mind of its own. People do.''
</P>
<P>
   The company will hold a strong network with a solid customer
base and sales staff, he said.
</P>
<P>
   World Access now has a high-speed network in the United States
and 13 European countries linked by fiber-optic lines, and it does
business in 200 countries. World Access has already more than
tripled in size during the past year thanks to acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego-based WorldxChange has switching facilities in 12
countries, mostly Europe, as well as Australia and New Zealand. The
company has revenue of about $600 million a year. As part of the
takeover, WorldxChange shareholders will receive 31 million shares
of World Access stock. World Access will also assume $225 million
of debt held by WorldxChange. WorldxChange will also be given the
right to elect one director to the World Access board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is expected to close by the end of the second
quarter but is subject to regulatory approval, as well as that of
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Star is also pegged to a stock transfer.
Owners of Star stock will see each of their shares converted to
.3905 of a share in World Access.
</P>
<P>
   World Access stock dipped $1.12 1/2 to close at $21.75 a share
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
