<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6872 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SCREEN--SIDE-SFCHRON &LR;      02-14 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCREEN--SIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING MICRODISPLAY ABCS: LCD, OLED AMONG
COMPETING  TECHNOLOGIES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The silicon-based microdisplays used in inViso's near-eye devices
are only one component in an alphabet soup of new technologies
bidding for a share of of the fast-growing display market.
<P>
   &UR; FED.  &LR; One alternative long touted as a possible replacement for
conventional cathode-ray tube (CRT) and liquid-crystal display
(LCD) technologies for desktop monitors is called field-emission
display (FED). Its chief proponent, San Jose's Candescent
Technologies, has attracted support from several industry
heavyweights: It has investments from Compaq and technology
alliances with Hewlett-Packard and Sony.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology has proven more difficult to bring to market
than originally expected, and many industry players have given up
hope for it. Since its founding in 1991, Candescent has already
spent nearly $300 million on the technology, which it calls
ThinCRT, and a company backgrounder on its Web site estimates that
``the journey to initial volume production will require an
additional $500 million.'' Privately, one securities analyst who
follows the display market called the company a ``black hole.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OLED.  &LR; The hottest new technology on the display scene today is
OLED, for organic light-emitting diode. More than 80 companies are
currently  &LR; working on it, according to analyst David Mentley of
Stanford Resources in San Jose, and the list includes such
behemoths as Dupont, Kodak and Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the small, gray-green LED screens familiar in everything
from calculators to microwave ovens, OLED screens will be bright
and colorful. And, proponents say, they'll be manufacturable simply
by spraying the necessary circuitry onto rolls of plastic in
machines that are something of a cross between an inkjet printer
and a web CQ-w is lower case &LR; printing press. If that comes to pass,
it will give OLED screens at least two advantages, especially for
mobile devices: They'll be ultracheap and ultrathin.
</P>
<P>
   As with LCD, OLED will come in both active-matrix and
passive-matrix variants. Sanyo, the Japanese electronics-maker,
recently showed a 3-inch active-matrix OLED display it developed in
cooperation with Kodak. Motorola last month announced plans to use
passive-matrix OLED screens, co-developed with Pioneer, in future
Web-enabled cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   According to analyst Barry Young of DisplaySearch of Austin,
Texas, passive-matrix OLED screens aren't suitable to devices much
larger than cell phones or personal digital assistants, because
they're limited to 240 rows of vertical resolution, half that of
the lowest-resolution notebook-computer displays. But Young said
these screens will be very appealing for small devices because
they're much brighter and more responsive than passive-matrix LCDs,
yet ``very cost-effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Other, still more exotic display technologies _ including use of
plastic transistors recently announced by Lucent Technologies _ are
further out on the high-tech horizon.
</P>
<P>
   With demand for screens, especially for mobile devices, expected
to soar in the next few years, investors are hungry for
opportunities to invest in the display industry, according to
Theodore O'Neill, senior research analyst at Needham &AMP; Co. in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity for just about anything that breathes in the
display sector, in terms of institutional investor interest,
couldn't be better right now,'' he said, during a presentation
entitled ``Why Wall Street is Betting on Displays'' at an industry
conference in San Jose earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, however, is convinced that new technologies will
have the mobile market to themselves. DisplaySearch's Young noted
that the technology that dominates the market for notebook-computer
screens _ active-matrix LCD, also known as ``TFT'' _ has been
improving at rapid rates in recent years and that costs are
expected to decline by 50 percent over the next three or four years
as new production capacity coming online in Asia alleviates recent
shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to bet,'' Young said, ``you have to bet on
TFT.''
</P>
<P>
   From a regional perspective, success for any of the new
technologies would mean a larger role for U.S. companies in the
display industry. A few American companies, such as Photon
Dynamics, a San Jose maker of test equipment for display
manufacturers, and Supertex, a Sunnyvale maker of chips used in
displays, have carved out profitable niches around the periphery of
the industry, but most of it has long since moved to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Within the United States, the Bay Area doesn't dominate what's
left of the display industry the way it does in, say,
semiconductors and Web development; in fact, many of the companies
working on advanced display technologies are located in Oregon,
Austin or the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Display Consortium, an organization created and
originally funded by the Clinton administration to revive the
industry in this country, has set up shop in San Jose. And Philips
Flat Display Systems, one of the world's largest makers of
flat-panel screens, also chose to make San Jose its headquarters,
even though its parent company is Dutch and most of its
manufacturing facilities (bolstered by a recent partnership with
Korea's LG Electronics) are in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, according to Steve Franzese, the Philips division's
vice president of marketing, is that in terms of new uses for
display technology, ``the Bay Area is where the action is.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of SCREENSI () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
