<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6874 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TINY--SCREENS-SFCHRON     02-14 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINY--SCREENS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP CLOSE AND PERSONAL: TINY NEW SCREENS GIVE WEB SURFERS THE BIG 
 PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; How do you fit a screen big enough for surfing the World Wide
Web into a device sufficiently petite to slip into your pocket?
<P>
   So far, you don't. Today's ``Web-enabled'' cell phones and the
wireless Palm VII don't let you surf the way you do from your
desktop; instead, they reduce the riches of the Web to a few lines
at a time of colorless text.
</P>
<P>
   But a new technology called microdisplay could change all that
soon if the companies developing it can work out the kinks _ and if
users prove willing to put on glasses or peer through a
microscopelike eyepiece to get the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   While the microdisplay rubric encompasses a variety of
approaches, they all share a basic principle: They uncouple the
size of the image the eye perceives from the dimensions of the
device that generates that image.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the application, the physical device can range in
size from just a few millimeters to a few inches, but it can create
an image with resolution comparable to that of a conventional
desktop computer monitor. To be readable, that image must then be
magnified, but that can be done with optics that add only a little
weight and bulk.
</P>
<P>
   The net result: You put on a pair of special glasses, or hold up
a handheld device an inch in front of your eye, and you see the
equivalent of a 19-inch monitor that is 21/2 two and half &LR;   &LR; feet in
front of you.
</P>
<P>
   Two such products, developed by a Sunnyvale startup named inViso
CQ &LR; , were displayed earlier this month at DAPPCON 2000, a
display-industry conference and trade show in San Jose. The
glasses, which inViso calls eShades, are designed to be connected
to a laptop computer, portable DVD player or other video source.
The other product, eCase, is a Windows CE-based personal digital
assistant with a built-in viewer designed to be held up to the
user's eye.
</P>
<P>
   According to inViso, both products will be ready for volume
production  &UR; Privacy &LR; . Whether viewed through glasses or held up to
the eye, microdisplays will deliver a degree of privacy standard
screens can't.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, inViso is developing a credit-card-size PC Card that
could be used to connect its glasses to a current notebook
computer. That would allow business travelers packed into a crowded
plane to work on their spreadsheets when passengers reclining in
the seat in front of them make it impossible to open their
clamshell computer completely _ or watch X-rated DVDs without
worrying about the prying eyes of passenger in the next seat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Price &LR; . Once they go into volume production, microdisplays
should be far cheaper to make than conventional screens.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because inViso's ``OptiScape'' displays are based,
quite literally, on semiconductors: They're manufactured by placing
tiny liquid crystals _ similar to those used in LCD screens for
notebooks and flat-panel monitors _ right on a silicon chip. That
means scores or even hundreds of them could be made from a single
silicon wafer.
</P>
<P>
   This technology, known as liquid crystal on silicon or LCOS, is
only one of a variety of approaches used to manufacture
microdisplays. And near-eye optics aren't the only way to scale the
miniature images they generate to a usable size _ several vendors
already use the technology in meeting-room systems that project
images up to 100 inches in size, and both Samsung and JVC
demonstrated pending upcoming  &LR; rear-projection televisions at last
month's Consumer Electronic Show in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Computer giants such as Compaq, Hewlett-Packard and IBM have all
explored the use of this technology for desktop displays, although
so far it hasn't proven cost-effective compared to well-established
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   (For an overview of the whole multifaceted microdisplay
category, see  &LR; www.mdreport.com/whatis.html. &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the advantages the technology seems to offer, no one
knows for sure that microdisplays will move into the mainstream _
the history of the display industry is littered with technical
innovations that once seemed promising but never worked out.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the biggest question mark, according to Barry
Young, vice president of DisplaySearch, an Austin, Texas,
market-research and consulting company, is not technology but user
reaction. ``Frankly,'' he said, ``holding up a phone or an
organizer to your eye is unnatural in most contexts. It remains to
be seen whether people will get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Some of Silicon Valley's heaviest hitters are apparently
willing to gamble, though, that the technology will find a market.
inViso is partly owned by Three-Five Systems, a Tempe, Ariz.,
company that manufactures screens for Motorola and other cell-phone
manufacturers and has invested in a variety of new display
technologies. But inViso's investor list also includes legendary
venture capitalist Arthur Rock, Intel co-founder and chairman
emeritus Gordon Moore, Intel board member Jim Guzy, Microsoft
co-founder Paul Allen's Vulcan Partners and several other prominent
venture funds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of SCREENS1 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
