A6877 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE--COLUMN-SFCH     02-14 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOLOGISTS, ENGINEERS TEAMING UP TO UNRAVEL GENOMIC THREAD
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; The next burst of discovery in the biotech world is being driven
by an alliance between curious biologists and clever engineers, who
are inventing new instruments to probe deeper into the processes of
life.
<P>
   Incyte Pharmaceuticals in Palo Alto is an example of this
convergence between DNA and silicon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about it, biology is a very complex software
system,'' says Randy Scott, Incyte's chief scientist and
co-founder. ``The genes in your DNA encode the information for how
to build a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Incyte is one of several firms racing to find _ and patent _
genes that govern disease or development. This effort, called
genomics, is expected to lead to novel drugs or other therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte and its genomics competitors didn't arise in a vacuum.
They relied on instruments built by companies like PE Biosystems in
Foster City and Amersham Pharmacia Biotech in Sunnyvale. These
instruments automatically scan the arrangement of chemicals in each
strand of DNA, and translate this chemical information into a
string of letters called a genetic sequence.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it should come as no surprise that DNA sequencing
instruments evolved here. Once biologists discovered that DNA had
electrical and chemical properties, they looked for ways to handle
and measure the stuff. Who knew more about turning complex
chemistry into practical devices than the scientists and engineers
who mass-produced silicon chips for PCs and lasers for CDs?
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to this marriage between technical skill and biological
need, new instrument-makers are sprouting up in the South Bay.
Affymetrix of Santa Clara makes chips that automate the process of
identifying genes. Today, they are research tools. One day, they
could be used for routine disease diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Ciphergen in Mountain View is creating chips to automate the
analysis of ``These machines cost hundreds of thousands of
dollars,'' says Ament, 27, raising his voice above the techno-pop
music that blares in the background like a drum beat. ``Every
minute they're down is money lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The data pouring off this sequencing assembly line flows into an
air-conditioned computer center. There, in the quiet chill, an
array of 1,500 PCs takes these raw gene fragments, matches them to
known sequences or marks them as novel, and deposits the data in
storage systems that are the information-equivalent of bank vaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built this center a year ago and we're just about out of
room,'' says Will Francis III, the 28-year-old system administrator
who manages the PC array.
</P>
<P>
   The array is another small innovation at the crossroads of
biology and computing. According to Francis, the data massaging
work doesn't require a very powerful computer. There's just so much
data spewing off the sequencing line that Incyte needed a cheaper
way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   So engineers wrote a program, based on the free Linux operating
system, that allows those humble PCs to divvy up the processing
chores. By using free Linux, and buying generic computers, Francis
estimates that Incyte gets the job done at 10 percent of what it
used to cost when the company used powerful workstations running
the Unix operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Saving money should cheer stockholders. But the collaboration
between biology and high tech also expresses itself in sexier ways.
</P>
<P>
   Sunnyvale's Amersham Pharmacia, for instance, is helping
scientists from the University of Delaware analyze microbes taken
from hydrothermal vents 11/2 miles beneath Mexico's Sea of Cortes.
</P>
<P>
   These microbes thrive in some of the harshest conditions on
Earth, says University of Delaware marine biologist Craig Cary.
They live in total darkness, in boiling water, with toxic chemicals
swirling about them and the weight of the ocean bearing down.
</P>
<P>
   These extreme bacteria _ scooped off the bottom by researchers
in a tiny deep-sea sub _ almost certainly contain proteins and
enzymes never before seen on the surface. Cary thinks some of these
chemicals could be used to make drugs or industrial solvents.
</P>
<P>
   But first, this bacterial DNA must be picked apart and examined
_ an ideal task for automated machinery. (See
 &LR; www.ocean.udel.edu/deepsea  &LR; for more on the project.)
</P>
<P>
   Just as our universe enlarged when we looked through the
telescope, and medicine changed when we bent over a microscope,
these new instruments will open new vistas in biology.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest challenges still lie ahead. What researchers are
doing is a gigantic exercise in reverse engineering. They're trying
to pick life apart and see how the little bits of it work.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they isolate more genes and proteins and enzymes,
they're going to want to know how they work together. Predicting
those interactions could make climate change modeling look like
child's play.
</P>
<P>
   IBM Corp. has already started on the process. In December, it
announced a $100 million program that will enlist 50 scientists
from San Jose, Yorktown Heights and six other labs worldwide, in
the development of a radical new computer system, dubbed Blue Gene.
</P>
<P>
   One of the IBM team's first challenges will be writing an
operating system capable of controlling more than 1 million
processors. Only then will they take a crack at the tough stuff,
figuring out how proteins behave.
</P>
<P>
   They'll probably be at it for a while. After all, unraveling
evolution takes time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
