<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6878 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-OUTTAKES--COLUMN-SFCH     02-14 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTTAKES--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SILICON VALLEY SHAPING NATIONAL POLITICS  &HT;     By JAN BOYD AND STAN BUNGER 
 &HT;         c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
``If you want to know what's going on in America in the 21st
century, you have to know what's happening in Silicon Valley,''
says Democrat Jeff Modisett, most recently Indiana's attorney
general and now vice president of TechNet, Silicon Valley's most
powerful lobbying group.
<P>
   It's no surprise that public officials and political candidates
are buying into that notion, but the numbers may surprise you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think over the last two years we've had over 200 elected
officials coming through here _ state, gubernatorial, senatorial,''
says Modisett's counterpart on the Republican side of Tech Net,
Lezlee Westine. ``Last December alone I think we had about a
quarter of the U.S. Senate here in the Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   The possible cash connection is the obvious attraction. But so
is information. Finding educated technology advisers inside the
Beltway isn't easy and at this point few elected officials possess
real in-depth technical knowledge. So national technology policy is
unquestionably being shaped by individuals here in the Bay Area;
individuals who have had no connection to the political process
until the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many politicians aren't taking any sort of stand on any
technology issues until they check with TechNet members. The tricky
part is finding an executive to actually meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great interest on behalf of the executives to spend
time with the elected officials, but they are just as busy as any
governor or senator or, frankly, presidential candidate,'' said
Westine, ``so it has been challenging for them to put on their own
calendar the time to meet with all the candidates that come through
here.''
</P>
<P>
   TechNet's primary lobbying issues include normalizing trade
relations with China, public school reform, encouraging accounting
standards that favor high-tech companies, increasing foreign worker
visas, and supporting federal funding for technology and science
research. Listen for evidence of the Silicon Valley influence in
political speeches as the California primary approaches.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL CAPITAL: The approach of the California primary is
also good business for Silicon Valley startup Broad Daylight. The
company makes money by licensing its question-and-answer technology
to Web sites such as Space.com and Gloss.com. But Broad Daylight is
also making its technology available for free to political
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The technology allows candidates to easily answer e-mailed
questions on any issue. The questioner receives a personalized
e-mail response. The candidate can also post the response on his or
her Web site. The answers to the most frequently asked questions
rise to the top of the list of answers on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain uses the technology on his site. The Arizona
Republican presidential candidate has about 200 posted answers.
Broad Daylight CEO Louise Kirkbride says seeing the common sense of
the voters is quite gratifying. ``Many times the questions that get
promoted in the more popular media tend to be more newsworthy
questions, tend to be a little more sensational questions,'' said
Kirkbride. ``What we find, because we track the actual frequency
with which the questions are asked and we see what people really
are interested in. For instance, the single most interesting
question on Senator McCain's site is about the budget surplus. What
would he do with the budget surplus?''
</P>
<P>
   If you are interested in finding your own answers to questions
about California ballot propositions, check out Broad Daylight's
own political site:  &LR; www.FAQvoter.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIDY LITTLE PROFIT: Never overlook the small stuff. Take 2Wire,
a Milpitas startup company that plans to soon begin selling a
product line that will let people with DSL connections easily
create a home network.
</P>
<P>
   2Wire's HomePortal products combine a router, a hub and, in some
cases, a DSL modem. The ``residential gateway'' devices are
expected to sell for $400 and up when they start shipping this
spring. Using a 2Wire HomePortal, a DSL subscriber could spread the
high-speed Internet connection around the house, using existing
internal telephone wiring.
</P>
<P>
   While 2Wire executives hope they'll have a hit product on their
hands, they've already been pleasantly surprised by the success of
a much more mundane offering. That would be a $9.95 filter, used to
isolate ordinary telephone traffic from the higher-frequency DSL
signal traveling over the same set of wires.
</P>
<P>
   The filters are being purchased by DSL providers, which install
them in customers' homes and offices to prevent interference
between voice and data traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joke about this (filter) becoming our flagship project,`
said 2Wire CEO Brian Hinman. He calculates the average home has 6
telephone jacks, each of which would need some kind of filter upon
installation of DSL service. And the surge in DSL connections is
something to behold.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hinman, ``My prediction for the year 2000 is that we'll see
about 3 million new lines installed. It's astronomical growth we're
seeing in the DSL market.'' While Hinman didn't provide exact
figures, he said the low-cost filter could easily represent 30 to
40 percent of 2Wire's revenue this year.
</P>
<P>
   Those little filters may turn out to be the tail that wags the
dog.
</P>
<P>
   NON-CEO CEO: It says so right on Ted Ganchiff's business cards:
``Employee Number One.'' Ganchiff is the founder of a San Francisco
company called GiveMeTalk, which bills itself as the home for
do-it-yourself Internet talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   In ordinary corporate-speak, Ganchiff is the firm's CEO, but he
has a reason for avoiding the term. ``There's something really
strange about calling yourself CEO at a company when it's two
people or three people,'' says Ganchiff. ``I thought `CEO' was
overstating it slightly.''
</P>
<P>
   GiveMeTalk still employs fewer than a dozen people, but has
managed to attract prerecorded audio shows from a wide variety of
people, including KFOG commentator Stan Sinberg and Dr. Moira Gunn,
host of public radio's ``Tech Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also this: a favorable astrological chart. So says
Marlene Caldes, a Mill Valley ``life strategist'' whose reading of
the stars convinces her GiveMeTalk will enjoy a long and successful
run. ``These guys are going to the moon,'' said Caldes. ``The day
they created their company, they had such great astrological
signatures that it would be impossible for them to be temporary.''
</P>
<P>
   Many a startup company wishes it were that easy to figure out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of OUTTAKES () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
