<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSN.COM--LOGO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MICROSOFT UNVEILS AN AD CAMPAIGN TO PROMOTE ITS PORTAL, MSN.COM  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Microsoft Sunday night launched a $150 million ad campaign, its
biggest ever for a consumer product, to promote its portal,
MSN.com.
<P>
   Microsoft hopes the big boost in ad spending _ MSN's last
campaign cost about $18 million _ will help it battle AOL for new
Internet users and brand-name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1999, MSN.com had more visitors than any other Web
site except for Yahoo, according to Media Metrix. AOL ranked No.3.
But many MSN visitors get there by default because it's the Web
page that pops up when computer users first launch Microsoft's
Internet Explorer Web browser. Microsoft believes MSN lags AOL in
consumer awareness.
</P>
<P>
   That's the reason MSN is also changing its logo _ from a
nondescript oval to a butterfly with the same four colors as the
Windows logo. The butterfly signals ``freedom, aspiration and
empowerment,'' as well as a ``rebirth for MSN'' according to
company officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about making the Web indispensable in people's
everyday lives,'' said Deanna Sanford, lead product manager for
MSN.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second MSN spots follow the daily lives of four people of
different ages, backgrounds and Internet experience, as they move
into a house equipped with nothing but a computer with a connection
to MSN.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 or so MSN ads follow different characters, from novices
to experts, as they all become more Web savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say MSN is making up for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons you go through a rebranding like this is to
step away from the past,'' said Rob Enderle, vice president of
research firm Giga Information Group. ``Microsoft did let MSN
languish _ it was lost in a morass of conflicting strategies _ so
it does makes sense to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   When MSN was launched in the mid-1990s, critics said it came off
as a cold, corporate Web site with limited appeal to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   With a relaunch last fall, and a new set of consumer-friendly
tools like instant messaging and community sites, MSN is finally on
track, Enderle said.
</P>
<P>
   But he thinks MSN will face stiff competition from the new
AOL-Time Warner juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft probably has more experience doing what they're
trying to do, and AOL is trying to get through a merger,'' he said.
``But AOL isn't being distracted by the (Department of Justice), so
you've got to give them the inside track.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is currently embroiled in an antitrust battle with the
federal government which contends that the Seattle company is a
monopolist that hurt consumers and used its dominance in the
software industry to stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of MSN14 () &QL;
</P>
