<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6881 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INDIA-ONLINE-SFCHRON &LR;      02-14 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 JUST CLICK TO MAKE A PASSAGE TO INDIA  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Every morning, Jayashree Sambamurthy pulls up RadioOfIndia.com on
her computer and listens to classical Carnatic music from her
homeland.
<P>
   Later, she'll tune in TVofIndia.com to watch a Hindi language
television show, or switch to PressOfIndia.com to read the online
version of a regional Indian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really great,'' said Sambamurthy, whose apartment in
Clovis near Fresno seems light years away from her native land.
``We are so far away from our homeland and we get it right on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The three sister sites were launched in the past month by
Homeland Networks Inc., a San Jose startup that believes the Web is
a prime vehicle for reaching the estimated 150,000 India natives
living and working in the Bay Area and an estimated 15 million
nonresident Indians worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indian community is one of the most computer-savvy and
connected immigrant communities in the world,'' said Homeland chief
executive Ron Victor.
</P>
<P>
   Homeland was co-founded in September by Sabeer Bhatia, who is
best known as the founder of Hotmail, the free e-mail service that
he sold to Microsoft in 1998 for a tidy $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   And one of Homeland's minority investors is the Indian media
company Unilazer Group, whose UTV unit is a television programming
company that is providing live and taped content for the site. UTV
invested about $1 million in Homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The TVofIndia site launched February 4 and offers TV shows like
``Amar Chitra Katha,'' a series depicting historical events in
India. Victor said another popular show is ``Meerabai,'' a series
about one of India's key religious figures.
</P>
<P>
   Also popular are game shows like ``Kricket,'' which is a cross
between a cricket match and a trivia show like ``Jeopardy.'' The
site was also able to Webcast the live India-Pakistan cricket
series earlier this month. That game is hugely popular in India but
not found on American sports channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't find it here, that's why they crave it,'' said
Victor, who also missed watching the game.
</P>
<P>
   Indian television is not new to the Internet. MSNBC.com, for
example, has a live 24-hour feed from India's NDTV network.
</P>
<P>
   But Victor said he hopes his site appeals to people who don't
want to buy a satellite dish to get more news and entertainment
from India or are not satisfied with the limited number of Indian
shows on broadcast stations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The shows appear in RealVideo streaming video at preset times;
there is one show playing at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   Victor admits the Web telecasts are best viewed by computer
users with high-speed Internet connections, not people with slower
56K connections. However, he's counting on the near future when
broadband connections become more prevalent in homes.
</P>
<P>
   The TVofIndia site also links to RadioOfIndia, which launched
January 4 and has about 600 regular daily listeners. The radio site
offers news, cricket matches and the soundtracks of the latest hits
from Bollywood, India's equivalent to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The site also has programing in four languages, Gujarati,
Malayalam, Tamil, Telugu, along with a selection of regional
religious music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep it on 70 to 80 percent of the time at work,'' said
Kishore Chanchlani, a technology manager with a company based in
Houston, Texas. His favorite is classical Hindustani music.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the radio site helps Chanchlani's family keep in touch
with their roots. ``It's important for our kids to know where they
came from,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Allen, an analyst with the research firm Aberdeen Group,
said he's not convinced computer users have the time or inclination
to watch television or listen to the radio all day, especially at
work where broadband connections are more prevalent. But he said
Homeland appears to be on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing some of the right things,'' Allen said. ``I
didn't come away with the feeling this was the greatest idea ever,
but I do like their focus on the Indian market. They've got
something they could develop. It's just a question of being
persistent and getting the right relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor said the company hopes eventually to offer programming
targeted to natives of other countries in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to position ourselves as a company that Webcasts
ethnic content around the world,'' Victor said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of INDIA14 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
