<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPROMISE ON CONFEDERATE FLAG GAINS SUPPORT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Gov. Jim Hodges won the support of several
ranking black state legislators on Monday for his proposal to
remove the Confederate battle flag from atop the state Capitol and
raise a smaller version of the flag near a monument on the side of
the Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP, which is boycotting the state until the flag is
removed, still opposes the plan. But a growing number of
legislators, black and white, now consider the plan a reasonable
compromise, raising the possibility that the NAACP may be isolated
by black leaders who want the issue put to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate what the NAACP has done to bring this to the
forefront,'' said Rep. Gilda Cobb-Hunter, a Democrat who is the
state House minority leader. ``But I think many of us in the
Legislative Black Caucus now recognize that this proposal has the
possibility of bringing all sides together.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges proposed putting a square version of the flag, which is
considered more accurate by many Civil War historians, near a
statue of Confederate Gen. Wade Hampton, who served as a senator
and as governor of the state. The site is not as prominent as
either the dome or the Confederate Soldiers' Monument in front of
the Capitol where many flag supporters have said the flag should
fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep our state's business climate strong, including
our important tourism industry,'' Hodges said. ``And we want to
send a signal to the nation, and to our children, that South
Carolinians can come together to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature controls the flag's fate, and several staunch
flag supporters in the Republican majority of the House oppose the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker David H. Wilkins, a leader of the pro-flag
forces, praised the governor for putting the plan forward. Wilkins
said he prefers putting the flag near the Confederate Soldiers'
Monument, but a statement he issued seemed to leave open the
possibility of compromise.
</P>
</TEXT>
