<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6886 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-STORMS-MOBILEHOMES-CO     02-14 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORMS-MOBILEHOMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stability of mobiles questioned
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Experts say there's no truth to the rumor that mobile
homes act as tornado magnets. But even the newer, improved variety
are less likely than traditional houses to protect their occupants
in bad weather, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of mobile homes were literally blown apart by a series of
violent tornadoes that swept through south Georgia counties, Grady,
Mitchell, Colquitt and Tift, shortly after midnight Monday, leaving
a war-zone's worth of death and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers, still searching the rubble late Monday, could
not say how many died in mobile homes. But officials said at least
some of the victims did.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of mobile homes were in the area the tornado hit,'' said
Sheriff's Lt. Cecil Wingate of Mitchell County. ``I'm almost sure
all of those killed here were in mobile homes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past 20 years, 45 percent of all tornado deaths
nationwide have been in mobile homes, yet only 7 percent of the
population occupy them, said Thomas W. Schmidlin, a meteorologist
and geography professor at Kent State University in Kent, Ohio.
Schmidlin and his colleagues have spent years studying risk factors
for death due to tornadoes in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1990 and 1998, 200 deaths were recorded nationwide in
mobile homes during tornadoes. Georgia had 35 such fatalities,
second highest in the nation, Schmidlin said. Florida led with 49
mobile home-tornado deaths, some of which were in parked
recreational vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, mobile homes in Georgia are required by law to be
anchored to the ground; the manufacturer usually recommends the
type of tie-downs to be used.
</P>
<P>
   But here, as in other states including Florida, tie-down
enforcement and inspection is spotty, said Gina Gassert,
spokeswoman for state Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine, whose
office regulates mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many states like Georgia rely on local code officials to
handle inspections,'' she said. ``It's up to the local building
code officials to inspect and make sure mobile homes are tied down.
But I'm sure there are some out there that aren't tied down and
aren't inspected.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine has a staff of six inspectors who check mobile home
installations only when their owners file complaints, Gassert said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million of Georgia's 7.8 million residents live in
mobile homes, and 60 percent of the mobile homes are on private
land, rather than in trailer parks, according to the Atlanta-based
Georgia Manufactured Housing Association. Although mobile homes
aren't cheap _ averaging $42,000 in Georgia, excluding land costs _
they still offer more affordable housing than site built homes.
</P>
<P>
   The average mobile home owner in Georgia is 33 years old, with
an annual income of $30,000, GMHA figures indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile home manufacturing is big business in Georgia. With 27
manufacturing plants employing more than 6,000 people, Georgia
leads the nation in the production of mobile homes, according to
GMHA.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, the federal department of Housing and Urban
Development, which regulates mobile home building, has been slowly
enacting more stringent construction standards, especially in
hurricane-prone coastal areas where mobile homes must be able to
withstand winds of 110 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studies have shown today's manufactured home, if properly
installed, will perform well from a safety standpoint,'' said
Charlotte Gattis, GMHA president.
</P>
<P>
   But they are still not as safe as site-built homes, said Peter
Sparks, a Clemson University professor who studies wind resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobile homes are not very heavy and they take off rather
easily,'' he said. ``People are always much more vulnerable in
mobile homes than in regular houses.''
</P>
<P>
   The risk of injury or death is so great that the National
Weather Service advises mobile home residents to take shelter in a
ditch or vehicle if a tornado threatens. Most tornado-related
mobile home deaths are caused by blunt force trauma from flying
debris, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidlin is conducting studies that suggest vehicles, with
safety glass and seat belts, may indeed be safer than mobile homes
in high winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally we're finding that cars and pickup trucks can
withstand winds of 118 miles an hour and above, which would
certainly destroy most mobile homes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He warned, however, that sturdy structures with windowless rooms
provide the best shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' he said, ``is that people in mobile homes
just ought to have someplace else they can go in a storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Jingle Davis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 2026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
