<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6894 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-BIGDIG-NAT     02-14 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BIGDIG-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        GOP LAWMAKER TO TAKE AIM AT BIG DIG
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 14 -- A powerful House Republican is
considering ways to strip next year's funding for the Central
Artery project, and may advocate a criminal investigation into
whether Big Dig officials lied to federal auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a federal audit of the Big Dig that suggests the project
could cost more than $12.2 billion, Rep. Frank R. Wolf, chair of
the House appropriations committee, could demand that funds already
authorized for the Big Dig be denied, a congressional GOP aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress has already authorized Big Dig funding through
its scheduled completion in 2005, Wolf may ask the Federal Highway
authorities to put an immediate freeze on contracting work on the
Big Dig, the aide said. The federal highway administration does not
need congressional approval to do this.
</P>
<P>
   He is to address the subject at a House hearing on
transportation spending Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The aide said Wolf, a longstanding critic of the Big Dig, is
furious at both Big Dig managers and the Federal Highway
Administration that oversees the project for failing to disclose
cost overruns and possibly trying to hide the true costs.
</P>
<P>
   Big Dig officials made the surprising announcement early this
month that the project would be $1.4 billion over budget.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is also reviewing whether Big Dig officials' failure to
report the shortfalls to the Department of Transportation inspector
general warrants civil or criminal penalties. The inspector general
Kenneth Mead was unaware of the $1.4 billion figure, but released a
report Monday arguing the overruns could be even greater.
</P>
<P>
   If the law was violated, Wolf may ask the Justice Department to
get involved, the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   And since Congress must approve funding levels authorized for
the Big Dig every year through 2005, Wolf could offer an amendment
that kills next year's funding for the Big Dig project.
Massachusetts would be able to keep the money for other road and
highway projects.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Olver, D-Amherst, who also sits on the subcommittee,
said he was skeptical the Big Dig could be killed in the
appropriations process.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to happen,'' Olver said. ``That's irrational.
I can't imagine that kind of thing coming out of subcommittee.''
But he added of tomorrow's hearing: ``It could produce some
considerable fireworks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout all of this, the crux of this is that the Big Dig's
got to be finished,'' Olver said. ``We've got to get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-MITROVICA-ART-     02-14 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MITROVICA-ART-815&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH AND U.N. OFFICIALS BLAME EXTREMISTS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ The two men in charge of this divided
town, a U.N. administrator and a French general, said Monday that
they were counting on two foreign judges to punish extremists after
12 days of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the violence stops, Mario Morcone, the U.N. administrator
in Mitrovica, and Gen. Pierre de Saqui de Sannes, the French
commander of peacekeeping troops in northern Kosovo, said they fear
that ethnic relations will be poisoned permanently.
</P>
<P>
   De Saqui de Sannes, who has blamed the violence on both sides,
said individuals were instigating attacks purposely to escalate the
violence and to destroy the last multiethnic town in Kosovo where
Serbs and Albanians are still living side by side, if uneasily.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are extremists who want the peace to fail,'' he said in
an interview at his headquarters. While the violence consists of
``isolated acts,'' he said, the strategy is to escalate tensions
and intolerance. ``I am worried that we may be in the process of an
escalation of intolerance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Albanians have wanted to push the Serbs in northern
Mitrovica and beyond out of Kosovo, and some Serbs have wanted to
do the opposite _ push the Albanians remaining among them south of
the Ibar river, which divides Mitrovica, in order to create a pure
Serbian area in northern Kosovo, he said. ``The people are hostages
to this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morcone said that it was now clear who the troublemakers were
and that it was critical to move against them. A judge and a
prosecutor, both foreigners, were arriving to start dealing with
the dozens of people arrested during Sunday's violence. ``You may
well see more arrests in the following days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to arrest people and remove them from the scene. We
know the people who are involved,'' he said. ``For me it has to be
the solution, not only for me here, but for all of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   French troops rounded up and arrested 46 people _ 45 Albanians
and one Serb _ on Sunday after a day of furious firefights between
NATO-led peacekeepers and local gunmen. A dozen were quickly
released, de Saqui de Sannes said, and the rest were being
questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that some Serbs would also be arrested, Marcone said,
``Yesterday was a bad day for the Albanians, but that will not be
all.''
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, Albanians engaged the French in heavy
firefights, and in the resulting melee two French soldiers were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   According to the general, a crowd of Albanians gathered Sunday
morning near a French guard post after a grenade exploded and
wounded five Albanians. The crowd began throwing stones at French
soldiers who then cordoned off the area. Then a man appeared from a
house, shouted at the people to get down, and fired directly at the
soldiers, hitting one in the stomach and a second as he moved to
react, the general said.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers pursued the man but did not catch him. There ensued
several hours of shooting as French soldiers moved into the
district and came under fire from several directions. Eventually
they surrounded some 18 people in a house and got them to
surrender. They found only one weapon in the house, but since then
have seized more weapons during house searches, the general said.
</P>
<P>
   There were women and minors among those arrested, he added. One
old woman was found to be concealing a Kalashnikov rifle under her
skirt, he said. Soldiers also stopped a local ambulance driving
towards Mitrovica on Monday and discovered 180 grenades and
anti-tank rockets inside, the general recounted.
</P>
<P>
   During the fighting Sunday a group of some 30 armed Albanians
also tried to ford the Ibar river to the west of the city, but were
spotted and deterred with warning shots, a spokesman for the French
force said.
</P>
<P>
   The events are likely to aggravate relations between the French
troops and the ethnic Albanians here. Thousands flocked on Monday
to the burial of the one man killed by French troops during the
fighting Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Avni Haradinaj, 35, a former guerrilla fighter of the Kosovo
Liberation Army and a local hero, was buried with full honors by
his former comrades in arms. His coffin, draped in the red Albanian
flag, was carried up the hill to the edge of a wood outside the
city, through a crowd of some 3,000 mourners.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian mayor of Mitrovica, Bajram Rexhepi, who said he had
been a friend of the dead man, said Haradinaj was unarmed when he
was shot by French soldiers and was in Mitrovica visiting his
sisters. ``There were four people with him and they explained that
he had no weapon at the moment he was killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   De Saqui de Sannes insisted that Haradinaj was armed and was
shooting at the French soldiers when he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   The general tried to reassure the Albanians of French
neutrality. ``If we were shot at by Albanians, it is difficult to
arrest Serbs,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the few weeks since he took command, peacekeeping troops have
raided a Serb bar that has frequently been identified as a hangout
of troublemakers, even of paramilitaries. They also arrested a man
close to the Serb leader of north Mitrovica for possessing a
telescopic sight, and expelled him from the city for 20 days under
a special resolution introduced by the United Nations last year,
the general said.
</P>
<P>
   The general defended his troops' actions on the night of Feb. 3,
when Serb mobs rampaged through the city and left eight Albanians
dead. The peacekeepers worked hard to contain the violence, he
said, blockading the city to prevent outsiders from adding to the
violence, and evacuating Albanians and foreigners to safety. ``If
the troops had not acted as they did, it would have been a lot
worse, a real massacre,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The need now is for a political solution, for institutions and
money, to lift the economy and deny extremists an open field, the
general said. ``I cannot do much more,'' he warned. ``I cannot stop
someone throwing a grenade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
