NYT-02-14-00 2036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0486 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-NYT &LR;      02-14 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE TESTS RUSHED, PENTAGON OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon is facing undue pressure to meet an
``artificial'' deadline for recommending whether to deploy the
national missile defense system, according to the project's senior
weapons tester, who said the current timetable disregards enormous
technical problems.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual report, released on Monday, Philip E. Coyle III,
the Pentagon's director of operational testing and evaluation, said
that the speed with which the Pentagon must judge the feasibility
of the multi-billion-dollar system to protect the country from
limited nuclear strikes is being driven more by President Clinton's
summer deadline than by scientific requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, Coyle said the Pentagon was facing undue pressure
``to meet an artificial decision point in the development
process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This pattern has historically resulted in a negative effect on
virtually every troubled D.O.D. development program,'' he added,
using initials for the Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first warning from a senior Pentagon official that
the test schedule prevents the military from reliably telling
Clinton by the June deadline whether the system is ready to deploy.
Coyle did not comment on the report on Monday, but said through a
spokesperson that his report stands on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The report also comes as European allies, as well as a handful
of members of Congress, are asking Clinton to delay his decision so
it can be made next year by a newly elected president and Congress.
But missile defense proponents in Congress, especially Republicans,
are urging a speedy deployment of the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be one of the most serious decisions a president of
the United States may make in modern times, and if the technology
piece isn't there to look at all of the options, then we have to
defer the decision,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who is urging
a delay even though he is a strong supporter of missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has twice tested components of a system to knock
down a missile in space. Monday's report confirmed that although
the first test last October was initially hailed as a success, it
is uncertain whether the interceptor could actually have hit the
mock warhead without having mistakenly steered toward the target by
locking in error on a decoy balloon.
</P>
<P>
   The more serious setback came last month, when the missile
test-fired from the Marshall Islands in the Pacific failed to hit
the warhead launched from a California air base. Investigators said
the problem might have been a leak in a pipe that cools infrared
sensors, blinding the interceptor in the last six seconds of the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   If that test had succeeded, the Pentagon would have met its own
minimum standard for advising the president that the technology was
feasible for deploying the system in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the failure pushed to the middle of May the third and
final test to show that the system works before the June review.
</P>
<P>
   ``This next test coming up doesn't give you a lot of time to
collect the data and present it for the review,'' said Lt. Col.
Richard Lehner of the Air Force, the spokesman for the Pentagon's
Ballistic Missile Defense Organization. ``Each test requires a
30-day review, a 60-day review and a 90-day review to understand
the data.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense officials have warned that the military was on a
``rigorous schedule'' that allowed for few failures in creating the
system to protect all 50 states from a a limited ballistic missile
attack.
</P>
<P>
   But in testimony before the Senate Armed Services Committee last
week, Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen said the project was
``on track'' and that he would be able to make his recommendation
to Clinton in June.
</P>
<P>
   Coyle's strong warning in the report on Monday questions that
assumption. While not openly asking for a delay, Coyle said the
administration must ``allow time'' to examine the results from the
third test.
</P>
<P>
   Critics and some supporters of the system have complained that
the deadline was dictated by election-year politics rather than
science. They argue that Clinton wants to decide whether to deploy
the system this summer in order to prevent the Republicans from
accusing the Democrats of being soft on defense in the general
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In order to deploy the system, the administration is asking
Russia to agree to amend the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty,
which forbids a national missile defense system. But the Russians
have refused to make any changes, saying the treaty is the
cornerstone to all non-proliferation agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott is leading negotiations
with Russia and discussions with the European allies, who have
raised questions about the system. In a visit to Washington last
week, Robin Cook, the British foreign secretary, said that as the
administration pursued a national missile defense it was ``very
important that we preserve the unity of NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbott is leading a delegation to Beijing this week to discuss,
among other issues, Chinese anger that the United States could
deploy such a system.
</P>
<P>
   China fears that the United States would use its missile defense
to protect Taiwan, which Beijing considers a Chinese province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
