<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS SEEK TO END A SOCIAL SECURITY PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas)  (lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in the House introduced legislation
Monday that would allow most Social Security recipients to earn as
much money as they want without giving up any of their retirement
benefit. President Clinton said he would sign the bill if it passed
Congress and came to him without being linked to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is intended to deal with a longstanding policy
that critics said discouraged older people from continuing to work
after they reached normal retirement age and began drawing Social
Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, Social Security recipients aged 65 through 69
lose $1 of their benefit for every $3 they earn beyond a maximum
amount that is recalculated each year. This year the maximum is
$17,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are no losses of benefits for those 70 or older. For
recipients aged 62 to 65, benefits are reduced by $1 for every $2
earned beyond a limit, which this year is $10,080.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, introduced Monday by Reps. Clay Shaw of Florida and
Sam Johnson of Texas, both Republicans, would repeal the earnings
limits for recipients from 65 through 69, allowing them to make as
much money as they want without any loss of benefit.
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 Social Security recipients aged 65 through 69 gave
up part of their benefit last year because of their earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of their reasons for working,'' Shaw said, ``they
are losing Social Security benefits that they earned, because they
chose to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would not change the earnings limits on beneficiaries
under the age of 65. About 400,000 people in that age group lost
part of their benefit. Because of the complicated way that Social
Security benefits are calculated, members of both parties said that
ending the earnings limit on early retirees could wind up reducing
benefits for some people over the long run.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday with CNN, Clinton said he was
``thrilled'' by the prospect of scaling back the earnings limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're 65 today in America, your life expectancy is 83,''
Clinton said. ``You want to be alert, you want to be physically
strong. And we know as people stay more active, they're going to
live better, not just longer. So I don't think we should penalize
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bipartisan cooperation on the bill, Clinton said, could be a
sign that Republicans are willing to work with him on the broader
problem of assuring Social Security's long-term solvency.
</P>
<P>
   Scaling back the earnings limit would result in Social
Security's paying out $22.7 billion in additional benefits over the
next decade, to be paid out of the payroll taxes that finance the
system.
</P>
<P>
   But the system's actuaries told Congress Monday that the change
would not affect Social Security's long-term solvency. That is in
part because the additional payments over the short run would be
offset over the longer run by a related technical change in the way
that older retirees are currently credited with a slightly higher
benefit for taking a reduced benefit in the early years of
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides and White House officials said the change
would also not reduce the projected federal budget surplus outside
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they intended to move the bill out of the Ways
and Means Committee in the next few weeks and bring it up for a
vote on the House floor soon after.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
