<HEADLINE>
U.S. SPACECRAFT ORBITS EROS ASTEROID 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A NASA spacecraft on Valentine's Day maneuvered into orbit
around a distant asteroid named for the Greek god of love.
</P>
<P>
   The $224.1 million Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous, or NEAR,
spacecraft reached 433 Eros on Monday _ kicking off a yearlong,
closeup study of a rocky celestial fragment likely left over from
the formation of the solar system 4.5 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The rendezvous, which began the first orbit ever of an asteroid,
thrilled scientists at the Johns Hopkins University's Applied
Physics Laboratory in Laurel, Md., who are conducting the mission
for NASA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be Valentine's Day for most people, but it's
Christmas Eve for me, with all the presents piled up and waiting to
be opened,'' said Andrew Cheng, the NEAR mission's chief scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Photos of Eros transmitted by the probe Monday revealed a gray
realm ravaged by impacts with meteorites. Among the many craters
scientists identified was a large heart-shaped depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The asteroids include many different kinds of objects,'' Cheng
said. ``Some of them are the building blocks that the terrestrial
planets were made out of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are the fragments you get when objects the size
of planets get blown apart (by collisions with other planets),'' he
said. ``In either case, we are looking back at a time that is very
close to the beginning of the solar system, something like 4.5
billion years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Theorists believe the early sun was encircled by a disk of dust
and rubble. As time passed, the smaller material joined into larger
objects that grew more massive, broke apart and rejoined through
processes, which are still not understood.
</P>
<P>
   Eros is peanut-shaped, or as one scientist characterized it,
contoured like a banana with a bite taken from the middle. It
measures 21 miles long and 8 miles wide, or about twice the size of
Manhattan Island.
</P>
<P>
   The asteroid circles the sun 160 million miles from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   NEAR's 57-second maneuver Monday placed it into an initial
204-by-280 mile high orbit around the slowly turning asteroid, all
but right on the money, said Robert Farquhar of Johns Hopkins, the
mission manager.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks, scientists plan to gradually reduce the
separation. They are discussing the possibility near the end of the
mission of attempting a gentle landing, a kind of planetary
touch-and-go that would disclose wc~+vther% &QC; M
</P>
</TEXT>
