<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-APPOINT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW POST FOR MERRILL LYNCH CFO SEEN AS LEADING TO CHAIRMANSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. has put its chief financial
officer, E. Stanley O'Neal, in charge of the nation's biggest
brokerage operation and on track to be the next chairman of the
firm.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, one of the highest-ranking blacks on Wall Street, is the
first person to be named to oversee Merrill's 14,200 brokers
without having been a stockbroker himself. He succeeds John L.
Steffens, a former broker who has been president of the brokerage
unit for 15 years. Steffens, one of Merrill's top three executives,
was named chairman of the unit.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill chose Thomas Patrick, 56, an executive vice president
who once was the firm's chief financial officer, to replace O'Neal
in that job.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and people inside Merrill interpreted O'Neal's job
switch as a sign that he has the early lead in the race to succeed
David H. Komansky as chairman and chief executive in a few years.
The firm's presidency, the slot directly below Komansky's, has been
vacant since Herbert M. Allison abruptly left the firm in July.
</P>
<P>
   Komansky, who is 60, said Monday that he intends to continue
working until he is 65. ``We certainly have no plans to name a
president for at least two years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That will leave time for O'Neal to prove his ability to run one
of Merrill's core businesses while it is going through a period of
sweeping change. The firm, which started out as a stock brokerage
firm and evolved over the years into a diversified provider of
financial services, derives about half of its profit from its
brokerage operations.
</P>
<P>
   In that post, people inside the firm say, O'Neal will be
competing with the heads of two of the firm's other business units:
Thomas W. Davis, who runs the institutional business, and Jeffrey
M. Peek, who is trying to turn around Merrill's mutual-fund unit.
One of the three is likely to be the next president, those people
say.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Komansky declined to handicap the competition.
``My very, very, very strong preference is to name an insider'' to
succeed Allison, he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said he had been studying the brokerage operation for a
couple of years, but added that ``there are a lot of people in this
business I need to meet.'' With Merrill's introduction of online
trading last year, he said, ``we've got the right formula and we
have all the right attributes to compete for garnering assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said they thought the job was now O'Neal's to
win or lose. ``I've got to believe he's the front-runner now,''
said Steve Galbraith, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.
``He's the one guy who will have had experience in all areas of the
firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming chief financial officer in 1998, O'Neal, 48, was
an investment banker. He joined the firm in 1986 from General
Motors, where he started out working the night shift in an assembly
plant in Doraville, Ga. After graduating from the General Motors
Institute, now known as Kettering University, O'Neal won a
scholarship from the automaker to attend Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving his master's degree from Harvard, he joined the
treasury department of General Motors in New York and worked there
until he left for Merrill. In 14 years at Merrill, O'Neal has run
its junk-bond business and has been co-head of its institutional
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Komansky said that O'Neal has the qualities necessary to make
the transition from one side of the firm to the other, which he
described as ``a lot of common sense and a willingness to learn.''
But some people close to the firm questioned whether O'Neal's
buttoned-down demeanor would suit him well as he tries to rally the
firm's brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment comes as Merrill is shifting away from charging
customers commissions on all transactions toward collecting annual
fees based on how much money customers invest with the firm.
Merrill also has embraced low-commission online trading after a
bruising internal battle over whether the firm should compete
head-on with the leading online brokerage, Charles Schwab Corp.,
and a raft of low-priced competition.
</P>
<P>
   That dissension played a role in the departure of Allison, who
was in line to be the first chairman of Merrill who had not been a
broker. Komansky is the latest in a long line of Merrill leaders
who started out selling stocks and bonds to individual customers,
and he eventually informed Allison that Allison would never succeed
him.
</P>
<P>
   It was Allison, a onetime investment banker, who identified
O'Neal as a potential leader several years ago. But, unlike
Allison, who thrived as the firm's chief financial officer, O'Neal
``never wanted it in the first place,'' said a person who knows him
well. Worse, he held the job at a difficult time in 1998, when
Merrill's bond business suffered huge losses in the aftermath of
Russia's default on its national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Komansky hinted at that sentiment when he goaded O'Neal to
answer a question about how he liked the finance job, a position
that is not held in high regard on Wall Street because its holder
cannot produce any revenue or profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be honest,'' Komansky said. ``Tell him how much you liked
being CFO.''
</P>
<P>
   But, true to his character, O'Neal declined to reveal his
feelings. People who know O'Neal often describe him as a
``conservative'' man who hold his cards ``very close to the vest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not fit the persona'' of past Merrill leaders,
likeKomansky and his predecessor, Daniel Tully, said a person who
has worked closely with O'Neal. ``He's going to have to glad-hand
and make nice-nice with clients. That's going to be a challenge for
Stan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6908 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NASA-EROS-HNS &LR;      02-14 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-EROS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SPACECRAFT ORBITS EROS ASTEROID 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A NASA spacecraft on Valentine's Day maneuvered into orbit
around a distant asteroid named for the Greek god of love.
</P>
<P>
   The $224.1 million Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous, or NEAR,
spacecraft reached 433 Eros on Monday _ kicking off a yearlong,
closeup study of a rocky celestial fragment likely left over from
the formation of the solar system 4.5 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The rendezvous, which began the first orbit ever of an asteroid,
thrilled scientists at the Johns Hopkins University's Applied
Physics Laboratory in Laurel, Md., who are conducting the mission
for NASA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be Valentine's Day for most people, but it's
Christmas Eve for me, with all the presents piled up and waiting to
be opened,'' said Andrew Cheng, the NEAR mission's chief scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Photos of Eros transmitted by the probe Monday revealed a gray
realm ravaged by impacts with meteorites. Among the many craters
scientists identified was a large heart-shaped depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The asteroids include many different kinds of objects,'' Cheng
said. ``Some of them are the building blocks that the terrestrial
planets were made out of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are the fragments you get when objects the size
of planets get blown apart (by collisions with other planets),'' he
said. ``In either case, we are looking back at a time that is very
close to the beginning of the solar system, something like 4.5
billion years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Theorists believe the early sun was encircled by a disk of dust
and rubble. As time passed, the smaller material joined into larger
objects that grew more massive, broke apart and rejoined through
processes, which are still not understood.
</P>
<P>
   Eros is peanut-shaped, or as one scientist characterized it,
contoured like a banana with a bite taken from the middle. It
measures 21 miles long and 8 miles wide, or about twice the size of
Manhattan Island.
</P>
<P>
   The asteroid circles the sun 160 million miles from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   NEAR's 57-second maneuver Monday placed it into an initial
204-by-280 mile high orbit around the slowly turning asteroid, all
but right on the money, said Robert Farquhar of Johns Hopkins, the
mission manager.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks, scientists plan to gradually reduce the
separation. They are discussing the possibility near the end of the
mission of attempting a gentle landing, a kind of planetary
touch-and-go that would disclose whether Eros has a dusty or solid
surface.
</P>
<P>
   On a grander scale scientists expect to reveal whether Eros is
actually one large rock or a collection of smaller fragments
corralled together by gravity. Those findings could help humans
defend themselves against a future collision with an asteroid, like
the devastating impact of more than 60 million years ago that
struck Earth with such energy it blinded the sun long enough to
wipe out the dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understandably, the physical characteristics are really
essential to know if we are ever called upon as a society to defend
against an asteroid on a collision course with the Earth,'' said
Carl Pilcher, NASA's chief of solar system studies. ``If you hope
to deflect an asteroid on a collision course, you'd sure like to
know how that asteroid will respond to whatever force you put on
it, either with an explosion or a (gentler) impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Launched from Cape Canaveral, Fla., on a Delta expendable rocket
Feb. 17, 1996, NEAR wound its way nearly 1.9 billion miles through
the solar system to keep its appointment with Eros.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, it was to reach its destination in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   However, after a Dec. 20, 1998, engine misfire during a steering
maneuver, NEAR spun out of control and nearly exhausted its
electrical power. With only minutes of power to spare, control
teams at Johns Hopkins regained authority over the spacecraft and
plotted the celestial U-turn that set up Monday's rendezvous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk about the difficulty of space. It isn't easy,'' NASA
administrator Dan Goldin said after Monday's success.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking the agency's helm in 1992, Goldin urged the
development of a smaller and less expensive class of robotic
planetary probes. His policies came under criticism as being too
frugal in the wake of last year's losses of the Mars Polar Lander
and the Mars Climate Orbiter. Both Mars craft lost communications
with Earth as they maneuvered toward their destinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not how you deal with success,'' Goldin said. ``It's how
you deal with failure, or the potential for failure, and come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
