<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6909 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-HEALTHEON-COX     02-14 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHEON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Healtheon/WebMD buying key rival for dominance on Net
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Healtheon/WebMD Corp. on Monday took a
multibillion-dollar step toward its goal of health care dominance
on the Internet by announcing the purchase of Medical Manager
Corp., one of its main rivals for that burgeoning business.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, valued at about $5 billion worth of Healtheon/WebMD
stock, also includes CareInsite, which is 69 percent owned by New
Jersey-based Medical Manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger of these three companies represents a critical step
in the realization of our collective vision to transform the health
care industry by using the Internet to enable a more efficient and
effective health care delivery system,'' said Jeff Arnold, chief
executive of Healtheon/WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Manager has several units, but its key business is
selling software to help run doctors' offices. The company has
connections to about 455,000 physicians. CareInsite aims to link
doctors, insurers and patients who need to exchange confidential
information. Healtheon/WebMD means to use the Net to offer
professionals and companies a cheaper way to transact business,
while giving consumers a source of medical data.
</P>
<P>
   That is an ambitious goal. Health care now accounts for an
estimated 14 percent of the nation's $7 trillion-a-year economy.
With most experts agreeing that much of the paperwork in health
care is costly and wasteful, Healtheon/WebMD aims to become the
pivot point for the expected surge of transactions to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``WebMD's strategy has not been to take a giant step, but
instead has been this continuous juggernaut of deals,'' said Eric
Brown, research director for health care e-commerce at Forrester
Research. ``They are not done.'' If there remains a major gap, it
is the inability thus far of Healtheon/WebMD _ or anyone else _ to
lure doctors into regular use of computer technology, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet to most consumers is a vehicle for self-service.
However, physicians mostly don't see the need for jumping onto the
Net at work, since they are not the source of the inefficiency that
Net use might resolve, Brown said. ``Yes, the system is
inefficient, but it's efficient for the doctors. A really great
story still has to be told to the docs.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is already the sum of a series of mergers and
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, founded in Atlanta by Arnold as a company sending medical
data via fax, merged in November with Healtheon, founded by
entrepreneur Jim Clark. The combination included Atlanta-based
Greenberg Networks and Mede America.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, Healtheon/WebMD has been a maker of
deals. The company has picked up some deep-pocketed partners _
among them DuPont, Microsoft and News Corp. _ providing capital
that can be used to emblazon the company's name on everything from
hockey arena walls to television commercials to CNN spots. To
extend the reach of its business, the company has forged deals with
Eli Lilly, Medibuy.com and drugstore chain CVS, among others.
</P>
<P>
   With name recognition, the company can increasingly lure
customers. And as it gathers still more capital, Healtheon/WebMD
can fill in gaps in its business or technology by making an
investment, as it did last week with Atlanta-based InfoCure, or an
outright purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the Medical Manager announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is compelling. Although CareInsite and Healtheon/WebMD
are not yet making a profit, they represent two of the most visible
providers of Internet health care service. Hundreds of others are
out there _ including Healthgate, Medscape and DrKoop.com _ but
none has the sheer marketing muscle of Healtheon/WebMD. Adding to
that power is the use of company stock as currency to make deals.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon/WebMD stock has not returned to its stratospheric
heights of last May when it crested at $105 a share, or even its
more recent surge to $70. However, at Monday's closing price of
$56.62 1/2 per share, the company is still worth about $8.5 billion
_ more than enough to buy Medical Manager, which has more than
twice the revenue of Healtheon. And in the wake of the Monday's
announcement, several analysts upgraded the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the power of the deal could work against it.
</P>
<P>
   That is, federal regulators may view the merger as creating not
just a pre-eminent company, but a rival against whom competing is
just too costly. If regulators think the merger erects walls that
are too high for potential competitors, they might force conditions
on the merging companies _ or even stop the deal.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, health care professionals may see dominance
of one Internet company as a positive that simplifies the industry
and lets other types of providers line up behind one set of
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators will have to decide ``whether higher volumes and
lower cost and greater efficiencies of the combined network will
create such entry barriers that there will never be another
competitor,'' antitrust attorney Robert Burka told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for Arnold to remain chief executive after
the deal is consummated. Michael Long would retain the chief
operating officer job and become co-chairman with Martin Wygod,
currently chairman of Medical Manager and CareInsite.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
