<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6910 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DIALLO-TRIAL-2NDTAKE-     02-14 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-TRIAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ALBANY, N.Y.: into buildings. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to figure out what's going on, what this guy's up
to,'' he said, referring to Diallo. He would ``peek out,'' then
``slink back,'' he said. Carroll said he also thought Diallo might
have been a lookout for a ``push-in robber,'' who would push his
way into an apartment and, possibly, attack or murder someone
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he and McMellon were the first to approach Diallo.
Carroll testified that as Diallo stood in the vestibule and the
officers were outside on the sidewalk, McMellon displayed his badge
and said: ``Sir, please, New York police. We need a word with
you.'' Then, again, McMellon said, ``Please hold it one second. We
need a word with you,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said Diallo then turned away ``as if he wanted to shield
from my view what he might have'' under his jacket. ``I said,
`Police. We want a word with you,''' the officer testified. Diallo
started digging into his pocket with his right hand. ``I heard
Officer McMellon say, `Please show me your hands,''' Carroll said.
Diallo, he said, just didn't want to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, things happened quickly. Diallo seemed to be pulling
an object from his pocket, ``and all I could see was the top slide
of a black gun,'' Carroll said. ``I just said, `Gun. He's got a
gun.'''
</P>
<P>
   Diallo was pointing the ``gun'' at McMellon, who said, ``What
are you doing? What are you doing?'' Carroll said. He said he
thought McMellon had been shot. In fact, he had backed out of the
building and fallen down the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there was rapid gunfire and, Carroll said, it
appeared that muzzle blasts were coming from Diallo's weapon.
Despite being hit by a number of shots, Diallo remained standing,
he said, adding that he thought Diallo must be wearing a
bulletproof vest. Then he began firing at Diallo's legs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although everything seemed like it was going in slow motion,
it was all over in seconds,'' Carroll said. After the shooting
ended and Diallo was on the floor, Carroll grabbed the black object
in the man's hand and realized it was a wallet.
</P>
<P>
   McMellon told a similar story, adding that when the shooting
started he tried to back out of the vestibule ``because I didn't
want to die.'' He fell down the stairs, and continued shooting from
the ground, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither officer would say who fired the first shot. Each said
they were not sure.
</P>
<P>
   Single and 27 years old, McMellon grew up in the Park Slope
section of Brooklyn and attended high school at the School of
Performing Arts. He attended college for several years and joined
the police department in 1993.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Monday, lawyers for the officers recalled Schrrie Elliott, a
witness they had called last week, but who surprised them with
damaging statements about the officers. Having had her declared a
hostile witness, the lawyers were able to cross-examine her about
contradictory statements she had made in the past about the
shooting. She had said that she witnessed it, and that she had
heard one of the officers shout, ``Gun!'' But she also said they
got out of their cars with their guns drawn and never gave Diallo
any warnings.
</P>
