<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ALASKA-CRASH-NYT &LR;      02-14 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIL SCREW SEEN AS CULPRIT IN CONTROLLING ALASKA JET  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An investigator at the National Transportation
Safety Board said Monday that experts at the agency were
increasingly convinced that a screw in the tail of an Alaska
Airlines jet was damaged before the plane crashed, and was a factor
in problems controlling the aircraft just before it went down in
the Pacific Ocean last month.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators had been seeking to determine whether the damage
to the part was a cause of the crash, or a result. The comments
Monday came as the airline made an unusual public reply to
questions of whether the part had been properly maintained.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development Monday, the Federal Aviation
Administration said that two airplanes, one at Delta and one at
AirTran, formerly known as ValuJet, had failed a test that measures
wear in that part.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of other planes are to undergo that test in the next 30
days. So far visual inspections have isolated 21 planes with
``positive findings,'' ranging from metallic grit in the grease,
which may be a sign of normal wear, to shavings, which are not.
</P>
<P>
   Under scrutiny is the jackscrew, similar to the screw that
drives a garage door, only shorter and thicker, and a nut that
rides up and down the screw as it turns to raise and lower part of
the tail called the horizontal stabilizer. The horizontal
stabilizer makes the nose of the plane point up or down.
</P>
<P>
   When the screw was recovered by the Navy off the coast of Los
Angeles after the July 31 crash, it was partly wrapped in metal
ribbon, apparently stripped off from the nut.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator said Monday that if the damage had occurred in
the crash itself, it would have been more localized _ confined to
the area where the nut had rested on the screw.
</P>
<P>
   The crew reported to mechanics on the ground that they could not
control the horizontal stabilizer. The final cause of the crash,
which killed all 88 aboard, is less clear, however, since
investigators have determined from the flight data recorder, also
recovered from the ocean, that after the stabilizer flipped to a
full nose-down position, the crew regained control and flew on,
experimenting with lowering the flaps and making preparations for
landing.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday evening, James E. Hall, the board chairman, released a
statement saying that when the screw and nut were last inspected in
September 1997, it was measured as having the maximum allowable
amount of play, and that the initial plan was to replace it.
Keeping the nut still and seeing how far the jackscrew will wiggle
is the approved method for looking for wear in the mechanism. But
the airline re-checked five times and found that the play was well
within tolerances, the safety board said.
</P>
<P>
   But the airline said that the first measurement showed play at
forty-thousandths of an inch, which is at the allowable limit, and
that subsequent measurements showed it was at 33 thousandths of an
inch, well within the limit. The MD-80 maintenance manual, drafted
by Boeing, adopted by Alaska Airlines and approved by the FAA, says
that the test should be repeated ``several times to ensure
consistent results,'' the airline pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You check and re-check and recheck,'' said Louis Cancelmi, a
spokesman for the airline, which is based in Seattle. ``That's what
aviation is about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other maintenance experts, with long experience at other
airlines, said it would not be unusual to send a second mechanic
and inspector to re-measure a part if fine tolerances were
involved. ``I would have a second set of eyes,'' said a maintenance
director at another major airline.
</P>
<P>
   The part, which is sold as a combination jackscrew and nut,
sells for $57,000, according to an airline that flies more than 100
planes that use them. But it seldom requires replacement, according
to a spokesman for that airline, who asked that he and his company
not be named. He said that in the last 20 years, the company had
replaced only three.
</P>
<P>
   Other maintenance experts suggested that if an airline was
seeking to cut corners, time would have been a bigger factor than
money, if locating a replacement would delay the plane's return to
revenue service.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive wear in the jackscrew or nut could make the weight of
the tail rest on less and less metal surface, eventually leading to
the nut stripping, according to experts. The screw is a hard steel,
but the nut is a softer material, an alloy of aluminum, nickel and
bronze, according to Mark Silk, president of Trig Holding Inc., the
manufacturer. The reason is that if both parts were steel, they
would not move smoothly against each other, according to
metallurgists.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the FAA said Monday that it might not have a full
count of problems with jackscrews until the middle of this week.
Last week when the agency ordered the visual inspections within
three days, it also ordered tests to measure play, within 30 days,
although some airlines, to save time, did both at once.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA also shortened the interval between play tests, to three
months from eight. One issue that the crash raises, according to
experts, is whether to test more frequently, or to base the test
interval on the amount of play observed in each test.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 2109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000214.0499 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6915 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      02-14 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
 THIS STORY ALSO MOVING IN THE ``E'' CATEGORY 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``COLORS OF THE MOUNTAIN'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Da Chen (Random House, $25)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is that rarity in these times, a truly marvelous book. Da
Chen was born in 1962, in a tiny town in southern China, and his
memoir begins with his childhood stories of life during the
Cultural Revolution. Chen's grandfather had been a wealthy
landlord, reason enough to incur relentless mistreatment for him
and his family (he lived with Chen's parents and their five
children), as well as the loss of their house, land and most
possessions. Food was scarce, humiliation was waiting around every
corner, and the future seemed without promise. And yet, the view
through young Chen's eyes is remarkably cheerful, made so by his
curiosity and pugnacity and by his parents' enduring dignity in the
face of their dreadfully altered lives. This big-hearted and
sometimes even humorous story is written in simple, evocative
prose, and it ends as Chen leaves for college in Beijing. It's a
moving moment, but not the book's first _ we were misty before we
got past the dedication. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE BRETHREN'' &QL; 
 &UR; By John Grisham (Doubleday, $27.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to mock a rich man, but we must give Grisham credit:
He doesn't take the advance and run. His new novel is inventive and
unpredictable, and very different from any of his previous books.
It focuses on three judges who are incarcerated in a
minimum-security prison for sins ranging from tax evasion to
driving drunkenly over two hikers in Yellowstone. In jail, they
preside over a ``court'' in which inmates file grievances against
each other (witnesses are expected to lie, and verdicts are quick
and without appeal). The judges also run a mail scheme in which
they pose as young, nubile inmates, bait wealthy men on the
outside, then blackmail them for the gay sex talk in their letters.
Trouble brews when they target Aaron Lake, U.S. congressman from
Arizona and the presidential candidate backed by the powerful
director of the CIA. Everyone's sleazy here, and the efforts at
damage control are complex and entertaining. When this one lands on
the bestseller lists, the honor will be deserved.  &QL; 
 &UR; ``MATCH WITS WITH MENSA'' &QL; 
 &UR; (Perseus, $19.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We have found our omnipotence, and it is in vocabulary _ we will
stomp all challengers into the ground. It was the only subject in
this book at which we showed any prowess, but thank God there was
something. The editors say they have assembled more than 800
puzzles. We were struck by the inordinate amount of yakking that
precedes them. You must wade through much discussion of a category
_ trivia, analogies, logic etc. _ and a sometimes lengthy list of
acknowledgments before you get to the tests themselves, which makes
us think that Mensa members need rest between bouts of mental
exertion. We were also struck by how much Mensa members _ to be
one, you must score in the top two percent of the population on any
standard intelligence test _ like to look at themselves in the
mental mirror. But we digress. Here is what the editors consider to
be a ``warm-up'' trivia question: ``Domenikos Theotocopoulus is
better known as who?'' The answer is El Greco, the painter. We
looked it up.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE WHITE DEATH'' &QL; 
 &UR; By McKay Jenkins (Random House, $23.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins calls John McPhee his mentor, and you can see McPhee's
influence in the way Jenkins comes at his subject _ avalanches _
from all sides. His main path is the story of five young climbers
who died in an avalanche on Mount Cleveland in Montana's Glacier
National Park in 1969. He mixes the personal stories of those young
men with fascinating information about snow, mountains, rescues and
survival. He shows us how terrifying it is to be caught under snow,
not knowing which way is up (the only way to tell, he says, is to
spit _ whichever way it falls, you should dig, if you can move, in
the opposite direction), how you increase your chances for survival
if you remember to shut your mouth (many victims are found with
their mouths full of snow), how your chances plummet if you are not
rescued within minutes. Dogs have found people alive in 15 feet of
snow, sniffing them out by their individual scents. Each living
person smells different, Jenkins says. All corpses smell the same.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
