<SLUG> BC-MAYTAG-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYTAG SHARES FALL ON NEWS OF LOWER EARNING EXPECTATIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan, Wash., Ill.)  By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Shares of the Maytag Corp., the giant appliance maker,
fell sharply Monday after the company warned that earnings this
year would not meet Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which makes everything from Magic Chef oven ranges
and refrigerators to Hoover vacuum cleaners, said first quarter
earnings could be down 10 percent from a year ago because of fierce
competition in the market for home applicances and weaker than
expected sales of its soft drink vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   The warning was the second in three quarters for Maytag, which
sharply reduced its earnings forecast for the third quarter of
1999, blaming weaker sales of its low-cost home appliances.
</P>
<P>
   The first warning sent shares of Maytag tumbling. After reaching
a high of $74 last May, shares fell to about $31.25 a share in
October, partly because it came shortly after Maytag officials had
assured Wall Street that profit growth was on track. Maytag shares
later climbed to about $50 a share through early this year partly
because of a strong fourth-quarter profit. But in the past few
weeks, the company's shares have tumbled again.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, shares of Maytag dropped $3.875, to close at $32.50, on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag advised Wall Street analysts to drop their year 2000
forecasts to the lower end of the $3.80 to $4.00 range. They did.
Nicholas P. Heymann, an analyst at Prudential Securities, revised
his earnings downward to $3.60 a share from $4.00. Russell Leavitt
of Banc of America Securities changed to $3.75 from $4.00.
</P>
<P>
   The company is going through a rough period, the analysts say,
and the stock price reflects that. But several analysts said the
company is expected to recover, if not later this year, perhaps
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some choppy air in earnings,'' Heymann said. ``We've
lost a year's worth of earnings growth this year. But the company
is in good shape, it generates lots of cash; but it needs some
things straightened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Maytag officials say they are moving in that direction. The
slowdown will not disrupt plans to introduce a new line of
innovative products, executives say. The company says it is
preparing for a time in the near future when home appliances are
smarter and perhaps even connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There is an alliance with Microsoft that could lead to smart
appliances and a partnership with the Sanyo Electric Co. of Japan
to develop more efficient home appliances. In the second half of
the year, the company projects a pickup in business, with earnings
climbing 15 to 20 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The current slowdown, company officials say, is tied largely to
the company's Dixie-Narco vending machines, which are supplied to
Coca-Cola and PepsiCo among other soft drink companies. Maytag said
orders were down sharply and a recovery might not come until early
next year. The company also said its Hoover vacuum business had
weakened because of stiff competition for bagless, upright vacuums.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag's line of Neptune and Performa washing machines and
Gemini oven ranges, however, continue to sell briskly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
