<HEADER>
A6919 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-HAWKS-COX     02-14 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So far, changes going nowhere
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ And now, we return to ``The Season of the Lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost, as in playoff opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Lost, as in player commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Lost, as in direction and hope and motivation.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks are 47 miles into an 82-mile journey, already
dangerously low on fuel, almost out of coolant. The 13 occupants
don't know each other well and don't play well together.
</P>
<P>
   The driver hasn't exactly lost control. The most obstreperous
passenger just tunes him out; the others nod and go their separate
ways.
</P>
<P>
   This season has been a disaster for the Hawks. Maybe there's a
payoff down the line. Isn't that why team president Stan Kasten and
General Manager Pete Babcock, even coach Lenny Wilkens, agreed to
dump the team's strong, veteran presence and take a lower road?
</P>
<P>
   None of the reasons for losing Steve Smith, Mookie Blaylock,
Grant Long and Ty Corbin has changed. In their advancing years,
they were only going to go so far, and they were going to stop far
short of a championship.
</P>
<P>
   But change didn't have to mean half-hearted effort and a stodgy
offense damaged by half-hearted defensive play.
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando Magic, which followed a similar plan, is two games
below .500 and 3 1/2 games better than the Hawks. Showing the
benefits of hiring diverse players who are fighting for new
contracts, they are gritty fighters under Doc Rivers. Even after an
eight-game losing streak, the Magic is right there in the fight for
a 4-8 seeding. The team has no hidden agendas.
</P>
<P>
   The same cannot be said about the Hawks. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dikembe Mutombo, first in the NBA in rebounding, second in
shooting percentage, third in blocked shots, is having a stellar
season while disowning his new teammates. ``I didn't make these
changes,'' Mutombo said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Alan Henderson has regained his competitive edge and sometimes
turns it into blind rage. Woe to the referee who misses a call.
Five technicals so far and a whisker away from at least one
ejection. Henderson, who has a strong move to the basket, is a
power forward who would rather shoot jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  J.R. Rider is strangling on his own game. See him come off a
screen. Fake the open shot. Stop. Look. Dribble. Wait for the
double team. Fire the fadeaway. Amble back on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want to shoot unless there's a strong degree of
difficulty,'' analyst Steve Jones said from the vantage point of
one who watched Rider almost daily for three years in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers for the team's leading scorer have dropped off
precipitously. Since peaking a dozen agames ago at 23.5 points per
game, .429 from the field and .796 from the line, Rider has
averaged 18 points and shot .387 from the field and .760 from the
line. Despite the drop off at the line, Rider shoots technicals,
ahead of Jim Jackson, No. 7 in the league at .871.
</P>
<P>
   Is this season Mutombo's fault, because he disdains the
newcomers? Or Henderson's, because his ego and temper get in the
way of what was once a strong supporting role? Or Rider's, because
he has not responded to Wilkens' patient, non-confrontational
handling?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. The emotional Mutombo relied on Blaylock to
complement his defensive skills, on Smith for emotional support and
a sound game and on Long for his selfless inside play.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson labors under the delusion that as a senior man the
stature of prime-time player is his due.
</P>
<P>
   And Rider is the same guy who drove them crazy in Portland, and
before that in Minnesota, with a few rough edges smoothed away. Do
we blame LaPhonso Ellis, whose body has broken down so often he no
longer wants to take the punishment inside where he once excelled?
Or Bimbo Coles, who plays to his limits, or Jason Terry, who needs
to grow up as a pro, or Jackson, who is better than advertised but
is a guard, not a full-time small forward?
</P>
<P>
   Do we blame Wilkens, who was handed the keys and told to drive?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Babcock takes the hit; he made the deals. Or Kasten; he
approved them. Or the bosses who trust them to do the right thing.
Didn't they say there would be no drop off in talent? Didn't we
believe it?
</P>
<P>
   Blame everybody: There's enough to go around. Meanwhile, we will
have to wait to see if there was anything to Kasten's threat to
dismantle this team by the Feb. 24 trade deadline. We also will
have to see if the Hawks draw one through eight in the lottery and
keep the draft pick that otherwise goes to the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, like Wilkens, we wait to see who is invited to camp in
October or how the Hawks handle the big chunk of salary-cap room
they will get in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Wait is all we can do.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA HAWKS AT MIDSEASON
</P>
<P>
   Grades are based on how well each player has performed to his
potential.
</P>
<P>
   B+
</P>
<P>
   Dikembe Mutombo
</P>
<P>
   Near-heroic performance with scant help. Has vastly improved
offensive skills.
</P>
<P>
   B-
</P>
<P>
   Bimbo Coles
</P>
<P>
   Plays to highest level nearly every night. Now is a fine
open-court shooter.
</P>
<P>
   B-
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jackson
</P>
<P>
   Insurance policy became a starter, but is out of position;
turnover prone.
</P>
<P>
   C
</P>
<P>
   Alan Henderson
</P>
<P>
   Too many jump shots and temper tantrums. Suffers a power
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   D
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Rider
</P>
<P>
   He's not ``the man'' _ too many sulks; his offensive game is in
steady decline.
</P>
<P>
   C+
</P>
<P>
   coach Lenny Wilkens
</P>
<P>
   He can still teach, but this bunch needs the hickory stick he
doesn't carry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
