A6920 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-UGA-GIBBS-COX     02-14 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-GIBBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New UGA coach soured on Oklahoma
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Gary Gibbs resigned as head coach at Oklahoma in
1994, he sounded like someone who wanted no more of coaching _
ever. One couldn't blame him.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, a linebacker on Oklahoma's 1974 national championship
team, had inherited a troubled program from Barry Switzer, who was
forced to resign in 1989. Oklahoma was on NCAA probation, which
included a two-year postseason ban. Many Sooners players spent more
time on the police blotter than in the sports pages. Gibbs called
the place ``a hell hole'' when he took over.
</P>
<P>
   He posted six winning seasons in a row and made three bowl
trips, but it wasn't enough. The Sooners were 2-14-1 against their
three biggest rivals _ Texas, Colorado and Nebraska _ and were no
longer national contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs cleaned up the program and kept winning. But the fans
wanted Switzer, warts and all, and they weren't bashful about
saying it. After a 1992 loss to Texas, Gibbs was doused with beer
from angry fans.
</P>
<P>
   When the harassment trickled to his family _ his two daughters
were 13 and 10 at the time _ Gibbs announced his resignation on the
Monday before the 1994 regular-season finale with Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my family started asking me why they and I were being
harassed and insulted and our coaches were not being appreciated, I
started asking myself some tough questions,'' Gibbs said at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs left football and went into private business. He tried
insurance. He worked with Nebraska coach Tom Osborne making
instructional videos, and said he missed working with players and
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Friends would ask whether he was ever going to return to college
football. Gibbs wondered the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty good football coach and I certainly know more
about X's and O's than I did about insurance,'' Gibbs said. ``Deep
down, I knew I would get back into it. I just didn't know when.''
</P>
<P>
   That time came Sunday night when Gibbs accepted Jim Donnan's
offer to become the defensive coordinator at Georgia. They had
worked together as coordinators at Oklahoma from 1985-88. When
Gibbs became head coach, Donnan remained as his offensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia position is the first coaching job that Gibbs even
considered since he left Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a great opportunity to work with a guy I like and
respect,'' Gibbs said. ``It was just too good to pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming head coach, Gibbs was Oklahoma's defensive
coordinator for eight years (1981-88). From 1984-87, Oklahoma
finished first nationally in total defense three times and second
once.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs says five years away from the game have not dulled his
skills. If anything, the time off has made him hungry again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had confidence in my ability, and now I get a
chance to return in one of the great programs in the country,'' he
said. ``I can't wait to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   THE GARY GIBBS FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: Aug. 13, 1952, in Beaumont, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  College: Oklahoma (1971-74); linebacker on 1974 national
championship team.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coaching: 1975-80, assistant at Oklahoma; 1981-88, defensive
coordinator at Oklahoma; 1989-94, head coach at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Record: 44-23-1, three bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Personal: Wife, Jeanne; daughters, Whitley, a freshman at OU,
and Jordan, a sophomore at a high school in Norman, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
