<HEADLINE>
NEW AUTO WORKERS, NOW WITH WHITE COLLARS, TRANSFORM MICHIGAN'S
POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, Mich. _ The popular perception that Michigan elections are
still dominated by legions of auto workers toting lunch pails is as
dated as a Chevrolet Citation.
</P>
<P>
   Here, as in New Hampshire and South Carolina, a new economy, in
which auto workers wear white collars, has generated a new
electorate, whose party affiliations are loose and whose votes are
hard to predict. Those voters have already helped change Michigan
politics in recent years, and, according to the latest polls, they
could be crucial in determining who wins the state's Republican
presidential primary next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The new, high-tech professionals are people like Joel Gibson, a
26-year-old car-engine software designer, whose father, grandfather
and great-grandmother were all auto factory workers and staunch
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lean Republican, but I like to look at each individual
candidate,'' said Gibson, who said he likes former Sen. Bill
Bradley and Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The new workers tend to vote Republican in state and local
elections, but they have proved unpredictable in contests for
national office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may identify themselves as Republicans, but when they
pull that curtain, the independent streak kicks in, much to my
chagrin,'' said one Republican officerholder, L. Brooks Patterson,
the Oakland County executive.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson knows those voters well, because it is here in Oakland
County, in Detroit's northwestern suburbs, that they tend to make
their homes. Macomb County, which lies along Oakland's eastern
boundary and is characterized by strip malls and small ranch-style
houses, remains the home of the so-called Reagan Democrats _ union
workers attracted to the Republicans' appeal to traditional values.
But Oakland County has dozens of auto engineering centers that have
sprung up in rows of new, tinted-glass office towers as starkly
anonymous as any in Silicon Valley, and tens of thousands of the
new workers live here.
</P>
<P>
   Dotted with small lakes surrounded by beautiful homes,
crisscrossed by freeways increasingly lined by those engineering
centers, Oakland County has 1.2 million people and is growing twice
as fast as Macomb County, with a population of 770,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland is where many of these people live, and is going to be
a battleground going into the future,'' said Jennifer Granholm, a
Democrat who was elected the state's attorney general in 1998
partly by doing well in the county.
</P>
<P>
   Granholm is a fairly recent arrival, having grown up in San
Francisco. Other recent arrivals, including many engineers, have
more than offset the constant stream of retirees moving South and
have raised the state's population to almost 10 million, from 9.3
million people in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and pollsters from across the political spectrum
give similar descriptions of the new workers: conservative on
economic issues, particularly in their skepticism about government
regulation, but moderate on social policy. They have helped
Republicans take control of both houses of the state Legislature as
well as the governor's mansion. But the new workers have also been
willing to vote for Democrats in national elections: Bill Clinton
beat former Sen. Bob Dole in Oakland County in 1996, and nearly
beat President George Bush in 1992. That inclination has
increasingly made them the swing voters in a state that is among
the nation's most evenly divided between Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the ones who come across and vote for the Democrats
who win in Michigan,'' said Robert Teeter, a Republican pollster in
Ann Arbor, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   But while Macomb County, characterized by strip malls and small,
ranch-style houses, remains the home of the so-called Reagan
Democrats _ union workers attracted to the Republicans' appeal to
traditional values _ the changing face of the work force has
brought a changing face to the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The number of unionized industrial workers as a proportion of
all voters in the state has dropped by nearly half in the last two
decades, to etween 6 and 9 percent, pollsters say.
</P>
<P>
   Auto production remains the state's dominant industry, but
automakers and auto parts companies are changing the way they do
business. For instance, while much of the actual manufacturing has
either been automated or moved to Southern states and overseas, to
take advantage of lower wages elsewhere, all but eight of the
nation's 200 auto parts engineering centers are now in Michigan,
instead of being scattered across the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of the growth in the tech jobs has really been
pretty profound and probably better than a lot of other parts of
the country,'' said G. Richard Wagoner Jr., president of General
Motors. ``It has changed the profile of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's long economic expansion has been particularly good
to the highly cyclical auto industry, like a prolonged return to
the early 1960s, before automakers' profits were crippled by
foreign competition and, arguably, government safety and
environmental regulations. The arts are flourishing in Detroit,
with the opening of a cavernous opera house and the restoration of
a magnificent symphony hall. Housing prices have been rising faster
across this metropolitan area than almost anywhere else in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   An acute shortage of skilled labor has kept Michigan's
unemployment rate below the national average since 1995. The
state's rate was just 3.6 percent in December, and the state plans
to start spending as much advertising for engineers to move here as
it previously spent to persuade businesses to relocate here.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's shift in employment toward white-collar jobs has
occurred on a massive scale. The number of unionized auto workers
in Michigan has plunged to fewer than 250,000 from 479,000 in 1980.
But total employment in the auto industry, the state says, has only
inched down to 471,000 from 507,000 two decades ago, and actually
grew in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
