<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MICH-PRIMARY-2NDTAKE-     02-14 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-PRIMARY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TROY, Mich.: state government. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Pontiac, several miles west of here, GM recently gutted and
remodeled two assembly plants with the combined floor space of the
Empire State Building, turning them into offices and laboratories
for 8,500 engineers.
</P>
<P>
   GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler can afford such grandiose
undertakings: They were the world's three largest companies in
1998, in terms of sales and share of global economic output. While
rising oil prices may have moved the Exxon Mobil Corp. into the
lead since then, auto companies continue to dwarf the rest of
corporate America. The nation's total retail sales of all products
over the Internet last year are estimated at $10 billion to $15
billion, but Americans buy $15 billion a year worth of GM's
Chevrolet Silverado pickups alone.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide poll a week ago by The Detroit Free Press found that
Gov. George W. Bush and McCain were evenly matched if Democrats and
independents voted in the Republican primary in fairly large
numbers, while Bush was ahead among registered Republicans. The
poll also showed that McCain enjoyed a sizable advantage in Macomb
County, partly because of Reagan Democrats, while Bush commanded
strong support in western Michigan, where abortion opponents are
numerous and active and have been leery of the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland County was a toss-up when Democrats and independents
were included, while Bush prevailed among only Republicans, the
poll showed.
</P>
<P>
   One issue on which Bush could ultimately prove vulnerable here
is government regulation. Michigan Republicans regularly deride
Gore for saying in his book, ``Earth in the Balance,'' that the
contribution to global warming from automobiles with
internal-combustion engines is ``a mortal threat to the security of
every nation that is more deadly than that of any military enemy we
are ever again likely to confront.'' The Republicans are eager to
attack Gore on the issue should he win the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But whether they would be able to do so with Bush as the
Republican nominee is uncertain. Criticized last autumn by
environmentalists in New England television advertisements, Bush
announced in New Hampshire last December that he had asked Texas
regulators to consider adopting California's new auto pollution
rules, which are stricter than the federal government's and are
particularly tough on high-profit sport utility vehicles and pickup
trucks. The regulators held hearings on the idea during the week of
the New Hampshire primary, and the conservative Detroit News sent a
reporter to Texas to cover them. The resulting story emphasized
that GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler sold 90 percent of the sport
utilities and pickup trucks in Texas, and ran under a big headline,
``Bush Cleanup Plan to Cut Truck Sales.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond environmental regulation lies the broader landscape
of a changing work force and changing politics here. Dwayne F.
Davidson, a 41-year-old GM manager, is a Republican leaning toward
Bush, trusting him to keep government small. Davidson said he
agreed on few political issues with his father, a lifelong Democrat
who spent 30 years welding car body panels in the same giant
building in Pontiac where the son now oversees the design of sport
utility vehicles and pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hung out with Republicans, I golf with Republicans,''
Davidson said, ``It has kind of rubbed off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
