<HEADLINE>
ONLINE CHATS MAY POINT TO SUSPECTS IN WEB-SITE ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Canada)  (mk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF and SARA ROBINSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Evidence fueling the hunt for suspects in the
recent attacks on leading Web sites may have been found in a set of
online conversations secretly monitored by computer security
experts before and during the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The conversations were recorded by security experts at Stanford
University and at Kroll-O'Gara, a computer consulting firm, from an
online chat system known as Internet Relay Chat. The system is
widely used by computer hobbyists and is frequently used for
anonymous communications between computer criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Five pieces of independent evidence including the intercepted
conversations point to one possible suspect, according to David
Brumley, a computer security officer at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   A network of computers at a Stanford-run oceanographic research
laboratory in Monterey, Calif., was among those used by outsiders
to relay at stream of data that overwhelmed eBay, the Internet
auction site, for several hours last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have four or five pieces of independent evidence that are
leading toward one person,'' said Brumley, ``and we give the FBI
every piece of evidence we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Brumley said he had intercepted a conversation in which the
suspect had asked his friends to name a site ``they really hated''
so he could attack it.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect's friends replied, ``eBay,'' Brumley said, and about
30 minutes later ``eBay went down.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had gathered other information pinpointing the city
in which the suspect resides. He would not name the city but said
he had given that and other information to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing in the chats is someone saying something is
going to happen, and then it happens,'' Brumley added.
</P>
<P>
   Even before last week's attacks, security experts like Brumley
were routinely capturing and archiving conversations on chat
channels with the purpose of saving the information so it can be
correlated against other data in tracking computer criminals.
</P>
<P>
   A Kroll-O'Gara computer security consultant, Joel de la Garza,
said data recorded in the Stanford case indicated that the
individual is a high school dropout who is self-taught in computer
programming and has developed relatively advanced programming
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the recorded conversations come from a chat channel
named ``goonies.'' The channel, which permits a number of computer
users to share a typed conversation, has been a cyberspace hangout
for young computer vandals involved in a variety of illicit
activities. Last week, after the channel was identified to
reporters and some computer security experts, it was closed to
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the suspect who has been tracked through chat
conversations, a second person with the Internet handle Mafiaboy
has become a subject of suspicion after claiming responsibility for
some attacks. That person has been tracked by computer security
experts for several years and they believe he lives in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   But Brumley down Mafiaboy's role, saying, ``We're not
sure how much hard evidence there is.''
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of Mafiaboy and the other suspect described by
Brumley was reported Monday in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Since the attacks, computer security experts who monitor the
computer underground said, there have been many such claims of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the focus on evidence unearthed at Stanford may be
unwarranted; law enforcement officials cautioned Monday that they
are not making public or private statements about their criminal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are saying a lot of things, and I'm not sure
if anyone has a complete picture,'' said an FBI agent, who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   One reason it may be particularly difficult to find the
perpetrators of last week's high-profile incidents is that the type
of attack, known as denial of service, is a frequent occurrence on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, before the attack on Yahoo, eBay and others, computer
administrators at the University of California at Berkeley said the
school's network had been under a similar attack beginning on
Friday, Feb. 4, and lasting through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Another short-lived attack was reported against Nextcard, the
Internet credit card company, for two hours on Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   And the Canadian-based site for HMV, the record chain, said
Monday that it had been temporarily disabled on Feb. 7, the same
day as the attack on Yahoo, by a similar onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been attacks like this in the past, just not at
this kind of level,'' said Rose Klimovich, director of Global IP
Network Services at AT&AMP;T. ``What it has done is heightened people's
awareness across the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday President Clinton plans to meet at the White House
with as many as two dozen executives of computer and Internet
companies to develop strategies to combat computer crime. In
addition to the president, Commerce Secretary William Daley; the
president's chief of staff, John Podesta, and the national security
adviser, Sandy Berger, are expected to attend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
