<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-STORM-HUMAN-COX     02-14 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-HUMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harrell family one of many affected by tornado
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Ga. _ At Sunday night church, Vickie Gainous couldn't
help but be distracted by 18-month-old Kylie Rae Harrell.
</P>
<P>
   ``That baby looked so pretty in her blue denim dress,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   At noontime Monday, Gainous was retrieving that same dress from
a field where the baby and her mother Shannon were hurled to their
deaths by the tornado that swept throughout southwest Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Gainous and the other sorrowful gleaners, friends of the
Harrells, stepped through the muck along rows of kale and collards
to salvage pieces of the family's possessions. The Harrells' mobile
home had been blown to the far end of the field, a good 500 yards
from the spot beside Ridge Road where it had been anchored to its
cinder block foundation. The field of greens was littered with
small shreds of shattered dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Death claimed half the Harrell family. Todd Harrell, 32, and his
stepdaughter Brittany, 11, survived with minor injuries and were in
stable condition Monday evening in a Cairo hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we know we had two miracles,'' said Annette Harrell,
Todd Harrell's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Of her daughter-in-law, she said: ``She loved her children with
all her heart. She and Todd put their marriage ahead of everything
else but the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day before they died, she said, Shannon Harrell took the
baby to get photo portraits made. The little girl was wearing the
blue denim dress.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Harrell said his son, from his hospital bed, was able to
tell him about the night of the twister.
</P>
<P>
   About 1 a.m., Todd Harrell said, he phoned a friend and told him
he and his family were getting ready to flee their home. But as
soon as he opened the front door, he was hit by overwhelming wind
pressure. All he could do was get back to his family and try to lie
down on the hall floor.
</P>
<P>
   He could feel the wind pull the mobile home from its
underpinnings, but he blacked out as the trailer broke loose and
started tumbling across the field.
</P>
<P>
   Once the storm had passed, he regained consciousness and was
able to find Brittany and make it to a neighbor's home, which had
suffered only roof damage. In the dark and rain, no one could spot
Shannon Harrell and the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Friends arrived, loaded Todd Harrell and Brittany into their
trucks and rushed them to the hospital in Cairo, about five miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   By late morning, all that could be done was for friends from the
Harrells' church, Pine Level Baptist, to come to the obliterated
home site and try to find salvagable scraps _ and to talk about
their devastated neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a lot of faith. They trusted in God for everything,''
said Duane Davis, who works with Todd Harrell at a farm credit
agency in Camilla.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who lives nearby, said he came to help search in the
middle of the night. He was one of the searchers who came upon the
baby's body in the field, lying near part of a broken water heater.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday morning, Davis went to the hospital to tell
Brittany that Cody, the family's Labrador retriever, was safe. The
dog had come to Davis' home before the storm hit.
</P>
<P>
   In the daylight hours, Davis' wife, Voncille, scoured the field,
looking for quilts and baby blankets made by Todd's grandmother.
She said today was to have been a special day for Todd and Shannon
Harrell.
</P>
<P>
   Todd was leaving the agency in Camilla for a job in Florida, and
his last day in the office was to be Wednesday. His co-workers were
planning a farewell luncheon for him today.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon had planned to go into town today and use a gift
certificate Todd had given her for a massage at a health spa, prior
to joining him for the luncheon. Voncille Davis had been looking
forward to babysitting Kylie Ray for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Belinda Smith said her friend Shannon was taking classes on the
Internet, working toward a certificate in medical administration,
until she got pregnant with Kylie Rae.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the Harrells' family life was centered around
their church. Todd serves as a lay minister in the Royal Ambassador
program, working with young boys in the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, who worked with the same program when Todd was a
boy, said knowing the depth of the couple's faith is helping her
endure the pain of the loss of her granddaughter and
daughter-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine the pain of any parent being in a hospital
waiting room like this and not knowing the condition of their
child's heart,'' she said. ``I know Shannon was a Christian, and
that can get you through anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd and Shannon Harrell apparently let anyone who visited their
home see their faith on display. One of the few things their
friends salvaged intact was an afghan embroidered with a Biblical
verse.
</P>
<P>
   Draped over a twisted piece of irrigation pipe in thefield, the
verse, I Corinthians 13, reads: ``Love bears all things, believes
all things, hopes all things, endures all things.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
