<SLUG> BC-DOUBLECLICK-DOUBLECLICK </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 DoubleClick, Under Fire, Vows to Shut Doors on Online Marketers  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Bowing to concerns by privacy advocates, Internet advertising
company DoubleClick Inc. yesterday announced steps to help
consumers ``opt out'' of having their personal data used for online
marketing.
<P>
   But consumer watchdogs were unimpressed. ``It's an empty
promise,'' said David Sobel, general counsel of the Electronic
Privacy Information Center in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for New York's DoubleClick, the largest
advertising network. The FTC has vowed to regulate online marketers
if they don't adequately address privacy concerns. Last week, EPIC
sent a letter to the Federal Trade Commission accusing DoubleClick
of ``unfair and deceptive business practices.''
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick, the largest Web ad manager, sends banner ads to a
network of 1,500 sites. By attaching ``cookies'' to a computer
user's hard drive, DoubleClick creates anonymous user profiles
based on which ads the Web surfer has seen and clicked on.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, DoubleClick came under fire for linking that online
behavioral data with information obtained from catalog companies,
which includes names, addresses, and purchase information of
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, DoubleClick ran ads in the New York Times, San Jose
Mercury News, Washington Post and Roll Call, a newspaper about
Capitol Hill, to convince both consumers and policymakers that it
is committed to privacy.
</P>
<P>
   It also will send out 50 million banner ads with the goal of
reaching ``slightly more than half'' of the United States' 80
million to 90 million Web users, said Kevin Ryan, DoubleClick's
president, in a telephone interview yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, which will cost DoubleClick more than $1 million,
direct consumers to a DoubleClick a Web site, privacychoices.org.
There, computer users can ask the company to stop tracking their
online behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But Sobel said surfers are unlikely to respond to the ads
because most have no idea that DoubleClick sends them the ads they
see as the traverse the Web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``People who go looking for this type of information read the
privacy policies on the sites they visit, like CNN.com or
whatever,'' said Sobel. ``That doesn't work with DoubleClick
because their collection of information is invisible to the user.''
</P>
<P>
   EPIC does not object to DoubleClick tracking online behavior as
long as the tracking maintains individuals' anonymity. DoubleClick
uses anonymous profiles to make sure it doesn't send people the
same ad too many times.
</P>
<P>
   But Sobel said the marrying of names and addresses collected
offline with online sufing data violates a privacy policy
DoubleClick published on its Web site in 1997 and 1998, which
promised that its profiles would remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said EPIC's contention is ``completely without merit.''
DoubleClick ``has committed that in the future we won't sell
information unless people have notice and choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the advertising campaign, DoubleClick said it
would set up an advisory board that would include consumer
advocates; hire an outside firm ``to perform periodic privacy
audits''; and create a new position, chief privacy officer, to
focus on privacy issues.
</P>
<P>
   For surfers who visit privacychoices.org to opt out of
information collection, DoubleClick installs a special cookie on
the user's hard drive that prevents future DoubleClick cookies from
being installed. DoubleClick does not plan to link offline data
with existing surfer profiles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
