<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-PHONE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Phone.com to Acquire Onebox.com  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Phone.com, a Redwood City software company whose ``minibrowser''
helps cell-phone users surf the Net, announced plans yesterday to
buy Onebox.com, a San Mateo company that lets customers access
e-mail, voice mail and faxes via a single Web site.
<P>
   Executives said the $787 million stock deal will give Phone.com
additional services to offer its customers, which include wireless
phone companies like AT&AMP;T and Sprint, for a few dollars per account
per month. Phone.com already offers e-mail, but not voice mail or
fax.
</P>
<P>
   It is Phone.com's third acquisition in recent months. A week
ago, it completed its acquisition of AtMotion, a Redwood Shores
voice recognition company. Last week, it agreed to buy Paragon
Software, an English firm that lets users download calender
information on cell phones, for $497 million. Onebox says it has
2.5 million registered users, more than half of whom use the
service regularly. Onebox had less than $1million in sales last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Linder, Phone.com's vice president of marketing, said such
``unified messaging'' services are ``very much in demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Linder pointed out that many cell phone companies already give
away voice mail to encourage customers to make more calls, both to
retrieve messages and respond to them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, phone companies want to let users accept
faxes through their cell phones to encourage them to hand out their
cell phone number more freely. ``In Europe, most people put their
cell phone number on their business card,'' Linder noted. Yet many
Americans keep the numbers relatively private, giving them out only
to family and selected co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most cell phones today can't read faxes. Most customers
would only be able to use their phone to forward the message on to
the nearest fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   But Onebox chief executive Ross Bott said a new wave of cell
phone will let users view faxes anywhere. Nokia recently introduced
such a phone, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Bott, who will be chief operating officer of Phone.com, also
envisions customers being able to use Phone.com's voice recognition
software to dictate e-mail messages, a handy feature considering
most cell phones lack keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   He said Onebox was planning to market its services to cell phone
companies anyway, so it was a good fit with Phone.com. The firms
wrapped up a deal in just seven days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, though, shrugged off the acquisition. Phone.com
shares closed down $2.63, to $118.50, yesterday, reducing the value
of the deal to $770 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are expressing their opinion,'' Linder said, pointing out
that stocks often fall when companies make acquisitions over
concerns that the deal could hurt short-term earnings. Phone.com's
stock has risen fifteenfold since it went public last year.
</P>
<P>
   Onebox has about 70 workers, compared with 500 for Phone.com,
making the deal worth roughly $11 million per Onebox worker. Bott
said he didn't know how many would become millionaires but said
such overnight successes are now an oft-told story in Silicon
Valley. ``It's becoming pretty boring.''
</P>
<P>
   No layoffs are planned, though Bott said the companies'
corporate headquarters probably will eventually be combined in one
location.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
