<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-ETRADE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 E-Trade's Clicks Get Bricks  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
E-Trade Group, the company that has come to symbolize the wired
world of Internet brokerage, is about to set up shop. A real shop.
<P>
   The nation's No. 2 online broker will open a walk-in office on
Manhattan's exclusive Madison Avenue toward the end of the year,
according to people familiar with the plan. The facility will be
E-Trade's first storefront location, a big departure for a company
that has been computer-based from day one.
</P>
<P>
   The move doesn't mean Menlo Park's E-Trade is about to open a
nationwide chain of offices, like rival Charles Schwab Corp., which
operates more than 300 branches to complement its online service.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, E-Trade seeks to create a big marketing splash with a
glitzy office in one of the country's most visible locations. The
site will be akin to electronic gizmomaker Sony's store in San
Francisco's Metreon theater complex or shoemaker Nike's flashy
NikeTown shops.
</P>
<P>
   While customers could presumably open accounts and perform other
business, the site's main purpose is marketing. The store will use
a contemporary, high-tech format to spread E-Trade's image to a
wide audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is anything but a branch strategy,'' said one person
close to E-Trade. ``This creates a concept store that presents the
brand.''
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade views its New York store as an experiment. If it creates
a buzz, then the company might open a few stores in other
high-profile locations, people familiar with the plan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News reported last week that E-Trade had leased 30,000
square feet of space at Madison and 55th Street, in the middle of
Manhattan's most fashionable shopping district. E-Trade declined to
provide details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at doing something, but we've confirmed
nothing,'' said spokesman Patrick DiChiro.
</P>
<P>
   Opening a New York store begs the question of whether E-Trade
will eventually be forced to put together a real branch network,
something many analysts say is unavoidable. A broker that just
offers electronic service will serve only a niche market, they
contend, while the mass of customers moves move  &LR; to firms that
offer multiple channels for doing business, including branches,
telephones and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At Schwab, for example, branches and the Internet _ bricks and
clicks _ reinforce each other. one another.  &LR; The firm draws most
deposits through its offices, but customers carry out more than
two-thirds of all trades online.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have aspirations to be Wall Street to Main Street,'' a
physical presence is a necessity, said James Punishill, an
electronic commerce analyst at Forrester Research in Massachusetts.
``Ninety percent of Americans aren't interested in a one-trick
pony.''
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade executives have debated adding brick-and-mortar offices
at length, insiders say. Officials understand that customers want
options in transacting business. But they worry that branches could
dilute E-Trade's Internet business focus and push costs through the
roof.
</P>
<P>
   At an investor conference last year, chief executive Christos
Cotsakos said E-Trade might add physical locations of some kind,
perhaps by buying another business. But in an interview last month,
E-Trade's chief stressed that assembling a traditional branch
network is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be offering some kind of blended model,'' Cotsakos
said. ``But we are not going to build a whole network of costly
physical infrastructure. That's a dinosaur, a prescription for
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade could extend its reach by opening relatively inexpensive
electronic facilities, such as computerized kiosks or ATM-type
machines, Cotsakos noted.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
