<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYBAGE/ARTHUR M. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   &HT;     Taxing Dividends Of DaimlerChrysler  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I was a longtime owner of Chrysler stock. Since the merger with
Daimler-Benz, I have held stock in DaimlerChrysler. My dividends
from DaimlerChrysler have been subject to a large deduction
described as ``foreign tax.'' Is there any way for me to get my
money back, or must I pay taxes to the German government from now
on?
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Welcome to the global economy!
</P>
<P>
   You can get some _ and perhaps all _ of your money back, but in
any case, the German government is legally entitled to a piece of
the action.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works, according to Tim Krause of the
DaimlerChrysler investor relations department:
</P>
<P>
   The dividends paid to shareholders of DaimlerChrysler, a German
corporation, are subject to a 26.375 percent withholding tax by the
German government. However, the German government will refund most
of that _ 16.375 percent of the dividend _ if you submit proof that
you are a U.S. citizen. The Germans are required to make the refund
under a tax treaty with the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's U.S. transfer agent, the Bank of New York, is
responsible for sending shareholder claims for refunds to the
German government. Krause says that if your stock is held by your
broker, the Bank of New York would have done this automatically,
and you should have received your refund by now.
</P>
<P>
   So I assume that you own the stock directly. In that case, try
calling the Bank of New York at (800) 470-7410, and someone there
will cut the red tape for you.
</P>
<P>
   The German government is entitled to keep the remaining 10
percent of your dividend. But you probably can get some or all of
that amount back indirectly, in the form of a tax credit, when you
file your U.S. income-tax form. The credit can be used to offset a
like amount of tax.
</P>
<P>
   You may not be able to claim the full amount as a credit if you
are subject to the alternative minimum tax, or for various other,
esoteric reasons, cautions Cynthia Leachmoore, an enrolled tax
agent in Soquel (Santa Cruz County).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this whole subject is so convoluted that you had better
do some serious homework. Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse
Weller suggests that you carefully study the instructions for the
complicated IRS Form 6251, headed ``Alternative Minimum Tax _
Individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   You also should look at the even more complicated Form 1116, and
its instructions. Some taxpayers _ but not all _ must fill out that
form to claim the foreign tax credit. Others can simply enter the
credit directly onto Form 1040.
</P>
<P>
   It might also help to get a copy of Publication 514, ``Foreign
Tax Credit for Individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   You can download forms and publications from the IRS Web site at
www.irs.gov, or get them mailed to you by calling (800) 829-3676.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Finding Historical Prices
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: I would like to do research into the historical prices of
certain stocks and mutual funds. I am looking for a Web site that
provides the closing prices going back many years. Can you tell me
where to find this data without having to pay for it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: I would look no further than the Yahoo Web site _ assuming
that it is up and running. When it isn't disabled, as it was
yesterday, it is a marvelous tool for the research you have in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Go to finance.yahoo.com/ and enter the symbol for the security
you are researching, then press the tab that says ``Get quotes.''
</P>
<P>
   That will lead you to a new page where you will see the
security's latest price. Click on the link that says ``Charts.''
That will send you to yet another page where you click on the link
for ``Daily'' under the heading ``Table.''
</P>
<P>
   Now you will find yourself on a page where you can set the
chronological parameters of your search _ the beginning and ending
dates. Do that, then click the tab that says ``Get historical
data.''
</P>
<P>
   Voila! You will find a table showing the security's opening,
high, low and closing prices for each date in your search range, as
well as the volume of shares traded.
</P>
<P>
   I tested this procedure myself, picking a stock at random _
Albertson's, the grocery chain. I was able to retrieve daily prices
for this stock going back to 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo offers a useful bonus near the bottom of the page where
the stock tables begin _ a link that lets you automatically load
all the information onto a spreadsheet, making it easier to slice
and dice the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Escrow Accounts
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: When do California title companies pay interest on escrow
accounts and when do they not? We were in escrow for $10,000 for 22
months and finally the deal fell through. I visited the title
company to ask about the interest and was told that the money was
not put into an interest-bearing account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Mark Bogetich, a spokesman for the California Land Title
Association, a Sacramento trade group, says that in residential
real-estate transactions, escrow money is almost never placed in an
interest-bearing account. Instead, it is pooled with other escrow
money in a bank account that pays no interest.
</P>
<P>
   He explains that in most cases, the money will remain in escrow
for no more than a few weeks. Whatever interest you might collect
from a segregated, interest-bearing account would be consumed by
the fees you would have to pay the bank, the title company, or
both, to set up the account.
</P>
<P>
   If you had known in advance that the escrow period would be
long, you could have requested a segregated account. If you agreed
to pay the set-up fee, the title company probably would have
complied.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
