<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6934 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TAX-TAX_SFCHRON &LR;      02-14 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-TAX </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Taxpayers Get Break With Free E-Filing  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
It normally costs $19.90 to prepare and file your federal and state
tax returns over the Internet, using Intuit's popular Quicken
TurboTax software.
<P>
   But during the current tax season, the service is being offered
free on selected financial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers with annual incomes of $20,000 or less, as well as
those eligible to file the simplified Form 1040EZ, can
automatically file for free, courtesy of Intuit. Just go to the Web
site at www.turbotax.com.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers who don't fit those categories can still file for
free, using Quicken, by taking advantage of special promotions
offered by a handful of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are Vanguard (www.vanguard.com), Fidelity Investments
(www.fidelity.com), E-Trade (www.etrade.com), American Express
(www.american express.com) and WingspanBank (www.wingspanbank.com).
</P>
<P>
   Log on to those sites, then follow the link to the Quicken site.
There, you can fill out your forms and send them along directly to
the Internal Revenue Service, and the financial institution you
choose will foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   There are some complications, however.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade, WingspanBank and American Express are restricting the
offer to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   In E-Trade's case, the service will be free to new customers who
open an individual retirement account.
</P>
<P>
   At WingspanBank, both new and current customers will get the
service free.
</P>
<P>
   At American Express, the service is available to new customers
who open a money-market or checking account with an initial deposit
of at least $500 by March 8.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a customer to use the Quicken software
through the Vanguard and Fidelity Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But if you aren't, you first must register on their sites,
identifying yourself by name and answering questions about, for
example, your Social Security number, your e-mail address, your
home address and your mother's maiden name.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity warns that Intuit will send Fidelity some of the
personal information you enter on the Quicken site. However, it
promises that this won't include any details from your tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you do register, you can expect to be badgered soon
afterward with junk mail or telemarketing pitches.
</P>
<P>
   You have to decide for yourself whether enduring that nuisance
is worth the money you will save.
</P>
<P>
   You also can prepare and file your taxes for free over the
Internet, using the Web site of H.D. Vest, a Texas
financial-services company. H.D. Vest has created an interface for
software provided by Tax Works of Utah. Go to the H.D. Vest site at
www.hdvest.com and follow the prompts. You don't have to be a
customer of H.D. Vest, or anyone else, to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   However, you might want to skip it if you are shy about your
age. In addition to the usual information about your home address
and e-mail address, you are required to state your date of birth.
</P>
<P>
