<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-COURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FORMER GOVERNOR ADMITS TO GRAFT AND IMPLICATES OTHERS IN MEXICO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mexico, Brazil, Cuba, Guatemala)  By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A former governor who fled underground to avoid
arrest on drug charges as his term ended last year, is ``living
like a guerrilla'' in a tropical region, sleeping by day and often
moving by night, a journalist who met him recently said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The former official, Mario Villanueva Madrid, has grown his
curly hair long and looks haggard, partly because he sleeps
frequently in the open air, the journalist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hiding like an animal in the jungle,'' said the writer,
Isabel Arvide, an independent journalistwith broad contacts in the
governing party. She met him in a rustic dwelling infested with
cockroaches in southern Mexico or in Belize or Guatemala, the two
countries to the south, Arvide said. She refused to pinpoint the
exact location.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva wept openly as he described to Arvide the trauma of
his 11-month flight and his feelings of betrayal by President
Ernesto Zedillo and other leaders of Mexico's governing party, she
wrote in an account of her meeting that was published on Sunday in
a weekly newsmagazine, Milenio.
</P>
<P>
   The former governor accused his colleagues in the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party of breaking pledges to protect
him. He said he had honored their requests to abuse his powers as
governor of Quintana Roo, a Caribbean state, to guarantee election
victories for the party candidates there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my part,'' Villanueva said, according to Arvide's
account. ``I made all the party's candidates win. I gave them
money. I ran campaigns for them. I controlled the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva has been sought on drug and racketeering charges
since April 1999, when he dropped from sight days before he was to
leave office. Mexican and U.S. authorities have accused him of
putting his state police at the disposition of traffickers who use
the Yucatan Peninsula as a beachhead to smuggle Colombian cocaine
north to the Texas border.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva confessed to Arvide that during his governorship,
starting in 1993, he had pocketed millions of dollars in corruption
profits, but denied he had been involved with traffickers. He
accused several senior Mexican officials of having joined in the
graft with him.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva said he had pocketed $1.6 million in kickbacks for
enabling a business group obtain the water concession for Cancun,
the resort city. The illicit deal was negotiated, Villanueva said,
by a former PRI governor who is in Zedillo's cabinet, Eduardo
Robledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait just a minute,'' Robledo said Monday, when a reporter
asked him to respond to Villanueva's assertions. Then Robledo
turned and disappeared into a government office building. A
spokeswoman for him, Virginia Bello, returned to say Robledo
preferred not to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva was reported to have said that as prosecutors were
assembling their charges against him in the months before he left
office, he met a PRI patriarch, Carlos Hank Gonzalez, who amassed a
fortune when he was Mexico City mayor in the 1970s'.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the advice Hank gave me before I fled, I sold
everything I could, collecting money, because he warned me, `To go
underground you'll need cash, lots of cash.''' Villanueva told
Arvide.
</P>
<P>
   Hank's secretary, Yolando Morales, said Monday that Hank was
traveling in the United States. ``I'm sure he's not seen Mario
Villanueva for a long time,'' Morales said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his financial descent, Villanueva complained that an
unscrupulous lawyer tied to the PRI had cheated him out of more
than $5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
