</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-STORMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(1140)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO WHIPS THROUGH SOUTHWEST GEORGIA, KILLING MORE THAN 20 
</HEADLINE>
  (UPDATES throughout with death toll at 22, fresh quotes, color from
scene, details; no pickup; story now in two takes.)  
(Eds: For a list of additional stories on the tornado in Georgia,
see the Cox News Service spot budget, BC-SPOT-BJT15-COX. For
questions, call CoxNet in Atlanta at 404-526-5456.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT8-NYT13 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMILLA, Ga. _ Attacking under cover of darkness and with little
warning, tornadoes rumbled through southwest Georgia early Monday
morning, killing at least 22 people, injuring more than 100 and
transforming peaceful subdivisions into wastelands of debris.
</P>
<P>
   Because the storms began just before midnight Sunday, many
sleeping residents had no idea of the danger until they heard the
cracking of pine trees and the shattering of window panes. Some did
not even have time to get out of bed and into a closet.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny local hospitals, far more accustomed to treating flu
symptoms than large-scale emergencies, were quickly overwhelmed and
had to dispatch the injured all across south Georgia. Power was
lost at the 24-bed Mitchell County Hospital, which spent much of
the night using an emergency generator.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until dawn broke, more than seven hours after the
storms began, that rescue workers could conduct any systematic
search for the dead and injured. That job continued throughout the
afternoon, carried out by an army of law enforcement officers
equipped with bulldozers and German shepherds.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors told stories of a midnight horror. In the minutes
after the tornadoes struck, dazed residents wandered into the
darkness to find that brick houses had disintegrated, mobile homes
had disappeared into the night and forests of pines had snapped
like matchsticks. Doused by heavy rain, many blindly followed the
wails of injured neighbors and then used cellular telephones to
summon emergency workers.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the help arrived too late. John Ira Williams, a
33-year-old diesel mechanic who lives here, had just pulled into
the driveway of the mobile home he shared with his 51-year-old
mother when the tornado blew through. Sitting in his Camaro,
Williams felt the trailer blow off of its cement-block foundation
and nudge up against his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the trailer just disappeared,'' he said. ``It just
disintegrated. I don't even know where it went. I saw the house
just come apart.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Rubye Lee Williams, had been sleeping inside,
snuggled in bed with her two granddaughters, ages 7 and 2, who were
spending the night. Williams found the older girl, his niece,
scratched and bruised, wandering outside in a dreamlike state,
trying to find her way back inside a house that was no longer
there. The younger girl was asleep in a puddle, apparently unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   Using a flashlight from his car, Williams searched for his
mother, eventually finding her some 75 yards from where the trailer
once stood. She was breathing, barely, but by the time a paramedic
arrived 15 minutes later she had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``He checked her pulse and said there wasn't anything more he
could do,'' Williams said, as his sister stood by with a salvaged
photograph of their mother in a red dress. ``I just kind of lost
it. I got real numb and couldn't do anything for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the deaths _ 14 as of Monday evening _ were here in
Mitchell County, a rural area of pecan groves, cotton fields and
peanut farms, with a population of 21,000. State officials said
that seven more people died in Grady County, just south of here,
and that one died in Colquitt County, just to the east. Gov. Roy E.
Barnes declared a state of emergency in those counties and Tift
County, which is northeast of Colquitt, and requested federal
disaster assistance.
</P>
<P>
   After surveying the damage by helicopter Monday morning, Barnes
said it looked as if one tornado had cut a swath 10 miles long and
1 and a half miles wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a mobile home park on the south side of town and it
just looks like a bomb dropped,'' Barnes said, speaking in Camilla.
``It's just flattened, nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called the loss of life Monday ``unusual and
terrible'' and asked for the country's prayers.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear exactly how many tornadoes had formed and how
strong they were. Matthew R. Volkmer, a meteorologist with the
National Weather Service in Tallahassee, Fla., said there were at
least two or three tornadoes in the area and five or six
``super-cell thunderstorms.'' Several residents here said they felt
a second, lesser tornado blow through about 20 minutes after the
first one.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross said that initial damage assessments
found that 198 structures, most of them houses, had been destroyed
here in Mitchell County. An additional 81 sustained major damage
and 87 had minor damage. The Red Cross opened a shelter in a middle
school here, and more than 100 people stayed there on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials reported an array of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had lots of lacerations, a lot of broken arms, legs,
internal injuries, head injuries, a lot of cut glass,'' said Ronald
M. Gilliard, administrator of the Mitchell County Hospital. Glen C.
Davis, the administrator of Grady General Hospital, in Cairo,
described much of the same, as well as one arm amputation. A
pregnant woman reportedly was injured; her baby was delivered by
Caesarean section.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly some of the worst damage occurred in a mobile home park
on the south side of U.S. Highway 19, just outside the Camilla city
limits. Many trailers were simply obliterated, and the park was
littered with downed trees and piles of nearly unrecognizable
rubble. The ground was tinted pink and black from tufts of
insulation and shards of shingles. Red drapery and silver strips of
sheet metal flapped like flags from the upper limbs of the few
denuded trees that still stood. A tractor trailer sat on its side,
as did countless cars.
</P>
<P>
   Residents scavenged through the sites of their former homes,
tossing keepsakes into piles, baseball trophies over here, photo
albums over there. Many said they would be happy to find enough
clothing to get them through the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Thomas, 42, huddling in a hallway with his wife, said he
could literally hear his manufactured home trying to split in two
as the tornado came through. His car, a red Escort, was lifted and
deposited 50 feet away. ``We started hearing people hollering for
help,'' he said. ``There were a lot of people out and about, just
screaming, trying to get out of the area.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of Highway 19, where the Royal Heights
subdivision of brick ranches once stood, roofs had been sheared
away by the wind and downed trees were everywhere. Four smashed
cars were buried beneath pine trees in the McCaskill family's front
yard.
</P>
<P>
   Gail G. Swindle, 60, who has lived in her house for 29 years,
escaped with relatively minor damage to her house but said the
night was horrific nonetheless. ``I got my pocketbook, the cell
phone and the car keys and got in the tub,'' she said. ``It was
terrifying. That's the most helpless feeling, because there's
absolutely nothing you can do. You just have to go with it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most fortunate people here were the Anglin family.
As the storm began, Chris and Cindy Anglin tried to roust their
four children into a single bathroom, but the family was separated
when the tornado hit. Cindy and the two boys hunkered down on one
end of the house, while Chris and the girls were trapped on the
other side. The tornado came straight down the middle, tearing the
roof off, collapsing the brick walls, and somehow leaving the
family with only minor scratches and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had been in the middle of the house, we wouldn't be
here,'' Mrs. Anglin said. ``We saw a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   While searching the debris Monday morning, Mrs. Anglin found the
waterlogged Valentine card she had bought for her husband, and gave
it to him. ``I've got one for you,'' he swore. ``I've got proof.
But I don't know where it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
