<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-COSTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSULTANT PREDICTS EVEN HIGHER `BIG DIG' PRICETAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The top management consultant overseeing the city's
``Big Dig'' says the project's cost may climb beyond the recently
announced $12.2 billion pricetag before its completion five years
from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you it's the end,'' said Matthew Wiley, top
official of Bechtel/Parsons Brinckerhoff, during a 90-minute
discussion Monday of project finances _ including the recent
surprise announcement that the project will grow by $1.4 billion
over projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you something's not going to occur underground
that we don't know about,'' Wiley said, sitting next to Turnpike
Chairman James J. Kerasiotes, the state official responsible for
managing the Central Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel project.
</P>
<P>
   But Wiley added that the $12.2 billion figure is an estimate,
and held out the possibility that project could cost less than
that. ``$10.8 billion is still a number we want to become close
to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The project officials met with reporters Monday to try to assure
the public that the massive highway construction is under control,
despite mounting criticism about the climbing cost.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, a federal inspector general's report was made
public. The report accused regional Federal Highway Administration
monitors of becoming too willing to accept state transportation
officials' cost estimates without verification.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the project officials told reporters that they did not
try to hide anything, that until last last year they were hopeful
the cost could be held to $10.8 billion _ and that, in any case, at
the time they did not have a precise estimate of how much the
project could actually cost beyond that figure.
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes acknowledged for the first time Monday that in 1993,
when he raised the official cost estimate from $6.4 billion to $7.7
billion to cover the cost of a new Charles River Crossing design,
he built in a ``cushion'' of about $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing costs, however, consumed that cushion by early last
year, he said, and dozens of opportunities to cut costs on the
project had been exhausted as well.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wiley said, ``I think there's opportunity there'' to find
savings in the project, though project officials acknowledged that
the $1.4 billion increase was necessary because by last fall they
had run out of ways to offset increasing construction costs
throughout the highway, tunnel, and bridge megaproject.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerasiotes vowed that the project ``is going to be done on
time'' by the end of 2004. ``I'm not worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite cost increases and the inspector general's report, both
Kerasiotes and Wiley insist that management of the eight-year-old
project is under control. Kerasiotes cited the lack of any known
significant corruption, the admirable safety record, and the fact
that traffic in the city has moved relatively well even during
heavy construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project has been managed very well,'' Kerasiotes said.
``I think this project has has superb management by any measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes said the continuous cost increases _ including a
steady rise from an optimistic mid-1980s estimate of $2.6 billion
to today's $12.2 billion figure _ should not come as a big
surprise. ``Anybody who's ever looked at a project like this knows
it's going to cost more . . . It's not that our heads are in the
sand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley was asked if this project was managed as well as the other
projects by Bechtel, the multinational construction consultant.
``I'd like to think it's a lot better managed,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1993, Kerasiotes made a firm statment that the project's
price tag would not go higher than $10.8 billion and he has stuck
to it since then _ sometimes angrily, when challenged. But he
downplayed that stance Monday: ``I haven't been out there selling
the number $10.8 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes said he asked Patrick J. Moynihan to ``do a complete
assessment of the project'' when Moynihan took over as project
director early in 1999. That ``bottom-to-top review,'' Kerasiotes
said, led to the recognition in the fall that there was no way to
stick to the $10.8 billion figure.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he and the financial managers who joined him in the
interview Monday said officials have been trying to pinpoint an
accurate, final estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes said the price tag would have been even higher had it
not been for his aggressive approach: ``We beat the living
daylights out of the number every day.''
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected the notion that Peter M. Zuk _ who managed the
project for almost eight years before Moynihan took over _ bore
some responsibility for the $1.4 billion increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's the case at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Reynolds, program and budget manager for the Big Dig,
said that he knew in 1993 that Kerasiotes' vow that the project
would not cost a penny more than $10.8 billion would be difficult
to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   The statement ``had aggressive assumptions in it'' about
cost-cutting, Reynolds said. ``I was getting somewhat uneasy in the
second and third quarters of 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said that the project's monthly management reports,
which purport to track the cost and schedule, have not reflected
the $1.4 billion increase because they aren't sure that they will
incur that cost.
</P>
<P>
   Those reports have consistently shown about $500 million in cost
increases beyond the $10.8 billion, though until recently the
increases were offset almost dollar for dollar by project
reductions or other cost-saving maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lewis, deputy project director, was asked why those were
taken more or less conveniently in increments, month by month, as
project costs increased _ rather than all being reflected at once.
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes has frequently criticized his predecessors in the
Dukakis administration for ``managing to a number'' _ carrying cost
estimates that were politically palatable but did not reflect what
the project would actually cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think it was prudent to . . . say the project costs
less,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Bechtel's Wiley said he was comfortable with Kerasiotes's
statements that the cost would be $10.8 billion, even when he knew
what number was slipping.
</P>
<P>
   Though the opportunities for savings shrank in the third quarter
of 1999, Wiley said, ``I did not have a problem maintaining the
`$10.8 billion', or statements the chairman was making.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Kerasiotes and the Turnpike have been more
difficult than other clients, Wiley said, ``No. They're probably
very good to deal with. There aren't many . . . organizations we
would go in to work with as a project team, especially in the
public contracting sector.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
