<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   European Union to Back German Official for IMF
</P>
<P>
   The European Union appears set to back a German finance ministry
official to head the International Monetary Fund, giving a boost to
a candidate Clinton administration officials privately argue is
ill-suited for the job. European foreign ministers, meeting in
Brussels, reached an informal consensus that Caio K. Koch-Weser,
55, a longtime World Bank official who currently serves as a state
secretary in Germany's finance ministry, should succeed Michel
Camdessus as head of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag Issues an Earnings Warning
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Maytag, the appliance maker, fell sharply after
the company warned that earnings this year would not meet Wall
Street expectations. The company said first quarter earnings could
be down 10 percent from a year ago because of fierce competition in
the market for home appliances and weaker-than-expected sales of
its soft drink vending machines. The warning was the second in
three quarters for Maytag.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain Hunting Sends Markets Up
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended higher as Wall Street scouted for bargains, notably
among cyclical stocks, after a sharp sell-off last week that sent
the blue-chip Dow index reeling into a correction. The Dow Jones
industrial average gained 94.63 points, or 0.9 percent, to
10,519.84, after losing 538.59 points or 4.9 percent last week. The
broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index closed up 2.82 points, or
0.2 percent, to 1,389.94. The Nasdaq climbed 23.10 points, or 0.52
percent, to 4,418.55.
</P>
<P>
   Search for Web Disrupters Narrows
</P>
<P>
   The search for suspects in the recent attacks on Web sites had
led to online conversations secretly monitored by computer security
experts before and during the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade Filings Exclude Some Data
</P>
<P>
   ETrade Group has spent millions of advertising dollars to build
its reputation as a company that empowers individual investors.
Along the way, however, it has been slow to provide investors some
crucial information about itself. On two occasions in recent
months, ETrade has excluded information about its executives' pay
packages from Securities and Exchange Commission filings, an
apparent violation of rules.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Official Is Paid $25 Million
</P>
<P>
   Henry Paulson, the chairman and chief executive of Goldman Sachs
Group, was one of at least five top executives on Wall Street to
take home more than $25 million last year. He joined three senior
executives at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and the chief executive of
Merrill Lynch in receiving 1999 pay packages of more than $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch Weighs Satellite Spinoff
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. said it is considering consolidating
all its satellite-related businesses into a single company that
could provide Internet service from space to nearly the entire
globe.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick Acts on Privacy Issue
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick, the Internet advertising placement company, started
a service and an educational campaign to help Web surfers protect
their privacy in response to growing criticism of its tracking of
consumers as they make their way around the Internet. But the
effort was denounced by privacy advocates as a feeble attempt at
crisis management.
</P>
<P>
   Demand Outpaces Inventories
</P>
<P>
   American companies bolstered their inventories by a modest 0.5
percent in December but their sales vaulted ahead at more than
twice that pace, a sign that businesses are struggling to keep up
with hardy demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
