<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY IN BRUSSELS 
POTTERY, COAST TO COAST 
FRANKFURT BALLET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
 (af)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I will be in London this spring and would like to travel to
Brussels by train, tour the city and return to London the same day.
Is this possible? And whom should I contact for information? _
Irving Greene, East Brunswick, N.J. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The folks in Brussels would probably tell you that it takes
more than a day to see their city, but if that's all the time you
have, then, yes, it can be done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fastest way to cover the 193 miles between the two cities is
by a Eurostar train, which goes through the Channel Tunnel. The
trip takes about three hours each way.
</P>
<P>
   From London, the earliest departure is 6 a.m. from Waterloo
Station, arriving in Brussels at 10:02 a.m. (remember that England
is one hour behind continental Europe). This train runs Monday
through Saturday under a schedule that is in effect through March
23. A 6:53 a.m. departure, available Monday through Friday, arrives
in Brussels at 10:37 a.m. And a daily departure at 8:13 a.m.
reaches Brussels at 12:10 p.m. There are other departures
throughout the day as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For your return trip, you can catch a 5:56 p.m. Eurostar train
in Brussels and, with the time difference, arrive in London at 7:39
p.m.; this train is available Monday through Saturday. There are
two later departures each day: 6:56 p.m., with arrival in London at
8:56 p.m.; and 9:01 p.m., arriving 10:59 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The standard fare (50 percent refundable up to three days before
the train's departure date) is $119 one way; a food-cart service is
offered, but meals cost extra. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The one-way fare is $199 in first class (50 percent refundable
up to three days before departure), which includes a wider seat
than second class, a free newspaper and a meal served at your seat;
first premium class, $329, adds a wider selection of drinks and
food, use of the Executive Lounge in Waterloo Station and a free
taxi ride from the station in London.
</P>
<P>
   The train station in Belgium is Brussels Midi, about 15 minutes'
walk from the center of the city. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You must reserve your Eurostar ticket in advance. You can book
on the Web at www.raileurope.com, at (800) 456-7245 or through a
travel agent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a limited number of hours in Brussels, you will want to
give yourself a good head start in planning your visit. Contact the
Belgian Tourist Office, 780 Third Avenue, Suite 1501, New York,
N.Y. 10017; (212) 758-8130, www.visitbelgium.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Brussels Tourist Office is in the Town Hall on the
Grand-Place; telephone (32-2) 513-8940, fax (32-2) 514-4538,
www.brussels.org. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be taking an Amtrak See America tour this summer and
would like to know of any pottery stores in New York, Chicago,
Denver, San Francisco and San Diego. I am interested in functional
handmade pottery, not big-name company outlets. _ Vickie Price,
Waldwick, N.J. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you can carry all this pottery, here are some
suggestions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In New York, TriBeCa Potters, 443 Greenwich Street, (212)
431-7631, produces handmade ceramic plates that are favored by
Manhattan restaurateurs looking to dress up their tables with
something beyond the ordinary. Try
hometown.aol.com/nycpotters/tribecapotters.html. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The people at TriBeCa, in turn, recommended that you stop at
Lill Street Gallery, 1021 West Lill Street, in the Lincoln Park
section of Chicago. It opened in 1975 in a former horse and
carriage barn and now includes a studio, classrooms and a shop.
Call (773) 477-6185; on the Web at www.lillstreet.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are two places you can try in Denver: Art Pedlar, 1071 Old
South Gaylord Street, (303) 744-3421, and the Clay Pigeon, 601
Ogden Street, (303) 832-5538; on the Web at www.claypigeon.com.
Each has been in business for decades, selling the wares of local
artisans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you reach San Francisco, there are a number of places to
look. The Virginia Breier Gallery (also known as the Virginia
Breier Contemporary and Traditional Craft), 3091 Sacramento Street,
has a great selection of pottery made by local artisans. Call (415)
929-7173. Also in the area is the Berkeley Potter's Guild, 731
Jones Street at Fourth Street in Berkeley, not far from the
freeway.
</P>
<P>
   They are a collective of 18 potters and have their work for sale
at that location, which houses their studios and showroom. But they
are open only on Saturday and Sunday from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Call
(510) 524-7031. For a more extensive guide to Bay Area pottery
centers, try www.claymedia.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Near San Diego, the Gallery Alexander, 7850 Girard Avenue in La
Jolla, (858) 459-9433, represents over 400 artists in various
media. It also presents numerous theme exhibitions each year. The
Web site is www.galleryalexander.com.
</P>
<P>
   For more extensive listings, you can contact the American Craft
Council, 72 Spring Street, New York, N.Y. 10012; (212) 274-0630, or
at www.craftcouncil.org. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in Frankfurt overnight on a layover on my return
from Malta in May, and I wish to attend a performance of the
Frankfurt Ballet. How would I make a reservation from the United
States? _ L.P., Portland, Ore. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Ballett Frankfurt (as the company has been known since 1984,
when William Forsythe, the American choreographer, took over as
artistic director) gives about 50 performances a year in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   From May 12 to 14 and 17 through 20, the dance company will
present ``DJamesDJoyceDead,'' a work by the Flemish theater
director and writer Jan Lauwers based on the life of Joyce and the
themes in his writings. The production will feature 12 Ballett
Frankfurt dancers and two actresses from Lauwers' Needcompany.
</P>
<P>
   The performances, which begin at 8 p.m., will be in the
Bockenheimer Depot, a former train station that has been converted
to a theater. The Depot, on Bockenheimer Landstrasse, is part of
the Johann Wolfgang Goethe University campus.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices range from $10 to $40, at 1.98 marks to $1. For
information, call (49-69) 212-37555. To order tickets by telephone,
call (49-69) 212-37222 or (49-69) 1340400; by fax, (49-69)
212-37999. Or, if you understand German, you can order on the Web
at www.eintrittskarte.de. And to learn more about the company, call
up www.frankfurt-ballett.de. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
