<HEADER>
A6955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EXECS-BIGBUCKS-NYT &LR;      02-14 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECS-BIGBUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS PROXY SHOWS CHIEF MADE OVER $25 MILLION  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Henry M. Paulson, the chairman and chief executive of
the Goldman Sachs Group, was one of at least five top executives on
Wall Street to take home more than $25 million last year, according
to the firm's first proxy statement.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson received $16.6 million in salary and bonus plus
restricted stock worth another $8.8 million, the proxy shows. He
joined three senior executives at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter _
Peter Karches, John J. Mack and Philip J. Purcell _ and the chief
executive of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., David H. Komansky, who received
1999 pay packages of more than $25 million, according to proxy
statements those firms filed last week with the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Each received more compensation than the top executives of Bear
Stearns Cos., which for years has had the highest-paid management
team on Wall Street. For the fiscal year that ended June 30, Bear
Stearns paid its chief executive, James Cayne, $23.2 million in
cash, stock and other compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the raise Paulson received is difficult to measure
because Goldman was a private partnership before it went public in
May. For Goldman partners, the annual growth of their stakes in the
firm was a significant component of their compensation. Excluding
that sum, Paulson received about $12.7 million in total
compensation in fiscal 1998, when he was running the firm along
with Jon S. Corzine, who was pushed to resign last year and is a
Democratic candidate in New Jersey for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most competitors, Goldman Sachs did not give stock
options to any employees last year. It does allow its managers to
invest in funds that Goldman manages. Paulson took distributions of
more than $5 million on his investments in those funds last year,
the proxy shows.
</P>
<P>
   John A. Thain and John L. Thornton, who share the titles of
president and chief operating officer for Goldman, each took home
more than $21 million in cash and stock for the period from May 7
through November. Robert J. Hurst, a vice chairman, received more
than $19 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
