<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6956 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-STORMS-GEORGIA-COX     02-14 1957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORMS-GEORGIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `We're just trying to make it to tomorrow'
 &HT;    By Alan Judd and Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMILLA, Ga. _ Georgia's fifth deadliest cluster of tornadoes
ripped apart South Georgia families and communities as cruelly and
as randomly as it did the tattered valentines found strewn among
ruined homes, barns and collard fields.
</P>
<P>
   The series of rare winter tornadoes savaged the counties of
Mitchell, Grady, Tift and Colquitt before dawn Monday, killing at
least 22 people, injuring 100 and destroying about 200 homes.
</P>
<P>
   No tornadoes to hit Georgia since World War II have been as
deadly.
</P>
<P>
   They tore a half-mile wide, 10-mile long swath of destruction
through Mitchell County, 30 miles from the Florida border,
obliterating trailers and houses, snapping old-growth oak and pine
trees, scattering cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell County was hit hardest with 14 reported deaths. The
injured included a 4-year-old boy found in the rubble of his
family's house trailer in Camilla late Monday afternoon. His
6-year-old sister died in the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was the devastation so thorough as in the mobile home
park just south of Camilla off U.S. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Where once stood 100 trailers, three remained. Survivors said
they had little, if any, time to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just woke up,'' Earnest Thompson said Monday as he and
his companion, Katherine Sharp, picked through the rubble of his
mobile home. ``I got up and cut the TV on, and it hit _ just that
quick.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple was thrown into a muddy, debris-filled front lawn as
their trailer exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was holding on to me,'' Thompson said, ``and I held her
down until it blew through. ... We're just glad to be alive.''
</P>
<P>
   At least seven people died in Grady County, and one person in
Colquitt County.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes declared a state of emergency for the four
counties before touring devastated sections of Mitchell County by
helicopter. He requested federal disaster relief upon returning
from his flyover of the obliterated mobile home park below Camilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like somebody dropped a bomb on it,'' Barnes said.
``It's a bad hit. It's a swath _ wide and long.''
</P>
<P>
   To local officials, the governor added, ``Whatever y'all need,
we're going to send you. It's that simple. Whatever we need to do,
we'll do it. We'll make sure this tragedy is not worse than it
already is.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials will make mobile homes available by Thursday for
victims left homeless by the storm, said Gary McConnell, director
of the Georgia Emergency Management Agency. The state also
dispatched law enforcement officers and electricity generators to
the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a long haul,'' McConnell told Mitchell
County officials.
</P>
<P>
   The county sheriff, W.E. Bozeman, remarked, ``Right now, we're
just trying to make it to tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gilliard, Mitchell County Hospital administrator, said the
33-bed facility quickly became ``a war zone,'' with more than 120
injured people pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hallway was lined with patients. We took mattresses off
older beds and put them on the floor. We had patients in chairs, on
cots,'' he said. ``My entire medical staff responded, including
off-duty people, and a lot of our folks have damaged homes, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the death toll was high because so few people
knew the tornadoes were coming. It was after 11 p.m., and many
apparently didn't hear the broadcast warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some warning, but everybody was asleep,'' Barnes
said. ``There was just not enough time for them to know. While
there was some warning, I would doubt there was very little
knowledge of the warning.''
</P>
<P>
   Most tornadoes to hit Georgia strike in March, April or May, not
mid-February. Most occur in the late afternoon or early evening
hours, once the day's heat sufficiently builds.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Monday's twisters were also eerily familiar. Mobile homes
and their dwellers were hit hardest. The survivors spoke of roaring
winds, sideways rain and of fear never before known.
</P>
<P>
   In the Tift County town of Omega, Jason and Robin Cone ran from
bedroom to bathroom, remembering that a bathtub is supposed to
offer safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when the window exploded, we ran back to the bed,'' Robin
Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   The winds lifted their home from its moorings before flinging it
back to the ground with a fury, splintering and shattering almost
everything. Remarkably, the bedroom was the only room that remained
intact.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 56 years since tornados claimed so many lives in
Georgia. On April 16,1944, in Gainesville, 41 people were killed by
twisters.
</P>
<P>
   Gainesville holds the dubious record of the state's most deadly
tornado site: Twisters in 1936 killed 203; tornados in 1908 killed
98. The Statesboro area registered 52 deaths in 1929. On February
10, 1940, in Albany, 22 were killed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, 13 people died when storms struck Hall and White
counties. Less than a month later, one person died in the Dunwoody
tornadoes in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   While South Georgia bore the brunt of the new century's first
tornadoes, North Georgia and much of the Southeast didn't escape
unscathed. Hail _ 1.75 inches thick _ pelted McDonough in Henry
County. Cedartown in Polk County and Cumming in Forsyth County
received inch-sized hail.
</P>
<P>
   Bursts of torrential rain and gusty wind swept across metro
Atlanta, causing little more than traffic tie-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Arkansas, Mississippi, Florida, Alabama and
Tennessee reported wind damage but no fatalities from the storms,
which hit them Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, a twister in southern Montgomery County flung pieces
of a factory's four metal buildings nearly 2 miles and caused
$400,000 in damage.
</P>
<P>
   In the Florida Panhandle just north of Panama City, tornadoes
were blamed for damage to at least 40 homes. In Arkansas, a twister
just east of Little Rock destroyed at least six homes.
</P>
<P>
   It was Georgia, though, where the nation's eyes focused Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very saddened by the terrible loss of life and the other
damage,'' President Clinton said at the White House during an
Hispanic American Achievement ceremony. ``The loss of life in
Georgia this morning is unusual, and terrible. And I ask for your
prayers for those people today.''
</P>
<P>
   No community suffered like the sprawling trailer park just south
of Camilla.
</P>
<P>
   Residents described the coummunity as a friendly place where
children played and neighbors helped each other. On Monday, most of
their homes were twisted into pieces of metal that were wrapped
around trees, scattered across a nearby pecan grove or impaled on
tree limbs.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the deaths and injuries in Mitchell County were
in the trailer park, said Robbie Hopkins, a county emergency
medical services official.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Monday, rescuers combed the trailer park _ some using
specially trained dogs, some operating heavy fork lifts, others
using their hands to scrounge through rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Rare good news came when searchers found the 4-year-old boy who
had been missing. He was hospitalized, but details of his condition
were not available late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   His home was across the street from a large field where at least
a dozen homes had stood. On Monday, a tractor-trailer sat on its
side nearby. Car windows had been blown out.
</P>
<P>
   An eclectic array of litter covered the soggy ground: stovetops
from electric ranges, videocassette recorders, cordless telephones,
unpaid bills and loose snapshots _ the remains of the lives the
tornadoes ravaged.
</P>
<P>
   The park's residents gathered at the piles of debris that had
once been their homes, looking for anything worth saving and
talking about the horror they had lived through.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the demolished trailer of his neighbor Freddy
Williams, Ricky Sessions was hailed as a hero.
</P>
<P>
   His own home suffered little damage. But after the storm passed,
he said, ``I heard somebody calling, 'Help, help!'''
</P>
<P>
   Sessions ran outside, where rain still pounded and a strong wind
howled. Rubble was everywhere _ as were downed power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started going door to door to see if everybody's OK,''
Sessions said. ``I just kept hollering, I just kept hollering, I
just kept hollering. Then I heard him say, 'Here I go! Here I
go!'''
</P>
<P>
   It was Williams. The 43-year-old man had been blown across the
street, 50 feet away. He tried to stand, but couldn't because of
injuries to his back and head.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions found a police officer and helped load the injured man
into the cruiser that would take him to the hospital. Williams was
in critical condition Monday afternoon, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   Others weren't so lucky. Laritta Jackson and Joyce Williams
walked through the trailer park Monday looking for friends from
church who were missing. Williams' cousin and her cousin's two
teenage children died in the tornado, she said, and her aunt was in
the hospital, paralyzed from the waist down.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the trailer park's residents spent Monday seeing what
they could salvage before they left for shelters or the homes of
friends or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm just homeless,'' said Katherine Sharp, who had
lived in the trailer with Earnest Thompson for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``No clothes, no nothing,'' Thompson said, assessing their
belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Their trailer was shoved 20 feet off its foundation, and one
wall was ripped away. Everything inside seemed to have been sucked
out and scattered. Sifting through the rubble, Sharp found her
purse. But she said, ``I wish I could find my wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson answered, ``That wallet's gone, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything was gone, and Thompson said his hip, chest and
shoulders hurt from being pummeled by flying debris. It could've
been worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good Lord was just with us, man,'' he said. ``Yep, the
good Lord was just with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The destruction was no less devastating to families in the Omega
community.
</P>
<P>
   Shredded pink insulation and torn Valentines were all that
remained of several homes along the Tift-Colquitt county line.
Nearby, homes, barns, and crops were leveled. The Dunn family
mourned the death of their friend Guadalupe Cervantes, 43, who was
killed when a pecan tree crushed her inside her mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took two hours to find her, with friends families and EMS
workers digging through the crushed trailer,'' said her brother,
Antonio Cervantes.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado blew another mobile home on top of her crushed
trailer, said Kenny Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was total devestation when we got there around 2 a.m.,''
said Dunn. ``Lupe, as she is known ... , will be missed and mourned
for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Up and down Omega-Eldorado Road, the damage was severe. Dorothy
Hall was found cut and bruised in her yard after the tornado
leveled her house. Nearby, a car was flattened under a pecan tree
and a tractor was overturned in a collard field.
</P>
<P>
   Junior and Betty Keith also survived the twister in their bed.
</P>
<P>
   The Tift County couple didn't know the tornado was aimed at them
``until the house started breaking apart and coming down,'' said
Betty Keith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard the boom when the skylight exploded and everything
was sucked out around us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Dunn, whose home was unharmed, said numerous farm families
in this community are suffering a double blow from the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farming hasn't been all that great in the past few years, what
with the severe drought of the past summer,'' he said. ``Now, folks
have lost everything _ farm vehicles, trucks, cars, and homes are
all totally demolished. I hope we can get some federal aid down
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox writers Gita M. Smith and Marlon Manuel contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
