<P>
   (NYT22) LA JOLLA, CA -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- SCI-DNA-BEADS -- The
more biologists understand of living cells, the more daunting seems
the task of figuring out everything they do. ``We said, 'Let the
DNA work for us instead of us working for the DNA,''' said Dr.
Sydney Brenner, the inventor of a technique which involves
attaching very large sets of DNA molecules, such as all of a cell's
active genes, to invisibly small plastic beads five microns
(millionths of a meter) in diameter. Brenner's technique would
greatly simplify this task. (Robert Burroughs/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DAVIS, CA -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- SCI-PARALLEL-UNIVERSE --
Dr. Andreas Albrecht, a cosmologist at the University of California
in Davis, says that all the simple ways of explaining the
astronomical observations had already been tried and have failed.
Albrecht is one of the many cosmologists on the cutting edge of a
trend in a branch of theoretical physics called superstring theory,
which suggests that the cosmic acceleration may be an effect from
some other universe. (Don Preisler/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- MERRILL-APPOINT -- Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. on Monday placed its chief financial officer, E.
Stanley O'Neal, in charge of the nation's biggest brokerage
operation and on track to be the next chairman of the firm. O'Neal,
seen in his office on Monday, is one of the highest-ranking blacks
on Wall Street and is the first person to be named to oversee
Merrill's force of 14,200 brokers without having been a broker
himself. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN -- Vice
President Al Gore during campaign stop at the Medgar Evers College
in Brooklyn, Monday. Cheering on Gore in the background is former
Mayor David Dinkins of New York. Gore started the day landing in an
upstate New York blizzard for a speech at the University of
Rochester promoting his proposals for tuition tax credits and
savings accounts. Gore continued to talk about education policies
at the college named after the slain civil rights leader. (Michelle
V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
