<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6961 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD     02-14 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS ORDER EVACUATION OF GROZNY
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS to recast, tighten top 7 grafs; Pickup 8th prv, ``I'm not
leaving ...)  
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ Russian commanders on Monday ordered the
devastated city of Grozny emptied of its surviving residents and
sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Nikolai A. Zaitsev, a senior Interior Ministry officer,
said the capital of the embattled province of Chechnya had become
too dangerous for its inhabitants. It will be off-limits for two
weeks while Interior Ministry troops comb the city for weapons,
unexploded bombs and booby-traps.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officers conceded that the move was also a precaution
against rebel infiltration. Leaflets circulated throught the city
Monday warning residents that militants were planning a new
guerrilla campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movement to Grozny will be restricted until March 1,'' Zaitsev
said, waving an order from the high command. ``Those civilians who
are already in the city will be gradually evacuated. There are
refugee camps, and if someone does not have permanent residence we
will send him there. We will provide transportation for those that
cannot walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers were also instructed to turn back any civilians trying
to return to Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how the Russian troops intended to
empty the city, especially since many of the residents who only
recently had emerged from their basement shelters after weeks of
bombardment and terror said they had no intention of abandoning
what little they had.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they simply had no place to move to, and little desire
to end up in an overcrowded refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not leaving,'' said Tamara N. Zheromyskaya, 57, a
veterinarian. She said she was not well enough to travel and wanted
to stay with her son. Beyond that, she added, ``I have nowhere to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   To anyone but the stubborn residents hanging on, Grozny seemed
beyond restoration. Demolition teams moved through the city blowing
up the half-destroyed shell of buildings. Huge explosions rocked
the city, sending dust billowing into the sky. With each explosion,
Grozny seems to sink further into the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Looting has been a serious problem. The first complement of
pro-Russian Chechen police officers arrived Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian aid convoys have begun to snake through the city, but
food and water are in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Still, thousands of civilians _ no one knew how many _ who
braved the war seem determined to endure the peace. They do not
have much: a one-room apartment, perhaps some furniture. But they
were determined to hold onto the little they have, despite the
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   And there were plenty. Zaitsev said, for example, that Russian
soldiers had found 11,000 explosive devices in the last few weeks.
Some are booby traps laid by the departing rebels, he said. Others
are unexploded ordnance, like the 500-pound Russian bomb that was
found across in the Zavodskoi district.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fear of renewed fighting is another concern. After the fall of
Grozny, most of the fighting shifted to the south. The Russian
troops blazed a path of destruction as they chased the remnants of
the rebel force in Grozny through towns like Katyr-Yurt and
Shaami-Yurt. Trying to regain the initiative, the rebels briefly
took the town of Gekhi-Chu. After they left, Russian artillery
pounded the settlement, causing numerous civilian casualties,
according to Russian media reports from the area.
</P>
<P>
   Leaflets distributed in Grozny on Monday warned that the
militants might strike on Feb. 23, the anniversary of Stalin's
attempt to deport the Chechen people to Kazakhstan. Stalin's move
was eventually reversed by Nikita Khrushchev, but not before it
fanned the rancor between the Russians and many Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflets read: ``The commanders of the illegal armed
formations want to draw your towns, settlements and streets into
the chaos of war and violence. Stay quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Akhmed Khizriyev, a 47-year-old construction engineer, and Asya,
his wife, fled during the war but returned to Grozny on Monday to
try to retrieve some of their belongings. They were surprised when
soldiers told them the checkpoints around the city were being
closed, and they were told the closing was ordered to prevent the
militants from infiltrating and carrying out partisan attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Viktor Kazantsev, the commander of Russian forces in
the North Caucasus, drove the point home Monday in an appearance
before Russian television reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bandits are sneaking through disguised as civilians in order
to take out their wounded who are still here and to strengthen
their positions in Grozny,'' Kazantsev said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Having suffered through several wars, however, Grozny residents
seem more concerned about the Russian evacuation plan than the
possibility of more fighting. They do not want to part with what is
left of their home or end up in a refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   Klavdiya M. Nefyodova, 88, summed up the prevailing mood: ``I do
not want to leave my belongings here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
