   (NYT22) LA JOLLA, CA -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- SCI-DNA-BEADS -- The
more biologists understand of living cells, the more daunting seems
the task of figuring out everything they do. ``We said, 'Let the
DNA work for us instead of us working for the DNA,''' said Dr.
Sydney Brenner, the inventor of a technique which involves
attaching very large sets of DNA molecules, such as all of a cell's
active genes, to invisibly small plastic beads five microns
(millionths of a meter) in diameter. Brenner's technique would
greatly simplify this task. (Robert Burroughs/The New York Times)
