new memoirs by authors with juvenile, or Type 1, diabetes,
addresses the burden of having a potentially fatal condition they
say they were expected to keep under wraps. (Don Hogan Charles/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BALTIMORE -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- SCI-FEMALE-ASTRONOMERS --
Many women are drawn to astronomy, yet even today, few are
advancing to the highest levels of the field, said C. Megan Urry,
an astronomer at the Space Telescope Science nstitute in Baltimore.
``With the Hubble Space Telescope and other advances, there's a lot
of excitement in the field now, and a lot of stuff for people to
do,'' said Urry during a recent interview. (Marty Katz/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- SCI-JUPITER-STORMS -- Using
photographs like these, taken by the Galileo spacecraft, scientists
have found that Jupiter's storms are caused by heat deep in the
planet. Scientists analyzing these types of photographs The weather
on Jupiter seems always stormy. Lightning flashes deep in the
enveloping gas clouds. Eddies of atmospheric turbulence bob along
the margins of jet streams, feeding energy into titanic, long-lived
whirl pools. Thunderheads tower more than 30 miles above
surrounding clouds, and new observations reveal that moist heat
rising in these stormy updrafts probably supplies the energy
driving most Jovian weather. (NASA/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BAYSHORE, N.Y. -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- KILL -- The body of
Kathleen Roskot is carried from St. Patrick's Roman Catholic Church
last week following funeral services. Roskot, 19, a student at
Columbia University, was killed allegedly by her former boyfriend.
According to statistics collected by the FBI, 32 percent of the
3,419 women murdered in the United States in 1998, the latest year
for which data are available, died at the hands of a husband, a
former husband, a boyfriend or a former boyfriend. (Vic DeLucia/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOISE, Idaho -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- FALCON-2 -- Kim
Middleton, of the Peregrine Fund World Center for Birds of Prey,
with a female peregrine falcon used in the center's education
program. Though conservationists say the war to save endangered
species is being lost, the peregrine falcon is a stunning victory.
The American peregrine now has about 2,000 wild pairs nesting in
the United States and Canada, up from 39 in 1975. (Glenn Oakley/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Feb. 14, 2000 -- FALCON-1 -- Tom Cade, a
leader in efforts to establish the peregrine falcon in habitats old
and new, with one of the birds he helped save. Though
conservationists say the war to save endangered species is being
lost, the peregrine falcon is a stunning victory. The American
peregrine now has about 2,000 wild pairs nesting in the United
States and Canada, up from 39 in 1975. (Peregrine Fund/The New York
Times) LITE
