<HEADLINE>
PICK A CITY, PICK A GUIDE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   sidewalk.citysearch.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can get a head start on a real visit to a city by paying a
virtual visit on the Web. Which hotel? Look at them here.
Restaurants and bars? Of course. Shopping, working out, going to
the theater? They are all here, and much else besides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is Sidewalk, which is what it was called when it was a
Microsoft site. Last fall, Microsoft's money-losing Sidewalk was
absorbed by the TMCS (Ticketmaster) City Search site. Although if
you have a bookmark for sidewalk.com it will still work, you
wouldn't recognize what you used to use.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 70 cities in the country covered, you can do all
of the above, as well as get a weather forecast, horoscope, movie
times, links to local Web sites and dozens of other things.
</P>
<P>
   You can reserve a hotel room or a theater ticket (with the usual
Ticketmaster surcharge of 10 percent to 15 percent), even find a
date or get a recipe (``Food editor Steven Stern sings an ode to
the humble sausage in all its varieties''). The exact possibilities
differ from city to city. In New York, for instance, you can buy a
MetroCard on line.
</P>
<P>
   All this information and these services are not just for
travelers. In fact, City Search seems to be aimed primarily at
residents. But the effect is to give someone planning a trip the
kind of knowledge heretofore limited to the destination's
residents, especially those who don't mind doing research. Despite
its fullness, the site was pretty easy to navigate and moved along
swiftly most of the time. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   home.about.com/local &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its own content, provided by local people who are
named and pictured, this three-year-old site offers a huge
collection of links to hotels, restaurants and just about anything
else you can think of. But since you are dealing either directly
with the establishment or through a service independent of
About.com, what you can do on line will vary widely _ that is,
whether you can just gather information or can actually make
reservations or buy tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City site was divided into nine areas, not just the
five boroughs but also the Upper East Side, the East Village, and
so on. I checked out the ``New York: Downtown Site'' and found 35
links to subcategories for hotels, restaurants, theaters, even
``Downtown Legends,'' prose sketches that included W.H. Auden,
George Burns and G.G. Allin, a punk rocker described as ``perhaps
one of the most reprehensible people ever to live.''
</P>
<P>
   G.G. Allin aside, this is a quirky site, informative and fun.
There's plenty of shopping, weather reports, a joke of the day, and
hotels, hostels, bed-and-breakfasts in all ranges. The hotel site
alone includes the SoHo Grand, a ``large, expensive, swanky new
spot on Grand Street,'' and the Inn at Irving Place, which is
``decorated like your insane grandmother's sitting room.'' Using
About.com is like having an eccentric New York friend, steeped in
lore, planning your trip to the city. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   lastminutetravel.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sidewalk and About are for people who know where they are going.
LastMinuteTravel is for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   It was founded in April 1997 by David Miranda, a travel
marketer, and lists just-released offers from some 500 companies _
airlines, hotels, resorts, cruise lines, theaters and such _ which
you have to grab in a hurry. Scores of New York hotels were on
board (Secaucus, N.J., apparently counts as New York), the
offerings good for just a few days.
</P>
<P>
   There were no last-minute flights from New York to Los Angeles
the day I looked in. If you don't mind giving your name, e-mail
address, and ZIP code, however, LastMinute will put you on the My
Travel Minder service, and send an e-mail when the flight, or
hotel, or whatever becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   It should be emphasized that LastMinute is a listing service;
you deal directly with the listed establishment when the time comes
to reserve a seat or room. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
