<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tracing Freedom's Trail Through Philadelphia &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the Civil War, the Underground Railroad helped slaves
escape to freedom in the northern states and Canada, and
Pennsylvania played an important role in it. The Multicultural
Affairs Congress of Philadelphia recently published ``Underground
Railroad: Trail to Freedom,'' a guide to sites in the Philadelphia
area that were ``stations'' _ the various safe houses and other
sites along the secretive network where slaves on the run could
find refuge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only station stop in Philadelphia open to the public is the
Johnson House Historical Site. Used as a safe house, this tavern in
the Germantown area was frequented by Harriet Tubman and William
Still. But the guide documents 17 historical sites in Pennsylvania
that fugitive slaves may have stopped at in their quest for
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Other stations include the Bethel African Methodist Episcopal
Church in Lancaster and William Still's Last Residence in
Philadelphia, the stopping place for an estimated 95 percent of
escaped slaves passing through Philadelphia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The brochure also illustrates the ambiguity of Philadelphia's
position on slavery. As an important port, Philadelphia was a place
where slaves were both traded and protected. Mother Bethel A.M.E.
Church, for example, was founded in 1787 and sits on the oldest
piece of land in the United States that has been continuously owned
by African Americans, at 419 Richard Allen Avenue. And a marker at
2 South Front Street designates the site of the London Coffee
House, where prospective buyers gathered to view and purchase
slaves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The guides are free at the Philadelphia Visitors Center, 16th
Street and John F. Kennedy Boulevard, or from (888) 999-4668. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Danish Design Center Moves Into a New Home &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Danish Design Center, a showcase for Danish and
international industrial design and graphic arts, moved to new
headquarters overlooking Tivoli Gardens in Copenhagen on Jan. 10.
The five-story building, created by a Danish architect, Henning
Larsen, is clad with an energy-conserving double-glass screen that
provides natural climate control.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conceived as a clearinghouse for the design industry, as well as
a museum for the public, the new building includes 9,700 square
feet of exhibition space, a store selling books; Royal Copenhagen
and Georg Jensen tableware and other design items; a cafe;
conference rooms, archives and offices. Several exhibitions can run
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   A current show, ``Every New Idea ... Is a Combination of Two
Existing Ideas,'' running through June 4, explores the
serendipitous fusion of objects into new concepts. The creative
process of Gianfranco Zaccai's Continuum design firm, of Italy and
the United States, is examined through photographs, videos,
diagrams and development models in ``Start Anywhere, But Step
Back,'' through March 26. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The design center is at 27 H.C. Andersens Boulevard, 1553
Copenhagen V; telephone (45) 3369-3369; www.ddc.dk. Open Monday to
Friday 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. and Saturday and Sunday 11 a.m. to 4 p.m.
Admission: $5.30, at the rate of 7.5 kroner to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Corinne LaBalme &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Caribbean Hotel Joins an Upscale Crowd &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A deluxe new Caribbean hotel, Point Grace, is scheduled to open
March 1 on a 12-mile white-sand beach along Grace Bay on
Providenciales. The beach is home to an assortment of upscale
resorts on the north shore of the island, also known as Provo, the
most developed of the Turks and Caicos, an archipelago rich in
coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
   Point Grace incudes two four-story building in British Colonial
style, with a total of 23 with one-, two- and three-bedroom suites.
There are also four cottages, with a total of 10 suites, and two
villas, built in gardens and each with a pool. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to local lore, Grace Bay is named for a woman who
spent her honeymoon on Provo more than a century ago. A house
similar to her honeymoon cottage will be Point Grace's reception
area, where Continental breakfast will be served, along with hot
and iced cappuccino, espresso and tea throughout the day and wine
and hors d'oeuvres in the evening, all free.
</P>
<P>
   Adjoining the reception area will be a business center, a TV
lounge and a library with books, CDs and DVDs. The cottage sits
beside a pool, where casual lunches will be served. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The suites are outfitted with kitchens with Italian granite
counter tops, Turkish-marble bathroom vanities, Indonesian teak
furniture, silk and cotton fabrics, king-size beds, Frette linens
and robes, and silk-screened Indonesian sarongs. Each afternoon,
fresh fruit sorbet will be served on the beach; housekeepers will
turn down linens at night and light bedside oil lamps (scented if
preferred).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   High-season double rates at Point Grace, Post Office Box 700,
Providenciales, Turks and Caicos Islands, British West Indies,
(888) 682-3705, fax (649) 946-5097, start at $395 in a cottage
suite, plus 19 percent for tax and service; it drops to $275 on
April 25. The use of water-sports equipment and a shuttle to
restaurants are included. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frances Frank Marcus &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Topkapi: You Saw the Movie, Now See the Jewels &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of imperial jewels and other treasures from the
Topkapi Palace in Istanbul, including many that have never before
left the palace, will be seen this year in Washington, San Diego
and Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 200 objects that will be on view in the show, ``Palace
of Gold and Light, Treasures From the Topkapi, Istanbul,'' are a
16th-century ebony and ivory throne, inlaid with mother-of-pearl,
thought to have been used by Sultan Sulayman I, the Turkish
lawgiver, conqueror and patron of the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Of perhaps more popular interest is the 18th-century dagger,
originally meant as a gift for Nadir Shah of Iran, that was the
focus of the 1964 film ``Topkapi,'' in which Melina Mercouri, Peter
Ustinov and Maximilian Schell portray thieves who stumble over one
another trying to steal it. The dagger has three large emeralds in
its handle and a fourth concealing a watch, as well as rows of
diamonds on both sides of the handle.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the show are Ottoman textiles and silk robes, wool and
silk carpets, armor, porcelains and musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   The show opens March 1 at the Corcoran Gallery of Art, 17th
Street and New York Avenue NW, Washington, and runs until June 15.
The Corcoran is open daily, except Tuesday, from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.,
and until 9 p.m. on Thursday. Admission is $10 for nonmembers and
$8 for members, students and those older than 60. Information:
(202) 639-1700.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop will be the San Diego Museum of Art, 1450 El Prado
in Balboa Park, where the exhibition will run July 14 to Sept. 24.
The museum, which is open every day except Monday, has not set the
hours or admission fees for the show. Information: (619) 232-7931.
</P>
<P>
   The last stop will be the Museum of Art, 1 East Las Olas
Boulevard, Fort Lauderdale, from Oct. 15 to Feb. 28, 2001. The
museum is open noon to 5 p.m. on Sunday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday,
Wednesday and Saturday, and 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. on Thursday; closed
Monday. Admission fees have not been set. Information: (954)
525-5500.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin Molotsky &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
