<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6977 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LEWIS-HEARING-COX     02-14 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-HEARING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After glowing testimonies, Lewis expected to be out on bond
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pro football star Ray Lewis is expected to walk out of
the Fulton County Jail today after posting $1 million bond.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors failed to persuade a judge Monday that the Baltimore
Ravens middle linebacker, accused of a double murder poses a flight
risk or a threat to the community.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Doris Downs placed several restrictions on
Lewis along with the $1 million bond, including a curfew and
requiring him to stay in Maryland or Georgia until trial.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old All-Pro NFL player's family and friends embraced
each other, praised God and talked of having dinner after a
nine-hour hearing in the stifling courtroom. Lewis and his
attorneys shook hands and whispered to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Joseph Sweeting, indicted along with Lewis and
Reginald Oakley in the killings of Jacinth Baker and Richard Lollar
of Decatur, Ga. in Atlanta on Super Bowl night, was being
questioned and booked into the Fulton County Jail. Sweeting
surrendered to Atlanta police at about 11 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At Lewis' bond hearing, his legal defense team _ attorneys Ed
Garland, Don Samuel, Jana Harris and Max Richardson _ called 16
witnesses who gave glowing accounts of Lewis' kindness, generosity
and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a black striped suit, Lewis displayed little emotion
in the courtroom. An exception was when Baltimore radio personality
Wenda Royster testified about when Lewis and other Ravens players
helped the family of a poverty-stricken child who had been shot in
an accident. The family _ there were 13 other children in the
household _ could not afford to continue paying the rent for the
girl's wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and the other players made sure the child had money for
the wheelchair and other medical needs and even carried the girl
from her second-floor apartment so she could go outside, Royster
said.
</P>
<P>
   As she testified, Lewis blinked a few times as he attempted to
hold back tears. At one point he put his hand on his face, but
quickly regained his composure.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the witnesses at the bond hearing were character
witnesses for Lewis. A Atlanta resident told the court she saw from
her apartment window the fight that resulted in two men being
stabbed to death after a night of Super Bowl partying.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Keeler testified she called 911 after she saw the
altercation just after 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up to a giant photograph of her neighborhood, she
pointed to the crime scene and told Garland what she had seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw five men beating on two men who were pretty small,''
Keeler said. ``Shots were fired and then the five men took off
running.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeler could not say whether the assailants climbed into Lewis'
limousine. Police have said blood and knives were found in the
40-foot Lincoln Navigator the football player had rented.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on behalf of Lewis was close friend Warren Sapp, a
defensive tackle for the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. He told the judge he
had a deep trust in his former college teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give my children to Ray,'' Sapp testified.''They are
the most precious things I have and I would trust Ray to take care
of them anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors introduced only three witnesses after Downs ordered
the attorneys to wrap up the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest testimony against Lewis came from Lt. Mike Smith,
commander of the city's homicide squad. Smith said Lewis lied to
police and refused to give investigators the names of the people
who rode in his limousine the night of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator said Lewis gave them an incorrect name _ A.J.
Johnson _ as someone who was in the limousine and whose head was
injured in the melee that led to Baker's and Lollar's deaths.
Johnson has since been cleared in the deaths. But ``A.J.'' is also
the nickname of Reginald Oakley, the third man indicted in the
slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Bruce Harvey, recently hired to represent Oakley,
said he anticipates his client will surrender today. ``He maintains
his innocence,'' Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   Other damning evidence came from FBI agent Pewter McFarland. The
agent, a member of the Georgia Bureau of Investigation's Crime
Scene Unit, said he searched Lewis' hotel room and found traces of
a ``reddish brown'' stain, which McFarland believed to be blood.
The stains were found on a white bathrobe, a tissue and on
pillowcases.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Hale, a latent fingerprint examiner with the GBI, said
prints that matched to Lewis, Sweeting and Oakley were lifted from
Lewis' eighth floor room at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The room was disheveled, a mess,'' McFarland said. ``There
were glasses and bottles everywhere, as well as a lot of clothes
hangers on the floor.'' There were no clothes in the room except
for the bathrobe and a black t-shirt on a bed.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, prosecutor Clint Rucker argued Lewis is a
flight risk. He said Lewis has obstructed justice and ''that in
itself is a crime. This highly responsible man that everyone has
praised should not be granted bond because he didn't even take the
time to call police.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis ''has been described as the most responsible man on the
planet,'' Rucker said. ``He takes care of everybody ... but for two
folks dead on the street, he just didn't have time. ''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Downs said the state failed to prove its case against
granting bond for Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The judge enumerated the different occasions where Lewis spoke
to police the day of the killings and cited Lewis' offer to come
back from Hawaii after the Pro Bowl to cooperate with
investigators. She also noted that after Lewis missed his noon
flight to Hawaii, he called police and offered to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   When he met with police at his attorneys' house later that
night, he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot find where the state carried their burden to prove
the risk of fleeing,'' Downs said. ''The state did not present its
strongest evidence. Usually the state is proud to present its
strongest evidence, but I did not see that.''
</P>
<P>
   She ruled that Lewis must stay in Maryland and can only leave
the state to travel to Georgia in connection with this case. He
cannot consume alcohol or drugs and must adhere to a 9 p.m. nightly
curfew. He must also surrender his passport.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Baker and Lollar, the young men killed in the Jan.
31fight, left the courtroom shaking their heads. They declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted in their hometown of Akron, Lollar's grandmother,
Joyce Lollar, said she was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm looking to God for the guilty party to be punished,'' she
said. ``It don't matter if you have money. It don't mean you have
the right to kill people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lollar mentioned that Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell had said he
would get justice. ``I'm holding him to it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
