<HEADER>
A6978 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-MULTIMILLIONAIRE-S     02-14 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MULTIMILLIONAIRE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MILLIONAIRE'S FINAL ANSWER _ I DO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mysterious millionaire chooses his bride from 50 willing
candidates at the Las Vegas Hilton showroom, and marries her on the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   That's ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?,'' a two-hour
special airing Tuesday on the Fox network.
</P>
<P>
   Some chronically grumpy critics of TV might call this stunt
tacky. But the Fox executive who dreamed it up says they'd be
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a nice, lovely, elegant show,'' says Mike
Darnell, Fox executive vice president for specials and alternative
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Darnell is the good-humored guru whose previous Fox triumphs
include scary police chases, good pets gone bad and alien
autopsies.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' could trump them
all and stand forever as Darnell's piece de resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm not saying you won't find it somewhat weird,'' he
acknowledged. ``But you will not walk away thinking it's sleazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox taped the spectacle last Tuesday in the Vegas hotel-casino,
with Jay Thomas as the host. In the absence of a preview tape, we
have Darnell's description of the show.
</P>
<P>
   He said it begins with the 50 bachelorettes introducing
themselves on stage _ ``It looks pretty much like a Miss America
pageant _ while the wealthy bridegroom looks on. But you won't see
much of him yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a sort of pod,'' Darnell said. ``You can't see him
except his shadow.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell said he's no chintzy millionaire. Selected from about
100 volunteer bachelor millionaires, he had to open his financial
records to Fox to verify that he's worth over $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox has been guarding the groom's identity. It will say only
that he's in his early 40s, ``attractive,'' never been married and
doesn't live with his mother. Also that he's not a computer nerd;
Darnell said his wealth derives from ``several different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the show. The field of prospective brides, none of whom
will have met the millionaire, will be pared to 10 semifinalists.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 then take part in a compatibility quiz devised by the
producers and the millionaire. Viewers will also meet the groom's
friends and family members _ including his mother _ backstage.
They'll be posting their own ratings of the bachelorettes.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, there is a ``beachwear competition.'' There's a good
reason, Darnell said: ``We explain that our millionaire is an
outdoorsman.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell added, ``They chose whatever they wanted to wear. Most
of them went with two-piece swimsuits, but with taste. Whatever
they were comfortable wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The women were culled from more than 1,000 who answered ads from
the network. Darnell said the youngest contestant is 22, the oldest
40. Among the original 50, he said, there are ``regular-looking
women.''
</P>
<P>
   The semifinalists are trimmed to five finalists, who emerge in
wedding gowns to answer ``intimate questions.'' One example: Name
three things your husband can do to make you happy, and three
things to make you unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next we reveal our millionaire,'' Darnell said. He'll be
introduced in a prepackaged video piece, then make his appearance
onstage.
</P>
<P>
   At the climactic moment, the millionaire will approach one of
the five finalists, all still in wedding gowns, and propose to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could have said no when he proposed,'' Darnell said. But
she didn't. A Nevada judge turns up to perform the wedding
ceremony, while the showroom audience watches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very romantic,'' Darnell said.
</P>
<P>
   There are lovely parting gifts from Fox. The bride gets a
$35,000 engagement ring, not that it's a lengthy engagement, and a
new car. A honeymoon in an undisclosed location is part of the
deal, too.
</P>
<P>
   If the show posts big ratings, more multimillionaire TV weddings
are likely. May sounds good to Darnell; it's the next ratings
sweeps month.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada is a community property state.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
