<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-NYT     02-14 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY, OUTRAGED, DEFENDS HIS HEALTH PLAN
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A visibly incensed Bill Bradley lashed into Vice
President Al Gore for turning sharply negative in recent days,
accusing him of resorting to ``outrageous scare tactics'' in
criticizing Bradley's plan for universal health care.
</P>
<P>
   Straying from his typically even-tempered manner, Bradley
appeared red-faced and almost speechless with anger during a news
conference he called to rebut accusations by Gore, printed Monday
in The San Francisco Chronicle, that Bradley's health care plan
would deprive people with HIV and AIDS of health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just another example of a kind of meanness in politics
that is fundamentally destructive of an open dialogue on issues,''
said Bradley, who was flanked by several leaders of gay and lesbian
groups in San Francisco. ``It was the worst use of scare tactics
that I had seen in many years.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Gore's latest attack ``made my blood boil.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's outburst came two days after Gore used a speech before
a convention of the California Democratic Party to return to the
harshly negative attacks on Bradley's campaign agenda and character
that he had first used much earlier in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   During that speech, Gore asserted that Bradley had ``attacked
and demeaned'' the Democratic Party by criticizing the Clinton
administration. Bradley, by contrast, had refrained from making his
harshest attacks on Gore in his convention speech.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bradley's plan would hurt poor people with HIV because
it called for abolishing Medicaid, the government health care
program for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley says his plan would call for current Medicaid recipients
to receive coverage under the system of private insurance that now
covers federal employees, which he contends would be superior to
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who delivered education speeches Monday in Rochester,
N.Y., and Brooklyn and attended a fund-raiser in Manhattan on
Monday night, did not respond himself to Bradley's accusations.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's press secretary, Chris Lehane, said, ``Bradley's
health plan would replace Medicaid with a $150 monthly voucher,
which will not begin to cover the many services required by people
with HIV/AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley has had six months to refute Al Gore's
challenges on the merits,'' he said, ``and he has been unable to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had begun the day with a speech at the Sierra Club in
downtown San Francisco in which he assailed Gore's record on the
environment, accusing him of conducting policy by photo opportunity
and repeatedly failing to protect sensitive ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
   Sharply hitting Gore on one of his strongest issues, Bradley
ticked off a list of promises Gore had made before the 1992
election that the administration had failed to honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has been long on promise and short on
action,'' Bradley said. ``To be a custodian of the natural world
means more than paddling a kayak for TV cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was referring to a campaign event last summer where Gore
paddled a canoe down the Connecticut River in New Hampshire. It was
later reported that a local power company had released millions of
gallons of water into the river during a drought to ease Gore's
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with Bradley Monday was Brent Blackwelder, president
of the Friends of the Earth, a small national environmental group
that has endorsed Bradley, and Stewart Udall, who was secretary of
the interior for Presidents Kennedy and Johnson in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club and other national environmental groups have so
far stayed neutral in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore, who has written a book on global warming, was
considered a strong advocate for the environment before 1993, many
environmentalists have expressed disappointment with the
administration's environmental record over the last seven years.
And Bradley was clearly trying to stoke that dissatisfaction
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The insurgent got the loudest applause from the crowd of 150
people when he attacked the administration's recent decision to
extend 36 off-shore drilling leases along the California coast.
Bradley has criticized Gore for not fighting within the
administration to block the extensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president's silence is loud and clear,'' Bradley
said. ``And if he hasn't fulfilled the promises he made in 1992,
why should we believe the promises he's making today?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also asserted that the administration has bent
environmental rules to help big campaign contributors. He cited a
case in which the administration backed the construction of a
shopping mall in the environmentally sensitive New Jersey
meadowlands. The developer was a major contributor to Gore's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to rid our political system of the taint of political
money, just as we rid our world of the stain of pollution,''
Bradley said. ``I don't think it's acceptable that we sacrifice
protection of our natural world to campaign fund-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore, said, ``Attacking Al
Gore on the environment is like taking on Bill Bradley over
basketball. This administration is the most pro-environment in a
generation thanks to Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley used his speech to outline a concept he calls ``the land
ark,'' which would use federal funds to create protected habitats
for endangered species on federally owned land.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would ban all off-shore drilling along the
California and Florida seashores, expand federal programs intended
to conserve privately owned land and cut subsidies for mining, oil
exploration and livestock grazing on federal land.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Bradley trailing Gore by a substantial margin in
California, which holds its primary on March 7 along with about a
dozen other states, including New York.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said Bradley believes he must win, or at least stay
very close to Gore here, to keep his underdog campaign alive. To
that end he is likely to spend part of every week in California
until March 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
