<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, FEB. 15
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-SCHULZ-NYT (moved on Sunday, Feb. 13)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Charles M. Schulz sent by the New York Times
News Service on Sunday, Feb. 13, misidentified the NASA moon
mission in which the lunar excursion module was nicknamed Snoopy
and the command module Charlie Brown. It was Apollo 10, not Apollo
11.
</P>
<P>
   BC-DEMS-ABORTION-NYT (moved on Friday, Feb. 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Feb. 11,
about the endorsement of Al Gore by the Human Rights Campaign, a
gay and lesbian lobbying group, referred incorrectly in some copies
to the year in which a gay college student, Matthew Shepard, was
killed. It was 1998, not 1999.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MARKET-NYT (moved on Friday, Feb. 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Feb. 11,
about the stock market misstated the change of the yield on the
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond on Friday. It was a drop to 6.26
percent from 6.32 percent. The 6.43 percent figure was for a
different bond on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT (moved on Sunday, Feb. 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Feb. 13,
about efforts to sell The San Francisco Examiner misstated the
given name of a former mayoral candidate who broke an ankle in a
scuffle with the newspaper's editor in 1993. He is Clint Reilly,
not Curt.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-PLUTONIUM-WEAPONS-NYT (moved on Monday, Jan. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Jan. 24,
about the stability of plutonium used in the nation's nuclear
warheads referred incorrectly to the views of Dr. Matthew G.
McKinzie, a researcher with the Natural Resources Defense Council,
a Washington-based group that tracks nuclear arms issues. He said
that in theory instability in plutonium could reduce the lifetime
of weapon cores, not that it might cut their lifetime to as little
as 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
