<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-DOG-SHOW-NYT &LR;      02-14 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-SHOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF A SINGLE SENSATION AT THE WESTMINSTER DOG SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also DOG-JUDGE) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The baker's dozen of standard poodles trotted around
Ring 1 at the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show Monday, offering a
parade of cream, black and brown bouffant coifs, feathery ears,
snowball tails and pompom ankles. How do you choose the best of
breed?
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Jacklyn E. Hungerland, observed them with a trace of
a smile as they trotted around the ring, led by their handlers. She
examined each dog individually: their teeth, eyes, back, legs,
chest, muzzles and tufts of fluff.
</P>
<P>
   At the last breed judging of the first day of the two-day show,
a crowd of canine lovers cheered, hooted and hollered. (No one
screamed, ``You the dog!'') Ch. Aleph Blue Skies Outrageous
received most of the applause. ``He's very famous,'' a fan said
knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   Hungerland narrowed the field to six, including Ch. Unique Reach
for the Rainbow, the rambunctious one in the bunch. All the
excitement made him bark and rear back.
</P>
<P>
   Hungerland eyed the semifinalists, walking slowly past each one.
She took no notes as she searched for each dog's essential
poodleyness. She sent the six on a half-circuit around the ring.
</P>
<P>
   More barking from the rowdy poodle. Then, another full circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, her choice: Ch. Lake Cove That's My Boy, known
familiarly as Treson, over Ch. Davroff Stolichnaya, a similarly
cream-colored dog.
</P>
<P>
   The 3{-year-old Treson won his breed and the Nonsporting group
at last year's show, and went on to be the No. 1-ranked dog in the
country in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hungerland described her methodology in decidedly unscientific
terms. ``It's difficult,'' she said. ``The two cream-colored ones
were so close. They each have their merits and little quirks, but
one of them eventually stands up and says, `It better be me and
that's it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The 124th edition of the Westminster, which continues Tuesday,
is a kaleidoscope of 156 breeds and 2,500 dogs. The best-of-breed
winners compete in seven group competitions, from which a single
winner will be chosen Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After the dalmatian judging, the sweet embrace between Cheryl
Bartell and Ch. Mt. Bryton's Eau De Chloe indicated victory for the
4-year-old bitch. Chloe licked Bartell, her co-owner, and Bartell
kissed Chloe. ``Oh, do you want steak?'' Bartell asked, as if she
were offering fine victory chow. But Chloe had earned only an award
of merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should have won,'' Bartell said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Mary Lou King swooped her papillon, Ch. Loteki Beach
Party, called Bikini, into her arms when the dog was declared best
of breed. King's saucer-eyed toy bitch took the acclaim in stride.
But King was ecstatic, rushing with Bikini in hand to telephone her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done this six other times before,'' she said, referring
to her streak of breeding six of the Westminster's last seven best
papillons, including Kirby, last year's captivating best in show.
``But it's the first time I've been on the other end of the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   She stood outside the ring, where her 3-year-old had beaten 21
other overwhelmingly adorable rivals, and fed Bikini pieces of a
hot dog. ``She absolutely loves doing this,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage, in the dimly lighted benching area, where the dogs
are shaved, trimmed, combed and blow-dried, Karen Cramer
contemplated the final performance of Ch. Glengarry Chatterbox, her
6-year-old Dandie Dinmont terrier. Sassy, as she is known, left
with an award of merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bitch who won is a good bitch,'' Cramer said, while
combing the tan hair on Sassy's head. ``But mine was the No. 1
Dandie Dinmont of the year.'' Sassy will be bred next month, but
Cramer knows one thing about her: ``She'd rather be a show dog than
a mom.'' The evidence? When Sassy sees Cramer packing for a trip,
``she jumps into the suitcase.''
</P>
<P>
   The benching area is the canine clubhouse, a place for
preparation and conversation, with no argument over which music to
play. Here, an Akita's coat received a spritz of hair spray; locks
of hair from a Siberian husky took flight in service to his sleek
grooming; the majestic white Great Pyrenees sat stoically through
vigorous last-minute brushing and the miniature poodles underwent
more intensive teasing than Little Richard.
</P>
<P>
   But the action, of course, is in the rings. After Ch. Reignon
Dassin Alexandra won best of breed among 14 miniature poodles, her
coif was steadied with a spritz of hair spray for a photo
opportunity. Joseph Vergnetti, Alex's ponytailed handler, co-owner
and co-breeder, exulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the judge saw Alex's poodle attitude,'' Vergnetti
said, sweating after several vigorous trots around the right with
his 4-year-old. ``She's loaded with charisma.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
