<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-PROFILE-DOG-JUDGE-NYT     02-14 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-DOG-JUDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG LOVER FINALLY HAS HIS DAY AS JUDGE FOR TOP PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: see also DOG-SHOW) 
(DW) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe it all started when his mother, with the
frugality-before-frivolity ethos practiced by so many
Depression-era moms, wouldn't let him have a canine companion back
in Boston no matter how passionately he pleaded. Then as now, for
Chester F. Collier, dogs are serious, serious business.
</P>
<P>
   That's why nothing makes the 72-year-old Collier, Westminster
Kennel Club's president, more uptight than his duty to emerge, in
tuxedoed splendor, from a two-day sequestration straight into
Madison Square Garden's main arena Tuesday night to anoint the new
king (or queen) of the canine universe.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask his wife, Dorothy, a veteran of the once-in-a-lifetime
experience of judging best in show at Westminster. She is worried
that her husband, an otherwise unruffled senior vice president for
Fox News, may fret himself into a frenzy the way he did on the
career-altering day in his youth when, as an aspiring theater
director, he scored an interview with Oscar Hammerstein. The
project was ``Me and Juliet,'' the place was Boston, and the
thrill, apparently, was all Collier's. Still is.
</P>
<P>
   ``There I was, sitting in a theater talking to Oscar Hammerstein
himself; I almost had a heart attack, and I didn't get the job,''
marvels Collier, whose dreams of becoming ``the next Josh Logan
doing the next `South Pacific''' turned to pipe dreams once he
accepted a television post in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Collier did land the most coveted job in the dog
show hierarchy, passing final judgment at the Y2K rendition of the
124th Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show. And it has been an
obsession ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known for almost two years that this night was going to
come,'' said Collier, whose office is decorated with three busy
television sets. There's also a menagerie of canine replicas
ranging from a life-size Rottweiler (he loves Rotties, shepherds
and standard poodles) in repose atop his entertainment center to a
bobble-headed beagle (he thinks) figurine on his desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that I've spent two years thinking about
something that's going to be over in 15 minutes,'' he says of his
Andy Warhol waltz with fame. ``My only concern is picking the right
dog: there's no pressure like this.'' At least not for Collier, who
says that the two times his own show dogs, bouviers des Flandres,
won their breed and earned group placements at long-ago
Westminsters were ``on a par with winning my seven Emmys.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside here: Westminster 2000 is the culminating chapter in
the coffee table tome that the club commissioned on its history, so
after a quarter century behind the scenes as the show's go-to guy,
he finally plays leading man in this annual doggie drama. The
downside: Collier, whose Kennel Club cronies affectionately call
him a bit of a control freak for tweaking every last detail of the
show, has to steer clear of the premises and remain ignorant of the
seven finalists, per his own rules, until summoned for the big
pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we could get rid of him for two days was to have
him judge best in show,'' the show's chairman, Ron Menaker, said.
``I don't think he's too enamored of staying away. But when you
think Westminster, you think Chet, and to think he'd never judged
here, well, this was the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier's timing has not always been perfect. The day he met
Hammerstein, he assumed the interview portended his big break from
local theater to Broadway. Instead, he found himself teaching
speech and drama at Cathedral High School until a friend tipped him
off to an opening at Channel 4, Boston's new television station.
Collier didn't even own a TV set when he was hired as a production
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I'd do television until I got to New York and got
into the theater, but that was 1952, and here I am still in TV,''
he says with a no-regrets grin. He did make it to New York in 1957
_ as national program director for Westinghouse Broadcasting. It
was Collier, a keen judge of human as well as canine talent, who
discovered Mike Douglas in Cleveland in 1961 (``I hired him for
$400 a week'') and plucked Regis Philbin from an obscure Saturday
night talk show in San Diego in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Collier was 38 when he showed his first dog, a bouvier, and in
1973 he was invited to join the boys at Westminster. (Ladies need
not apply, a tradition dating back to 1877. As is giving away all
show revenues: greyhound rescue, police dogs and guide dogs are
current causes).
</P>
<P>
   After surviving the bark, bite and beauty of 2,493 other
contenders, this year's seven finalists, with an American TV
audience of 18 million and dog-crazy fans from 26 other nations
tuned in, will be scrutinized by Collier. There is no runner-up,
hence the nerve-racking mandate to point at the right pooch; human
egos, canine stud fees and sirloin at Sardi's for the champ all
depend on it.
</P>
<P>
   If Collier has a favorite dog, and he does, this is not the time
to dwell on it. Fact is, his heart, after 15 dogless years spent
working, judging, and settling into a second marriage with the
blessing of three grown children from the first, now belongs to
Lola, the piquant, portable Norwich terrier who runs things at the
Colliers' home in Norwood, N.J. Here, then, is Tuesday night's
final mantra: ``I'm not supposed to pick a cute one; I'm supposed
to pick the best one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
