<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION RIGHTS GROUP TO BACK GORE: Since Bill Bradley said last
month that Vice President Al Gore was being dishonest in denying
his past votes against abortion, the Gore campaign has worked
feverishly to secure an endorsement from abortion-rights
proponents, and that endorsement appears to be at hand. The
National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League is planning
to bestow its endorsement on Gore on Tuesday. Its past rating of
Gore, for voting in favor of abortion rights only 23 percent of the
time during his House tenure from 1976 to 1982, has been used
against him, but the group wants to repay the Clinton
administration for its strong support of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Katharine Q. Seelye
</P>
<P>
   NO TEXAS OFFICE FOR BRADLEY: Vice President Al Gore's campaign
opened a Texans for Gore office in Austin on Saturday in
anticipation of the state's March 14 primary. But local forces for
former Sen. Bill Bradley say they have no plans to open a state
headquarters. ``We don't spend money on space,'' said Peck Young,
political director for Bradley's Texas campaign. ``We spend money
on volunteers and materials. We really don't need a place for
people to hang out and drink Cokes.'' Garry Mauro, a former state
land commissioner and longtime friend of President Clinton, will
lead the vice president's Texas campaign. Bradley's effort will be
led by John Sharp, a former state comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   By Ross Millo
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   THE WAGES OF NEGATIVITY: Negative advertisements seem to be
effective _ in helping the candidate being attacked. In a Los
Angeles Times poll released on Sunday, 70 percent of the
Republicans surveyed said they had seen negative campaign
advertisements. But 64 percent of that group said the
advertisements made them react more negatively to the sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   THE STANDINGS IN OHIO: Gov. George W. Bush is still well ahead
of Sen. John McCain in Ohio, the latest poll shows, but his lead
has shrunk in the last month. The Ohio Poll, conducted over the
week that ended last Wednesday by the Institute for Policy Research
at the University of Cincinnati, found Bush ahead, 59 percent to 25
percent. A Jan. 19 poll had Bush ahead, 64 percent to 19 percent.
Gore's lead over Bradley, 68 percent to 24 percent, grew by 23
points since the January poll.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES:
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE: Republican candidates, Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: Atlantic City, N.J., and Brooklyn
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Irmo and Batesburg-Leesville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Baltimore, Washington and Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: Irmo and Columbia, S.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
