<HEADLINE>
WEATHERING THE STORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  SIMI VALLEY _ The Wood Ranch Golf Club's layout, with an
assist from Mother Nature, gave the LPGA fits during last weekend's
Los Angeles Women's Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Just six players finished under par in the three-round event,
played for the first time at the Simi Valley course.
</P>
<P>
   But the players' consensus on the quality of the course was
positive considering the miserable weather. Saturday's and Sunday's
rounds were played through steady rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough course. And when you throw in the wind and the
rain, it becomes even more difficult,'' said champion Laura Davies,
who finished 5-under par.
</P>
<P>
   At least two holes were deemed almost unplayable due to standing
water in the landing area. But that didn't prevent the leaders from
giving Wood Ranch a positive review.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a great course and it would have been great to
play it a little later in the year, maybe in March or April,'' said
Carin Koch, one of three golfers to share second place behind
Davies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the time would make a difference, but the greens
held up really well considering. The whole course was well
maintained and I liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Redman, another of the three runners-up, admitted the
bad weather kept the scores up. But even in the best of conditions,
the course wouldn't have made it an easy round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a pretty good golf course. The rough was tough; you
had to hit the ball straight, which I like. I think if they got the
fairways in a little bit better shape, it'd be great,'' Redman
said. ``You still have to hit the ball pretty straight here.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step is ensuring that the tour makes another stop at
Wood Ranch next year. The event was held at Oakmont Country Club in
Glendale for three years before Wood Ranch, the LPGA and tournament
promoter Group Dynamics Inc. struck a deal. The contract is for
three years, but each of the next two include an option to continue
the current setup for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do an evaluation whether or not to move forward for the
next two years,'' said Group Dynamics vice president Bob Collins,
who also served as the tournament's director.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's based on the (LPGA golfers), their contentedness for
the golf course. Also the LPGA's comfort level for the golf
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins' group will meet with the LPGA, the city of Simi Valley
and Wood Ranch representatives to discuss the tournament's future
in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Group Dynamics, an L.A.-based sports and
entertainment promotion company, has strived to develop a solid
working relationship with the city, Wood Ranch and its parent
company, American Golf Country Clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament organizers had to round up more than 365 volunteers
who did various jobs on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key here is . . . building relationships and everyone
working together. That's what Simi Valley offers,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially the city of Simi Valley. They want a big event.
They've got a big event. Now the key is for all of us to work
together to keep the event here so that it doesn't bounce around a
whole lot in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
