<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6991 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DRY-CLEANERS-ART-2NDT     02-14 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRY-CLEANERS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: as perc.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Micell's decision to create the Hangers franchise concept to
market the technology is another complication. Micell figured
franchising and exclusive territories would help overcome cleaners'
qualms about the big investment in equipment. But many cleaners do
not believe the Hangers name is as valuable as the familiar names
that have often hung on their stores for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Bruce Barish, a third-generation owner of Ernest
Winzer Cleaners in the Bronx, say they are interested in the
technology but are leaning toward working with a competing dioxide
design from Global Technologies, an El Segundo, Calif., company
that has been progressing more slowly toward commercialization than
Micell. Global has licensed seven manufacturers to make machinery,
which it said will be widely available later this year with no
franchising strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   The market was muddied further by the sudden appearance last
year of Zoots, a Newton, Mass., enterprise founded by Thomas
Stemberg, the chairman and chief executive of Staples, and Todd
Krasnow, one of his top lieutenants. Zoots is counting on marketing
and expansion skills learned at Staples to help it quickly create a
nationwide cleaning company emphasizing drive-through service and
other conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   Krasnow, Zoots' chief executive, said that he wanted nothing to
do with perc but that petroleum cleaning systems met Zoots' quality
and environmental needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the marketing geniuses versus the technology
mavens,'' joked Sam Brickle, the 62-year-old Rhode Island
industrialist who bought the rights from Micell to develop the
Hangers concept in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Brickle, who owns the last major textile mills in the region's
once-thriving textile industry, knows plenty about competition. At
this stage of Hangers' development, such experience has become more
crucial to Hangers' chances of fulfilling its green-chemistry
promise than DeSimone's technical brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Brickle rejected Micell's original concept of locating its
machines in stores. His cleaning plant is in a former metal
recycling mill in an industrial park he owns. Some customers come
right to the plant, but most clothes arrive from the three Hangers
shops that have opened in recent months. The plan is to open three
more by summer and a total of up to 25 within a 20-mile radius.
</P>
<P>
   Hangers of New England executives are also searching for
locations near Fairfield, Conn., Lowell, Mass., and Manchester,
N.H., to set up similar factories with satellite stores.
</P>
<P>
   Like many an investor in green-chemistry innovations, Brickle is
ending up more deeply involved than he originally envisioned. ``My
initial goal was to sell 1,000 franchises in New England,'' he
said, reflecting on his surprise at perc's continued hold on the
industry. ``Now it looks like we'll have to own a lot of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
