<SLUG> BC-SKATE-TV-RATINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SKATING TOPS THE RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first weekend without pro football since September, the
highest-rated televised sports event was the U.S. national
figure-skating championships.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Kwan's victory in the women's competition on Saturday
night helped ABC to an 8.5 overnight Nielsen rating, up 23 percent
from last year. The pairs competition, which was shown during the
first hour, rated a 7.6. But from 10 p.m. to 10:30 p.m., the
women's competition between Kwan and Sasha Cohen rated a 9.2, and
then jumped to a 9.7 from 10:30 p.m. to 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association All-Star Game on NBC on
Sunday evening fell 31 percent to an 8.3 overnight rating, down
from a 12.1 two years ago, when Michael Jordan made his final
appearance at the midseason game. The owners' lockout last season
prevented the playing of the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tiger Woods did not win his seventh consecutive PGA
Tour tournament at the Buick International on Sunday afternoon, the
event scored a higher overnight rating than it did last year, when
he won it. The 8.0 rating was 31 percent higher than the 6.1 posted
for the final round of the tournament last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
