<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEWIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAIL IS SET AT $1 MILLION FOR LEWIS IN MURDER CASE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JON NORDHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A state judge ruled Monday night that All-Pro
linebacker Ray Lewis may be released on $1 million bail but must
remain at his home in Maryland except for court appearances here.
Lewis faces murder charges in connection with two stabbing deaths
after a Super Bowl party two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers said it would probably take until Tuesday for
the bail arrangements to be made. Lewis, 24, a star of the
Baltimore Ravens, must remain in Fulton County Jail until then.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis buried his face in his hands at the announcement by Judge
Doris L. Downs of Superior Court and hugged his attorneys, his only
show of emotion after sitting through nearly seven hours of
testimony and argument.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens' owner, Art Modell, headed a group from the club who
came to Atlanta in support of Lewis. Modell, Ernest Byner, director
of player development, and Rod Woodson, a safety, all took the
stand along with a long line of other character witnesses to
portray Lewis as ferocious middle linebacker on the field but a
peacemaker off it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been a good citizen for the Baltimore Ravens,'' Modell
said. ``He's the first to respond to visit a hospital or a
children's home.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay defensive end Warren Sapp, his trademark long braided
hair falling on broad shoulders packed tightly in a dark business
suit, described his former teammate at the University of Miami as
easygoing and fun loving. ``I would entrust my kids with him, and
they are the most important parts of my life,'' he told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The bond hearing did not rest on Lewis' guilt or innocence, and
in fact the judge said that the state had determined ``not to
present the strength of its case today.''
</P>
<P>
   Downs said the state had failed to persuade her that Lewis posed
a danger to the community or would attempt to flee from
prosecution, the criteria for denying bail. She also said the
absence of a felony police record weighed in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   She did, however, say he could not leave Maryland, his principal
residence, unless it was to appear in Georgia for proceedings in
his case. She also imposed a curfew for him to be home by 9 o'clock
every night and to completely abstain from consuming alcohol and
illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what the curfew and the limits
imposed on his movements outside Maryland might do to his playing
career if his case was not resolved before next summer, when the
Ravens begin preseason games. Those close to the defense said that
if necessary, the court would be asked to adjust his bail
requirements to allow him to pursue his livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis became the National Football League's highest-paid
linebacker in 1998 when he signed a four-year contract worth more
than $26 million. Lewis, who is 6 foot 1 and 245 pounds, is
credited with 673 tackles in 60 pro games.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has been held without bail since his arrest on Jan. 31,
the day of the stabbings. He and two companions were indicted last
week on murder and assault charges. Investigators said the three
were the principal figures in the attack on Richard Lollar, 24, and
Jacinth Baker, 21, who were stabbed during a fight outside an
Atlanta nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday one of the suspects, Joseph Sweeting of Miami,
turned himself in, a spokesman for the Atlanta police said. The
other suspect, Reginald Oakley of Baltimore, is still at large, the
police said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lewis and his party of 10 left the Cobalt Lounge in the Buckhead
section of Atlanta shortly before 4 a.m. What happened when some of
the men in Lewis' group tangled with a group of about a half-dozen
men while walking to his hired limousine remains in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers describe the scene as beginning with an exchange
of words that suddenly flared into an eruption of violence. They
argue that Lewis' only role was a short-lived attempt to drag his
companions away from the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the state's case apparently rests on the testimony of
the limousine driver, Duane Fassett of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   When Ed Garland, the lead defense lawyer, tried Monday to get
Atlanta homicide detectives to divulge elements of interviews with
Fassett, the prosecution objected, saying hearsay evidence could
not be introduced at a bond hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
