<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAN IS MORE THAN HALF A MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - His name was Ira Pomerantz.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when we didn't know who he was, which made it a
lot easier to talk and even (be honest) joke about his death and
the horrible things done to his body. But now we know.
</P>
<P>
   His name was Ira Pomerantz.
</P>
<P>
   He was 60 years old and the father of grown daughters. He had
friends, a life, a past. He had hopes and dreams, though perhaps
fewer than when he was young. Then, one day in January, he
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, a deliv eryman described for Mesa po lice
how he watched a small, blond woman in a 1997 Jaguar pull up to a
trash bin behind the Bashas' supermarket at Mc Dowell and Power
roads. He said the woman hauled a large bundle from the car, lifted
it into the trash, then drove off.
</P>
<P>
   It was part of a man's body, the torso. No arms or legs or head.
</P>
<P>
   In my business, we love these stories, and for good reason. We
love them because you love them.
</P>
<P>
   Within a day or so after the gruesome discovery, all the
television stations in town pro duced special logos that flashed
behind the news anchors when ever the story was discussed. ``Torso
Investigation,'' one said. And ``Torso Murder'' and ``Torso Case.''
</P>
<P>
   The new definition of TV news: A talking head discussing a
torso.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same in the papers, even after the body had been
identified.
</P>
<P>
   The woman behind the wheel of the Jaguar, a Scottsdale beauty
salon owner named Vale rie Pape, was arrested and eventually
charged with the murder of her husband, Ira Pomerantz. His body had
been cut apart, possibly with an elec tric saw.
</P>
<P>
   Pape said she found Pomer antz dead, lying in a pool of blood in
the kitchen of her Scottsdale home. Supposedly, a gun was nearby.
Pomerantz was shot in the back. Pape admitted tossing part of her
husband's body in the trash, but wouldn't say what happened to the
rest of him.
</P>
<P>
   Friends have described her as ``gentle,'' though it's difficult
to imagine such a person help ing to dismantle and dispose of human
being _ a person by the name of Ira Pomerantz.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long last name. It doesn't have the zip that ``torso''
does. ``Bullet found in torso case'' read one headline. And ``Torso
discovery horrifies, fas cinates Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   As if it's possible for a man to be less than the sum of his
parts.
</P>
<P>
   There was trouble in the cou ple's marriage, reporters learned.
There were accusa tions of violence, and struggling business
ventures. But there was at least one area of his life in which
Pomerantz had sup port. It came from his girls.
</P>
<P>
   They wrote a letter to a local newspaper that read in part:
``While we are in the process of mourning the loss of our father
and trying to understand his needless and brutal murder, we deeply
regret that the media has chosen to portray him in such a negative
and false light.''
</P>
<P>
   They went on to say, ``During the course of his (15 year mar
riage) to our mother he never abused her in any way and in our home
we were never ex posed to any abuse, whether physical or otherwise.
. . Throughout his life, he never failed those close to him.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know him. I don't know all of his faults or all of his
good qualities, only what I read in the papers and what his
daughters said about him.
</P>
<P>
   His name, however, was Ira Pomerantz. The next time some media
type calls him ``the torso,'' do his family a favor, do yourself a
favor, and remember what he really is _ the victim. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini &LR; Arizona Republic.com or (602)
444-8978. &QL; 
 &QL; 
His name was Ira Pomerantz not ``The Torso.'' We should remember
that. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
