<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH-SATELLITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS CORP. STUDYING MERGER OF ITS SATELLITE UNITS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. said Monday that it
was strongly considering consolidating all of its satellite-related
businesses into a single company that could provide Internet
service from space to nearly the entire globe.
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp. is expected to control the new company but could
offer a minority stake to the public, a person close to the
situation said. It might also seek investments from computer
software and hardware companies, and providers of entertainment and
information.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement issued Monday, the company said, ``It is
premature to speculate on the final format of this umbrella entity,
the makeup of its assets, the identity of its investors or whether
the entity will be a public company.''
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp. hopes that its satellites, which already provide
television to Europe, Latin America, Asia and Australia, could be
used to provide high-speed data transmission as well. This would
place the satellites in competition with cable modems and digital
subscriber telephone lines, which are now starting to offer
high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning off part of the satellite company to the public would
also be a way for News Corp. shareholders to realize a higher value
from the satellite holdings. The company has previously offered the
public a minority stake in Fox Entertainment, which represents the
News Corp.'s entertainment, cable and sports assets.
</P>
<P>
   Providing Internet access and other data services over satellite
is likely to become a competitive field. Hughes Electronics, the
General Motors Corp. subsidiary that owns the DirecTV satellite
television service, and rival Echostar Communications are each
planning such services, as are start-ups like Teledesic, a company
run by Craig O. McCaw, the cellular telephone pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp.'s weak spot is the United States, where it does
not own satellite broadcasting operations. If it wanted to get into
the American market it might have to buy Hughes or Echostar, both
of which are very pricey because of rapid run-ups in their stock,
or one of the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   But the News Corp. hopes that by using its existing satellites
it can get a jump on the market, particularly outside the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp. owns Star TV in Asia, a 40 percent stake in
British Sky Broadcasting, and minority stakes in Japan Sky
Broadcasting, Sky Latin America, Germany's Premiere, Italy's Stream
and Australia's Foxtel.
</P>
<P>
   All of those are expected to be included in the umbrella entity
along with the News Corp.'s 80 percent stake in NDS Group PLC, a
publicly traded pay-television technology company, and its 20
percent stake in TV Guide International, the company that will be
formed when Gemstar International Group completes its acquisition
of TV Guide. Plans for the new satellite company were first
reported in Monday's Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Peled, chief executive of NDS, once known as News Digital
Systems, said the company's satellites would first be used to
deliver popular Web pages at speeds of up to eight megabits per
second. Satellites can broadcast these pages to millions of users
at the same time at the same high speed, while cable modems slow
down as more people use the system. These pages could be stored on
a computer's hard disk for users to call up at their convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Early systems will not allow users to transmit to the satellite,
so consumers wanting to request a specific Web page or to send
electronic mail will still need a telephone line or cable modem.
Two-way communication with a satellite will come in a few years
with a new generation of satellites, Peled said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
