<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI GOES NORTH TO CRITICIZE CLINTONS ON HEATING-OIL PRICES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Soothing Republicans who complained that he had
not campaigned enough upstate, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani made a
hastily arranged trip here Monday to criticize Hillary Rodham
Clinton and President Clinton for their handling of rising
heating-oil prices, a pressing issue in northern New York state.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Saturday, Giuliani's aides said he had no plans
to travel north of New York City this week. But that was before
news reports quoted upstate Republican officials who insisted that
he must spend more time in the region to defeat Mrs. Clinton in the
race for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor contended that his visit, to speak to a private
meeting of Republican county chairmen and other party officials,
was aimed only at publicizing the problem of heating-oil prices and
at pressuring the Clinton administration to address it.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had called the state party chairman, Bill Powers,
during the weekend. ``I asked Bill if I could come talk to them for
a few minutes,'' he said, ``and then the fact is we knew that if we
did that, we would be able to draw a few of these cameras so that
we could get this message out.''
</P>
<P>
   But some party leaders said the visit was meant to give Giuliani
needed exposure in a region where Clinton has campaigned
extensively. They said they were placated by his appearance and by
indications that the mayor planned to get upstate more often.
``This gets him on the evening news, which is what we need,'' said
one county chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani repeated his call for the president to release oil from
the Strategic Petroleum Reserve to drive down the cost of home
heating oil. Oil-producing countries have cut back production,
driving up the price of gasoline and heating oil. Prices have risen
fastest in the Northeast, with suppliers' low inventories on
reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has refused to release oil from the
federal reserves, saying it should be saved for true emergencies.
But this month, the administration authorized $130 million in
federal aid to low-income people to help with their heating bills.
The largest piece of that, $34 million, went to New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
