<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-BALLOT-NYT &LR;      02-14 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BALLOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ALBANY'S SNOOZING LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 15:
</P>
<P>
   Now that a federal court has blocked attempts to keep Sen. John
McCain off the ballot in New York's March 7 presidential primary,
the state's top lawmakers need to turn their attention to permanent
reform of New York's insane presidential ballot rules. So far only
one Albany leadership figure, the State Senate's Democratic
minority leader, Martin Connor, has shown any interest in this
vital project. The real powers in the capital _ Gov. George Pataki;
Joseph Bruno, the Senate majority leader; and Sheldon Silver, the
Assembly speaker _ are demonstrating a collective failure of
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Connor introduced a measure that would lift New York
into the ranks of such recognized democracies as Connecticut and
California. Under Connor's legislation, Senate Bill 6482, the
executive director of the State Board of Elections would put on the
ballot all ``nationally known and recognized candidates'' who wish
to appear. Delegates would be apportioned based on the popular vote
for the candidates in each congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Connor has gotten things rolling in the right
direction, Pataki has a special obligation to help repair New
York's reputation. Along with State Republican Party apparatchiks,
he tried to rig the primary for Gov. George W. Bush _
notwithstanding the court's rejection of a similar attempt to limit
the primary ballot for former Sen. Bob Dole in 1996. But Pataki
seems becalmed when it comes to the subject of changing the state's
unfair election laws. His press office says that having failed to
fix the state's presidential primary system during six years in
office, the governor feels he can wait an additional four years
until he has to address the issue. It's odd that Pataki, who labors
so hard to look progressive on other issues, wants to look like a
machine pol on this one.
</P>
<P>
   Also puzzling is Sheldon Silver's refusal of the mantle of
progressive leadership. As the Legislature's most powerful
Democrat, he should lead on voting rights and ballot access. But
instead of joining with Connor, Silver is hunkered down like
Pataki. The speaker sent word through his press secretary that he
``doesn't want to rush into anything.'' How long, one wonders, does
Silver need to ponder a proposition that was pretty well settled by
the American Revolution? Hey, let people vote!
</P>
<P>
   As for Bruno, he reacted to Connor's bill by going into partisan
attack mode, allowing his spokesman to say that the majority leader
does not take his lead from Senate Democrats. He also said that
Connor, an election lawyer, would be a more credible spokesman for
ballot reform if he gave up representing private clients in fights
over petitions and other ballot matters.
</P>
<P>
   The point about Connor's outside legal practice is well taken.
But it does not detract from the obvious merit of his proposal to
put New York's battalions of ballot-blocking lawyers out of work.
If Bruno is unhappy about following Connor's leadership on this
issue, he has the votes to take over the crusade. The current
Pataki-Silver-Bruno strategy of immobilization cannot repair the
state's democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
