u a BC-KIMES-TRIAL-510&AMP;ADD-N     02-14 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIMES-TRIAL-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNTANGLING COMPLEX SCHEMES IN DEATH OF SOCIALITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mother and son accused of murdering an Upper East
Side millionaire devised a scheme to steal her town house with so
many details that they were eventually tripped up by the complexity
of the scheme, prosecutors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The plan by the mother and son, Sante and Kenneth Kimes, to
steal Irene Silverman's $10 million home and then kill her included
the use of 30 false names, three fake offers of Caribbean
vacations, and a well-used stolen credit card, the lead prosecutor,
Connie Fernandez, said in her opening statement in the Kimeses'
murder trial in state Supreme Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their arrogance and greed overcame their common sense,'' said
Fernandez, an assistant Manhattan district attorney. ``They left a
trail of bread crumbs, so to speak, for police to follow, from
California to Las Vegas, from Las Vegas to Florida, from Florida to
New York City and to Irene Silverman's home.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Kimeses made their way through Manhattan, Fernandez said,
they tried to trick people into helping them seize control of
Silverman's East 65th Street mansion. They tried to persuade two
bankers to alter a check, two notaries public to certify a forged
deed, one of Silverman's employees to reveal a Social Security
number, and another person to give up a parking space, Fernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman, a widowed socialite, was 82 when she was last seen by
an assistant on July 5, 1998, a day after she told friends that she
planned to evict Kenneth Kimes from a $6,000-a-month apartment in
the town house that he had rented under a false name, Fernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after the assistant left Silverman alone in her
room, the prosecutor added, the Kimeses killed her, put her body in
a duffel bag and disposed of it in an effort to buy enough time to
finish gaining control of the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe she is dead,'' Fernandez said. ``We believe they
murdered her and that they did it to get her out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverman's body has never been found. But prosecutors said
dozens of spiral-bound notebooks filled with writings by the
Kimeses provided the outline and evidence of their scheme to steal
the mansion. The notebooks, the prosecution said, contain a list of
information the Kimeses needed about Silverman, detailed schedules
of her domestic staff and notes about New York's complex real
estate laws.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Kimes, 24, grew pale as he listened to the prosecutors'
opening argument, in stark contrast to his demeanor a few hours
earlier, when he was laughing with his lawyer. Sante Kimes, 65, who
has given up her dyed black hair, wide-brimmed hats and dark
glasses for gray hair, a pantsuit and half-glass spectacles, looked
equally sober, and at one point halted her almost incessant note
taking, the same habit that prosecutors contend will seal her fate.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is to give its opening statement Tuesday. An
84-count indictment accuses the Kimeses of second-degree murder,
robbery, conspiracy, fraud, weapons possession, larceny and
eavesdropping, among other charges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Justice Rena K. Uviller, who is presiding over the case, has
issued an order prohibiting the lawyers from discussing specifics
of the case. But Mel A. Sachs, Kenneth Kimes' lawyer, said: ``This
case should be based on the evidence and the lack of evidence. The
jury should consider the quality, not the quantity, of evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez recited for jurors the first names of at least a dozen
of the 125 prosecution witnesses they are to hear from. Among the
most important may be the assistant, identified only as Aracellis,
who last saw Silverman and who Fernandez said took three suspicious
calls at Silverman's home on the day of the socialite's
disappearance _ two from Kenneth Kimes and one from a person
apparently disguising his or her voice.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said the Kimeses had made those calls to learn where
Aracellis was and what she knew, and to try to persuade her to
leave the house.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors will also rely on the testimony of Stanley
Patterson, who they say was summoned to New York by Sante Kimes to
take over the town house, fire the staff, change the locks and
evict the tenants. But Patterson was an informant for the FBI and
tipped off investigators. After he and Sante Kimes met,
investigators arrested the Kimeses on a Utah warrant accusing them
of buying a car with a bad check.
</P>
<P>
   Inside that car, Fernandez said, investigators found a gun,
ammunition, syringes, a powerful sedative, disguises, a page of
stolen Social Security numbers and some of the Kimeses' notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Because Silverman's body has not been found, the evidence from
the car, along with the fake deed, will be crucial. But despite the
lack of a body, Fernandez told jurors, the prosecution would have
no trouble proving that Silverman was murdered and did not simply
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they would also show that Silverman would never
have sold her house. ``She was a sharp businesswoman,'' Fernandez
said. ``She knew what she wanted and she knew what she didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
