<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-14 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7134 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-ALASKA-CRASH-SPI &LR;      02-14 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-CRASH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA DEFENDS MECHANICS' DECISION NOT TO REPLACE PART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Alaska Airlines said its mechanics did exactly what
they were supposed to two years ago when they decided not to
replace a key part of the stabilizer control system on the plane
that crashed two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The part _ a large nut that runs up and down a jackscrew to move
the stabilizer wing atop the tail _ was initially believed to be in
need of replacement. But it was left in place after it was tested
several times and determined to be well within the wear limits set
by Boeing, Alaska Airlines officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the multiple re-checks of the jackscrew and gimbal nut
assembly found it to be within specifications, no action was
necessary under Boeing's maintenance manual, which is approved by
the FAA,'' Alaska said in a statement on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Questions are being raised about Alaska's maintenance work after
the National Transportation Safety Board disclosed Sunday night
that mechanics at the airline's heavy maintenance facility in
Oakland, Calif., decided in 1997 to replace the nut, then changed
their minds the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators suspect a badly worn jackscrew assembly led to the
Jan. 31 crash of Alaska Flight 261. All 88 people on the jet died.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's 40-foot horizontal stabilizer, which controls the
airplane's tendency to pitch up and down in flight, is known to
have jammed 12 minutes before the crash, sending the plane into an
initial dive of more than a mile from its cruising altitude of
31,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots regained control of the jet and flew for another nine
minutes before a second and much more violent dive _ still
unexplained _ sent the plane plunging into the ocean from 18,000
feet.
</P>
<P>
   During a heavy maintenance check on the plane on Sept. 29, 1997,
mechanics performed a test to determine the looseness of the
8-inch-deep nut. This is known as an ``end play'' check. The nut is
kept still and mechanics see how far the jackscrew can wiggle.
</P>
<P>
   The initial examination of the jackscrew and nut assembly
indicated that the endplay of the jackscrew was .040 of an inch,
within limits prescribed by Boeing, Alaska officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing instructs mechanics to ``Check that endplay limits are
between .003 and .040 inch. Readings in excess of above are cause
for replacement of acme jackscrew and nut.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's instructions also state that the measurement should be
repeated several times to ensure consistent results, Alaska said.
So mechanics the next day re-tested the nut and found the endplay
was .033. Five more checks showed the nut was within standards,
Alaska said.
</P>
<P>
   An airline spokesman said the nut and jackscrew assembly would
have been checked for wear again in about 30 months.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska's statement does not explain why mechanics initially
decided to replace the nut before doing additional tests.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation consultant C.O. Miller, a former NTSB senior
investigator, said Monday he has questions about why mechanics
changed their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always suspicious of paperwork,'' he said. ``You can get a
much different understanding of what happened once you talk with
the mechanics ... and investigators will certainly be doing just
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said investigators, among other things, will want to know if
replacing the nut would have delayed returning the plane to
service.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB investigators reportedly are exploring a theory that the
nut was so badly worn before the crash that it was able to slip
freely up and down the jackscrew, which works much like an electric
garage door opener.
</P>
<P>
   The stabilizer was jammed in its full up position, which was
pushing the nose of the plane down with such force that it likely
took the efforts of both pilots pulling on their control columns to
keep the plane's nose up.
</P>
<P>
   If the stabilizer suddenly deflected further, past mechanical
stops because the nut slipped up the jackscrew, that might explain
the plane's violent fatal dive, aviation experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Under orders from the FAA, airlines Friday began a visual
inspection of the jackscrew assembly in about 1,100 planes _ the
entire U.S. fleet of MD-80s, MD-90s, their predecessor, the DC-9,
and a newer derivative, the Boeing 717 (formerly the MD-95). The
deadline to complete those inspections was Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency also gave airlines 30 days to measure wear in
the jackscrew assembly.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, U.S. had airlines reported 23 planes with
``positive findings,'' ranging from metallic grit in the jackscrew
grease, which may be a sign of normal wear, to shavings, which are
not, said FAA spokesman Less Dorr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to speculate on what the results mean because
there is no pattern, at least none that has been found,'' Dorr
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some airlines performed the test for wear at the same time
mechanics made the visual inspection.
</P>
<P>
   At least two planes, one at Delta and one at AirTran, failed the
test that measured the nut and jackscrew assembly for wear.
</P>
<P>
   The jackscrews were replaced in a number of planes after the
inspections, Dorr said. They are now in the hands of either the FAA
or the safety board and all will be examined.
</P>
<P>
   No problems have been found in 29 C-9 aircraft operated by the
Navy and Marine Corps, said Navy spokeswoman Lt. Elizabeth
Zimmermann. The C-9 is the military version of the DC-9.
</P>
<P>
   Dorr gave this breakdown of what has so far been reported to the
FAA by the airlines:
</P>
<P>
   _ Airborne Express, 75 planes: Two jackscrews needing
lubrication.
</P>
<P>
   _ AirTran, 44 planes: Two had grit in the jackscrew grease, one
failed the wear check. All three jackscrews replaced. All were
DC-9s, and none of AirTrans' nine new Boeing 717s had problems, a
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alaska Airlines, 34 planes: Eight were found to have metal
shavings on or around the jackscrew. Four jackscrews replaced,
others being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   _ American Airlines, 284 planes: One jackscrew lacked lubricant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Continental Airlines, 69 planes: One plane had grit in the
jackscrew grease. The part was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   _ Delta Air Lines, 136 planes: Four problems found, including
the one that failed the wear test. That plane's jackscrew assembly
was replaced. Two planes had grit in the assembly. One had metal
shavings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hawaiian Airlines, 15 planes: Two had shavings in the grease.
Both jackscrews replaced.
</P>
<P>
   _ Northwest Airlines, 172 planes: One found with grit in the
grease. The jackscrew was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   _ TWA, 131 planes. One plane with with metal shavings. The
jackscrew was replaced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
