<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SHIFTING POLITICS OF THE CONFEDERATE BATTLE FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republicans began this election cycle with a conciliatory
tone on race, hoping to attract support from members of the black
middle class, many of whom fit the GOP profile but were put off by
the race-baiting and Willie Hortonizing that dominated Republican
politics during the 1980s. George W. Bush seemed to be reaching out
to black voters early on, when he took his message of inclusion and
``compassionate conservatism'' into African-American communities
that had rarely seen Republican candidates in the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans have reverted to old tactics in South
Carolina, where the two leading presidential candidates have hedged
their bets for the Feb. 19 primary by supporting the right of South
Carolinians to fly the Confederate battle flag over the State
Capitol, despite the flag's association with segregation and the Ku
Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   This compromise with bigotry has proved convenient for the
candidates at this moment. But it could also stimulate the black
vote across the Deep South in the general election, threatening the
Republican grip on Congress and aiding the Democratic attempt to
keep control of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took the traditional states'-rights approach in South
Carolina, arguing from the start that the issue of whether to keep
the flag rested with South Carolinians themselves. But Sen. John
McCain took one side and then the other, saying at first that the
flag was ``offensive'' and a ``symbol of racism and slavery,'' then
reversing himself, saying that it was defensible to fly the flag
over the capitol because it symbolized Southern honor in battle. In
truth, the Confederate battle flag as we know it today has little
to do with the glories of the Civil War and everything to do with
the backlash against civil rights that eventually made the flag a
symbol of choice among neo-Nazis, skinheads and other bigots.
</P>
<P>
   In the years immediately following the Civil War, the
Confederate battle flag was not an omnipresent symbol in the South.
But around the time of Jefferson Davis' death in 1889 there was a
blossoming of ``lost cause'' nostalgia, and the flag emerged as an
icon of defiance and racism.
</P>
<P>
   The flag returned to popularity in the 1890s just as the former
Confederacy was stripping blacks of the rights to vote and hold
political office, which they had briefly enjoyed just after the
Civil War. The flag had begun its transformation from an emblem of
a dead cause to a symbol of resistance to Reconstruction and civil
rights and, later, to an emblem associated with night riders and
vigilante terrorists. By the mid-20th century the battle flag had
been fully appropriated by the Klan and other extremists, who
displayed it at cross-burnings and lynchings and to show resistance
to black demands for civil rights and equal treatment under the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Apologists in South Carolina say that the flag was hoisted over
the capitol for the centennial of the Civil War, then mistakenly
left flying. In truth, the flag went up in 1962, a full year after
the centennial. State officials were in a dispute with the Kennedy
administration, which had urged the integration of the Charleston,
S.C., hotel where a centennial convention was being held. When
South Carolina refused to admit black delegates to the hotel, the
convention was moved to a nearby military base.
</P>
<P>
   The flag's appearance a year later was an implicit endorsement
of segregation _ and the premise that black citizens were unworthy
of sharing public accommodations with whites. South Carolina's
present governor, Jim Hodges, tacitly acknowledged this negative
symbolism in this year's State of the State Message, when he
implored the legislature to remove the flag, reminding it that
``the entire nation is watching and listening to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In previous presidential campaigns, the flag issue in South
Carolina came and went quickly with little fanfare or lasting
impact. This year's dust-up brought a demonstration by civil rights
activists that included nearly 50,000 people, followed by the
threat of an economic boycott against the state. In a development
that should shame both Bush and McCain, a group of former state
legislators who were serving while the flag went up recanted the
decision and urged the current legislature to bring it down.
</P>
<P>
   The flag will eventually come down, making South Carolina the
final state to put it away. By failing to take a strong position
now, the GOP has missed an easy opportunity to distance itself from
offensive racial politics and to build the beginnings of a bridge
to the black electorate. In the quest to wring every possible white
vote out of South Carolina, Bush and McCain have identified their
party yet again with forces that have poisoned our national
politics for more than 100 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-00 2349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
