<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-SCENE-715&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSTILE CHORUS PUNCTUATES TESTIMONY IN DIALLO TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The hooting started around the time Sean Carroll
said he had become a police officer because he was raised to help
people. For the busload of people who had come from New York City
to the overflow courtroom in the Albany County courthouse, where
the trial can be seen daily on closed-circuit television, that
answer was only one of many that strained credulity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liar,'' one woman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When does he get his Academy Award?'' a man asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told better lies to my mother,'' another said.
</P>
<P>
   When Carroll choked up as he was asked about the fatal shooting
of his friend Officer Kevin Gillespie, the room rocked with
disdain. ``Unh unnhhh,'' people called out. A few hissed.
</P>
<P>
   When Carroll said he had seen Diallo ``slink back'' into the
vestibule, there were grunts of outrage. When Carroll said he and
Officer Edward McMellon had clearly identified themselves as
police, there were guffaws of skepticism. And when Carroll said
Diallo ``just didn't want to listen,'' a chorus of heys and ohhhs
rose up in response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quiet,'' court officers barked, not for the first time. ``If
you can't control yourself, you're going to have to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Court officers said they were under orders to run the overflow
room like a regular courtroom. But one said: ``You try to be a
little understanding. You have to understand that people are going
to get emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the overflow room was the Rev. Calvin Butts. He
said he was struck by Carroll's ``sense of arrogance,'' and that he
doubted several aspects of the officer's testimony, particularly
when he said he could not tell from down the street that Diallo was
black.
</P>
<P>
   Also there was Abdul El-Amin, 59, who had come from Manhattan on
his day off from his security job. ``Policemen have been getting
away with murder for years,'' El-Amin said. Then he turned back to
the screen, where Don Levin was beginning his cross-examination of
Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, prosecutors,'' El-Amin said, ``earn your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Diallo's shooting, Police Department officials and
Stephen C. Worth, a lawyer who was hired through the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association and now represents McMellon, said that the
officers were hunting for a serial rapist that night and thought
Diallo resembled ``in a generic way'' the sketch of the rapist.
</P>
<P>
   That account of the officers' assignment that night was repeated
countless times in news articles.
</P>
<P>
   But the story raised some eyebrows, both because people in the
neighborhood said they had not been warned of the rapist's
existence, and because the man arrested and accused of the rapes
two months later, Issaac Jones, 38, bore little facial resemblance
to Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Carroll did indeed bring up the rapist, saying that
the officers were regularly given new intelligence reports about
him and had a sketch of him with them that night. Before
encountering Diallo, he said, he and his fellow officers had
fruitlessly pursued a man at the Bronx River Houses who fit the
rapist's description.
</P>
<P>
   The rapist was supposed to be a male Hispanic or, more likely,
black, between 5 feet 5 inches and 5 feet 8 inches tall, weighing
between 130 and 150 pounds. He used either a small black gun or a
small silver handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Upon seeing Diallo, Carroll said, he thought, ``He definitely
resembles the description of the rapist.''
</P>
<P>
   Diallo was 5 feet 6 inches and weighed 150 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   But on cross-examination, Carroll was shown a sketch of the
rapist that he was carrying the night Diallo was shot, and conceded
that it bore ``minimal resemblance'' to Diallo. He also conceded
that the last rape by the suspect in the 43rd Precinct had been in
March 1998, almost a year before the shooting. (Prosecutors said
afterward that it was actually January '98.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he suggested that from down the street, the
officers could not determine that Diallo was black. And he said he
had a ``hunch'' that Diallo was a lookout for a push-in robber.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll did point out that there were several composite sketches
of the rapist produced by the Police Department. But one that has
been widely circulated, because it does slightly resemble Diallo's
face, is dated Feb. 14, 1999, 10 days after the shooting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whether the four officers were the proxies for or victims of
their department's policies is an issue that both the prosecution
and the defense have danced around in the trial. All were members
of the Street Crime Unit, and as Carroll said Monday, in the 1990s
the unit's attention turned to getting illegal guns off the street.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the unit's work then became stopping and frisking young
men, most of whom were blacks and Hispanics. Sometimes, but not
always, it was because a bulge in their clothes or furtive
movements suggested they might be carrying guns. Although the unit
was given a lot of the credit for reducing violent crime in New
York City, much of the outcry after Diallo's death focused on the
way innocent people had been caught up in those searches.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Levin, who was cross-examining the officers, tried to
capitalize on that backlash, repeatedly asking the officers about
``stop-and-frisks'' in a tone that sounded as if he were talking
about people who rob Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   He got Carroll and McMellon to concede that most of the people
they thought had guns turned out to have been carrying ``innocuous
objects, like wallets or beepers.'' Diallo was found to have only a
wallet and a beeper after he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   And Levin tried to get them to say that only about 10 percent of
all the stops they make result in arrests. But both officers would
concede only that they did not arrest most of those they frisked.
</P>
<P>
   Levin also focused on a stop they made earlier in the evening
for which they failed to file paperwork. He said that meant there
would have been no accountability if they had violated the rights
of the person they had stopped. And he implied that perhaps the
officers had performed other stop-and-frisks that night for which
they also had filed no reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting here under oath I don't remember any other
stop-and-frisk,'' McMellon said. ``It was a very trying night for
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
