</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THOMAS-TRIBUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY SAYS GOODBYE TO DERRICK THOMAS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Moments past noon Monday at Arrowhead
Stadium, a sleek B-2 stealth bomber glided overhead, slipping
across the sky like a huge, flat and thin shiny silver coin. Below,
in a gold coffin in one of the end zones, lay the body of Derrick
Thomas, No. 58, the great Kansas City Chiefs linebacker who died of
a blood clot last Tuesday, 16 days after an auto accident had left
him paralyzed from the chest down.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand Chiefs fans sitting in the stands applauded the
majestic tribute to a man whose father was an Air Force pilot who
never returned from Vietnam. On the field, several members of the
Chiefs organization awaited the arrival of Thomas' family from one
of the stadium tunnels. Edith Morgan, his mother, led a group of
more than 20 family members toward the tent that covered the
coffin. She was rolled forward in a wheelchair, too weak to walk,
too numb to speak. The group formed a half circle around the
coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Then one of Thomas' brothers, 20-year-old Jay Morgan, walked
toward the middle of the field, his eyes locked on the big screen
high above that projected Thomas in his Chiefs uniform, smiling,
seemingly peering down on them all. Morgan squatted squarely in the
center of the field with his head in his hands and remained there
until his relatives embraced him and coaxed him to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the reality of all of this, it was too much,'' Morgan
said later, explaining his own special midfield tribute. ``I was
just sitting there thinking: `I'm right where my brother played.
This is it.' I talked to Derrick twice while he was in the
hospital, including the day before he died. We talked about me
moving from tight end to defensive end at my college, Jones Junior
College, in Laurel, Miss. Derrick was happy about that and my
grades. I just told him we needed him to get well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminded me that the key to winning football at my position
was that the lowest man wins. `Get low and you can blow them off
the ball,' he said. That's what he did all of the time. I was in
class when my teammates came and got me and told me that he had
died. The whole family now, we just keep telling each other that
God doesn't make mistakes and to just believe.''
</P>
<P>
   On this Valentine's Day, when more than 20,000 came to the
stadium to view Thomas in an open coffin in a procession that
lasted all day, everyone tried persuading others to just believe.
To believe that Thomas' life _ cut short at age 33 _ was a life
worth celebrating as much as mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``So young, but he lived a good life,'' said Lamar Hunt, the
Chiefs' owner, who stood on the field and tried comforting the
Thomas family. ``I've seen messages from Denver fans and Raiders
fans, our biggest rivals, who said they still hate the Chiefs but
spoke with so much respect and sympathy. I was at the AFC
championship game when I got the news that Derrick had been in the
accident. And then for those few days he seemed to be in good
spirits and there was hope that he would one day walk again. And
then this. It is harder because it was totally unexpected. This
outpouring of affection here today is tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could remember a professional football player having such
a tribute, on the field, the coffin open for fans, who waited in
long lines that descended the stadium steps for a glimpse of their
hero. A private service at a local church was scheduled for the
evening and another service on Tuesday morning at Kemper Arena was
planned. Attendees were to include former Chiefs Joe Montana and
Marcus Allen, NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue and Hank Williams
Jr., who planned a musical tribute.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, a day that began with dark and cloudy skies but
ended in bright sunshine, was especially for the people of Kansas
City. It was for the Chiefs' cavalry of fans who had watched Thomas
arrive here from the University of Alabama in 1989 and play 11
seasons, nine of them as a Pro Bowl player.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Brown, 43, of nearby Lee Summit, Mo., said he took the day
off from his delivery job to pay his respects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here Tuesday night, Wednesday, Friday and today,'' said
Brown, who wore a red Chiefs jacket, a white Chiefs cap and a
yellow button that featured a red No. 58. Everyone entering the
stadium Monday received one of those buttons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respected Derrick as a man, a young man who did great work
on the field and great charity here off of it,'' Brown said. ``He
was taken away from us so early. He brought so much excitement
here. When I looked at him in that casket, I tell you, it looked
like to me he was smiling. If anyone looks at those tributes to
Derrick out in front of the stadium, that will tell them everything
they need to know about what Kansas City thinks of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on a 20-yard stretch of lawn under a tent in front of
Arrowhead, there is now a shrine left by Chiefs fans _ balloons and
flowers, posters and pictures, stuffed animals and footballs,
banners and newspaper clippings, T-shirts and hats, poems and
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Dan and Kelly Boyd took their 2-year-old son, Dan Jr. ``We
wanted our son to see this, even if he doesn't always remember it,
because this is a part of our history,'' Kelly Boyd said. ``I felt
OK until I actually saw Derrick. Seeing his body, I was moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Boyd said: ``I did not know Derrick Thomas. But I watched
him for the last 11 years play Chiefs football, and seeing him on
TV in our living room meant he was like a part of my family. My son
is going to grow up and play football. I hope he becomes a player
and a man like Derrick Thomas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
