<SLUG> BC-NY-FORECLOSED-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN WHO LOST HOME TO $58 BILL WILL GET IT BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ A Rockland County woman who lost her town
house to foreclosure because of a missed $58 tax payment and a
whole lot of red tape will get it back under an agreement reached
Monday with the county government and the man who bought the
foreclosed house.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Mireille Leroy, 38, of Spring Valley, had never been
late with a mortgage payment and first learned that her $114,000
home had been foreclosed upon and sold at auction when she was
served with an eviction notice by the new owner on Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Her mortgage holder was responsible for paying her taxes and had
done so, except for one $58 installment that the county Tax
Department had not notified it about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very relieved and thankful,'' Leroy said in a statement.
``No one should ever have to go through what I went through here. I
wouldn't wish it on my worst enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan negotiated by Ryan S. Karben, a Rockland county
legislator and chairman of the Tax Delinquency Committee, the
county will seek to have the state Supreme Court void the
foreclosure. Then the county will reimburse Carlo Jean Pierre, the
man who bought the tidy brown-shingled town house for $60,000 at a
county auction as an investment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Norwest Mortgage, the bank that held the mortgage
on the property and was responsible for paying Leroy's property
taxes out of an escrow fund, will pay Jean Pierre $15,000 for the
mistake. Community groups will also chip in to pay the roughly
$2,000 in legal bills accumulated by Leroy, a single mother and
registered nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Karben has also proposed legislation, which is expected to be
called ``Mireille's Law,'' that would require a county worker to
visit all homes threatened with foreclosure for tax delinquency.
``This is a testament to the neighborly spirit of Rockland
County,'' Karben said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
