<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BETTENHAUSEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONY BETTENHAUSEN, 48, YOUNGEST BROTHER IN AUTO RACING FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD GOLDSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Lee Bettenhausen, a member of a prominent auto racing
family who owned a racing team and once drove Indy Cars, died
Monday in a plane crash on a farm near Leesburg, Ky. He was 48.
</P>
<P>
   The crash, which occurred midday about 30 miles from Lexington,
Ky., also killed Bettenhausen's wife, Shirley, the daughter of the
longtime Indy Car driver Jim McElreath; Russ Roberts, a partner in
Bettenhausen's racing team; and Larry Rangel, a businessman from
Indiana, according to Brad Stevens, a spokesman for the
Indianapolis-based Bettenhausen Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   The plane took off from Tri-City Airport in Blountville, Tenn.,
and was on the way to Indianapolis, the Federal Aviation
Administration said. Bettenhausen was returning home from
Homestead, Fla., where he had been involved in testing for the
Championship Auto Racing Teams circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was a twin-engine Beech Baron belonging to
Bettenhausen, according to a report by the Speedvision cable
television network. It was not immediately clear whether he was
flying the plane, but he had a pilot's license, according to the
network. The cause of the crash was not known.
</P>
<P>
   Bettenhausen was the youngest of three racing brothers and the
son of Melvin Eugene (Tony) Bettenhausen, a two-time national
champion who was killed during a practice run for the Indianapolis
500 in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Lee Bettenhausen drove Indy Cars from 1979 to 1993 and
raced 11 times in the Indy 500. He had 103 career starts in Indy
Cars with a best finish of second and was the U.S. Auto Club rookie
of the year in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   He earned $2.4 million in his driving career, and his CART team
earned nearly $6 million in prize money with 13 different drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Bettenhausen began his career racing stock cars in 1969, joined
the Winston Cup circuit in 1974 and competed in the U.S. Auto Club
stock and midget divisions in 1975 and 1976.
</P>
<P>
   His father raced at the Indianapolis 500 from 1946 to 1960. The
elder Tony Bettenhausen was killed while taking a practice run at
Indy as a favor to another driver, Paul Russo, who felt that
something was wrong with his car and asked if Bettenhausen could
discover the problem. While Bettenhausen was driving that car on
the main straightaway, a 5-cent pin in the steering system came
loose. The car hit a wall, soared high in the air, crashed and
burned, killing Bettenhausen instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Lee Bettenhausen's brother Gary was a well-known race car
driver. Another brother, Merle, lost his right arm in a wreck in
July 1972 at Michigan International Speedway, racing in the
Michigan 200.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Lee Bettenhausen bought a CART team in 1988 and made his
last start at the Indy 500 in 1993. As an owner in CART, he fielded
two rookies of the year, Patrick Carpentier (1997) and Stefan
Johansson (1992).
</P>
<P>
   Gary, the oldest son, began racing stock cars in 1965. He made
his Indy Car debut at Phoenix in 1966 and the first of 21 starts at
Indianapolis in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Merle Bettenhausen drove champ cars, dirt cars, sprints and
midgets before coming to Indianapolis in 1972. He passed his Indy
500 rookie test that year but never made a qualification attempt
before losing his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Lee Bettenhausen was involved in an accident at the
Indianapolis 500 in 1987 that resulted in a spectator's death. A
tire that came loose from Bettenhausen's car as he approached the
home straightaway was hit by the car of Roberto Guerrero. The tire
flew into the top row of the grandstand, striking and killing Lyle
Kurtenbach, 41, of Rothschild, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Bettenhausen, who struggled with financing in the last few
years, had been expected to run a car for Michel Jourdain in the
2000 CART FedEx Championship series.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife are survived by two daughters, Bryn, 18, and
Taryn, 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
